<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SECT-MURDER-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN HARGED IN 1984 MURDER THAT PROSECUTOR TIES TO A SECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Serice   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ An East Newark man was charged with murder Friday
in the stabbing death of a homeless man here in 1984, a killing
that the Essex County prosecutor said was carried out as ``a
sacrifice'' to honor the leader of a religious sect that considers
itself a lost black tribe of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Patricia A. Hurt, said investigators believed
that the suspect, John Armstrong, 40, who also uses the name
Yokonon Israel, was a follower of Yahweh ben Yahweh, the founder of
a Black Israelite group whose doctrine portrays white men as
devils. The man he was charged with killing was white.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt did not describe any signs of ritualism or other
evidence that would distinguish the killing from a random street
crime, but she said the stabbing occurred on July 3, 1984, just two
days before Yahweh ben Yahweh visited Newark, and within a block of
the sect's Newark temple.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday to announce the murder charge, Ms.
Hurt referred to the group as a cult and said: ``It is black
supremist and they have racist ideologies. One of their premises is
to kill white males, and the victim in this case was, in fact, a
white man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt would not say what evidence prompted Armstrong's arrest
in Newark on Wednesday, more than 14 years after the crime.
Investigators from the Newark police, the Port Authority police and
the FBI's joint terrorism task force worked on the case, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt identified the victim as Attilio Cicala, 52. Officials
said they believed that Cicala did not know Armstrong and that
Cicala was stabbed eight times in the chest and abdomen on South
Orange Avenue in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Yahweh ben Yahweh, whose name in Hebrew literally means ``God
the son of God,'' and six of his disciples were convicted of
conspiracy by a jury in U.S. District Court in Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., in 1992 for ordering the murders of 14 white vagrants and
disobedient black disciples in Florida. Yahweh ben Yahweh was
sentenced to 18 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment filed in that case, Yahweh ben
Yahweh instructed members of his group to ``kill me a white devil
and bring me an ear.'' The white vagrants killed in Florida had
their ears sliced off. An investigator, speaking on the condition
of anonymity, said Cicala's ears were not cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who officials said has been a self-employed artist
recently, was arraigned Friday morning before Judge Betty J. Lester
in Essex County Superior Court. Judge Lester set bail at $250,000,
and officials said that Armstrong was being held at the Essex
County jail.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt said that the Yahweh temple in Newark had closed,
although officials did not know when. Investigators said that
Armstrong remained a follower of the Yahweh doctrine, but they did
not explain how they had linked him to the sect, one of several
Black Israelite groups in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The various groups share similar ideologies about blacks being
the ``true Jews'' and members of lost Hebrew tribes and about
whites being devils. They are not accepted by mainstream Judaism,
which considers some of the groups anti-Semitic. Ms. Hurt called
the Yahwehs ``a faction of the Black Hebrew Israelites.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the better known of such groups are the Black Israelites
who proselytize in Times Square and recently reached a compromise
with Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani over the use of loudspeakers. A
leader of that group could not be reached Friday night, but there
did not appear to be any connection between the New York group and
the Florida-based Yahweh group.
</P>
<P>
   Yahweh ben Yahweh was born Hulon Mitchell Jr. in Oklahoma, but
rejected that name as a ``slave name.'' He had been active as a
Black Muslim in Chicago before moving to Miami in 1979 and founding
his group, known both as the Yahwehs and as the Nation of Yahweh.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Encyclopedia of American Religions, the Nation
of Yahweh believes that black people are the true lost tribe of
Judah but have not assumed their destiny as a ruling class. They
wear white robes and believe that all people who oppose God are
devils.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt and her investigators said they believed that the
killing of Cicala was racially motivated and instigated by the
sect's antiwhite doctrine. Ms. Hurt called the stabbing ``a
sacrifice'' that was carried out ``in anticipation of the arrival
of the cult's leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that an indictment of Armstrong by a state grand
jury was expected sometime in the next few weeks and that he was
not expected to enter a plea in the case until then. Ms. Hurt would
not disclose Armstrong's home address and it was not immediately
clear whether he had retained a lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
