<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-MOCEANU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADULTHOOD NOT GYM-DANDY  
 MOCEANU FEELS SHE'S STARTING OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 5-foot-1, soon-to-be-married Shannon Miller reached up to
hug Dominique Moceanu when they met Friday in an Arizona State
University gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better not be taller than me,'' Miller said, realizing
that her 1996 U.S. Olympic gymnastics teammate and one of the 12
bridesmaids for her June 12 wedding now has at least an inch on
her.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 inches or more Moceanu has grown since the Americans won
their first women's Olympic team gold in Atlanta _ and became
forever linked as the Magnificent Seven _ is minuscule compared
with the 17-year-old's leap into adulthood during the past four
months.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu has been transformed in the days since Oct. 17, when her
father, Dumitru, fired Dominique's coach to trigger a chain of
dramatic events. The situation culminated with Moceanu being
legally declared an adult and her father being ordered to stay away
from her for a year.
</P>
<P>
   From a fearful girl unsure of her future to a luminous young
woman, able not only to intelligently discuss the breakup of her
family but to look past it to a future she still hopes will include
the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at myself and I thought I was growing up last year, and
now I just keep learning more and more about life and everything,''
said Moceanu, who is here to sign autographs before the Reese's
Gymnastics Cup at 7 tonight at Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not about the money. I have no money. I didn't get any
money out of this. I pay attorneys, I pay all these people, there's
not anything at all. I told him I'd leave all the money behind. I'd
start over fresh. But it hurts because I worked for that, and that
would have been my life that I could have just retired. I have to
start over now, and that's fine. I learned early what it's like to
fall down and pick yourself back up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not the world to me. Money I can live without.''
</P>
<P>
   The money is the estimated $2 million to $2.5 million that
Moceanu has earned in a career that took her from junior national
champion in 1994 to senior national champ in '95 to, at age 14, the
youngest U.S. gymnast ever to win an Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   It went into a trust under the control of her parents, with
Dumitru spending much of the fund on a 72,000-square-foot gym in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The family tension erupted just days after the dismissal of
Luminita Miscenco, who coached Moceanu since January 1998, a year
in which she was third all-around in the U.S. Championships and won
the Goodwill Games all-around gold.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu filed a lawsuit asking for legal control of her affairs.
Then events took a darker turn. In November, Dumitru was accused of
trying to arrange for the murders of Miscenco and a friend of his
daughter's. Law enforcement authorities said he was not charged
because he had not paid for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   After spending Thanksgiving in the Valley with Olympic teammate
Amanda Borden, Moceanu was back in court in early December, when
her father was ordered to have no contact with her other than in
writing through her lawyer. Dumitru has violated that ruling once
by calling her, Moceanu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak with my mom (Camelia) and my sister (Christina),''
said Moceanu, who lives alone in a Houston apartment and spent
Christmas with her mother's relatives. ``Now it's over with, so
hopefully he (Dumitru) can deal with it, but I don't know how he
is. He keeps wanting to appeal, and it's just wasting everybody's
money and time. He just needs to put it behind him and deal with it
and accept it, because he can't do anything about it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and wearing a yellow shirt and white pants, accessorized
with an expensive watch, earrings, bracelets and necklaces, Moceanu
is glad to be moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   In November, she re-signed, on her own, with Gold Medal
Management and is making some appearance money. On Monday, she will
return to training at Brown's Gymnastics in Houston with a new
coach, Alexander Alexandrov, who worked with her as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Miscenco now coaches at Nadia Comaneci's gym in Oklahoma.
Moceanu does not rule out working with the coach again.
</P>
<P>
   Although circumstances prevented her from completing high school
at Northland Christian, she soon will begin writing and
communications classes at Tomball Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Like Miller, Kerri Strug and Dominique Dawes, who parlayed a
team bronze at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics to a gold in Atlanta,
Moceanu is hopeful that a second Olympics would be her best.
</P>
<P>
   She was ninth all-around and did not win an individual medal in
'96.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominique is so talented,'' said Miller, the winner of more
Olympic/World medals than any other American gymnast. ``She is one
of the most talented gymnasts I've ever seen. She handled it (the
Olympics) so well, she was so composed and so focused on what she
was doing, but you could still see she was a little bit young in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years to go (until the Sydney Olympics), I don't think it
will be a problem for her to get back in shape, if that's what she
wants. Your body kind of retains the memory of how to do a lot of
the basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 1992, I grew 4 or 5 inches. People always say, she's 19,
4 inches taller, 20 pounds heavier, and you think, oh my god, 20
pounds. But 5 pounds an inch is average, so it's not really that
big of a deal. It gave me more power to do bigger skills.''
</P>
<P>
   For Moceanu, another Olympics or World Championships would be
less about a medal or monetary reward than her validation as a
decision maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time it's for me, not anyone else,'' she said. ``I'm
choosing my path.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
