<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST PEERING OVER TYSON'S BIG SHOULDERS  
 TYSON FACES TOUGHEST FOE _ HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS - A long-running rematch, Mike Tyson's biggest fight,
continues tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Call it shadow boxing.
</P>
<P>
   It's Tyson vs. Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson always seems caught in a desperate confrontation with the
ominous shadow cast by the demons lurking in his dangerous past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got so much anger in me from past things,'' he said. ``Don't
take it personal. I'm dealing with a crisis in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't Tyson have it wrong here? Didn't he mean to say dealing
with a life that is a crisis?
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's comeback bout against Frans Botha is just the latest
chapter. He is expected to win at the MGM Grand in his first fight
since he bit Evander Holyfield's ears 19 months ago. Botha is a
credible opponent. But in this psycho soap opera, he has a cameo
role.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Botha wins, the unknown heavyweight probably will be
cast as a fighter who happened to be there when Tyson beat Tyson
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   That's not fair to the friendly South African, but boxing and
fair play never have been related. The business specializes in the
strange, and the Tyson story is about as strange as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   He has walked in and out of prison, blown unimaginable wealth,
gone bonkers against Holyfield and undergone psychoanalysis on the
public stage.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder he sounds confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the last time I was happy,'' said Tyson, who
also faces a possible return to prison after a Feb. 5 sentencing
hearing on misdemeanor assault charges in Maryland. ``When things
go great, I worry the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to be here now. I'm supposed to be
Thorazined-out. Lithium, yeah. I deal with my problems in front of
the whole world. If I have a fight with my wife, the whole world is
going to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an educated person. I'm not pompous. I've been to
prison. I've done bad things. I've been as low as I can. Nobody
knows. Only the Shadow knows . . .''
</P>
<P>
   There it is again, the Shadow. Boxing's feared knockout artist
never has been able to knock out the biggest threat of all. The one
from within.
</P>
<P>
   He's wants to break habits that have shackled him to a
well-worn, self-destructive past, his new circle of management
says. He's trying, adviser Shelly Finkel says.
</P>
<P>
   The mental sparring has been evident in the sudden flash of
angry eyes and the repeated outbursts of profanity ever since he
started training at Phoenix's Madison Square Garden. But the
volatile process can't be a source of much comfort for advisor
Finkel, trainer Tommy Brooks or promoter Dan Goosen.
</P>
<P>
   They've watched Tyson go from an eerie calm to sudden storm
without an apparent reason or sign of imminent change. A tornado is
more predictable. The inescapable conclusion is that nobody can
forecast what Tyson will do tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty is part of a sales pitch for a fight that
largely has been met with public indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's advisers see his comeback as a long-term investment. The
idea is to re-introduce him tonight en route to a second Holyfield
rematch and, possibly, a long-awaited fight with 50-year-old George
Foreman. Both bouts promise to be record-setting money makers.
</P>
<P>
   All those hopes would suddenly end with an unexpected loss to
Botha or a repeat of the Bite Fight insanity. Still, the promoters
sell the uncertainty, almost as if they are pushing Tyson to the
very edge of the demise they hope to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has watched and worked with Tyson through long sessions
at the gritty downtown Phoenix gym.
</P>
<P>
   The repetition _ the punch, counter-punch _ has been an attempt
to re-instill fundamental skills so that they become intinctive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Mike created a lot of bad habits over the last
10 years,'' said Brooks, who was in Holyfield's corner when the two
last met. ``I'm trying to change that. Boxing is readjust,
readjust, readjust.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooks is not a mind reader. He can remold Tyson the boxer
in the gym. But he can't re-make the mind, which, in the end, will
determine whether Tyson employs the tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's temper has repeatedly, and inexplicably, exploded
thoughout the past week in interview sessions. If it happens behind
a microphone, can't it again happen in the ring?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could answer that question,'' Brooks said. ``I'm not
a psychologist. He's a human being. I'm just a fight trainer. I'm
teaching him how to fight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
