<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LIGHTNING-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPING DEVILS GET BETTER AGAINST THE LOWLY LIGHTNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The timing was absolutely perfect for
the league's worst team to visit the Devils Friday night. With New
Jersey having lost its previous three games, the Tampa Bay
Lightning provided just the kind of soft touch needed by the
Devils, who posted a 3-1 victory at Continental Arena on the
strength of three goals on consecutive power plays in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   The victory averted what could have been a fourth consecutive
loss for the first time in almost four years for the Devils. Tampa
Bay has only one victory in its last 14 games and occupies last
place in the the National Hockey League with a record of 9-30-3.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston, Petr Sykora and Denis Pederson scored for the
Devils, who fired 33 shots at Corey Schwab in their second victory
in seven games (2-4-1) this month. The victory also ended a
four-game streak without a victory at home.
</P>
<P>
   The bad stretch has cost the Devils (23-13-5) first place in the
Atlantic Division, which is now occupied by the Philadelphia
Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're struggling, you want to get people to the net,''
said Pederson, whose goal was his first in 14 games. ``It was a big
win for us to get us over our slump, but we realize we're not
playing the hockey we need to be playing to win a majority of our
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Martin Brodeur, who lost to Ottawa twice this week,
played one of his better games in recent weeks and improved his
record to 19-11-5. His only blemish Friday night was a goal by
Darcy Tucker on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils paid tribute to Ken Daneyko before the game for
becoming the franchise leader in games played. Daneyko set the
record last month in his 935th game. He was honored by the Devils
at center ice Friday, along with his family and John McMullen, the
chairman and owner of the Devils. Then Daneyko went out and played
in his 951st game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had trouble holding the tears toward the end, that's why I
kept the speech short,'' Daneyko said. ``Dr. McMullen has been more
than a boss to me. He's more like a father to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek dressed seven defensemen and was forced to
play another one, Brad Bombardir, as a center because the team's
list of flu sufferers reached four on Friday. Jason Arnott joined
Jay Pandolfo, Patrik Elias and Chris Terreri on the list started by
Lyle Odelein four games ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning was left with only four defensemen after the first
period when Kjell Samuelsson pulled a hamstring and Ken Bannister
injured his right wrist in a collision with Sergei Brylin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tampa Bay opened the scoring 5 minutes 18 seconds into
the second period when Tucker converted Chris Gratton's pass for
his 11th goal of the season. It came during Tampa Bay's second
power play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston tied it for the Devils with his 11th goal of the season
just over two minutes later, on the Devils' second power play. Then
Sykora scored his 12th goal the next time the Devils had a one-man
advantage to give them the lead with 5:32 left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was extended to 3-1 with 1:38 left, when Pederson
scored his sixth goal. The Devils had entered the game with just
two power-play goals in their previous five games.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the fifth in five games against the Devils for
COREY SCHWAB, the goaltender who was traded to Tampa Bay by the
Devils three seasons ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
