r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-CASSTEVENS-TYSON-     01-16 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CASSTEVENS-TYSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISE FANS LOOKING GIFT TURKEY IN MOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The MGM Grand is offering two breakfast buffet
coupons to taxi drivers who will pick up passengers at the hotel
after tonight's fistic extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know why?'' the cabbie said.
</P>
<P>
   Our eyes met in his rear-view mirror. ``'Cause nobody wants to.
It's a ``garbage'' crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Last time Mike Tyson climbed into a boxing ring he suffered
temporary insanity and bit off Evander Holyfield's ear. Gun shots
reportedly rang out in the hotel casino, although a story put out
later said popping champagne corks caused the noise.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming tables shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In the panic, the cabbie said, more than 30 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Two $10 breakfasts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it,'' the cabbie said.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed not to go near the hotel. Judging by lagging ticket
sales many others are opting to stay away, too, not out of fear for
their safety but because no matter how you promote this heavyweight
event it bears a suspicious resemblance to one of those frozen
birds Mike handed out in Phoenix during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Only this turkey isn't free.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets range from $200 to $1,200. It's not worth $45, the price
to watch it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tyson can't sell a fight against Francois Botha, the Great
White Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Those foolish enough to fall for the come-on will do so
primarily for the same reason people pay to go behind the curtain
at a carnival freak show.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months of counseling and obedience training apparently
have done wonders for the ex champ. After his exile, Tyson moved to
the Valley. He signed autographs. He gave toys and food to the
needy. His generosity and attempts to improve his image were
front-page news.
</P>
<P>
   Mike's handlers say he no longer bites. He still snaps
occasionally, but mostly at letter carriers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The only intrigue will be if oddsmakers and Steve ``Crocodile''
Finch are wrong. Tyson's paid cheerleader loudly predicts his man
``will tear Botha's head off.''
</P>
<P>
   What round?
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' Croc said. ``Knock him out ``cold.''''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is expected to begin the fight as he usually does,
launching himself like a missile from a silo. But what if Botha
withstands the early assault? If Tyson can't put his opponent away
quickly will he become frustrated, and give in to his animal urges?
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas hopes not. The blackjack dealers want Tyson to win. So
do the dice tables and the roulette wheels and the strip hotels,
especially the MGM Grand. Dorothy and Toto (featured in the Oz wing
of the giant hotel) were spotted Friday at the sports book, betting
on Iron Mike, and giving 7-1 odds.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson wins he will get another Vegas fight, a bigger one, and
then another _ possibly, and don't laugh _ against 50-year old
George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   The high rollers would love that one. So would the casinos and
the Nevada State Athletic Commission which gave Tyson's license
back.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson is Las Vegas' prodigal son.
</P>
<P>
   He is welcome here. He belongs here. Tyson can be as crude as
the limericks of Andrew ``Dice'' Clay who is appearing at Bally's.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's history with women suggests he believes in the
spontaneity of romance. In this town that never sleeps
companionship can be found simply by picking up a telephone and
dialing a number advertised in the pulp magazines and X-rated
calling cards that litter the sidewalks along the neon strip.
</P>
<P>
   What does it say about boxing that Tyson remains the sport's
biggest draw? What does it say about society when Iron Mike strips
to his briefs at the weigh-in and poses and female admirers cheer?
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is incapable of feeling embarrassed. Tyson can't be
shamed. How does he feel about being characterized as a reclusive
rapist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not a recluse,'' said the former champ, as he
awaits a $10 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   David Casstevens can be reached at 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
