<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BLACKHAWKS-RANGER     01-16 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLACKHAWKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-PLACE BLACKHAWKS TOO GOOD FOR RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Play enough last-place teams in succession and eventually one
will beat you. Friday night it was the Chicago Blackhawks, at the
bottom of the Central Division of the Western Conference, who
visited the Rangers at Madison Square Garden. Without a victory in
their previous seven games, the Blackhawks were well rested, having
spent the previous three nights at a Colorado resort.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Rangers, they resorted to the neutral-zone trap,
some opportunistic shooting and a little bit of undetected
interference at a key moment before leaving town with a 3-1
victory. The result ended the Rangers' winning streak at two games
and dropped them below .500 as they began the second half of their
82-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks have scored barely more than two goals a game,
and their final one Friday night was into an empty net. Brian
Leetch, the Ranger captain, seemed irked that he and his teammates
were unable to beat the Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold them to two goals and we should win that game,'' Leetch
said. ``We made a couple mistakes against a team that doesn't score
a lot.'' Despite the minislump of the Rangers' league-leading power
play, Leetch said, ``We need to score five-on-five.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch has not scored, on the power play or at even strength, in
the last 16 games. He had three shots on goal Friday. Wayne Gretzky
had four, as did Manny Malhotra and John MacLean. But the only
Ranger to beat goalie Jocelyn Thibault was Marc Sarvard, who
gathered a rebound after a power play to tie the score at 1-1
midway through the second period. Thibault made 32 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's winning goal, by Mike Maneluk, came at 4 minutes 48
seconds of the third period. He scored off the rush, finding
himself alone on Ranger goalie Mike Richter after the Blue Shirts
were caught in a line change. Rangers Coach John Muckler said the
problem occurred because Chicago players were interfering with
Ranger defenseman Jeff Beukeboom as he tried to get to the bench.
Beukeboom agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy pinned me while I was trying to get off,'' Beukeboom
said. ``I definitely didn't have the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, it was the third of four consecutive games
against teams in last place in their divisions. After beating Tampa
on Sunday, the Rangers beat the Islanders on Wednesday and they
play the Canadiens Saturday in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers played without Todd Harvey, their aggressive right
wing, who is expected to miss at least four weeks with a
second-degree sprain of the medial collateral ligament in his left
knee. Defenseman Mathieu Schneider was back in the lineup after
missing two games with a groin pull.
</P>
<P>
   New to the lineup was forward Derek Armstrong, recalled from the
Hartford farm club, with 19 goals and 26 assists with the Wolf
Pack. He was on the right side of center Marc Savard for some
shifts and played for 3:16. MacLean, recently Savard's right wing,
moved over to Gretzky's line to replace Harvey. Also in the lineup
was defenseman Jan Mertzig, called up from Hartford this week. He
began the season with the Rangers, but was sent down in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   Following the game, the Rangers sent Armstrong back to Hartford
and recalled Scott Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Rangers' best players was Malhotra, who started the
game as the fourth-line center and finished as a third-line right
wing. A hard forechecker with good instincts, Malhotra played 9:20
and earned praise from Muckler, who reviewed his play as
``excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks came into the game with two consecutive defeats and an
0-5-2 record in the previous seven games. With an 11-25-6 record,
their .333 winning percentage was better than only Tampa's in the
27-team National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case in Wednesday's game with the Islanders, the
visiting team scored on the first shot of the game. This time it
was by Doug Gilmour, the former Devil, who stood in the slot
uncovered, took a right-to-left pass from Nelson Emerson and beat
Richter at 1:10 to give Chicago a 1-0 lead. It was the 10th of the
season for Gilmour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be sharper early,'' Richter said. ``We just have
to be more prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was polite after the game, but he seemed to be
containing a smoldering anger. ``We just can't allow it, especially
in your own building against teams that are struggling,'' Gretzky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky finished the game at minus-2 in the plus/minus ratio.
His total for the season is minus-10, tied with Adam Graves for
worst on the team.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-game ceremony, the Rangers and the league honored
defenseman ULF SAMUELSSON, who played in his 1,000th. NHL game on
Wednesday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
