</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WILCOX-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER CONCEDING NOTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He has not won a tournament on the Senior Tour in
11 years and victory might never visit him again. Arnold Palmer is
69 now, an age most measuring devices calculate as old and he is
burdened with fighting his own cancer and helping his wife, Winnie,
fight hers.
</P>
<P>
   The trophy case and bank account are full and for most this
would be a complete ledger. Palmer is rich enough, and fortunate
enough, to watch the twilight years unfold from a porch of his
choosing.
</P>
<P>
   But he still deals with life like a putt just outside the
leather, conceding nothing. So ``retirement'' becomes just another
word in the dictionary, a concept as foreign as laying up on a par
5.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good thing for anyone who is a fan of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer will continue to play in selected tournaments and the
Senior Skins Game, which he has won three times, is on the horizon.
He will also play in the ``Hope,'' where he is the only five-time
champion, when the regular tour stops in Palm Springs. And in April
he will walk the hills of Augusta National and again soak up the
cheers from an appreciative Masters gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is an exercise in diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   He played 13 events in 1997 and won $29,052. The same kind of
schedule last year yielded a return of $20,454 and placed him 111
on the elder tour's money list, a position that will do nothing to
denigrate his place in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Because wherever he goes, the gallery is sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   So now he shrugs off advancing age and disease and tries to find
the game that used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played very poorly,'' said Palmer during a conference
call. ``I guess through the midst of radiation I underestimated how
strong the stuff really is. I was weak and my game just went bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As his strength began returning, so did his swing. Both will be
precious commodities during the Senior Skins Game to be played at
Mauna Lani Resort on the big island of Hawaii during Super Bowl
weekend. The field features Raymond Floyd, Jim Colbert and Hale
Irwin, who treats the Senior Tour like an ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is trying to win for the sixth consecutive time, which
stokes Palmer's competitive fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty phenomenal that he's done as well as he has. I can
tell you this, there will be three guys out there trying to
dismantle him this year,'' Palmer said of Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   That the Senior Tour has flourished, and given marginal players
on the regular tour a shot at cashing big checks rather those from
social security, is pretty much Palmer's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think that when I started, the total tournament purse
was $10,000 and now we're looking at some tournaments with purses
over $5 million, that is a pretty rapid progression,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This glut of money might do what money sometimes does; breed
jealously and tear a sport apart. For proof we only need to look at
the shambles in which professional basketball now finds itself.
</P>
<P>
   So Palmer, who has earned the right to be his sport's elder
statesman, cautions against a gilded view obscuring the memories of
where the game came from and what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concerns are protecting the game and keeping the game, the
tradition and the integrity that made the game so great for so long
and not getting into squabbles about how we distribute money and
how we make eligibility rules,'' he said. ``All those things should
be worked out with the PGA Tour, and that door is open.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is aware that time is now the most precious commodity he
has. And while he has graced golf's landscape for 45 years, he will
continue to grace it still. And the sporting world is richer for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball invasion: Michael Jordan and Charles Barkley will be
adding to the gallery buzz at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic next
week. Jordan, who said bye-bye to hoops this week, and Barkley have
accepted invitations to play in the pro-am that annually features a
big celebrity field.
</P>
<P>
   Other athletes competing will be tennis star Pete Sampras and Cy
Young Award winners Roger Clemens and Tom Glavine. Former president
Gerald Ford will also play _ so wear a hard hat if you plan to
follow his group.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Barkley will be paired together for four rounds
starting next Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
