<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-AIRPORT-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN SEEKS TO RESTRICT SPENDING ON CITY'S AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Responding to Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's
proposal to reclaim Kennedy International and La Guardia Airports
from the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, Gov. Christine
Todd Whitman has suggested that the agency withhold billions of
dollars that it has committed for improvements there over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Whitman, who has been challenged by Giuliani in recent
weeks on issues as varied as garbage hauling and the New York Jets,
said she had supported billions of dollars in improvements to the
two New York City airports. But, she said, it would be fiscally
irresponsible for the Port Authority, which is under contract to
operate and pay rent for the two airports until 2015, to make
long-term capital investments if Guiliani is serious about breaking
the lease and bringing in a private management company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the mayor's comments, it would make no sense for the
Port Authority to make any new investments in the New York airports
until their future is determined,'' Gov. Whitman said. ``If
Governor Pataki is interested, I would be happy to discuss with him
the appropriate restructuring of the agency, as long as it is in
the best interests of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Gov. Whitman and Gov. George E. Pataki share control of
the agency, she alone cannot dictate how the Port Authority spends
its money.
</P>
<P>
   But her comments made it clear that she does not intend to sit
idly by while Giuliani announces possible plans affecting its
future.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's statements, made during his State of the City speech
on Thursday, are the latest salvo in his campaign to regain control
of the two airports . Since his first campaign for mayor in 1989,
Giuliani has said that the authority favors New Jersey over New
York and diverts nearly $200 million per year from the airports'
profits to underwrite losses from the unprofitable PATH train
system and the Port Authority bus terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony P. Coles, a senior adviser to the mayor, said that
during the last five years, the Port Authority had paid a total of
less than $100 million in rent for the two airports. Meanwhile,
Coles said, Port Authority officials have paid for dramatic
improvements at Newark International Airport, while allowing the
city's airports to become rundown and outdated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a cash cow the P.A. can continue to milk for
generations,'' Coles said. ``The city is not going to renew that
lease when it expires in 2015. So what the Port Authority should do
is return the airports to the city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
