<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-FREE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDYESS TAKES HIS TIME  
 SUITORS MUST WAIT FOR DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
 AGENTS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suns free-agent forward Antonio McDyess apparently is in no
hurry to decide where he will play basketball next season, and his
agent said he won't push him for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based agent Tony Dutt insisted that none of the leading
contenders _ the Suns, the Denver Nuggets and the Houston Rockets _
has a particular edge at this point.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, how long will the Suns wait? Camps were
originally supposed to open Monday, and the NBA has pushed that to
at least Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he's holding up a lot of decisions,'' said
Dutt, who along with James Bryant, is representing McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   One decision he apparently isn't holding up is that of Chicago
free-agent center Luc Longley. Sources say Longley has agreed in
principle to join the Suns and will be in Phoenix for the start of
training camp early next week. Players cannot sign contracts until
the NBA's new collective-bargaining agreement is in writing.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that ink will be dry long before McDyess even
makes up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough problem for (the Suns), and it's a tough problem
for Antonio,'' Dutt said. ``But he's getting close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want teams to be able to do what they need to do, but we'll
know where he's going when he makes his choice. There is no hidden
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   That agenda issue is a sensitive subject for Dutt.
</P>
<P>
   He said there have been accusations that he is attempting to
direct McDyess to Houston because Dutt lives there. And the Nuggets
have his client and McDyess' friend, guard Nick Van Exel, under
contract for only this season. There also have been suggestions
Dutt might be trying to broker a new deal for Van Exel in return
for delivering McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there have been some rumors that I'm trying to get him
to go where I want him to go,'' Dutt said. ``That's not true. I've
got 12 clients and none of them are Houston Rockets. They may want
to live here in the off-season, but they don't play for the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took heat when Shawn Kemp left Seattle, and I can take the
heat now. That's my job. To be honest, I'll be happy whichever team
he picks as long as he's happy. There are no agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutt said he has been told the Suns may be ready to renounce the
rights to McDyess, which would free the club to use McDyess's $5.7
million salary cap space for other purposes. But he repeated what
Bryant said Thursday _ the Suns have not set a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Suns have been very supportive _ but firm,'' Dutt said.
``The sad part of this is that there have to be an awful lot of
assumptions under the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we would really like to do is sit down and meet with the
coaches to get a better feel for what they plan to do. Danny Ainge
has an edge there because Antonio knows him.''
</P>
<P>
   McDyess was in Houston for much of the off-season, so he's
probably gotten a good idea about Rockets Coach Rudy Tomjanovich,
if not face-to-face, then from Rockets players.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has a new coach, Mike D'Antoni, and McDyess has not met
him yet. But McDyess knows Nuggets General Manager Dan Issel well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at how competitive the team will be, too,''
Dutt said. ``Phoenix has always done well. Houston has done well.
He loved Denver. It shocked him when he was traded, but who knows
if Nick is going to be there next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, he can only pick one, and he hasn't made that
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, the Suns are expected to offer Clifford
Robinson a new contract if McDyess doesn't return, and the club
could try to lure free agent guard Brent Barry.
</P>
<P>
   The club also would have a $1.75 million salary cap exception.
Terry Porter, a 35-year-old point guard who played last season in
Minnesota, is a possibility for that exception. The Suns need a
backup point guard and three-point shooting. Porter is a career
37.6-percent three-point shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Terry brings is high character, the ability to come in
and run a team and hit a shot when you need it and a solid role
model for younger players,'' said Porter's agent, Charles Besser,
who confirmed that the Suns have been in contact. ``If the deal is
right, I can easily see Terry playing in Phoenix.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
