<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONNING ENJOYS LIFEIN NASHVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Former Coyotes' center &UR; Cliff Ronning faced the
unknown when the Coyotes sent him to the expansion Nashville
Predators after seven games this year to create more playing time
for rookie &UR; Daniel Briere.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, the unknown isn't all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I wasn't sure, leaving a place like Phoenix where the
fans are great and it's an exciting place to play,'' said Ronning,
who centers the Predators' No. 1 line. ``I was going to a place
where you weren't sure fans would be in the stands. But the fans
are super-loud and they got right into it and enjoy the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronning had two goals and five assists in Phoenix, but since the
trade to Nashville he has had eight goals and 16 assists and leads
the expansion team in scoring (10-21-31).
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade hit me hard,'' Ronning said before Friday night's
meeting with the Coyotes. ``I am a human being and I was putting
everything I had into the team. Everything was the Coyotes to me.
But that's the way it goes. That's the business of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it has been great here, and the organization is
first-class. It's been fun and I'm excited to go to the rink. There
isn't a lot expected of us. The biggest thing we expect of
ourselves is to work hard every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade, Briere has scored five goals and had four
assists in much less ice time than Ronning receives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tkachuk back? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Keith Tkachuk, who has been practicing for a week and looked
solid in Friday's morning skate, keeps making rumblings about
moving up his return from a broken rib to Sunday's game with
Chicago instead of Tuesday at home against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we'll evaluate before the Chicago game,''
General Manager &UR; Bobby Smith said, leaving the door open to an early
return. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tough defense &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newly obtained defenseman &UR; J.J. Daigneault thinks the Coyotes
have the potential to have a great defense when &UR; Gerald Diduck
returns from the injured list in a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1993, when we won the Stanley Cup in Montreal, all of our
defensemen were very quick, mobile and good puck handlers,''
Daigneault said. ``That's what I see here with  &UR; Oleg (Tverdovsky),
 &UR; Teppo (Numminen), &UR; Jyrki (Lumme), &UR; 
 &UR; Keith (Carney) and Gerald and the good younger guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to be first on the puck, the way the game is
played today because there is a lot of dumping the puck in and
forechecking. If you have mobile defensemen who are first to the
puck, it's a lot less battling you have to do in your own defensive
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some irony in the fact that after being traded to
Phoenix on Wednesday, Daigneault's picture was on the cover of
Friday's game program _ in a Predators uniform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
