<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN TO HAUNT VALLEY OF THE SUN?  
 EX-BULLS STAR LIKES AREA, MAY HANG OUT HERE OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was that Michael Jordan you saw strolling the fairways at The
Raven at South Mountain golf club?
</P>
<P>
   Could that have been his Airness sipping a cool one at Planet
Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't that Jordan's famous tongue wagging over his favorite
crispy Chinatown Chicken Spring Rolls _ smothered in spicy mandarin
orange syrup _ at Roy's of Scottsdale?
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't, it probably will be soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan for years has made Phoenix one of his favorite getaways.
He has been spotted playing many of the Valley's top golf courses,
including Phoenix Country Club, Paradise Valley CC, The Raven and
Grayhawk.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jordan has officially retired from the Chicago Bulls,
don't be surprised if he pops up even more often.
</P>
<P>
   There were rumors that Jordan is having a home built in the
area. It's not true.
</P>
<P>
   But he has had a new home constructed in the posh northeast
Valley for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan is in town to see his mom, it's a safe bet he'll
also stop by Charles Barkley's place. The former Suns forward and
current NBA free agent is one of Jordan's closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him big brother, and he calls me big brother,'' Barkley
said. ``When we played in the (NBA) Finals in 1993, I remember
people were criticizing us because we played golf together and had
dinner every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic Johnson said we shouldn't be doing it during the Finals.
We talked about it, and we decided we're going to be friends a lot
longer than we're going to be basketball players.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even neighbors someday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Barkleys and the Jordans might soon have a nice
new place to dine.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Longley, Jordan's former teammate in Chicago and a player
the Suns are attempting to sign for the upcoming season, has a new
restaurant opening in Scottsdale this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Longley, a 7-foot-2 center from Australia, owns several
``Seasons'' eateries in other cities, which Jordan is known to have
found to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether he's a big tipper. But we'll probably know
that soon enough, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 0033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
