<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GOODYKOONTZ-SUPERFAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'LL FILL JORDAN'S SHOES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKNOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that he's officially (or at least ``99.9 percent'') retired,
there seems little argument that Michael Jordan is the best
basketball player of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Well, duh. Anyone who has seen an NBA game in the past 10 years
knew that. Anyone who has never seen an NBA game still probably
noticed the media saturation of Jordan's retirement press
conference, which drew only slightly less coverage than Neil
Armstrong walking on the moon. (Fitting _ Jordan played like he was
also in a lighter gravity. Plus, he walked a lot, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Now there seems to be consternation on everyone's part that,
without Jordan, NBA games will draw fewer viewers than ``Gilligan's
Island'' reruns. True, I don't anticipate many people rearranging
their busy schedules to squeeze in a Raptors-Clippers game. But
that episode where the castaways do a musical version of ``Hamlet''
_ you just can't see that enough.
</P>
<P>
   But the game must go on. Now, the question is: Who will be the
next Jordan? (It's important that we do this little exercise now.
The anti-Jordan backlash already has begun. You know the drill _
sure, he was a great player, but Jordan didn't do enough for the
rest of humanity at large. Soon the image Jordan's name will
conjure won't be a sculpted athlete dunking a basketball. It will
be a heartless scoundrel stealing gruel from orphans.)
</P>
<P>
   I've got my own list of candidates, which I'll share with you
shortly. But I'd also like to hear from you. (See the bottom of
this column for information on how to reach me.) Which player _ if
any _ will assume the mantle of Living Legend? Why? Why not? The
person who sends in the best response will receive for his efforts
a hearty thank-you, as well as a prominent mention in next week's
column. (Hey, sorry, but I don't have Jordan's money to throw
around.)
</P>
<P>
   My picks, pro and con, in descending order:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen Iverson _ Pros: incredible talent, exciting game,
unstoppable offensive machine. Remember, in Jordan's first few
years in the league, critics complained that he was a
one-dimensional ball hog, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Arrest record. Apparent unwillingness to work on team
aspect of his game. Or, according to some reports, to work on any
other aspect, either.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Scottie Pippen _ Pros: Teamed with Jordan to win those six
championships. Tremendous talent in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Seems surly. Pouts. Subject of my all-time favorite Jordan
quote. Remember when Pippen missed a playoff game because of a
migraine? During the next season's playoffs, after Pippen played a
horrible game, Jordan said two words to him: ``Headache, Scottie?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Grant Hill _ Pros: Excellent player, unselfish, hard worker.
Like Jordan, couldn't have guessed by his college game that he'd be
this good. Doesn't have as many endorsements as Jordan (who does?)
but pitches an awful lot of products.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Grant who? Seems like a nice guy. Too nice (an image he
has parodied in commercials). Only guy in the league you wish would
act a little more like a spoiled millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shaquille O'Neal _ Pros: Hulking monster who can't be stopped
near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Surlier than Pippen. Worst free-throw-shooting star since
Wilt. Two words: rap career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles Barkley _ Pros: Great rebounder (just ask him), great
personality (just ask him), great quote (just listen to him).
Wouldn't suffer the slings and arrows Jordan has for not being a
social activist _ he's already told us he's not a role model.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Like a '76 Vega, he's old and breaking down. Fast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Garnett _ Pros: Exciting young player.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Huge contract blamed for lockout. Don't spend it all in
one place.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chris Webber _ Pros: Bald head.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Everything else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Latrelle Sprewell - Pros: Excellent grip.
</P>
<P>
   Cons: Temper, temper. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
