<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ALBANY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SINGLE VOTE BOLSTERS CLOUT OF SENATE GOP  
 PATRONAGE BOSS OR BUFFER?  
 A PERPETUAL FUND RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The recent elections may have sowed tumult in
Washington, but here in the state capital, the Legislature that
began meeting this week was a virtual replica of the last one, as
seasoned _ or calcified, depending on one's view _ as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single lawmaker seeking another term lost in November,
which is not all that flabbergasting, considering that the
incumbents have so many advantages, especially in fund-raising,
that dislodging a veteran is kind of like evicting a tenant from a
rent-controlled apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to pad its ranks at the ballot box, the Republican
majority in the state Senate found another way, one that was far
cheaper than raining millions of dollars in campaign money _ most
of it collected from donors with matters before the Legislature _
on elections. It pilfered one of the opposition members. The cost,
it would seem, was the chairmanship of the Agriculture Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The defector was state Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffman of Syracuse,
who, oddly enough, had long delighted in haranguing the Republican
senators about their misguided ways. Whatever the cries of
hypocrisy from the Democrats, her reasons for switching, a month
after she was re-elected, point up the stark differences here
between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   More so than in Congress, the minority parties in Albany are
powerless. Ms. Hoffman said in an interview that she had wearied of
that status, and wanted to give her constituents the ample benefits
of being in the majority _ a bigger staff, more state government
grants and the ability to introduce bills that actually have a
chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hoffman could not resist throwing a few stones at her former
compatriots, most of whom are from New York City, saying that they
had little, if any, sensitivity to the concerns of upstate
communities, particularly rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   She is certainly able to address those issues more forcefully
with her new chairmanship. Asked whether garnering that post was
part of a deal with the Republicans, she responded tartly,
``Everything fell into place comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans now have a 36-to-25 edge in the Senate. The
beleaguered Democrats _ who have been in the Senate minority for
nearly all of this century _ sarcastically wished her good luck.
``Perhaps she got tired of arguing her convictions and standing up
for what's right,'' said state Sen. Martin Connor of Brooklyn, the
Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   PATRONAGE BOSS OR BUFFER?
</P>
<P>
   When Eliot L. Spitzer was trying last fall to oust Dennis C.
Vacco as attorney general, he repeatedly characterized Vacco's
office as rife with Republican patronage. Now that Spitzer has the
job, he has gone out of his way to extol the accomplishments _ and
lack of political connections _ of his own management team.
</P>
<P>
   The officials whom Spitzer hired include two former U.S. Supreme
Court clerks, several former federal prosecutors, a former director
of the state Ethics Commission and others with similarly notable
resumes.
</P>
<P>
   But Spitzer has raised eyebrows with his choice for the deputy
attorney general overseeing regional offices _ Martin J. Mack, the
former chairman of the executive committee of the State Democratic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer contends that Mack is no patronage boss, but rather the
person who has basically been charged with telling local Democratic
chieftains who are seeking patronage jobs to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said he had been inundated with calls and letters from
local leaders seeking favors and had politely let them know that
politics would not play a role in hiring.
</P>
<P>
   The response, he said, has ranged from ``respectful silence, to
anger, to rather acrimonious letters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a political price, but it is one that I am
obviously going to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer added that Mack was a highly respected lawyer who had
held a number of prominent government jobs, including county
attorney and mayor of Cortland, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A PERPETUAL FUND RAISER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Re-election may be a long way off, the oaths of office having
just been uttered, but state politicians are already beginning to
raise money for their next campaigns. Gov. George E. Pataki, a
Republican, has a handful of events scheduled for the next few
months, with ticket prices up to $2,000, while the state
comptroller, H. Carl McCall, a Democrat, is having a party at
Tavern on the Green in late January, at $1,000 a person. If they
seek re-election, both men would next face New York voters in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Only a decade ago, the Albany campaign machinery would typically
go into hibernation after elections. These days, the campaign, or
at least the fund raising, never ends. Incumbents in particular try
to collect money early, in an effort to demonstrate their strength
and ward off challengers, a tactic that both Pataki and McCall
adopted for the 1998 races.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's spokeswoman, said he needed adequate
resources to promote his record. ``You certainly can't rely on the
press to get your message out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also presumably intends to use his campaign to pay for
some of his trips around the nation as he seeks more influence in
the Republican Party. He is expected to begin traveling in early
February.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, who are up for re-election in 2000, are also starting
to collect contributions. Several are sponsoring fund-raisers in
Albany in January and February, while the Legislature is in
session, to attract lobbyists and interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of states have banned such practices.
``These events are unethical and corrupting,'' said Blair Horner,
legislative director for the New York Public Interest Research
Group. ``In some ways, we have more of a fund-raising session than
we have a legislative session in Albany.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
