<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS SEE CHANCE TO BREAK UA STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although series records and early scores differ, two facts are
certain about Arizona State vs. Arizona in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ASU still leads the rivalry, 29-17 by its count and 31-22 by UA
records, even though the Sun Devils are on a 10-game, five-year
losing streak that covers both the Jacquie Hullah and Charli Turner
Thorne coaching eras.
</P>
<P>
   Maura McHugh was the coach when ASU last beat the Wildcats, in
front of a home crowd of 4,110 in February 1993, and its last win
in Tucson was earlier that season.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of a streak-buster at 1 p.m. today at McKale Center are
about as even as the team records _ ASU (7-6, 1-3 Pac-10), UA (6-7,
1-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as gettable as they've been since I've been here,''
Turner Thorne said.
</P>
<P>
   But winning on the road against a team with a gritty, veteran
backcourt that can exploit ASU's penchant for turnovers will not be
easy. Felecity Willis alone can bring the ferocity needed to win a
rivalry game and will test ASU guards Natalie Tucker and Kitch
Kitchen at every chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Kitch I recruited her to play against Willis,'' Turner
Thorne said. ``I told her to take a UA tape, check out No. 23 and
get ready to play her.''
</P>
<P>
   How the ASU starting guards hold up against Willis, Lisa
Griffith and Reshea Bristol probably will determine the outcome.
The Sun Devils committed 92 turnovers (to 58 for their opponents)
in losing their first three Pac-10 games. Not coincidentally, ASU
had seven fewer turnovers than Washington State in winning, 63-54.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working on our floor leadership with Natalie and
Shelly (Tom),'' Turner Thorne said. ``To get away from a few
players playing poorly so the whole team plays poorly. We've had
that in too many games.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker had 13 points, six assists and two turnovers against
Washington State compared with six points, three assists and 10
turnovers in an 86-54 loss to Washington two days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had to win that game (Washington State), and I made
myself concentrate the whole morning before on what I had to do,''
said Tucker, ranked fourth nationally in free-throw percentage
(92.9). ``I'm a young point guard, and I've had a few bad games
that people have seen (on tape). I know I can deal with the
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has the Pac-10's worst three-point defense (ASU is No.
1) and was smoked for 14 treys in an 87-77 loss to Washington
State.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will try to exploit that with Tom, the Pac-10
three-pointer percentage leader, Tucker, Georgie Lang and Kristine
Sand.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has the most experienced posts in juniors Rachel Holt (11.0
ppg, 5.8 rpg) and Sand (11.2, 4.0). But the Wildcats are getting
ample production from freshman Elizabeth Pickney (12.4, 6.2) and
junior-college transfers Tatum Brown (9.5, 5.2) and Angela Lackey
(12.4, 4.8).
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne is encouraged about about the return of 6-foot-3
freshman Theresa Jantzen from a fractured left foot and the
impending return of 6-2 freshman Leah Combs, who could be recovered
enough from stress fractures in both legs to return to practice
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to regroup a little bit with the injuries,'' Turner
Thorne said. ``My approach is to play well every game and be
competitive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
