<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GARBAGE-NEIGHBORHOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RED HOOK, PIERSIDE BRAWL WITH CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Benny Torres was working the phone in his insurance
office on Richards Street in Red Hook. A sign in the window
declared, ``Real Estate Coming Soon.'' Torres is a loyal son of Red
Hook, down to how he was born: at home in the nearby projects, not
away at some hospital. He just got his real estate license. Now he
has plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm opening up a second office,'' he said. ``People have heard
good things. They no longer shriek when you tell them you're in Red
Hook.''
</P>
<P>
   The city also has plans for this Brooklyn peninsula, and it's
making Torres shriek. Last month, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
proposed it as the site for a transfer station, where tons of
garbage would be packed onto barges daily. This came while Red Hook
residents were savoring the promise of housing and commercial
development after enduring years of blight from drugs, crime and
official neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Even in bad times, Red Hook residents refused to be bystanders.
In the mid-1990s, a group devised a blueprint for community renewal
that would have turned it from an urban stepchild into a maritime
village that capitalized on its assets, especially its spectacular
waterfront views. The plan was hailed by neighborhood advocates and
city officials. Some improvements began. But residents wonder if
they toiled in vain, because they fear that the landscape they
envisioned will be obliterated by trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has been paving the streets in Red Hook,'' said
Torres, 35. ``They just fixed up the pier on Coffey Street.
Inspectors came by last year and were giving summonses if people
had dirty yards. That's in direct contradiction to what the city is
planning. In one sense, they say they're trying to improve the
neighborhood. On the other hand, they're trying to destroy it by
bringing in a waste transfer station.''
</P>
<P>
   The revitalization plan was the work of advocates, merchants and
residents, and a major goal was to stop the proliferation of waste
transfer stations. ``We got together to fight it out and come up
with a cohesive plan, rather than spend the rest of our lives
fighting noxious uses,'' said Sue Peebles, who was on the
committee. ``We devoted years of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was approved by the Department of City Planning in 1996,
some changes were made at the city's insistence. Ms. Peebles said
the community had sought to rezone some industrial areas to
preclude transfer stations, but city officials reviewed the issue
in light of the impending shutdown of the Fresh Kills landfill,
which is forcing the city to find new ways to dispose of its trash.
The final plan concluded that ``it would be premature to adopt new
zoning regulations for waste-related businesses at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   There is truly a need for the city to dispose of its trash. And
residents in any neighborhood chosen for a transfer station will
tend to oppose it. But in Red Hook, the idea of receiving more
garbage makes them worry that their dreams will be delayed.
Besides, is this their thanks for having spent hours away from home
and work devising a plan?
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a very sad message to communities that would like to
have a certain amount of control over their destiny,'' said Craig
Hammerman, the district manager of Community Board 6, which
includes Red Hook. ``It sours them on the notion that government is
there to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the garbage plan still faces hearings and
reviews. Any actual proposal, they said, would be viewed in the
context of the community's planning efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barbara Longobardi, who worked on the Red Hook plan,
feels betrayed. ``It's like a shot to the heart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This neighborhood knows about shots. Bullets cut down Patrick
Daly, the principal of Public School 15, in 1992, and focused the
city's attention on Red Hook. During the American Revolution, it
was home to Fort Defiance, whose memory persists in a community
garden by that name that juts out into New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It played a role in the Battle of Brooklyn,'' said John
McGettrick, a co-chairman of the Red Hook Civic Association. ``It
should be noted that the Battle of Brooklyn was a rout for our
side. But we came back to win the war.''
</P>
<P>
   McGettrick vowed to rally his neighbors in the garbage war,
which he insisted was not over. ``People continually underestimate
the residents of this community,'' he said. ``This is one more time
when they're going to be proven wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
