r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-COHN-NOTEBOOK-AZR     01-16 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COHN-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 RACE LOOKING AS IF IT'LL BE WACKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To update Forrest Gump, life's a lot like Pac-10 basketball. You
never know what you're going to get.
</P>
<P>
   We're not even finished with the third week of the season, and
already the needle on the wacky-o-meter is well into the red area.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: On Thursday in front of more than 13,000 fans going
bonkers at Wells Fargo Arena, Arizona beat Arizona State by one
point when  &UR; Eddie
 &UR; House's &UR; jumper bounced off the rim . . . and it wasn't even the
best game of the night.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Oregon 87, Washington State 83 in triple-overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Oregon won because it was on the road. The Ducks, who
won at California two weeks ago, returned home and dropped a pair
to Southern California and UCLA, by a total of three points.
Oregon's last three games have been decided by one point, two
points and in triple-overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And how about ASU? The Sun Devils are 2-3 in the Pac-10, the
losses coming to USC on the road by 2, to UCLA on the road by 3 in
overtime and to Arizona by 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, parity means mediocrity. But in the Pac-10, parity
means unprecedented balance and outcomes you can't predict with a
crystal basketball. Last week, Oregon State, which is supposed to
be one of the league's doormats, swept USC and UCLA at home.
Washington, picked to finish in the top three, started 0-3 before
beating Oregon State on Thursday. Of the 23 conference games played
to date, 12 have been decided by three points or less or in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The only parity-proof team is Stanford, which just might go
unbeaten in the conference. Although you shouldn't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a dogfight for second through whatever in the
league,'' Arizona Coach  &UR; Lute Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Stanford has shown they have the depth and the
experience and the ability and the size, and everything else you
need to have. If they lose, it'll be a surprise to pretty much
anybody. And I think the rest of us are going to keep banging away
and teams are going to lose, especially in road situations.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for an early coach of the year candidate, try
Oregon State's  &UR; Eddie Payne. After  &UR; Corey Benjamin left early for
the NBA draft and
 &UR; John-Blair Bickerstaff and  &UR; Ron Grady transferred, the Beavers were
presumably hard-pressed to match last year's three Pac-10
victories.
</P>
<P>
   But guard  &UR; Deaundra Tanner is an emerging star, everybody else
knows their roles, and they all listen well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people know about Oregon State, and consequently
they're surprised we're able to win,'' Payne said. ``But what they
don't know is, they don't know these guys. I don't think I've ever
had a group of players quite like this team, in terms of approach,
attitude, character and focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best group of guys I've had in terms of working to
get better and responding to coaching.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Not chopped liver &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maryland got a commitment from an unusual player and made an
unusual commitment in return.
</P>
<P>
   The player is  &UR; Tamir Goodman, a 6-foot-3 guard who is a junior
at Baltimore's Talmudical Academy, an all-boys school for Jewish
students.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Goodman is a junior. He won't enroll at Maryland
until fall 2000. But he's been a lifelong Terrapins fan and besides
that, he can play, even though this is just his second season of
organized basketball.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Baltimore Sun,'' Terps assistant  &UR; Billy Hahn
saw Goodman at a summer camp and recommended him to Coach  &UR; Gary
Williams. But what really sold Williams was a tape that showed
Goodman flashing an array of no-look, behind-the-back passes, dunks
and 25-foot jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one catch. As an Orthodox Jew, Goodman, who is
expected to grow to 6-6, cannot play between sunset Friday until
sunset Saturday to observe the Sabbath. But Williams has told
Goodman's coach that he will schedule around that, and ask the
Atlantic Coast Conference to do the same. &QL;  &QL; 
Declawed &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati finally lost, 62-60, at North Carolina-Charlotte on
Thursday, thanks to an inspired effort by the home team, something
less than that by the visiting Bearcats and a strange play at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   With 17.3 seconds left, and NC-Charlotte up by two, 49ers guard
 &UR; Diego
 &UR; Guevara missed the front end of a 1-and-1. His teammates thought a
two-shot foul had been called and didn't try for the rebound. But
Cincy's  &UR; Melvin
 &UR; Levett did. He grabbed the ball, dribbled downcourt and hit a
three-point basket.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the officials had blown the whistle and the shot was
waved off. Later, lead official  &UR; Tom O'Neill said it was an
``inadvertent'' whistle, meaning Levett's shot should have counted.
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats took the ball out of bounds and still had a chance,
but  &UR; Kenyon
 &UR; Martin missed a 1-and-1 with 3.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Levett took the loss like a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't cry about (the officials' mistakes),'' he told the
``Cincinnati'' ``Post.'' ``Those guys played a great game, and we
didn't meet their emotion at the beginning of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cincy Coach  &UR; Bob Huggins, ``They led the whole game. They
played better than us. . . . We had absolutely no enthusiasm. It's
like we're going to just show up and win, and that's not the
case.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Big win &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a start that earned mention on many ``most disappointing''
lists, Tennessee might have turned things around with a 47-46
victory over Kentucky, at Rupp Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first win at Kentucky in 20 years for Tennessee, a
preseason top 10 team according to many, but which hadn't seemed to
get over its season-opening loss to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols won ugly, but who cares? Tennessee shot 30.4 percent
from the floor, Kentucky 30.9 percent. Both were season lows.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, the first team to outrebound Kentucky this season,
had lost its past 11 games to the Wildcats, and had come within
single-digits just four times in the road losses.
</P>
<P>
   Putting it in perspective, Vols guard  &UR; Brandon Wharton said,
``You know what this is like? It's just like the football team
beating Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UCLA reserve guard  &UR; Rico Hines is expected to miss four to six
weeks after suffering a broken foot. He actually suffered the
injury several weeks ago, but kept playing. Hines was averaging 3.3
points and 2.1 rebounds in 16 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Coach  &UR; Billy Donovan and South Carolina's  &UR; Eddie
 &UR; Fogler, who are feuding because of Fogler's comments about
Donovan's recruiting, hid their feelings before the two teams
played, shaking hands and smiling. Then Florida went out and beat
the Gamecocks, 68-51.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State scored its fewest points at home in 30 years in a
54-43 loss to rival Oklahoma. It also was the Cowboys' lowest
points-total in any game since 1976. Oklahoma Coach  &UR; Kelvin Sampson
used a variety of defenses and credited his players with executing
them. Oklahoma State Coach  &UR; Eddie Sutton said, ``It was a screwy
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the game was on ESPN, Texas Christian's victory over
Southern Methodist ended after 1 a.m. That was fine with TCU
forward  &UR; Lee
 &UR; Nailon, who said, ``I'm usually getting my second wind at around
11.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
