<HEADLINE>
TWO STARS ENJOY THE POND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Wild Wing must look like a bull's eye to Mike
Modano and Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The popular beak-faced mascot that sits upon the chest of the
Mighty Ducks of Anaheim has brought nothing but good luck to two of
the Stars' biggest stars. And last night was no exception as Modano
and Belfour led the Stars to a 3-1 victory before 17,150 quacking
fans at the Arrowhead Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Modano had three points to raise his points per game average
against the Ducks to 1.6 in his career _ his highest against any
NHL team. And Belfour stopped 27 shots to tally his 12th win in 16
career appearances against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour now is 12-3-1 lifetime against the Ducks with a 1.42
goals against average. While he did much of that damage to Duck
pride with the Chicago Blackhawks, he fits in perfectly with the
Stars, who now are 16-3-1 in their past 20 meetings with the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The game was just the medicine the tired Stars needed as they
ended a five-game road trip, their longest of the season, with a
2-2-1 record. With Joe Nieuwendyk (knee) and Jamie Langenbrunner
(shoulder) out of the lineup and playing their third road game in
four nights, the Stars gave a gritty, hustling effort that pushed
their NHL-best record to 27-7-7 at the season's 41-game midpoint.
They are now 10 points ahead of their nearest Western Conference
competition, the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   With 61 points, the Stars are on pace for a 122-point season,
which would shatter last season's franchise record of 109 points.
Through 41 games last season, the Stars were 25-9-7, good for 57
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, one of the Stars Pacific Division rivals, fell to
16-18-8.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they had Wednesday in San Jose, the line of Modano,
Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen gave the Stars an early cushion.
Lehtinen picked up a loose puck in the nuetral zone, pushed into
the offensive zone and fired a hot slap shot from the left point.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks goalie Guy Hebert made the first stop, but then had to
slap a loose rebound away from a hard charging Hull. However,
Hebert's poke check went right to Modano, who scored from 20 feet
at the 5:27 mark for his 15th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen them made it 2-0 at the 13:11 mark of the first period
with his 15th goal of the season. Hull picked off an errant
clearing pass from the Ducks' Teemu Selanne and fed Modano, who
found Lehtinen in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   What was billed as a head-to-head battle of two of the best
lines in the NHL _ Selanne, Steve Rucchin and Paul Kariya vs. Hull,
Modano and Lehtinen _ was quickly over. Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg
started to play his role players more as the Stars had won a mental
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour then started what would become a key insurance goal in
the second period. With the Ducks short-handed and making a line
change, Belfour quickly fed a dump-in back to Sergei Zubov in the
neutral zone. Zubov pushed the puck ahead to Modano and Modano fed
Mike Keane flying into the slot behind a confused Ducks' team.
</P>
<P>
   That power play goal made it 3-0, and Belfour closed the door
the rest of the way, losing his shutout (he already has six against
the Ducks) when Fredrik Olausson scored a power play goal at the
8:50 mark of the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
