<HEADLINE>
TYSON GETS VOTE OF CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _  &UR; Tommy Brooks has a new corner. And a very different
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   As &UR; Evander Holyfield's assistant trainer, Brooks once suggested
that no cornerman could halt the deterioration of Mike Tyson, 0-2
against Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   But, today, Brooks says Tyson would prevail in a third bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson beats Holyfield,'' Brooks said this week as he prepared
his new fighter for &UR; Frans Botha tonight at the MGM Grand. ``Mike
still has the speed and he still has the power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference this time is that he has a corner. In the past
two fights, his old corner just told him to knock Evander out. But
they didn't tell him how. They just thought Evander was a washed-up
fighter with one arm and one eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was annoyed when Brooks' comment reached him in
Houston, where he is training for his March bout with  &UR; Lennox
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he said that, it's just because he wants to take the
money,'' Holyfield said. ``I don't know if he really believes it.
But if that fight ever comes about, he can't win. If Mike loses,
Brooks gets fired.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The schedule &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opening bell for Tyson-Botha is expected between 9 p.m. and 9:30
p.m. (Arizona time), according to Showtime, the pay-per-view
network that will telecast the card.
</P>
<P>
   The televised portion of the undercard is scheduled to begin at
7 p.m. with Brooklyn junior-welterweight &UR; Zab Judah (18-0, 13 KOs)
against Puerto Rican
 &UR; Wilfredo Negron (17-3, 14 KOs) for the International Boxing
Federation title.
</P>
<P>
   Two other title fights are scheduled. In one, Puerto Rican
junior-lightweight  &UR; Jojn John Molina (45-5, 30 KOs) challenges IBF
champ  &UR; Roberto
 &UR; Garcia (31-0, 24 KOs) of Oxnard, Calif. In the other, Mexican
lightweight &UR; 
 &UR; Goyo Vargas (38-6-1, 28 KOs) faces African &UR; Ben Tackie (18-0, 11
KOs) for a fringe Continental title sponsored by the World Boxing
Council. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Also in the ring &QL; 
 &QL; 
With  &UR; Mills Lane in retirement and presiding over a made-for-TV
courtroom, veteran &UR; Richard Steele draws the referee assignment for
Botha-Tyson.
</P>
</TEXT>
