<HEADLINE>
AN UNLIKELY ALLY FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert,
weighed in Friday on the timing of the State of the Union address,
saying President Clinton should deliver his speech as planned on
Tuesday even though the Senate is in the middle of his impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are extraordinary times,'' Hastert said. ``The president
is on trial in the Senate, facing serious charges regarding perjury
and obstruction of justice. Some have said we should simply cancel
the State of the Union speech, given the discomfort surrounding the
president's trial in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his aides have said he would stick to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, Hastert said, should go ahead with the address, ``out
of respect for the Office of the presidency and for a desire to
hear about the state of the union.''
</P>
</TEXT>
