<SLUG> BC-BBC-UTAH-ARI-Z </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU PUTS WOOD TO SLOPPY UTAH  
 14 WALKS HELP HIT TING ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ital)Crack.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Crack?
</P>
<P>
   The ping that has defined college baseball was replaced by the
crack of wooden bats Friday night when Arizona State and Utah
opened their seasons at Packard Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pac-10 has agreed to the use of a modified aluminum
bat for the 1999 season, unresolved indemnity issues involving bat
manufacturers, the NCAA and member schools prompted ASU to go with
wood Friday. It didn't seem to make a difference. The Sun Devils
pounded 12 hits and rolled to a 17-4 victory over the Utes in front
of 1,150 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are one of the few teams in the country that
practice with wooden bats, and it paid off. Third baseman Andrew
Beinbrink led the way, going 4 for 5 with four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Williamson (1-0), a transfer from Northwestern, replaced
Chad Pennington after 5 innings to pick up the victory. He allowed
no runs or hits and struck out two.
</P>
<P>
   The Utes struggled on the mound throughout, allowing 12 hits and
issuing 14 walks. Troy Beckman (0-1) was tagged with the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ASU jumped out to a 1-0 lead in the first on back-to-back
doubles by Jay Sitzman and Beinbrink. Utah tied it up in the second
after Mike Wood walked and came home on a single by Adam Castleton.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils asserted themselves in the third and received a
little help from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   After Dustin Delucchi reached first on a throwing error by Utes
pitcher Troy Beckman, Willie Bloomquist, ASU's walk leader last
season, drew another. Both scored on Beinbrink's hit up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Sitzman got on base when Utah left fielder Jed Chrisman bobbled
a fly ball and later scored on another error. Casey Myers'
groundout brought home Beinbrink, and ASU had a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wood made it 5-2 in the fourth after scoring on Chrisman's base
hit.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sun Devils didn't let up.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Duncan singled and scored on Mark Ernster's base hit.
Delucchi, who reached first on a walk, and Ernster scored on
Bloomquist's single to left. Beinbrink logged his fourth RBI of the
game with a hit to left that drove in Bloomquist, increasing ASU's
lead to 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   After the Utes added another two in the fifth, the Sun Devils
replaced Pennington with right-hander Williamson. He retired Utah
on a pop-up and a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Scott Goodman, a transfer from Cuesta College,
gave Williamson a little more cushion with a triple in the fifth
inning. He scored on Jeff Phelps' sacrifice fly to center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils added five in the sixth. Bloomquist and Sitzman
drew walks and scored on another error by Chrisman and a passed
ball, respectively. Brendan Hines came home on a double by Goodman,
who was pushed home on a walk by struggling pitcher Brandon
Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, E.J. Martinez, couldn't do much better and
walked home Phelps. ASU's lead increased to 15-4. &QL; 
Notes
</P>
<P>
   Among the fans in attendance was former ASU pitcher Ryan Mills,
who was a first-round draft pick by the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of a new scoreboard at Packard Stadium will get
under way Monday and is expected to be completed by the team's next
homestand, beginning Jan. 29. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
