<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE DEFENSE PROVES EQUAL TO TASK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar probably couldn't bear
to watch the closing moments of the 31-point loss at Gonzaga last
week, the worst defeat in five years for the Waves.
</P>
<P>
   But he liked what he saw against Santa Clara on Friday night, at
home and in a game that was crucial to the team's West Coast
Conference title and NCAA Tournament hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves forced 23 turnovers and forced the Broncos into 40
percent shooting from the floor in a 67-56 win in front of 2,238 at
Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with our guys' intensity,'' Romar said
after Pepperdine improved to 2-1 in the WCC and 11-7 overall. ``Our
guys fought hard. . . . It was a game that we had to win. To be
honest, we have to win the rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzaga loss included a stretch at the end of the first half
when the Waves were outscored 20-4. This time, Pepperdine didn't
fall into a lapse like that, even though it took the Waves 3{
minutes to score their first point of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, Santa Clara (6-9, 2-1) was dictating the pace.
It was 11-8 when Pepperdine reserve guard Tezale Archie, a 6-foot-1
junior, came off the bench and immediately made a 3-pointer that
set the tone for the rest of his night.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 13 points and was just as valuable on defense, getting
a team-high five steals in only 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a role and that's mine, to come off the bench and
provide a spark,'' Archie said. ``I was playing in passing lanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Romar said Archie ``played a large part toward winning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tezale Archie gave a great lift for us,'' he said. ``We expect
him to do that. He was exceptionally quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie broke his left pinky finger in Pepperdine's second game
of the season and was sidelined for a month.
</P>
<P>
   He's been a key player since he came back in late December.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Archie) brings a lot of energy to the team,'' said Jelani
Gardner, Pepperdine's leading scorer who had 20 points Friday
night. ``He can pressure the point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara coach Dick Davey was impressed with the Waves' team
defense. Pepperdine made 12 steals and blocked seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give Lorenzo credit,'' Davey said. ``He's gotten
his defense to the level where they can play with almost anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine hosts the University of San Francisco tonight at 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
