<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5815 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-CHOICE-LADN     01-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-CHOICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. PANEL OKS CABLE DEAL; LEAVES ONLINE ACCESS ISSUE UNRESOLVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Under ferocious lobbying from giant companies,
the Los Angeles city commission on technology Friday approved
AT&AMP;T's takeover of east San Fernando Valley cable television
service without deciding whether consumers should have open access
to the Internet service provider of their choice on cable.
</P>
<P>
   The board's indecision leaves it to the City Council to decide
-- with national Internet, telephone and cable companies watching
closely -- whether consumers have to pay a premium for cable online
services of their choice or whether cable operators have a
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The city Information and Technology Board agreed to transfer the
Van Nuys, Calif., franchise of cable giant Tele-Communications Inc.
to joint possession of TCI and AT&AMP;T, which are in the process of
merging. They are not required to provide access to other Internet
providers until a federal state or local government adopts a
regulation demanding such open access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city in this case got the best of all possible worlds,''
said board president Alan Arkatov. ``We were excited about bringing
AT&AMP;T in as a partner while keeping the promise of the Internet,
which means nondiscriminatory access.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to use the cable system to deliver not only
television programming, but high-speed Internet access 100 times
faster than telephone connections provide. That would allow
downloading of complex graphics and videos in just seconds, instead
of the minutes it now takes for most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan said he received calls on the issue from
top executives at AT&AMP;T and America Online. While he declined to
take a position before the decision, he said through a spokesman
that he was pleased at the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor wants to make it known that he applauds the action
of the board today,'' said Assistant Deputy Mayor Juan Pittman.
``AT&AMP;T is a terrific company and we're proud to have them as part
of our franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   As AT&AMP;T completes its merger plans, it must individually request
cable franchises from each city in which it operates -- giving
local governments an unprecedented chance to shape
telecommunications law.
</P>
<P>
   However, that law remains a murky area. Neither federal nor
local laws precisely define what kind of access cable companies
must provide to other online providers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While other Internet providers say they want to plug into AT&AMP;T's
cable modem platform -- the hardware of its cable network -- AT&AMP;T
says they can only access it indirectly through the AT&AMP;T online
service.
</P>
<P>
   If consumers want cable Internet access but still want to use
America Online or another service provider, they must pay
separately for both services.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T argued that the cable lines are inextricably linked to its
Internet service, Home, making it technologically infeasible for
numerous Internet service providers to directly connect to the
cable system.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from AOL, GTE and other companies countered that it's
clearly possible for AT&AMP;T to provide direct cable access to other
Internet service providers, ensuring less expensive and more
diverse high-speed Internet access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The board decision leaves open that disagreement -- requiring
the company to comply with all laws regarding ``nondiscriminatory
access'' -- but declining to set those laws itself.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the board resolved to complete a study within 180 days
on a citywide policy for online cable access.
</P>
<P>
   The board's decision will go to a City Council committee on Jan.
21, and then to the full council.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides declared satisfaction at the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased they recommended the approval of the transfer,''
said Lois Hedg-peth, AT&AMP;T's president of operations in the pacific
western states. ``They approved the transfer with no regulations or
rules that we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   George Mihlsten, an attorney for America Online, was jubilant
that the agreement requires compliance with future laws. He said
he's confident the FCC or the city itself will soon require AT&AMP;T to
allow other online providers to directly access its cable system.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is now required to comply with any local, state or
federal requirements on open access,'' he said. ``That is
historic.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
