<HEADLINE>
CONTRACTS OF CARDS ASSISTANTS EXTENDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis becomes head coach of
the Chicago Bears, the Cardinals' staff will come back intact.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Bill Bidwill has extended the contracts of eight assistant
coaches whose deals expire next month, ``The Republic'' has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the team said Bidwill gave two-year contracts
with ``significant raises'' to quarterbacks coach Geep Chryst,
running-backs coach Johnny Roland, wide-receivers coach Vic Rapp,
McGinnis, defensive-line coach Joe Greene, linebackers coach Glenn
Pires, secondary coach Larry Marmie and special-teams coach Alan
Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Three other assistants _ offensive coordinator Marc Trestman,
offensive-line coach George Warhop and tight-ends coach Hank
Kuhlmann _ already were under contract, having just completed their
first years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very important,'' one Cardinals assistant said.
``There are a lot of (coaching) jobs open, and we didn't want to
lose anybody. We've got a great thing going on here. Everybody's
excited, and it's only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals recently completed their first winning season
(10-8) since moving to Arizona in 1988. They advanced to the
playoffs for the first time in a non-strike year since 1975, and
the franchise won its first playoff game in 51 years by beating
Dallas, 20-7, in an NFC wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   The eight assistants' new contracts will expire at the same time
as head Coach Vince Tobin's, which has two years remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the assistants _ McGinnis, Rapp and Greene _ were
scheduled to leave today for the Senior Bowl college all-star game
in Mobile, Ala. The rest of the staff is expected to go to the
Senior Bowl on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Cardinals' personnel department spent the
past few days in the Bay Area scouting players at East-West Shrine
Game workouts.
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis, meanwhile, appears to be one of five finalists for the
Bears' job.
</P>
<P>
   The others are Buffalo offensive coordinator Joe Pendry, Green
Bay offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis, Jacksonville defensive
coordinator Dick Jauron and Pittsburgh offensive coordinator Jim
Haslet.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists will meet with Bears President Michael McCaskey
next week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
