<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS_ANDERSON-DAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING OUT OF A BIG CROWD  
 TYSON SECURITY CHIEF GIVES NFL SON AN EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It's probably no coincidence that Atlanta Falcons
running back Jamal Anderson knows how to follow his blockers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's dad has been leading people through some of sports'
toughest crowds all his life.
</P>
<P>
   James Anderson is chief of security for Mike Tyson. He also has
worked for Sugar Ray Leonard, Donna Summer, the Jacksons and Boyz
II Men. But his biggest job was for Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a training class with the New York Police Department
and was assigned to Ali,'' James Anderson said this week as he
diligently kept an eye on all the security details in the
ever-present storm that has surrounded Tyson for tonight's fight
with Frans Botha at the MGM Grand. ``Once I worked with Ali, doors
started to open.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, there was Jamal, who had seven relatives all
named Uncle Muhammad while growing up.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, Jamal likes to call himself ``pretty.'' It's a word
Ali often used to describe himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's just Jamal adding it and then blaming it on Ali,''
said James Anderson, a 48-year-old native of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, James Anderson's interest and energies will be
divided. Tonight, he's working for Tyson. On Sunday, he'll be
watching his son as the Falcons play the Minnesota Vikings in the
NFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 1 a.m. flight from Las Vegas to Minneapolis on
Sunday,'' James Anderson said. ``It arrives in Minnesota at 6:30
a.m. I usually don't go to Jamal's away games. I'm superstitious,
and I don't want to break the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure I'll make the game.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, Anderson expects to watch it on a big-screen
television at Tyson's Las Vegas' home, which is up for sale. Tyson
calls himself one of Jamal's biggest fans. They almost grew up
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson used to come to our house all the time,'' Anderson said.
``They would keep keep in constant contact. They feed off each
other. What Jamal has achieved makes Mike want to get his title
back. Mike's comeback makes Jamal want to go to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his son's relationship with famous fighters, he never
was tempted by the fight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamal and his brother, Jay, used to travel with me to Sugar
Ray Leonard's fights,'' James Anderson said. ``The amazing thing is
that neither of them ever picked up a glove or ever showed an
interest in fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became aware of his athletic ability when he was about 6. He
just started running over people.''
</P>
<P>
   The only boxing-related skill is Jamal's jab-like stiff arm. Dad
takes credit for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he perfected it, eventually,'' James Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   A prediction?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson only had one. The security professional said he's
expecting an excellent fight.
</P>
<P>
   But the dad picks the Falcons, 34-31. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
