<SLUG> BC-OLY-ASU-WASH_GYMNASTICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS FLOOR WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overcoming four falls on balance beam with a dominating floor
exercise performance, sixth-ranked Arizona State beat No. 8
Washington, 193.15-192.25, in its gymnastics opener Friday night at
Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The meet was much like the 1998 Midwest Regional when ASU
started with three falls on uneven parallel bars yet qualified for
the NCAA Championships, finishing sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to do it that way,'' said Elizabeth McNabb, who
for a third consecutive season scored 9.95 on floor to complete the
comeback from a .55 deficit after three events. ``That's not the
best way for the team, but luckily we have a good floor lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils lost junior all-arounder Amy Shelton to a
dislocated left elbow in warm-ups. Washington (0-2) was without its
six-time All-America, Tiffany Simpson of Tempe, who has a stress
fracture in her leg that could require surgery and may require her
to take a redshirt season.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' other former Desert Devil, Amber Erdos of
Scottsdale, had a rough meet, falling on bars, one of her vaults
and beam. But it was a fall by Sidney Field, Washington's final
beam performer, at the end of her aerial series that gave ASU
enough room to extend its home winning streak to 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils scored no lower than 9.7 on floor, capped by McNabb's
near perfect routine to the music from Evita that she used last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a 10 sometime in my career,'' McNabb said. ``I'd
rather think team than I, but sometimes I wonder what they take off
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers Lea Carver and Rhonda Robinette as well as juniors
Michelle Hess and Elizabeth Reid, on her mount, fell on beam, more
than erasing ASU's .675 two-event lead. The Devils also had to
count a fall on bars as sophomores Becky Acker and Kim Skinner went
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that we won, but I'm most pleased with the
character our kids showed and that they stayed focused,'' ASU Coach
John Spini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we went up on floor, I said this is the same situation
you put my blood pressure in every year. Just do your job, and what
will be, will be.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ARIZONA STATE 193.15, WASHINGTON 192.25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VAULTING _ 1, tie, Michelle Hess, ASU, and Elizabeth Reid, ASU,
9.75; 3, tie, Leah Waaramaki, W, and Amber Erdos, W, 9.7.
</P>
<P>
   UNEVEN PARALLEL BARS _ 1, Elizabeth Reid, ASU, 9.85; 2, Wendy
Ellsberry, ASU, 9.825; 3, Lanna Apisukh, W, 9.775.
</P>
<P>
   BALANCE BEAM _ 1, Elizabeth McNabb, ASU, 9.85; 2, Lauren
Riesenman, W, 9.775; 3, Michelle Hess, ASU, 9.70.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOR EXERCISE _ 1, Elizabeth McNabb, ASU, 9.95; 2, Elizabeth
Reid, ASU, 9.875; 3, Lanna Apisukh, W, 9.85.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-AROUND _ 1, Lauren Riesenman, W, 38.925; 2, tie, Elizabeth
Reid, ASU, and Lanna Apisukh, W, 38.825. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
