<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-CAPPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE DOORSTEP  
 CLOSE LAST YEAR, CAPPS EYES BIGGER THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the John Force regime over? And if so, who next will occupy
the National Hot Rod Association Funny Car throne?
</P>
<P>
   Cruz Pedregon? Tony Pedregon?
</P>
<P>
   What about Ron Capps, who almost defrocked the seemingly
invincible Force last season, holding a 31-point lead entering the
homestretch before slipping to a career-high runner-up finish?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances, there's no getting around that,'' said
Capps, 33, who is entering his third season driving the Copenhagen
Racing Camaro owned by legendary Don ``Snake'' Prudhomme. ``(Force)
left the door open a little bit. We got through the door, but we
just couldn't get all the way through the door and shut it behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Force shut the door, collaring an unprecedented eighth
championship this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Although Capps captured the Big Bud Shootout all-star show
during the same U.S. Nationals weekend, he couldn't put away Force
when they met in the second round in the national event.
</P>
<P>
   And Force made Capps pay dearly for it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Capps stretching the tenuous lead, Force left
Indianapolis in front by 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Capps and Force again found themselves
staring at each other at the starting line. And, again, Force won
the showdown, defeating Capps in the semifinals and widening a
47-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was going so well at the U.S. Nationals,'' Capps
said. ``Even during the heat of the day, I was running good and
Force was smoking his tires every run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, right when (Force) and I met in the second, there was a
cloud cover. John ran a big time, and I had a $20 part go bad that
cost me the race. I truly believe we would have beat him if I had
had a clean run.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I guess that's why he's an eight-time champion. He stepped
up to the plate, pointed to the outfield and hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   End of story.
</P>
<P>
   And end of Capps.
</P>
<P>
   But a new season is approaching _ the Winternationals opener is
in three weeks, followed by the Checker/Schuck's/Kragen Nationals
on Feb. 25-28 at Firebird International Raceway Park _ and an
invigorated Capps is minus the cruel disappointment of letting a
possible title slip away.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Capps is encouraged he can do what only one other
driver this decade has been able to do, which is wear the Funny Car
crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could make excuses all day long about what happened last
year,'' said Capps, who credits Prudhomme's guidance and crew chief
Roland Leong's mechanical expertise for much of his progress. ``If
we wouldn't have all those first-round and second-round losses, we
would have had the consistency to beat Force. But we still had a
great year. It's just that John had a better year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year really teased us. It showed us we're destined to be
a championship team. The (crew) knows they have it in them to win
this thing. We know how much of a champion Force is, but we also
know we can run with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Force also knows his days may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Although he won three events last season, giving him 65 wins
since 1990, it was two less than Capps, and was Force's lowest win
total of the decade. Force won an incredible 13 races in 1996, the
season he was named motorsports' Driver of the Year, and was an
11-time winner in 1993 and won 10 more in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Until last season, the fewest he had won over the past nine
seasons was six. Even in 1992, when he finished second to Cruz
Pedregon, he won a season-high nine races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting tougher each year,'' Force said. ``The
competition isn't letting up. I knew that Snake was going to be
tough when he hired that kid, Ron Capps. I've got to keep an eye on
him. All he thinks is win. Those kind of guys get you on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how good he is. I tried to hire him, but Snake got him
first.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite Capps failing to protect a late-season lead,
Prudhomme is far from unhappy with his driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a terrific year,'' Prudhomme said. ``(But) now
our appetite has been whetted. We were busy during the winter.
We've developed a little sleeker Camaro body. We're always looking
for more downforce. We did a lot of development work over the
winter. We'll be running some new cylinder heads, and we're looking
forward to getting the new year started.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't have to wait long.
</P>
<P>
   Capps and several other teams will test next week in the John
Myers Winternationals Warm-ups at Southwestern International
Raceway in Tucson. The six-day event runs from Jan. 21-26.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several other pro teams will test Jan. 22-24 at the
Hot Rod magazine PRO National Time Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Capps hardly can wait to get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock for a lot the year last season,'' Capps said.
``We won the first race of the season and led the points for a long
time. Even when we fell back, we only fell back to third place.
It's not like we were ever out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that if we keep chugging along, we're going to be in
the hunt. We're just not going to take no for an answer this
year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
