<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARMIJO-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BET FARM ON 3-PEAT BY GORDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions, questions, questions. Now for some answers.
</P>
<P>
   Can  &UR; Jeff Gordon make it a NASCAR Winston Cup three-peat in
1999?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Put it this way. Take next month's rent, fly to Las
Vegas and put it squarely on Gordon's nose. The kid can't lose, can
he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon's team isn't going to get any worse, so the rest of us
have to get better,'' driver  &UR; Ken Schrader said this week during
the annual media tour hosted by Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Just how good do you have to be?  &UR; Mark Martin won a career-high
seven races and still was a speck in Gordon's rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be more side-by-side racing and a lot less
Gordon-Martin runaways?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Or, at least, let's hope so.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, NASCAR officials may have corrected the lack of door
to door racing, when at the final race of the season, they inserted
rules to increase downforce.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet is unveiling a new Monte Carlo this season, most
likely at the Coca-Cola 600 in May at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
What's the early report card?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one is saying.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's anything like the 1995 Monte Carlo that replaced the
Lumina, the Chevy contingent will do cartwheels down pit road. The
'95 model was a killer machine right out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Childress Racing and Hendrick Racing have been privately
developing the car, testing it thus far at Daytona International
Speedway and Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Top rookie?
</P>
<P>
   A:  &UR; Tony Stewart, Elliott Sadler and  &UR; Buckshot Jones are getting
all the headlines, but don't forget  &UR; Mike  &UR; Harmon and  &UR; Dan Pardus
also are rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, scratch Harmon and Par dus.
</P>
<P>
   Now scratch Jones, whose aggressiveness gets him into too much
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart may be the most talented but, like Jones, he is working
with a rookie crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   Why put a rookie driver with a rookie crew chief?
</P>
<P>
   At least, Stewart won't have to go at it alone. Unlike Jones, he
has a teammate in  &UR; Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Rookie of the Year nod goes to Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler not only has respected crew chief  &UR; Mike Beam and the vast
experience of the Wood Brothers team to drawn upon, he also has
owner's provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Stewart do not.
</P>
<P>
   Next question, please.
</P>
<P>
   Will any racetracks currently on the Cup schedule receive a
coveted second date in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   A: No,  &UR; Bruton Smith. A thousand times, no.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose profitable Speedway Motorsports Inc. owns several
racetracks, include Texas Motor Speedway and Las Vegas Motor
Speedway, believes NASCAR would do itself a huge favor by granting
second races to Texas and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Texas and Las Vegas draw huge crowds. But so do California
Speedway and Phoenix International Raceway, which, by the way,
aren't going to receive second race dates, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not going to happen, no matter how many facilities
Smith puts in SMI's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The next racetrack to get a date will be Kansas City, and it
isn't even built.
</P>
<P>
   Barring splitting the circuit into an American and National
League, which Smith has been promoting and NASCAR has been shooting
down, Smith believes there is room for four more additions to the
current 34-race schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith believes two divisions is the answer to ``curing the
saturation.''
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's utopia, one circuit would be in the eastern United
States and one in the western. Two races would be held on the same
day in a doubleheader format.
</P>
<P>
   One question: What happens when one section of the country gets
Gordon and one doesn't? Or one gets Earnhardt and the other
doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   And, finally: NASCAR celebrated its 50th anniversary last
season. Where will the sport be 50 years from now?
</P>
<P>
   A: In Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be there in 2020,'' Charlotte Motor Speedway
President
 &UR; Humpy Wheeler said. ``It's going to become an international sport.
I think Mercedes and BMW are going to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have 20 races in this country and 10 races overseas in
Europe, the Far East and Australia. I just don't think you can keep
this sport in this country. Too popular.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly ... &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next November,  &UR; Dale Earnhardt Jr., will make his inaugural
appearance at Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   In a NASCAR Busch Grand National race, not Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt will appear in five Winston Cup races this season, but
none is scheduled at PIR. Earnhardt's debut will be in the May 30
Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Other Cup starts will be at New Hampshire (July 11), Michigan
Speedway (Aug. 22), Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway (Oct. 17) and
the season finale at Atlanta Motor Speedway (Nov. 21).
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt will drive the No. 8 Budweiser Chevrolet, which is the
same number his father and late grandfather drove in late models
and sportsman racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special number in our family,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``I
feel honored to be the next one to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robby Gordon has formed his own team to compete in the
Championship Auto Racing Teams circuit, driving a Toyota-Swift.
Gordon also will enter the Indianapolis 500 in a car owned by  &UR; John
Menard, a minority owner in Gordon's CART team.
</P>
<P>
   CART and Indy Racing League teams have been sharing PIR lately
in test sessions. Unconfirmed reports are the IRL cars have posted
better speeds. At one test, IRL's  &UR; Scott Goodyear was four-tenths
of a second quicker than  &UR; Michael Andretti. Andretti, however, was
equipped with the smaller, lower-downforce rear wings that curb
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   In a unique sponsorship arrangement, Sara Lee will sponsor
 &UR; Derrike  &UR; Cope this season.
</P>
<P>
   Four brands of meat products will rotate primary sponsorship
throughout the 34-race season. Derrike Cope will drive the State
Fair Corn Dogs No. 30 Pontiac at PIR.
</P>
<P>
   The first ontrack confrontation between  &UR; Jeff Gordon and
Earnhardt Jr. is a Busch race scheduled March 28 at Texas Motor
Speedway. A spokesman for Dale Earnhardt Inc., however, said it
will happen earlier, but wouldn't elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you've rented a blimp, Indianapolis 500 and Brickyard 400
spectators at Indianapolis Motor Speedway are prevented from having
an unobstructed view of the gargantuan oval. In fact, some road
courses provide better fan viewing. IMS President  &UR; Tony George,
however, finally is doing something he should have done long ago. A
tentative agreement recently was reached with a South Dakota
company to install seven large television screens around the
2.5-mile oval. Just don't turn the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Feb. 1, Phoenix-based Action Performance Inc. will
introduce SpeedMall, a virtual shopping mall featuring motorsports
and other automotive-related products and services on the Internet.
The site's address is www.goracing.com.
</P>
<P>
   Former Indy 500 chief steward  &UR; Tom Binford died Thursday. He was
74.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greg Moore is the cyberspace choice to win the Championship
Auto Racing Teams title. A total of 43,232 visitors to the CART Web
site cast ballots, and 36.8 percent picked Moore.  &UR; Jimmy Vasser
(23.9 percent) was next, followed by  &UR; Paul Tracy (7.9),  &UR; Dario
Franchitti (7.6) and  &UR; Michael
 &UR; Andretti (6.5).
</P>
<P>
   The American Motorcyclist Association Cruise America Superbike
Challenge is March 20-21 at PIR. But the festivities continue
throughout the next week with several special events encompassing
the Arizona Motorcycle Rally, including the All Harley Drag Racing
Association Pure Steel Nationals at Speedworld Motorplex. Call
970-3757 for more information. &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
