<HEADLINE>
MONEY MAKES DIFFERENCE  
 FULL SPONSORSHIP HAS GILLILAND RARING TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
 WEST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watch out for Butch Gilliland.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with more financial ammunition than ever before, Gilliland
is looking to bag a second NASCAR Winston West championship in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a full sponsorship program with Ralph's Food For
Less,'' said Gilliland, who despite three wins last season finished
No. 6 in the final standings behind champion Kevin Harvick. ``It's
the first time I've ever started a season with the proper funding
to really do the proper job that I've always wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an experienced crew, our equipment is top-notch and
I think we'll be a contender at every racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilliland, 40, shouldn't have any problems in Sunday's season
opener at Tucson Raceway Park. Gilliland is the defending champion
and also holds the one-lap qualifying mark at 88.328 mph. In a
seven-race span between 1993 and 1996, Gilliland captured five of
the seven pole positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fast ever since the first time I raced (at
Tucson),'' said Gilliland, who won the '97 title with the aid of
four wins and 10 top-five finishes in 14 starts. ``It was like a
natural thing for us to run good.''
</P>
<P>
   And, naturally, Gilliland hopes to add to that record against
the likes of Lance Hooper, the 1996 champion, and 1994 titlist Mike
Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Other former champions entered include Bill Sedgwick (1991-92)
and Rick Carelli (1993), who's expected to start in the RE/MAX
International Chevrolet owned by balloonist David Leniger.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, who lives in North Carolina, hasn't been a series regular
since winning the '94 crown, but he plans a full-time effort in
1999. He made three starts last season and none in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   Harvich recently signed a contract to drive on the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series and won't defend his title.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Burns of Phoenix will return. Burns finished 12th in
last year's standings.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, appears to be looking forward to the season
more than Gilliland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to run one more year of Winston West, then try and
get a Winston Cup program going,'' said Gilliland, who lives in
Anaheim. ``But a lot depends on how well we do this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building four brand-new cars and we already have three
in our inventory. Two or three of the cars we'll use for five
Winston Cup races that we plan to enter.''
</P>
<P>
   The five scheduled Cup races are at Phoenix International
Raceway, Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Las Vegas Motor Speedway,
Sears Point, Calif., and Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   David Gilliland, 22, Gilliland's son, will drive the team's
second Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run him the whole season because he's a pretty good
driver,'' the elder Gilliland said. ``It just depends on whether we
can get some more sponsorship. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
