<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAKY DEFENSE SINKS NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOZEMAN, Mont. _ The despair is in their eyes, in the way their
mouths hang open and the way they gaze aimlessly around the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Defense is supposed to be the chore. It's work and not fun, and
right now the Matadors don't like to work very hard. And it's why
the Matadors had that look.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge came close, which it usually does, but the
inability to get key stops on defense resulted in an 87-82 loss to
Montana State in front of 5,011 Friday night at Worthington Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Matadors' third straight loss. Montana State is 8-0
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's defense,'' CSUN forward Rico Harris said. ``It's
frustrating me, but I keep a level head. This is a new experience
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also the usual offensive stagnation that burdens the
defense even more, and CSUN hit it again.
</P>
<P>
   When that time arrived, it was Montana State which was able to
work the shot clock down and hit open shots. They made 12 of 24
from 3-point range and shot 54 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore forward John Lazosky was the biggest benefactor. He
scored 21 points, breaking his career-high of 15 by halftime. And
though the Matadors, and foul trouble, kept the Big Sky's leading
scorer in Nate Holmstadt to 12 points, guard Danny Sprinkle had 22
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to play hard, but it's another thing to play
smart,'' CSUN coach Bobby Braswell said. ``Our guys were well aware
of who their shooters were and where we needed to have our bodies,
but as coaches you can't go out and play the game for them. And
that's the frustrating part.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (9-8, 1-4 Big Sky) was able to claw much of the way back
from a 13-point deficit with 15 minutes to play with pressure, but
never pulled even.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the half-court offense would either evaporate into
forced shots or end with a turnover. By contrast, Montana State
(8-7, 2-2) countered any CSUN challenge with crisp ball movement
and uncontested shots.
</P>
<P>
   It happened a few times, but none more crushing than in the
final minute. A 3-pointer by Greg Minor and a chippie from Derrick
Higgins brought CSUN within 78-75 with 1:30 left, the closest it
had been since the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Bobcats work the 35-second clock and get an
open 3-point attempt afterward, but Lazosky hit the shot to give
Montana State an 81-75 lead with 49 second remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep game fast-paced and not let the wide-open
dudes shoot like that,'' said Minor, who scored 16 points. ``That's
what hurt our chances. We're making a run and they just hit big
threes.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN's offensive lapse customarily begins with the second half,
but against the Bobcats it came a few minutes earlier. It allowed
the Bobcats to turn a two-point game into a 48-39 lead at the half
with a 9-2 run in the final 2:04.
</P>
<P>
   Most distressing was that Montana State built its lead without
the aid of the conference's leading scorer. Holmstadt played 10
minutes because of foul trouble, and in his absence Lazosky had the
half of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that same thing again,'' Braswell said. ``We come out
flat. We don't come out really getting after it. We get ourselves
out of a hole, and then we fight out of it. But every game we run
out of energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
