<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS LOSE TO DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks needed more than an improved work
ethic against the Dallas Stars -- they needed a another miracle.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1998 Anaheim scored twice in the final 38 seconds to
tie the Stars, but it was back to reality on Friday night against
the NHL's best team. Dallas dominated the Ducks in a 3-1 victory
before 17,150 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a better team in the league I would hate to see
it,'' said Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg. ``They are machine-like,
they don't make mistakes and if you make mistakes they make you
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who lead the league with 61 points, took full
advantage of three Ducks mistakes to take a 3-0 lead 70 seconds
into the in the second period and put Anaheim out of its misery
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make them earn their chances,'' said Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks beat the Stars the first three times the two teams
played back in the 1993-94, but the series has provided Anaheim
nothing but heartache since. Dallas is 16-3-1 in the last 20 games,
outscoring the Ducks 74-35 in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya, who along with Teemu Selanne, was contained by the
defensive duo of Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk, admitted
Anaheim might be intimidated by the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you play at home, you have to come out and
play your game, not worry about what they are doing,'' said Kariya,
who was the recepitant of several hard checks during the evening.
``I think we were watching and waiting too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg shuffled three of his four lines and dropped Travis
Green and Marty McInnis from the second line to the fourth, but the
changes became a moot point early on.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' energy level was up from Wednesday's loss to Calgary
-- ``that's not saying much,'' said Kariya. But Anaheim fell behind
when Guy Hebert couldn't control a rebound and then put an
ill-advised clearing pass on the stick of Mike Modano. The Dallas
center easily scored his 15th goal of the season into an empty net
at 5:27.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of three points on the night for Modano, who
has scored 31 points against the Ducks, the most by any oppossing
player.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas made it 2-0 at 13:11 when Ruslan Salei's attempted
clearing pass bounced off Brett Hull to Modano, who quickly fed
Jere Lethinen in the slot. Lehitnen scored his 15th goal by beating
Hebert high over the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always seem to start fast,'' said Anaheim defenseman
Fredrik Olausson. ``But that's no excuse for way we started. We
can't give them a 2-0 lead. They are too hard to comeback on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Ducks weren't done gift giving. With the Stars on the
power play, Dallas goalie Ed Belfour caught Anaheim on a line
change. Two quick passes later and Mike Keane had the puck alone
between the circles. The checking forward had plenty of time to tee
it up and beat Hebert at 1:10 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who improved to 12-3-2 with 1.42 goals against average
against the Ducks, nearly shutout Anaheim for the seventh time in
his career. But the Ducks, as has become the norm recently, were
able to manufacture some offense on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis centered a pass to Olausson cutting in front of Belfour
and the Ducks defenseman tucked in a backhander in for his ninth
goal of the season at 8:50 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   But five-on-five the Ducks could generate nothing, even though
they were outshot only 29-28.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said he'd love to see his team use Dallas an an
example.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have four lines that play the same way,'' he said.
``That's the kind of team we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Olausson agreed with his coach that you might as well pattern
yourself after the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to aim for perfection and Dallas is very close,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks also know they have a long way to go before they
are in the same class as the Stars, especially when it comes to
putting out a consistent effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the effort (Friday night), but not enough to beat a
team like that,'' said Hartsburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
