<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-AIRTOUCH-1STLEDE     01-16 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-AIRTOUCH-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VODAFONE BEATS OUT BELL ATLANTIC IN BID TO BUY AIRTOUCH
COMMUNICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 1st, 2nd,   3rd &AMP; 6th grafs to confirm sale and provide
financial and logistical details; Adds quote from Airtouch chairman
in 7th graf; subs 10th graf for clarification of Vodafone history;
Adds 2 grafs to end of original text for details of talks. )  (af)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vodafone Group PLC, Britain's largest mobile phone company, has
agreed to buy Airtouch Communications Inc. for more than $60
billion, edging out Bell Atlantic Corp. in a bidding war for the
nation's largest wireless company, the companies confirmed Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The combined entity, to be known as Vodafone Airtouch PLC, will
be the largest wireless telecommunications company in the world and
is being formed in one of the largest cross-border deals ever.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone sweetened its original cash- and-stock offer to $97 a
share, which includes giving Airtouch stockholders the equivalent
of half a Vodafone American depository receipt, plus $9 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, an on-again, off-again suitor of Airtouch, proposed to
buy the company after it was reported two weeks ago that Bell
Atlantic, the largest local phone company in the United States, had
been in talks to acquire Airtouch in a $45 billion stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch's board of directors met Friday to review the two
offers. Bell Atlantic's board of directors met Friday and, said a
person close to those talks, agreed to submit a higher offer than
the $45 billion originally offered, but that offer was rejected.
The higher offer was not disclosed. Bell Atlantic released a
statement Friday night saying it had ended its discussions with
Airtouch.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone and Airtouch will have an equal number of seats on the
board in the combined entity and senior management positions will
be equally shared. The chairman of Airtouch, Sam Ginn, is expected
to be named nonexecutive chairman of the combined entity. Chris
Gent, chief executive of Vodafone, will remain in that post.The
company will be based in Newbury, England, with U.S. operations in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vodafone Airtouch will have the size and financial resources
to take advantage of future opportunities,'' Ginn said.
</P>
<P>
   An Airtouch-Vodafone combination will create an international
powerhouse. The combined company will dominate throughout Europe.
Vodafone's customers outside Britain are largely in Northern
Europe, including Sweden, France, Germany and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch's European operations are mainly in the southern part
of the Continent, including Italy, Spain and Portugal. In all,
international wireless services make up 57 percent of Airtouch's
operating income, according to Deutsche Bank Research. The two
companies compete in Germany and are partners in ventures in both
Sweden and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Until now Vodafone had shunned the U.S. market. In fact, the
company had been in talks earlier this year with Airtouch about
acquiring its European assets. Since splitting from Racal
Electronics, a maker of telecommunications gear and military
electronics, in 1988, Vodafone has grown into Britain's largest
wireless carrier, with almost 5 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers are attracted to its prices. In the last quarter
of 1998 alone, for instance, the company added more than 930,000
customers, mostly on the attraction of a plan that allows users to
pay as they call, rather than sign a long contract.
</P>
<P>
   A merger with Bell Atlantic, which had been in talks with
Airtouch for some time and already has 5.7 million cellular
customers blanketing the East Coast, would have aided the local
phone company's desire to be a national presence. Bell Atlantic's
bid for Airtouch had the blessing of GTE Corp., which Bell Atlantic
plans to buy this summer in a $52.9 billion stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's offer for Airtouch came two weeks ago when the
company delivered a preliminary proposal to Airtouch over the
weekend of Jan. 3. Vodafone said it would consider buying the
company for stock worth about $90 a share plus $5 to $6 in cash.
The price was higher than Bell Atlantic's offer, which at the time
was valued at $45 billion. But Ginn had earlier said he liked the
Bell Atlantic currency.
</P>
<P>
   One of the holdups in the Bell Atlantic and Airtouch talks was
whether the companies could combine under favorable accounting
rules. If allowed, Bell Atlantic would have avoided hefty charges
on future reported earnings. These issues were resolved this week
when the two companies received word from the Securities and
Exchange Commission that it would approve a favorable accounting
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies expressed interest in Airtouch, including MCI
Worldcom, which talked to the company but did not make a formal
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch was advised by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. Vodafone was
advised by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
