<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-COMPENSATE (Washington) _ The United States and Germany
Friday announced a tentative agreement for the German government to
compensate an estimated 240 Americans who were imprisoned in Nazi
concentration camps. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   PERSIAN-GULF-OIL (Kuwait City) _ For a quarter century, oil has
allowed the gulf states a self-sufficiency and political leverage
far in excess of what comparably sized countries could hope to
achieve, and has formed a dependable pillar of legitimacy for the
region's six monarchies. But now revenues have plunged by 30
percent in a year, a loss of $25 billion. And there is no rebound
in sight. By Douglas Jehl. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IRAQ (United Nations) _ Russia, which is opposing any
revival of the present arms inspection system in Iraq, Friday gave
the Security Council a detailed blueprint for a new monitoring
apparatus having much less independence. It was the fourth proposal
this week as nations lay out their positions and try to influence
others. The bargaining could turn into a long debate if the
Security Council is to reach a common position. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTESTS (Beijing) _ Thousands of farmers demonstrating
against local officials clashed with hundreds of police officers in
a small town in southern China last week, the latest and perhaps
largest in a series of farmer and worker protests that have sprung
up around China in the last year. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-FEUD (Johannesburg) _ President Nelson Mandela and
former President F.W. de Klerk negotiated this country's peaceful
transition from white supremacist rule to democracy, then ruled for
two years as president and deputy president. In 1993, they shared
the Nobel Peace Prize. But after years of silence about the
relationship, de Klerk has unleashed his anger at Mandela. His
autobiography, which is to be published in London on Tuesday, reels
with it. By Suzanne Daly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STORM-BUFFALO (Buffalo) _ Even in a place that is proud to be
called the snow capital of America, enough is enough. Piles of snow
are so high in most places that houses and storefronts are barely
visible from the street. On Friday, Buffalo contended with its 14th
consecutive day of snow _ with levels approaching 60 inches and the
flakes still falling. ``Even people in Buffalo are getting pretty
sick of this snow,'' said Stacie Simmons, 31. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-WILSON (Los Angeles) _ For eight years in Sacramento, Pete
Wilson had to look no farther than the big portrait of Ronald
Reagan in his office to dream of what the future might hold for a
Republican governor of California. Now, in his second week as a
private citizen, Wilson has begun sharing an office suite here with
the former president himself, but the dream remains uncertain. By
Todd S. Purdham. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ No matter how much senators say
they want to avoid it, the partisan split over witnesses appears to
be hardening each day that the House managers present their case
against President Clinton, with a near party-line vote in favor of
taking more testimony looking ever more likely. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ In an opinion poll conducted last
month in 21 congressional districts around the country that tend to
swing between Republicans and Democrats, three-quarters of those
questioned said they agreed with the proposition that ``instead of
spending time on a lengthy impeachment trial, Congress and the
president should focus on issues and legislation important to
average families.'' So it is not surprising that as the trial of
Clinton began in earnest this week, Republican senators bent over
backward to make the point that they were also tending to the
people's business. By David E. Rosenbaum. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (New York) _ Likened to Martin Luther King and
doused with praise for his economic leadership, Clinton was
celebrated on Wall Street on Friday at a conference of mostly
minority businessmen as House prosecutors assailed him for a second
day before the Senate. By James Bennet. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STRATEGY (Washington) _ The House prosecutors appeared
close to asking the Senate to formally invite Clinton to testify in
his impeachment trial. By Eric Schmitt. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ Many of the Republican
Party's most influential financial backers have castigated the
party's chairman and congressional leadership at closed-door
meetings here in the past few days, warning that they were
sacrificing voters by failing to articulate a clear message while
focusing on scandal and impeachment. By Richard L. Berke. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The scene at the trial remained one
of great patience more then fresh sensation until an unexpected
moment late in the day when a senator dared to utter the very first
objection of the proceeding from the floor. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HARKIN (Washington) _ Sen. Tom Harkin interrupted the
GOP manager, Rep. Barr, and objected to being called a juror.
Rehnquist ruled in Harkin's favor. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   JAMA-SEXSURVEY (Undated) _ The American Medical Association
dismissed the editor of its leading journal, charging that he had
rushed through a paper on whether college students think oral sex
is ``having sex'' in order to influence President Clinton's
impeachment trial. The article, which will appear next week in the
Journal of the American Medical Association, describes an
eight-year-old study, which found that 59 percent of those surveyed
did not believe the act counted as sex. By Gina Kolata. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RDP (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agreed to judge the
validity of a federal law the Clinton administration says is needed
to protect compulsive gamblers from the lure of casinos and games
of chance. The justices said they would decide whether free-speech
rights are violated by the government's ban on television and radio
ads that promote casinos not owned by Indian tribes. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-HMOS (Washington) _ Medicare officials announced a new
way of paying HMOs that will punish those who avoid sicker patients
_ and reward those who enroll such sick people. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-RDP (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ Brazil abandoned its
efforts to defend its currency, allowing it to float freely.
Brazilian stocks shot up an astonishing 33 percent, its second-best
day ever. By Diana Jean Schemo. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-PRIMER (Undated) _ A Brazil crisis primer, written for
the general reader. By Sylvia Nasar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-IMF (Washington) _ Brazil got a muted but clear warning
from the International Monetary Fund and the United States Friday
that failure to act quickly on pledges to bolster its financial
condition through spending cuts and tax increases would lead to a
downward economic spiral. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-LATAM (Buenos Aires, Argentina) _ Stock markets
throughout Latin America rebounded strongly Friday on hopes that
Brazil's currency would not tumble out of control. But analysts
warned that several countries in the region faced a period of
extreme economic volatility, with the likelihood of devaluations,
rising interest rates and growing unemployment through the rest of
the year. By Clifford Krauss. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETWATCH.COM (Undated) _ In an indication that investors
remain manic for new Internet stocks, the price of Marketwatch.com,
operator of a popular financial news Web site, rose more than 573
percent Friday, its first day of trading. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   BELL-AIRTOUCH (Undated) _ Vodafone Group PLC, Britain's largest
mobile phone company, has agreed to buy Airtouch Communications
Inc. for more than $60 billion, edging out Bell Atlantic Corp. in a
bidding war for the nation's largest wireless company, according to
people close to the talks. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ We didn't need Larry Flynt to tell us
that Bob Barr is a hypocrite. But we may need Larry Flynt anyway _
not to expose any impeachment manager's sex life but simply because
his very presence exposes the disingenuousness of everybody else,
conservative and liberal, Republican and Democrat, press and
public, who inhabits the epic Bosch canvas that is Monicagate. In
the land of the pious hypocrite, the honest pornographer is king.
By Frank Rich.
</P>
