<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-16 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILT OR KAREEM? CHRIS OR MARTINA?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports fans, a compulsive lot, love their lists. The other day I
found myself standing in front of the rather forlorn-looking NBA
store on Fifth Avenue evaluating a montage of the alleged 50
greatest players in National Basketball Association history and
saying out loud, ``Jerry Lucas???''
</P>
<P>
   But that's all right. Most people in New York talk to
themselves, so nobody noticed.
</P>
<P>
   This is the ultimate year for lists _ the 100 greatest pastry
chefs of the 20th century, the 100 greatest math teachers of the
20th century, the 1,000 greatest people of the millennium. What,
they left off Jerry Garcia? You see what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a sports list that will keep people talking for the
entire year _ the ESPN rating of the 100 greatest North American
athletes of the century. Talk is cheap, lists are facile, but ESPN
did its homework, consulting a panel of experts who have lived a
good bit of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but ESPN has also hidden its Gen-X persona and
put on its journalistic hat (a fedora, in this case), producing a
documentary series called ``SportsCentury,'' including weekly
portraits of the top 50 individuals, as well as longer features.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to love a list that includes at least three
four-legged athletes, Citation at No. 97 and Man o' War at No. 84,
to say nothing of Secretariat, who I can only assume is somewhere
in the top 50. The big red beast had better be pretty high, too,
after the way he aced the 1973 Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at ESPN craftily released the list of Nos. 51 through
100 last week to generate publicity for the first show, on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In the first segment, Chris Evert (No. 50) tells how she and
Martina Navratilova (who, Evert huffily suggests, is placed
somewhat higher in the ranking) get together near their homes in
Aspen, Colo., for the occasional friendly hit that soon escalates
into points, contested as if the Duchess of Kent were beaming down
at them from the Royal Box.
</P>
<P>
   There will be insights like this throughout the year because a
bright young producer, Mark Shapiro, and his crew sought out the
top athletes as well as the people who coached them and reported on
them. The ESPN people copiously interviewed the fabled columnists
Shirley Povich and Jim Murray, on tape, before their deaths in the
past year, as well as Weeb Ewbank, Florence Griffith-Joyner, Jack
Brickhouse and Don Dunphy before their passing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but also Rod Laver, the Australian tennis star _
not eligible to be rated in this North American series, but surely
a part of it _ suffered a stroke while being interviewed, and has
since resumed his daily life.
</P>
<P>
   The operative theory from Steve Bornstein, now the ESPN
chairman, and John Walsh, the executive editor, was that the
ranking had to be based on athletic ability rather than historic
significance.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Patrick, who narrates the top 50 segments, admitted,
``You can't overlook it,'' referring to the impact of Jackie
Robinson, the great three-sport athlete from UCLA who broke the
color barrier in major league baseball in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also led the Brooklyn Dodgers to the World Series in 6
of his 10 seasons. He wound up somewhere in the top 50, which is
where he belongs, according to those of us who saw him dance off
third base, unnerving a pitcher, or diving to catch a line drive to
save a season.
</P>
<P>
   Deserving pioneers and activists and just plain characters were
not overlooked by ESPN, if only because they had to be great
athletes to make their impact. Jack Johnson (No. 100) infuriated
white America by daring to knock down white boxers and date white
women. Joe Namath (No. 88) quarterbacked the biggest upset in Super
Bowl history and seemed to personify the liberated 1960s in sports.
Josh Gibson (No. 73) hit home runs longer than Babe Ruth's, but
lived and died in the era of the Negro leagues. Althea Gibson (No.
65) was the first great black American tennis player. Satchel Paige
(No. 63) kept pitching until baseball opened up for him. Billie
Jean King (No. 59) won major tennis titles while advancing women's
sports. And Pete Rose (No. 56) hit and hustled his way onto this
list long before his gambling and tax problems caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   The top 50 will evolve over this year _ starting with Evert,
then moving to a running back named Simpson, oh, just by
coincidence, No. 49, in time for the pre-Super Bowl show. After
that, there will surely be people like Howe, Spitz, Brown,
Navratilova, Lewis, Louis, Gretzky, DiMaggio, Robinson, Koufax,
Didrikson, Thorpe, in undisclosed order, leading up to Ali and
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it Jordan second and Ali first? ESPN is giving no clues,
but that's how I would have it. I know, I know, the ground rules
were that social implications didn't count, but this ESPN series
seems legitimately rooted in history, by adults, for adults. Ali
told us he was the Greatest, and I take him at his word. At the end
of the next century, more people will remember Muhammad Ali than
Michael Jordan. I'm saying Ali should be first. Want to argue?
We've got all year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 0941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
