</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THREE POINTS, NOT STYLE POINTS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For Sunday's American Football Conference championship
game, the marquee is crowded: Bill Parcells' opportunity to lead
the Jets to the Super Bowl, John Elway's likely last game in Mile
High Stadium, Vinny Testaverde's new life, Terrell Davis'
galloping, Curtis Martin's workhorse burden, Shannon Sharpe's trash
talk, Keyshawn Johnson's versatility, Mike Shanahan's reputation as
the Broncos' ``genius'' coach.
</P>
<P>
   But if this game comes to a boil in the final minutes, a
field-goal kicker might well make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kicking a game-winning field goal,'' John Hall, the Jets'
kicker, likes to say, ``that's all I ever think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall did just that during the season in Kansas City, booting a
32-yarder in a driving rain as time expired for the Jets' 20-17
victory. His two field goals against the Seahawks made the
difference in that 32-31 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Elam, the Broncos' kicker, hasn't had to make a crucial
field goal since the 27-21 victory over the Patriots in the season
opener, but his 63-yarder at Mile High Stadium on Oct. 25 tied the
long-distance record set by Tom Dempsey in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to calm down,'' Elam said after that kick. ``I know
how to react in certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam or Hall, if not both, may need to react. In two of the
previous seven AFC title games, a field goal made the difference:
24-21 for Denver over Pittsburgh a year ago, and 10-7 for Buffalo
over Denver in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And when Parcells' 1990 Giants upset the 49ers in San Francisco
in the National Conference championship game, Matt Bahr kicked five
field goals for the 15-13 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hall is doing very well now,'' Parcells said. ``He's a
much improved kicker from what he was. My confidence in him is
growing. He's a more well-rounded kicker. He can do a lot of things
with the ball now.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a field-goal kicker, style points don't count. Only 3
points do. Hall has been more efficient since the Jets signed the
37-year-old John Kidd as their punter and Hall's holder.
</P>
<P>
   Back when Brian Hansen, the Jets' previous punter, was his
holder during the first eight games, Hall made only 11 of 17
field-goal opportunities, a shaky 65 percent. But with Kidd holding
throughout the second half of the season, Hall made 14 of 18
(including one blocked kick), 78 percent. That lifted his season
average to 71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In last Sunday's 34-24 playoff triumph over Jacksonville, Hall
added two clutch field goals: a 52-yarder for an early 10-0 lead
and a 30-yard clincher in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's got a really strong leg,'' Kidd said. ``He's athletic.
He's played other sports, so he's more of an athlete than just a
kicker who is off in another world.''
</P>
<P>
   At a sturdy 6 feet 3 inches and 223 pounds, Hall is much bigger
than most kickers, one reason his kickoffs are much longer than
those of most kickers. His 24 touchbacks ranked second in the
entire National Football League during the recent season; as a
rookie, his 29 touchbacks led the league.
</P>
<P>
   But as a field-goal kicker, Hall's improvement has coincided
with Kidd's arrival as his holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``John might be the best holder I've ever had,'' Hall said.
``He's the same in practice as in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first day together in practice back in early November,
Hall made 20 of 21 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been on a roll ever since,'' Kidd said. ``He trusts me to
get the ball in the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has been a holder for the Bills' Scott Norwood (but not
when Norwood missed the 47-yarder against the Giants in Super Bowl
XXV), for the Chargers' John Carney and the Dolphins' Pete
Stoyanovich, among others. But as a rookie with the Bills in 1984,
he held for Joe Danelo, once the Giants' kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was the most meticulous kicker I've ever worked with; he
could tell if the ball was half an inch off the spot where he
wanted it,'' Kidd said. ``All the kickers want the laces facing the
goal post and leaning a little toward the holder. When it's leaning
toward the holder, it takes the hook off the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall has kicked in this mile-high altitude before, as a
Wisconsin freshman against Colorado in nearby Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was on artificial turf, Mile High has grass,'' he said.
``But your ball travels a lot farther here in the thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam knows. At a chunky 5-11 and 200 pounds, he had an excellent
85 percent average in his sixth season, hitting 23 of 27, with one
blocked. In the 38-3 playoff rout of the Dolphins a week ago, he
was 4 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Elam's holder is Tom Rouen, the Broncos' sometimes excitable
punter. When Rouen realized that Elam was about to try that
63-yarder, everybody on the field heard Rouen yell: ``Whooo-ee!
We're going for the record!''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday Jason Elam and Tom Rouen, as well as John Hall and
John Kidd, will be going for the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
