</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-AGENT WEEK, FULL SPEED AHEAD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What you will not see when the National Basketball Association's
free-agent madhouse begins: anyone signing a contract for $126
million. What you will see: a number of deals worth $80 million to
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett's big score in 1997 may be an anomaly, but already
the Nets' Jayson Williams, a role-playing forward, has commanded
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   When the lockout is lifted and training camps open on Tuesday,
signings are expected to come spilling out of the NBA's offices
like candy out of a pinata. With more than 200 free agents suddenly
able to sign contracts, a flurry of activity is expected to
significantly alter the league's power structure.
</P>
<P>
   The players' concession on salary limits was supposed to help
the league's fractured economic system. Well, even an aging,
injury-prone center like Rik Smits is expected to sign for more
than $10 million a year with Indiana, while Luc Longley, who helped
the Bulls to three straight NBA titles, may sign with Phoenix for
about $4 million a year, less than half of what Smits may receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a great disparity among players with
similar talents,'' the agent Marc Fleisher said. ``One will sign
for $5 million a year, the other will sign for $12 million. They're
two almost identical players, but it doesn't matter. It's really
which teams have the money and whether they like you. A lot of guys
will be able to push the envelope if they have one other suitor.
But I think you'll see a lot of guys take bad deals under this
agreement, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The dismantling of the Bulls is about to begin in earnest when
Scottie Pippen leaves for either Houston or another playoff
contender. But it is unclear how many premier free agents will
actually change addresses _ especially because their own teams can
pay them more than any other franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio McDyess of Phoenix, Damon Stoudamire of Portland, Tom
Gugliotta of Minnesota and Rod Strickland of Washington _ some of
the bigger names available _ may end up staying put. McDyess, for
example, could receive no more than $67.5 million over six years
from a new team under the new labor agreement. But the Suns could
offer him a contract of $86.6 million over seven years because he
is their free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason several franchises may not go after that
special someone this week: a more attractive special someone could
be available this summer. Stephon Marbury, Antoine Walker, Marcus
Camby, Ray Allen and Allen Iverson, who all will be free agents
after this season, represent a younger, more potent future for many
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams might be saving their money when a better class of
free agents becomes available,'' said Ernie Grunfeld, the Knicks'
president and general manager. ``You might not see the movement
everyone expects.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bracing for a Chilling Effect &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the players association's decertification of
Steve Woods, an Atlanta-based agent who blasted the union during
its negotiations with the NBA, several other agents were concerned
about their involvement in the labor dispute and how it would
affect their relationship with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who said, among other things, that he would not trust
Patrick Ewing, the union president, to organize a company picnic,
was notified of the decertification on Thursday in a letter. It
said Woods' ``inaccurate statements indicate that you are not
qualified to represent members of this union in individual contract
negotiations with NBA teams.'' The union's action prevents Woods
from negotiating contracts for NBA players. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woods has since filed an unfair labor practice charge with the
National Labor Relations Board against the union. The charge will
be investigated next week.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has only two clients, Kevin Willis and Willie Burton.
Willis is under contract with Toronto, but Woods has written the
union a letter requesting that he be allowed to negotiate a deal
for Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The union declined comment, but the action taken against Woods
could signal disciplinary action for agents like Harold MacDonald
and Norman Blass, who also openly criticized the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all he did was express his opinion, I'm concerned about
taking this type of a measure without due process,'' said Marc
Fleisher, who represents Vlade Divac, among other players.
</P>
<P>
   The agent Leonard Armato, even though he did not publicly
criticize the union, was seen as a nettlesome presence during the
labor negotiations, and not many agents engendered as much ill will
among their peers. But the union probably will not scold Armato,
because of the stature of his only client, Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as a liaison for Billy Hunter, the union's executive
director, and NBA Commissioner David Stern, Armato arranged a
secret meeting between the two at his Los Angeles office on Dec.
23.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming his friendship with Stern made him privy to how the
commissioner thought, Armato tried to soften the union's hard-line
stance toward the league during a conference call with other
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Arn Tellem, the agent for Kobe Bryant and several other stars,
took to calling Armato ``Tessio,'' after the character in ``The
Godfather'' who betrays the Corleone family.
</P>
<P>
   The day before the agreement was signed, Armato, frustrated with
the lack of progress, was poised to lead a group of agents in a
minirevolt against the union.
</P>
<P>
   But he disagrees with the notion that he was going behind
Hunter's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a facilitator of communication at first and then I
became sort of a mediator at the end,'' Armato said. ``I pulled the
parties together. I would not have been willing to let the league
blow up. If I could be helpful in any way in fashioning a
compromise, I've done my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all his peers agreed, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, let's see, Shaq's his only client and he gets about 4
percent of Shaq's $15 million, which is zero if you don't have a
season,'' the agent Keith Glass said. ``Sure, Leonard was concerned
about the integrity of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final week of negotiations, Armato faxed to Hunter a
draft of a proposal that he thought might keep Stern talking. It
included a limit on maximum salaries with three exceptions: a
player could be paid any amount if he was an All-Star for the last
seven seasons, had made the all-NBA first team in two of the last
three seasons, or qualified for the Jordan exception, meaning he
had either won a championship or been named most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were 7 foot tall, went to LSU, wore a purple-and-gold
No. 34 for the Lakers, those exceptions were for you,'' a union
lawyer said on condition of anonymity. ``Leonard was trying to find
out 50 different ways to grandfather his client.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   Roomie There for Jordan
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson was not there. Neither was Scottie Pippen or Ron
Harper. But Buzz Peterson did show up for Michael Jordan's
retirement announcement on Wednesday, and Jordan's former North
Carolina roommate promptly dusted off the stories.
</P>
<P>
   Now the coach at Appalachian State, Peterson roomed with Jordan
their freshman and junior years. He said he could be blamed for
Jordan's obsession with golf.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels had been eliminated from the 1984 NCAA tournament
by Indiana and had time to kill in their hotel rooms when Davis
Love 3d asked Peterson to go out to the driving range. Peterson
asked a depressed Jordan to tag along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of bummed how the season ended, because we were
28-3 and had been No. 1 the whole year,'' Peterson said. ``We went
out and hit golf balls. The next day, we played nine holes. The day
after, nine holes. Then after that, it was all over with. We were
golf fanatics. He got hooked. I got hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, back then, I could beat him a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson showed up in Chicago last week unannounced. When Jordan
saw him on Wednesday, he immediately gave him a hug and said, ``I
can't believe you're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said, ``You knew I'd be here for you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
