<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-FALCONS-N     01-16 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-FALCONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARPLUGS READY? COTTON IN HAND? FALCONS IN THE METRODOME  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Minutes before the Minnesota Vikings began to
demolish Arizona in their divisional playoff game last Sunday,
Cardinals guard Lomas Brown was talking to a teammate just half a
foot away. Soon enough, Brown realized something: he was screaming
at the top of his lungs and his friend could barely hear him.
</P>
<P>
   And this was before the game started.
</P>
<P>
   That is what you call dome-field advantage. So is this:
Arizona's Jake Plummer, like all quarterbacks, has a headset in his
helmet with which he can listen to plays called in from the
sideline. With almost 70,000 Vikings fans screaming at the top of
their lungs, he could not hear the plays. The noise was a big
reason the Cardinals had three turnovers that led to 17 Viking
points.
</P>
<P>
   There is not only dome-field advantage, but also Metrodome
advantage. The former can be annoying, while the latter can be
destroying. The Metrodome advantage is a big reason the Vikings
went 8-0 at home in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the noisiest stadium in the NFL,'' said the Vikings'
owner, Red McCombs.
</P>
<P>
   When the Vikings play the Atlanta Falcons here in the National
Football Conference title game on Sunday, with the winner going to
Super Bowl XXXIII against the Jets or the Denver Broncos, Minnesota
will have one more weapon besides Randall Cunningham, Randy Moss
and Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Don't underestimate how significant an advantage it is for
Minnesota to have such a loud stadium. The Vikings have built their
team around a fast artificial turf and raucous fans. They like to
jump ahead by using their explosive offense; then, with the other
team trailing, their defense and their fans take over. The two feed
off each other.
</P>
<P>
   When the fans are at their loudest, it is hard to hear the
person next to you talking. The sonic vibrations sometimes cause
the dust to stir atop the press box roof. To add to the din, the
Vikings pump heavy metal music and canned noise through a speaker
system behind the visiting bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers complained to the National Football League office
about the speaker system during the regular season, as did the
Falcons this week in an attempted pre-emptive strike. Minnesota
insists it stays within the rules, shutting off the artificial
noise when the opposing team breaks the huddle. But with or without
the canned noise, the Metrodome is extremely loud.
</P>
<P>
   The noise has caused numerous false starts by offensive linemen
because they cannot hear the quarterback barking the signals. Many
teams try a silent snap count, but the noise causes even the
calmest of players to get nervous and throws off the rhythm of the
silent count.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd gave Arizona a lot of problems early in the game''
Atlanta Coach Dan Reeves said. ``These are the type of things we've
got to be ready to deal with. You can't change them. They're going
to be there. We've got to deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the Falcons this week, Reeves, who is 3-1 in
conference title games, has done what he did as coach of the Giants
before they played in a loud stadium: practice to the accompaniment
of taped crowd noise. It helps, but it is not the same _ sort of
like turning up a loud rap piece on the stereo as opposed to
hearing the group in concert.
</P>
<P>
   The only sure way to quiet the Minnesota fans is to stay ahead
of, or close to, the Vikings. Move the ball downfield, and the
Metrodome becomes deathly quiet. ``If we can get first downs and
eat up yards and have long drives, then we can shut down the crowd
a little bit,'' Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons may not be quite as susceptible to crowd noise as
other teams because they play in a dome themselves. ``That's some
advantage,'' Reeves admitted, ``but when we are at home, and on
offense, our crowd is quiet. That won't be the case against
Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Vikings, home-field advantage used to mean bitter cold
and blowing snow. Now, it is heavy metal music and high-decibel
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares if it's fair or not?'' Vikings fullback Leroy Hoard
said. ``We earned it. Everybody has the same opportunity that we
had to get home-field advantage. We got it. It's got to be good for
something, that noise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
