<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-LINE-NYT &LR;      01-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-LINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECT COMPLIMENT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ Their kangaroo court remains in session,
though they lost two of their founding justices. They still sit in
their own corner of the Denver Broncos' locker room, though they
have relaxed their rules against talking to teammates and the news
media. But the Broncos' offensive line is still undersized, still
downright ornery and still very good.
</P>
<P>
   How good? Behind the linemen, Terrell Davis ran for 2,008 yards
to post the third-highest single-season rushing total _ after Eric
Dickerson and Barry Sanders _ in National Football League history.
Behind them, John Elway directed the Broncos to 380.8 yards of
total offense _ the third-most productive attack in the league
</P>
<P>
   How ornery? Left tackle Tony Jones has not answered the phone
all week. His best friend is the Jets defensive end Anthony
Pleasant. He played six years with him with the Browns, one with
the Ravens, and works out with him nearly every day in the off
season in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   They will line up against each other in Sunday's American
Football Conference championship game. One of them is going to have
more to talk about than the other for the next eight months. Jones
believes it will be him, and so does his wife, Kamilla. Early this
week, Renita Pleasant called Kamilla and let slip that the
Pleasants were making Super Bowl travel reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she said something back to her,'' Jones said, smiling.
``I don't want talk to him until after the game, and then we'll hug
and make up.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the season, and despite last year's title, there was
talk about whether the line might hinder the Broncos' chances of
repeating. The unit lost tackle Gary Zimmerman to retirement and
the free-agent guard Brian Habib to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The two veterans were credited for developing the line's
``us-against-the-world'' mentality by creating the court that fined
fellow linemen for offenses ranging from mental mistakes in
practice ($5), talking to the news media ($10), and up to $3,000
for a ``prima donna'' transgression. At the beginning of the
season, the Broncos still had Jones, guard Mark Schlereth and the
Pro Bowl center Tom Nalen, but had to replace more than 22 years of
NFL experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people were right to say you don't replace guys like
that, but they didn't realize we have a system and standard of hard
work around here and those guys who stepped in understand that,''
said Jones, who was voted to the Pro Bowl this season for the first
time in his 11-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, guard Dan Neil and tackle Harry Swayne played 10
games for Denver last season, mostly on special teams. Their
addition did not make the Broncos any bigger _ they average 287.6
pounds, the lowest of any playoff team _ and barely got younger.
Only the second-year men Neil and Nalen are under 30. In fact,
Swayne began his 12-year career as a defensive end for Tampa Bay
before being converted to the offensive line in 1990 at San Diego,
where he started in Super Bowl XXIX for the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't missed a beat; they are tough guys,'' Elway said
of Neil and Swayne. ``It's a group of guys who fight and claw and
never give up. They play together and take a lot of pride in what
they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Their quickness is what is most apparent on the field _
Schlereth and Neil always manage to get wide on those 8-yard deep
pitches to Davis. The linemen cleared the way for the Broncos to
gain 250 yards on the ground last week against Miami and allowed
Elway to be sacked only once.
</P>
<P>
   But it is their toughness that has made admirers out of their
teammates. Schlereth, for example, had arthroscopic surgery on his
left knee _ for the 12th time and the 21st surgery of his career _
and did not miss a start all season. Jones has played through a
groin strain and a sprained left ankle. He also sprained his knee
against Miami, but will play against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Nalen, who was chosen for his second consecutive Pro Bowl, said
it was easy to limp onto the field when you have a back like
Terrell Davis driving for 2,000 yards. He said he knows it kept
Jones and Schlereth going this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really cool to know that we were part of the reason that
he became one of four guys to get that many yards,'' Nalen said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Neil and Swayne filled Habib's and Zimmerman's positions
on the field, Schlereth has filled in for them off the field. He is
now the kangaroo court's chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our leader,'' Jones said. ``When you look at all he's
been through and how hard he plays, you got to follow his
example.''
</P>
<P>
   In the corner, Schlereth wraps tape around both his knees and
fires a dirty look in Jones' direction. The 10-year veteran remains
the most reluctant member of the line to answer questions about the
unit. He has overhead Jones and threatened a fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the difference between last year is?'' Schlereth
asks, looking at Jones. ``We don't like each other this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
