<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      01-16 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE JETS, A LANDMARK SEASON GETS TOUGHER AT MILE HIGH STADIUM  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Jets seem to get it, finally. They face the Broncos
on Sunday in the franchise's first trip to a championship game in
16 years. In between, they became a symbol for finding ways to lose
and excuses for losing.
</P>
<P>
   This season, though, the dangers of the road, the pressure of
big games, the weight of their own failed history all but
disappeared down the stretch. The Jets are, for the first time in
30 years, a division champion. They are winners of 13 games,
including a playoff victory last week, and they are having fun.
</P>
<P>
   But now they play a team that is attempting to defend its Super
Bowl title and that scored 501 points in the regular season. And
they face a quarterback, in John Elway, who may be playing his
final home game before heading to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The American Football Conference title game is something that 38
Broncos appeared in a year ago. The last time the Jets got this
far, it was the 1982 season, when their future seemed bright and
they were going to unleash the league's best rushing attack against
the Dolphins in Miami. But the rain, the mud _ the very forces of
nature, it seemed _ conspired against the Jets to produce a shutout
loss that day.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken all this time for them to get back.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets are back by any measure. They stand among the
highest-scoring teams in the National Football League, with
quarterback Vinny Testaverde and running back Curtis Martin teaming
up as one of the NFL's more dangerous passing-running duos, and
interesting offensive alignments that can include Keyshawn Johnson
going in motion or blocking for the run, or tight end Kyle Brady
playing fullback.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets' defense constantly shifts, or blitzes, or gets
into combinations of zone and man-to-man coverage to fool offenses.
Opposing quarterbacks completed barely 52 percent of their passes
and averaged slightly more than 6 yards an attempt. In a
bottom-line business, the Jets allowed fewer points than any team
in the NFL except the Dolphins, who allowed only 1 fewer point.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 60 minutes away from a trip to Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami,
all the Jets have to do is put it all together against the
powerful, confident, we-know-how-to-win Broncos. For all the
cleverness of the Jets' offense and the cerebration of their
defense, they have to concern themselves with simply being
outmanned.
</P>
<P>
   It will start with this: the Jets have to stay even early,
perhaps by coming out with newfangled attacking schemes. When teams
don't, the Broncos are merciless: in the regular season, Denver
outscored opponents by 47-9 on its opening drives, by 144-54 in the
first quarter and by 300-141 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, no other team has had a 90-point differential in
the opening quarter. No wonder Denver is favored in Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   But here is something that has been lost in all the wonderment
over the Broncos' quick starts: the Jets, including their playoff
victory over Jacksonville, have a 44-7 advantage after their
opening drives.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, it has been the Broncos' opponents who have
abandoned their game plans against Denver and its sustained attack.
They start to throw the ball. When Dan Marino tried to do that last
Saturday in the divisional playoff here, his Dolphins teammates
could not hear him barking out signals. More than 75,000 fans at
Mile High Stadium _ which has been sold out for Broncos games since
the 1970s _ tried to help their team with so much noise that
audibles were impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins beat the Broncos just last month. But that was in
Miami, and the Dolphins did not commit a penalty. They committed 10
last Saturday, including six false starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems so elementary to say you'll run the ball,'' said a
scout who, in the tradition of his brotherhood, requested
anonymity. ``But this team gets up on opponents so fast, and
continues to score. A lot of teams abandon the game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   If both clubs keep to their game plans, these are likely to be
the keys to their success:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BRONCO OFFENSIVE LINE &LR;  _ Denver's line, which must protect
Elway and block for Davis, is efficient, and is helped by receivers
who are not afraid to block, too. With a mobile quarterback such as
Elway, and an all-round running back such as Davis, who rushed for
2,008 yards this season, the line has learned that it can be
successful merely by nudging the defense. Just getting defenders
turned slightly is all that either Elway or Davis needs. And Elway
can still run for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe,'' Denver Coach Mike Shanahan said, ``in attacking
a defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis says the Jets' defense reminds him of the Broncos': ``Not
a lot of big names, but blue-collar workers. They may not have big
names, but they play like they have big names.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense has not permitted a runner to gain 100 yards
in 11 straight games. Davis got 199 last weekend against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE JET OFFENSIVE LINE &LR;  _ The line has improved to the point
where it is allowing the Jets to churn out the third-and-short
yardage they had failed to gain much of the season. It will have to
be alert against a mobile defense that enjoys taking chances when
it feels it has the opposition in a hole. There will be all sorts
of unusual ``games'' played by the Broncos linebackers John Mobley
and Bill Romanowski, who may line up in different spots and run
stunts to disguise from where they are rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team will do that when it has the lead,'' Jets Coach Bill
Parcells said. But his style has been to insist that the Jets play
solid offense and continue to run the ball, even when behind. The
Jets have been fortunate this year: they have rarely trailed and
are 11-0 when scoring first.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE EXPERIENCE FACTOR &LR;  _ Jet fans should be concerned by the
team's breakdowns last Sunday against the Jaguars. Jerome Henderson
failed to come over in time to help Otis Smith on Jimmy Smith's
52-yard touchdown catch as the half ended. Curtis Martin lost a
fumble; it was only his second of the season in more than 400
carries, but it came at a potentially critical point in the game.
Wayne Chrebet fumbled in the fourth quarter. And Testaverde threw
an interception in the end zone (a bad play call, Parcells said).
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Jets, whose errors could be considered physical
miscues, the Jaguars made some truly bad plays.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, on the other hand, was unstoppable in clobbering Miami.
On the surface, it appeared that the Broncos rebounded from a
troubling end of the regular season while the Jets, who went into
the playoffs with a six-game winning streak and playing virtually
error free, reverted to some of their poorer performances earlier
in the season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE QUARTERBACKS &LR;  _ Elway is the greatest at fourth-quarter
comebacks in NFL history. His coach believes this will be Elway's
final game at Mile High Stadium, and who can put a figure on what
that might mean?
</P>
<P>
   He may not have faced a defense as unsettling as the Jets' this
season, though anything they do to him will matter only if they
have already contained Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, meanwhile, has not had a bad game in his 13-1
stretch as a starter. He hints that he knew from the beginning,
when he was named Glenn Foley's backup, that he would be able to
help bring the Jets to this point. He is not surprised, though,
that few others thought that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
