<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5863 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-800&AMP;AD     01-16 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-800&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT SQUEEZE FOR SEVERAL GOP SENATORS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a strange sight. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
was offering a compromise plan that would have abbreviated
President Clinton's impeachment trial and avoided witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was only trying to please the many moderates in his state
who support Clinton and want the trial over with. But his proposed
compromise was shot down by his fellow Republicans in the Senate,
and it infuriated conservatives in his state, who have vowed to
field a candidate against him.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton is part of a small but conspicuous class of 13 Republican
senators whose political futures may hang in the balance along with
Clinton's. They have the distinction of being up for re-election in
2000 and representing states that voted for Clinton in 1996. And
these are states where voters now strongly oppose Clinton's
impeachment. (There are six other Republicans facing re-election,
but they are from states that did not support Clinton in 1996.)
</P>
<P>
   This potential vulnerability makes these senators the prime
audience for White House lawyers, who are to begin Clinton's
defense on Tuesday. Assuming all 45 Democrats hold together in
support of the president, the White House needs to win over only 6
Republicans to end the trial. The pressure will be especially
intense on Senate Republicans from the Northeast and the West
Coast, where support for the President is the strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Their future viability is not far from their daily calculations
as they navigate the thickets of impeachment, each according to his
or her own political needs back home. Uniting them is the hard
reality that approval ratings for Clinton have soared during the
impeachment process while those of the Republican Party have
plunged.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a concern, increasingly raised by Republican
strategists, that a drawn-out impeachment trial could drag them
down in 2000 just as it dragged down House Republicans last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment debate has become the Republicans' Vietnam,''
said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta. ``It's a
war fought for all the right reasons. But we've lost the support of
the American people _ we never had it _ and in a democracy, you
can't continue to prosecute a war without the support of the
people. What we need is peace with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   This view is not universal. Some Republicans believe that 2000
is so far away that impeachment will have little effect on the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will have zero impact, either positive or negative, on
the election of U.S. senators in a presidential year 22 months from
now,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who heads the committee
that oversees the election of Republicans to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, McConnell pointed to the early support by some
moderates for calling witnesses, a stance that had mostly been
advocated by conservatives but now seems the prevailing sentiment
among Republicans. ``That's a clear indication that the Republican
conference, from the left to the right, is viewing this as a
constitutional duty and a serious responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, even before the Senate has taken a single significant
vote _ that is to start the week of Jan. 25 _ impeachment is
complicating the landscape for several Republicans up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, who has been elected and unelected from a state that
swings back and forth between Republicans and Democrats, has
prompted the conservative American Heritage Party to threaten to
run a challenger against him. The conservatives were upset that he
proposed a compromise that would have short-circuited the process
and, in their view, not have punished Clinton sufficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heritage Party drew enough support last year to
cause Rep. Rick White, a Republican, to lose his seat, and it poses
the same threat to Senator Gorton. ``The Heritage Party will
remember the proposed compromise, regardless of how he votes,''
said David Olson, a political science professor at the University
of Washington. ``They have put a sword into the ground on this one.
I don't know what he could do to erase that threat from the
right.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rhode Island, a Democratic stronghold that gave Clinton 60
percent of the vote in 1996, Sen. John Chafee, a Republican, has
almost the opposite problem. He faces little threat from the right
but could draw a serious Democratic challenge from the secretary of
state, James Langevin.
</P>
<P>
   While Chafee is a reliably moderate voice in the Senate, he
surprised many with his early call for witnesses. Darryl West,
chairman of the political science department at Brown University,
suggested that Chafee was simply shoring up his standing with
Republicans in Washington, who already view the senator with
suspicion. But West said Chafee would face more pressure when the
time came to vote on whether to end the trial and then whether to
convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chafee's problem is not the Republican right wing in the
election as much as it is a strong Democratic challenger,'' West
said. ``But he worries about the right wing in terms of his
position in Washington. The witness issue is a procedural issue he
needs to finesse so that he doesn't offend the right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other moderate Republicans face similar quandaries. Sen. James
Jeffords of Vermont, another pro-Clinton state, is more likely to
draw a challenge from the Democrats _ chiefly from Gov. Howard Dean
_ than from his own party. Jeffords' support for witnesses, like
Chafee's, is a setback for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, who represents a state where voters
have been receptive to independents and even elected one as
governor, could also draw a challenge in 2000. While she says she
remains undecided on witnesses, her Republican colleague, Sen.
Susan Collins, who is not up for re-election until 2002, surprised
many by calling early for witnesses, even though she too is
perceived as a moderate.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, another state that Clinton carried, Sen. John
Ashcroft, a Republican, is already in a race with the Democratic
governor, Mel Carnahan. Ashcroft was an early proponent of
Clinton's resignation but has softened his stance lately.
Regardless of how Ashcroft votes on Clinton's fate, the Carnahan
campaign is ready to pounce. If Ashcroft votes to convict Clinton,
they will say he is out of touch. If he votes to support Clinton,
they will say he has flip-flopped from his earlier calls for
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams of Minnesota, like Ashcroft, is more conservative
than his constituents, and there is no shortage of Democrats and
independents in Minnesota who want to run against him. They include
Ted Mondale, a former state senator who is the son of former Vice
President Walter Mondale, and former Rep. Timothy Penny.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., is in the same category and could
draw a Democratic challenge from former Rep. Marjorie
Margolies-Mezvinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the 13 Republicans who are from states that
supported Clinton in 1996 are Sens. Spencer Abraham of Michigan,
Mike DeWine of Ohio, Bill Frist of Tennessee, Jon Kyl of Arizona,
Connie Mack of Florida and William V. Roth Jr. of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Most have avoided the spotlight on impeachment. Mack, for
example, while enormously popular in Florida, has stayed in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kane, a Fort Lauderdale pollster who publishes an
independent monthly political journal called Florida Voter, said,
``I think that tells me this is not a winning issue for a candidate
that's up in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick for all Republicans will be to hold those
conservatives who supported impeachment in the House and at the
same time bring back the independent voters who have been turned
off by it.
</P>
<P>
   Linda DiVall, a Republican pollster, told the Senate Republicans
in a briefing last week that the party was now defined by
impeachment and that it needed to move on to other issues, like tax
cuts and Social Security. One of her polls showed that voters
ranked the Republicans' handling of impeachment as their chief
reservation about whether Republicans should keep control of
Congress. However, she said, short-circuiting the process now would
be worse than playing it out. Republicans need to show they are
being fair and thorough.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, analysts said, Republicans cannot afford to
alienate their conservative base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in a tough re-election fight, you have to go in with
your base secure,'' said Bill Pascoe, political director of the
American Conservative Union. ``It makes more sense for Rod Grams,
say, to vote to convict, even though the majority of his state may
be saying in polls that they oppose conviction. If he abandons his
base, it's not like the left-wing Democratic-Farm-Labor guys are
going to embrace him.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick for all Republicans will be to hold those
conservatives who supported impeachment in the House and at the
same time bring back the independent voters who have been turned
off by it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-LEGACY-NY     01-16 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-LEGACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING EARLY FAILURES, BRONCOS NOW RIDE A LONG TRAIL OF
SUCCESSES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Denver Broncos are the defending Super Bowl
champions and one of the National Football League's most successful
franchises over the past two decades. But the Broncos who will face
the New York Jets on Sunday in the American Football Conference
championship game first had to undergo a stunning makeover to
evolve from crude league doormat to sophisticated champions.
</P>
<P>
   Their quarterback, John Elway, is a star. Their coach, Mike
Shanahan, is one of the brightest in the game. The Broncos dress in
striking blue, orange and white uniforms. Their logo is of a
fierce-looking horse with an orange mane.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Denver and the Broncos will begin building a
76,000-seat open-air stadium scheduled to be in use for the 2001
NFL season. With that new stadium and new lease, the Broncos are
assured of remaining in Denver for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   They have traveled a long way since becoming a charter member of
the American Football League in 1960 and then joining the National
Football League when the leagues merged in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   In their earliest days, the Broncos dressed in vertically
striped socks and wore dull mustard-colored shirts, brown pants and
brown helmets with numbers on the sides. The team's management was
so cheap that during games employees would race into the stands to
retrieve balls that had been kicked there, literally swiping them
back from fans.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing worse than the uniforms was their record. For
their first 13 years, the Broncos produced one horrible team after
another.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' first winning season didn't arrive until 1973, when
they compiled a 7-5-2 record. They didn't make it to the playoffs
until their 18th season, in 1977, when they went straight to the
Super Bowl under Coach Red Miller. They lost that game to the
Dallas Cowboys, 27-10, but the Broncos were just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves, who is coaching the Atlanta Falcons in Sunday's
National Football Conference championship game with the Minnesota
Vikings, arrived in Denver as head coach in 1981, and the Broncos
began to blossom. Elway arrived in 1983. Pat Bowlen purchased the
team in 1984. Along the way, the Broncos returned to the Super Bowl
after the 1986, 1987 and 1989 seasons, only to lose each time.
Their final breakthrough came last January, when they defeated the
heavily favored Green Bay Packers in Super Bowl XXXII and brought
the NFL championship home to their long-faithful fans.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Broncos' early failures, their home at Mile High
Stadium has been sold out for every game since 1970, with the
exception of two games played with replacement players during the
NFL strike in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is really very little like the relationship between this
city and this team in the NFL,'' Bowlen said. ``There is a bond
here and it works this way, even back when the Broncos were awful.
It's sort of like if somebody called your sister ugly. You go to
kick their tail. It doesn't matter if your sister really is ugly or
not. It's that kind of an attachment that goes beyond
expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bowlen's ownership, expectation has only increased. Denver
has won seven divisional titles, made nine playoff appearances and
put together a 96-25 record at home. The Broncos have won the last
18 games they have played at Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I purchased the team in 1984, I could see that it was a
franchise that had rounded the corner from its problematic early
history but was in the middle of the pack in the NFL,'' Bowlen
said. ``Dan Reeves had a lot to do with elevating the franchise
further. He brought his winning experience as a player and a coach
from the Dallas Cowboys here and showed this organization how to
win. The standard was set then by Dan that anything less than
making the playoffs each season was a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan arrived with Bowlen in 1984. He was an assistant coach
from 1984 through 1987 and again from 1989 through 1991. He then
spent three years as the offensive coordinator for the San
Francisco 49ers and was part of the 49ers' staff that coached the
team to a Super Bowl victory after the 1994 season. Bowlen brought
him back to Denver in 1995 as head coach and the man in charge of
football operations.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Shanahan turned out to be the move that elevated
the Broncos to their current status, to a level of achievement that
is now envied in pro football. The Denver standard now is Super
Bowl or bust.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan is not only a noted offensive strategist and teacher;
his leadership and personnel decisions have helped Denver develop
from an 8-8 team in 1995 to 13-3 in 1996, 12-4 and Super Bowl
champions the following year, and this season's 14-2 regular-season
record _ which included winning its first 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mike Shanahan had been here longer and especially with
Elway, you would have seen more Super Bowl championships for
Denver,'' said Broncos defensive end Neil Smith, who joined the
team last season as a free agent after playing nine seasons for the
Kansas City Chiefs. ``There is a spirit here inside the
organization and with the fans that makes things happen. Good
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Williams, another Broncos defensive end, played college
football at the University of Colorado beginning in 1987 and played
for two other NFL teams before returning here as a Bronco in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Denver Broncos have been invigorating the city of Denver
for a long time,'' Williams said. ``There would probably not be a
Colorado Avalanche pro hockey team here if it wasn't for the
Broncos. There would probably not be a Colorado Rockies baseball
team here if it wasn't for the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans here loved this team but were frustrated over a
championship for the team, and one for John Elway, for so long
after so many close tries. But last year we got it and the
appreciation and outpouring of affection was tremendous. We got to
ride on the big red fire truck through downtown Denver, around all
of the fans, in the big parade. We want to get on that fire truck
again. And ride.''
</P>
<P>
   What Sunday's game against the Jets here has anticipated is not
simply the chance to advance to the team's second consecutive Super
Bowl. It is also the notion that Elway, the pride of the Broncos, a
player in his 16th season with the team, might be playing his last
game in Mile High Stadium. Maybe even his last game as a Bronco.
Elway has indicated he will retire after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let that enter my mind, what I'm doing next
year,'' Elway said. ``We were in the same situation last year, but
I think you have to savor each one. You've got to focus in on each
one, because you never know how many opportunities you're going to
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Elway almost retired after winning the last Super Bowl, he
appears gone if he wins this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's going to happen,'' Bowlen said, ``but we
expect that John will retire. And if that is the case, come to that
stadium on Sunday and you will see something that has rarely
happened in sports before. The Broncos playing to get to a Super
Bowl and Elway and the fans saying goodbye? That is something that
would be very emotional for Denver and for Colorado. It would
transcend beyond the football game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
