<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDGETING-CALORIES-RE     01-16 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDGETING-CALORIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIT DOWN. NO, STAND UP. HAVE WE GOT NEWS FOR YOU. 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's enough to get someone struggling to lose those
all-important 20 pounds lathered up into a frenzy, but come to
think of it, a frenzy may be just what the doctor ordered.
Old-fashioned fidgeting _ tapping your pencil against a conference
table in a make-or-break meeting, jiggling your leg while gabbing
on the telephone, pacing back and forth until you wear a hole in
the carpet behind your desk _ may emerge as a new weight-control
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be a major implication of a Mayo Clinic study,
which fed 16 people 1,000 extra calories a day for eight weeks and
then told them to simply lounge around, have a good time _ and,
most of all, refrain from strenuous exercise. The researchers
wanted an answer to a question that has been voiced with equal
parts anger and green-eyed envy by anyone who has discovered that
last year's suits do not fit this year's dimensions: Why can some
people eat anything and everything and not gain an ounce, while
others bulk up with every swallow?
</P>
<P>
   The researchers were surprised to find that some people _ the
fortunate ones, they said _ work off the extra calories by
fidgeting (``nonexercise activity thermogenesis,'' nutritionists
call it).
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the notion that something as painless as ordinary
movements _ a tensing of a muscle here, a run to the lavatory there
_ can lead to weight loss (or at least weight control) will open
new horizons for the billion-dollar diet industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ferguson, the Duchess of York and spokesperson for Weight
Watchers, may face competition if Roadrunner (the hero of the Wile
E. Coyote cartoons) starts doing endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores, too, can profit by clearing away some of those
no-pain, no-gain books for the blockbuster literature of fidgeting.
``There's an opportunity here for me to become a fidget guru,''
said Lewis Grossberger, author of ``The Non-Runner's Book''
(Collier, 1978). ``I'm going to write a best-selling health book
called `Fidget Your Way to Health' and tell you how to lose weight,
improve muscle tone and your sex life by fidgeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The realization that fidgeting is good may also force a
fundamental change in family dynamics _ after all, parents will no
longer have to tell their children to stop fidgeting at the dinner
table.
</P>
<P>
   Adults, too, can stop worrying about acting like worrywarts
because of the health benefits. (Here things get confusing, though.
If they stop worrying, they might gain weight.) How many calories
does a shifty-eyed person use glowering at everybody in sight? Is
that how Richard M. Nixon kept fit during the dark days of
Watergate? Perhaps indoorsy types can skip the gym in favor of a
couple of practice golf swings during everyday conversations _ who
knew Johnny Carson had figured out the secret to a flat stomach?
</P>
<P>
   But isn't fidgeting just another name for nervous energy?
Apparently so. ``Let's be real,'' said Annette Hastings, director
of nutrition at Bronx-Lebanon Hospital Center. ``If you are the
kind of person who moves around a lot, you're going to have higher
calorie needs. This is plain old common sense. Surprise,
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some researchers say there is food for serious thought in
the fidgeting findings. Karen Miller-Kovach, the lead scientist for
Weight Watchers International, said fidgeting ``seems to be a
personal characteristic that may have some hereditary links, but it
doesn't seem to be a habit that you can form.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, like charisma or sex appeal, you either have it
or you don't. ``It's pretty much unconscious or subconscious
movements, even down to the people with nervous tics,'' she said.
``That all takes energy to make those muscles contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller-Kovach described studies where researchers computed
calories consumed by subjects in controlled environments. ``The
people who are genetically or biologically predisposed to be couch
potatoes sit on the bed and read a book or whatever they do,'' she
said. ``The nervous-energy types are touching their toes, cracking
their knuckles, not sitting in one place for more than a minute or
two.'' (She is one of them. ``I had my pencil going against my
leg'' while describing the study, she said in a telephone
interview.)
</P>
<P>
   Other experts warn against expecting large, quick losses from
adopting a daily regimen of fidgeting. Annette Hastings, director
of the Bronx-Lebanon Hospital Center, calculated that fidgeting
could add 5 to 10 percent to a man's basic metabolic rate (the
number of calories burned by doing nothing).
</P>
<P>
   That works out to only 200 calories a day. Jogging or playing
tennis would burn that many in an hour. Still, she said, ``over 365
days in a year, that's a lot of calories.''
</P>
<P>
   Not willing to wait a year? Try a short-term calculation. ``In
17 days you lose a pound,'' she said, ``if you're not eating to
support the fidgeting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-CHILD-KILLING-2N     01-16 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-CHILD-KILLING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRIDGEPORT, Conn.: they were.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one has been charged with the deaths of B.J. and Ms. Clarke.
Peeler may have an alibi: by court order, he was wearing an
electronic bracelet that tracked his movements. But he was arrested
this week on a charge of possessing a stolen shotgun, and his bail,
which had been $900,000 on the charges of attempted murder and the
later murder of Snead, was raised to $1.65 million. He remains in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   As he was led into the Bridgeport courthouse to be arraigned on
Thursday, he was asked if he had had anything to do with the death
of B.J. Brown. Peeler kept his head down and did not answer.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport was the third stop for B.J., who was born in Brooklyn
as Leroy George Brown Jr. but quickly became known by the initials
for ``Brown, Junior.'' For his first two years, he lived with his
grandparents in Fort Lauderdale, then joined his mother in
Bridgeport in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clarke was an energetic, hands-on mother who personally
delivered B.J. to school and after-school activities, and could
always be counted on to help chaperone a field trip or to bring
cupcakes to school for Valentine's Day, relatives said. She was
born in Jamaica, where she was a Girl Scout, then immigrated to the
United States, settling in Fort Lauderdale just before high school,
where she ran track.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, she briefly studied to become a medical
administrative assistant, then moved to New York to live with a
cousin, Janet Gordon. A year after Ms. Clarke gave birth to B.J.,
she joined Ms. Gordon in Bridgeport, and took classes at a
community college before going to work at the counter of the U-Haul
moving center in Bridgeport. She was promoted to the state
headquarters in nearby Orange, where at the time of her death she
worked as a coordinator of equipment traffic.
</P>
<P>
   B.J.'s father, Leroy Brown Sr., had not been around much, but he
attended the double funeral on Thursday night at the Refuge Temple
Church of God here. He said that in a recent chat with Ms. Clarke,
she had told him about buying the $76,000 house on Earl Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she finally felt like she was getting somewhere in
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their son had been thriving, too. Sandra Gonzalez, 9, a
classmate in second grade at B.J.'s former school, Webster
Elementary, remembers him giving her a ring and quarters to buy
cotton candy at a nearby deli.
</P>
<P>
   He spent afternoons at the Boys Club, where he wrestled, swam
and played the jokester. The director, Steven S. Jones, said he was
always one of the most neatly dressed children.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Torres, his intended when he turned 10, remembered him
telling her appreciatively, `` `You're blazing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd touch my butt and then run, so I'd chase him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The exuberance was snuffed out by the drive-by shooting on Sept.
2, 1997. Snead and Peeler had apparently had a long feud that had
begun over $90.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how Snead and Ms. Clarke came to associate with
Peeler. But in doing so, they were drawing B.J. into Bridgeport's
wilder side. Peeler had been charged with having drug
paraphernalia. And after the drive-by shooting, according to court
documents, his girlfriend told Ms. Clarke that Snead ``should not
have been driving with kids in the car when he had a beef with
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgeport Police Chief, Thomas J. Sweeney, said B.J. was
very open with detectives and gave a very helpful statement. ``He
had an impressive ability to recall and reconstruct events _ better
than some older people,'' Chief Sweeney said. He said that over the
months they had spent talking to him, investigators had become fond
of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and his mother, though, knew they were in danger. Ms.
Marquez, the Boys Club counselor, said Ms. Clarke told her that
they moved last summer partly ``to get away from all that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first week or so after the move, an officer in a marked
car was stationed outside whenever the family was home, and the
officer followed Ms. Clarke when she went out of town, sometimes as
far as the state line. But then she asked the police to end the
protection, feeling it made them even more conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 8, Ms. Clarke's body was discovered by a co-worker about
11 a.m. after she did not show up for work. Investigators believe
that she had been killed about 6 the night before, when a neighbor
heard a noise that could have been gunshots or a car backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   On her bed was her Bible, open to Psalm 20. ``May the Lord
answer you in the day of trouble,'' it begins.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clarke had been a parishioner at the Refuge Temple Church of
God, a Pentecostal congregation. At the end of Sunday services,
which sometimes last three hours, she often answered the altar
call, which people more commonly respond to just once, when they
accept Christ. The pastor, the Rev. Courtney Williams Jr., said
regular appearances at the altar indicate either a special response
to the sermon or ``a deep need for spiritual counsel or prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is the children of Bridgeport who are seeking strength.
They thronged to the funeral, many standing on tiptoe to sign the
guest book, and a dozen wearing their Boys Club basketball jerseys
under heavy winter coats.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the youngsters at the club said they had heard a name
on the street in connection with the killings. Their buddies have
advised them to shut up about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
