<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; var-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-REVI     01-16 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING THE AIRPORT CHECKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: Also sent with ``a'' code) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Screeners at airport security checkpoints miss
weapons that undercover testers hide under their clothes, or they
notice them but do nothing. Ticket agents forget to ask if
passengers are carrying packages from strangers, or fail to react
properly if the answer is yes. Airport employees don't single out
passengers who buy tickets with cash at the last minute or
otherwise act suspiciously. Ground crews leave airplanes unlocked
and unattended, giving intruders an opportunity to plant a weapon
or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Airport security can leave passengers feeling insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines pass most of these tests, Federal Aviation
Administration officials say, intercepting hundreds of weapons each
year. Potential terrorists face a high likelihood of detection. But
it is hard for outsiders to determine how well the FAA and the
airlines are doing. Last week the agency gave The New York Times
reports on 71 security violations at USAir, now US Airways.
Concerned about the airport failure rate, the Transportation
Department's inspector general is testing security arrangements and
its report is expected to go to Congress in February.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts wonder why the system works at all, especially at
the level of screeners, most of whom are hired at minimal wages by
security companies trying to maximize the chance of getting the
contract from the airlines, which are responsible for the security
at their check-in desks, gates and terminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the same money, or more money, you can go over to Pizza
Hut or McDonald's in the same airport, and maybe get better
benefits, and get a free lunch out of it,'' said a federal official
who spoke on condition of anonymity. And a job in fast food has few
worrisome responsibilities, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy job turnover _ often well over 100 percent in a year _
also has its effects. At the Dallas/Fort Worth airport in 1995, an
FAA agent with a weapon strapped to the small of his back set off a
metal detector. The screener used a hand wand.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation showed that the screener, who was on only his
third shift, had not completed training; he didn't realize that
when the agent spread his arms, his jacket stood away from his
back, shielding the gun from detection.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, a screener at Cleveland Hopkins
International Airport failed to detect a weapon smuggled in by
another agent in 1995, and USAir asked for leniency because the
screener had been on the job four years. That, said the airline in
a letter to the FAA, constituted ``extensive experience (in terms
of screener turnover).'' In this context, four years is a lengthy
career.
</P>
<P>
   At the checkpoint, ``the ability of people to find things on the
X-ray screen is shockingly low,'' said Dr. Michael Cantor, a
psychologist formerly employed at Argenbright, one of the nation's
largest airport security contractors. Some people are
detail-oriented and are very good at spotting guns or bombs. Others
have other useful traits, he said, being ``highly extroverted'' and
willing to challenge people who are often of higher social status.
</P>
<P>
   ``But supervisors are not savvy,'' Dr. Cantor said. ``They don't
do a division of labor.'' Workers rotate between viewing the X-ray
screen and the other checkpoint jobs. Cantor developed a quick test
to find detail-oriented people but could not persuade the FAA to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   People are, in fact, the weak spot in the system. Airlines and
the FAA are installing more and more high-tech machines to scan
bags, but the airlines do not always send the bags through.
Mechanics, baggage handlers and others often fail to wear required
identification, or fail to challenge persons not wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, experts say, to stay vigilant about a threat that is
intermittent at best. It's like looking through a haystack that
might have a needle in it. The FAA is even considering a checkpoint
system that would periodically show an X-ray image of a bag with a
gun in it, just to keep screeners on their toes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5878 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-REVI     01-16 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING THE AIRPORT CHECKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: Also sent with ``t'' code) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Screeners at airport security checkpoints miss
weapons that undercover testers hide under their clothes, or they
notice them but do nothing. Ticket agents forget to ask if
passengers are carrying packages from strangers, or fail to react
properly if the answer is yes. Airport employees don't single out
passengers who buy tickets with cash at the last minute or
otherwise act suspiciously. Ground crews leave airplanes unlocked
and unattended, giving intruders an opportunity to plant a weapon
or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Airport security can leave passengers feeling insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines pass most of these tests, Federal Aviation
Administration officials say, intercepting hundreds of weapons each
year. Potential terrorists face a high likelihood of detection. But
it is hard for outsiders to determine how well the FAA and the
airlines are doing. Last week the agency gave The New York Times
reports on 71 security violations at USAir, now US Airways.
Concerned about the airport failure rate, the Transportation
Department's inspector general is testing security arrangements and
its report is expected to go to Congress in February.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts wonder why the system works at all, especially at
the level of screeners, most of whom are hired at minimal wages by
security companies trying to maximize the chance of getting the
contract from the airlines, which are responsible for the security
at their check-in desks, gates and terminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the same money, or more money, you can go over to Pizza
Hut or McDonald's in the same airport, and maybe get better
benefits, and get a free lunch out of it,'' said a federal official
who spoke on condition of anonymity. And a job in fast food has few
worrisome responsibilities, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy job turnover _ often well over 100 percent in a year _
also has its effects. At the Dallas/Fort Worth airport in 1995, an
FAA agent with a weapon strapped to the small of his back set off a
metal detector. The screener used a hand wand.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation showed that the screener, who was on only his
third shift, had not completed training; he didn't realize that
when the agent spread his arms, his jacket stood away from his
back, shielding the gun from detection.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, a screener at Cleveland Hopkins
International Airport failed to detect a weapon smuggled in by
another agent in 1995, and USAir asked for leniency because the
screener had been on the job four years. That, said the airline in
a letter to the FAA, constituted ``extensive experience (in terms
of screener turnover).'' In this context, four years is a lengthy
career.
</P>
<P>
   At the checkpoint, ``the ability of people to find things on the
X-ray screen is shockingly low,'' said Dr. Michael Cantor, a
psychologist formerly employed at Argenbright, one of the nation's
largest airport security contractors. Some people are
detail-oriented and are very good at spotting guns or bombs. Others
have other useful traits, he said, being ``highly extroverted'' and
willing to challenge people who are often of higher social status.
</P>
<P>
   ``But supervisors are not savvy,'' Dr. Cantor said. ``They don't
do a division of labor.'' Workers rotate between viewing the X-ray
screen and the other checkpoint jobs. Cantor developed a quick test
to find detail-oriented people but could not persuade the FAA to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   People are, in fact, the weak spot in the system. Airlines and
the FAA are installing more and more high-tech machines to scan
bags, but the airlines do not always send the bags through.
Mechanics, baggage handlers and others often fail to wear required
identification, or fail to challenge persons not wearing it.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, experts say, to stay vigilant about a threat that is
intermittent at best. It's like looking through a haystack that
might have a needle in it. The FAA is even considering a checkpoint
system that would periodically show an X-ray image of a bag with a
gun in it, just to keep screeners on their toes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
