<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SO WHAT'S A RETIRED ROLE MODEL TO DO?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At his news conference Wednesday announcing his retirement from
basketball, Michael Jordan was asked if he might now try to help
``solve some of the world's problems.'' Quite a question with which
to confront a basketball player, but then Michael Jordan's persona,
like few others, transcends the hemispheres.
</P>
<P>
   He had said that he still has television commercials to perform
in, golf to play and three children to help bring up. Besides, he
added, ``I can't solve the world's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but he might be able to make a contribution, of the kind
he has consistently avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been exceedingly cautious as to where he places his
name. As a player, this might have been enough for him to retain
the image he so assiduously constructed for himself. While the
phrase, ``role model,'' has been overworked and distorted sometimes
beyond recognition and credulity, Jordan was exemplary in a variety
of ways: he was the best of employees, a good teammate, a dream to
coach, courteous to fans.
</P>
<P>
   He was conscious about looking neat off the court, and, except
for a few times playing poker with questionable characters and
inadvisably going to the gaming tables in Atlantic City the night
before a playoff game in New York, Jordan's image remained squeaky
clean. He has aligned himself to some charities, and he has made
some significant financial contributions _ he gave $1 million, for
example, to his alma mater, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is said to be worth $500 million. He has built this
fortune through salaries, but more from endorsing commercial
products and business interests. If Jordan would simply get 5
percent bank interest on his $500 million he would have to live on
$25 million a year. So it may be safe to say that he doesn't need
to do another Tweety Bird commercial the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   What he can do is take stands, when the situation requires. If
he isn't playing basketball, he should have enough time to read up
on issues. And there are few people in the world who might have the
influence Jordan does.
</P>
<P>
   The Nike debacle tarnished his image. When it was learned that
the shoe company he hyped mistreated employees in Southeast Asia,
Jordan said in effect that it wasn't any of his business. When that
didn't go over too well, he made overtures about visiting the
factories, but never found the time.
</P>
<P>
   After his father was shot to death in an act of random violence,
he might have said something publicly about the use of handguns in
the wrong hands. He chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   Always, he was fearful of tainting his image. Maybe now, that he
has terminated playing a game that little boys play, perhaps he
will put away childish things.
</P>
<P>
   It may be unfair to expect Jordan to be someone like Muhammad
Ali, who is not only on a religious crusade but who has also given
himself to being an international man of good will. As it happens,
though, Jordan does have the global stature of Ali.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be unfair to ask Jordan to be Jackie Robinson, who,
after his retirement from baseball, remained a powerful force in
politics and business in seeking fairer treatment for blacks. Nor
does Jordan have to be Jim Brown, who in the last several decades
has devoted much of his life to inner-city youth.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he have to be Arthur Ashe, who was a national and
global presence for equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that every black athlete or entertainer has an
obligation to thrust himself or herself into positions of
leadership,'' Ashe wrote in ``Days of Grace,'' his posthumously
published autobiography. ``However, our situation is increasingly
desperate, and I admire those athletes, and entertainers who
consciously try to give something back to people, if only by
exemplary behavior. I admire former stars such as Julius Erving in
basketball, or Lynn Swann in football, for what they have made of
themselves. I am less happy with the demureness of someone like
Michael Jordan, who is as popular as he is rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I defend Jordan's right to stay out of politics in
general, I think he made a mistake in declining to give any open
support to Harvey Gantt, the respected black politician who ran for
the U.S. Senate in 1990 from Jordan's home state of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the main point is not that Gantt and Jordan are both
black; rather, it is that Gantt's opponent, Jesse Helms, has a long
history of supporting segregation, and the contest was close. For
blacks across the America, that Senate contest was the most
important in decades. Instead, Jordan stuck to his apolitical
position. `I don't really know Gantt,' he said, in response to
criticism of his silence. `Well, Michael,' I would have told him,
`pick up the telephone and call him!'
</P>
<P>
   ``A few appearances with Gantt might well have made the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more faint-hearted than not taking a stand on an
issue you believe in is not believing in anything beyond the purely
personal.
</P>
<P>
   It would be terrible to contemplate that beneath Michael
Jordan's magnificent basketball exterior is, by choice, nothing but
a basketball interior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
