<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF GOD, THE BEAUTY OF HUMILITY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ Randall Cunningham is talking about the
power of God in his life, about the peacefulness he feels and about
the beauty of humility. The setting could be a pulpit instead of
the Minnesota Vikings' weight room. He is speaking so softly that
20 reporters lean closer to hear him. It is obviously worth
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cunningham expounded on conquering the Atlanta Falcons in
the National Football Conference championship game on Sunday, and
before he raved about how exhilarating it is to throw bombs to
Randy Moss, he talked about the excitement he feels to simply be
playing football while feeling so righteous about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of peace inside of me now because of what God
is doing for me and the power and grace that he has brought down on
me,'' Cunningham said. ``I'm happy that I'm standing here. I'm not
thinking that I've got to hurry up and get this interview done. I
appreciate each moment.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been so much for Cunningham to appreciate in a season
when he began as a backup for the second year and elevated himself
to the best quarterback in the National Football League. How did
Cunningham get here? Where had he been? Why is he successful again?
It is a story of resentment and retirement, retribution and
rejuvenation, and Cunningham is soaking up each second like a
35-year-old who has seen the light. That is because Cunningham has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate every grace that God has given me,'' he said.
``To be able to do this with this group of guys and this team means
a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And Cunningham's ascension means everything to the Vikings
(16-1), a team that feels empowered with its empowered quarterback
in charge of a dazzling offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Randall about this,'' said Dennis Green,
Minnesota's head coach. ``Randall Cunningham is a winner. He wants
to be a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Brad Johnson fractured his right leg in the second game of
the season, Cunningham figured he would be a backup again. But
after Johnson went down against St. Louis, Cunningham came in to
throw the game-winning touchdown pass in a 38-31 victory and never
gave the job back. Instead, he developed into the leader on an
offense that set a league record with 556 points. Cunningham threw
for 34 touchdowns, was intercepted just 10 times and had a
quarterback rating of 106, a Viking record and the best in the
league. ``What Randall has done,'' said Vikings receiver Cris
Carter, ``is phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Billick, the savvy offensive coordinator who had to
truncate the Minnesota offense when Cunningham replaced the injured
Johnson for five games last season, now watches the rangy
quarterback with the powerful arm thrive in the system in series
after splendid series. There were doubts about whether Cunningham,
too selfish and immature when he was with the Philadelphia Eagles,
could succeed in Minnesota's demanding scheme.
</P>
<P>
   But they vanished as Cunningham, who never had to dissect
defenses as much and never had weapons like Moss, Carter and
company in Philadelphia, stayed in the pocket longer, looked for
secondary receivers and learned how to be a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Randall is one of the great stories in sports in a
year that has had some great stories,'' Billick said. ``You talk
about a guy that has gone through what he's gone through, the
transformation that he's gone through and to be able to come in and
be the catalyst for the team the way he has, it's a great story.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is, but it was not so great for Cunningham when he left
Philadelphia feeling bitter and unwanted after 11 roller-coaster
seasons. He discovered he really was unwanted when no one signed
him for the 1996 season. So Cunningham retired and started a marble
company in Las Vegas. Even though Cunningham owned Custom Marble
and Granite Accessories, he worked with the laborers each day and
found out what life was like off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all humility,'' said Cunningham, who signed with the
Vikings in 1997. ``I don't think I had a huge ego, but I think I
was a certain way with my life. I learned a lot about myself. To
get down with guys and bang tile and grind counter tops and your
eyes are burning and your back hurts, it made me realize it was a
whole lot tougher out there. It showed me another side. It humbled
me.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his company ever made gravestones, Cunningham
said, ``I didn't deal in any, but I've kind of been resurrected.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Cunningham talks about the post-season as if he is
talking about the birth of a child. Two years removed from being a
tile man, Cunningham is two victories away from steering the
Vikings to a Super Bowl title. It is an improbable story, one that
Cunningham is cherishing, moment by moment, and discussing,
syllable by syllable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has sunk in to a certain extent, but I don't want it to
sink all the way in,'' said Cunningham. ``If you let it sink all
the way in and say, `That was great,' then I think you can begin to
take things for granted. That's the way I'm approaching it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
