<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     01-16 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM KELLY AND THE TWINS BATTLE THE ODDS  
 MYSTERY BUYER HE ISN'T  
 A JORDAN 2-POINTER 
PHILLIPS FALLOUT?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago Jim Leyland grew tired of losing with no break
in sight and parlayed his unhappiness into a World Series
championship and then a $2 million-a-year job. Tom Kelly is no less
tired of losing than Leyland was, but as loyal as Leyland was
initially, Kelly has remained so loyal he is going down with the
ship.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a Viking ship. The Vikings are the successful Minnesota
team, the one playing in a conference championship game in the
Twins' ball park Sunday. Kelly didn't plan to be at the game, but
it wasn't a case of sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years ago Jerry Burns and I were pretty close friends,''
Kelly related, referring to a former Vikings head coach. ``I used
to go to all the games. The last game he was coaching, they were
playing the Packers and both teams were around .500. It was the
man's last game. The Packers were ahead, 20-0, at the end of the
first half, and the Vikings, in my mind, didn't show up. I thought
that was a sad display of football. I left the building and never
went back to another game. I just had a bad feeling that day. I
couldn't understand the effort that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Effort has always played a major role in Kelly's style of
managing. It will be an even bigger component during the coming
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot to be said about playing the game the
right way, doing things right on the field,'' Kelly said. ``We're
going make sure we do all of those things. I don't know if that's
going to put people in the building, but the ones who show up
deserve that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins, who last season had the third poorest won-lost record
in the American League, aren't expected to fare any better in 1999.
Kelly, whose 12-year tenure in Minnesota is the longest of any
current professional manager or coach, could have thrown himself on
the mercy of the owner, Carl Pohlad, and asked out. But he did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people call it stupidity; some call it loyalty,'' Kelly
said. ``I haven't decided which it is with me.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the manager's plight even more dire, his team became
worse not long after Kelly reaffirmed his intention to remain with
the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple weeks after the season, the owner asked me to stay,''
the 48-year-old Kelly said. ``He outlined a little plan he had. It
was my understanding we were going to keep the shortstop, and we
didn't do that. That was the only thing I was disappointed about.
</P>
<P>
   The shortstop is Pat Meares, who last year had a $2.5 million
salary and would have gained about a $1 million raise through
salary arbitration. But when the Boston Red Sox gave Jose Offerman,
a free-agent infielder, $26 million for four years, the prospect of
a much bigger raise prompted the Twins to sever ties with Meares,
who has yet to sign with another team.
</P>
<P>
   A hefty salary for their shortstop would have made it impossible
for the Twins to reach Pohlad's desired payroll level of $10
million to $15 million. That was the ``little plan'' the owner
outlined after the season for Kelly, who said he understood the
reasoning. Their $24.5 million payroll didn't get the Twins
anywhere last season, and raising it to $30 million or so would not
have made a difference, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   So why did he decide to keep his job?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable here,'' Kelly said, referring to himself and
his wife, Sharon. ``We enjoy it here. My wife has family here. My
son lives here. Personally I have a lot of money tied up here. My
people explained if I move, I'm going to lose a lot of money that's
tied up in bonds and different things. So you add it all up and ask
is it economically important to move? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kelly acknowledged, he probably would have a better chance
to win elsewhere. But, he added, ``I weighed everything and decided
we'd stay here and do what the owner asked me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But he really would like to have had Meares' stabilizing
leadership in the infield. ``I'll try to remedy that situation,''
Kelly said. ``I'll see what we have in spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who also has lost Paul Molitor's overall team leadership,
will have plenty to scrutinize in spring training. Will Denny
Hocking, a good utility player, be able to replace Meares on an
everyday basis? Is Doug Mientkiewicz ready to play first base
regularly? How about Corey Koskie at third? Can Torii Hunter win
the center field job?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important of all, can Marty Cordova, who has
salaries totaling $6.75 million the next two years, find the bat
that made him rookie of the year in 1995 and an even better hitter
the next season but has deserted him the past two years?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the team's No. 1 pitcher, Brad Radke, whose record
plummeted from 20-10 to 12-14. The Twins have been reported to be
considering trading Radke, but Kelly said Terry Ryan, the team's
general manager, had not said anything to him about such a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be afraid to,'' Kelly said, still able to joke in the
face of serious adversity.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY BUYER HE ISN'T
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous telephone caller to the sports department of The
New York Times said he knew who bought the $3 million baseball, the
one Mark McGwire hit for his 70th home run that had been auctioned
the night before. Who was it? Allan Byer, the called said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the person who made the winning bid _ via telephone _
had chosen to remain anonymous, this tip was worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Byer is a limited partner in the ownership of the San
Francisco Giants. He also owns a clothing company and is in real
estate. A call was placed to his home in the San Francisco area.
His wife answered and said he wasn't home. All right, did she know
if he bought the McGwire ball?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did,'' she replied, obviously amused by the idea, ``he
hasn't told me. That's funny, but the answer is no. I'm sure he
hasn't gone completely insane over baseball, just a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Another call was then placed to Byer's son, Alex, who also is a
Giants limited partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to be kidding me,'' Alex Byer said, laughing. ``Oh,
that's absurd. That is outlandish. Maybe if the ball was 100
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   When Allan Byer was finally reached, he didn't laugh but said it
was not he who won the bidding. Why would someone think he could be
the $3 million man?
</P>
<P>
   ``I collect baseballs,'' Byer said. ``I have about 900.''
</P>
<P>
   To put his collection in economic perspective, Byer said he had
never determined the value of his collection but added, ``If it's
$100,000, that would be a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   His baseballs, he explained, are mostly from the 1940s through
the '70s, the time when baseball most magnetically held his
interest. His most valuable ball ($5,000, he estimated) is one with
Mel Ott's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' he said, ``that's an expensive ball. I'm not about
to spend $3 million for a baseball. Even if I could afford it, I
wouldn't do it. It doesn't make any kind of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Mrs. Byer knows her husband.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A JORDAN 2-POINTER
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan will be remembered for far different reasons, but
he may have a unique position in sports history: He most likely is
the only player to retire from two sports during labor disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jordan didn't announce his basketball retirement until
after the lockout had ended, he knew during the work stoppage that
he would not resume work when the league did. Nearly four years
ago, he retired from his short-lived baseball career during the
players strike and as a direct result of it.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan went to spring training with the Chicago White Sox minor
leaguers in 1995, but he became increasingly uncomfortable because
it appeared he would be labeled a replacement player, a designation
and a reputation he wanted no part of.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not what I'm here for,'' Jordan said on his first
day in camp when the subject of replacement games arose. ``I've
always said I wouldn't be a replacement player. I don't consider
myself one being here. I consider myself a minor leaguer. That's
why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the exhibition games approached and it became clear that
major league players would consider anyone who played in them
replacement players, Jordan decided it was time to go. And he went
_ back to the National Basketball Association, whose commissioner,
David Stern, nearly four years later tried to frighten the
locked-out players by threatening to use replacement players.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIPS FALLOUT?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since their general manager was accused of sexual
harassment in November, a charge he denied, the Mets have been
ultra-sensitive. They recently conducted employee seminars, for
example, on club policies, including sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a rumor last week that the Mets plan to ban sex
magazines, including the Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue, from
their clubhouse. David Howard, the club's senior vice president for
business and legal affairs, declined to confirm or deny the rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot comment,'' he said, ``about how our policies would be
applied in any instance.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets do plan a ban on sex magazines, they most likely
will encounter opposition from the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the union had a position on such club actions, Gene
Orza, the No. 2 official, said: ``If magazines of any kind were
allowed previously, if one of their working conditions was that
magazines were allowed, this would be a change and would have to be
negotiated with the union. They can't stop serving free food or not
allow employees to have cell phones. They can negotiate those
things with us, but they can't make unilateral changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The players could always sneak the magazines into the clubhouse
and read them under cover of politically correct periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
