<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-A     01-16 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A HIGH SCHOOL COACH HAS HIS DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note. No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Testaverde's high school coach is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve years. That is how long Bill Piner has waited to watch a
game like Sunday's, and right in his own living room.
</P>
<P>
   How many times, when Vinny Testaverde was throwing pro passes
for Tampa Bay, for Cleveland, for Baltimore, did he have to go
searching for a sports bar or a friend's house with a satellite
dish? How many lost Sundays, meaningless games, wasted seasons? How
many conversations with his former honorable mention high school
all-America player that sounded like pep talks and ended with the
promise that, sooner or later, Testaverde's time would come?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, sooner or later is right now, Sunday at Mile High
Stadium in Denver, the Jets and the Broncos, Testaverde trying to
answer the question asked of every quarterback who is handed a
competitive team: can you take it to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   This is no attempt to reduce the American Football Conference
championship game to a tale of dueling quarterbacks. History, which
records but seldom recalls which part of the offensive line broke
down, will do that, anyway. Testaverde's team will defeat John
Elway's team, or it won't. Testaverde will come out of this with
the benefit of the doubt for all the frustration that came before,
or he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three things that must be in place for a quarterback to be
successful are organization, supporting cast and coaching,'' said
Piner, who was Testaverde's coach at Sewanhaka High School in
Floral Park, N.Y. ``Vinny's never had all three of those things in
the past. His talent hasn't changed. But the ghosts are there. He
understands that. The realities of pro football are that you've got
to get to the game. Until you do, you're going to be thrown in with
the rest of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would be a shame, Piner said, a crying shame, and not
because Testaverde was blessed with a Super Bowl body. ``For the
way he has handled all he's been through, and the kind of person he
is, and has always been,'' Piner said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, now 54 and the athletic director at Cold Spring
Harbor (N.Y.) High School, is plenty partial, and why not? This
game, not only to be watched from home, hits home in a way that few
others could. Testaverde is much more than a former star pupil. He
is Piner's own son's boyhood hero, the big man on the University of
Miami's campus who received a letter one day from the Sewanhaka
High ball boy back on Long Island, asking that Testaverde come home
and be his sponsor on the day he would be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Piner is 25 now, but his father can close his eyes and
conjure up the most pleasing image in less time than Testaverde can
take the snap. He can still see his son walking into St. Barnabas
Church, hand in hand with Jimmy Johnson's starting quarterback. He
can remember a football in Testaverde's hand, and a copy of Sports
Illustrated magazine, with Alonzo Highsmith on the cover, following
a 1-point Miami victory over Nebraska in the 1984 Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this football?'' Testaverde asked the boy, who obediently
nodded. ``That's this ball right here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Vinny signed it and handed it to Michael,'' Bill Piner
said. ``He still has it.''
</P>
<P>
   Father and son have been riveted to their television screens, in
the storybook homecoming season of Vinny from Elmont. As the stakes
have risen, Sundays have been savored like a glass of fine wine
from a bottle unopened for 12 long years.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang in the Piner home late last Sunday afternoon,
the son calling from the road on business, out in western Canada,
but not out of Testaverde range. ``You see that game?'' he asked,
knowing there was no chance his father had not seen every play of
Jacksonville at Jets. They toasted the notion of Testaverde in
Denver, one step away.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Piners, nor anyone else, could have known what good
fortune Testaverde was returning to, though Bill Piner suspected
early on that, for Testaverde, this would no season on the brink,
or the bench. He and his wife, Patty, were chatting with Testaverde
at the Jets' Hofstra training camp last summer, when Piner noticed
Bill Parcells eyeing them from a distance. When Testaverde walked
away, the Tuna strolled over to introduce himself.
</P>
<P>
   They made small talk, and Parcells, one coach to a
coach-turned-administrator, teased Piner about making sure his
team's buses were on time. ``But right as he was walking away, he
looked back and said, `Vinny is doing a heck of a job,''' Piner
said. ``He said, `Don't worry about him; I know what I'm doing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Piner went home happy that his guy was in Parcells' hands. He
always hoped Testaverde would follow the path of other failed Tampa
Bay quarterbacks. Doug Williams won a Super Bowl in Washington.
Steve Young in San Francisco. Testaverde still has a mile high
climb just to get to Miami. One last, towering hurdle, but this
time, with the organization, supporting cast and coaching lined up
with Testaverde against the Broncos, and the ghosts of seasons
past.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
