<HEADLINE>
ETHAN NADEL, EXPERT ON BODY TEMPERATURE AND PEDAL-POWERED AIRPLANE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn., Mass, Ore., Calif.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ethan Richard Nadel, a Yale University physiologist and
authority on the body's temperature adjustments during exercise and
heat exposure, died on Dec. 26 at his home in Guilford, Conn. He
was 57.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, a Yale spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nadel was noted for his expertise in sports medicine, body
fitness and aging. At his death he held professorships of
epidemiology and public health and of cellular and molecular
physiology at the Yale School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 until last year he was director of the John B. Pierce
Laboratory at the Center for Research in Health and the
Environment. He oversaw the expansion and renovation of the
laboratory, added to its research staff of scientists and
postdoctoral students, and strengthened direct ties with the
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Dr. Nadel's research centered on the mechanisms by which
the body achieves physical fitness through exercise training and
becomes acclimatized to heat exposure. A special interest was the
physiological factors that regulate blood volume and their effects
on physical performance and heat tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   He also ran a project to observe patterns of exercise and
fitness among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Nadel, who was born in Washington, graduated from Williams
College in 1963 and earned master's and doctoral degrees in
environmental physiology at the University of California at Santa
Barbara. He completed postdoctoral studies at the Pierce Laboratory
before being appointed to the Yale faculty in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Nadel is survived by his wife, Emilia Bergamasco; his mother,
Ruth G. Nadel, of Washington; two daughters, Dana Foley, of
Manhattan, and Maya Bergamasco, of Guilford, and three brothers,
John B. and Roger S., of Los Angeles, and Gordon L., of Jasper,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Nadel was a consultant to the 1980s Massachusetts Institute of
Technology Daedalus Project in human-powered flight, named after
the figure in Greek mythology who, held prisoner on Crete by King
Minos, escaped to Sicily on wings of wax and feathers.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT project used a 70-pound airplane powered solely by
bicycle pedals. It completed a nonstop flight from Crete to the
Aegean island of Santorini in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Nadel called it a ``tremendous athletic feat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken it to running two three-hour marathons back to back,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
