A5920 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-AUTHORITY-2ndTa     01-16 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-AUTHORITY-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: got to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the issue are the insurance companies that
paid out millions of dollars more in claims than they expected
because of the magnitude of the Northridge quake.
</P>
<P>
   The temblor sprang from what is called a ``blind thrust'' fault
deep under the valley. This fault had never produced a rupture at
the earth's surface, thus its name. And the energy it released did
not have to travel far by earthquake standards to reach heavily
populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   The quake literally threw structures up in the air as well as
shook them from side to side, which compounded the damage.
</P>
<P>
   And the models that insurance companies had used to assess their
potential exposure for years became useless in less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bigger than the models indicated,'' Peter Debreceny, a
spokesman for Chicago-based Allstate Insurance Co. ``Nobody was
aware of this fault and the earth movement was different and
unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   All insurance is a balancing act on the part of both the
companies and consumers. Does the risk of something bad happening
merit the cost of a premium?
</P>
<P>
   That question has as many answers as there are homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, though.
</P>
<P>
   The quake laid waste to the kind of policies that were available
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect that you'll ever see the standard earthquake
policy that was there before,'' said Candysse Miller, regional
director of Western Insurance Information Service, an industry
trade group. ``It's just not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
