<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5921 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-AUTHORITY-2TAKE     01-16 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-AUTHORITY-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTERSHOCKS OF '94 QUAKE STILL ROCKING CALIFORNIA'S INSURANCE
INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Five years ago, on Jan. 17, 1994, the city shook
for 30 seconds -- enough time to wreck $25 billion in damage and
wipe out a pool of earthquake insurance premiums that had been
accumulating for a quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the financial aftershocks still reverberate throughout
the state's insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of companies and the California Earthquake Authority,
a quasi-governmental agency created by the legislature to bring
order out of chaos after the quake, are writing homeowner
earthquake insurance policies and trying to bring more choices to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, though, say what coverage is available falls far short
of offering any kind of security to property owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's overpriced and we don't think people are getting
enough coverage for what they are paying for,'' said Lillian
Salinger, a staff attorney at the Santa Monica, Calif.-based
Foundation for Taxpayer and Consumer Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the tab for the nation's worst natural disaster
continues to mount even as life, for the most part, has returned to
normal and the memories of that deadly day lose their sharp edges.
</P>
<P>
   As of last Sept. 30, property owners had filed 443,228 claims
with insurers to cover damage estimated at $15.3 billion, according
to the Institute for Business and Home Safety, a Boston-based
nonprofit group established by the insurance industry to help
reduce the impact of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   The institute ranks the Northridge quake second to Florida's
Hurricane Andrew in terms of loss to insured property and estimates
the total economic loss at $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with this kind of reality the insurance industry, much
like homeowners and businesses, had to rebuild. How it all shakes
out may eventually impact the way carriers across the country
structure policies to cover natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers, pushed to the precipice of insolvency under the
crushing weight of claims, shunned the marketplace after the 6.7
temblor. Ninety percent of those doing business in California
ceased accepting new homeowner customers or drastically cut back on
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the state needed to act. In 1995, then-Gov. Pete Wilson
signed AB 1366, sponsored by then-Assemblyman David Knowles,
R-Placerville, which became the framework for the quake coverage
product offered today.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the CEA was created and it soon began offering the
infamous bare bones ``mini-policy'' featuring a 15 percent
deductible on damage to the home, contents coverage capped at
$5,000 and living expenses capped at $1,500 while a home is being
repaired. Coverage rates are based on the house's location, with
those in quake-prone areas like Los Angeles paying some of the
highest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Before the quake deductibles typically were 5 percent to 10
percent and some policies included generous living expenses and
coverage on other structures like fences, patios and free-standing
garages.
</P>
<P>
   Now the CEA, with Knowles installed as chief executive officer,
is proposing a package it is touting as more consumer friendly.
</P>
<P>
   In December, on the same day Knowles became the agency head, the
CEA's board approved a rate reduction that averages 4.5 percent
statewide. And it is also seeking permission to offer supplemental
coverage during the year's second quarter. This could bring down
the deductible and expand allowances for temporary shelter and the
contents of a house.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the CEA to offer its basic policy and nine
other coverage options. Deductibles are 10 percent and 15 percent
and the coverage for contents and temporary living expenses are
capped at $100,000 and $15,000, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   A decision from the state Department of Insurance should come by
spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed rate schedule for the bare-bones policy, based
on ZIP codes, is no bargain for the suburban San Fernando Valley
area of Los Angeles. There are 84 ZIP codes in the region and 63 of
them will have their rates increased.
</P>
<P>
   And homeowners in 33 of those ZIP codes will pay the highest
rate of $4.98 per $1,000 of coverage. That means that for a home
costing $190,000, the premium would be $946 a year, up from $805
under the old structure.
</P>
<P>
   With the 15 percent deductible, the home would have to sustain
$28,500 in damage before the coverage kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the San Francisco Bay Area, another seismic hot
zone, is tabbed for a rate reduction with coverage set at between
$2.59 and $4.41 per $1,000 of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say the rates were set according to a quake risk
assessment by EQE International in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, the former chief deputy insurance commissioner, said
the new rate structure could entice more property owners to buy
policies. Currently the CEA policies cover about 900,000 property
holders in the state and the agency could pay $7 billion in claims.
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, the policies available now are intentionally not
designed to replicate what was offered in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bare-bones coverages were not designed to fully replace
spacious half-million-dollar homes or million-dollar mansions. They
were designed to get a roof back over people's heads and get their
life back in order as soon as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that, says former Chatsworth, Calif., resident Jerry
Yandell, who moved to Las Vegas last summer, is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Yandell was living in a Chatsworth townhouse in the
northwestern San Fernando Valley and owned eight rental properties.
He eventually discovered they had a total of $600,000 damage and
ended up in a lawsuit with his insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they did away with the standard quake policies and
implemented the CEA policies I decided I couldn't recover from
another quake so I took my assets and moved to Las Vegas,'' he
said. ``Hopefully by the end of '99 I will be out of the state of
California and it's really sad because I'm a native. I'm too old to
start over and this is my retirement, I've got to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
