<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BULGARY' IS THE LEAST OF ILLS IN THESE `UNTIED' STATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., S.C.)   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-EAGLES,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Given the gravity of the occasion and everything on
the line, an observer might reasonably expect an attention to
detail that is, well, unimpeachable.
</P>
<P>
   But a certain sloppiness has infected the trial of President
Clinton, at least when it comes to spelling.
</P>
<P>
   The first big mistake came on the first day, when senators
signed their oaths to be impartial with pens whose inscriptions
scrambled the letters in the country's name, and in a rather
ominous fashion. The senators would be serving and safeguarding the
``Untied States'' as they weighed the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Then the president's highly paid and skilled lawyers churned out
a trial memorandum for the Senate this week that bobbled their
boss's surname, dropping a consonant. The cover page read, ``Re
Impeachment of William Jefferson Cinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Thursday, Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, one of
the 13 Republican congressmen acting as prosecutors in the Senate
trial, took a pointer and turned toward an intricate chart with one
glaring mistake. The first word of its title was misspelled, so
that what Hutchinson was referring to was a ``Calender of Job
Search Activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's a spelling gremlin loose somewhere around the
United States Capitol. Or perhaps events are hurtling forward with
too much speed and passion to accommodate such niceties as
linguistic accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a flurry of activity,'' explained Christopher
Battle, a spokesman for Hutchinson. ``The charts did not arrive
until practically moments before the presentation. We were back
there behind the Senate chamber unpacking them even as the
congressman was preparing to go on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle said in an interview on Friday that Hutchinson and his
staff members noticed the error but decided it was not important
enough to ditch the chart altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But Battle said that other hastily produced charts for other
congressmen came back from printing companies so riddled with
errors that they were unusable. He spotted one, he said, that
listed the punishments for a crime called ``bulgary.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle said he had had only a few calls on Friday from people
who noticed the chart error. By contrast, John DeCrosta, a
spokesman for Senate President Pro Tempore Strom Thurmond of South
Carolina, said he had gotten scores of calls about the pens.
</P>
<P>
   DeCrosta conceded to being mystified by all the misspellings.
``They are certainly not indicative of the character or caliber of
the men and women in the Senate,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
