<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5923 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENGLISH-IMMERSION-LAD     01-16 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLISH-IMMERSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS, TEACHERS APPLAUDING ENGLISH-ONLY SWITCH IN L.A. SCHOOL
DISTRICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In Room 9 at Erwin Street Elementary School in
suburban Van Nuys, 19 young voices belt out the Pledge of
Allegiance, then segue into the Woody Guthrie folk song ``This Land
is Your Land'' -- in perfect English.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, the same group of second-graders was learning
how to read and write in Spanish in a bilingual class. But under
Proposition 227, passed in June by 61 percent of California voters,
bilingual education largely has been replaced with
English-immersion classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really transitioning very well,'' second-grade teacher
Amy D'Elia said. ``Parents have been very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months after the Los Angeles Unified School District began
implementing the law, teachers and parents in the San Fernando
Valley area of the city say the transition from bilingual education
to English immersion has been largely successful.
</P>
<P>
   At Erwin Street and other valley schools, the biggest challenge
posed by the new law has been improvising lesson plans because of a
lack of textbooks and other materials in English.
</P>
<P>
   Restricted in speaking the children's native languages, teachers
say they are using more visual aides and performing even more
hands-on demonstrations in class to overcome language barriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a change of the whole way they do things,''
Erwin Street Principal Marla Mondheim said. ``It's been a real
learning experience for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of Proposition 227 claim that the district is
defying the law by allowing teachers to use students' native
language and granting too many waivers to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little compliance in terms of what the
proposition intended to happen,'' said Alice Callaghan, an
Episcopal priest who is one of the leading proponents of
Proposition 227. ``This year, children should be beginning to read
and write in English, but that's not what's occurring in many, many
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Proposition 227, schools are required to teach non-native
speakers in a one-year English-immersion program. Students who
already know English, are 10 years old or older, or have special
needs can receive a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   About 11 percent of parents districtwide have requested and
received waivers so far. Since school officials had only two months
to implement Proposition 227 after it was approved by voters,
schools have had to overcome a number of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Douglass, principal of Fernangeles Elementary School
in Sun Valley in the San Fernando Valley, said the new law forced
the multitrack school to hold multiple parent meetings for each of
its three calendar sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible disruption,'' Douglass said. ``It's not bad
if you have 30 kids in a school, but when you have 800 Limited
English Proficient children, that's an incredible job to get every
one of those parents to come in and explain what the proposition
says and what their options are.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``When people voted for 227, they had no idea the
tremendous amount of time and money it would cost schools to
implement something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The law was implemented so quickly that teachers at Canoga Park
Elementary School in suburban Canoga Park didn't have a chance to
order English language textbooks and materials; they bought and
made their own supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to jump right in,'' said Lorraine Mariglia, principal
of Canoga Park.
</P>
<P>
   Campus teachers said their biggest challenge, so far, has been a
lack of textbooks and other materials in English. The district used
part of a major state allocation to buy Spanish readers -- now
unusable in English-immersion classrooms. The district is
considering exchanging the Spanish books for English ones with the
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our textbooks are brand new but we can't use the textbooks
because they're in Spanish,'' said D'Elia who has her pupils sing
songs, read poetry aloud and chant phonic exercises to help them
learn English and other subjects. ``We're modifying what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Materials is where we're feeling the biggest crunch,'' Erwin
Street Principal Mondheim said, explaining that teachers have
either made or bought their own materials to make up for the lack
of textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers have been real troopers,'' Mondheim said.
``They've been real professional and been real generous with their
time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers also are using visual aids and hand gestures -- along
with some Spanish -- to help the children understand English,
social studies, science and other academic subjects.
</P>
<P>
   At Canoga Park Elementary, teachers are using more hands-on
demonstrations in class, Mariglia said. One teacher explained
westward expansion by having pupils make covered wagons while
another had kids learn about seismic activity by making stilt
houses in sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more hands-on and a lot more vocabulary
development,'' Mariglia said. ``It's been a challenge, but
(teachers and pupils) have met the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents agree with the rosy review of some educators.
Mariam Adamian pulled her two boys out of bilingual education when
they were younger because she felt they weren't learning enough
English. Now her 10-year-old son is in an English-only classroom at
Erwin Street and has been identified as gifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing well,'' said Adamian, who pulled her son out of
bilingual education when he was in third grade. ``I was seeing that
he was being taught in Armenian a lot. He was learning more
(English) by playing outside with children and watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lidia Valladares, who placed her 8-year-old son in a
bilingual class at Fernangeles Elementary in Sun Valley, felt her
son would suffer academically in an English-only classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting him in an English-only class would be more
difficult,'' said Valladares, one of many parents at Fernangeles
who opted for a waiver. ``We wanted him to have English, but with
Spanish support.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fernangeles, about 92 percent of 521 students who were in
bilingual classes last year requested waivers to continue with the
bilingual courses, according to district records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents are very strongly in support of it. They want
their children to be bilingual,'' said Douglass, who said her
school has only one English-immersion class in the calendar session
that started in September.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Room 9 at Erwin Street Elementary, D'Elia watched
proudly as her second-graders eagerly corrected sentences in
English filled with grammatical and spelling mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about them,'' D'Elia said. ``If this is best,
let's make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
