<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMPEACH-EAGLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEEK EAGLES TO HELP THEM SOAR 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Attn: Fla, Tenn., Ohio, Texas, Va., N.Y., N.D., Ohio, Okla.)  By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Posing for a photographer at the entrance of
The Breakers, a palatial Italian Renaissance resort where wealthy
Republicans converged this week, former Gov. Lamar Alexander of
Tennessee could not resist a quip about the party of Abe Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't exactly a log cabin,'' he said, recalling Lincoln's
humble birthplace. Then, looking as if he was having second
thoughts, he added, ``This confirms everyone's worst suspicions of
what Republicans are.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Alexander stood patiently for a photographer because
he is running for president _ and knows he must do whatever he can
to get his mug in the newspaper as he struggles to stand out in an
increasingly crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other Republicans who gathered here were less eager
to draw attention to their presence at this sunny resort as
Washington is overcome not only by frosty weather but by the
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that contributors traveled here _ and politicians
from Capitol Hill flew in to hobnob with them _ is testament to how
nothing gets in the way of Republicans courting, wooing and hitting
up the party's most reliable donors. (Democrats are no different;
on Friday, Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and their wives were the
main speakers at the party's $15,000-a-person fund-raising dinner
and concert at the Corcoran Gallery in Washington).
</P>
<P>
   For years Republicans, including many corporate lobbyists, have
been accused of using these private retreats to buy access to the
powerful. Whether or not that is the case, it is clear from the
meetings at two lavish resorts here of the Republican Eagles and
Team 100 in the past few days that the party goes out of its way to
pamper its most reliable _ and altruistic _ backers.
</P>
<P>
   While contributors paid their own way, they were treated to
special panels on issues as well as their own sporting events, like
the ``Eagles Cup Tennis Tournament'' (the dress, participants were
advised, is ``tennis whites'') headed by Rep. Thomas J. Bliley Jr.
of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the ``Eagles' Cup Golf Tournament,'' headed by
Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma. (Nickles, the majority whip, had to
send his regrets at the last moment because of the impeachment
trial.) Then there was dinner on Wednesday night at Donald J.
Trump's gold-lined private club, Mar-a-Lago (Trump was out of
town).
</P>
<P>
   The politicians were as interested in rubbing elbows with the
donors as the donors were interested in rubbing elbows with the
politicians. Candidates here talked about ``stroking dollars'' from
monied Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, the top Republican
champion of campaign finance overhaul, had planned to speak at a
dinner here but he and several colleagues, including Trent Lott,
the Senate Republican leader, had to cancel because of the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians were undeterred. Alexander, who stepped down
as honorary chairman of the Eagles, and Rep. John R. Kasich of
Ohio, who is also running for president, found themselves chatting
up prospective fund-raisers for their campaigns. Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, the Republican whip, was the dinner speaker Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's buying access,'' said Mel Sembler, a shopping center
magnate who is the national party's finance chairman (and who is
being wooed to raise money for expected presidential races of
Alexander and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas). ``This is how you get
involved in the process: You entertain them a little; you put on
some panels.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the palm tree-dotted surroundings were so luxuriant that
a few participants seemed a bit embarrassed. ``They picked one of
the most expensive, exclusive locations in the country to hold a
major meeting,'' said Scott W. Luellen, an Eagle who owns an
information technology company in Fairfax, Va. ``It's a billboard
for hypocrisy. If you don't want to appear exclusive, don't hold
your meetings at a $400-a-night-hotel.'' (Luellen, in something of
a personal protest, stayed at a hotel down the street for half the
rate.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in the privileged world of big contributors, some are
bigger than others. While the Eagles (they must donate at least
$15,000 a year) stayed at the five-star Breakers, members of Team
100 (they must give $100,000 every Presidential year and $25,000
the other three years) were housed nearby at the opulent Four
Seasons. That hotel, Team 100 members were quick to point out, is
not as historic but has bigger rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Some Team 100 members, with their understated silver-and-black
name tags, see themselves as in a more exclusive class than the
Eagles, with their clunky, oversize gold-colored badges that
feature a drawing of an Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group here seems to be a real hybrid of well-to-do
business people and zealots,'' Luellen explained. ``It makes
discussions among Eagles require a lot of judiciousness. You don't
know if you're talking to a zealot or a successful businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Many big donors complain that they are not taken seriously
enough by politicians who do not sufficiently seek them out for
their counsel on political matters. But party officials seemed to
take their concerns seriously in the last few days, when many
contributors accused Jim Nicholson, the party chairman, and
congressional leaders, of allowing the party to be defined by
impeachment _ and not putting forth a forceful issue agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setting, the panels did not sound like fluff. For
example, Frank Gaffney, an assistant defense secretary under
President Ronald Reagan, made a presentation to the Eagles about
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, the Republican strategist who addressed a panel on
Presidential politics on Friday with Michael K. Deaver, President
Reagan's image adviser, warned that the donors should not be
underestimated. ``I was very impressed with the breadth of their
political knowledge and by their desire to make not only a
financial but a strategic contribution to the party,'' he said.
``It was not just a bunch of large donors just trying to have lunch
with someone who has power.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the benefits is that Eagles are included in periodic
conference calls with party officials. In a move to build
membership, the brochure says, ``new members receive a limited
edition lithograph of world famous painter John Ruthven's American
Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a subgroup called the Young Eagles, who receive
full benefits with a contribution of $7,500. ``We have Young Eagles
so we can get them started young in the political process,''
Sembler said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, weighty issues often took a back seat to conversations
about golf, tennis, and whether Trump's club was too garish. While
party officials wheeled in televisions to a luncheon so Eagles
could watch the opening of the Senate trial, many donors conceded
that they were not following the proceedings closely.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his panel address, Reed changed from his
pinstripe suit, dashed up to his room to put on his golfing attire
and headed for the links with Team 100 members (and prospective
future clients).
</P>
<P>
   While politicians were hunting for generous donors, the donors
were looking for favors as well. As he headed onto his green golf
cart for the Eagles' Cup Tournament, Curly Haugland, a
manufacturing executive in North Dakota, said: ``I'm here to get
the flavor for the national political conversation. I'm also trying
to find a speaker for our Lincoln Day dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Haugland can look forward to the next big
Eagles events. In April, in Washington, is ``The RNC Gala,'' billed
as ``the premier black-tie fund-raising event of the party.'' In
August, they will gather at the Sagamore Resort in Lake George,
N.Y., for ``A Day at the Saratoga Races with the members of the New
York Congressional delegation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
