<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER SEETHING OVER FASSEL'S `NO INJURED' EDICT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corey Miller spent more than seven years as a linebacker for the
Giants. He played through severely sprained ankles and broken ribs
and, most recently, had a bulging disk in his neck that threatened
his spinal cord if he took another hard hit. Miller did not mind
sacrificing his body, because he was highly paid for it. And
moreover, the Giants always treated him like family.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Miller said he was shocked when asked to leave the
field before a Giants home game this season because of Coach Jim
Fassel's rule that prohibits injured players from being around the
team. Miller said he was stopped from entering the Giants' locker
room for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of teams' handling of injured players has long been a
sensitive one in the National Football League. An ESPN report
earlier this season in which injured players emotionally discussed
their feelings made clear the extreme upset they can endure.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches like Fassel and Miami's Jimmy Johnson do not like having
injured players around practices or games because they consider
them a distraction. Unlike Johnson, Fassel will make exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who said the swelling from the disk between his sixth
and seventh vertebrae has improved dramatically and hopes to make a
comeback with some other team, said not being allowed around his
teammates was crushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone from being angry to being humiliated to being angry
again,'' he said. ``I'm not going to take this lying down. I'm
going to fight back.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   After sustaining the neck injury last August, Miller could not
play this season, but he still wanted to watch practices and be on
the sideline during games. He came to the season opener against
Washington on Sept. 6 and was on the field before the game,
speaking to teammates and coaches, when the Giants' trainer, Ronnie
Barnes, approached.
</P>
<P>
   Miller recalled, ``Ronnie came over and said: `You can't be on
the field. Jim doesn't want injured guys around.' The coach of the
Redskins was asking how I was doing, but my own coach was telling
me to leave the field?''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he then approached the locker room to clean out his
belongings, but was told by a team security official that he could
not go in. Miller said he was offered a ticket so he could watch
the game in the stands. He declined.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Miller said, cornerback Jason Sehorn, wearing a
brace because of season-ending knee surgery, greeted Miller and the
security official and proceeded into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I was not allowed in, but Jason was?'' said Miller. ``It
made me wonder, `What kind of double standard is going on here?'
Why bend the rules for one guy and not the other? Teammates were
telling me Jason was in the locker room all the time. When I would
watch games on television, Brian Williams, who was out with an eye
injury, was always on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller remained angry all season and finally met with the Giants
on Jan. 7. He and his agent, Ray Anderson, met with Fassel and
General Manager Ernie Accorsi at Giants Stadium for an
uncomfortable two hours. Miller said he and Fassel argued back and
forth, with the bulk of the conversation dealing with what Miller
perceived to be a double standard between him and Sehorn.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants declined to comment on the specifics of Miller's
accusations. Privately, however, team officials have confirmed that
Miller was barred from the locker room and was asked to leave the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Giants officials said the team implemented a policy preventing
anyone except owners, coaches and noninjured players from entering
the pre-game locker room. The policy was implemented, the officials
said, because the locker room had become too much like a social
club, with players even being asked to sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants also said that Miller never asked about the policy.
If he had, they said, this might have prevented his later
embarrassment. They added that Sehorn was excused from the rule on
several occasions for personal reasons after he discussed them to
the team, and the Giants thought that an exception in his case
needed to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tension between Miller and Fassel has to do with
their stormy personal relationship. Miller missed a voluntary June
camp for personal reasons, which upset Fassel. Miller also showed
up at camp in August carrying 12 extra pounds, again irritating
Fassel. Miller said the added weight was muscle and came from
having taken creatine, a supplement used by many players.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Fassel may disagree about much in their relationship,
but one thing is clear: A coach may risk alienating players if his
rule about not having injured players around the team is not
thoroughly explained to each of them.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why some players may hate such a rule.
With injuries such a key part of the game, it is disconcerting to a
player to know that one minute he may be risking serious injury to
play, and the next minute the team may not want him around because
he is hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the rule say it simply keeps players focused.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Miller, 30, a sixth-round draft pick who was second
on the team in sacks with six and a half in his third year, 1993,
will try to restart his career. He knows he will not be with the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching List Swells
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's program of videotaping coaches for a database that
owners can review when looking for candidates continues. And now,
more names of coaches taking part in the program are beginning to
leak out.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty pro coaches and seven college coaches have been
identified as potential candidates in a memo sent to team
executives by Roger Goodell, the N.F.L.'s executive vice president
in charge of league and football development.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the NFL assistants named were Green Bay's Emmitt Thomas
and Sherman Lewis, Oakland's Wille Shaw, Kansas City's Jimmy Raye,
Cincinnati's Jim Anderson, Jacksonville's Dick Jauron and Chris
Palmer, the former Carolina assistant Vic Fangio, Pittsburgh's Jim
Haslett, Denver's Gary Kubiak, Minnesota's Brian Billick, Atlanta's
Art Shell, the Jets' Bill Belichick, and the Giants' John Fox and
Johnnie Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Of the college coaches, the most notable are Stanford's Tyrone
Willingham, Miami's Butch Davis, Michigan State's Nick Saban and
Wisconsin's Barry Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many of the candidates will actually take part
in the program, which is designed in large part to improve the
hiring chances of minority candidates. About half the coaches on
the list are black and about half are white.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Montana Throws a Pass &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch this week signed with the agent
Tom Condon. How did Condon get him? Couch recently went to dinner
with the Hall of Fame quarterback Joe Montana, another Condon
client, and that basically sealed the deal. Couch is expected to be
the first pick in the April draft. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
