r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKE-ANNIVERSARY-2TA     01-16 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-ANNIVERSARY-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFECTS OF NORTHRIDGE EARTHQUAKE LINGER FOR SURVIVORS FIVE YEARS
LATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- When the Northridge Earthquake hit Jan. 17, 1994,
at 4:31 a.m., the swath of destruction included Mike Eller's
collection of English china -- and his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally lost my nerves. It was a trigger that really set me
off,'' he said, adding that since that day he has suffered heart
problems, depression and panic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it also brought the 57-year-old computer consultant closer
to his neighbors in suburban Winnetka in the San Fernando Valley
area of Los Angeles, and spurred him to prepare for the likelihood
of another quake.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Eller's experiences reflect those of us all.
Still, for every person who survived the 6.7-magnitude earthquake
there is a story as unique as Eller's.
</P>
<P>
   Some people shaken from bed resolved never to be caught unaware
again, and laid in supplies for The Big One. Others unwilling to
endure another quake simply packed up and left town.
</P>
<P>
   Some soldiered through the aftershocks and years of recovery and
now barely think of it. And still others look back on the
earthquake with curious fondness, choosing to remember the good
deeds and heroism in its aftermath. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; While many still mourn the the 57 confirmed deaths from the
quake, Valentine and Christina Rodriguez rejoice over their
``miracle baby.''
</P>
<P>
   When the quake hit, their son Johnnie was 12 days old and in
intensive care at Northridge Hospital Medical Center, where he
wasn't expected to survive a bout with jaundice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up yelling, `My baby, my baby,' '' Christina said, when
she felt the tremor at their home in Moorpark. And the couple's
anxiety deepened when it took them two days to learn he had been
transferred to a Tarzana hospital from the damaged Northridge
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to just keep cool,'' Valentine said. ``I kept telling
her, He's in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Johnnie is a typical 5-year-old, with bright eyes he
bashfully averts from strangers, and no signs of after-effects from
the quake or the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our miracle baby,'' said Christina, who relives her
elation by watching tapes of news accounts that revealed her boy
was at the Tarzana hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people went through a lot of things that day,''
Valentine added. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The temblor hurled Mayor Richard Riordan from a sound sleep to
the floor of his Brentwood home. He immediately tried his telephone
and cell phone, but neither worked, so he donned his sweats and
drove to the city's emergency operations center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a life where I've had enough crises,'' Riordan said.
``You don't get scared. You just go forward and do things.''
</P>
<P>
   That day five years ago was filled with see-saw emotions for
firefighter Mike Henry -- elation and pride at the lives saved, and
sadness for those who couldn't be rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, a hook-and-ladder driver with the Los Angeles Fire
Department, pulled Jerry Prezioso to safety after he had been
pinned for six hours from the waist down when the Northridge
Meadows apartments collapsed in Northridge, about 25 miles
northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Prezioso, 73, recalls the incident with laughs and jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the good people die,'' Prezioso cracked, and guessed that
it's not yet time to meet his maker. ``He keeps throwing me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the earthquake, Prezioso said, ``I don't particularly
like to discuss it, but I don't avoid it. There's going to be more
tragedies, and people need to have hope.''
</P>
<P>
   So Prezioso tries to do his part by spreading encouragement
through humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, laughter is the best medicine in the world. It makes
you forget about the pain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Henry said he doesn't dwell on the events of that day -- the
emergencies he faces every day at work prevent that. He thinks
about Northridge only when an anniversary reminds him, or when
Prezioso stops by the fire station with a bottle of homemade
marinara sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good friendship, and I'm sure it will be
lifelong,'' Henry said of their rapport, which started when they
talked for an hour while Prezioso lay buried. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; It's the cooperation and compassion that arose in the quake's
aftermath that enables Dr. Pamela Davis to look back on the day
with some good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good memories, once we got back our water and
electricity,'' said Davis of Northridge Hospital Medical Center.
``Everyone pulled together.''
</P>
<P>
   The quake displaced scores of people, who camped in parks or
parking lots near the hospital and lacked food or supplies for
their babies.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, her husband, Dr. Carl Jonokuchi, and some colleagues
decided to raise money for the needy and started selling T-shirts
with a map of the hospital site and the date of the earthquake on
the front. Printed on the back was ``Northridge Hospital Medical
Center,'' with ``Medical Center'' crossed out and replaced with
``epicenter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made 20 and ended up selling 2,000,'' Davis said. The
$10,000 raised went to the homeless surrounding the hospital for
food, diapers, medicine and other supplies. She said her family
also took two doctors into their home in the San Fernando Valley
community of West Hills after theirs had been destroyed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A Los Angeles native, Eller said he'd survived other
earthquakes, including one in the San Fernando Valley community of
Sylmar in 1971. ``Nothing has bothered me like this quake has,'' he
added quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is good that springs from tragedy. Eller said the
quake bonded him and his neighbors, as residents on his cul-de-sac
fired up barbecue grills to feed each other, and scooped out pool
water to flush toilets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had something to give each other,'' said Eller, who
retired from Pacific Bell and now works as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others around the city, he said he sought
psychological help to deal with his fears in the months and years
that followed the quake. But now he feels he could cope if another
``big one'' hit today.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: he feels he could cope if another ``big one'' hit
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some minor shakers. I could feel them but I didn't
feel the beginnings of a panic attack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the quake did spur him to buy a 26-foot travel trailer and
stock it with food and other supplies. Just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live in it. Wherever, whenever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Roller said the earthquake cost him much more than the mere
expense of rebuilding his home. He blames it for the loss of his
wife, Beatrice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stress of the earthquake brought on her death,'' said the
78-year-old resident of the San Fernando Valley community of Studio
City. He believes the breast cancer that killed her two years ago
originated with her trauma from the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to grieving for his spouse, Roller has had to
wrestle with his insurance company for a settlement, and then
redecorate alone the condominium where only a year before the
earthquake he and his wife had picked out every curtain, every
knickknack, every stick of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   But he was determined to rebuild -- to honor his wife's memory,
to please his children, and because he had nowhere else he wanted
to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of nights I was back were very traumatic. I
had sleeplessness, a loss of appetite,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still traumatic, but not as much,'' Roller said. ``Time
heals all wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   And, having already lost something he can't replace, Roller is
philosophical about the threat of another earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell, if it's going to happen, it's going to
happen,'' he said. ``If it does happen, I'm not going to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
