<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-U.S.-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA AND U.S. MEET OVER INSPECTION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ With tensions rising on the Korean peninsula, the
United States and North Korea opened new talks here Saturday over
whether North Korea would allow inspections of a suspected
underground nuclear facility.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, which are to continue Sunday, precede a new round of
four-way meetings planned here next week aimed at reaching a formal
peace treaty for the peninsula, where war ended 46 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the fourth such gathering in the past 13 months of
North and South Korea and their chief allies, China and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks North Korea has issued a series of unusually
belligerent statements, threatening that the United States ``will
be reduced to ashes and will no longer exist if they ignite the
train of war.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks follow a visit to South Korea by Secretary of Defense
William Cohen, who agreed on Friday with his South Korean
counterpart to strengthen their military alliance to counter ``a
wide range of possible threats'' from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Among the security concerns are the suspected underground
nuclear site and the North's missile capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the North launched a three-stage rocket over Japan,
catching American intelligence by surprise. The test demonstrated
that North Korean missiles could reach as far as Tokyo and all
major American military bases in South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond concerns over the missile program, satellite photos have
fueled suspicions that North Korea may also be developing one or
more underground nuclear installations.
</P>
<P>
   The activity has raised concerns in the Clinton administration
that the North will scuttle a 1994 accord that guarantees
international aid in return for a pledge from the North to freeze
its nuclear weapons effort.
</P>
<P>
   The accord also promised North Korea heavy fuel oil and two
nuclear power plants that would produce radioactive waste that
would be more difficult to turn into warheads.
</P>
<P>
   But the North has repeatedly accused Washington of not keeping
its end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Since last August, administration officials have been seeking
access to a vast underground installation in North Korea near
Kumchangri, about 25 miles northeast of Yongbyon. The site, the
topic of three previous rounds of talks, is expected to be the
prime topic Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   During his trip to Asia, Cohen said there was ``sufficient
evidence to be suspicious of that site.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   North Korea's response to demands for access has only added to
the anxieties. Initially officials demanded $300 million for a
visit, which was rejected. More recently they suggested that food
aid could win entry. Washington has already donated substantial
food supplies, including grain, to the famine-stricken North.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has argued that opening the site to outside scrutiny
can jeopardize its national security. And in December, North Korea
announced it was prepared to launch another medium-range missile.
</P>
<P>
   A second missile test could jeopardize congressional approval of
any further role in the 1994 accord. Congressional review of the
pact is expected by May.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering the administration's stand, Cohen's trip to East Asia
began with a declaration in Japan that it was important to
``maintain a very strong deterrent against any attack upon the
South or upon Japan on the part of North Korea.'' In South Korea,
where 37,000 American troops are stationed, Cohen reportedly
approved that nation's development of longer-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean missile development has so far been curbed because
of American concerns about proliferation. The specifics of the new
U.S.-South Korea arrangement have not yet been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the tensions, China's official news agency said, ``It
seems rather unjustified and ridiculous that the United States
should demand that it can monitor another country's activities
simply because it merely suspects that country is up to no good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
