<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURUNDI-SANCTIONS-600     01-16 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURUNDI-SANCTIONS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANCTIONED BURUNDI ANTICIPATES BREATHING EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi _ No gasoline is supposed to come into
Burundi, yet the streets here are full of cars. No commercial
flights are supposed to arrive, yet cargo planes land regularly
from Belgium and the United Arab Emirates, full of foreign goods
that no one here is supposed to get: radios, Moet &AMP; Chandon
Champagne, whisky, cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The strict economic sanctions imposed on Burundi by its
neighbors in August 1996 have not worked out exactly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   And now it looks increasingly likely that Burundi's neighbors
will decide late this week to suspend the sanctions, in an
acknowledgment that they have outlived their usefulness and may be
doing more harm than good to Burundi's fragile peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension of the sanctions is being awaited with great hope in
Burundi. They have become an all-purpose demon, cited as the cause
of everything from stunningly high prices, which is true, to the
continuation of ethnic and regional violence in Burundi, which
seems less certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the sanctions are lifted, people will live together
happily, with no problems,'' Marcel Averimana, 25, a shoe seller in
the main market in Bujumbura, said optimistically. Since a civil
war broke out in 1993, 200,000 people have been killed in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, a suspension of sanctions would be likely over time
to decrease prices, stimulate the economy and give the population a
psychological push toward normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   But there are dangers. It might also lead rebel fighters who
support the sanctions to increase their violence. In addition, some
outside officials are worried about the effect a suspension could
have on the stability of the government of Maj. Pierre Buyoya, who
led the coup in July 1996 that prompted the sanctions in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things do not improve when the sanctions are lifted,'' said
one relief agency official here, ``then this government has a
problem, maybe, because the expectations are very high.'' The
official spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In a search for regional stability in 1996, a group of East
African nations _including Tanzania, Rwanda, Uganda, Kenya,
Ethiopia and Zaire (now Congo) _ protested the coup by cutting
trade and transportation links to landlocked Burundi. Under the
embargo the countries, which surround Burundi, make use of their
roads and airspace off limits to people and goods bound there.
</P>
<P>
   There were several goals. One was to force Buyoya, who is Tutsi
and to some degree represents the powerful ethnic minority of Tutsi
who run Burundi, to negotiate with Hutu rebels. People from the
Hutu ethnic group make up 85 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Julius Nyerere, the former Tanzanian president, the
neighboring countries also demanded that Buyoya form a Tutsi-Hutu
coalition government and restore both the National Assembly and the
constitution drafted in 1993. He complied with their demands.
</P>
<P>
   International organizations did not oppose the sanctions
initially, in part because they were regarded as a local solution
to a local problem. But now there is much debate about whether they
were a success and how the tactic might affect other regional
efforts, ranging from peacekeeping to economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first year, smuggling became institutionalized as
goods leaked through the borders in vast quantities. Local
merchants, many from the Tutsi elite, made fortunes charging
wartime prices for basic goods. Their foreign partners, many
critics maintain, were often officials from the governments that
had imposed the sanctions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While goods like gasoline and luxury items were smuggled in
because they were profitable, relief officials say that necessities
like medicine and fertilizer often did not make it through. And
although merchants have few problems getting goods in, the costs
have doubled, tripled or more while salaries have remained flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy, but it's expensive,'' said Thomas Bangurambona,
37, a minister who was shopping at a market stall stocked with
biscuits from Oman, toothbrushes from Uganda and notebooks from
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the borders are porous, many experts argue, the
sanctions succeeded in that they caused enough hardship to force
Buyoya to negotiate with the rebels and other Hutu groups.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks began last summer in Arusha, Tanzania, and are
scheduled to resume Jan. 23. The main Hutu opposition party, the
Front for Democracy in Burundi, says Buyoya has also complied with
demands for greater power-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly brought Buyoya to the table,'' said a U.N.
official in New York, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It's
not perfect. But it's certainly a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, though, even supporters of the sanctions, like
the Organization of African Unity and the United Nations, have
urged that they be lifted. These groups argue that the effect on
Burundians has been too harsh and that the sanctions have killed
any economic progress in a country already isolated and desperately
impoverished. Several officials say they also worry that Tutsi
hard-liners may topple the government, or force Buyoya to end the
peace talks, unless some concrete gesture is made toward easing
economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. official said that Nyerere, the leader of the peace
talks, has said privately that at the Arusha talks he will urge a
suspension, not an outright lifting, of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   One major worry, officials say, is whether once sanctions are
withdrawn Buyoya will renege on his commitment to the peace talks.
Several outside officials said he seemed committed to the talks and
understood that any gains, with both the Hutu opposition and
international groups, would be wiped away if he backed out.
</P>
<P>
   And they point to his unusual provenance: Buyoya has taken power
twice by force, the first time in 1987, but he also has the odd
distinction of having given up power after organizing, and losing,
Burundi's first elections in 1993. The winner, the Hutu politician
Melchior Ndadaye, was assassinated soon after taking office,
igniting the violence that is now in its fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya's spokesman, Apollinaire Gahungu, said the stakes were
too high for the president to give up his commitment to peace
talks. Denis Nshimirimana, a Hutu opposition politician who is the
minister of public works, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone comes today and says he does not want to
negotiate,'' he said, ``nobody will support him. To say you don't
want to negotiate, that means you want to fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
