u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YACHTS-KEYWEST-NYT &LR;      01-16 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHTS-KEYWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE WEEK BECKONS BEST ITALIAN SAILORS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA LLOYD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An annual regatta on the warm, aquamarine seas off Key West,
Fla., is a winter magnet for many of the most competitive sailboats
in the United States. But this year, foreign teams, especially the
Italians, are flocking to the regatta as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Of the record 276 yachts expected to compete this week at the
GMC Yukon Yachting Key West Race Week, 37 are from 18 foreign
countries. But the team with the biggest presence is from Italy.
Six boats, twice as many as last year, are most likely to make
other sailors take notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italians are always incredibly competitive,'' Ken Read,
twice United States yachtsman of the year, said last week from
Newport, R.I. ``I sailed against some of them last fall at a world
championship in Hilton Head, S.C. They were the best prepared,
sailed the best boat, and were the fastest on the water. They're
not to be taken lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Italian contenders at Key West is a three-boat team
led by Breeze, a Farr 49 owned by Paolo Gaia of Milan. Its crew
makes no secret of its intention to use Key West as a training
ground for winning the Admiral's Cup next summer off England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Italian Sailing Federation has committed us to racing in
Key West,'' Tommaso Chieffi of Italy, helmsman for the 49-foot
Breeze, said in a recent telephone interview from Milan. ``They are
making it part of our selection trials for the Admiral's Cup. There
are not many opportunities to train and practice here in Europe. It
is a great chance for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians' hopes are tangled in a lost laurel at the 1997
Admiral's Cup. A freshening breeze allowed competing boats in the
final Fastnet Race that year to overtake Brava, the Italian leader.
It was enough to allow the United States to win over all instead.
</P>
<P>
   So focused are the Italians on winning next time that they are
looking at every ngle. By entering two of their new Sydney 40
yachts in Key West Race Week, they will be racing each other in a
mixed fleet. They are the only two boats of that design entered,
leaving race officials no choice but to place them in their own
handicap division.
</P>
<P>
   But the Italians don't care. The Sydney 40 is one of three new
designs required under Admiral's Cup team racing rules. That makes
it a necessary component of the nation's Admiral's Cup selection
trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a strange deal,'' said Dave Ullman, a sailmaker from
Newport Beach, Calif., who will crew on Seven Things, one of the
two Sydney 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be match-racing with each other to see who will be
first,'' Ullman said. ``What all the other boats in the class are
doing will be secondary. It is not a normal situation at all, which
will complicate things for the Italians enormously.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a long train of events that carries Italy's
momentum. ``They work on end-sight goals,'' Read said. ``Americans
tend to compete on an event-to-event basis. Every goal is
individualized. But the Italians are always looking at the end of
the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   For American sailors, Key West is one of those isolated goals.
Competition is apt to be intense regardless of which handicap rule
or one-design class a team belongs to. Among the top United States
sailors competing will be Ed Baird, Peter Holmberg, Peter Isler,
Gavin Brady, Harry Melges, Philip Garland and Vince Brun.
</P>
<P>
   International helmsmen include Russell Coutts of New Zealand,
the America's Cup skipper; and Karol Jablonski, of Germany, a
four-time iceboat world champion.
</P>
<P>
   In the team racing division, 10 groups will be competing with
three boats each. The winner of the team event will be determined
by overall scores from competition in each boat's respective class.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big boats competing in team racing are: Exposure, a
Castro 50 from the Netherlands; Beau Geste, a Farr 49 from China;
Rubin XV, a Judel-Vrolick 49 from Germany; Numbers, a Taylor 49
from New Zealand; Hi Fling, a Carroll Marine 60 from England; and
Idler, a Nelson/Marek 50 from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The competition calls for eight windward-leeward races from
Monday through Friday this week. Unlike in other national regattas,
the competition officials are not allowing teams to discard their
worst-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
