<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN PARTY'S NEW COALITION PARTNER SEEN AS `TIGER IN THE TENT'
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The coalition announced last week by Japan's governing
Liberal Democratic Party with the smaller Liberal Party was clearly
calculated to gain support in Parliament, but it may amount to more
trouble than it is worth, political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance pulls the Liberal Democrats farther to the
right, but it appears to have been based as much on arithmetic as
anything else. Although the party controls the Lower House, it
desperately needs more votes in the Upper House. It lost many seats
there in elections last summer, when the electorate turned out in
record numbers to vote for opposition party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much has been said about the seeming significance of the
realignment,'' the Japan Times, an English-language daily, said of
the new coalition in a lead editorial Friday. ``But it seems to
have ended up, essentially, as another political numbers game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberal Democrats could have used a better calculator.
Their alliance with the Liberals, the fourth-largest opposition
party, still leaves them 10 votes short of an outright majority in
the unruly Upper House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make it less likely that there will be elections any
time soon, and thus we have the primary reason for making the
coalition in the first place,'' said John Neuffer, senior political
analyst at the Mitsui Marine Research Institute. ``But I think the
LDP has bought itself a lot of trouble. It has let a tiger back
into the tent.''
</P>
<P>
   That tiger is Liberal Party leader Ichiro Ozawa, whose 1993
defection from the ruling party toppled it from power for the first
time since the 1950s. It returned to power in 1994 but only as part
of unstable coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Having Ozawa on board moves the Liberal Democrats decidedly to
the right. Whether Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi can manage the
internally fractious party from the right instead of its
traditional centrist position remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risky position for him,'' said Ikuo Kabashima, a
political- science professor at Tokyo University. ``It makes the
division between political parties here much clearer, and that
could be an opening for the opposition if the Liberal Democrats
make any mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, who is the closest thing Japanese politics has to a
neo-conservative of the Thatcher-Reagan mold, is a proponent of
smaller government and a bolder defense policy, which is a touchy
subject here.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the coalition almost foundered over Ozawa's demand for
a higher-profile role for Japanese forces involved in military
peacekeeping operations, including broadening the U.S.-Japanese
defense relationship. Ozawa and his supporters in the governing
party favor proposed legislation that would allow Japanese forces
to support U.S. forces in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Younger governing party leaders and opposition parties are
staunchly opposed to expanding the role of the Self Defense Forces,
as is much of the public. Indeed, many have speculated that Ozawa's
real aim in establishing a coalition is to split the governing
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ozawa is trying to deliver a punch to the ruling
party,'' Yukio Hatoyama, deputy secretary general of the Democratic
Party of Japan, the largest opposition party, said in an interview
when the Liberal Democrats and the Liberals were just beginning
their courtship.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of Ozawa's power, however, is unclear. Although the
Liberals did win their demands for a smaller Cabinet, they won only
one seat for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
