<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITY-SOCIALWORK-AR     01-16 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-SOCIALWORK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UTILITY AS SOCIAL WORKER: HELPING CUSTOMERS WITH THEIR LIVES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mich., Md., Wis.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, Joy Chatel appeared in Civil Court in
Brooklyn to account for her $7,000 unpaid gas bill. A contractor
had bilked her out of $40,000, she told the judge, forcing her to
close her beauty parlor. She had no income and four grandchildren
to raise. When her husband died at about this same time, she had to
barter two years of free hairstyling for a proper funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The judge instructed the lawyers from Brooklyn Union Gas Co. to
work out a payment plan with Ms. Chatel, and the lawyers handed her
account to Kristen Yontz. Ms. Yontz, though, is not a bill
collector. She is a social worker, part of the utility's experiment
in getting people to pay their bills by helping them straighten out
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   She has met regularly with Ms. Chatel, advising her on
low-interest loans, enrolling her in a grandparents support group,
steering her to federal emergency funds and, significantly for
Brooklyn Union, placing her on a flexible repayment plan. Ms.
Chatel is still struggling, but she has reopened her beauty parlor
and soon plans to rent the top two floors of her building.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help me manage,'' Ms. Chatel said.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities, which for decades have operated as regulated
quasi-governmental entities, have provided some aid and emergency
help to their low-income customers. Many collect fuel funds, which
are emergency grants for customers about to be cut off, as well as
weatherization programs and other services. But in these last few
years of shrinking government benefits, Brooklyn Union and a small
group of other utilities across the nation have gone one step
further, into a realm once reserved for nonprofit social service
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   At Brooklyn Union, Ms. Yontz is one of four certified social
workers in what the utility calls its On Track program; in three
years, its clients have reduced their arrears by an average of 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, which has one of the nation's first and most
extensive welfare-to-work programs, Wisconsin Gas works with
nonprofit agencies to offer social services for low-income
customers in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1994, a staff of 15 at Baltimore Gas &AMP; Electric,
including several social workers, have offered counseling, job
referrals and other services to about 3,000 low-income Maryland
families every year. ``As the social service community began to
scale back in some of the services they had provided, we began to
develop some of the needed assistance programs,'' said Don Dasher,
the utility's director of customer assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But if these initiatives are admired, they are not necessarily
imitated. Nationally, as the industry undergoes deregulation, many
utilities that once operated as regional monopolies are now cutting
costs to prepare for competition. Because low-income programs often
do not pay for themselves, some utilities are quietly eliminating
them.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Consolidated Gas Co. in Detroit recently discontinued a
program much like the one now offered by Brooklyn Union, in part, a
company official said, to prepare for deregulation. Last year, the
New York State Electric &AMP; Gas Corp., an upstate utility, had
proposed eliminating one of its two low-income programs. After
criticism from advocacy groups, the New York Public Service
Commission, which regulates utilities in the state, required the
company to continue and expand the program. But advocates for
low-income customers warn that other utilities could also try to
eliminate such programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could happen is that an outside supplier of natural gas
who is located in, say, Texas, is not committed to the people
Brooklyn Union has been serving for the last 20 years,'' said Jim
Benfield, executive director of Campaign to Keep America Warm, a
low-income advocacy group in Washington. ``In order to stay
competitive, Brooklyn Union is going to have to get out of the
social service business.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a buoyant national economy, advocates say, large numbers
of low-income customers continue to struggle to meet their utility
bills, particularly during the bitter cold of winter. For
competitive reasons, Brooklyn Union refused to release the dollar
amount of unpaid bills due the company. But in Ohio, which collects
such statistics on a statewide basis, the dollar amount of unpaid
bills by all low-income utility customers has risen to about $110
million in 1998 from $48 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation, advocates say, is Congress' cutting the federal
emergency relief program for the poor, known as the Low Income Home
Energy Assistance Program. Its funding has fallen to $1.1 billion
this year from $2.1 billion in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn Union, which supplies natural gas to 1.1 million
customers in Brooklyn, Queens and Staten Island, began On Track as
part of a rate agreement with the Public Service Commission that
also created the utility's current holding company, Keyspan Energy.
Before On Track, company officials commissioned an internal study
in 1992 and 1993 that found that 43 percent of the company's
delinquent residential customers were considered low income, or
about 150 percent of the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Today, On Track is two-pronged: 1,500 delinquent low-income
customers are selected each year. Most of these customers receive
telephone counseling, money management advice, a video cassette
recorder, a series of instructive videos and a magenta box to help
organize their bills. As an incentive, participants in the program
are forgiven $400 against unpaid bills. Of the overall group, 250
customers, usually with debts greater than $1,000, are assigned a
social worker.
</P>
<P>
   The program costs slightly more than $1 million a year, said
James M. Jacob, the manager of Brooklyn Union's consumer advocacy
division. He said the program essentially pays for itself by
reducing the company's overall collection costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yontz, the 27-year-old daughter of an Illinois farmer, knew
very little about utilities when she joined Brooklyn Union in
October 1995. She had decided to become a social worker after a job
in a soup kitchen, and was completing her master's degree in social
work at Columbia University when she heard about the job at
Brooklyn Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really strange,'' Ms. Yontz said. ``I feel like I say all
the time, `Yes, I am a social worker, and yes, I work for the gas
company.'''
</P>
<P>
   She now rattles around Brooklyn in a company sedan, calling on
about 50 ``clients'' in a job that seems equal parts cheerleader
and trouble-shooter. Usually, the people she meets hover just above
poverty line: grandparents on fixed incomes or people like Ms.
Chatel, whose modest income falls short of her monthly expenses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to teach people not to live in crisis, and maybe
learn different behavior so they are not living crisis to crisis
and month to month,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yontz describes part of her duties as ``advocating,'' or
navigating the social service system, whether government or
nonprofit, to find any and all benefits that a client might qualify
for without knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   In her role as adviser, Ms. Yontz says she often has to help
people make difficult decisions. When she and Ms. Chatel discussed
ways to earn more income, they decided to rent the two floors atop
the beauty parlor to help meet the mortgage. But doing so meant
telling Ms. Chatel's 26-year-old son to move out and find a job.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Norlander, deputy director of Public Utility Law Project,
an advocacy group for low-income customers based in Albany,
commended On Track as a responsible collections program. But
Norlander said the Public Service Commission needs to place as much
emphasis on rate reductions for the poor as on collection programs.
In Massachusetts, he said low-income customers qualify for rate
reductions of up to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamental affordability is a major issue that must be
addressed, and it has not been addressed by the Public Service
Commission,'' Norlander said. ``They're only giving it lip
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Flanagan, a spokesman for the commission, said that
officials were aware of the problems facing poor customers in a
deregulated environment and that the commission was experimenting
with pilot programs in two upstate counties to find ways to hold
down rates.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Yontz, deregulation and its potential problems are just
distant, unheard noise by the people she serves. Last week, she
visited Samuel Wilson, a 92-year-old Jamaican immigrant, now a U.S.
citizen, who lives alone in a small apartment in Canarsie,
Brooklyn. Wilson had received $129 every month in food stamps for
more years than he can remember when, last year, the benefit
inexplicably stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yontz intervened, discovering that Wilson had either failed
to fill out necessary paperwork or the form simply had not been
sent. She quickly organized his application and appeared at the
welfare office on his behalf. While Wilson waited two months for
his food stamps to be restored, Ms. Yontz and social workers from a
social service agency arranged for meals from a food pantry.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilson's landlord recently sold the Canarsie row house, Ms.
Yontz helped Wilson navigate the social-service bureaucracy,
finding him a subsidized studio apartment in Far Rockaway, Queens.
He will likely move later this month. ``You can't imagine how happy
I am to have you here today,'' Wilson told Ms. Yontz before she
left last week. ``I wish you were here all day to talk to, to cheer
me up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
