</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLICE-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CITY POLICE CHIEF PURGES TOP BRASS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Alejandro Gertz, the Mexico City police chief, sat
at his desk at headquarters the other day reviewing the dismal
results from a recent inspection that led him to dismiss six of his
seven top police commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This officer wasn't at his post,'' Gertz said, leafing through
a stack of inspection reports. ``This guy didn't have his weapon.
This one had taken his badge off. Here's a fellow driving his
patrol car outside his precinct. This guy was asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This can't continue!'' Gertz said, slamming his hand on his
desk. ``I won't be held hostage to corruption and sloth.''
</P>
<P>
   His dismissal of the six top commanders this month was his most
forceful action since Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the city's reformist
mayor, appointed him in August to modernize the force. He said the
dismissed officers had been systematically undermining his
campaigns against graft, inefficiency and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never told me, `I'm not going to obey this order,' ''
Gertz said. ``They just wouldn't do what I told them, so what could
I do but get rid of them?''
</P>
<P>
   The dismissed officers included the chief of operations and all
five regional commanders, who oversaw the 52 precincts and 36,000
uniformed officers. The only top commander to survive the purge was
Gertz's chief of staff, Miguel Gonzalo Adalid.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 7, the police chief dismissed five more senior
commanders, all members of the headquarters staff.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office, Gertz said, he has set up a computerized
statistical system that allows him to track crime rates virtually
block by block. As a result, he can review the performance of his
force's officers far more consistently, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In November, shortly after the system was up and running, Gertz
announced a surge in violent crime, and he accused organized crime
leaders, who he said worked closely with corrupt commanders, of
ordering the violence with the aim of beating back his reforms. In
recent weeks, however, violent crime has fallen back to levels that
were average before he took office, Gertz said.
</P>
<P>
   Truck hijackings and car thefts have fallen, he said, partly
because major companies now report to authorities when their
tractor-trailers enter the city, allowing police computers to
monitor their movements.
</P>
<P>
   But armed robberies, home burglaries and many other crimes
continue at epidemic rates, he said. The stable rates of many
crimes, he said, suggest that police commanders and organized crime
leaders have set up a quota system in which a certain number of
crimes are tolerated as long as criminals share the profits with
the police.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gertz, a former university rector who once headed Mexico's
antinarcotics campaign, is the latest in a string of recent police
chiefs who have promised to end corruption. His predecessors all
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cardenas took office in December 1997 as the city's first
elected mayor, the federal government ran Mexico City directly, and
President Ernesto Zedillo ordered thousands of soldiers into police
duty and installed a group of generals to command them. But that
effort collapsed when the generals were accused of organizing death
squads to kill recidivist teen-age criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Gertz said he decided to dismiss almost all his top supervisors
after reviewing the latest depressing internal reports on his
force. ``You know what I felt after I let these people go?'' he
said. ``I felt freer. Suddenly I had a sensation of not being
surrounded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-MA     01-16 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-MATCHUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING A COMMON GOAL: EXPLOITING MISMATCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add graphic note. No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Both offenses in the American Football Conference
championship game on Sunday will slyly attempt to create
mismatches, either by formation or by movement. Then both will try
to take those mismatches and burn the defenses. All day long.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to trick the defense with a crafty appearance. Force
it, for example, to mistakenly place a slow linebacker in pass
coverage on a speedy wide receiver, or a sluggish strong safety on
a lightning-quick running back. Create a situation in which a tiny
cornerback is blocked and crushed on a running play by a mammoth
pulling offensive lineman, or the shortest defender on the field is
forced to pass protect against the tallest offensive player on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Football is a game of matchups. Creating mismatches in those
matchups is a staple of the game. The Jets and the Denver Broncos,
Sunday's AFC title finalists, have been masters of the tactic this
season.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason both teams have reached this pinnacle in Mile
High Stadium, an emotional and dramatic stage on which to decide
who advances to Super Bowl XXXIII and who heads home for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it; the Jets do it,'' said Mike Shanahan, the Denver
head coach. ``In the mismatch game is where you tend to find a
number of big plays being made.''
</P>
<P>
   Both team's offenses have soared, in part, by employing this
scheme. The Broncos rank first in the conference in total offense
(380.8 yards a game); the Jets rank second (357.2). The Broncos
rank first in the conference in points scored (31.3 a game); the
Jets rank second (26.0).
</P>
<P>
   Each offense versus each defense will be a sparkling show. But
since the defending Super Bowl champion Broncos feature the star
quarterback John Elway, the 2,000-yard rusher Terrell Davis and
Shanahan's crisp play-calling, the guessing game between Shanahan
and Bill Belichick, the Jets defensive coordinator, will be the
game within the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known Bill for years and I have called games against
him before,'' Shanahan said. ``He's adjusted over the years and so
have I. This will be fun. I've looked at all 16 Jets games from
their regular season. I looked at them in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked, what if Belichick had looked at the Broncos for
that period and even at tapes of the Broncos' preseason games?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't get a picture after 16 games ... '' Shanahan
said, a bit taken aback at even the thought that the Jets, that
Belichick, could possibly be more prepared for the mismatch game
than he. ``Let's just say if they have and it works, they are
smarter than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have been smart in gathering players. That is where
it starts.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has a quarterback, a running back, a tight end (Shannon
Sharpe) and receivers (Ed McCaffrey and Rod Smith) who are
explosive and spread defenses. The Jets, in their quarterback
(Vinny Testaverde), running back (Curtis Martin), tight end (Kyle
Brady) and receivers (Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet) believe
they can match Denver's offensive power. Toss in two strong,
versatile offensive lines and intricate designs to create
mismatches, and what lurks is a blinding offensive show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about two multiple-formation teams who rely on
this strategy a little more than others,'' said Norv Turner, the
Washington Redskins' head coach. ``You're talking about teams who
have a lot of people who can do a lot of things. It's the
quarterbacks; they are experienced. It's the personnel. Even the
backups behind these guys are good. These are teams that are
efficient. You can draw it up all day long. The players have to
perform it. They do.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for that, said Chan Gailey, the Dallas
Cowboys' head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be different, to scheme things that create mismatches, a
lot of times you have to have people in place who have been there
for awhile,'' Gailey said. ``This Denver offense has been together
for a little while with the same coaches. That is a great edge.
They can work off a base that everyone there knows. And then later
in the season they can say, `Hey, remember in Week 3 when we did
this? Let's change this part of it and do this.' That kind of stuff
on a particular play can go back even a year or two. And you have
to have smart players to do that. And a coach willing to try
different things. Denver puts all of this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating mismatches starts with formations and movement, and the
effect is bolstered when defenses make mistakes in substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use two tight ends, two backs and a wide receiver, does
the defense stay with four linebackers?'' Gailey asked. ``If so,
you've got an edge in the running game. If you use three wides, a
running back and a tight end, do they stay in their base defense?
That's to your advantage on the deep pass. If you line up with five
wide receivers, the quarterback looks to see which one has the
mismatch. If you put a tight end out wide as a wide receiver, if
the cornerback walks out there it tells the quarterback zone. If a
linebacker walks out, it is man coverage. These are indicators that
set up your mismatches on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and the Broncos play it both ways: both will read and
react on offense and at other times both will dictate.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey prefers read and react. He likes to see what the defense
does, how it responds to formations, and then adjust to find the
mismatch. Is it a defense based on speed and getting upfield? Is is
it one that sits back and waits for you? Is there a lineman who
pushes so hard upfield that the ball can be thrown behind him in
the vacated spot? Gailey searches for these keys.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Turner, however, likes the attack mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best strategy can be to dictate,'' Turner said. ``I like
these teams' offenses when they create situations where they are
not reacting to people but people are reacting to them. Denver does
a great job in the running game of the cutback runs. I coached
Marcus Allen at USC and he had this knack of cutting back on his
runs near the line of scrimmage. So, we said, if he's going to be
doing that, let's give him some help. Let's block the back side.''
</P>
<P>
   That creates plenty of mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find ourselves here in the running game making sure the
backside is tied down and worked out,'' said Mark Schlereth, a
Broncos offensive guard. ``That means keeping the safeties blocked.
Sometimes linemen do that. It is a big advantage for us. It has
become a major part of our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the coaching booth, defensive coaches look for the
offensive players being sent in by position from the sideline and
attempt to match that by inserting corresponding defensive
personnel. Three wide receivers come in? Three cover guys are sent
in to cover them. If a mistake is made in personnel deployment
Sunday, it could prove costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why there were screams a few years ago when teams were
putting 12 men in the huddle and then one guy was leaving the field
before the snap,'' Turner said. ``You couldn't set your defense.
But sometimes, despite that, the mistakes upstairs still happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And a huge mismatch can ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Matchups in Sunday's game could swing on a healthy player versus
an injured one. On faulty defensive technique, on picking on a
defensive player at a particular position at a particular spot on
the field because of his faulty technique.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets would love to see their fast receiver Dedric Ward
aligned in man coverage versus the slower Broncos safety Tyrone
Braxton. The Broncos would enjoy finding the 6-foot-5-inch receiver
Ed McCaffrey versus the 5-8 cornerback Ray Mickens on a lobbed
pass, a jump-ball situation in the end zone. Jets receiver Keyshawn
Johnson would smile if he were covered in a crossing pattern by
Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski. Schlereth (287 pounds) would
grin if he found himself pulling and blocking cornerback Aaron
Glenn (185 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and Broncos will spread the defenses thin. Use their
offensive talent. Create mismatches in the matchups.
</P>
<P>
   But here is the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people start spreading out in this game and creating
things, they also can leave a variety of holes,'' Turner said.
``And if a defense is able to find and defend the hot receiver for
the quarterback and take away that dump-off pass, take away the
quarterback's safety valve, then you are vulnerable. You've got to
be able to handle the blitz and pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both defenses from the Jets and Broncos are going to create
overloads on the blocking schemes with major blitzes. The team that
handles that best will enjoy the mismatch game. The team that
doesn't will be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1259EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
