</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND CONGRESS PLAYS THE WINDMILL
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Facts are the enemy of truth,'' says poor, pure-hearted Don
Quixote in ``Man of La Mancha,'' the musical based on Cervantes'
classic novel.
</P>
<P>
   A friend recently gave Rep. Henry Hyde, the House Judiciary
chairman, the original Broadway cast recording of that show, and
when in odd moments he listens to its hummable tunes about the
Spanish Inquisition, he also hears Quixote sing: ``Heathens and
wizards and serpents of sin, all your dastardly doings are past.
For a holy endeavor is now to begin and virtue shall triumph at
last!''
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``The Impossible Dream,'' theme song of the virtuous
but doomed, the president's chief prosecutor in the Senate also
gets a dose of such relevant numbers as ``A Little Gossip,'' and
``I'm Only Thinking of Him.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, America is divided over whether Hyde is now
appearing in the role of the romantic, persecuted Quixote, or the
pitiless fellow inmate who shoves a looking glass in the deluded
hero's face and shouts: ``Look in the mirror of reality and behold
things as they truly are. Drown in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jones clearly isn't his Dulcinea, the victimized barmaid
in whom Quixote sees only virtue; on ABC's ``Nightline,'' Hyde
referred to her sexual harassment suit against the president as a
``petty matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps when Quixote wonders if facts really are the enemy
of truth, he means that everything depends on what the meaning of
``facts'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Leigh, who wrote the music for the show, said he doesn't
like either the president or his prosecutor for the part. But when
he read that Hyde was a fan, he said, ``After one loud guffaw I
thought, well, if it helps him turn back into Dr. Jekyll, then I'm
glad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
