<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      01-16 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
364 DAYS LATER, SHADOW OF JONES SUIT LENGTHENS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Va., Texas)   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK, IMPEACH-EAGLES,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(jw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was the eve of the most woeful of anniversaries,
that of President Clinton's deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
Saturday dawned with the Senate's trudging through the wintry
morning to attend a third salvo of impeachment arguments that the
president deserves to be banished for all the misdeeds that came to
light following upon that ill-fated event.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that lawsuit has been settled. But it continues to
haunt the president, leaving him on the brink of political
extinction before the Senate. His defense lawyers complained
outside the chamber on Friday that the House Republican prosecutors
had been referring ``again and again'' to Clinton's deposition in
the Jones suit, despite the fact that the full House rejected
perjury charges built around that testimony.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17 a year ago, long months of chaos began with an
unlikely trip of a few blocks by the president to his lawyer's
office, his limousine notably minus the fender flags of office
because of his personal mission. It was in the Jones deposition
that the president first denied a sexual liaison with Monica
Lewinsky, even as the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr, was laying the groundwork for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate closes in on final judgment, the House prosecutors
are insisting that now is the time to bring Ms. Lewinsky forward,
to observe her and judge her credibility as she tells her story to
the Senate and the nation. ``Let's examine her face to face,'' said
one House prosecutor, Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla. The Democrats only
shudder at the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   NO `JURORS,' BUT A JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are still smarting from the rebuff delivered by
Chief Justice William Rehnquist, the trial chairman, when he agreed
with an unusual Democratic floor objection on Friday that it was
inaccurate to call the senators ``jurors,'' because they are a
complete court of impeachment with far more powerful options than a
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House Judiciary Committee, where the
impeachment articles were spawned, immediately put out a sharp
statement praising their own prosecutorial arguments before the
Senate. ``One hopes that such protests arise from linguistic
scrupulosity and not the fear that `jurors' are expected to convict
when the evidence is overwhelming,'' declared the committee
spokesman, Paul McNulty, in an echo of the House rancor the
senators have vowed not to duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice directed the ``jurors'' ruling at Rep. Bob
Barr, R-Ga., and thereby delighted Democrats. The sharp-tongued
Barr is a conservative acolyte of former Speaker Newt Gingrich and
bare-knuckled Clinton critic who first urged the House on toward
impeachment. ``We were lectured to,'' said Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga.,
annoyed like some other lawmakers at Barr's tone of professorial
self-certainty in addressing the Senate as an outsider. ``This is
not the way you win an argument in the Senate,'' said Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   The incident underlined the question of just how much guidance
senators, Republican or Democrat, will tolerate from House visitors
eager to see the president removed.
</P>
<P>
   SCURRYING IN THE TUNNELS
</P>
<P>
   Because of intensified security cordons around the Senate
chamber's work areas, the trial has seen the blossoming of a great
subterranean stakeout of passing senators by news workers who now
loiter about the network of pedestrian tunnels under the Capitol.
Police trying to frustrate reporters and shield senators are
themselves being frustrated by the reporters' guerrilla tactic.
There are Keystone Kops chases at times that offer a leitmotif to
the trial above. When the senators' special electric subway system
broke down on Friday, the tunnel walks were the only alternative.
Reporters fell upon a veritable sluiceway of talkative senators.
</P>
<P>
   During the short trial breaks, police try to rope the news
workers off into pens, but they have blazed roundabout routes to
the ground-floor cafeteria where senators have a fast cup of coffee
before resuming their silent task as ``triers,'' not jurors.
``You've got a tough job,'' Sen. John Warner, R-Va., told reporters
who found their way to his side at the cafeteria. ``And I've got a
tough job _ keeping quiet,'' he added apologetically.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED AUDIENCE
</P>
<P>
   The assortment of people who turn up each day for the trial
offers a wide range of presidential friends and foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see justice dispensed,'' said David Bossie, a
Republican specialist in negative research. He served on the
Whitewater investigation by Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same motive, to see justice through to the very end,
was voiced by a far different politician in daily attendance, Rep.
Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas, who as a member of the House Judiciary
Committee fought the president's impeachment every bit as much as
Bossie was cheered by it.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORLD GOES ON
</P>
<P>
   Anyone reeling from trial fatigue and yearning for the
nontabloid routine of self-government could, in the spirit of
political Groundhog Day, warily turn to the rack of Senate press
releases. Of 17 publicity handbills being offered on midday Friday,
only four were about impeachment. The rest were on sundry mundane
legislative topics, with action verbs like ``announces'' and
``praises'' and ``launches'' in the headlines, and not a mention of
high crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5950 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-HONDURAS-HURRICANE-     01-16 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HONDURAS-HURRICANE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL LOCKED IN A STORM'S HORROR, HONDURANS DESPAIR OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add photo note. No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA DE AGUAN, Honduras _ Mirtha Martinez Arriola returned
to her home on a recent Sunday and wept when she saw her husband's
hat floating in brackish water beneath the roofless frame house
where they once lived.
</P>
<P>
   She wept not for the things they had lost, not for the years
they had worked to build their home and found a family, but for him
and for three of her children, who were all swept out to sea in
October and drowned in the worst hurricane of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to go far from here, to forget all this,'' she
said. ``Somewhere where there is a future.''
</P>
<P>
   Around her lay the detritus of broken houses and derailed lives,
left there by the wrath of Hurricane Mitch. Half of this coastal
village of 6,000 people _ more than 80 houses _ was swept out to
sea or submerged under the engorged River Aguan during three days
of floods, gales and rain so hard it felt like a thousand whips.
Forty-one people perished in a desperate attempt to reach higher
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was a road into the village, there is now only
a wide expanse of dirt-brown water, with the wreckage of two school
buses peeking from the waves. The grade school and high school have
been wrecked, along with the bus station, the library and several
businesses. Dozens of houses not swallowed up entirely by the sea
have been reduced to piles of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The storm even changed this sleepy village's geography. More
than 200 yards of land disappeared under the relentless pounding of
the surf. The narrow river that once ran through the village has
been moved a quarter of a mile from its original course and has
expanded to four times its normal size. Part of the community has
been turned into an sad island of devastated homes.
</P>
<P>
   More than two months after the hurricane struck, little has
improved. Power and phone lines are still lying on the ground.
There is no potable water. Many children are sick with diarrhea and
unexplained fevers. Although some shipments of food and medicine
have been ferried in by charities and the government, two large
containers of aid from a New York City group are being held up in
port by customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   And though it was always remote and impoverished, the village is
more isolated than ever. To reach Santa Rosa, one must travel more
than two miles on a dirt road, cross a swollen river in a canoe
where there was once a ford, then travel 11 more miles to the edge
of the village, where a canoe or launch can carry the traveler to
the town's center a mile across the water on the other side of the
Aguan River.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1887, Santa Rosa de Aguan has never had much
political influence in the capital, Tegucigalpa. Only in the last
few years was electricity brought in, and requests for a paved road
and a bridge to link the town to the outside world have been bogged
down for decades.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is cultural. Like many coastal communities in
Honduras, the village is dominated by the Garifuni, descendants of
slaves and Carib Indians from the island of St. Vincent who were
exiled to Central America in 1795 after a revolt there. The
Garifuni, of African descent, have never wielded as much political
power as lighter-skinned Hondurans of Spanish and Indian ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people appear to be still in shock from the
hurricane. Like shipwrecked sailors, some spend their days
scavaging wood from the wreckage to build temporary shelters.
Others who lost family members have fled to live with other
relatives in nearby towns like Trujillo and La Ceiba, unable to
bear the place any longer. But most of the villagers were born here
and say they want to rebuild their small town.
</P>
<P>
   One is Robert Blanco, who spent 23 years working on tracks for
the Metro North railroad in New York before returning four years
ago to retire on a pension. Blanco's house is under the river,
along with all his belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people say they are going away, and others say they
will rebuild in a different spot,'' he said. ``I'm going to build
me a little house over here because I don't want to leave the
place. I was born and raised here.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say they would leave if they could, but they have nowhere
to go. Ms. Martinez Arriola's mother, Hilda Arriola Arouz, runs a
soda shop and outdoor restaurant on the side of town that was
largely swept away by the river. She used to live with her youngest
daughter, Nori Esperanza, but the 32-year-old woman has lost her
composure completely and can no longer bear to be in the village.
She becomes hysterical each time she returns, Mrs. Arriola Arouz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arriola Arouz is 67, and a widow. So many people have
abandoned the village there is no business for her restaurant. Her
son-in-law and four grandchildren are dead. Her surviving daughters
are both having trouble coping with the tragedy. The twisted roof
of her house lets in the rain now and she has no way to fix it. The
house seems dark and empty to her, bereft of children, who are the
light of the world, she says. Although she puts on a brave face,
she too says it is hard to confront each new day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most days I pass in sadness,'' she said, ``because all the
grandchildren that I lost lived most of the time in my house. Now
I'm sad and there is nothing but this sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Heartache: Sad Songs Are Sung For a Lost Family &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For many people here, the grieving appears to have just begun.
Some seem still in a state of denial. It is a measure of their
reluctance to talk about what happened that no Mass has been yet
been held for the victims of the storm, and though the municipal
authorities are supposedly planning one, no date has been set.
Still, the families have begun to grieve in private ways.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent night, Mrs. Arriola Arouz, her mother and a cousin
from the United States, Maria Guity, who had come to visit, sat up
late around a fire and sang sad songs of the Garifuni.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has trouble talking about what happened, Mrs.
Arriola's voice is full of pain when she sings. In the clear and
nasal lilt can be heard the echoes of slavery, of revolts against
planters, of great storms, and all the hard history of her people.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Mrs. Arriola ran into two acquaintances
as she walked through the part of town on the west bank of the
River Aguan. Both women had lost their houses in the flood and were
living like squatters in a half-finished Catholic church with
borrowed clothes and a few sticks of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the three women were telling one another how they had
survived. Their voices rose and their hands flailed the air in
describing the force of the rain, the immense pounding of surf, the
rising river. Then the conversation died down, like a storm
passing, and the women's eyes went daydreamy and still.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us from this neighborhood are left without homes,''
said one of the women, Enriqueta Martinez. ``It takes years to
build a house and it is destroyed in a few seconds.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other victims of the storm say they find it hard to talk about
it. One woman, Isabella Arriola, 32, a schoolteacher who is not
directly related to Mirtha, was swept out to sea and survived for
five days by clinging to the remains of a wooden roof before being
picked up by a ship. Her husband and children perished.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arriola wears sunglasses these days and black dresses.
Whenever she appears here, the townspeople crowd around and offer
condolences and small gifts. When she was approached by a reporter,
she first maintained she was someone else from another town and had
not been in Santa Rosa during the storm. When confronted with her
identity, she said it was too painful to recount what had happened
to her. ``I don't want to talk about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Hardship: A Farmer's Family Sinks Into Poverty &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Even those whose families were unscathed have trouble
understanding the extent of what has befallen them. Before the
storm, Omar Lopez was a successful dairy farmer by local standards.
He and his wife had saved enough to build a spacious home for about
$7,500. He ran 200 head of fine dairy cattle on 150 acres inherited
from his father.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a third of his farm lies under the river. The house was
swept out to sea, with all his belongings. Worse, he lost all but
10 of his cattle. ``Everything was invested in the farm, and I
didn't have any insurance,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of cattlemen in this river valley lost their stock _
some 20,000 head in all. Even those whose livestock survived have
trouble getting their beef to market because of the damage to the
country's roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who is 30, has rented a house on the edge of town and has
moved his wife and their five sons into it. They are living with
borrowed furniture. His children, once among the best dressed in
town, now run around barefoot in tattered clothes given them by
charities.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding his business at this point is a pipe dream, Lopez
said, unless he and other farmers like him obtain some sort of
low-interest loans or grants from the government. In the meantime,
he said, he and his family depend on food from charities and the
United Nations. The children have been sick with diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are completely dependent on what they send us, because we
can't produce anything,'' he said. ``One maintains hope that
perhaps the government will do something.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Response: Aid From New York Is Held Hostage &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the government's response to Santa Rosa's
crisis has been minimal. The power and telephone lines are still
down, the schools closed.
</P>
<P>
   Military helicopters have delivered about 20 tons of food aid
from the United States and Canada and a few trucks from the United
Nations and various Catholic charities have managed to get through
the river ford. In addition, five tons of aid arrived from a group
of Hondurans in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But at least two containers full of aid gathered by Hondurans in
New York City were bottled up in the port of Cortez in December,
where customs agents demanded $740 in duty before they would let
them into the country. The Mayor, Biato Gonzalo Castillo Guity,
made a three-day trip over damaged roads and severed bridges in an
effort to free the hostage cargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have the money,'' said Cruz Castillo, the
chairman of the village's emergency committee. ``If the government
doesn't help us, it's possible we won't be able to bring those
containers in.''
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said they were negotiating to buy several acres
of land to parcel out to people whose houses were inundated. ``We
have to move everyone,'' Castillo said. ``We have to find a place
for them to live.''
</P>
<P>
   But Castillo said these measures did not begin to address the
larger problems of unemployment and economic ruin. Most of the
villagers worked as hired hands on fishing boats or on one of the
local cattle ranches. Now the boats are largely destroyed, the
cattle drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Many see no future. On a recent afternoon, Hilberto Sanchez, who
is 40, was trying to build a house from bits and pieces of wood he
had salvaged from the debris that was once his brother-in-law's
house. His own home had been washed out to sea. A friend gave him
permission to build on a small plot in the section of the village
that survived.
</P>
<P>
   He has put up a rickety frame on the sandy soil, salvaging even
the nails he used to hammer it together. He says he knows it will
be a temporary dwelling, a flimsy house that will not withstand the
first tropical storm, but he has no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stay in the church any longer,'' he explained,
surveying the wreckage with weary eyes. ``We have to keep fighting
because after everything we can't just cross our arms and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than two months since Sanchez worked on the
fishing boats or farms. He has nine children. Asked what he will do
once the house is finished, he shrugged in an expression of utter
despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this I am the most worried,'' he said. ``Because here we
have no source of work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
