<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-2TAKES-     01-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS END PRESENTATION WITH CALL FOR CLINTON'S REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Miss., Ind., S.C., Utah, Ky., S.D.)  (Eds., story will be updated as conditions warrant.) 
(See also IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK, IMPEACH-EAGLES,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican prosecutors contended Saturday
that President Clinton, in committing perjury and obstruction of
justice, had weakened the country at home and abroad and deserved
to be convicted and removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   As they wound up their three-day presentation, House managers
argued that Clinton's offenses, which they said they had proved on
Thursday and Friday, were neither private nor trivial, but rose to
the level of the ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' that the
Constitution sets as a standard for impeachment and removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your judgment should rise above politics, above partisanship,
above polling data,'' Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said in his prepared
closing statement. ``This case is a test of whether what the
Founding Fathers described as `sacred honor' still has meaning in
our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The centrality of Saturday's presentation to the entire trial
was underlined before the session began by Sen. Thad Cochran,
R-Miss. As he entered the chamber, he said, ``This may be the
biggest challenge of all _ to show that the offenses rise to the
level of impeachment.'' Many Democrats have insisted, long before
Saturday's arguments, that the alleged offenses fell far short.
</P>
<P>
   In a critical speech in only the second presidential impeachment
trial in the 209-year history of the Republic, Rep. Steve Buyer,
R-Ind., said the president's offenses ``assault the administration
of justice.'' And justice, he said, was an essential core of the
nation because only with confidence in settling disputes in court
could society avoid relying on ``brute force.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., conceding with a folksy manner that
the proceedings could be called ``a snoozer,'' said that
demonstrated the country was calm and could survive either
conviction and removal or acquittal. What other country, he asked,
could be so ``calm'' in the face of a possible sudden change of
government.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer (pronounced BOO-yer) warned against what he expected the
White House lawyers to argue in their defense: ``Do not be tempted
to believe the argument that lying about sex doesn't matter, that
it's private.'' He said the judicial system was essential to the
enforcement of laws against rape and sexual harassment, and that
without the perjury and obstruction laws, none of those rights
``could be vindicated in court.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that this argument, in fact, ``demeans the civil rights
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   And Buyer contended that the president's reputation as a liar
had weakened the nation abroad, especially by damaging morale in
the military. He said this should matter to the Senate, which would
never vote to promote a military officer charged with the offenses
of which Clinton is accused.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer opened the House case Saturday morning by ridiculing the
White House argument that the alleged crimes were not the sort of
crimes against the state that merited impeachment and removal from
office _ the consequence of a Senate conviction by a two-thirds
vote.
</P>
<P>
   He called it ``the `so what' defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he contended, ``willfully and repeatedly violated the
rule of law and abused the judicial system.'' The subject of the
lies and obstruction was irrelevant to the dominant fact that they
were committed within the judicial system, which those crimes
undermined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer argued that while lying to someone's wife about an
extramarital affair was not a crime, lying about it in court was
``a crime against the state and is therefore a public matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Acts which are not crimes when committed outside the judicial
realm,'' he said, ``become crimes when they are committed inside
the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   And as to whether those crimes merited impeachment, Buyer said
they did. He cited James Madison, one of the Constitution's chief
authors, as holding the British legal analysis of Blackstone's
Commentaries in the highest regard, and observed that Blackstone
put bribery and perjury on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, he said, when the Constitution said impeachment was
proper for treason, bribery and other high crimes and misdemeanors,
it was clear that perjury was one of those ``other'' offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer said, ``What I'm saying unto all of you is that there is
no difference here, and that's the pain of this case. There is no
difference between a cash bribe or sitting before a federal judge
and perjuring oneself. Whether it be in the underlying civil
deposition or in fact the grand jury perjury, perjury and bribery
are side by side.''
</P>
<P>
   Their presentations, and the reaction from Republican senators,
left House managers optimistic that they had succeeded in
persuading a Senate majority to let them go forward and call
witnesses. In their three days of opening arguments, the House
managers had argued that if senators had any doubt of Clinton's
guilt, they had to summon witnesses to resolve any questions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One Republican who was persuaded, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said
Saturday morning, ``There are some very clear conflicts that need
to be resolved.'' He added, ``I don't see how we can avoid
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers have made it clear they will attack that
argument in the 24 hours they are allowed for opening defense
arguments that begin on Tuesday. If the House needed no witnesses,
they have said, neither does the Senate. They have also warned that
calling witnesses, who would be questioned under oath by both sides
before possibly appearing before the full Senate, would drag out
the proceedings for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said Saturday that the
final presentation by the House managers was ``a clear concession
and admission that their case isn't strong enough without the need
for witnesses. They were given 24 hours to make their case and
they've spent the bulk of it arguing for the need to call
witnesses. When all the politics is stripped away, what we have are
House managers conceding that they haven't built the case and they
need something more.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton was spending much of the day preparing for
the State of the Union Message on Tuesday. A practice run-through
was scheduled for Saturday afternoon in the White House family
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators sought to offer the White House a
slightly less unpleasant alternative _ ``stipulating'' or agreeing
to various facts they said witnesses could confirm if they
testified. Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the Rules
Committee, said that while a ``rather strong case'' had been made
for witnesses, ``Maybe the president will stipulate to the facts
and it won't be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The witness issue _ the most difficult the Senate had faced in
its efforts to appear more sober and dignified than the House _ has
produced repeated clashes. Another of those clashes came with an
exchange of letters between Senate Republican and Democratic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, laid out his plan
in a letter sent late Friday to Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the
minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that a bipartisan group of senators could
anticipate and help resolve in advance any complications that may
be presented by our hearing the testimony of witnesses,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Daschle said in a letter Saturday, ``I appreciate
your desire to continue to work toward a fair and expeditious
conclusion of this matter. I strongly believe, however, that
appointing a group of senators to make preparations for witness
testimony would violate the bipartisan agreement that now governs
our process.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the bipartisan agreement reached last week, he
wrote, ``Senate Resolution 16 anticipates that issues related to
witnesses would be addressed if _ and only if _ the Senate votes to
compel such testimony,'' and he added, ``It is my hope that such
arrangements will ultimately prove unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott has written that he supports considering ``safeguards now,
so that testimony could begin as soon as fairness allowed _ should
the Senate decide to call witnesses. Forming a bipartisan group to
consider witness issues now may save us time and trouble in the
days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That group could be the instrument for our communication with
both sides in this trial,'' Lott said. ``Because senators are
judges, as well as triers of fact, it is our responsibility to work
with both sides to arrange the logistics of the trial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
