</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES: INDIANA, OREGON, LOUISIANA
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANA: Extramarital Penalty, Hoosier Style  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how they handle a sex scandal involving an elected
official and an office intern in Indiana:
</P>
<P>
   Last September, The Kokomo Tribune reported that state Sen.
Steven Johnson, a 50-year-old Republican who represents four
counties in the central part of Indiana, had engaged in an
adulterous relationship in 1997 with a 23-year-old college intern
who worked in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the Senate's ranking Republican, did not deny the
report and engaged in no verbal hair-splitting. Rather, he
confessed to committing ``a moral and ethical wrong'' and said
``choices should have consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, on a voice vote and with no debate, the Indiana Senate
set forth the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   It removed Johnson from two of the Senate's most powerful
committees, Ethics and Finance, took away his chairmanship of the
Planning and Public Services Committee, and most punishing of all,
in a way, banished him to a seat in the very back of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose marriage failed as a result of his affair,
accepted the sanctions, which will remain in effect for two years,
and praised his Senate colleagues for their ``civility and grace.''
He said that ``in a very strange sense'' he had been given a
``fascinating'' opportunity to start his life anew.
</P>
<P>
   Then, noting that he would be up for re-election in 2002, he
added, ``I'll go on from here, and in four years we'll let the
constituents determine the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   OREGON: Voting Easy May Be No Democratic Vote
</P>
<P>
   No state tries harder to make voting easier than Oregon. And in
an era when the voter participation rate is scandalously low in
most states, no state consistently enjoys a higher rate than
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   How does Oregon do it?
</P>
<P>
   Mail ballots are readily available and mail balloting is
aggressively promoted. In fact, the state's presidential primaries
are now entirely vote-by-mail affairs, and almost 60 percent of the
voters participated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble looms. The Democratic National Committee says
Oregon's delegates to the 2000 national convention may not be
seated unless the state changes its vote-by-mail procedure for that
year's presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand, the primary will be held March 14, which is
fine with the Democratic committee. What is not fine is that
ballots will be mailed out about three weeks earlier, in late
February, and thus voters will be able to vote not only well before
primary day but, more to the point, well before March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Under new DNC rules, no state, other than the
first-in-the-nation states of New Hampshire and Iowa, can hold a
primary or caucus before March 7. The party imposed that threshold
for Election 2000 because officials were worried that the primary
and caucus calendar had been unbalanced by the recent rush of
states to vote earlier and earlier to increase their nominating
clout.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, for example, joined the stampede in 1996, moving its
voting date to March after many years of voting in May. As DNC
officials see it, the stampede will grow even more thunderous next
year if Oregon permits voters to cast mail ballots before March 7,
even though the ballots are meant for a March 14 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, some officials say, news and polling organizations
will try to get an early _ and possibly disruptive _ read on where
the primary is headed by contacting some of the voters who mail in
ballots earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't want to keep pushing the date,'' Tom Wyche, a
Democratic committee spokesman, said last week, calling for
negotiations on the issue. Then he warned, ``For any state that
selects delegates outside our rules, there's a possibility their
delegation might not be seated.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon election officials deny any intent to break party rules.
They also question whether the committee intends to go after every
state that has scheduled an early primary and intends to send out
mail ballots, regular or absentee, before March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to disenfranchise the voters of Oregon,'' the
state's secretary of state, Phil Keisling, argues. ``It's absurd,
offensive, a phony problem.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the rules are somewhat different and
there is no clash of dates.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA: From Dudley Dudley To Monica Monica
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a name from the political past. For years she was a
power in the Democratic Party of New Hampshire, someone
presidential wannabes always called on while tramping through the
snowy notches during primary season, someone no out-of-state
reporter could resist quoting.
</P>
<P>
   Comes now her replacement, as it were, one Monica Monica _ no
relation to Monica Lewinsky, though there is something of a
political nexus. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Monica _ Monica Squared to her friends _ is a New Orleans
ophthalmologist. She is running for Congress, seeking, along with
former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke, to succeed a fellow
Republican, Bob Livingston. He is leaving because, just as the
House moved to impeach President Clinton as a result of l'affaire
Lewinsky, it was revealed that Livingston had also had adulterous
dalliances.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Monica says her candidacy is not some ``politically cute''
trick and that she plans to put at least $500,000 of her own money
into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was Monica long before the other one was,'' she says, noting
that at 48 she is almost twice as old as Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   How did she get her double moniker?
</P>
<P>
   From her father, Elihu Root Monica, she says, who was himself
named for the famed secretary of state, and who, she recalls, once
told her:
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved you so much and felt so much honor in the name Monica
that I named you twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
