<HEADER>
A5967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-KOSHER-CHIN     01-16 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-KOSHER-CHINESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: INVOKING THE BIBLE IN A KOSHER WAR OF THE WOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (Duplication notice: also sent with `d' code) 
(bl) 
By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ This is the story of this city's Great
Kosher Chinese Food War.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning _ two years ago, that is _ Michael Zeitouni
opened a delicatessen on North Avenue. He sold pastrami and
knishes. He sold falafel. He also sold Chinese _ General Tso's
chicken, moo goo gai pan _ absolutely, incontrovertibly kosher
Chinese prepared by a Chinese chef.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last month, 10 doors down, Kevin Cohnen opened Eden Wok.
He did not sell pastrami. But he did sell Chinese, absolutely,
incontrovertibly kosher and prepared by four seasoned Chinese chefs
working at six woks.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni's business, Wykagyl, went into a nose dive, tumbling 30
to 40 percent. He had to fire a counterman and a deliveryman and
bring in his wife, Beth, to help. Business has been so bad that
Zeitouni has publicly turned his complaint into a religious issue.
He accuses Cohnen of violating a verse in Deuteronomy that has to
do with moving boundary markers, but has been interpreted by some
rabbis as barring one Jew from opening a business that directly
injures another Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking my traffic,'' said Zeitouni, 45, a bearded Israeli
immigrant whose woes are written on his weary face. ``We're
fighting over the same 700 religious families. They're either going
to eat by me or they're going to eat by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni is so angry that he is considering the ominous step of
hauling Cohnen into a beth din _ a rabbinical court _ for a
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Cohnen, who at 23 has made himself into the New York City
region's kosher Chinese king (he has 3 of the more than 30 kosher
Chinese restaurants around), thinks Zeitouni has no case. Zeitouni
sells deli; he sells Chinese. ``I don't look at it as stealing
business,'' he said. ``I look at it as expanding the kosher
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is indisputably bitter, but a kosher fortune cookie
might suggest looking on the bright side. What the fight
illuminates is that New Rochelle's Orthodox population is
flourishing, having doubled in just two decades as Orthodox
professionals snap up the classic Tudor-style houses in the city's
north end. Two of the four Orthodox synagogues have built or are
planning new sanctuaries, and the two restaurants share North
Avenue with a kosher bakery, a kosher pizza shop and a kosher
grocery.
</P>
<P>
   If the Orthodox continue to multiply and their craving for
Chinese food rises to that of less stringent Jews, both restaurants
should do well. But both may not survive the waiting, which is why
Zeitouni has resorted to his biblical argument. Some rabbis would
say that Zeitouni may make a tasty corned beef sandwich but his
biblical scholarship leaves them with heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi William Herskowitz, administrator of the Westchester Vaad
Hakashruth, the board that supervises kosher shops, said that in
Eastern Europe's tightly knit communities, rabbis could enforce
communal edicts, but in a democratic country like the United
States, with laws prohibiting restraint of trade, he cannot deny
Eden Wok a kosher certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say, `It's not nice, it's foolhardy, it's stupid,'''
he said. ``But I can't force anybody not to open up on the same
block.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni has asked the Vaad to restrict Eden Wok to takeout. He
has even contended that Eden Wok's menu has matzoh ball soup. (Eden
Wok's owners say the broth has Chinese flavors.) It has all been to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The deli's biggest problem, the Zeitounis concede, is that it is
a deli, not a Chinese restaurant. If they're eating Chinese,
Orthodox diners want to see Chinese waiters, not Jewish faces like
Zeitouni's.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitouni may insist, ``My Chinese food is better than his
Chinese food, my portions are bigger.'' But the manager of Eden
Wok, David Zaitschek, retorts, ``You can't do Chinese without
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Impishly watching the dispute has been Paul Ciafolo, a gentile
whose kosher pizza shop has ducked the fire because it serves dairy
only. ``It's a meat war,'' he said. He doubts Zeitouni will prevail
in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the Torah and there's the Constitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had this advice for Zeitouni: ``He should make the best damn
deli and the people will come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
