<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ROSS-ART-700&AMP;     01-16 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ROSS-ART-700&AMP;ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY RECALLS A SENATOR'S LEGACY OF HONOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., N.M.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton on trial for his political
life, the name of Sen. Edmund G. Ross of Kansas is apt to come up
whenever people talk about courage, honor and duty.
</P>
<P>
   In American political legend, he chose personal ruin rather than
betray his principles, defying his party leadership in voting to
acquit President Andrew Johnson during the last presidential
impeachment, in 1868. If he had voted the other way, Johnson would
have been removed and American history might have been much
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost literally looked down into my open grave,'' he wrote
of the vote that he knew would destroy his Senate career.
</P>
<P>
   His sacrifice stirs admiration among his descendants. ``We're
proud of our ancestor,'' a great-grandson, Edmund Pitt Ross, a
retired clergyman and civil engineer from Albuquerque, N.M., said
the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our family lore,'' said a great-great-grandson
who is a foreign service officer for the State Department and
agreed to speak only if his name was not be used. ``He was someone
who kept his own moral compass.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also a man who found his way out of the political
wilderness, leaving a legacy beyond the Senate vote that John F.
Kennedy wrote about in his 1955 book ``Profiles in Courage.'' He
was a man who lived to see himself vindicated by history and who,
in writing his own political obituary, showed that he had not only
a sense of duty but a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Gibson Ross had been a printer and owned an interest in a
Topeka newspaper, been a dedicated abolitionist and helped to
organize a railroad before the Civil War. He was an officer in the
Union Army and had a powerful presence.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise when the Kansas governor appointed him to
the Senate in 1866. Ross was a Republican, named to take the seat
of another Republican, Jim Lane, who had been so vilified as a
supporter of Johnson's that he committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat and Southerner, Johnson was detested by those
Republicans who wanted to punish the defeated Confederate states
rather than continue Abraham Lincoln's policy of reconciliation, as
Johnson did. So Johnson's enemies were overjoyed at the selection
of Ross, who had been sharply critical of Lane and disliked the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had given Republicans an excuse for impeachment by
moving to dismiss Secretary of War Edwin Stanton, a Lincoln
holdover whom he distrusted, in 1867. The president's action defied
an act (later ruled unconstitutional by the Supreme Court) that had
been passed by Congress to hobble his power to remove
officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   Incensed, the Republican-controlled House voted overwhelmingly
to impeach. Since there were 42 Republicans and only 12 Democrats
in the Senate, the Republican leadership could lose six votes and
still have the two-thirds majority necessary for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   To the party leaders' dismay, six Republicans soon announced
that they had found the evidence insufficient and would vote to
acquit. That put terrible pressure on Ross, who had not declared
his intentions but who, as a lawmaker from a state whose people
generally loathed the president, was at first counted as a safe
vote for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Ross was 51 years old in 1868, with a seemingly bright political
future. But his dislike of Johnson notwithstanding, he thought the
president was right. On May 16, 1868, he voted to acquit. The tally
was 35 to 19 in favor of conviction. Had he voted the other way,
Johnson would have been ousted and, historians agree, the
presidency would have been seriously weakened. (Votes on two other
articles of impeachment 10 days later were anticlimactic; the
outcome was the same.)
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kansas, he held interests in several newspapers and ran
for governor as a Democrat in 1880. He lost. Two years later, he
moved to Albuquerque, thinking that the dry air would be good for
his health. In the 1884 campaign, he was a strong supporter of
Grover Cleveland; the new president named him governor of the New
Mexico territory.
</P>
<P>
   His stubborn principles served him well. He battled land
speculators and, perhaps more important, worked tirelessly to
establish public schools. Providing an education, he said, ``is the
highest duty and most sacred function of government.'' The
University of New Mexico was founded in 1889.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of Ross's great-grandsons, Edmund Ross Harrington, is a
retired school superintendent from Redondo Beach, Calif. ``We are
proud that our great-grandfather was a man of courage,'' Mr.
Harrington said recently. He, two brothers and a sister are the
grandchildren of Arthur Ross, one of the Kansas Senator's six
children.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Pitt Ross of Albuquerque, who is 73, is a grandson of the
senator's son Pitt. Ross said he and his brother, Everitt, and
their sister, Elizabeth Lackman, were pleased that an elementary
school in Albuquerque was named after their great-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Gibson Ross was nothing if not a political realist. When
Benjamin Harrison defeated Grover Cleveland in 1888, he knew what
it meant. ``I was again, and very promptly, relegated to private
life,'' he reflected later, ``and am now by turns printer, farmer,
gentleman at leisure, author, philosopher, tramp _ but never a
sorehead.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His place in history secure, surrounded by family and friends,
Ross spent the evening of his life quietly and happily. He died in
New Mexico on May 8, 1907, at the age of 80.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
