<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-POLICE-CHIEF-NYT     01-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-POLICE-CHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNYIELDING CHIEF FOR THE LOS ANGELES POLICE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Attn: Penn.)  By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One of the complaints heard most often about the
tenure of Police Chief Willie L. Williams earlier this decade was
that he was just too soft for the job, too soft in his heart when
it came to disciplining his officers and leading them to better
days.
</P>
<P>
   He was in a tough spot. The Los Angeles Police Department's
reputation and morale had suffered in the wake of the Rodney King
beating, and Williams was brought in from Philadelphia to right the
department after the rage and flames of the riots of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was popular with the public, Williams, the city's
first black police chief, was forced out in 1997 after one
five-year term. He was replaced by Bernard C. Parks, a
ramrod-straight disciplinarian and 32-year department veteran.
</P>
<P>
   No one would ever accuse Parks, who is also black, of being
soft. He looks as if Hollywood had sent him to play the part of the
chief. But the hardness that served him so well on the mean streets
and the treacherous world of office politics at police headquarters
is now apparently a source of growing discontent within the ranks
of the 9,730-officer police department.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his officers grumble that Parks is so hard, strict and
unfair when it comes to discipline that a group of them do not want
him to attend their funerals if they are killed in the line of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Los Angeles Times, which first reported the
officers' requests on Friday, some of the officers have even
included a no-Parks last wish on their emergency information cards,
which are left at their stations when they go on out patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hepburn, president of the Police Protective League, the
police union, which has been at odds with Chief Parks over work
rules and discipline issues since his tenure began in August 1997,
said that the funeral protest was not orchestrated by the union. He
also said he did not know how many officers were involved, although
it is believed the number is several dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't our idea and we don't support it,'' Hepburn insisted
at a news conference about the protest. ``But we understand why the
officers are upset. What it indicates is the depth of the negative
feelings towards the chief.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Parks refused to comment as he attended a graduation
ceremony at the police academy. But during his speech, the chief
told the new officers that ``we will accept nothing less than
professional conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 54 officers were fired by the Parks administration
for various infractions and seven others resigned before they could
be dismissed, Hepburn said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, only 11 officers were dismissed. The year before, it
was 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is when is enough enough?'' Hepburn said. ``This
is a shock to the system. The officers are used to one level of
discipline and this chief is firing five times as many officers as
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 54 officers dismissed last year were ousted for
excessive force and several longtime observers of the department _
from a retired assistant police chief to a civil rights lawyer to
the writer of a book on the history of the department _ say that it
is about time that someone cracked the whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernard inherited something that had been allowed to slip and
one of the things that had slipped was the attitude toward police
misconduct,'' said David D. Dotson, a former assistant chief, who
retired in 1992 after 34 years. ``He believes that sometimes you
have to do unpopular things if you are going to turn the ship
around, you're going to have to bloody a few noses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Manes, a lawyer for Police Watch, a citizen's group that
monitors the department, said the department had had ``very little
self control over the officers, at least in the area of excessive
force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is,'' Manes said, ``Parks is doing what
has got to be done. The city is paying millions of dollars a year
in excessive force cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But how much and what kind of changes Parks is committed to is
uncertain, the observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out,'' said Connie Rice, a civil rights
lawyer, who is suing the department on behalf of a group of women,
both civilian employees and police officers, alleging
discrimination and harassment. ``He could be the most brilliant
police chief we've ever had, but I see some disturbing signs of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those signs, Ms. Rice said, is Parks' apparent hostility
to meaningful civilian input into the police department, a longtime
goal of advocates of departmental change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no confidence,'' she said, ``that civilian oversight is
taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, crime is down in Los Angeles, as it is many big cities
across the country, and Parks seems popular outside of the police
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job Chief Parks is doing is outstanding,'' said Ken
Ferber, a spokesman for the Police Commission. ``You would probably
be concerned if there weren't grumblings.''
</P>
<P>
   When people talk _ or grumble _ about Parks the words
``brilliant,'' ``charismatic,'' ``stubborn,'' ``tough'' and
``autocratic'' come up again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parks is one of those people who are convinced that they are
never wrong,'' said Joe Domanick, the author of a history of the
department, ``To Protect And To Serve.'' ``I think this is both an
asset and a problem for him. He's so convinced that he's always
right, there's an unwillingness to learn and to assimilate other
people's point of view. That's a problem for him, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotson, the former assistant chief, said that Parks was not the
first chief to feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that infects most chiefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dotson said that he was worried that Parks, who used to be
his highly capable subordinate, might be too enamored with his own
counsel for his or his department's own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does seem to be extremely autocratic,'' Dotson said. ``He's
making a lot of important and long-lasting changes and he's
accomplished more than any other chief I've known. But his handling
of people has suffered. He seems to be sort of oblivious to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
