particularly in the West. Phoenix has really elevated its play.
Dallas has gotten stronger each of the last three years. Colorado,
after a slow start, has come on. So getting to the finals will be
more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On whether Sergei Fedorov's effort has diminished since his
big contract: ``Sergei has had a tough year. He hasn't played with
consistency, but we all have flaws in our game. We'd like him to be
a dominant player, and he has that ability. But I don't think it
has anything to do with his contract.''
</P>
<P>
   THRASHERS UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   When the Toronto Maple Leafs traded Felix Potvin to the New York
Islanders, it strengthened the chances the Thrashers will get a
strong goaltender in the expansion draft in June. How so?
Twenty-one of the 27 existing NHL teams must expose one of their
two goaltenders and the Islanders' Tommy Salo became a likely
discard when Potvin arrived. Teams that can't lose a goalie are
first-year Nashville and five other teams who lost one last year _
Buffalo, Los Angeles, Montreal, New Jersey and the New York
Rangers. Though Salo would be attractive, Roman Turek of Dallas
likely remains the team's top choice. Assistant general manager Les
Jackson, formerly of the Stars, and Thrashers goaltending
consultant Andy Moog, who played in Dallas and continues to live
there, both are familiar with Turek. A handful of teams with strong
backups _ the Stars, Islanders, Detroit (Norm Maracle), Phoenix
(Jim Waite) and San Jose (Steve Shields) _ have several options to
avoid losing a goaltender without compensation in the draft. The
two most plausible: 1) dealing a netminder to another team down the
stretch to get a player in return; 2) making a pre-draft
arrangement with the Thrashers to accept a draft pick or other
compensation in lieu of Atlanta taking a goalie. Nashville
stockpiled draft choices with similar deals last season. But
Atlanta general manager Don Waddell has said he won't likely make
as many pre-draft deals as the Predators, citing a preference for
the team to be competitive quickly. ... The team's scouting staff
began week-long meetings in Fort Lauderdale Friday. Scouts will
begin the process of ranking amateurs and potential available pros.
... Waddell hopes negotiations for a Thrashers' practice site are
completed ``in the next couple of weeks.'' Existing rinks in Duluth
and Alpharetta are the bidders.
</P>
<P>
