<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KING17-COX     01-16 1979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Capturing the spirit of a King
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As he rode through Selma, Ala., on a spring day
in 1975, John Hindsman perched in the passenger seat of his Pontiac
and tensed his finger on the shutter button of his Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where it all began,'' said a friend as Hindsman
snapped frame after frame of the landmarks rolling by.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Dallas County Courthouse, where 10 years earlier
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. had led hundreds of blacks in a
futile voter registration effort. There was Brown Chapel, where
King's followers gathered to march for justice. There was the
Pettus Bridge, where state patrolmen turned back the demonstrators
with tear gas, bullwhips and rubber tubes wrapped in barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time Hindsman had been to Selma, but the
memory of violence that hung over the city made it feel like coming
home. Hindsman grew up on a Georgia plantation in the 1920s, when
the law and the lash made a pipe dream of equality. He had seen
black men imprisoned on trumped-up charges. He had seen his father
routinely cheated at the commissary. He had inhaled the stench of a
burning cross.
</P>
<P>
   King's crusade changed everything, but Hindsman wasn't around to
witness it. Like so many others, he left the blistering cotton rows
and teeming boarding houses for the promise of a better life up
north. While King and his allies dodged police cudgels and
firehoses, Hindsman was in Dayton, working at a hospital and
rearing eight children.
</P>
<P>
   Yet stepping out of history's stream left him with a smudge of
discontent. He carried his memories of the civil rights movement in
a scrapbook. Many who stayed in the South carried them in scars.
</P>
<P>
   That day in Selma, as Hindsman burned through his film, an idea
struck him. Maybe he could make up for his absence.
</P>
<P>
   With camera in hand, he vowed, he would follow the path King
took, from Montgomery to Memphis. He would record the places where
King, with little more than the force of his personality, caused
America's apartheid to crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one man,'' Hindsman would reflect 20 years later. `` You
can take it all the way from Abraham to Moses to David to Solomon,
all down through history. Just one man. He always gets the
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston, Ga., doesn't exist anymore. It hemorrhaged people for
so long that the surrounding county finally swallowed it.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1917, when Hindsman was born, Winston was a tiny farm
town to the west of Atlanta, the kind of place where the mayor ran
things from his general store. Hindsman's home was a shotgun house
with a tar paper roof on the grounds of the David T. Howard
plantation.
</P>
<P>
   For $200 in annual rent, the family broke the plantation's rich
soil to raise corn, cotton, sugar cane and melons. They kept a
garden for themselves and supplemented it with the wild greens and
onions that grew in the lowlands. They got their meat with a
12-gauge shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   The children went to school just three months of the year. Their
parents needed them at home, and not simply for work, for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring, a man from the county inspected the community on
horseback to see how well everyone tended their crops. He couldn't
abide waste, and in his mind, that included sending black children
to school when they could be plowing or picking. Brooking his
displeasure meant a flogging for the man of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Hard times nurtured a stern religion among the county's black
folks, and Sundays brought shouted threats of hellfire and
damnation from the pulpit. Some of the most energetic soul-saving
came from an Atlanta preacher by the name of Daddy King.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy King brought his wife and three children to revival week
services at the Old Mountaintop Missionary Baptist Church, and one
of the kids caught Hindsman's eye. He was a little boy called M.L.,
12 years Hindsman's junior, who sat quietly during the marathon
orations while other children fidgeted or tried to sneak from the
tent.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, after Hindsman had moved to Atlanta to car
hop and bus tables, he saw that boy again, at the Yates-Milton Drug
Store. He was the magnetic center of a crowd of kids, as radiant
and self-assured as a prince. Hindsman felt privileged to hand him
a nickel for an ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last Hindsman would see of Martin Luther King Jr.
In 1940, King went to Morehouse College, a 15-year-old prodigy. In
1941, Hindsman went to Burma, a freshly drafted member of the
United States Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman became a dispatcher with the 823rd Aviation Engineer
Battalion, a segregated unit that carved out a supply road to
China. Japanese troops clustered just across the Pataki mountains,
and their Zeros filled the sky like insects at twilight.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers dynamited a path over frigid peaks and bulldozed
through swamps overgrown with 10-foot tufts of elephant grass. Asia
in wartime could be a terrible place, yet what struck Hindsman most
was its beauty. The fierce colors of its gardens. The mad pageantry
of its festivals. The serenity of Mahatma Gandhi, who chatted with
the international soldiers one day as they pushed the road through
India.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman longed for a camera to capture these images, but the
Army wouldn't let him have one. Security reasons, they said. But
the seed had taken root, and at war's end, when Hindsman returned
to Georgia, one of the first things he bought was a $1.25 Kodak
camera.
</P>
<P>
   He started slowly, taking shots of his new bride, Hazel, and of
their families. People liked his work, and soon, they invited him
to photograph weddings, reunions, church functions and conventions.
</P>
<P>
   While a new world cracked open before his lens, the old one
seemed as constrictive as ever. Hindsman had guided a huge fleet of
vehicles as an Army dispatcher, but in Georgia, the only work he
could find was tending crops and delivering groceries.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1947, when a buddy told him about high-paying
manufacturing jobs in Dayton, he made his decision in a heartbeat.
He and his wife were gone.
</P>
<P>
   His first job at Frigidaire didn't last long, but he quickly
found a secure position as a nurse's assistant at the Veterans
Administration Hospital. A few years later he bought a house, and
he and his wife took their places in the city's black middle class.
</P>
<P>
   But as they settled into Dayton life, their old homeland
convulsed. Civil rights organizations grew ever more restless with
segregation's status quo. White authorities cracked down ever
harder. Boycotts and sit-ins were met with bombings and assaults.
In the middle of everything was that luminous child Hindsman
remembered so well, now a world-famous man.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman followed Martin Luther King Jr.'s exploits with relish,
scarcely believing anyone had the guts to buck the system he grew
up with. He pasted all the great events in a scrapbook: The
Montgomery bus boycott. The March on Washington. The Selma to
Montgomery March. The Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Had he not left the South, Hindsman figured he might have been
part of it all. But when he went to Selma in 1975 to hear his
pastor lecture, his tour of the history-soaked city convinced him
he could still participate.
</P>
<P>
   So four years later, he took a week's vacation from his nursing
job at the hospital, packed a camera into his Oldsmobile
Bonneville, and headed to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman began in Atlanta, a city that had become into
cosmopolitan boomtown in his absence. Still, he remembered the
curves of its streets, and he didn't need to ask directions to get
where he was headed.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped by Auburn Avenue to photograph King's home, then
headed two blocks west to the Ebenezer Baptist Church where King
returned in 1960 to preach alongside his father. He shot the
buildings and grounds of Morehouse College, where King turned a
class assignment on David Thoreau's ``Civil Disobedience'' into a
strategy of nonviolent resistance.
</P>
<P>
   From there Hindsman took Interstate 85 to Montgomery, Ala., the
city where King first became a pastor, and where he first reached
national prominence by leading a boycott on the city's segregated
bus system.
</P>
<P>
   King preached at the Dexter Avenue Baptist Church, a small
building across the street from the state capital. The
juxtaposition that jolted Hindsman no less than it did King when he
took the job in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have come together without all this struggle,''
Hindsman would reflect years later. `` ... Yet we had to kill and
we had to march and we had to boycott and all these kind of things,
because the system says that it's separate but equal. And that was
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery led to Selma, where Hindsman revisited Brown Chapel
and Pettus Bridge. He took photos of Highway 80, the road on which
King and his partners overcame savage resistance to lead thousands
of demonstrators on a march to the state capital in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Selma gave way to Birmingham, the city that in 1963 boiled with
televised mayhem. This was the city of Bull Connor, the police
commissioner who didn't hesitate to unleash police dogs and
firehoses on peaceful protestors. Here, Hindsman photographed the
16th Street Baptist Church, where four little girls were killed in
an bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for the final destination: the Lorraine Motel
in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   King had come to the city in 1968 to support striking garbage
workers. His mission of desegregation had evolved into a campaign
against poverty, and he arrived in Memphis aiming to help the
nearly all black sanitation union gain better wages and improve
working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, King addressed a throng at the city's Mason Temple.
He was tired and had not wanted to go, but his words were
nonetheless electric, sounding even then like a prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anybody, I would like to live a long life,'' he said at
one point. ``Longevity has its place. But I'm not concerned with
that now. I just want to do God's will.
</P>
<P>
   ``And He's allowed me to go up to the mountain. And I've looked
over. And I've seen the promised land. And I may not get there with
you. But I want you to know tonight that we as a people will get to
the promised land.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as King stood on the balcony of the pale green
Lorraine Motel, a sniper across the street shot him in the head. He
was taken to a nearby hospital, where he was pronounced dead at
7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman was unemotional as he photographed the motel, which had
been preserved as a memorial. He had always accepted the hard
things in life. He knew he had no choice but to accept this too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what happened,'' he would say later. ``You know he's
not coming back. Life goes on. That's what you have to live by in
order to get some strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindsman created a slide show of his photos, calling it ``From
Montgomery to Memphis.'' He showed it at family gatherings and at a
Dayton fraternal hall, but that was it. He didn't think anyone else
would be interested in his pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The photos have since scattered among the thousands of others
Hindsman has taken over the years, but he plans to reorganize them
someday. He wants to leave this record to what he calls ``the
unborn generations.''
</P>
<P>
   But he rarely feels an urge to look at those 1979 photos. He
says the images from his journey shine brighter in his mind than
they do on paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always emphasize, `Keep the dream alive,''' he says.
``Now how do you keep the dream alive? You keep the dream alive by
remembering (King's) dedication to the civil rights movement.
Remember what he has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time I go now into the South - and the North - and I
sleep in a hotel or a motel, I always thank God for Dr. Martin
Luther King. Because it was he who had this vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
