<SLUG> BC-BKN-BRADLEY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perfect time for Jordan's exit
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``A devastating blow to an already-hurting NBA.'' That
was the unanimous verdict regarding Michael Jordan's retirement.
Me, I find unanimity boring. And in this case, I find it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This truncated NBA season was already shot. Resentment over the
lockout will fade eventually but not immediately. Great as he is,
Jordan couldn't have overridden the fallout by himself. He'd have
helped, sure. But then he'd have retired over the summer, and that
would have touched off another round of hand-wringing, would have
led to another shakedown season.
</P>
<P>
   Better it happened this way. Better to get all the bad news out
now. Better to treat the 50-game schedule and subsequent playoffs
as an extended rehearsal, not yet the real thing. And then, when
the new full season commences this fall, the Jordan understudies _
Shaquille O'Neal, Grant Hill, Kobe Bryant _ will have had the
chance to learn their lines. And we'll have had the chance to
decompress post-MJ.
</P>
<P>
   Come autumn there will be a new defending champion, a new
glamour team, a new scoring champion, new rivalries beginning to
boil. The Bulls' reign was riveting to watch, but even the most
stimulating programming loses oomph over time. How many more times
could Jordan hit the winning shot? How many more times could we be
awed when he does? How much longer before we got sick of seeing the
same guys win?
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll see someone else. (Early-line favorite: The
long-suffering Indiana Pacers.) It will take some getting used to,
but there's time. The masses will watch this season out of the
corner of a collective eye, not sitting rapt in anticipation of the
latest Jordan wonder. Ratings will be way down. Fences will need
major mending. But this, remember, is the NBA. Unlike baseball, pro
basketball is a user-friendly product, and the NBA has proved it
can do the marketing dance like no other league.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of 15 years, Jordan was the central
component of that sales pitch. But the NBA revival was in flight
before Jordan left Chapel Hill. Earvin Johnson and Larry Bird
already were trading titles. Jordan took the league to a higher
plateau, but at some point the NBA was going to have to learn to
live without him. The guy couldn't play forever.
</P>
<P>
   As with almost everything else, Jordan got retiring right. He
leaves at the absolute pinnacle. He leaves having won a
championship with the final shot of his competitive life. He leaves
having left nothing undone. He leaves at a time when his leaving
will be one of two major stories, not the unchallenged focus. And
he leaves having removed the league's sky hook.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kareem Abdul-Jabbar invented the shot of the same name, a
sky hook was a magical contraption we mortals grabbed at for
balance. So long as Jordan played, the NBA would have kept reaching
for him. Now he's gone, and the league has to find something else,
something tangible. Maybe it never will. But at least this way it
gets to find out, sooner rather than later. And it gets to do it in
a season of lowered expectations. What's a little more turbulence
when you're already in flux?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
