<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks could lose Henderson
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't be surprised if the Atlanta Hawks start the
season next month with a brand new power forward that is only a
short-term solution to their needs. The team appears close to
losing both of its free agents, Alan Henderson and Christian
Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   As agents and teams talk money and options, Henderson is getting
a sense of his worth that might far exceed what the Hawks are
willing to give him.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock won't say so, but Henderson
apparently believes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing things,'' Henderson said with a coy smile Friday
at Life University's gym.
</P>
<P>
   What Henderson hears is that there are a handful of teams with
some important money to spend and that he is at least an object of
their affections.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is eligible for a contract that could start as high as
$9million with annual raises of 10 to 12 percent, the low number if
he signs with any team but the Hawks. Voted the league's most
improved player, he averaged 14.3 points a game, 19 as a starter,
and 6.4 rebounds last season. That makes Henderson an attractive
athlete at age 26. The Pistons, among others, have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is one of the names they are mentioning in Detroit.
But they also are talking about Laettner, Cliff Robinson, Joe
Smith, Loy Vaught and Matt Geiger. What the Pistons want most is a
big man who can shoot, to open the lane for Grant Hill. That's not
necessarily Henderson, whose best game is in the paint, but his
passion for the game might make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner continues to be linked with Detroit because he played
so successfully with Hill at Duke. However, it has been reported
reliably that Laettner is asking for $8million, which might kill
his chances. Laettner played so indifferently with the Hawks that
he lost his starting job, then he tore an Achilles tendon in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Lon Babby, who also represents Hill, said, ``Our doctors
say he could play as early as March and for sure by the playoffs.
Obviously, they can't guarantee anything, but Christian is ahead of
schedule, and that is what we are shooting for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, however, aren't buying. Their medical information is
that Laettner can start working on the court in March, not that he
can play.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line on Laettner is that the Hawks would sign him to
trade him, thereby helping a team that has cap trouble, but that he
won't play here again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Philadelphia is ready to offer the Hawks a
sign-and-trade deal for Henderson if his asking price is more than
Atlanta can swallow. However, the player offered is Derrick
Coleman, who weighs close to 300 pounds now.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock responds with the air of a man who has heard it all
before. ``When we get the numbers from the league and know what all
the values are, then we can make some decisions,'' he said. ``Right
now, all the talk is interesting, but for the most part it's only
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have made no secret of their desire to remain flexible
for next summer's round of free-agent signings. That's when Shareef
Abdur-Rahim, Allen Iverson and Stephon Marbury come on the market.
</P>
<P>
   With such veteran big men as Popeye Jones, John ``Hot Rod''
Williams, Cherokee Parks, LaPhonso Ellis, Will Perdue, Bill
Wennington and Antoine Carr available _ some at door-buster prices
_ the Hawks might take a step back, in hopes of taking a giant step
forward July 1.
</P>
<P>
   HAWKS TRAINING CAMP
</P>
<P>
   _ Start: Tuesday, at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Format: Twice daily at several area sites, including Life
University and Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access: Closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exhibitions: At Charlotte, Jan. 29, 7:30 p.m., and at Georgia
Tech, Jan. 30, 7:30 p.m. Admission is free with vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Season opener: Tentatively Feb 5.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
