</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free agent rumor mill's in overdrive
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Somebody's lying. Maybe everybody's lying. It's a
time-honored sports tradition during a signing period, but the NBA
is over the limit here.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta is going to sign with Phoenix, Houston or
Minnesota, with maybe a sign-and-trade to the Lakers for Elden
Campbell. Why Elden Campbell? Who knows? Just remember that the
Wolves' Kevin McHale previously signed Stojko Vrankovic and gambled
on Stanley Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only the beginning. Today, we will take you through
the fact and fancy of cranking up an NBA season in February. All of
this is credible. Someplace.
</P>
<P>
   As teams, agents and players look closer at the new
collective-bargaining agreement, it's clear that several teams that
expected to be contenders for free agents this summer aren't going
to have anywhere near the salary-cap room they anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, for instance, was hoping it might have nearly
$15million but will be closer to $3million unless the Kings
unexpectedly renounce rights to some of their own free agents,
including Corliss Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is compromised because it wants to retain a few of its
free agents, notably Rex Chapman, but the Suns could open
$15.6million under the cap. Denver has $13.5million available if it
renounces forward LaPhonso Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Houston has the inside track on Scottie Pippen. The
deal is estimated at four years, starting at $9.3million. Pippen's
agents are trying to get the Bulls to do a sign-and-trade so Pippen
can get the maximum, but Chicago GM Jerry Krause can't seem to pull
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockets have interest; Scottie has interest,'' agent
Jimmie Sexton confirms. ``It's more than (casual). It's something
that he's considering strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   And Charles Barkley doesn't want to leave the stage in Texas.
``I would love to play for the Rockets,'' Barkley said. ``If
they're handcuffed, we'll have to see how it works out. Money will
not matter. If I have to play at minimum, that's cool. I have
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley might leave Bulls
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls also are on the verge of losing center Luc Longley to
the Suns for six years, starting point at $3.5million. That would
allow the Suns to double dip and go after Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   Longley's agent, Jeff Austin, confirms there are talks going on,
but said he was unsure a deal will be struck, saying, ``Either
you're there or you're not. Right now, we're not there.''
</P>
<P>
   On a smaller scale, both Indiana and Milwaukee are after forward
Sam Perkins, who apparently is done in Seattle. The Bucks also like
Derek Harper. So does Indiana if ex-Georgia Tech point guard Travis
Best elects to go somewhere else for starter's money.
</P>
<P>
   The price of centers
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte has a problem with Glen Rice, who demands a
renegotiation with two years at $5.4million and $7.1million. But a
Rice signing would compromise the Hornets' chances of getting a
center. They already cringe at the idea of having to pay Vlade
Divac $105.875million over seven years or Matt Geiger as much as
$86.625million over seven. But if the Hornets want a center who can
take them back to the playoffs, those are the prices. Alternatives:
Ike Austin (ex-Clippers) or 76ers free agent Theo Ratliff, both
looking at $67.5million over six.
</P>
<P>
   Pistons clean house
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are prepared to renounce Grant Long, Rick Mahorn,
Steve Henson and Malik Sealy and unload Eric Montross and Charlie
O'Bannon, if they can. Then, if they can sign Jerry Stackhouse and
Joe Dumars at $3.5million each, they could clear $8million and go
after a combination of power forward Christian Laettner or Loy
Vaught and $1million shooter Steve Kerr or Dennis Scott. But there
also is a report that Detroit has settled on Cliff Robinson to open
the inside for Grant Hill. ... Denver is one of four teams _ along
with the Suns, Rockets and Bulls _ who can make a play for Antonio
McDyess, whose talent is enormous but whose command of the game's
intricacies remain in question.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets also want Chauncey Billups, the ex-Colorado point
guard now under contract in Toronto. They are willing to send a
first-rounder and role player to get him. ... With Michael Jordan
gone and Pippen no longer welcome, the Bulls also got the cold
shoulder from McDyess. Now, they can turn their attention to free
agent Brent Barry, who is 6-foot-6 and can pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprewell bidding
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Knicks have joined the Heat and Pacers in talking
to the Warriors about Latrell Sprewell. The Spurs have dropped out
of the bidding for lack of ammunition, narrowing the field to
three.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what each is offering: the Knicks have put up Chris Mills
and Chris Childs, but John Starks could come into the picture if
the Warriors reject Childs; the Pacers are dangling Dale Davis,
Jalen Rose and Haywoode Workman to make the cap work; Miami is
offering Jamal Mashburn and Voshon Lenard, but the Warriors want
P.J. Brown instead of Mashburn, and that's a deal-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks have another problem, trying to re-sign free
agent point guard Charlie Ward, who opted out of his last contract.
Since Childs is starting the third year of a six-year deal
averaging $4million, figure that Ward will get more. Ward's wife,
Tonja, a lawyer with a sports-marketing business, has suggested
that he ask for a no-trade clause. That would put him in New York
for seven years. Asking price: $5million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's Best is another young free-agent guard who would
accept a nice raise to stay with his team. ``The rules don't allow
for a lot of movement,'' Best said.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando also likes Austin, but the Magic might bite on another
rumored deal with the Lakers that would re-unite Horace Grant with
Shaquille O'Neal and send Campbell to the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
