<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC gets high rating from Fox
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since Fox began televising the NFL in 1994, it has
grown accustomed to getting a ratings windfall from the NFC
Championship Game. The network also has grown accustomed to having
the Cowboys, 49ers or Packers playing.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, America also has grown accustomed to seeing one
of those three teams in the title game. The last time there was an
NFC championship that didn't include at least one of them was 1991,
when the Redskins trounced the Lions 41-10.
</P>
<P>
   That game drew a 29.5 Nielsen rating on CBS, just a shade below
Fox's 30.1 average for the past four years. So Fox is quite
confident viewers across the country will be drawn to Atlanta and
Minnesota in similar fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no concerns about that,'' Fox executive producer Ed
Goren said. ``It goes back to the fact that our playoff ratings
this season are up 19 percent (with a 21.4 average), and we've had
three new teams, Atlanta, Minnesota and Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Falcons never have been in the NFC title game, and
the Vikings are ending a 10-year drought, Fox was heartened by the
21.4 rating for last week's Cardinals-Vikings game, and the 18.2
for the Falcons and 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the championship game, the public appreciates the
fact the two teams have earned the right to be there,'' said former
CBS Sports president Neal Pilson, who operates a television
consulting company. ``The public is not sensitive to market size
and who's playing. The key to the ratings will still be the quality
of the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the quality of competition won't affect the bottom line for
the telecast. Fox has sold out the advertising for the game, which
is usually two to three times higher than regular-season rates and
can generate more than $20 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fox is coming off a championship telecast that drew the
first sub-30 rating in the network's brief NFL history. Last year's
NFC Championship Game between the Packers and 49ers got a 26.2, the
lowest number for the title game in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was still the second-highest-rated show in all of
television behind the Super Bowl, and we expect this game to beat
that number, even in the early window,'' Goren said. ``With all the
options viewers have today, cable, DirecTV, computers, big-event
sports still draw eyeballs to the sets like no other programming.
Major sports is the real must-see TV, because people want to see it
when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
