<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-BIGGAME17-COX     01-16 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-BIGGAME17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elder Falcons play advise and consent role
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cornelius Bennett has counseled Chuck Smith on
everything from the mushrooming media horde to the value of
postseason travel agents. Tony Martin has conveyed the wonder, and
urgency, of playoff football to such January innocents as O.J.
Santiago, Henri Crockett and Elijah Williams. And the other day in
practice, Eugene Robinson imparted a most practical lesson to Tim
Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bennett and Martin, Robinson tried to explain about playing
in an NFL conference championship game _ and for a shot at the
Super Bowl. It is something that younger Falcons players have been
asking all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the football field, that's when you (often) get
that type of question,'' said Robinson, the 14th-year free safety
who played in the past two Super Bowls with the Green Bay Packers.
``When I come over the top and say, `Hey! You've got to be over
here!' And Tim Dwight says, `Hey, Gene, I need you to slow down,
man. You're too hyped up.' I said, `Tim, the reason why I am
(hyper) and running all over the place is because that's what
you've got to do at this juncture. So if I have to push you out of
bounds or I have to get my hands in your face and you don't like
it, I'm sorry. Cause I'm going to make sure I'm doing my thing. So
you get on the same boat.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm that you run across the field (with), it
conveys to the other guy that this is an important deal: `I'm 35
years old. I shouldn't be outrunning you. So you'd better get in
gear. Let's get ready to go and play a huge game.'''
</P>
<P>
   The survivor of today's Falcons-Vikings NFC title game goes to
Super Bowl XXXIII on Jan. 31 in Miami. Only four Falcons _Robinson,
Bennett (a four-time loser with Buffalo), Martin and backup
cornerback Randy Fuller _ have Super Bowl experience. Just two
others _ defensive backs Ray Buchanan and William White _ played in
conference championship games. Since the Falcons clinched the NFC
West title on Dec. 20, those six players have tried to explain the
aura and seriousness of such games and detail the necessary
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Bennett told some players after last Saturday's playoff
victory against San Francisco: ``You have to realize we're playing
for the greatest trophy in all of sports, the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, this game has more media representatives. And
additional security guards at the stadium. More TV commercials
interrupting play. Travel on Friday instead of Saturday. And a
Friday news conference for some players. As for game tickets, plane
flights and hotel rooms, Bennett advised, ``Just get your
significant other there. Trying to get people in town, get hotel
rooms and tickets, that's not something we need to worry about. Let
the travel agent worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different game when you get to this level,'' said
Martin, whose only catch in the 1994 AFC title game was a 43-yard
touchdown reception that gave San Diego a 17-13 victory in
Pittsburgh. ``It requires a high-level intensity.'' To younger
teammates who have wondered what it's like playing for, then in,
the Super Bowl, Martin used such words as ``wonderful,''
``indescribable'' and ``the ultimate high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell 'em, `It's amazing,''' he said. ``Once you get to this
level, it's amazing to keep winning and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson advised how loud the Metrodome will be. How emotion is
crucial, but, ``you've got to remain (fundamentally) sound.'' And
most of all, how the time is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to go out there and seize the moment,'' Robinson
said. ``If you don't seize the moment, man, it's going to pass you
by, and you'll be watching someone else play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
