</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-BIGKICK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andersen's Super goal: Kick up heels at dance
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He can hyperbolize with the rest of 'em. ``The Big
Dance,'' ``the Ultimate Dance,'' ``a Wonderful Show,'' Morten
Andersen called the Super Bowl, all in a single conversation. In a
17-year football career, he's attended eight Super Bowls, seven
while working as an analyst for Danish television on TV 3 ScanSat.
In Minneapolis today, Andersen will be one victory away from
finally putting his best foot forward on sport's grandest stage.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Big Ultimate Not-So-Wonderful irony of it all.
</P>
<P>
   The one year that Morten Andersen _ the Ernie Banks of kickers,
the best kicker to never sideswipe in a Super Bowl _ has a chance
to reach the Roman-numeral affair and erase the lone blemish on his
resume, the game won't be televised in his native Denmark, land of
the midnight kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewership last year was too poor to warrant showing it,''
Andersen said. ``So unless you have satellite TV and you want to
watch the Danish guy kick the football, you're out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Danes always could go to Norway to catch the Super Bowl. Or, as
Andersen discussed with his father, Erik, back in his hometown of
Struer, ``You'd need a (TV) de-coder to watch it.'' Otherwise, if
the Falcons upset the Vikings in the NFC Championship Game, the
Danes couldn't watch the Danish guy kick at night on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me as kind of odd,'' Andersen said. ``All these
years we've shown it with me as a commentator, and now I may get to
play in it and...''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not being televised in Copenhagen, pre-empted by _
what? A Fran Tarkenton infomercial? The Sunday midnight movie, ``On
Frozen Fjord''?
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me kind of weird,'' Andersen said. ``Ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the Danes could do something, to find a way to show
XXXIII on TV 3 if it includes Andersen. He is, after all, a
national hero in Denmark and one of the greatest kickers in NFL
history, the holder of seven NFL records who has converted 25
game-winning field goals in his career. He is to long-range kicking
what Michael Jordan was to mid-air majesty. The best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting, an exciting time for me personally because I've
never been this far,'' Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   Until last Saturday's victory against San Francisco, Andersen
had played in five NFL playoff games, losing all five: Four with
New Orleans, where he played from 1982-94, and a 1995 wild-card
defeat in Green Bay with the Falcons. After kicking two field goals
and two extra points in the 20-18 victory against the 49ers,
Andersen finds himself a game away from a Super Bowl blackout back
home in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to describe what it means to me personally is hard to
describe,'' said Andersen, the NFL's No. 3 career scorer with 1,761
points _ 71 points behind Vikings kicker Gary Anderson (``More of a
finesse kicker, a very pure ball; and I'm more of a power
kicker''). ``But it's more important to this team and this city.
Win Sunday, and you get to the ultimate dance.''
</P>
<P>
   If that would leave 'em re-programming in the studios of
Copenhagen, it would also greatly satisfy Andersen, 38. ``It just
means if you stick around long enough, you'll get a chance to be
here,'' he said, smiling. ``It's something that's been missing in
my career. I've never gotten to the big dance. We're one step
away.''
</P>
<P>
   A Super Bowl. ``As time goes on, who knows if it's ever going to
happen?'' Andersen recalls thinking. ``But it won't be, `If I don't
go, if I don't make it, I'll be devastated.' I'll be disappointed,
but I won't lose sleep. But there's no doubt I want to play in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen will have a life after football, whether he ever plays
in a Super Bowl. Asked what it would mean to finally kick in a Big
Ultimate Wonderful Dance, he replied, ``It would mean closure in
some way, I guess. I don't mean I would retire. (But) I would feel
I couldn't say I wasn't afforded that opportunity. And how you
handled that opportunity is what defines you as a person and a
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
