<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bourbon Street bound
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The record-setting goaltending of John Vanbiesbrouck
is getting most of the credit for making the Philadelphia Flyers
into the hottest team in the NHL. But maybe the players are just
trying to pay back coach Roger Neilson. The Flyers, like many NHL
teams, will take a warm-weather retreat to get some R&AMP;R. But the
destination isn't the usual Florida or Arizona. A four-player
committee of Rod Brind'Amour, Eric Desjardins, John LeClair and
Eric Lindros selected New Orleans as the team's destination for a
four-day break in March. Surprisingly, Neilson agreed. ``I was a
little worried about the drinking, but they assured me there would
be drinking everywhere we went,'' he said. Bourbon Street and all
its lures will be waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada Centre, Toronto's new home replacing Maple Leaf
Gardens, will open on Feb. 20. Among the special features in the
new arena is an exhaust system in the coaches' quarters designed to
filter out cigar smoke. That would be because coach Pat Quinn, a
former Atlanta Flames defenseman, is a legendary cigar smoker. The
last game at Maple Leaf Gardens is Feb. 13, against the Chicago
Blackhawks. The team already is practicing at Air Canada Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Speed kills
</P>
<P>
   The way the young Ottawa Senators are playing now, they might
turn into the surprise team of the playoffs. What makes Ottawa a
threat is its speed. ``We have a lot of young, fast guys on this
team, and that's what the NHL is about these days,'' defenseman
Jason York said. ``Speed kills. Teams with speed are the teams that
are winning.'' New Jersey forward Brian Rolston said, ``If you turn
the puck over they can turn it up ice pretty quick. There is no
question they have speed. They have a lot of speed, but they are
disciplined as well. If they don't have an opportunity to
forecheck, they stay back and clog up the neutral zone. They're
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   New York Rangers center Wayne Gretzky, who has never missed an
NHL All-Star Game, trails only Gordie Howe's record 23 appearances.
Selected as a reserve on the North America squad, Gretzky will play
in his 18th All-Star Game at Tampa on Jan. 24. ...Washington
defenseman Sergie Gonchar was penalized two minutes for using an
illegal stick in a game in which he already had scored two goals.
``It's just a long curve,'' Gonchar said.... Maple Leafs president
Ken Dryden says goaltender Curtis Joseph allows his team to play a
go-go offensive style: ``Our thought is, if you have a good goalie,
why do all this work to only let him face 20 shots a game? If you
have a good goalie, you have to trust him.'' ...Rangers forward
Todd Harvey is expected to be sidelined 4-6 weeks with a sprained
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
