<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going over the line
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Things could get interesting Monday when the San Jose
Sharks host New Jersey. Devils defenseman Scott Stevens could be a
target after some trash talk the last time the teams met. He is
accused of calling Sharks right wing Brantt Myhres ``a drunk'' and
saying he should ``have another beer.'' Myhres, a former Atlanta
Knight, spent the start of this season in alcohol rehabilitation,
his second time in treatment. ``He's a kid trying to get his career
together,'' Sharks right wing Owen Nolan said about Myhres, 24.
``What was said is unacceptable. If they're going to suspend people
for (making racial comments), this is just as bad.'' Stevens
wouldn't confirm or deny the remarks, saying, ``Sometimes you say
things you regret.'' Stevens' longtime teammate Ken Daneyko spent
time in a rehab center last season.
</P>
<P>
   Looking glass
</P>
<P>
   The new Staples Center in Los Angeles, which opens next season,
will not have the seamless glass above the boards that has been
blamed by players for injuries because it's rigid and doesn't give
when heads and bodies hit it. ``The seamless glass is nice to look
through and gives nice, true bounces, but we were worried about
concussions,'' said Kings general manager Dave Taylor, whose career
was ended because of a head injury. The Atlanta Thrashers have not
made a decision on what type of glass will be installed in their
new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Service
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver general manager Brian Burke might have infuriated
Canucks fans with his attempts to trade Pavel Bure, but he made one
fan for his response to a testy e-mail. Travis Lindgren, an
educator in Napean, Ontario, said he just wanted to get a few
things off his chest. But Burke responded, and included his private
phone number. Lindgren called, and the two spoke for 15 minutes.
``I was pretty impressed,'' Lindgren said. Burke said he was glad
to restore the faith of at lease one fan. ``I take that very
seriously,'' Burke said. ``From my perspective, it's really
important, especially in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit will have the most players (five) in the All-Star Game
at Tampa on Jan. 24. Left wing Brendan Shanahan and center Steve
Yzerman will start for the North American team, defensemen Nicklas
Lidstrom and Uwe Krupp for the World squad. Defensman Larry Murphy
was selected as a North America reserve.... Despite the best record
in the league, Dallas has only three players in the game, all
reserves.... Kingscenter Ray Ferraro had surgery to repair torn
cartilage in his right knee. He may be sidelined 4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
