</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small-game workshop set
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fostering respect for the environment is one of the
chief goals of an upcoming small-game hunting workshop sponsored by
the Wildlife Resources Division of the state Department of Natural
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Introduction to Small Game Hunting for Youth program, 10
a.m.-4 p.m. Saturday at the Charlie Elliott Wildlife Center in
Mansfield, will provide hands-on instruction and activities for
children ages 10-12. Wildlife Resources associates and volunteers
will provide the instruction for the free workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting kids involved in outdoor sports such as hunting at a
young age teaches them respect for the environment, wildlife and
other natural resources,'' WRD director David Waller said.
``Workshops like this offer youth a chance to learn new outdoor
skills in a fun, non-threatening and safe environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids first will be taught how to identify the main small
game species found in Georgia. Then the group will be introduced to
appropriate beginner firearms, firearms safety and Georgia's
hunting rules and regulations. Squirrel- and rabbit-hunting
techniques will be taught using dogs trained for hunting those
small game species on the Clybel Wildlife Management Area.
Participants also will have the opportunity to practice shooting
.22 rifles under the direct supervision of WRD associates.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife Resources will provide all firearms, for safety
reasons, but each participant must bring a fluorescent orange
hunter-safety vest. Preregistration is required, and registration
is limited to the first 25 applicants. An adult at least 21 must
accompany the youth for the entire length of the program.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call Kimberly Brooks at 770-784-3060.
</P>
<P>
   Here come the pros
</P>
<P>
   It seems appropriate that BASS Fishing Techniques '99, the
bass-fishing seminars sponsored by the Bass Anglers Sportsman
Society, is part of Kennesaw State University's Continuing
Education Program. Learning to catch America's favorite gamefish is
an ongoing process for anglers of all skill levels.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day course, Saturday and Sunday at the Wyndham Garden
Hotel in Marietta, covers most techniques from lure presentation to
bass behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The class is taught by six top tournament professionals,
including two-time BASS Angler of the Year and BASS Masters Classic
champion Larry Nixon. The Bee Branch, Ark., pro has competed in 16
Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Other pros expected are Jack Hains, Alton Jones, Rich Tauber,
Greg Hines and Gerald Swindle.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are from 7 a.m.-3:30 p.m. Saturday and 8 a.m.-3:30 p.m.
Sunday. Cost is $89, $44.50 for a spouse or a child 16 or under.
The class is part of a nationwide program that began in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Kennesaw State course, call
770-423-6765.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is
</P>
<P>
   The trout fishing and wild-turkey hunting in the Chattahoochee
National Forest and paddling down Talking Rock Creek are three
reasons why Ellijay is Georgia's best outdoors sports towns,
according to the February issue of Sports Afield magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The publication's ``50 Best Towns'' feature, which lists the
best in each state, says the north Georgia city of 1,700 located in
the southern foothills of the Appalachians also offers rugged
mountain-biking terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
