<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-REEVES17-COX     01-16 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-REEVES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves seeing another side
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves has made his living in football since 1965,
when he poured his soul into making the Dallas Cowboys' roster as
an undrafted quarterback who was moved to running back.
</P>
<P>
   After his playing days, he kept chasing his dream, becoming an
assistant in Dallas, then head coach of the Denver Broncos in 1981
and head coach of the New York Giants in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Football took him across the nation, but his heart stayed in his
native Georgia, where he grew up on a farm in Americus.
</P>
<P>
   After the Giants fired him in 1996 and the Atlanta Falcons
offered their job, it was automatic that Reeves would return to
Georgia. But only after he underwent quadruple heart-bypass surgery
on Dec. 14, and Atlanta fans exhibited their love for the coach,
did he and his family truly grasp the meaning of what it meant to
be back home.
</P>
<P>
   It has been magical watching the Falcons set all kinds of
records while going 15-2 and advancing to today's NFC Championship
Game for the first time in the team's mostly dreadful 33-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming an icon, and, more important, getting a chance to
extend his life, has been Reeves' ultimate _ yet trying _
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very much hurt, disappointed, with an aching in my heart
when they said `bypass,''' said Pam, his wife and high school
sweetheart of more than 34 years. ``The last two years in New York
(1995-96) were very hard ... to where it was hard for Dan to go to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gotten through that, we had gotten to Georgia, and you
could see the changes taking place,'' Pam Reeves said. ``My first
thought was, `No, we're on the brink of something here. It's not
fair that he won't be able to finish it out, to enjoy it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 54, will enjoy today's game against the Minnesota
Vikings (16-1) on the sideline at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   His energy level in increasing daily, his color is better, and
he's not getting winded during interviews. All that will continue
to change.
</P>
<P>
   Some things won't.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of heart surgeon James Kauten holding Reeves'
non-beating heart in his hand roughly a month ago ``still blows me
away,'' Reeves said, and it always will.
</P>
<P>
   And there may be no way to surprise him as much as he's been
surprised by the reaction caused by his condition.
</P>
<P>
   Home, sweet home.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are the envy of the NFL and the talk of the town.
Signs all over the city, callers to radio shows and letters to the
editor profess fans' faith in their team and its coach.
</P>
<P>
   The city has fallen in love with Reeves, and he's shocked more
by that than the miracle last month of having his heart stopped for
three hours during bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been overwhelming how many cards and letters and so forth
have come in. You think about yourself getting sick, but you don't
think about that many people responding to it,'' said Reeves, who
has received 1,500 to 2,000 letters and cards. ``It's amazing when
we're out ... how everybody sees you and wishes you well, and tells
you they're praying for you and they hope the team does well. They
seem to recognize you a lot more than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' son Lee, 31, a lawyer in Atlanta, said, ``There have
been so many blessings this year. It has been a great year for the
city of Atlanta, the Falcons and the Reeves. We're thankful. You'd
be amazed at how people have rallied around the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reeves family _ which includes wife Pam, daughters Dana and
Laura, two sons-in-law, a daughter-in-law, granddaughters Caitlin,
Ashley and Morgan, and Reeves' 82-year-old mother, Ann _ has always
been close by any description. It's closer now.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves got choked up several times at his Dec. 18 news
conference when he was first released from the hospital. Earlier
this week, he again had to pause a couple times, thinking back to
Dec. 14, when his family _ minus his mother, who remained in
Americus _ was at the hospital. His older brother, Charles, was
there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tense time,'' Reeves said, pausing for about 20
seconds. ``My brother ... led us in a word of prayer. That was the
most touching thing. I don't know how he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Reeves, 62, lives in Dunwoody, where he just retired
from a job as president of a crushed-stone company.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up eight years apart, but the two have always had a
special relationship. It grew stronger after Charles graduated from
Georgia Tech, where he was a manager for Bobby Dodd's football
teams, and returned to Americus.
</P>
<P>
   While working, he followed his brother's athletic career, even
driving the bus for road games when Dan played basketball. Miles
separated them during the years, at least until Reeves moved to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, they couldn't have been closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember whose idea (the prayer) was,'' Charles Reeves
said. ``It could have been any one of us. It wasn't the first
(prayer). You don't wait until this crisis to start praying for the
well-being of your family.''
</P>
<P>
   The past month has left other impressions on Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   He went back in the hospital on Dec. 20, when his heart rate
started fluctuating at home, just a couple of hours before he was
going to watch the Falcons play the Lions on television, a game
Atlanta won 24-17 to clinch the NFC West title.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the scariest time for my family because
nobody knew what was going on,'' said Reeves, who was released from
the hospital a second time on Christmas Eve. ``Through it all, Pam
has been the one who has taken the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' brother said the prayer that day, but Reeves' wife has
been the family's pillar, leaving him both in awe and completely
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Doctors) won't let you do anything, lift anything,'' said
Reeves, who still is limited to 30 pounds. ``You go through
Christmas, and everything is taken down. She's doing that, and I'm
trying to help, but I can't, and I feel worthless. She was doing
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves packed a few Christmas tree ornaments away, but Pam
handled most of the work. That's not all she handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the one thing that has slapped Dad in the face is how
strong my mom is,'' Lee said. ``She has been the beacon. He might
have expected it to be a male in the family, maybe me or him. I
crumbled in my mom's arms, my dad's arms. She has been so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves said she just did what she had to. ``Nurturing is
maybe a little bit more of a female characteristic,'' she said.
``If they perceive me as coming through as strong, I would say,
thank you very much. But I don't know if I felt strong. We had no
time to think about it; it was just upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have shown their concern for Reeves. NFL commissioner
Paul Tagliabue called, and Reeves has spoken with Tom Landry, under
whom he played and coached with the Dallas Cowboys (1965-80).
</P>
<P>
   He also has heard from actor Burt Reynolds, New York Yankees
owner George Steinbrenner and comedian Bill Cosby, whom he first
met in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill sent me a card that said something like, `I've got 12
pounds of bacon and deep-fried hamhocks when you're ready, but get
well first,''' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves always thought her husband should have shown his
Cosby side. ``People have always thought of Dan as stern or stoic,
but in our family people always thought of him as Bill Cosby,'' she
said. ``I've always said, `Dan, just please try to be at your press
conferences like you are when you go golfing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves earlier this season joked that former Cowboys teammate
Walt Garrison was his friend until Reeves became a player-coach and
had to supervise Garrison with the Cowboys. The other day, Garrison
sent Reeves a talking and singing frog.
</P>
<P>
   ```Frog' was a nickname he gave me years ago,'' Reeves said,
referring to a moniker he got for his low, rumbling voice.
</P>
<P>
   Another high point came during halftime of the final
regular-season game Dec. 27 against Miami. Reeves spoke to the team
before the game at the Georgia Dome and then watched on television
at home. At halftime, 14 get-well cards, each 4 feet by 8 feet,
were paraded on the field with signatures from thousands of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got that on video,'' he said proudly. ``It was
overwhelming. Who thought of that? It's just amazing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After he won the Associated Press Coach of the Year award a
couple of weeks ago, Reeves joked that the ``sympathy vote'' was
part of the reason. But there's no joking about the fact his
perspective on life has been reinforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've always had a good understanding of how fragile
life is,'' he said. ``Any of us who've had a death in the family
understand it's very short and it goes by very quickly _ that
everything is very precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Reeves said ``people's perception of Dan has changed. Maybe
they saw him at the news conference tear up. Those are the same
people who see him ... on the sidelines ... when he's exploding at
officials. People's perception of Dan is that he's mellowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves dismissed the rumor that he will step down as coach after
the season, work only in the Falcons' front office and appoint a
successor, perhaps defensive coordinator Rich Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a question about that,'' he said. ``Unless
something happens that I can't foresee, I should be better able to
(coach) better than I was able to this past year. I'll have more
energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I want to coach 10 more years, but as long as I
feel good, enjoy what I'm doing, and I'm good at it, I plan to keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   His son sees a new kind of energy in his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk a couple times a day, and, if anything, he may be a
little more mellow in that he appreciates life that much more,''
Lee said. ``Praying in the hospital was nothing new. Dad was best
man at my wedding (last fall), and he prayed for me to give me a
stillness before I went out in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible, scary situation last month, but it unified
us even more as a family. Dad has seen God's blessing on his life
in more ways than he did a few weeks ago, and we all have, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
