u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MLK-STREETS17-COX     01-16 1909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-STREETS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The many signs of Martin Luther King Jr.
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His name is on street signs just about everywhere in
Georgia _ everywhere except the white part of town.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 cities and towns all across the state have named
streets for the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., a tribute to his
message of equality and unity that will be celebrated with Monday's
national holiday in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   However, the geographical reality of King's asphalt legacy is
more about boundaries than about bridges.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, with only minor exceptions, King's namesake streets
are fully contained in black neighborhoods. Some of those streets
are busy and thriving urban thoroughfares; others are little more
than country lanes; and several are home to vacant lots and public
housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   None of the numerous state academic and economic experts
consulted could name a city where the Martin Luther King namesake
street runs outside a black neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker, the first black person
to hold that office, said the number of King namesake streets is
more important than their location.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who has traveled Georgia extensively, said he couldn't
recall a city that has a Martin Luther King Street in a
predominantly white neighborhood; nevertheless, he said the
proliferation of streets named for King is a ``tremendous honor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been concerned over which streets cities have
chosen to name after Dr. King,'' he said. ``The key point is that
so many cities, in Georgia and around the nation, have chosen to
recognize Dr. King and his achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   But some who live and work on the Martin Luther King streets ,
boulevards and avenues around Georgia express concern that the
streets typically don't run outside their communities _ although
most of those interviewed seemed glad that they can see King's name
on virtually every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remembrance of what he stood for,'' said Faison Elijah
as he walked down Albany's Martin Luther King Drive. ``That man
gave his life for his dreams, and that street keeps the dream
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be celebrations and memorials on many of Georgia's
Martin Luther King roadways this week. Here is a sampling of what
those streets are like and what's on the minds of some of the
people there:
</P>
<P>
   WAYCROSS
</P>
<P>
   This city's Martin Luther King Drive would be a pleasant place
to live in any part of town. The homes are neat and well-kept.
There are palm trees and children's bikes in the yards. But there
also is disquiet in Neyea Harris' voice as she talks about street
names and racial understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only find Martin Luther King streets in African-American
communities,'' she said. ``I feel like all people should remember
him. He helped all the people. But here, it's still segregated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waycross MLK has something many other King streets in
Georgia do not have: a monument to the slain civil rights leader.
It is a polished granite marker partially surrounded by a low brick
wall, located adjacent to a city housing project and a few yards
from a maintenance garage.
</P>
<P>
   Unilla Mitchell, who lives a few houses away from the marker,
thinks the setting detracts from the desired effect of the
monument. A large dumpster for the housing project sits close by,
and the area is often clogged with garbage trucks and maintenance
vehicles, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the way it's so jammed-up looking,'' Mitchell
said. ``No offense, but I just think it should be displayed
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY
</P>
<P>
   Here, there's a street named Martin Luther King Drive and a
parallel road, Jefferson Street, that some residents would like to
re-name Martin Luther King Drive. The former street begins and ends
within the black community; the latter runs the length of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The street-name debate has been a political hot potato for
years. The majority of the City Council has switched back and forth
from black to white in recent elections, and the issue of renaming
Jefferson Street for King has flared up in most of the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Ewings Sr., who directs the Martin Luther King
Outreach Mission in south Albany, said those who oppose the
renaming of Jefferson Street cite problems such as the costs to
businesses that would have to change their mailing addresses. They
typically sidestep the racial implications, he added, but most
people know they exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Martin Luther King Drive runs out of the black community,
then it gets to be a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ewings thinks the prospects are good for improvement in
race relations in Albany. ``Things are going to change,'' he said,
``and we'll be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewings acquired his patience the hard way. His mission was in
the sector of Albany most devastated by the floods of 1994. After
years of waiting for recovery programs to be implemented, he gained
approval last February for an expansion of his center.
</P>
<P>
   Then new floods hit last March, and the paperwork mountain had
to be climbed again.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks from the mission is the recently opened Albany
Civil Rights Movement Museum, and here one can find indications of
progress in the causes that King lived and died for. Museum
director Angela Whitmal said blacks and whites alike turned out for
the museum's 1998 dedication ceremonies; and the local paper, which
opposed many of the actions of civil rights activists in Albany in
the 1960s, gave the museum front-page coverage for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes will be the featured speaker at Albany's Martin
Luther King Day celebration this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably not going to change the world, but all these
things taken together are significant for Albany,'' Whitmal said.
</P>
<P>
   FORT VALLEY
</P>
<P>
   From the railroad tracks south of downtown to the city limits,
Martin Luther King Drive is a renamed highway running through a
decidedly non-bustling industrial and commercial district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing much going on here; over in Warner Robins,
they got new stuff going up all the time,'' said Frank McCrary, who
owns a grocery on the strip. ``It holds the small man down.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrary said his market does pretty well in the summer, when
there's plenty of fresh vegetables to sell. In winter, the traffic
is pretty much limited to folks buying turnips and processed
collard greens.
</P>
<P>
   Several other businesses along the section of Ga. 341 renamed
for King have folded in recent years, McCrary said.
</P>
<P>
   A Martin Luther King Day parade will pass McCrary's stand. There
could have been more of a crowd if the local Bluebird bus plant had
given its workers a day off for the holiday, McCrary said.
</P>
<P>
   DARIEN
</P>
<P>
   There are two majestic live oaks at one end of Martin Luther
King Jr. Boulevard. Otherwise, the median of this four-block-long
street is pretty much barren. It runs through a residential
neighborhood that has modest homes, trailers and some vacant lots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could use a little sprucing up,'' Jerry Bradley said as he
paused during a bicycle trip down the boulevard. But then, he
added, the same could be said about a lot of things in this quiet
coastal county seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of changes could be made in this little town,'' Bradley
said. ``It's slow, and so many things need to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   One change that has been made is in the McIntosh County
sheriff's office. During the 1950s and '60s, the office was held by
a man whose patronizing and domineering attitudes towards blacks
were a main topic of the award-winning book ``Praying For
Sheetrock.'' Now, the sheriff is a black man, Charles ``Chunk''
Jones, a Vietnam veteran and a former shrimpboat captain.
</P>
<P>
   SAVANNAH
</P>
<P>
   The King name has added a little bustle to old West Broad
Street.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, West Broad was the commercial artery of
Savannah's black community. Since its name was changed to Martin
Luther King Boulevard, and a freeway exit ramp added, traffic is up
and business is great at Gene Stevens' Rib Castle restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everybody knows where Martin Luther King ... is,'' Stevens
said. ``It's like this is the main drag.''
</P>
<P>
   A sizeable segment of Savannah's tourist trade cruises across
town on MLK, and regular customers, from soldiers to plant workers,
find their way to the small, concrete-block building that sends up
the sweet smoke of a barbecue fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sell out every day,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks down MLK Boulevard, Alberta Passmore sits on her
stoop, enjoying a cool January evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right here it's a nice neighborhood, but over there in the
projects, it was kind of rough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the housing project on the opposite side of the street from
her apartment is being remodeled, so no one lives there and she
feels better about sitting outside.
</P>
<P>
   Passmore said she's puzzled that most of the streets named for
King are found only in the black community. ``He wasn't nobody to
be afraid of,'' she said. ``Looks like to me, he was trying to help
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   WAYNESBORO
</P>
<P>
   A passerby stops in City Hall to ask directions to Martin Luther
King Drive. A white woman in the office shrugs; a black woman at
the next desk knows right where it is.
</P>
<P>
   The street spans a placid 10 blocks or so. A cemetery takes up
the land on one side for about half the length of the street. There
are two businesses, about six blocks apart.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ebony House of Styles, Clarence Johnson said he's
delighted to work on a street named for King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an honor,'' he said, ``something really special
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma Adams and her husband George operate a coin laundry with a
candy counter. They moved back to her hometown of Waynesboro after
living in New York for about 30 years. Emma said she's glad to be
home _ although things have changed. Drug trafficking in and around
the housing projects up the street have brought fear and crime, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here, but I didn't recognize the neighborhood when I
got back,'' she said. ``Now, you don't open the door without a
shotgun nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   The street may be named for King, but Adams isn't sure his story
is being told so much nowadays. ``Parents are not really teaching
their children what the man stood for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, life along the street is mostly good, she said. There are
plans for a local black history museum in the one-room schoolhouse
where she went to school up the street.
</P>
<P>
   And Adams and her husband get a chance to follow the growth and
struggles of the children who stop into her store for candy. She
relishes the triumphs of the ones who go on to good schools and
good jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some great things are happening on Martin Luther King Drive,''
Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Across Georgia, the streets named for King intersect other
streets with evocative names: Peace, Hope, Cotton, Victory. But
you'll have to look hard to find places where King's vision of
black children playing harmoniously with white children is realized
on Martin Luther King Street.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, it's more important that King's name is
perpetuated, no matter where the street runs.
</P>
<P>
   On the corner of Martin Luther King Boulevard and Victory Drive,
in Savannah, an elderly man named Thomas Brown summed up those
feelings succinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good,'' he said, ``that people can remember him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
