<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogs and cats living the dream as America's pets
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ 59 million dogs.
</P>
<P>
   71.8 million cats.
</P>
<P>
   The American Pet Association keeps tabs on such awe-inspiring
numbers (figures as of December 1994) while promoting responsible
pet ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs have come a long way from the days when they hunted for a
living. And cats _ first domesticated in Egypt _ went through that
nasty period of being feared and associated with witches.
</P>
<P>
   In my next life I am coming back as one of my dogs, who lead
more pampered lives than either my husband or my children and
certainly ones more carefree than mine. Think about it. Food,
medical care, clothing and shelter are provided for pets with a
minimum of demands. My dogs never drove a carpool, cooked a turkey
dinner for 16 guests or waxed a floor.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom does my mail not include a question (or six) on the
foibles of the Fidos and Garfields of Central Texas. To what
lengths do pet owners go to ensure the life, liberty and pursuit of
furry-friend happiness? Take a peek at what the Greig Files contain
on pets.
</P>
<P>
   _ What's that, Lassie? What did you say, girl? Timmy is stuck at
the bottom of a gorge and forgot to mail your insurance premium?
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a long line of commercial pet ventures is pet
medical insurance. The oldest pet insurance outfit is Veterinary
Pet Insurance, covering dogs and cats beginning at eight weeks _
with no age cap. More than 850,000 policies have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage includes vaccination, routine care, cancer, heart
conditions and accidents. The best part? VPI says the average
turnaround time for a claim is one week and coverage starts at $89
a year. (Think the company would want to take on humans?)
</P>
<P>
   _ Does your ``best friend'' need a little help these days
getting around on all fours?
</P>
<P>
   Custom Pet Wheels of Austin makes devices to help pets when they
can no longer use one of their limbs. All sizes, all prices.
</P>
<P>
   For an order form, call 837-7509 or fax 835-6479.
</P>
<P>
   _Could you pass the catnip, Lefty?
</P>
<P>
   Most cat lovers are surprised to learn that many cats are either
right-pawed or left-pawed. The feline encyclopedia ``Cat World,''
by Desmond Morris, says after careful tests (no idea what the tests
were) it was revealed that out of every 100 cats, about 40 percent
are left-pawed, 20 percent are right-pawed and 40 percent are
ambi-pawed. A sharp contrast to humans, where left-hand preference
is the exception.
</P>
<P>
   _ According to the American Pet Association, 41 percent of
American pet owners display a picture of their pets in their homes
and 17 percent have a photo in their wallet or purse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does this jacket make my flanks look big, Morris?
</P>
<P>
   A one-stop shopping collection of fashions for pets is Posh Pups
of California, where biker outfits, cowboy hats and jackets in
pinto pony patterns are de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   And if you feel the need to have your pet go to the altar, it
also stock-- bridal outfits and tuxedos. Call (800) 347-0567 to
order. The small sizes for dogs are perfect for felines.
</P>
<P>
   Another catalog is In the Company of Dogs at (800) 924-5050.
Leather jackets and cocktail attire are just a couple of the items.
Pet Quarters at (888) PET-NETT stocks jackets _ denim, biker,
bomber._To shave or not to shave?
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarian John Treadwell has many clients who elect to shave
their chows and even a few Labs (once in the spring and again in
August). When in doubt, ask your vet.
</P>
<P>
   Carol-Lynne Meissner of Mobile Veterinary Clinic says it is
appropriate to shave chows and other furry breeds such as Norwegian
elkhounds, leaving about one-fourth to one-half inch of fur for
protection. Chows are susceptible to skin problems and need to be
shielded from the sun. Slather your favorite sun block on Fido's
pink skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Book of Dogs'' notes ``chow'' is Cantonese for ``food.''_ Want
spaghetti with that garlic?
</P>
<P>
   Some pet owners report success in keeping pets flea-free with
the regular addition of garlic and brewer's yeast to a pet's diet.
Prepared, pre-mixed flakes are available at area pet stores or you
can make your own.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for a 25-pound dog begins with a half clove of garlic
minced with a 1/2 teaspoon of yeast per day. Work up to a full
clove of garlic and 1 teaspoon of yeast per day. The animal's coat
then becomes inhospitable to fleas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where does blood come from for animal transfusions? Donor cats
and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarian Rick Lusk says a transfusion is given to about one
animal a month at Westgate Pet and Bird Hospital. Cats are more
likely to need transfusions for treating flea anemia. Donors
usually are the hospital staff's pets, whose vaccination and
disease histories are well-known, although there are a few animal
blood banks in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Emergency Animal Clinic of Northwest Austin keeps cat and
dog blood on hand, whereas Westgate collects it as needed. Donor
animals regenerate blood in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Cats have three blood types; dogs, eight. In the canine world,
there are universal donor blood types; in felines, purebred cats
(often Type B) donate for purebreds, and nonpurebreds (usually Type
A) for nonpurebreds.
</P>
<P>
   A new blood product called Oxyglobin carries oxygen just like
blood does.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do any vets prescribe Prozac for cats? Mine bites her fur off.
</P>
<P>
   Your cat has a case of flank sucking (common in depressed cats),
known as psychogenic dermatitis, or inflammation of the skin from
self-trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Felines are susceptible to stress just like humans. The ideal
solution? Eliminate the cause of the stress, says veterinarian Ed
Childress of Highland's Pet Medical Clinic. Have a new pet in the
house? Been away? ``Chemicals should be used as a last-ditch
effort,'' adds Childress. Risks are associated with any drug,
including anti-depressants for animals with separation anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   _ This little pig went to market; this little pig did not come
home.
</P>
<P>
   A popular pet tidbit is baked pig ears. Yep, real pig ears. But
watch those calories, pet owners.
</P>
<P>
   Smokehouse Dog Treats sells about 12 million pig ears annually
and estimates each ear is 30 percent fat. The average baked ear
weighs 1.1 ounce and delivers 150 to 165 calories.
</P>
<P>
   Is it good for your dog? Veterinarian Geoffrey Wisbrock of the
Love Pet Hospital says if a 50-pound dog has a weight problem, the
culprit is probably overall diet rather than the one-pig-ear-a-day
treat. A 50-pound dog should be getting between 1,500 and 2,500
calories per day. Of course, working or pregnant dogs need more
calories. All treats should be given in moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Did Wisbrock ever give his dogs pig ears? Nope.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, several dogs have experienced dental problems caused
by chewing hooves, another popular treat. And dogs sometimes
swallow a bigger chunk than they should. Gulp!
</P>
<P>
   _ Out! Out! !!! spot!
</P>
<P>
   Keep a clean, dry rag under a chair cushion in every room where
Garfield or Fido might have an accident. This allows you to blot up
puddles immediately. Should you discover it later, use club soda
and cornstarch (pat, sprinkle, let dry, vacuum, repeat) to leach
the stain from carpet or upholstery. Always test for colorfastness
on fabrics. Some readers report luck with Windex as a quick fix
since it contains ammonia. Others swear by enzyme-based cleansers.
Vinegar neutralizes odors _ pet and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Face it, they all shed
</P>
<P>
   Keep masking tape in the car to remove pet hair from your
clothes at the last minute. Toss pet bedding covers in the dryer on
fluff to remove first layer of pet hair before washing. Brush your
pet often to remove loose hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shopping for Fido's vittles
</P>
<P>
   The ``Good Dog! Dog Product Buyers Guide'' offers these tips.
More than 250 products for your dog were tested and reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Try several brands for six to eight weeks before settling on
one. Use the brand that keeps your dog looking his best. Read
ingredients label for content of protein, fat, etc. Dried meat has
less water than fresh meat and therefore weighs less. Spend more to
save more. Premium dog foods have more nutrition per bite and so
may cost less per serving. Interpret the date code. Foods with
chemical antioxidants will generally be edible for one year; with
natural antioxidants like vitamin E, about nine months. Calculate
the shelf life based on your usage and the manufacturer's ``best
before'' date or manufacturer's code date.
</P>
<P>
   For a free sample of Good Dog! magazine call (800) 968-1738
(United States/Canada) or 454-3420. The ``Dog Product Buyers
Guide'' is available for $18 (includes shipping).
</P>
<P>
   _ Dog days
</P>
<P>
   Romans called the hottest days of the summer ``caniculares
dies,'' or ``dog days'' (July 3 through Aug. 11). It was believed
the appearance of Sirius, the dog star, contributed to the heat.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Presidential Pets' for $200, Alex
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon Johnson had beagles named Him and Her.
President Truman's dog was an Irish setter named Mike.
</P>
<P>
   The White House pooch of Nancy Reagan was Lucky, a bouvier des
Flandres.
</P>
<P>
   President and Mrs. Bush had the talented writer Millie, a
springer spaniel, while President Clinton's pooch is a chocolate
Labrador retriever, Buddy._ Pets on the Net
</P>
<P>
   Your faithful friend may be more than just the source for your
computer password. For pet advice in cyberspace, try these
interesting sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.petloss.com _ Personal support and advice for grieving pet
lovers.
</P>
<P>
   www.herpeton.com _ The care and feeding of birds, snakes, fish
and other pets.
</P>
<P>
   www.avma.org/care4pets _ American Veterinary Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   www.roadsideamerica.com/pet _ Roadside America Pet Cemetery:a
tribute to many legendary pets.
</P>
<P>
   www.napcc.aspca.org _ ASPCA/National Animal Poison Control
Information Page.
</P>
<P>
   dontshootthedog.com or clickertraining.com _ Information, books
and videos on pet training.
</P>
<P>
   homearts.com/depts/pastime/petnam16.htm _ Help for naming a pet.
</P>
<P>
   www.rahul.net/hredlus/pat1.html _ How to choose and train a dog
and the popular puppy aptitude test.
</P>
<P>
   www.missingpets.com and www.missingpet.org _ These sites assist
owners to reunite with lost pets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dog biscuits just like Mom used to make Bored after the
holiday frenzy? Whip up a batch of Dog Biscuits Deluxe, courtesy of
``Dr. Pitcairn's Complete Guide to Natural Health for Dogs and
Cats,'' by Richard Pitcairn and Susan Hubble Pitcairn (Rodale Press
Inc., 1995) To order this book, call (800) 848-4735.
</P>
<P>
   Dog Biscuits Deluxe
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon bonemeal (available at pet stores)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sunflower or pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cloves minced garlic or 1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon nutritional yeast (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted butter, fat or oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsulfured molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs mixed with 1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Mix the flours, cornmeal, bonemeal and seeds together. Add the
garlic and yeast, if desired. In a separate bowl, combine the
butter (or fat or oil), molasses, salt and egg/milk mixture; set
aside 1 tablespoon of this liquid mixture and combine the rest with
the dry ingredients. Add more milk, if necessary, to make dough
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Knead together dough for a few minutes and let the dough rest a
half hour or more. Roll out to 1/2-inch thick. Cut into shapes and
brush with remaining egg mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes or until lightly toasted. To
make harder biscuits, leave in turned-off oven for an hour or more.
Biscuits keep longer if you use oil instead of butter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tattoos not just for people
</P>
<P>
   To protect and identify animals, many owners have registration
numbers tattooed on a pet's tummy or thigh. Here are a few places
that perform such a service: Century Animal Hospital (442-9518) and
North Austin Animal Hospital (459-7676). Prices vary.
</P>
<P>
   Tattooing is done while an animal is sedated. Consider having
the tattoo done during Garfield's or Fido's next surgical
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   A less visible and less expensive alternative is an AVID
microchip implant. Contact your veterinarian or Century Animal
Hospital for details.
</P>
<P>
   _ Here, Max The ASPCA contacted 42 veterinarians
</P>
<P>
   and gathered more than 300,000 pet names to come up with the
definitive list of the top 500. Here are the top 20:
</P>
<P>
   1. Max
</P>
<P>
   2. Sam
</P>
<P>
   3. Lady
</P>
<P>
   4. Bear
</P>
<P>
   5. Smokey
</P>
<P>
   6. Shadow
</P>
<P>
   7. Kitty
</P>
<P>
   8. Molly
</P>
<P>
