<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-GACASES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not all Georgians leaving welfare are going to work
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Overhauling welfare was meant to get people off of aid
and onto someone's payroll. But Georgia's shrinking caseload, which
dropped from about 114,000 when the overhaul began to 73,000 by
June 1998, isn't the sole result of people finding jobs, numbers
show.
</P>
<P>
   The lower numbers also resulted from fewer people applying for
welfare and the state denying more applications, according to
statistics reported to the federal welfare agency by the Department
of Human Resources, which operates Georgia's welfare program.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, caseworkers were confused by the new rules and
may have denied welfare assistance to people who were eligible for
help, officials acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   During 1997, the year the state began changing the welfare
system, about 20,000 fewer people sought public assistance than in
previous years. The state also denied 31,801 and turned away 28,983
others, instead providing them with some type of one-time
assistance, according to the statistics DHR reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although seldom mentioned, the number of people denied,
discontinued or diverted from public assistance is a significant
part of Georgia's diminishing caseload. DHR does not know how many
of those might actually have qualified for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a void in our conversation,'' said Kathy Palumbo,
community services director of the Atlanta Community Food Bank and
a member of the Georgia Safety Network, an assembly of nonprofit
advocacy organizations that keeps track of the changes in welfare.
``We can't gauge how well or how poorly we are doing if we don't
know something about what happens to how many.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three years before Georgia implemented Temporary
Assistance for Needy Families, the new welfare program that
requires recipients to work, an average of 93,000 Georgians applied
for public assistance each year, records show.
</P>
<P>
   But when TANF began in 1997, the number of applicants fell to
73,430. And caseworkers turned away 43 percent of applicants
compared to the average 35 percent denied in each of the three
previous years, according to statistics from the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Beavor, a member of the state's Welfare Reform Advisory
Council, has noted two possible reasons for the drop in
applications through her work on the council and in her previous
job as director of the Legal Clinic for the Homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The word on the street among needy people was that it was harder
to receive benefits, so some people didn't bother to apply, Beavor
said. Council members also learned there was a lot of confusion
about TANF policy because specific guidelines for Georgia's welfare
program hadn't yet been established when caseworkers began
implementing TANF, she said. Consequently, caseworkers did not
grant benefits to some people who might have been eligible.
</P>
<P>
   When the program began, there was some confusion about the new
policy and who did or did not qualify for benefits, acknowledged
Peg Peters, director of the Division of Family and Children
Services, which administers the welfare program for DHR.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were thousands of people who lost their welfare
benefits because they failed to comply with the new rules. During
the first six months of TANF, the period for which statistics are
available, caseworkers discontinued benefits in more than 15,208
cases for that reason. An average case involves a mother and two
children, so those cases could represent some 45,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   However, Peters contends that in all 11,186 cases removed from
the welfare rolls during the second quarter of 1997 for failing to
follow the new rules, the recipients voluntarily decided they did
not want to receive welfare anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Records don't reveal how many, if any, of those people returned
to the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Stiffer rules may have weeded out people who weren't in dire
straits but who would have applied for benefits before TANF, when
it was easy, said Darcy Olsen, an entitlements policy analyst at
the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have a temporary crisis, such as a broken car or
loss of a babysitter, that keeps them from working and prompts them
to seek public assistance. With new welfare laws, Georgia now can
pay for the necessary service that will allow them to continue to
work, or start working, and divert them from welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Before welfare's overhaul, that type of one-time help wasn't
available.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1997, when TANF began, to June 1998, the latest
month for which statistics are available, welfare workers diverted
28,983 people, 11,274 at the time they applied and 17,709 who found
work before benefits took effect.
</P>
<P>
   DFACS spent $7 million on diversion expenses. Child care
services cost $4.3 million, transportation assistance $1.2 million
and incidentals such as uniforms, glasses or professional licenses,
$1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
