u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASSHOTELS17-COX     01-16 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASSHOTELS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bass keeps growing
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANA _ Thomas R. Oliver was once asked by a search firm if he
knew of someone capable of assuming the helm of one of the world's
largest hotel companies.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Oliver, then chairman and chief executive
officer of AudioFAX, an Atlanta-based telecommunications company,
said he knew just the right person.
</P>
<P>
   Himself.
</P>
<P>
   What may have seemed a bit self-aggrandizing at the time has
perhaps turned out to be one of the best personnel recommendations
for Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts, the largest operating unit of
London-based Bass PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Since Oliver joined the division in 1997, the company has
continued to expand its reach. It now owns, operates or franchises
more than 2,700 hotels in 95 countries. And it just seems to keep
growing.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next five years, the company plans to add more than
1,200 properties worldwide to its portfolio of some of the world's
most recognized brands, including Holiday Inn, Holiday Inn Express,
Crowne Plaza and Inter-Continental Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've got is a company that's got a very, very strong
position in major markets that is not only growing now and not only
grew in the last five years, but frankly, for as many years as we
can foresee,'' said Oliver, 57, chairman and chief executive
officer and a member of the board of the division's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   Such growth has not gone unnoticed ``across the pond.''
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1998, the division constituted about 40 percent of
Bass PLC's operating profits, up from about 25 percent a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the company announced it was moving several key
executives, including Oliver and Vice Chairman Craig Hunt, from its
Dunwoody headquarters across the street from Perimeter Mall to
London to be closer to parent company Bass PLC. Hunt, 46, is the
former president of Holiday Inn, North America.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Crowne Plaza and Inter-Continental Hotels brands will
be based in London, along with the international operations for
Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Several operations will remain here, including Holiday Inns
North America. Additionally, more than 800 employees will stay in
metro Atlanta, including top executives such as John T. Sweetwood,
president of Holiday Inns North America.
</P>
<P>
   The move signals the growing importance of the hotel division to
Bass PLC, which also has pubs, restaurants and branded drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said the move makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that we now have such a significant global
presence,'' said Oliver, the former chief operating officer and
executive vice president of worldwide customer operations for
Federal Express in Memphis. ``Our being much closer to the people
in London allows us to have a substantially better communications
process.''
</P>
<P>
   The move also simplifies the operations here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel business has taken on even greater significance
``because that's where the investment is going and the other
divisions (brewing and pubs) have done rather worse than
expected,'' said Fraser Ramzan, an analyst with Lehman Brothers in
London. ``There was a bit of a hiccup in 1998,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, profits in the company's soft drink business were
down due to product recall and high marketing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Good reputation is key
</P>
<P>
   The company has come a long way since 1952 when entrepreneur
Kemmons Wilson opened the first Holiday Inn hotel on U.S. 70 in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson became a pioneer in the franchising business and quickly
expanded the chain. Eventually, Holiday Inn became a well-known
name in the lodging industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost unbelievable the way it's kept on growing,'' said
Wilson, 86, whose hotel business still includes four Holiday Inn
Expresses, two Holiday Inns and one Holiday Inn Select. ``The key
is to build a good reputation where everyone knows they will get a
nice room at a reasonable price.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass acquired the Holiday Inn chain in 1990, moving its
headquarters from Memphis to metro Atlanta a year later. But the
chain's U.S. operations were starting to show their age and at some
units the quality of service started to decline. That, and
competition from newer hotel properties such as Hampton Inns, led
to a drop-off in customers.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the company began an ambitious program to
spruce up its properties and expand its brand offerings.
Franchisees, tired of losing business to their fresher competitors,
heartily embraced the move.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 hotels have undergone some level of renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Under Oliver's direction, the company also strongly pushed
separate brand identities.
</P>
<P>
   Last March it purchased the Inter-Continental hotel chain. That
acquisition was indeed a feather in Bass' cap, analysts noted,
nabbing one of the world's most recognized high-end hotel
properties, which already had operations in 73 countries and
contributed significantly to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the company changed its name from Holiday
Hospitality to Holiday Inn Worldwide and eventually _ reflecting a
change in image from a dowdy, midscale, U.S.-focused franchise
operation to a global player _ to Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   `Our plate is full'
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the company plans to continue to aggressively eye
both domestic and international markets. Oliver estimates Bass
Hotels &AMP; Resorts will contribute more than 50 percent of the parent
company's operating earnings within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Further acquisitions are not in the immediate future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much digesting what we acquired with
Inter-Continental,'' Oliver said. ``Our plate is full so we're not
aggressively seeking those opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   On the domestic front, the company is especially optimistic
about the prospects of one of its newest brands _ Staybridge Suites
by Holiday Inn. Already more than 25 franchises have been sold. The
first opened this month in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Growth is planned for other brands as well. Bass' Hunt estimates
20 percent annual growth alone for the upscale brands outside of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the company plans to open another Crowne Plaza and
an Inter-Continental in downtown and Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, who also will be in charge of development of businesses
outside of the hotel brands, said possible options include vacation
ownership, assisted-living facilities and other franchising
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   With Bass set on such an aggressive course, an oversupply of
rooms is an obvious concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a dramatic increase in the supply of
economy-oriented limited service hotels throughout the United
States, particularly in the Sun Belt within the last six months,''
said Mark Woodworth, executive vice president of PKF Consulting in
Atlanta. ``As a result, the development of these limited service
properties has slowed down dramatically. We expect the growth of
the Holiday Inn Express brand to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   From Oliver's vantage point, on the 31st floor of an office
complex in Dunwoody, that growth will be fueled by two factors _
service and employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always approached business from the standpoint that you
have to make sure your customers and employees are happy and
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
