<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-ADVICE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    May your dreams fit your abilities
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is a coincidence, but in the same week when Chicago
Bulls legend Michael Jordan announced his retirement, Kenneth I.
Chenault spoke at Clark Atlanta University and advised young people
to dream practical dreams, not pipe dreams like being the next
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media often encourages us to indulge in magical thinking,
that we can be Michael Jordan,'' said Chenault. ``But we should
dream realistically and then work to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, 47, is a living example that dreams and hard work can
have wonderful results. He is president of American Express and one
of the world's authorities on credit cards. By any measure he is
one of the most senior African-Americans in corporate life and an
executive on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Clark Atlanta last week as a participant in a series
of forums in the Clark Atlanta School of Business Administration
called the Dean's Executive Lecture Series. The talks have featured
such outstanding black executives as Ann Fudge, president of
Maxwell House Coffee; Raymond McGuire, managing director of Merrill
Lynch; and Ernest Green, managing director of Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, like the rest, came to give practical advice and also
to embody business success for the students. He was greeted by
hundreds of students who filled the main gathering place in the new
student center and gave him several standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, the son of a Morehouse College-educated dentist, was
featured in Business Week magazine last month in a piece that
credited him with bringing the huge 147-year-old financial firm
back from the brink of trouble. He seems destined for bigger things
at American Express.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Chenault's message to the black students was
that they need to ignore racial prejudice and any other artificial
barriers that may seem to bar them from succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to tell me that whatever happens, there is one
thing I can control, and that's the quality of my own
performance,'' said Chenault. Regardless of the attitude of others,
he said, personal fortitude could overcome the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Even the great dreamers have often sold African-Americans short,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jefferson said all men are created equal, but there was
evidence he did not believe his own words,'' said Chenault. ``But
DuBois did, and he said education can lift us all.'' His reference
was to William Edward Burghardt DuBois, the historian and political
activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jefferson said we, the races, could not live together because
black people would be too consumed by hatred and retribution (over
slavery and mistreatment), but DuBois knew better.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when some young African-Americans and women are
choosing to use their business and financial education to start
their own businesses, Chenault urged the students to strive for
whatever goals satisfied them.
</P>
<P>
   But he said certain facts of life must be kept in mind by those
who hoped to succeed. Opportunity is expanding, he said, with the
fall of geographic barriers, changes in the global economy and
changes in the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Low-skilled jobs are leaving, many headed for overseas,'' he
said, ``and clearly knowledge is the power that each of us needs to
succeed in the new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenault laid out some very practical steps students could take
to improve their own chance to succeed in life and business. He
said:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep personal integrity in mind. Don't go with the highest
bidder, but ``go with a company whose goals and purpose you can
embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Associate with the best and brightest people in the company.
``Stay away from dumb people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Do your job. ``People talk so much about networking, but the
most important rule is to complete the job at hand. In college you
can do all the networking you want, but it means nothing when the
blue books (test booklets) show up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't fear chaos. ``When the company is undergoing change and
may be in trouble, that provides the best opportunities for those
willing to pitch in and work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Realize that as college graduates, joining the mere 11
percent of African-Americans who are graduates, you will be looked
upon as a leader. You need to act like leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   The students gave Chenault a spirited standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously had connected with them.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Boyce, an undergraduate student in finance, took notes
furiously during Chenault's presentation. She said afterward she
was enlightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard him say `enjoy what you do, but be prepared,' and
that's what I plan to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: holsen(at)mindspring.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
