<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lyricist of 'Chicago' enjoying Act II of his success
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As goes Fred Ebb, so goes the fortunes of the
American musical.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The career of the lyricist for ``Chicago,'' the hit musical that
arrives Wednesday at Bass Concert Hall, is not as illustrious as
Stephen Sondheim's, nor as popularly favored as Jerry Herman's.
Yet, among Americans writing musicals, Ebb, and collaborator John
Kander, closely track the rise and fall _ and rise again _ of the
artform over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Ebb, 66, feels mellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regional theater is healthy; Broadway is healthy,'' Ebb said
from Arlington, Va., where he is rehearsing his latest show, a
musical version of Thornton Wilder's ``The Skin of Our Teeth.''
``Passing that line at TKTS (the Times Square half-price tickets
service) just makes your eyes water. Knowing that people will line
up all around the block in the cold, simply to see a show, that's
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebb and Kander, who penned ``Cabaret,'' ``Kiss of the Spider
Woman'' and ``New York, New York,'' among other shows, are on
something of a roll in the late '90s. Although their last original
show, ``Steel Pier,'' sunk like, well, a steel pier, two highly
acclaimed revivals have reminded theatergoers why the team is among
the most auspicious ever to write for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   A slimmed-down, sexy version of ``Chicago,'' their 1975 satire
of show business and crime in the 1920s, is still playing to full
houses on Broadway after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Broadway is a rethinking of ``Cabaret,'' their 1966
musical about pre-Nazi Germany, set in a confined, grimy space to
give the period piece a distinctly period feel. After winning a
handful of Tony Awards, the revival moved to the former Studio 54,
home base of another era's ``divine decadence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both have been reimagined by extremely talented directors,''
Ebb said of ``Chicago'' and ``Cabaret.'' ``I am delighted to have
my material molded in that way, the work of different
imaginations.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other musical-makers, Kander and Ebb are not so touchy
about new interpretations of their shows. After all, they allowed _
and loved _ the eccentric takes on their greatest songs in the
revue ``The World Goes Round'' (yet to be staged in Austin.)
</P>
<P>
   Kander and Ebb came into their own during the '60s and '70s, the
so-called Silver Age of the American musical, well after the Golden
Age of the '40s and '50s. They persisted during the dark days with
minor shows, such as ``The Happy Time'' and ``70, Girls, 70.'' But
midcareer, they created a highly acclaimed musical, ``Chicago,''
which nevertheless failed to capture the imagination of the times.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the Sin City of the '20s, it concerns women who turn
their criminal fame into show-biz glamour, while their lawyer spins
the tabloid press with fantastic versions of their stories. No
wonder it speaks more clearly in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``O.J. Simpson was on the page month after month, and everybody
knew about his trial and who represented him. Everybody had an
opinion about the justice, or lack of it, in the judicial system
and the world of journalism,'' Ebb said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebb feels he follows in the tradition of the great lyricists _
Ira Gershwin, Oscar Hammerstein, Cole Porter, Dorothy Fields, Alan
J. Lerner, Frank Loesser _ who also spoke for their times. Of
course, he admires his contemporary, Sondheim
</P>
<P>
   ``He's superior in every way. There's a great, great craft at
work there,'' Ebb said.
</P>
<P>
   As for failing to attract the kind of attention Sondheim gets _
the books, the articles, the inductions into bookish societies _
Ebb is philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's never been terribly important to me,'' he said. ``I
just wanted to do my work and wanted people to like it. I love
putting on the radio and hearing Frank (Sinatra) singing my songs,
or walking down the street and hearing a truck driver whistling one
of our songs.''
</P>
<P>
   As each year passes, it seems more likely that Ebb, like the
musicals he creates, will outlast the former underestimation of his
work encapsulated in historian Gerald Bordman's one-time
evaluation: ``His lyrics have rarely displayed any exceptional
characteristics other than admirably suiting the mood and period of
text and music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People love music; it's the universal language,'' Ebb said.
``They know that's what they are going to get in a musical, the
emotional involvement, the immediacy of having live performers in
front of you with real voices. That's tremendously attractive. It
always has been and always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
