A6019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JANUARY-SLUMP17-COX     01-16 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANUARY-SLUMP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Break out of that post-holiday slump
 &HT;    By Vikki Ramsey Conwell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you've had trouble getting back into the swing of
work, don't despair. You could be suffering from a holiday
hangover.
</P>
<P>
   A workplace slump at the start of the new year is only natural,
experts say. It's so widespread, it shows up as a seasonal slump in
the economy in December and January, and again in August _ when
summer vacations end, according to the Conference Board, a business
research group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For computer consultant Keith Debowles, being away from the
office for two weeks made him realize how good it is at home. ``I
just had too much fun spending time with my kids,'' said Debowles,
who took an extra week off to be with a sick daughter. ``When I
went back to work, I suffered a slight relapse. I was very slow
getting up and running again.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of returning to a job is not energizing for many
people, said Bill Kahnweiler, associate professor of human resource
development at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize how good it is not to be there,'' said Kahnweiler.
``When you're caught up in the treadmill of working, you don't have
time to think about how bad it is. When the treadmill slows down or
stops, it gives you time to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This holiday slump generally lasts a week or two, experts say.
If it still has a grip on you, the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday
Monday will give many people another three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That can only work in your favor.
</P>
<P>
   If you're back on track, an extra day off could further energize
you. If you're not, experts say, this may be a last shot to recover
_ at least until spring break and summer vacations roll around.
Until then, there's a long stretch between now and the next major
holiday, which isn't until Memorial Day, May 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just that you've been out of the office partying and
sleeping,'' said Eric Greenberg, director of management studies at
the American Management Association in New York. ``There are
physical factors such as colder temperatures and shorter days.
Then, there's the extra 5 to 7 pounds that most people gain during
the holidays. Lugging around that extra weight drains our energy
and makes us feel sluggish,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back into a routine can be difficult for most people,
Greenberg said. How well you handle it depends on what you do
before and after your break. But there are steps you can take.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you should sprint toward a holiday instead of
cruising into it, Greenberg recommends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decide to have a clear desk before you leave so you won't be
swamped when you get back.''
</P>
<P>
   When you return to work, pace yourself. Don't overdo it trying
to make up for lost time, experts say. Regular breaks can help keep
you focused.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Jackson, a computer analyst with the state of Georgia,
sometimes listens to the radio while at work and takes breaks
periodically to either walk or read the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exercising is good to increase your energy level,'' said
Jackson, of Decatur, who has been on the job 22 years. ``Meditating
is also good.''
</P>
<P>
   Too many workers, though, have a tendency to put too much
pressure on themselves at the beginning of a new year, said Emory
Mulling, president of Mulling Group, an Atlanta outplacement firm.
Then they get overwhelmed and become more down than normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is your responsibility to take charge of a slump and do
things that will get you out of it,'' said Mulling. ``Knowing what
it takes is a gift to yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Start by making a list of short-term goals. Also, now is a good
time to set performance goals with your supervisor, if you haven't
already.
</P>
<P>
   Managers also need to allow workers to ease back into their jobs
after a break, said Kahnweiler.
</P>
<P>
   If expectations are too high, ``the employee gets discouraged.
Managers should be mindful of the delicate balance between
stretched goals and unachievable goals that discourage people from
even trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Many employers recognize such a slump is ``just a byproduct of
being a human being in this country,'' said Burke Stinson, a
spokesman with AT&AMP;T operating headquarters in New Jersey, one of
the nation's largest employers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company really doesn't address the issue formally
because ``it's short-lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, however, require their managers to stay in touch
during long breaks.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 survey by the American Management Association, 81
percent of managers and executives reported they kept in touch with
their offices by phone during vacations and holiday breaks. Another
21 percent kept in touch by e-mail, and 43 percent said they did
some sort of office-related work while they were out. Sixteen
percent of employers said they required managers and executives to
keep in touch while on extended vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies realize that productivity is lost in direct
proportion to how much time a person is away,'' said Greenberg.
``It is worth their while to establish guidelines about keeping in
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   But such down periods can be a good thing, said Stinson.
</P>
<P>
   It's similar to what happens when people leave for lunch, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   People leave their work on their desk, eat a meal and then come
back refreshed and renewed.
</P>
<P>
   He sees holidays as an extended period to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an intellectual exercise,'' said Stinson. ``The new
perspective you have can produce very healthy and positive
results.''
</P>
<P>
   _Vikki Ramsey Conwell is a free-lance writer living in DeKalb
County.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
