<SLUG> BC-KIDS-WEB17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web's just like TV: Parents need control
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The good thing about the Internet also is the bad
thing, if you're a parent. There is information on almost any topic
you can name, out there for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   So parents often face this worry: Do I let my kids have full use
of the Web and take a chance they'll run into adult material or
violence or even strangers who are dangerous? Or do I shield them
from all that and take the chance they won't do as well at school
as their friends who do use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That's why _ for some parents _ the middle ground is best:
Control the Internet and Web, just as some parents control the use
of the TV and video games. There are sites built especially for
kids that are designed to keep out objectionable material (although
a smart parent will still rely on his or her own judgment, not that
of a stranger).
</P>
<P>
   For starters, here are some Web sites made for kids that would
be accepted in most families.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yahooligans: It's a search engine made to be used by young
people. There's less chance of it being used to find sites not
approved in your family. It is, of course, owned by Yahoo!, the
same folks who made the search engine popular.
http://www.yahooligans
</P>
<P>
   .com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Kid's Corner: It's more of a full-blown destination than
Yahooligans. You will find ways to surf the Web here, but there
also are games and areas where art and stories by other kids are
displayed. Everything here is rated G and should meet demanding
standards of most homes. http://kids.ot.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Kids Identifying and Discovering Sites: If there are nights
when you need homework help and no one in the family has the needed
knowledge, this is the place for you. There are lots of links to
places that cater to the kindergarten through high school grade
range. http://wwwscout.cs.wisc.edu/scout
</P>
<P>
   /KIDS/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
