<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVINGS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simple, reliable savings bonds just got easier to buy
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ U.S. Savings Bonds, an old-fashioned investment, have
gone electronic.
</P>
<P>
   Although they pay rates of return below most private
investments, millions of Savings Bonds have been bought by
Americans over the years because of their simplicity as an
investment and because of their Uncle Sam-guaranteed safety.
</P>
<P>
   But for many would-be investors in the past, there was a
problem: How do you buy Savings Bonds?
</P>
<P>
   Previously there were two ways investors could buy the bonds.
They could buy them through a bank or broker, or through payroll
deduction at work if their employer offered the service.
</P>
<P>
   But about 120 million Americans worked for companies without
payroll deduction for the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   So last month the U.S. Treasury initiated the EasySaver Plan for
Savings Bonds, which allows investors to buy the bonds by
authorizing the agency to deduct a set amount each month from their
checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Two types of Savings Bonds are available through the plan _ the
Series EE bonds, which sell for half of their face value that's
paid at maturity; and the Series I bonds, which sell at face value
and pay inflation-indexed interest.
</P>
<P>
   Series EE bonds are available in $50, $75, $100, $200, $500 and
$1,000 denominations, and Series I bonds in $50, $75, $100, $500
and $1,000 denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Investors choose the dates and amounts to charge their account
for the bond purchases. The only requirement is that investors must
purchase at least two bonds each year.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish to set up an account can call 1-877-811-7283, or
download the EasySaver enrollment form from the Treasury's Web site
at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .easysaver.gov.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about four weeks to set up the account. Then the
Treasury will begin debiting your account for the amount you said
and send you the applicable bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
