<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Saturday, Jan. 16, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file this story for Sunday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ House prosecutors, concluding their
arguments about why the Senate should remove President Clinton from
office, offer the reassurance that Vice President Al Gore is
``waiting outside the door'' to quickly step in as the nation's
next chief executive. House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., warns that the presidency could be ``permanently
damaged'' if the Senate fails to remove Clinton from office for
perjury and obstruction of justice in his cover-up of a sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. By
STEWART M. POWELL And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service/Washington
