A6032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THARPE-COLUMN17-COX     01-16 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THARPE-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bottom line: Economics does matter
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Think you know a lot about sports? Then answer this
question: Why do professional sports players generally earn more
than farmers and steelworkers?
</P>
<P>
   Before answering, you need to understand it's not really a
sports question but an economic question that was asked in a recent
survey of consumers by the Minneapolis Federal Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
   What's your guess? Because athletes usually are bigger and
stronger than farmers and steelworkers? Because tickets to
professional sports events are so expensive?
</P>
<P>
   No, those answers are wrong, but don't feel too dumb if you
can't answer the question. Only one in four participants in the
survey answered correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is scarcity. When something is scarce, and
there's a demand for it, its price is high. The Minneapolis bank
explained it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Salaries earned by most individuals depend basically on the
demand for their services relative to the supply of such services.
Since excellent baseball players are very scarce relative to the
strong demand for their services from major league clubs, the
salaries they receive are higher than those received by most other
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey asked 12 other questions and, in total, the
respondents flunked, with an average score of 45 percent. But the
outcome was not surprising, because numerous surveys have shown
that most Americans are economically ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of understanding about ``pure'' economics, as taught in
college, is understandable because it can be a rather dull subject.
But understanding ``real life'' economics is important because it
directly affects salaries, investment and credit. A better
understanding of economics usually means a better standard of
living.
</P>
<P>
   Around the nation, a number of groups are trying to teach that
lesson, beginning with improved courses at all levels of school.
The Georgia Council on Economic Education, for example, works with
various groups to provide schools with economic education materials
to help teach personal finance and its relation to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   As with many lessons, however, the best place to begin is at
home, which is the goal of College Parents of America, an
association that seeks to help parents talk to their children about
``the financial facts of life'' and how the proper use of money and
credit affects their entire lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of students will turn to their parents for advice
on money matters,'' said Richard Flaherty, president of the
Washington-based association. ``Our goal is to be sure parents are
ready to answer the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   To assist parents, the association, in conjunction with
MasterCard International, has produced a 10-page brochure to make
the financial conversation more effective _ ``Money Talks: Helping
Your High School and College-Aged Children Master the Financial
Facts of Life.'' For a free copy, call toll-free 1-800-999-5136.
The text can also be found online at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .collegeparents.org.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: gtharpe(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
