<HEADER>
A6033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      01-16 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE MOUSE CHECKS IN BUT NOT OUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)  (jw) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Mice are the No. 1 infestation problem in the city
today,'' said Michael Deutsch, an entomologist with Allied/Pioneer
Pest Management Companies in Manhattan. ``We have a pretty good
handle on roaches. But the rodent population has been steadily
increasing. I would say that most buildings in the city today have
some level of infestation.''
</P>
<P>
   While such an assessment might appear self-serving coming from
an employee of an extermination company, others agree Deutsch may
be right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be at all unusual to find mice in most New York
City buildings,'' said Richard Ostfeld, an animal ecologist at the
Institute of Ecosystem Studies, a research organization in
Millbrook, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Ostfeld said that there were basically two kinds of mice in and
around New York _ the house mouse and the white-footed mouse, which
prefers the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The house mouse, Ostfeld said, settles more or less permanently
inside buildings to be near a steady source of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``A female house mouse can produce litters of eight new mice
every three or four weeks,'' Ostfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   The white-footed mouse prefers to remain outdoors _ at least
until the weather turns cold. ``The white-footed mouse will enter
people's homes, especially in the fall and winter,'' he said,
adding that while the numbers of mice fluctuate from year to year,
the fluctuations can often be predicted by the number of acorns in
their environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are a lot of acorns in the fall, there are a whole
lot of mice the next year,'' he said. ``We've had two good acorn
years in a row and that's produced high numbers of mice. And when
the weather turned cold, they probably started moving inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Crudo, president of Paladin Pest Control in the Bay Terrace
section of Staten Island, can vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year or so has been terrible,'' Crudo said. ``We deal
mostly with apartment buildings in Manhattan, and the influx of
mice has been so bad, we've had to re-treat some buildings two or
three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Crudo said there were three basic strategies for dealing with
mice _ sealing, trapping and baiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sealing up holes is the first line of defense,'' he said,
explaining that any hole with a diameter larger than that of a
pencil can be an entry point for mice. Such holes can be found
around plumbing lines, heat pipes and in gaps between floors and
baseboards. ``We generally use an expanding foam to seal all entry
points,'' Crudo said, explaining that while steel wool is sometimes
used to seal holes, the steel will deteriorate over time if the
mice have not already clawed through it.
</P>
<P>
   Once a house or apartment is sealed as tightly as possible,
Crudo said, it is then necessary to eliminate the source of the
problem using poison bait or traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important rule for using bait is to keep it out of
sight and out of reach,'' Crudo said, adding that the best strategy
for using any kind of poison is to use tamper-resistant bait
stations that mice can get into, but children and pets cannot. Such
products can be bought at hardware stores, he said, adding that it
was usually best to buy a bait station with the bait pre-installed.
</P>
<P>
   Crudo said that mouse baits generally come in two forms:
single-feed, fatal after just one feeding, and multiple-feed, which
requires several feedings to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The multiple-feed works best,'' he said, explaining that more
mice are likely to use it because its delayed reaction makes it
less likely they will recognize the bait for what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you use, it's important to follow the
instructions on the package, and check the baits on a regular basis
so you can replace any that have been eaten,'' Crudo said. He added
that it usually takes several days for the mice to become
comfortable enough with the bait stations to start to eat. And, he
said, the old story about mice eating the bait and dying in the
walls is unfortunately true. ``It probably happens more often than
people know,'' he said. ``But mice are so small, they dry up and
skeletonize pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to avoid having poison in their house and
skeletons in their walls, there are alternatives. ``There are
several traps on the market that are very effective,'' said Kirk La
Pierre, owner of A-1 Saver Services, a pest control company in
Rutherford, N.J. ``But the kind of trap to use depends mostly on
your attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the least expensive and most effective traps _ the
glue-trap _ also happens to be the cruelest for its victims. A
glue-trap, La Pierre said, is basically a stiff piece of cardboard
coated with glue. Bait is placed in the center of the trap _ an
unshelled peanut with a drop of almond extract works best _ and the
trap is placed on a floor or ledge next to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   La Pierre, who is also president of the New Jersey Wildlife
Damage Control Association, said that since a mouse trapped on a
glue board could suffer considerably before it died, it was usually
preferable to use more humane ``snap traps'' that would kill
instantly. Such traps, which come in easy-to-set plastic models as
well as the standard wood-and-spring latch-type designs, should
also be set along walls where mice meander, taking care to keep
them out of reach of children and pets.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer to evict the invaders rather than execute
them, La Pierre said, there are a number of ``humane'' traps on the
market. Such traps, he said, can be either single-occupancy devices
that a mouse enters but cannot exit, or multiple-catch machines
that catch and hold several mice without harming them. The problem
with such traps, however, is disposing of the day's catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to release the mice a decent distance from the house
or they'll just find their way back,'' said Ostfeld, the animal
ecologist. ``A mile away is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   A mile?
</P>
<P>
   ``Mice have surprisingly good homing instincts,'' Ostfeld said,
explaining that he once conducted an experiment in which
white-footed mice were marked to identify them and then taken more
than a mile away from home and released.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days later, we started getting animals returning,'' he
said, noting that to do so, the mice had to cross a busy road, swim
through a rapidly moving stream, and then climb a three-foot high
fence, passing through some perfectly acceptable mouse country
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how they did it,'' Ostfeld said. ``But these
mice were obviously highly motivated to get home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
