<P>
   MLK-STREETS _ A reporter visits MLK drives, boulevard and
streets throughout Georgia (Fort Valley, Albany, Darien, Macon,
Savannah) to see how MLK's name is used and honored. What do the
street signs say about the legacy of the civil rights movement,
40-plus years after King vaulted into national prominence with the
Montgomery bus boycott? (Osinski, Atlanta Journal-Constitution),
50. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/KING _ As he rode the streets of Selma, Ala., in 1975, a
camera in his hands, John Hindsman grew inspired. He was a black
man who grew up on a Georgia plantation in the 1920s, when the law
and the lash made a pipe dream of equality, but he left the South
for Dayton as a young man and stayed on the sidelines of the civil
rights movement. Yet on that spring day in Selma, he knew how he
could do his part. He could photograph every place where Martin
Luther King Jr. _ whom Hindsman had met in his long-ago Southern
days _ had taken his crusade for justice. (Keilman, Dayton Daily
News). 50. WITH PHOTOS (Several of Hindsman's photographs plus a
portrait of him). MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
