<P>
   WELFARE-GACASES _ Overhauling welfare was meant to get people
off of aid and onto someone's payroll. But Georgia's shrinking
caseload, which dropped from about 114,000 when the overhaul began
to 73,000 by June 1998, isn't the sole result of people finding
jobs, numbers show. The lower numbers also resulted from fewer
people applying for welfare and the state turning away more
applicants, according to statistics reported to the federal welfare
agency by the Department of Human Resources, which operates
Georgia's welfare program. (Oglesby, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
32. MOVED
