<P>
   MEXICO-POPE _ MEXICO CITY _ Pope John Paul II will visit Mexico
City for four days beginning Fri., Jan. 22. And with no clear
agenda released yet by the Vatican, Mexicans wonder if the pope
will address human rights, poverty and the economy, religious
competition, abortion -- or even drug trafficking -- during his
visit. The visit marks the closure of a bishops' conference on
challenges to the Catholic church in the Americas. In addition to
church business, however, the frail Catholic leader often comments
on broader questions of social policy. A Catholic Diocese in
Mexico's Southern Chiapas state, is hoping the Pope will take on
the Mexican government and the long-simmering Chiapas conflict,
which has led to the expulsion and imprisonment of Catholic
priests. The Diocese may present a report to the Pope claiming that
Chiapas' poor and Indian populations are victims of human rights
violations, haphazard free-market economic policies and the
corruption of drug traffickers. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
