   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   BASSHOTELS _ Bass Hotels is undergoing a lot of changes: moving
several top executives to London, focusing on international brands,
and focusing more on opporunities outside the industry, including
vacation ownerships and assisted living facilities. We talk to
Chairman Thomas Oliver and vice chair Craig Hunt about the outlook
for the company, the industry. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JANUARYSLUMP _With the new year under way, many people have
returned to work only to find that halfway through January, they're
still trying to shake off the holiday doldrums. But some find it
harder to shake off than the extra weight they may have put on.
This slump is psychological, physical, and seasonal, industrial
psychologists say. Cold temperatures and shorter days, less
sullight, aren't helping. How do you get back into the swing of
things? No. 1, make sure you're in a job you like, experts say.
Story w/ tipbox on how to motivate yourself. What management can do
to help motivate sluggish workers? (Conwell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   THARPE-COLUMN _ Think you know a lot about sports? Then answer
this: Why do professional athletes generally earn more than farmers
and steelworkers? Before answering, you need to understand it's an
economic question that was asked in a recent survey of consumers by
the Minneapolis Federal Reserve Bank. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-TAXES _ Interest is growing in a first-class way to save
for a college education and defer taxes on those investments.
Hundreds of thousands of families now pour their money into the
plans, turning over the investment decisions to others in return
for tax deferred earnings. The strategy has some risks, as does
anything in life. But it has some uncommonly attractive features,
too. Georgia does not have such a plan, but Peach State residents
can enroll in the plans sponsored by New York, New Hampshire,
Delaware and a handful of other states. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-ADVICE _ Ken Chenault, president of American Express and
arguably the highest ranking African American in corporate America,
had some special
</P>
<P>
   encouragement for students at Clark Atlanta last week. It's time
to quit worrying about the attitudes of racists and others who
stand in their way. The simple alternative, he said, to do your
best, associate with smart and ambitious people, regardless of race
and push hard to make contributions. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-WEB _ The good thing about the Internet also is the bad
thing, if you're a parent. There is information on almost any topic
you can name out there for the taking. So parents often face this
worry: Do I let my kids have full use of the Web and take a chance
that they'll run into adult material or violence or even strangers
who are dangerous? Or do I shield them from all that and take the
chance that they won't do as well at school as their friends who do
use the Internet. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS _ U.S. Savings Bonds, an old-fashioned investment, have
gone electronic. Although they pay rates of return below most
private investments, millions have been purchased over the years
because of their simplicity as an investment and because of their
Uncle Sam-guaranteed safety. But for many would-be investors in the
past, there was a problem: How to buy Savings Bonds. They could buy
them through a bank or broker, or through payroll deduction at
work. But about 120 million Americans worked for companies without
payroll deduction for the bonds. Last month, the U.S. Treasury
initiated the EasySaver Plan for Savings Bonds, which allows
investors to buy the bonds by authorizing the agency to deduct a
set amount each month from their checking account to pay for them.
(Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
