<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: IN PHILADELPHIA, CENTER CITY TOWERS GET NEW USES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By DAVID J. WALLACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Stimulated by a 1997 city tax abatement for
conversion of older commercial buildings, there has been a rise in
the renovation of downtown towers. About a dozen buildings have
taken advantage of the abatement, and when all completed they are
expected to add about 1,000 apartments to the city's inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Although most may turn out to be standard apartments leased to
users, some of the buildings are emerging entirely or in part as
extended-stay corporate apartments, a conversion approach that was
under way in response to market demand even before the abatement
was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Three towers have been renovated entirely for this type of
housing, which mainly serves relocated executives and employees
working on open-ended consulting projects. Two of them, former
office buildings at 1411 Walnut Street and 120 South 17th Street,
have been converted for leasing to companies in the business of
operating extended-stay apartments. They supply furnishings and
some household services and lease the apartments to corporations or
to individual tenants on a short-term basis.
</P>
<P>
   The third tower, a former apartment building at 222 Rittenhouse
Square, was bought by Korman Communities, a Philadelphia-based
owner, which renovated it and reopened it with 100 extended-stay
apartments. Because it had originally been an apartment house it
did not qualify for the tax abatement.
</P>
<P>
   These renovations created about 350 downtown apartments,
developers said. The Walnut Street and 17th Street projects are
expected to qualify for the tax abatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia has been a huge market for us and there was an
opportunity for us to take a large block of rooms downtown,'' said
Robert Philips, spokesman for Oakwood Corporate Housing, a Los
Angeles company that leases apartments and furnishes them for
tenants. ``Business travel and relocations are our biggest uses
there, compared with other cities. And our length of stay has been
increasing, particularly for financial companies that are moving
people around for six months at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Oakwood's clients is SmithKline Beecham, the
pharmaceutical company, which has its national headquarters here.
Others include financial companies addressing mergers or Year 2000
computer consulting in longer-term projects, Philips said. In some
cases, Oakwood and other companies lease vacant units in existing
apartment houses on an as-needed basis, furnishing them and paying
the owner a higher monthly rent than he could get on an annual
lease.
</P>
<P>
   The tax abatement allows developers to avoid for 10 years any
tax increase based on the higher value that results from
redevelopment. Modeled on a similar law crafted for lower
Manhattan, the abatement applies to any institutional or
nonresidential building that is more than 50 years old or has more
than two-thirds of its potentially residential space vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The abatement, which expires in 2002, requires property owners
to apply for it within 60 days after getting a building permit for
the reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Dranoff, a developer who championed the tax incentive and
is using it to develop standard apartments, said the ordinance was
vital to developers seeking financing. He is creating 152 rental
apartments at a former printing plant at 25th and Locust Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Dranoff said the additional rental income made available by
holding taxes to $60,000 a year for 10 years made it possible to
finance the $24-million project.
</P>
<P>
   No older office buildings had been sold in nearly five years
before the rush of transactions in late 1997 and last year, said
Neal Rodin, who heads a real estate development firm here. His
$16-million renovation of the former PNC Bank office building at
120 South 17th Street will yield 200 apartments, a new health club
and restaurant, scheduled to open in April.
</P>
<P>
   Rodin said he expected to sell the building to Club Quarters, a
New York operator of extended-stay apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-story office building at 1411 Walnut Street was purchased
by the Philadelphia Management Corp. for $2.8 million and converted
at a cost of $8.2 million to create rental apartments on the top
eight floors, said Ronald Caplan, president of the corporation.
Four of these floors have been leased to Oakwood for extended-stay
units, he said. The base floors will be used for stores and
offices.
</P>
<P>
   For the furnished extended-stay apartments, with services
included, operators typically get rents of $2,300 a month for a
one-bedroom unit to $3,300 for a two-bedroom. In standard
unfurnished apartments, with much lower operating costs, rents may
range from $825 for a one-bedroom to $1,500 for a two-bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Removing nearly one million square feet of Class B, or
secondary, office space has driven vacancy rates in that sector
down to 15 percent, said Jeff Seligsohn, president of
Seligsohn-Hess, which specializes in leasing and sales of older
buildings. And with choice buildings for restoration already gone,
he said, asking prices have risen as much as 50 percent on
remaining properties,
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail is slowly coming back downtown and it's getting more
exciting to be in Center City,'' Seligsohn said. ``The bargains are
gone. People are shopping for `good enough' because if they wait,
the few opportunities go quickly.'' Incentives by sellers to spur
sales are a thing of the past, he said, and prices are rising.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dranoff and other builders are now seeking a similar abatement
for new construction of residential towers. Demand for luxury
rental apartments here is strong enough that developers are
floating proposals after a decade-long absence of new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Rents for apartments in full-service buildings here rarely
exceed $2,000 a month. At 222 Rittenhouse Square, however, rents
range from $2,100 a month for a studio to $3,800 for a two-bedroom
unit, with housekeeping and concierge service. The renters are
usually relocating executives, participants in corporate training
programs, convention visitors and other clients, said Larry Korman,
executive vice president of Korman Communities, which operates 600
other extended-stay and hotel rooms and suites in downtown
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Korman, who declined to give the cost of renovating his
Rittenhouse Square building, said that the owners of buildings
devoted entirely to extended-stay apartments were keeping their
options open, watching the hotel and apartment vacancy rates. ``Now
there are lots of people who want to be in the city,'' he said.
``But we have flexibility and a hedge. If individual, as opposed to
corporate, rentals get hot, we can convert the building, or if a
hotel is needed we can go that way and get rezoning.''
</P>
<P>
   With lower operating costs because of limited housekeeping and
other services, extended-stay apartments are a fast-growing and
profitable industry, said Warren Marr, a lodging and hospitality
analyst at PricewaterhouseCoopers in Philadelphia. Most companies
restrict leases to a minimum of 30 days to avoid the higher
turnover business of convention or conference visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's hotels are experiencing annual occupancy rates
above 70 percent, and during high-demand weekends and special
events, there may be no rooms available downtown, Marr said. For
some large events, visitors are forced to stay in hotels as much as
a half hour's drive from the downtown Pennsylvania Convention
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Yet extended-stay rooms account for only 3 percent of the
lodging-room inventory nationwide, according to a recent
PricewaterhouseCoopers report. As many as 300,000 rooms in the
category may be added nationwide, the report says, as demand for
lower-priced accommodations rises and the length of stay increases
for certain business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for downtown apartments means the long-ignored luxury
market for individuals is ready to expand, said Albert M.
Greenfield III, the third-generation of his family to develop real
estate in Philadelphia. He is renovating a 1922 office tower at
15th and Chestnut Streets into 162 apartments. Apartments in the
$30-million project at 1500 Chestnut, scheduled to open in March,
will range from $1,150 for a one-bedroom to $1,775 for a
two-bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teaching hospitals, conventions and corporate job growth
are all bringing people here,'' he said. ``But there are still
fewer than 1,000 new apartment units being created by all this
activity. More supply won't hurt the market. It will generate more
business and prices will rise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
