<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Jan. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous storm system will pound the Pacific Northwest on
Sunday as a persistent onshore flow continues across the region.
Heavy rain will fall in coastal areas from Washington to northern
California, with rainfall amounts of more than 2 inches possible in
some spots. The additional rainfall will only act to worsen
existing flooding problems brought on by recent rains. Up to a foot
on snow will fall in the Cascades, with snow levels lowering to
near 3,000 feet by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will also fall in the northern Rockies from Montana to Utah
while scattered rain showers occur in the valleys of eastern
Washington and Oregon and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will grace the Great Plains from central Texas to the
western Dakotas as brisk breezes from the west are forced to
descend the sloping terrain. It will be very mild, with many areas
experiencing readings as much as fifteen degrees above average.
</P>
<P>
   Developing low pressure will spread a mixture of precipitation
across the Ohio and Mississippi Valleys. Patches of wet snow will
occur from central Iowa and southern Minnesota to central
Wisconsin. A few inches of snow accumulation are likely. Rain
showers are expected from central Michigan southward. A
thunderstorm is even possible near the Gulf coast, where a powerful
jet stream disturbance aids in lifting the warm air over the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, partly sunny skies are expected in the Piedmont of
the Appalachians. Areas near the East Coast will experience bright
sunshine, where retreating high pressure will provide mild readings
and breezes from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Siege Ends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The siege of wintry weather has temporarily ended in Chicago. At
2 a.m. Saturday, the mercury reached 32 degrees for the first time
in 1999 at O'Hare airport. Temperatures had been below freezing
since December 29, a period of 18 days. The longest period below
freezing in Chicago occurred in 1977, when 43 consecutive days had
sub-freezing readings. The current thaw will continue through much
of this coming week as a series of Pacific air masses bring more
seasonable conditions. There could be some wet snow Sunday night,
but the milder weather should help reduce the snowpack. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
