</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARCE OR A FIGHT? IT'S TYSON-BOTHA
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Some people who follow boxing believe that the
heavyweight boxing bout between Mike Tyson and Francois Botha at
the MGM Grand on Saturday night is nothing more than a carnival
sideshow. They think that many of those who tune in on the
pay-per-view telecast will do so only to see if Tyson will snap
again and commit an even more flagrant foul than he did in his last
bout against Evander Holyfield on June 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In that bout, Tyson bit both of Holyfield's ears, was
disqualified and subsequently had his boxing license revoked. It
was reinstated by the Nevada State Athletic Commission on Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Only the outcome of Tyson-Botha will determine whether it is a
farce. But what is the impact of the bout on the heavyweight boxing
picture?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to have any effect on the heavyweight
division,'' said Lou DiBella, senior vice president of programming
for HBO/TVKO.
</P>
<P>
   DiBella's view may be clouded by the fact that his network has
the pay-per-view for the heavyweight championship unification bout
between Holyfield and Lennox Lewis scheduled for March 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what's going to happen after Holyfield and
Lewis,'' said the veteran trainer Lou Duva. ``There's going to be
an opening there for someone to take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has said if he wins the undisputed championship, he'll
be satisfied. But recently he has said that he is willing to fight
Tyson in a third bout if the price is right. However, in light of
the Holyfield-Lewis unification bout Tyson-Botha is merely an
exercise for Tyson to regain his viability in the division. It
could be a long climb.
</P>
<P>
   Even Tyson's next bout might not have any effect on the
heavyweight division. If Tyson beats Botha, the plan is for him to
fight either Brian Nielsen, Vaughn Bean, who went the distant with
Holyfield before losing a unanimous decision last September, or
Axel Schulz, whom Botha defeated for the International Boxing
Federation championship in 1995. Botha was later stripped of that
title because he tested positive for steroids after the bout.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, which will broadcast the Tyson-Botha bout on its
pay-per-view arm, Showtime Entertainment Television, has signed
Tyson to a four-fight deal. They are hoping that he displays some
of the explosiveness that made him one of the top grossing
pay-per-view attractions in television. Tyson-Holyfield II drew 1.9
million buyers, a pay-per-view record. Tyson has been involved in
the top four all-time pay-per-view events.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Greenberg, executive vice president of Showtime, believes
that a great performance against Botha can catapult Tyson back into
the heavyweight mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson needs to demonstrate that he's fit to fight again,''
Greenberg said. ``If he demonstrates that he's the Mike Tyson of
old, he's at the top of the list again.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will Tyson have to show in order for Greenberg to
determine whether he is the Tyson of old?
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mike looks sharp, if he is in control of the fight in the
ring, if he is connecting with a high percentage of his punches,
then I think that will show that he's back,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Holyfield-Lewis unification bout, it will be a while
before Tyson gets a chance to fight for the title, particularly if
Lewis wins. There will be mandatory bouts lined up for the winner
of the unification bout. Although stranger things have happened, it
seems unlikely that any of the boxing organizations would make
Tyson a No. 1 contender at the expense of those boxers who are
already there after only one fight against an opponent like Botha.
But money changes everything in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the younger heavyweights are crowded at the top of the
list and many will be in action during the first three months of
the year. But there will always be room for Tyson. Tyson's handlers
will be very careful who they put him in against, which means he
won't be fighting any of the noteworthy young heavyweights anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson loses to Botha, then Botha will figure into the mix.
But not nearly as prominently as Tyson. Botha was the IBF's No. 1
contender, before he opted to fight Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   A loss would not completely sink Tyson in the division.
Greenberg believes a Tyson-Holyfield III is viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our research,'' Greenberg said, ``we've determined that
people would like to see that fight again, because they didn't get
to see the fight they wanted to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
