<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-WHITMAN-TAXES-2TAK     01-16 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-TAXES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 NEW JERSEY'S GOVERNOR HOPES TO PUT REBATE CHECKS IN THE MAIL 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ When Christine Todd Whitman was trying to decide
between seeking an income tax cut or property tax relief during her
1993 gubernatorial campaign, her top political advisers said
lowering property taxes would earn the most points with voters.
</P>
<P>
   But her economic advisers, including her childhood friend, the
publisher Steve Forbes, pushed for the income tax cut, arguing that
it would best help the state recover the jobs lost to the
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman's plan for a 30 percent income tax cut helped her
win the election that year and made her the darling of the national
Republican Party. But her decision not to provide direct property
tax relief during her first term angered enough voters that she
nearly lost her re-election bid four years later.
</P>
<P>
   By proposing last week to use $1 billion from the state budget
to reduce local property taxes over the next five years, Mrs.
Whitman said she had now addressed voter concerns well enough that
she might just ask for a recount. Yet, she said, she has no regrets
about adopting the income tax cuts first and waiting to propose the
more politically popular property tax relief plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly would have made my life easier 18 months ago,''
she said in an interview at her State House office. ``But the time
is right now. It is because of what we have done over the last five
years that we are in a position to do something more. The economy
is doing well. The state is doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Mrs. Whitman proposed cutting New Jersey's
income tax rates in 1993, supporters and critics have debated the
role that tax cuts play in stimulating the state's economy. The
governor herself concedes that the booming national economy played
a major role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, the national recovery helps,'' Mrs. Whitman said.
``There is no question about that. I would be the last person to
ignore that or claim that it did not have a role. But what you have
to look at is the relative positions of the states, and that their
internal policies and tax policies make the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that by June 1997, New Jersey had recovered all
the jobs lost in the recession, something New York did not achieve
until a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Economists agree that Mrs. Whitman's tax cuts, including reduced
corporate taxes, reinforced her message that New Jersey was ``open
for business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that New Jersey has led the region in terms of job
growth and recovery,'' said John L. Wieting, regional commissioner
for the Federal Bureau of Labor Statistics. ``The reasons are
multiple and varied. It is very difficult to separate out the
factors that contribute to growth. But something like tax cuts
would give a perception that it is a friendly place to do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Seneca, chairman of the New Jersey Council of Economic
Advisers and a vice president of Rutgers University, said that all
economic indicators, from personal income growth to retail sales,
have been up in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to disentangle the causes of the state's
strong economic performance,'' he said. ``But there is no question
that the improvement in the business climate, broadly defined, has
been a significant, positive factor in the strength of our economy.
The income tax cuts were an important component of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Shure, a former top aide to Gov. Jim Florio who now runs a
public policy group, New Jersey Policy Perspective, takes a
different view. He said the national economic boom was coming to
the state, regardless of New Jersey's income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she cut the income tax, she fixed the one tax that wasn't
broken,'' Shure said. ``That helped the politician's image as a tax
cutter, but the income tax in New Jersey was never so high that
cutting it would have had any large economic impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Shure said that Mrs. Whitman should have addressed the state's
heavy reliance on property taxes for local school costs. The state
now pays a little more than 40 percent of the cost of public
education. The national average is 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is the approach that Florio adopted. He raised state taxes
by $2.8 billion, poured money into local schools, and found himself
in the midst of a taxpayer revolt. Property taxes remained low for
a couple of years, but then they began to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dire predictions from Democrats that Mrs. Whitman's
income tax cuts would lead to skyrocketing property tax increases
because fewer state dollars were going to cities, towns and
schools, property tax collections statewide have slowed in the last
few years. Even so, the average property tax bill in New Jersey is
$4,000, the highest in the nation. There are many contributing
factors, including the longstanding tradition of home rule: 566
municipalities, 611 school districts, 21 counties and 188 fire
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman said she decided to send rebate checks directly to
homeowners rather than to dole out extra state dollars to local
governments because she wants to keep pressure on them to reduce
their costs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To pay for her income tax cuts during her first term, Mrs.
Whitman used several fiscal maneuvers, like a massive pension
borrowing program, which raised questions among some Wall Street
analysts and conservatives about the state's fiscal management.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey, like many other states, is now flush with cash
from the booming economy. The state is expected to end the fiscal
year on June 30 with a budget surplus exceeding $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   So both state officials and Wall Street analysts say that the
Whitman administration can probably afford to pick up the cost of
the property tax rebate checks in the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But the size of the program raises questions about whether the
next governor and future state legislatures would be able to afford
it. Mrs. Whitman's second term ends in 2002, two years before the
five-year program is to be fully implemented at a cost of $1
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mrs. Whitman's proposal, which is similar to the Pataki
administration's property tax rebate program in New York, the
average check to 1.9 million homeowners would be $600 a year,
beginning in 2004. The plan would also provide tenants with an
average check amounting to $100. There are no income limits. In New
York, homeowners do not get rebate checks; they get a credit on
their property tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman promises that if the Legislature approves the plan
by April 15, she will send out the first checks by Labor Day. This
year the average check would be $120, 20 percent of what a
homeowner would get once the plan is fully phased in. The amount of
the rebate checks would increase by 20 percent each year until
2004. The amount of local school taxes paid determines the size of
the rebate checks.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the state budget begins at about $200 million in the
coming fiscal year. It climbs by $200 million each year until it
reaches the full cost of $1 billion annually by 2004, about 5.5
percent of the state's total budget.
</P>
<P>
   Despite concerns about paying for the plan in future years,
Democrats and Republican lawmakers are expected to adopt it.
</P>
<P>
   Economic analysts seem to approve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the economy, and the structure of the tax system, they
are generating pretty large surpluses,'' said Timothy Blake, vice
president of Moody's Investors Service. ``They seem to be disposing
of the surpluses prudently. We changed our outlook from negative to
stable in September 1998 and that was in reflection of the fact
that structural balance has improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman said she did not think future lawmakers and
governors would consider eliminating the rebate checks. ``I believe
that this is going to be a priority for state government because it
is going to be a priority for the people,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
