<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR OF WORDS ESCALATES ON ISSUE OF IMPEACHMENT TRIAL WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D., Ill., Fla., Ky., N.J., Ariz.)  (Eds: This is a page 1 story replacing IMPEACH-REPUBS, which now
runs inside.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
consisting of biographies of four House managers is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, DOWD-COLUMN,
EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW, IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the duel over impeachment witnesses intensified,
Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, has suggested to
Democrats that a bipartisan group of senators deal with the issue,
but the Democratic leader rebuffed his offer and called it
premature.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by several Senate Republicans who are concerned about
the near party-line split over witnesses, Lott sent a letter to
Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., the Democratic leader, on Friday
evening, in the hope of reviving bipartisan discussion groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that a bipartisan group of senators could
anticipate and help resolve in advance any complications that may
be presented by our hearing the testimony of witnesses,'' Lott
wrote. ``Forming a bipartisan group to consider witness issues now
may save us time and trouble in the days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle turned Lott down. He said that any discussion of
witnesses would be premature if it occurred before the full Senate
takes a vote later this month to decide which, if any, witnesses to
depose. He said those talks ``would violate the bipartisan
agreement that now governs our process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that such arrangements will ultimately prove
unnecessary,'' Daschle wrote, ``regarding the many complicated
issues that will result if the Senate votes to call witnesses in
the impeachment proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   In a war of words that is beginning to echo the verbal crossfire
in the House, some Democrats say they are growing increasingly
convinced that Senate Republicans want to call witnesses simply to
embarrass President Clinton and draw out the trial. Republicans
counter that they must take seriously their mandate as jurors and
judges, and that means trying to clarify conflicting testimony and
unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman James Kennedy said Saturday that the House
prosecutors' insistence on calling witnesses ``illustrates their
lack of confidence in their circumstantial case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who demand witnesses are demanding delay and we don't
think a long and drawn-out trial is in the interest of the
Congress, the president and the American people,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's exchange of letters was only the latest partisan volley
in the debate over the trial's second phase: whether the Senate
needs to hear from Monica Lewinsky; Betty Currie, Clinton's
secretary, and Vernon Jordan Jr., his friend, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last week, Daschle expressed anger and surprise when he
learned that three Republicans had met secretly with House
prosecutors to discuss witnesses. Republicans invited Democrats to
attend the second meeting, but Daschle declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take a vote on whether to take
depositions from witnesses once the White House completes its
presentation and senators query both sides. If 51 senators vote to
move forward with the depositions, votes would be taken at some
point on which, if any, witnesses to summon before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican prosecutors argued forcefully and repeatedly
during their presentations last week that the Senate must hear from
witnesses in order to deliver an informed verdict.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the House
Judiciary Committee, said bluntly that getting witnesses to appear
before the Senate is ``our purpose. We try.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The strategy has worked, at least for now. Many Republicans,
even those who were disinclined to hear from witnesses just last
week, have said the prosecutors' arguments persuaded them to change
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a sense of inevitability,'' said Sen. Connie
Mack, R-Fla., a party leader. ``There are more and more people who
believe we will end up with witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., another Republican leader, put
pressure on the White House Saturday, raising the possibility that
if Clinton were to acknowledge some of the allegations presented by
House prosecutors, the Senate may not have to summon witnesses at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a rather strong case on that point,'' McConnell
said, referring to the House push for witnesses. ``Maybe the
president will stipulate to the facts and it won't be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House is not likely to bend on the question of
stipulations. ``We already have stipulated to the record and, as we
will demonstrate next week, the House managers have ignored and
misstated many of the relevant facts contained in that record,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats stood firm Saturday on the point of witnesses.
Many of them said Daschle was right to turn down Lott's suggestion.
``It's too late,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli argued that a ``critical moment'' will come when the
Senate decides whether to dismiss the case, a vote that is
anticipated on Jan. 25. The vote requires a simple majority, and
will likely fail, but Democrats are painting it as a decisive
factor in the trial's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is clear that significantly more than 34 Senators
support dismissing the case, then the dynamics are altered,''
Torricelli said. ``Because then it becomes a question of what value
these witnesses would provide if more than one third of the Senate
believes the case should be dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., who was one of the three Republicans who
met with House prosecutors, also said he saw no need to resume
bipartisan discussions on the question of witnesses until after the
first series of votes. ``It's fine to wait until the decision is
made on whether there are witnesses, and then we can get together
at that time,'' Kyl said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
