<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JUDGES-NYT &LR;      01-16 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JUDGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS REMIND SENATE OF JUDGES WHO WERE IMPEACHED FOR
LYING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Va., Texas)   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK, IMPEACH-EAGLES,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(DW) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House managers Saturday implored the Senate to
hold President Clinton to the same standard that it used in 1989 to
remove two federal judges from office for lying under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Three House managers drew a parallel between the accusation that
Clinton lied before the grand jury about his relationship with
Monica S. Lewinsky and the Senate's perjury convictions of Judge
Walter L. Nixon Jr. of Mississippi and Judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors reminded the senators that Nixon was convicted
because of a ``single, discreet false statement before a grand
jury,'' as Sen. Herb Kohl, a Democrat from Wisconsin , said in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the president's lawyers' arguments next week
that Clinton should not be removed from office, the prosecutors
repeatedly challenged the senators who had voted a decade ago to
convict Nixon and Hastings to apply the same standards when they
judged Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate should not establish a lower standard for integrity
for the president than the standard it has already established for
federal judges,'' Rep. Charles T. Canady, a Republican from
Florida, said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' message clearly was intended for the Democrats
who voted to remove both Nixon and Hastings. They include Sens.
Edward M. Kennedy and John Kerry of Massachusetts, John B. Breaux
of Louisiana, Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia and Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   When he was removed from office, Nixon was in prison, serving a
five-year term. He had been convicted of lying to a grand jury when
he denied that he had influenced a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy oil man, Wiley Fairchild, had asked Nixon to intervene
in a drug case against Fairchild's son. The judge persuaded the
prosecutor, an old friend, to dismiss the charges. In an interview
with federal agents, Nixon denied that he had any involvement in
the case. He repeated those denials before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   After the conviction, on two counts of perjury, the House passed
three articles of impeachment, charging the judge with making false
and misleading statements to the grand jury and to federal agents.
In 1989, the Senate convicted Nixon of perjury on two articles
(with votes of 89 to 8 and 78 to 19).
</P>
<P>
   ``The question becomes,'' Rep. Lindsay Graham of South Carolina
told senators Saturday: ``If a federal judge can be thrown out of
office for lying and trying to fix a friend's son's case, can the
president of the United States be removed from office for trying to
fix his case? That's not a scholarly word, but that's what
happened. He tried to fix his case.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hastings was impeached and convicted, he already had been
acquitted by a jury in Miami of bribery charges. But the House
voted 413 to 3 to impeach Hastings in 1988, approving 17 articles
of impeachment. Fourteen of them accused Hastings of lying under
oath at his trial.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers' report on the Hastings matter said that
lying under oath is an impeachable offense. ``It is important to
realize that each instance of false testimony charged in the false
statement articles is more than enough reason to convict Hastings
and remove him from office,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 69 to 26 to convict and remove Hastings from
office. Hastings, 62, returned to the public stage, winning a seat
in the House of Representatives from Florida. A Democrat, he voted
last month against the four articles impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even have to be convicted of a crime to lose your
job in this constitutional republic if this body determines that
your conduct as a public official is clearly out of bounds in your
role,'' Rep. Graham argued.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prosecutors drew parallels between the convictions
of the federal judges and the article of impeachment alleging
perjury against Clinton, there are also some striking distinctions
that the president's lawyers are expected to draw next week.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cite a section of the Constitution that says federal
judges ``shall hold their offices during good behavior.'' But there
is no similar language about presidents. The cases against the
judges were related to misstatements under oath related to bribery
cases. The president's lawyers are expected to argue next week that
the allegations against Clinton involve a private affair and are
not analogous to the judges' cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
