<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WEATHER-SNOW-NYT &LR;      01-16 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEATHER-SNOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK RETURNING TO CALMER CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After two days of storms dropped more than a foot of
snow across New York state, stranding travelers, knocking out power
and causing roofs to collapse, the weather settled into relative
calm Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 15th straight day, it snowed in Buffalo on Saturday
morning, a light dusting that pushed the city's total accumulation
this month to 60.5 inches. The one-month record is 68.4 inches, set
in December 1985. The 15-day streak could end Sunday, said Paul
Knight, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible it will be the first day without snow,'' Knight
said, adding that there is a chance of rain.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the temperature hit 29 degrees in Central Park
at 11 a.m. Saturday. It was colder than Friday morning, when the
temperature in the commuting hours hovered around 32 and the wind
pelted freezing rain at people venturing outside. Knight said the
forecast called for Sunday to be clear, with temperatures in the
40s and a chance of rain on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
