<HEADER>
A6067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEATURE17-COX     01-16 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rule changes not helping
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the NHL enters its All-Star break later this week,
league officials can feel comforted that rule changes implemented
before the season have not destroyed the fabric of the game. But
they haven't helped, either.
</P>
<P>
   Despite moving the nets farther from the end boards to create
more skating room, shrinking the neutral zone, shrinking the size
of the goal crease and placing new restrictions on the size of
goaltenders' pads and jerseys, teams are scoring at the same pace
as last year _ 5.3 goals per game through 500 games. When broken
down in 50-game segments, scoring steadily increased from 4.7 goals
in the first 50 games to 5.7 in games 150 to 200, seemingly an
indication that players were adjusting. But then, averages declined
again.
</P>
<P>
   League officials may have to start making Goaltenders Central
its marketing campaign: 32 currently had saves percentages of .900
or higher entering the weekend, five had goals-against averages
under 2.0 and 16 were at 2.5 or less. Conversely, only nine
forwards had reached the 20-goal plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made those (goalie pads) smaller and the goalies are
even better now,'' Anaheim forward Teemu Selanne said. ``The
goaltending is just better now. It's a big challenge right now to
find the way to score. The style of the hockey has changed so much.
Most of the teams play so good defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell believes it's too early to
judge the affect of the rules changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the expectations were in terms of the
scoring, but I think the games are more entertaining,'' he said.
``When teams dump the puck in, not as many goaltenders can come out
to stop it for their teammate because the boards are too far away
now. So there's more action behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you make a rules change, you need to give it two or
three years before you can be objective about it. But there's no
question the goaltending is better now than 10 years ago, and
there's more depth at that position.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been some discussion about removing the center red
line, which would eliminate the offside (two-line) pass. There was
not red line at the recent World Juniors Championships in Winnipeg.
``I found the games really interesting that way,'' said Thrashers
assistant general manager Les Jackson. But many in the NHL consider
removing the center line as too radical a change.
</P>
<P>
   Other numbers from the first half of the season are more
encouraging:
</P>
<P>
   _ Attendance has been a problem in some cities, like Carolina
(where the Raleigh-based franchise is playing in Greensboro), Tampa
(which is struggling) and Long Island (where the New York Islanders
have suffered ownership problems). But overall attendance in the
league is running at 90.6 percent capacity. Crowds were at 88.3
percent capacity at this point last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ The two-referee system and crackdown on penalties behind the
play and hits to the head have been a success. League vice
president Colin Campbell has handed out 28 suspensions since the
exhibition season. That's one more than predecessor Brian Burke
handed out all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   The league did not make any significant gains during the NBA
lockout _ but it also avoided a marketing campaign intended to
capitalize on it. ESPN spokesperson Diane Lamb said NHL ratings on
ESPN and ESPN2 are running equal to last season.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL and some teams actually have been contacted by some NBA
officials regarding how hockey made the transition from its lockout
in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions from basketball officials have pertained
to marketing. The NHL will not offer any advice on how to increase
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
