<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-GANGA17-COX     01-16 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GANGA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young, Ganga benefited from business, IOC dealings
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In August 1990, a month before the International
Olympic Committee voted to award the '96 Summer Games to Atlanta,
Andrew Young traveled to the Republic of Congo to visit Jean-Claude
Ganga, his new friend.
</P>
<P>
   Young, an original member of Atlanta's Olympic bid committee,
didn't go empty-handed. He brought boxes full of athletic shorts
and shirts, soccer balls and basketballs. ''We took all the
athletic equipment we could beg from around here,'' Young recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It proved a worthwhile trip. Ganga, an IOC member and president
of the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa
(ANOCA), became a last-minute convert, withdrawing his support of
the Toronto bid and throwing it to Atlanta as host of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, Ganga is believed to be one of nine IOC
members facing possible expulsion for their dealings with the Salt
Lake City bid committee, which won the 2002 Winter Games. Several
news agencies have reported thatGanga made $60,000 in a Utah land
deal arranged by a member of the Salt Lake committee, has received
up to $70,000 in cash payments to help children in his homeland,
and obtained, along with his mother, free medical care. Ganga has
not addressed the specific allegations but has said he did nothing
illegal and will fight any attemt to oust him from the IOC. He
could not be reached for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Friday his offerings to Ganga nearly a decade ago
were ``humanitarian aid,'' not bribes. Young recalls seeing
youngsters eating their food off leaves, running around in little
more than loincloths.
</P>
<P>
   Such sights spur Young to action. A former U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations and one-time Atlanta mayor, he says he's always
maintained a warm spot in his heart for the needy people of Africa.
As Atlanta readied for the 1996 Games, his generosity and energies
touched African athletes _ and officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bid committee had left Young on his own to work
Africa, recognizing no one could do it better. (It wasn't until
late in the process that Melbourne or Toronto had minorities on
their bid teams.) Young visited Africa to develop international
business in his position with the firm Law Engineering and to sell
Atlanta as a city where African-Americans could prosper and hold
positions of power. If the trip generated support in IOC balloting,
all the better.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did what we do in local politics: We'd go to each (IOC)
voter personally, reach every voter we can, to try to make our
point because people do vote relationships,'' Young said. ``You
cannot buy votes. I mean, you cannot buy votes in a secret
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Payne, who led the bid group and later the Atlanta Olympic
committee, said: ''Andy, not bribery, is the reason we were
supported by the African continent. They saw in Atlanta a
black-white city that worked and made them proud.''
</P>
<P>
   At the IOC voting in September 1990, the Young-generated backing
from Africa is believed to have kept alive Atlanta's bid through
early rounds of voting until it eventually won.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think (relationships) were very important because Africa had
been neglected,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Told by the president of Mozambique that its women marathoners
couldn't afford the proper foods to get enough protein in their
diet, Young returned to Atlanta and organized companies to send
foods and protein powder. He ultimately oversaw the shipment of 56
tons of food to 13 African nations _ after the IOC vote, Young
noted.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped set up a training center for African athletes in
LaGrange, Ga.; and he and his friends approached airlines for free
tickets to bring African athletes to Atlanta before the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his work unmistakably benefited Ganga.
</P>
<P>
   The Ganga-led ANOCA was allowed by the Atlanta Olympic committee
to market its own T-shirts and merchandise in Atlanta during the
Games, even though licensing practices that compete with official
sponsors are frowned upon by host organizers. A press release
announcing the deal credited Ganga with ``rallying African nations
to support Atlanta's bid to host the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   And in 1991, when Ganga requested equipment for his
association's office, printers, computers and other office supplies
were shipped to the Congo. The two printers came from the city of
Atlanta after it closed down its print shop. Young said the
shipments were lost or stolen in the Congo and never reached Ganga.
</P>
<P>
   Young understands why some might view this assistance in the
wrong light, but he casts it as just helping the needy. He preaches
that the Olympic movement should use more of its wealth on the less
fortunate. He operates under the premise that providing goods and
even cash shouldn't be frowned upon so long as it gets to people
who deserve it and there's accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga's friends in Atlanta include Shirley Franklin,
administrative chief during Young's term as mayor and later a
senior Atlanta Olympic official. She first met Ganga at the opening
of The House of Africa, a hospitality facility for the 1996 Games,
and later started a nonprofit business with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know him as a very influential leader among his peers in
Africa,'' Franklin said. ''I know him as a visionary.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Olympic flame went dark in Atlanta, Franklin had
hatched plans to establish USA/Africa Sports Development Fund Inc.,
with the idea of raising corporate and other monies in the United
States to upgrade sports facilities in Africa, train coaches and
athletes, and help African athletes to attend U.S. colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Secretary of State records show the corporation was
registered as a domestic nonprofit June 13, 1997, identifying Ganga
as chief executive officer and Franklin as secretary. The
corporation lists an Atlanta address; Ganga provided an address in
Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've served as an unpaid consultant,'' Franklin said. ''I'm
not trying to make money on it, and I don't think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin said the corporation is not up and running because the
Internal Revenue Service has not granted it tax-exempt status.
''There's no money or fund-raising yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   George Howell, who is handling the application, said the IRS has
asked the corporation to restructure the board of directors so its
majority is U.S. citizens. Young is currently the only American
director. Howell said the change will be made, but Ganga will be
retained.
</P>
<P>
   Howell said he hasn't heard from Ganga since last year on who he
wants on the board.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation will require ''millions of dollars'' to fund
what Ganga has in mind, Howell estimated. Sam Zamarripa is another
friend of Young who developed a relationship with Ganga. He was
employed by a telecommunications company that worked for Young's
unsuccessful gubernatorial campaign in 1990, and later contracted
to install a voice-mail system at the Atlanta Olympic headquarters.
Zamarripa was looking to strike up business deals with IOC members
he met in Atlanta. He went to the Congo at Ganga's invitation,
although the visit was fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were doing great things in building relationships with IOC
members to do business,'' Zamarripa said. ''I didn't have a bad
experience with Jean-Claude.''
</P>
<P>
   Young vows to stand by Ganga, who could be expelled from the IOC
in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jean-Claude Ganga is a friend, and I don't run out on my
friends when they're in trouble,'' Young said. ''I think
Jean-Claude Ganga is a man who genuinely loves people, loves sports
and loves the international community. But Jean-Claude Ganga's life
has been in turmoil because his country is in turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the African National Olympic Committee, which he heads, to
produce as many athletes as they are producing...he is doing
something right. And he is getting little or no support from
anybody (within the IOC).''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less kind.
</P>
<P>
   In international sporting circles, Ganga, who lives most of the
time in Paris, is seen by some as seeking to take advantage of his
IOC status.
</P>
<P>
   Mal Whitfield, who spent 47 years in Africa as an official of
the U.S. Information Agency, said he helped arrange meetings in
Africa for the Atlanta bid team. A two-time Olympic gold medalist
in the 800 meters, Whitfield described Ganga as a ''leech.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hated to deal with him,'' Whitfield said. ''He wanted
scholarships from the American side. I'm on to this stuff. I don't
give bribes or do favors.''
</P>
<P>
   Young acknowledges that Ganga is an exceptional pitchman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'll make you give out of your pocket,'' Young said,
``because he is so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-HISTORY17-COX     01-16 2672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-HISTORY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History of trying to gain favor of IOC now `implicity required'
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr. and Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the evenings before the big vote, the heavily laden
carts would begin rolling down the carpeted halls at Tokyo's New
Prince Takinawa Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The young Japanese porters would consult their lists, check the
room numbers and knock softly. When there was no answer, they would
enter the rooms with pass keys to place the offerings to await the
International Olympic Committee members who were residing there.
</P>
<P>
   The carts carried jewelry, handmade crystal knick-knacks, pewter
statuettes, kimonos and other more personalized items, like a rare
book for an IOC member who was a collector.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the 1990 vote to select a host city for the 1996
Centennial Games, some IOC members were joking that their rooms
looked like a cross between an airport duty-free store and a pawn
shop. Many left the trinkets behind when they checked out to return
to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, nearly nine years ago, the sheer excess of the
gift-giving _ let alone a few more unsavory allegations _ was
unsettling to some IOC members. There were calls for moderation,
even reform.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it has proven impossible _ or impractical _ for the IOC to
give up the heady delight of the bidding pageant, with its free
first-class travel, five-star hotels and endless supply of fine
goods and exotic novelties happily presented by willing cities
desperate to win their votes.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta was selected to stage the '96 Summer Games, the
idea of serving as host had become so attractive the six cities
seeking those Olympics spent at least $80 million campaigning for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta bidders said they spent far less than most _ about $7.4
million, primarily from private contributions _ and have always
argued that it was a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are so high that civic leaders who campaign for them
often must weigh the importance of winning against their own sense
of propriety, or at least good taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to trust your judgement and conscience,'' explained
Charlie Battle, a charter member of the volunteer Atlanta bid
committee and head of its international relations. ``Everything we
did I felt like was within the spirit of what was going on. That
was the world as we found it and we were playing by the rules. You
just hope they will think well of you, so they will vote for you.
But I will be the first to say the process needs to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Change may occur, beginning next weekend, when a six-man IOC
panel investigating allegations of bribery for votes that helped
earn Salt Lake City the 2002 Winter Games meets in Lausanne,
Switzerland. Thirteen IOC members accused of excessive gift-taking
are invited to plead their case before the commission Saturday, and
the board could recommend their expulsions along with reforming the
bid procedure next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The only goal of any bidding committee is to obtain a majority
of votes from the IOC, a self-perpetuating organization with 114
members. The IOC assembly has little if any official purpose other
than selecting host cities.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the campaigns tend to focus intensely on the
individual members and what it would take to curry their favor. It
is a targeted lobbying process, said Sir Bob Scott, who spent a
decade leading two unsuccessful bids for Manchester _ one of them
in competition with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You create this unbelievable intimacy with IOC members, which
meant that you got to know them, their hobbies, their passions,
their infidelities,'' Scott said. ``I used to put it in the terms
that you have to know the second daughter's shoe size. You did an
enormous amount of research, and having done all that research,
then the question was what did you do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you discovered that a man's passion was tennis, then you
made sure you found a way to invite him to go to Wimbledon with his
wife. And if he said, 'Can I bring my children with me?' then you
found a way around that, didn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Newton Thomas, one of seven paid staff members of
Atlanta's bid effort, was the international protocol expert. She
compiled dossiers on every voting member. ``We got to know them
personally. We took an interest in their families. Nothing warms
people up like asking about their children. We didn't just bring
them here and say, 'Vote for Atlanta.' ``
</P>
<P>
   And when an IOC member came to visit, his or her day was packed
with memorable experiences, from a tour of the venues accompanied
by a personal driver and hostess, to a private dinner in a Buckhead
or Dunwoody home. The visits were personalized to each IOC member's
passions. Outings to Augusta National for the golfing enthusiasts.
A visit with John Portman for the Mexican delegate who is an
architect. Nightclubbing in Midtown for Prince Albert of Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's real interested in dog breeding, you take him to
see a dog breeding kennel,'' Battle said. ``If he's in charge of
telecommunications in his country and and wants to go see
BellSouth, you arrange to take him there and have them show him
some stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you measure what you do. I remember going
swimming in the Danube River when it was polluted and frozen, and
it was just because the granddaughter of the IOC member (from
Slovakia) wanted me to go swimming with her,'' Battle said. ``Oh
God, I thought I was going to die. But she was a nice girl and she
was my ticket to him. She spoke English.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Atlanta's bid came together in the late 1980s,
ambitious cities around the world were beginning to see hosting the
Olympics as a veritable panacea for civic needs. The Games are a
unique way to build stadiums, redevelop sagging neighborhoods and
accomplish countless other important projects. This was a
revelation from the 1984 Los Angeles Games.
</P>
<P>
   After the financial disaster of the 1976 Games in Montreal _
which generated $1 billion in debt _ there was genuine fear within
the IOC that no city would want to host the 1984 Games. Contingency
plans were drawn in case no one came forward.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a team from Atlanta in 1977 studied and dismissed the
idea of bidding as foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the basis of the Montreal experience, one might question
why any city would ever again seek to host the Olympic Games,'' a
Research Atlanta team wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Little changed the perception of the Games as a loser with the
debacle of the American boycott of the 1980 Moscow Games coupled
with the $11 million deficit left by the Winter Games in Lake
Placid, N.Y., that year.
</P>
<P>
   Only two cities informed the IOC they would bid for the 1984
Summer Games: Teheran and Los Angeles. Teheran eventually bowed
out, to the relief of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   In partnership with a weakened IOC, Los Angeles reinvented the
Games as a marketing event and generated a $235 million surplus.
More importantly, metro Los Angeles reported that the Games created
a $3.3 billion economic boost.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, bidding committees began springing up around the
globe. By 1987, three American cities were seriously pursuing the
'96 Games _ Minneapolis, San Francisco and a latecomer, Atlanta.
Their international competition was Athens, Toronto, Melbourne,
Manchester and Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   As committed as they were to winning, the lawyers, volunteers
and city officials leading the bids tended to be unsophisticated
about the ways of the Olympic world. In short, it would be hard to
imagine an easier target if someone wanted to take advantage of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all dreadfully naive,'' said Scott of Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, members of bidding teams were approached by
Olympic insiders who said they could unlock the IOC's votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always told either genially or sinisterly by someone
that 'I can deliver x-votes for you, so you need to talk to me,' ``
Scott said. ``This is utter nonsense. I mean, how could any one
member of the IOC deliver another IOC member's vote in any
meaningful way?''
</P>
<P>
   Battle said he was never approached, but was aware ``these
so-called agents'' were sniffing around the bid cities. And there
was no doubt that some IOC members would use the bidder's eagerness
to please to their advantage. ``There's no doubt they try to get
opportunities, especially for their children,'' he said. ``I'm sure
that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no malicious intent, no venal attempt to bribe
someone, as funny as that may sound. These are relationships and
you want to help people. You have a capacity to help them and you
do help them or their countries because they don't have anything.
You go over there and everyone is running around barefoot and poor,
and we think we ought to do something for these people and, yeah,
wouldn't it be great to educate some librarian in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to win the Games takes place primarily on two
fronts: visits to host cities by IOC members, and in the lobbies,
bars and suites at luxury hotels favored by the IOC for official
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   On the first front, bidding cities pick up the tab for IOC
members and a guest _ usually a spouse, but not always _ to travel
first class, stay in the finest hotel and experience the best a
city can offer in terms of food and entertainment. Unfortunately
for Atlanta, most of the IOC members didn't know where it was or
anything about it. Consequently, they weren't all that eager to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the bid cities at that time were working hard to get
the members just to come to their city,'' recalled Ginger Watkins,
a charter volunteer. ``It was not considered a junket by the IOC
members.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bid committee was eager to entertain on its home
soil. ``The world didn't know a thing about Atlanta; they came
looking for gambling and Tara,'' Watkins said. ``We encouraged them
to please come and see our city because we knew they didn't have
the perspective we wanted them to have.'' When they came, Watkins
said, she scheduled every minute of their day with guided tours.
</P>
<P>
   At fine hotels where IOC members and reporters were put up,
bidding cities set up hospitality suites that were overflowing with
free liquor and canapes, and staffed by young, attractive and
ever-smiling volunteers. A sure-fire way to gain access to large
groups was hosting a dinner or lunch for IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Both practices have since been outlawed by the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   At major meetings where dozens of IOC members attended, the
schtick here was to set up an ``Atlanta House,'' usually in a
private home near the center of official activity. It would be
staffed by volunteers and filled with Southern samplings, such as
Claxton fruit cakes and Vidalia onion relishes.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, who later became a top ACOG executive, organized the
Atlanta Houses. ``Everyone was drawn to the house and comfort of
going to someone's home and having a good time,'' she said. ``No
matter what culture you're from, your home is your most comfortable
place.''
</P>
<P>
   It's at these IOC meetings where the gift-giving gets out of
hand, Battle said. ``It gets to be comical. They end up with this
roomful of stuff. It's something you have to do out of a sense of
protocol. But there's so much gift-giving and there's so many
cities that you wonder how you are going to distinguish yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's why you end up doing things like scholarships
(for IOC members' children in American universities, which Salt
Lake City is accused of). Because you get into a syndrome of
searching for things you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of corruption were leveled almost immediately after
the IOC _ which always votes in secret _ picked Atlanta to host the
'96 Games. Representatives of five of the six bidding cities
traveled to Lausanne to review the process and discuss the
allegations. One city, for example, was suspected of stretching the
rules by handing out $3,000 diamond necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``(IOC President Juan Antonio) Samaranch used to say, 'Give me
evidence,' `` Scott said. ``For the top people at the IOC, nothing
would have suited them better than to have a ritual slaughter. They
begged for evidence, but none of us could produce any.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing years, allegations about the bidding process
would surface from time to time. In 1992, the German newsmagazine
Der Speigel reported that sources with the Melbourne and Athens
bidding committees had made a number of allegations about the
campaign for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said some IOC members met secretly at the King
David Hotel in Jerusalem to determine the price for their vote. The
meeting, the magazine said, was organized by an IOC delegate from
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said IOC members inspecting Atlanta were given gold
credit cards (which some retained for years); were offered free
heart surgery; took up to $120,000 in bribes (18 members); and
accepted large gifts (26 members).
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the IOC and Atlanta condemned the article as
groundless and irresponsible. Former Atlanta Olympics chief Billy
Payne threatened to sue for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, the IOC official now investigating allegations
against Salt Lake City, at the time demanded proof of the
magazine's allegations, and when he didn't get it the committee
ceased to pursue the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was becoming clear to many insiders that the
membership held some bad apples who were not above the kind of
behavior being alleged. Officially, the IOC said it would expel
anyone whose misdeeds could be verified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't like we just suddenly woke up now; we've been aware
of rumors for some time,'' said Michael Payne, the IOC marketing
director. ``Nobody was willing, or had the evidence and was
willing, to come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the IOC has attempted to tighten the rules by
restricting visits to host cities to three days and limiting to
$150 the value of gifts offered to members. Still, the IOC today
finds itself embroiled in the biggest scandal in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake Olympic officials have admitted that six relatives of
IOC members were among those who benefited from nearly $400,000 in
scholarship aid from the bid committee. There is growing evidence
of other favors for IOC members, including free medical care and
gifts far in excess of the $150 limit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the IOC's own investigation, the allegations are
being probed by the U.S. Justice Department and the U.S. Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As a followup to next weekend's IOC ethics panel session in
Lausanne, all 114 IOC members will meet in mid-March to vote on
expelling members accused of corruption and possibly tightening
procedures for selecting host cities. It's the first time in its
105-year history that the committee has taken such drastic action.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal already has prompted Samaranch to suggest banning
visits by members to bidding cities, stripping the full IOC of the
vote and leaving the selection to the executive board or other
small ``electoral college.'' But some critics of the IOC and of
Samaranch believe this scandal could have been avoided if the
committee had reacted more decisively to past allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Helmick, the only IOC member ever to quit in an ethics
scandal, blames the current crisis on Samaranch, who he says failed
to pay enough attention when allegations of corruption first
surfaced a decade ago. He said Samaranch and other top IOC
officials ``in the know'' should resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very good people in the IOC, but the system has
gotten corrupt,'' Helmick said. ``I think what happened with Salt
Lake is that they were playing the game that the IOC implicitly
required.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott still believes that instances of bribery are rare. ``But
the accusation we could never get away from was that for the 2000
Games, maybe $80 million had been spent by the bidding cities,'' he
said. ``And where on earth did that benefit world sport?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
