</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-Q&AMP;A17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commonly asked questions about Olympic crisis
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's been said that an International Olympic Committee member
has the world's greatest job, even though there is no salary. How
do I become a member? How long can I serve?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is no salary, but all travel expenses are paid.
Prospective members are nominated by IOC members when there's an
opening due to retirement, death or an expansion of the board. The
whole body votes on prospective members, and those who are approved
can serve until they turn 80.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the makeup of the IOC?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are 114 members. Not all Olympic countries are
represented. Countries that have hosted the Games usually have more
than one member.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there anybody or any body responsible for oversight of the
IOC?
</P>
<P>
   A: The IOC is governed by its executive board but there is no
outside oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the IOC subject to any laws?
</P>
<P>
   A: The organization is a nonprofit that is subject to the laws
any nonprofit must obey. In many countries, there are special laws
protecting the committee's marketing rights and exclusive rights to
stage the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were the Games always awarded to cities that offered gifts
and other goodies to IOC members?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Games always have been awarded to cities with the
majority of votes from IOC members. The gifts have long been part
of the campaign cities wage to lobby IOC voters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did the process evolve into the mess we're in today?
</P>
<P>
   A: Everything changed after the 1984 Los Angeles Games, which
were financially successful and made the Games attractive to cities
with lots of money to spend. There were concerns about excesses
with the bidding process in the contest for the 1988 Games, which
were awarded to Seoul, but the first widely reported allegations of
extravagant gift-giving and even bribery surfaced around the time
Atlanta was awarded the Games in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why has Atlanta been under suspicion in some areas?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps because Atlanta won, and there are many people around
the world who can't accept that the city was chosen on its merits.
The city's connection to Coca-Cola _ the patron sponsor of the
Games _ also has raised questions. However, no one has provided any
evidence of wrongdoing with regard to the Atlanta bid, and Atlanta
officials insist they only gave IOC members relatively minor gifts
and small favors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do IOC members justify making repeated trips to bid
cities? Can't they pass judgment with fewer trips?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are supposed to make only one trip to each bidding city.
They argue _ and bidding cities agree _ that they can't fairly
judge a city's ability to host the Games without personal visits to
view the venues, speak to officials and get a first-hand sense of a
city. IOC members often lament that all cities look the same in the
slick brochures and video presentations they produce with their
bids. However, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said recently
the visits are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much of the suspicion around Salt Lake, and perhaps Atlanta,
deals with an African bloc of votes. Is there such a thing?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's debatable. For one thing, no one knows how IOC members
vote because their ballots are secret. There is an assumption that
IOC members in some regions are motivated by similar factors and
therefore can be lobbied in a bloc. It has always been assumed that
Atlanta was appealing to Africans because of the city's standing as
a center for African-Americans in the United States. Former Mayor
Andrew Young, who co-chaired the bidding commitee with Billy Payne,
had deep ties in Africa, in part from his days as UN Ambassador
under President Carter. It has always been suspected, but never
proven, that the African IOC members favored Atlanta for the 1996
Games and provided the city its core of support.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is likely to result from the Salt Lake scandal?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's anybody's guess, but the most likely outcome is that the
IOC will ask the offending members to resign. It also is possible
that the organization will alter its host city selection procedure
and rules for bidding to minimize the chances of another scandal.
However, it is unlikely that the IOC will end the right of its
members to cast the final vote for host cities _ which is, for all
practical matters, the only function IOC members perform.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
