<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-RECRUIT17-     01-16 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-RECRUIT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defense Tech's top priority
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech appears to have addressed its defensive
concerns, particularly in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets have five commitments from defensive backs
and additional help coming from redshirt freshman Marvious Hester.
</P>
<P>
   Coach George O'Leary will have between 25-27 scholarships to
give on Feb. 3, National Signing Day, and they look as if they will
be able to recruit to fill all of their needs.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 other commitments include four offensive linemen, two
quarterbacks, three running backs, one linebacker, three defensive
linemen, two receivers and two kickers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Camp of Dublin, Ohio, was the state's player of the year
as a linebacker and quarterback. Running back Sidney Ford from
Pepperell was an Atlanta Journal-Constitution Super 11 player, and
running back Mike Kitchens of Lebanon, Pa., was a SuperPrep
All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Other top commitments include wide receiver Anthony Lawston, a
6-foot-4, 215-pounder from Baltimore who also was a SuperPrep
All-American, and Jeremy Muyres, who played free safety at
Parkview. Muyres is the younger brother of Tech wide receiver Jon
Muyres.
</P>
<P>
   Roderick Middleton, a 6-2 receiver from St. Stephens, S.C., is
the first cousin of quarterback Joe Hamilton, but is not related to
former record-setting receiver Harvey Middleton.
</P>
<P>
   Both Camp and Middleton are planning to enroll in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Jackets think they have a good chance of landing quarterback
Willie Simmons (6-1, 190) of Quincy, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   They, however, are still looking for a fullback, a tight end and
an H-back type of player to help replace Charlie Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
