<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Middle Georgia players go Div. I
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Middle Georgia Junior College football coach Randy
Pittman couldn't have asked for much more success during his first
season. Middle Georgia finished 11-1 and blasted Northwest
Mississippi 41-3 in the Mineral Water Bowl in Excelsior Springs,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But Pittman has set some pretty lofty goals for the offseason _
landing scholarships for all 15 of his seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is for 100 percent of our sophomores to get
scholarships to NCAA schools,'' Pittman said. ``By the time we're
finished, we'll probably get to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittman expects four players to sign letters of intent with
Division I programs, including quarterback Jason Vaughn, a graduate
of North Springs High. Vaughn, a 6-foot-4, 205-pound transfer from
Ole Miss, already has committed to UNLV coach John Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Georgia linebacker Kendrell Bell (6-2, 250), a first-team
JUCO All-American, visited Mississippi State this weekend. He
probably will decide between Georgia and Mississippi State this
week, Pittman said. Nose guard Nakia Adderson (6-3, 270) chose
Houston, while free safety Will Pettis (6-4, 200), a former Georgia
Tech signee from Bradwell Institute, is considering Houston and
Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   In-state news
</P>
<P>
   Latrez HarrisonWest Laurens High linebacker Rodney ThomasCharles
Jones ... Defensive lineman Jeff Barnes Dantonio Burnette Jatavis
Sanders SEC and ACC notesBobby BlizzardArtose PinnerBlizzard (6-7,
240) was considered one of the nation's top prospects at Hampton
High in Virginia. Pinner (5-11, 197) rushed for 3,274 yards during
his senior season at Hopkinsville High in Kentucky. ... Tailback
Santonio Beard Durrell Robinson Kevin Breedlove Reggie Brown all
coveted by Georgia. The Vols also are hosting linebacker Kendyll
Pope
</P>
