<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FOCUSING ON STATE OF THE UNION
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-JUDGES) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton kept a studied distance Saturday
from his impeachment trial in the Senate, focusing not on the
charges laid out against him by Republican prosecutors, aides said,
but on the next big event on his political calendar: the State of
the Union speech on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent the morning reviewing the lengthy draft of his
seventh State of the Union speech with a small group of aides, in
preparation for a more formal run-through Saturday afternoon in the
White House family theater. In his customary preparation for the
speech, Clinton was expected to speak from a lectern before a small
invited audience of speech writers, political aides, policy
advisers and friends.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said that Clinton _ who
does not have a television in the Oval Office _ had not watched any
of the presentations on Capitol Hill on Saturday. However, the
President's lawyers and his advisers were preparing to brief him on
the impeachment sessions when the Senate adjourned for the day.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what not what was highlighted on Clinton's public
schedule. At 10:06 a.m., speaking from the Oval Office, Clinton
delivered his weekly radio address, and the topic was the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday celebration on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this national holiday should be a day on, not
a day off, for as Dr. King once said, life's most persistent and
urgent question is, `What are you going to do for others?'''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Until all children of all backgrounds have the
chance to live up to their God-given potential, free from want in a
world of peace, Dr. King's work and our work will not be
complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spent the day monitoring the situation in Kosovo,
where a massacre of about 40 people was uncovered Saturday, said
State Department spokesman James Foley. The president later issued
a statement condemning the massacre in ``the strongest possible
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   But the State of the Union address took up most of the
president's day. Clinton had rejected the suggestion of some
Republicans that he delay the speech, and the timing of the address
appeared to play somewhat to his advantage this weekend, his aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the impeachment proceedings, Clinton has portrayed
himself as tending to the duties of his presidency. The demands of
speech preparation Saturday allowed him to fill up with work what
otherwise might have been a relatively eventless winter Saturday in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1520EST &QL; 
