A6083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-RECRUIT17-COX     01-16 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-RECRUIT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrison adds Dogs to his list
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Bulldogs are making a late push for
quarterback Latrez Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, a Super 11 selection from Atlanta's Booker T.
Washington High School, originally did not consider Georgia one of
the major players in his recruitment. But the exodus of two of
Quincy Carter's backups and the possible defection of a third has
rekindled both Harrison's and the Bulldogs' interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Nate) Hybl leaves, I'd definitely consider coming to
Georgia,'' the 6-3, 190-pound Harrison said. ``I'd love to back up
Quincy Carter, but I want to go somewhere I'd be able to play
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Georgia quarterbacks, Daniel Cobb, a redshirt freshman, and
Mike Usry, a sophomore, already have announced that they are
transferring. Hybl, a redshirt freshman, said he is considering
``all my options'' and could transfer as well. However, Georgia
coach Jim Donnan maintains that Hybl ``isn't going anywhere,'' and
the quarterback is enrolled for winter semester and recently
announced plans to join the Bulldogs golf team.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison already has visited Auburn, Georgia Tech, Syracuse and
Maryland and was scheduled to visit Central Florida this weekend.
He has a press conference scheduled for 10 a.m. Tuesday at
Washington High but said that could ``get pushed back'' depending
on what happens over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, record-setting quarterback J.R. House of Nitro,
W.Va., might be leaning toward signing a pro baseball contract,
with the possibility of returning to college football later. House,
who set the national high school career and single-season passing
records in the fall, visited Georgia two weekends ago. He's
considered a major-league prospect as a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bulldogs' standing with Carrollton wide receiver
Reggie Brown and other in-state recruits could only have improved
with the hiring of former Tennessee secondary coach Kevin Ramsey as
defensive coordinator. Ramsey was recruiting Brown, the No. 1 wide
receiver prospect in the South, for the Vols, as well as LaGrange
running back Bruce Thornton, Creekside defensive lineman Charles
Roberson and Dunwoody defensive lineman Jeff Womble.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
