<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Jan. 24.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. Please see BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Jan. 9, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION
</P>
<P>
   1. THE STREET LAWYER, by John Grisham. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A young lawyer comes to terms with himself
</P>
<P>
   after discovering his prestigious firm's dirty secret.
</P>
<P>
   2. INNER HARBOR, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   The final volume of a trilogy about three brothers
</P>
<P>
   contending with a crisis in their family's life.
</P>
<P>
   3. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager, left stranded in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town, finds help and caring from its
</P>
<P>
   inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   4. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Rebecca Wells. (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three
</P>
<P>
   generations of Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   5. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE, created by Tom Clancy and
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pieczenik. (Berkeley, $7.99.) In 2010, federal
</P>
<P>
   agents combat terrorist sabotage of defense and
</P>
<P>
   intelligence computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   6. MIDWIVES, by Chris Bohjalian. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, legal and moral, haunts a midwife who may have
</P>
<P>
   killed a woman while trying to save the baby's life.
</P>
<P>
   7. FEAR NOTHING, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A man whose health forces him to live at night
</P>
<P>
   witnesses mysteries only he can solve.
</P>
<P>
   8. MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) After finding a seaborne bottle
</P>
<P>
   containing an enigmatic letter, a divorced woman
</P>
<P>
   encounters love.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) SWEET ANGER, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $6.50)
</P>
<P>
   A television newscaster is obsessed with
</P>
<P>
   the man who shattered her late husband's life.
</P>
<P>
   10. TOM CLANCY'S POWER PLAYS: RUTHLESS.COM, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   America is imperiled by computer-based terrorism
</P>
<P>
   in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   11. OLIVIA, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket, $7.99.) The fifth
</P>
<P>
   volume in a series about the Logan family.
</P>
<P>
   12. (x)COLD MOUNTAIN, by Charles Frazier. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A wounded Confederate soldier journeys home toward
</P>
<P>
   the end of the Civil War to meet an old love and a
</P>
<P>
   new world.
</P>
<P>
   13. MAD JACK, by Catherine Coulter. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Romance, mystery and family problems in Georgian
</P>
<P>
   London.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE GHOST, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to New England, a troubled man finds answers to
</P>
<P>
   his problems in diaries in an old trunk.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision,
</P>
<P>
   $5.99.) A World War II veteran meets an old flame who
</P>
<P>
   is about to be married.
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   1. A CIVIL ACTION, by Jonathan Harr. (Vintage, $14)
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit brought by Massachusetts householders
</P>
<P>
   against industrial polluters. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $12.) How daily activities can
</P>
<P>
   be enhanced by feelings of meaning and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   3. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   4.(x) THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a crew of
</P>
<P>
   fishermen from Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. THE END OF THE DREAM, by Ann Rule. (Pocket, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Four true crime cases in which people's dreams were
</P>
<P>
   destroyed by acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   7. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography
</P>
<P>
   of a man who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   8. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A celebration of life in the
</P>
<P>
   Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   9. INTO THE WILD, by Jon Krakauer.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.) How a young man's
</P>
<P>
   obsession with the wilderness had a tragic end
</P>
<P>
   in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE MAN WHO LISTENS TO HORSES, by Monty Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $7.99.) The memoirs of a professional
</P>
<P>
   horse trainer.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x)`N' SYNC: The Official Book, by 'N Sync with
</P>
<P>
   K.M. Squires. (Dell, $9.95.) A profusely
</P>
<P>
   illustrated account of the pop group.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE VIRTUES OF AGING, by Jimmy Carter. (Library
</P>
<P>
   of Contemporary Thought/Ballantine, $9.95.) Reflections
</P>
<P>
   on the rewarding opportunities of old age by the former
</P>
<P>
   president. (b)
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic
</P>
<P>
   tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE MAN WHO ATE EVERYTHING, by Jeffrey
</P>
<P>
   Steingarten. (Vintage, $14.) The food critic for Vogue
</P>
<P>
   recalls his gastronomic adventures.
</P>
<P>
   15. UNDAUNTED COURAGE, by Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   (Touchstone/S&AMP;S, $16.) Lewis and Clark's
</P>
<P>
   exploration of the West. (b)
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF ... AND IT'S ALL SMALL STUFF,
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Carlson. (Hyperion, $10.95.) How to enjoy life
</P>
<P>
   more and contribute to the world we live in. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL II, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eades. (Bantam, $6.50.) Two physicians
</P>
<P>
   offer a protein-rich, low-carbohydrate plan for
</P>
<P>
   losing weight.
</P>
