<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-ATTYGEN-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR ON GUARD OVER NEW ATTORNEY GENERAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last month, Gov. George Pataki quietly switched
lawyers defending him in a lawsuit. The change drew little notice,
but it could be a sign of a tense relationship to come between him
and New York's new attorney general, Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Democrats in the State Assembly sued the
Republican governor over his budget vetoes, Pataki's response was
routine: He turned to Attorney General Dennis Vacco to defend him.
But in November, Vacco, a Republican closely allied with the
governor, was unseated by Spitzer, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Pataki hired a private team of lawyers to take over
his defense. Spitzer had not even taken office yet, and he had
given no hint of where he stood on the case. But the message from
the governor was unmistakable: The new Attorney General could not
be trusted to represent Pataki in a politically charged, partisan
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer may present a range of problems for the Republican
governor, most small, but some of considerable weight. The attorney
general has the power to set the state's official position in court
cases _ even if that means defying the governor's wishes _ and in
some instances, he can hinder Pataki's ability to direct state
policy.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general can also conduct potentially damaging
investigations into the administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the most frequent area of conflict between Spitzer and
Pataki is likely to be in the attorney general's primary job,
defending the state in the thousands of lawsuits filed against it
each year. The attorney general's defense of the administration is
expected and routine in most of these cases, which usually involve
mundane matters like injuries on state property or tax disputes.
But disputes between governors and attorneys general have occurred,
even when both officials were from the same party.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when the attorney general sides with a plaintiff,
rather than the governor? What happens when the state loses a case
at trial and the governor wants to appeal, but the attorney general
says no? Pataki was apparently unwilling to find out in the case of
the budget lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this would pose a conflict for Spitzer,'' said
Zenia Mucha, Pataki's communications director, though she would not
elaborate. As evidence of a conflict, other Pataki aides pointed to
Spitzer's listing of Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, the plaintiff
in the suit _ along with every other leading Democratic state
official _ as a member of his transition advisory team.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign that Spitzer, who declined to be interviewed
for this article, will play the antagonist. But state officials in
both parties say he does not have to be combative for confrontation
to arise; merely being politically independent of the governor is
enough.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his first term, Pataki had the advantage of working with
Vacco, who barely won office in 1994 on the governor's coattails.
Vacco could be counted on to throw the weight of the state's top
law enforcement official behind the governor, or at least to avoid
public disagreements with Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer has promised repeatedly to be a different kind of
attorney general, more aggressive than Vacco in enforcing laws on
the environment, governmental ethics, voting rights, state
contracting and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the governor, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
conceded that they feared the new attorney general might look for
ways to cause trouble for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``An aggressive guy, looking to make a name for himself on the
governor's back, could be a real problem,'' said one Pataki aide.
``The A.G. has to sign off on a lot of state contracts. On that
level alone, he could be a real pain, but it would backfire on him
if he looked too partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   One policy area in which Spitzer and the governor are likely to
clash is the environment. Under Pataki, the State Department of
Environmental Conservation has taken a more business-friendly
approach to law enforcement, cutting back on fines for corporate
polluters and reducing the number of polluters who are referred to
the attorney general's office for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But Spitzer says he will not wait for referrals from the
department before taking polluters to court, an approach that will
put him directly at odds with administration policy.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Mario Cuomo said that even when there was no
political motivation, conflict was ``inevitable when the two people
have different philosophies of the role of government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer to have a member of my own party than a member
of the opposing party,'' he added, ``because there's always the
temptation for the opposing party to try make political mileage out
of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many examples of officials of opposite parties working
together without rancor. In the late 1970s, Gov. Hugh Carey, a
Democrat, had a fine relationship with Attorney General Louis
Lefkowitz, a Republican. And for the last four years, Connecticut
has had a Democratic attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, and a
Republican governor, John Rowland, without any serious friction.
</P>
<P>
   But Spitzer's youth _ he is 39 _ and obvious ambition could
sharpen the potential for confrontation. ``The administration can't
help but look at him as a potential future political adversary,''
said Blair Horner, legislative director of the New York Public
Interest Research Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
