<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 STATEN ISLAND AND BROOKLYN GETTING INTO THE MINORS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bronx has the Yankees, Queens has the Mets and
Manhattan may be getting a domed stadium to lure the Jets. And now
Brooklyn and Staten Island are also getting new city ballparks, to
house new farm teams for the Yankees and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's proposal for the Manhattan stadium drew
most of the attention in his State of the City speech on Thursday,
and both Yankee and Shea stadiums may be rebuilt. But the mayor
also announced that agreements had been reached to build two minor
league baseball parks at a cost of about $20 million each.
</P>
<P>
   The city ballpark in the St. George section of Staten Island
will be home to the Indians, a newly affiliated Yankees farm team
that is moving from Watertown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this summer, they will play at a field at the College
of Staten Island at Willowbrook as a temporary site until the new
park's completion, projected for a couple of years from now.
</P>
<P>
   The ballpark in Brooklyn will be part of a long-planned sports
complex on Coney Island. Mets officials say they are looking at
several minor league teams and will choose one to affiliate with
and move to Coney Island.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are confident we will reach an agreement fairly soon,''
said David Howard, a Mets senior vice president. The farm team will
start playing in Coney Island by 2001 if not before, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Yankees and Mets plan contests for fans to name the new
teams. They are legally precluded from reviving the Brooklyn
Dodgers name.
</P>
<P>
   The Watertown Indians, previously the Pirates, are owned by
Sandlot Sports, a company held by a Manhattan family, Stanley and
Phyllis Getzler and their son Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   Watertown Mayor Jeffrey Graham said he was sorry to see the team
go. But considering the sparse attendance it drew in that city of
30,000, he said the departure was ``not a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The two new farm teams would compete in the Class A New
York-Pennsylvania league, which has 14 teams.
</P>
<P>
   The two ballparks will be conveniently close for fans when the
two teams play against each other. Howard envisions a new New York
baseball rivalry, ``not a subway series, but a Verrazano-Narrows
Bridge Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
