<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MEDICAL CENTERS UNITE TO GAIN DRUG RESEARCH FUNDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Underscoring a new trend toward cooperation in the
New York region's intensely competitive health industry, five major
academic medical centers quietly have joined forces to pursue a
larger share of the billions of dollars that drug companies now
lavish on other parts of the country to test new products.
</P>
<P>
   Their new consortium, the Biomedical Research Alliance of New
York, is one of several new projects intended to help restore New
York's pre-eminence in biomedical research, generate thousands of
jobs in the region and bolster efforts to recruit top scientists.
Its members are Montefiore Medical Center, Mount Sinai School of
Medicine, New York University School of Medicine, Saint Vincents
Hospital and Medical Center and the North Shore-Long Island Jewish
Health System.
</P>
<P>
   Working with manufacturers on drug trials is nothing new for
these academic institutions. But, hobbled by cumbersome and
antiquated practices, New York medical centers have been able to
capture only a minuscule portion of what is now a $5 billion-a-year
business, said Dr. Eileen Hilton, a specialist in infectious
diseases who is now the chief executive of the new consortium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The academic medical centers were interested in the business
of research for the sake of research, not business,'' Hilton said.
``They were not fast enough or cost-effective enough for
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of new drugs, manufacturers have demanded
speedier clinical trials in the hope of getting their products to
market before the competition. At the same time, the U. S. Food and
Drug Administration has set higher minimum levels for the number of
subjects required for testing the safety and effectiveness of new
drugs, and has insisted that a range of ages and ethnic groups be
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Because of what she described as ``bureaucratic delays,'' like
difficulty arranging meetings with the appropriate departments, it
could take as long as five months for a clinical-trial project to
be approved at one of the members of the alliance _ compared with a
week or two at a private company, Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
   To simplify procedures, the new consortium has one review board
and one standard contract covering all five institutions.
</P>
<P>
   If most academic institutions were slow to respond to the
explosion in the clinical-trials business, private industry was
not. Increasingly, drug companies began farming out their
large-scale clinical tests to companies known as contract research
organizations, which have sprung up in the Research Triangle of
North Carolina and elsewhere across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance is seeking contracts from these private
organizations, as well as from the drug companies, said Dr. John W.
Rowe, the chairman of the biomedical alliance and the president of
the Mount Sinai-N.Y.U. Medical Center and Health System. These
private companies will gain access to more than 7,000 doctors and
2.4 million patients, Hilton said.
</P>
<P>
   No one connected with the biomedical alliance can estimate just
how many jobs will be created. But since much of the data from
clinical trials is entered manually, the business is very labor
intensive, said Raymond G. Falci, a health care analyst with Bear
Stearns. The project received a $1 million loan from the New York
City Investment Fund, a private fund that tries to stimulate job
development.
</P>
<P>
   One labor pool for the alliance is likely to be immigrant health
professionals who have been unable to get licenses to practice
medicine but can be trained as clinical research coordinators, Rowe
said. Hilton said that coordinators were also being recruited from
among the many health care professionals who have lost their jobs
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the alliance was begun in September at North Shore Medical
Center, it has received $3 million in contracts, exceeding its
initial expectations, Hilton said. Yet more than half of the
proposals have been rejected on ethical grounds, or because doctors
felt a particular study was poorly designed or would not adequately
protect the patients being tested, she said. In addition, she said,
the alliance will not accept trials for competing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Trials are under way for more than two dozen drugs for treating
everything from AIDS to impotence, she said. The alliance recently
opened its first New York City office in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   One company that has contracted with the alliance is Pfizer
Inc., which is based in New York City. Joseph M. Feczko, a senior
vice president for medical and regulatory operations, said that
with several academic centers to draw from, it would be easier to
recruit the appropriate patients for a particular clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   He added that companies would benefit from the abundance of
highly skilled doctors in New York's prestigious institutions. The
doctors would also benefit by acquiring access to new drugs, Rowe
said, and because profits earned by the consortium will be plowed
back into their institutions and medical groups.
</P>
<P>
   From 1983 to 1997, New York State's share of research funds from
the National Institutes of Health _ considered an important
barometer for measuring the decline _ fell to 10.7 percent from
15.2 percent, with a loss of $2.4 billion in grants.
</P>
<P>
   The first new initiative in the effort to reverse that decline
was announced in November, when Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani said that
the city would commit $12 million to a major research study on
cancer involving 25 of the region's medical schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, 10 academic medical institutions said they were
joining together to create the New York Structural Biology Center,
which will house machines employing high-field magnets used to
study molecules. The center is to open next year on the City
College campus of the City University of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
