<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6092 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     01-16 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Jan. 24) 
(mk) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A STONE OF THE HEART
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Grimes. Southern Methodist University, $12.95. An
overweight 14-year-old boy, starved for affection and trying to
stay afloat in a dysfunctional Irish-American household in Queens
in 1961, seeks refuge in Roger Maris' pursuit of the home-run
record. In 1990 our reviewer, Hilma Wolitzer, called this a
``compact and affecting first novel.''
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND THE OVAL OFFICE: GETTING REELECTED AGAINST ALL ODDS
</P>
<P>
   By Dick Morris. Renaissance, $16.95. President Clinton's former
adviser tracks the arc of his own career, giving plenty of
attention to the mechanics of polling and policy-making, as well as
the overwhelming influence of money and television in presidential
politics. This curious artifact has been updated with a new
introduction and the weekly briefing papers given to the White
House by the author and other political consultants during the 1996
campaign (and later subpoenaed by the Justice Department). Morris
``has written an account that future historians of the Clinton
Presidency will not be able to ignore,'' James B. Stewart wrote
here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   THE HEALING
</P>
<P>
   By Gayl Jones. Beacon, $12. Narrated by a faith healer and
former rock star manager, this funny novel leans on free
association to explore the power of faith to banish violence and
paranoia. Last year in these pages, Valerie Sayers praised the
``gradual building of connections and insights that culminates in a
giddy outpouring of language.''
</P>
<P>
   A PRAYER FOR THE CITY
</P>
<P>
   By Buzz Bissinger. Vintage, $15. A journalist with extraordinary
access tells the inside story of Philadelphia's remarkable mayor,
Ed Rendell, whose drive and honesty helped restore hope and fiscal
soundness to a city on the edge of collapse. Last year our
reviewer, Robert Fishman, said this ``full-scale portrait of a
struggling metropolis ... brings to mind such classics of urban
reportage and analysis as J. Anthony Lukas' `Common Ground.' '' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI, by Joan Didion (Vintage International, $12), is a more
impressionistic account of an American city, dwelling on the Cuban
exile community and the shadowy links between the Bay of Pigs
disaster and events like Watergate and the Kennedy assassination.
``The world Miss Didion describes in beautifully evocative prose is
... a world of menace and elliptical connections,'' James Chace
wrote here in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS PUBLIC AND PRIVATE: ASPECTS OF AN AMERICAN CITY, by
Warren Leslie (Southern Methodist University, $14.95), was first
published after President Kennedy's murder and seeks to explain a
city whose mix of extreme conservatism, religious expression and
political excess made it a place where nasty things were bound to
happen. This study, which includes a new foreword and preface, ``is
a good deal more than a revealing, a valuable and a careful book,''
George Fuermann said here in 1964. ``It is also a courageous one.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PERON NOVEL
</P>
<P>
   By Toms Eloy Martinez. Translated by Helen Lane. Vintage
International, $14. This Argentine novel imagines the life of the
strongman Juan Peron, particularly his 18 years in exile and his
ill-fated return to power in 1973. The book ``is a brilliant image
of a national psychosis,'' Jay Cantor wrote here in 1988. TALES
FROM THE BLUE ARCHIVES, by Lawrence Thornton (Bantam, $13.95), is
the last of three dream-driven novels by the author revolving
around Argentina's ``dirty war.'' It focuses on a woman's search
for her grandsons, who were among the ``disappeared,'' and on what
happens when she finally finds them. The tale ''blends the mundane
violence of recent Latin American politics with the high tragedy of
Elizabethan drama,'' Robert Houston wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   COUNT ME OUT
</P>
<P>
   By Russell James. Foul Play/Norton, $10. When one of the robbers
of an armored car takes off with all the loot, the mastermind of
the heist tries to track him down through the crook's ex-boxer
brother and his 8-year-old daughter. In 1997 our reviewer, Marilyn
Stasio, admired this British mystery for ``the depth, as well as
the darkness'' of its insights.
</P>
<P>
   THE HISTORY OF JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   By Ted Gioia. Oxford University, $15.95. This concise,
accessible overview covers jazz from its roots in slavery through
jazz-rock fusion and beyond. In 1997 our reviewer, Peter Keepnews,
said that despite its occasional omissions and lapses, ``the book
is peppered with pithy and thoughtful observations.''
</P>
<P>
   TRESPASSING: MY SOJOURN IN THE HALLS OF PRIVILEGE
</P>
<P>
   By Gwendolyn M. Parker. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $11. A
well-off black lawyer tells how she rode the fast track to success
in corporate America, and how the pressures of racial tokenism
finally caused her to hop off. In these pages in 1997, Deborah E.
McDowell called this an ``engagingly written and fluidly paced''
memoir.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND AWAY
</P>
<P>
   By Joanne Meschery. University of California, $13.95. During the
Gulf War, a California woman struggles to balance her growing
political awareness with a troubled marriage and other personal
crises. The novel ``manages to deal sensitively with serious
issues,'' Constance Decker Thompson wrote here in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
