<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-ADVANCE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vin-dication? Testaverde burning to show he can win a big game
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Twelve years after he was supposed to burn up the NFL
as the Heisman Trophy star with the kind of talent most
quarterbacks would kill for, Vinny Testaverde enters today's AFC
Championship Game with a raging inferno in his belly.
</P>
<P>
   His remaining skeptics _ those who regard his conference-best
101.6 passer rating in '98 as a fluke and will view this
afternoon's matchup against the Denver Broncos with a morbidly
curious anticipation of Testaverde falling on his face _ likely
will suggest the source of the unease is the quarterback's own
apprehension at playing in the biggest game of his professional
career.
</P>
<P>
   The bubble, they figure, is overdue to burst. And where better
for Testaverde's magical season to be transformed into a grim fairy
tale than at the cusp of the Super Bowl? To be honest, Testaverde
acknowledged Friday evening, he realizes that anyone beyond the New
York state border has handicapped today's game as the latest Vinny
pratfall.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is good reason, given that in past postseason
appearances Testaverde's windpipe was much tighter than his
spirals.
</P>
<P>
   Without rancor, though, he predicted the doubters will be sorely
disappointed. The journeyman quarterback who finally is living up
to the press clippings from a dozen years ago fully expects to look
back on this game as his Vin-dication Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident, but I'm not going to predict victory, because
the Broncos are a helluva team,'' Testaverde said. ``But I know
we'll play well and I know I'll play well. What's going on in my
stomach is a burning desire that hasn't been with me the past few
years. It's not nervousness, it's more like nervous energy ... and
that's different. Honestly, I can't wait for the game to be here.
Because, even as jacked up as I am, I've got this inner peace
that's telling me I'm going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   There now is a serenity about Testaverde, 35, that has been
lacking in the past. One can see it in his eyes, and Denver free
safety Steve Atwater said Testaverde's newfound confidence is
noticeable even on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Significant to the success Testaverde enjoyed in 1998 is that he
was able to share it with the people he most cares about. When Jets
assistant head coach Bill Belichick, who was head coach in
Cleveland when Testaverde played there, convinced Bill Parcells to
sign Testaverde as a free agent, he had no idea what effect the
quarterback's homecoming might have on his roller-coaster career.
</P>
<P>
   Having a tight-knit support group, however, has made a
difference in Testaverde's life on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Right down to the Joe Namath poster that still hangs on the wall
of what used to be his bedroom, Testaverde grew up a Jets fan in
Elmont, Long Island. His father, ``Big Al,'' and mother Josie long
ago gave up attending Testaverde's games as their son's career took
him from Tampa Bay to Cleveland and then to Baltimore. Because of
heart problems and his inability to keep himself sedate while
watching Vinny perform, ``Big Al'' has been ordered by doctors not
to attend the games.
</P>
<P>
   Not until he knows the final score, details of the game and
Vinny's statistics does Al Testaverde sit down and view the
videotape. He has vowed to attend the Super Bowl if the Jets win
today, noting: ``If I'm going to have the big one, where better
than in some 50-yard line seat at a Super Bowl, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually it is the seats around Al and Josie's dining room
table, now full every Tuesday night, that brings the most pleasure
to the Testaverde extended family.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, it has been a tradition that Josie cooks for the
entire family on Tuesdays, when huge vats of spaghetti sauce boil
over onto her new stove. The four Testaverde daughters and their
familes have made the trek ``since forever,'' Josie said. ``But
Vinny, when he played somewhere else, he could only make it in the
offseason once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the quarterback is in charge, not just of calling signals on
Sunday afternoons, but also calling the menu selection on Tuesday
nights. His favorite pass might be the post route, but his dinner
of choice is chicken parmigiana with pasta on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times this year,'' Testaverde said, ``when I've
looked around the dinner table after having been gone so long and
thought, `Man, how good is this?' The success we're having (on the
field) is like the stromboli after dinner, you know? To be playing
well in front of people who have known you all your life, to live
four miles away from a house I grew up in ... sure, it's great to
be back at home again.''
</P>
<P>
   Every morning at 7:30, Testaverde and daughter Alicia, 7, drive
to a bakery shop near their home. The two have bagels and cream
cheese, Alicia with a chocolate milk chaser and Vinny with orange
juice. Then on the way to school, Testaverde quizzes his oldest
child on the week's spelling words. Last week's thrill: When Alicia
got ``streetlight'' right after several days of stumbling on it.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bill Piner, the quarterback's coach at Sewanhaka High
School: ``It's amazing all the little things that mean so much to
Vinny now. He really is at peace. At this point in his career, he
appreciates all this so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his NFL career, Testaverde is surrounded
by a balanced and skilled supporting cast and is working for a
coach who believes in him. In his weak moments, Parcells has
conceded he was initially as skeptical as the detractors who've
hounded Testaverde for 12 seasons. He had watched Testaverde throw
35 interceptions in 1988, the second-most in NFL history. And he
had seen examples of Testaverde wilting under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and the Jets players expect no shrinking violet today.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have judged Vinny on what happened in the past always was
unfair,'' said fullback Keith Byars. ``He always had to be the
whole show by himself and no man can do that in the NFL. But in
this offense, with the talent we have, he doesn't have to win every
game or make every play. All he has to do is drive the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   After 12 seasons, this is the day Testaverde tries to collect
the big fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that, just to be in the NFL, you have to
be in the top 1 percent of the top 1 percent,'' Testaverde said.
``This game can make it all worth the while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
