<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway's retirement all but official
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Although he has talked openly about perhaps playing
again next season if the Denver Broncos win Super Bowl XXXIII and
have a chance for a ``three-peat'' in 1999, all indications now are
that quarterback John Elway plans to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Elway missed four games this season with rib, hamstring and
shoulder injuries and has told friends he plans on stepping away
from the game. His father, Jack Elway, conceded on Friday night
that's likely the case. And when Juliana Elway, his youngest
daughter, hinted she might watch today's game at a friend's house,
the 16-year veteran strongly suggested she attend what figures to
be his final appearance in Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Steve Atwater, who also is considering retirement,
acknowledged there is ``a sense of urgency in our locker room to
win one more for (Elway).'' Added coach Mike Shanahan: ``The
chances are good this is John's final game at Mile High and I think
we all pretty much know that.'' Agent Marvin Demoff said late last
week he ``assumes'' this is his client's final NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   Elway wanted to retire after last year's Super Bowl but the
feeling is he played in '98 to help owner Pat Bowlen get a
referendum passed for a new stadium here. Elway told Miami
quarterback Dan Marino after last week's divisional game that his
body ``is just begging me (to quit).''
</P>
<P>
   When asked Friday night if he can walk away knowing he probably
still has a few good years in him, Elway said: ``I think I'll
always have a lot of football left in me. Whether I can play it or
not is another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan reiterated that if Elway retires, Bubby Brister will go
to training camp in '99 as the Broncos' No. 1 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Dawg day afternoon
</P>
<P>
   This might be a bad sign for the Jets: The only backs who had
100-yard performances against the New York defense in 1998 were Gar
of football development Gene Washington into the 49ers front
office. . . . Look for the Redskins to name all-time wideout Art
Monk to a post with the team. Also expected to join the Washington
front office is former Jaguars team president David Seldin. . . .
Several veterans in Jacksonville will test coach Tom Coughlin by
boycotting his offseason workouts this spring. . . . Giants GM
Ernie Accorsi, satisfied with the play of backup Conrad Hamilton,
will jettison veteran cornerback Carlton Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert stumbling
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to owner Jerry Richardson, who assembled much of the
offensive coaches, new Carolina coach George Seifert has at least
half a staff. But Seifert is having a problem landing a defensive
coordinator. His first choice, Ray Rhodes, went to Green Bay as the
head coach. His second pick was Emmitt Thomas but the former Eagles
defensive chief went with Rhodes. Third choice Wannstedt rejoined
Johnson in Miami. Now Seifert is courting Baltimore defensive
coordinator Marvin Lewis and Cunningham. Lewis turned down an offer
from new Eagles coach Andy Reid last week but still is keeping
options open because has a lot of irons in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing for freedom
</P>
<P>
   When agent Frank Bauer drew up the contract that enabled
restricted free agent Chad Cota to leave Carolina for New Orleans
last spring, he knew that the three-year, $5.4 million deal was a
masterstroke of structure. But not even Bauer could have foreseen
just how much the cleverly-constructed contract would work in favor
of the scrappy safety. The deal included six team-performance
clauses, any of which would trigger an opt-out decision for Cota
this spring. The only clause that had a shot entering the final
game of the season was one that would grant Cota his freedom if the
Saints improved eight spots over their 1997 rank in interceptions.
New Orleans was 13th in pickoffs in '97 and rated just No. 7 going
into the finale. By grabbing three interceptions of Buffalo
quarterback Rob Johnson in the final game, the Saints moved up to
No. 5. So Cota earned $2.5 million for his one season in New
Orleans and now gets his unrestricted freedom. The Saints are left
with an unexpected salary cap acceleration of $1 million. And the
Panthers, still scrambling for safeties, may pursue Cota.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
