<HEADLINE>
FLOODED PLAZA COLLAPSES INTO UNDERGROUND GARAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a thunderous rumble and a rush of air, a
playground and a concrete plaza collapsed into an underground
parking garage at an apartment complex on Manhattan's Lower East
Side late Friday night, crushing dozens of cars and shaking nearby
buildings with the force of a small earthquake. No one was injured,
and there were no reports of missing people, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers, who used heat-seeking devices and search dogs to
comb the rubble, said they did not believe that anyone had been
trapped when the plaza collapsed shortly after 11 p.m., leaving a
150-foot-wide crater and a jumble of concrete in the middle of the
Seward Park cooperative apartment houses at Clinton and Grand
streets.
</P>
<P>
   But fire officials said they would have to excavate tons of
debris and wrecked vehicles before they could be certain no one had
been buried when the ground gave way and a four-feet-thick layer of
concrete and topsoil dropped, along with a swing set and park
benches, into the parking garage below.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who visited the scene shortly after the
collapse, said it appeared to have been caused by the wet weather.
Several residents said that much of the plaza had been flooded with
water about six inches deep Friday and that the water had leaked
into the garage. Officials at the complex's management office could
not be reached by phone Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents who live closest to the plaza, in the building
known as 413-415-417 Grand St., said they were asleep or had just
settled in to watch the 11 o'clock news when the floors and walls
began to tremble. There was a whoosh of air, a thundering noise and
the cable television service went out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was an earthquake,'' Richard Chartoff said.
``I ran out in the hallway, and by the time I put it together, I
figured something either exploded in the garage or outside.'' His
wife, Margot, said, ``The floors shook, the walls shook, my
furniture shook.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Chartoffs rushed down into the garage to check on their
silver Toyota Camry. ``We saw our car crushed to pieces,'' Mr.
Chartoff said. ``It was gone, like an accordion. It seemed to have
been buried or sunk down. It seemed to have disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   They saw the garage ceiling buckling above them and ran out.
</P>
<P>
   As emergency vehicles surrounded the apartment complex, the
residents of about 40 apartments closest to the collapse were
evacuated. They were allowed to return about four hours later after
officials deemed the 21-story building to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the garage, which serves all four buildings in
the Seward Park complex, was almost always full, with as many as
500 cars. It can take years on a waiting list before a resident can
lay claim to one of the coveted spots, which cost from $100 to $220
a month, depending on the location.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that as many as 50 or more cars, parked at the
back of the garage, might have been destroyed. And even residents
whose cars had been spared said they were now facing the almost
equal nightmare of weeks or months without a place to park in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The residents, a middle-class mix of Orthodox Jews who are a
vestige of the old Lower East Side and newer Hispanic and Asian
immigrants, said they felt blessed that the collapse had occurred
late on a cold night, when few people were parking their cars or
sitting out on the benches in the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summertime, this would be crowded until 11 or 12
o'clock at night,'' said Rose Chen, whose 1997 Honda Accord was
parked at the front of the garage and was not damaged. ``The kids
play football. People sit on the benches. We are really lucky no
one got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the snowstorm on Thursday followed by ice,
freezing rain and flooding on Friday might have weakened the
ceiling of the garage. But they said the exact cause would not be
known until an engineer conducted a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a pancake collapse of the roof of this parking
garage,'' said Chief Jack Kelly of the Fire Department's 11th
Division. He said excavating the debris with a crane would take
three to four days. The garage was about 40 years old, he said, but
he did not know whether age had been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know now, it's a mystery,'' he said. ``Until the
engineer takes a look at it, we won't know for sure.'' Kelly said
subway trains on the F line, which passes nearby, had been slowed
to reduce vibrations that could further weaken the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, residents said they went through a
terrifying experience in which, for a few seconds, the Lower East
Side felt like San Francisco. ``I didn't hear anything, but I felt
the movement, the tremor,'' Shevi Stetansky said. ``It was like an
earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray Cohen, 83, a school aide, said the evening newscast was
cut short. ``I was watching the news, and I heard an explosion,''
he said. ``I thought they bombed the building. We thought it was a
bomb. We heard a big bomb, and the cable went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Penina Mezei, 26, on her way to synagogue Saturday morning with
her three children, said the collapse had shaken her out of bed.
``I thought it was a gunshot, and I got scared,'' she said. Her
husband, her parents and her brother all had cars parked in the
garage, she said, but she did not know whether they had been
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's the Sabbath, so we'll worry about it after sundown,''
she said, adding that the plaza and playground lie between her
apartment building on Grand Street and her parents' building on
East Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   She said the scene from her apartment window _ jagged concrete
slabs, upended park benches and the playground swing set virtually
intact but dropped 12-feet below ground _ had captivated her
children all morning. ``They said, `The swings are in the garage,'
and I said, `We can't go into the garage to play on the swings,' ''
Mrs. Mezei said. ``The swings are no more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
