<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS CITE HISTORIAN WITH AN OPPOSING VIEW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Fla., Ill.)   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES) 
(jw) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, members of Congress have taken to quoting famous
historians to back up their own views on the impeachment of
President Clinton. Twice Saturday, for example, House Republicans
Steve Buyer of Indiana and Charles Canady of Florida quoted the
writings of Arthur Schlesinger Jr. to argue for Clinton's removal.
</P>
<P>
   Just one problem: Schlesinger, the Pulitzer Prize-winning author
who was an aide to President John F. Kennedy, has come out firmly
against Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Schlesinger appeared before the House Judiciary
Committee to argue that, though he had favored the impeachment of
President Richard M. Nixon, delivering the same punishment to
Clinton ``would permanently weaken the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the Senate on Saturday morning, Buyer quoted a
sentence from Schlesinger's book, ``The Imperial Presidency,'' a
study of the growth of presidential power over two centuries. ``The
continuation of a lawbreaker as chief magistrate,'' Buyer quoted
from the book, ``would be a strange way to exemplify law and order
at home or to demonstrate American probity before the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger, 81, did not offer an opinion about the Republican
appropriations of his views in responding to a phone call placed to
his home in Manhattan, but he said it was not the first time it had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Hyde actually on Dec. 8 made somewhat the same kind of
comment,'' Schlesinger said, referring to the House Judiciary
Committee's Republican chairman, ``claiming that I changed my views
about impeachment, that I advocated in the Nixon case and opposed
it in the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've not changed my view. As I faxed to Chairman
Hyde, when he made that charge on Dec. 8, if Clinton had done what
Nixon did, I would certainly favor his impeachment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
