A6100 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLD-W     01-16 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS END PRESENTATION WITH CALL FOR CLINTON'S REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new, updated top, new byline, and major rewrite with new
reporting.)  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES,
IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER) 
(mk) 
 By R.W. APPLE JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Summarizing the Republican case against President
Clinton in a speech evoking the shades of heroes past, Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., said Saturday afternoon that the presidency could be
``permanently damaged'' if the Senate failed to remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that a hundred years from today, people will look back
at what we have done and say, `They kept the faith,''' Hyde, the
chief prosecutor, declared in an emotion-laden presentation
accusing Clinton of fraying the bonds of trust between those who
govern the United States and those who are governed.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Hyde said one last time, is not about sex but about
``the rule of law'' _ ``one of the great achievements of our
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., told senators that the
president must be removed from office because he had ``made himself
a notorious example of lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the final day of the Republican presentation of the
impeachment case against the president, Canady, like Clinton a
graduate of Yale Law School, also argued that the Senate could not
set a lower standard for a president than for judges who have been
ousted in recent years for making false statements under oath.
Clinton is accused in one impeachment article of committing perjury
in his testimony to the grand jury investigating his sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared closing statement, Hyde told the Senate: ``Your
judgment should rise above politics, above partisanship, above
polling data. This case is a test of whether what the founding
fathers described as `sacred honor' still has meaning in our
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Canady and two colleagues on the panel of House managers, Reps.
Steve Buyer, R-Ind., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., sought to
pre-emptively rebut arguments of Clinton's defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Citing British and American authorities in a session that often
turned the Senate chamber into a constitutional history classroom,
they contended that the offenses Clinton is accused of, not only
perjury but obstruction of justice, meet the constitutional
standard of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' for impeachment; that
missteps in his private life had led to crimes in his public
capacity; that the Senate had convicted judges in recent years for
analogous offenses, and that if Clinton was guilty he must not be
allowed to remain in the White House, as Canady put it, ``in all
his infamy.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has argued from the start that even if Clinton
was guilty, nothing he did would justify the removal from office of
a popular president, twice endorsed by a national electorate. It
was that argument, which Buyer termed the ``so-what'' argument,
that the three sought to nail Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer (pronounced BOO-yer) attacked on several levels in a
passionate presentation, urging the senators not to give way to any
of several double standards.
</P>
<P>
   In response to those who note that perjury, unlike treason and
bribery, is not enumerated in the Constitution among ``high crimes
and misdemeanors,'' Buyer cited Sir William Blackstone, the great
18th-century English jurist whose book of legal commentaries, James
Madison wrote, was ``in every man's hand'' as the constitutional
draftsmen went about their labors.
</P>
<P>
   Blackstone, Buyer said, included perjury among his list of
public offenses, placing bribery and perjury side by side. From
there, he jumped to the assertion that ``there is no difference''
between ``sitting before a federal judge and perjuring oneself''
and offering that judge a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging widely, Buyer quoted Black's Legal Dictionary, Gen.
Douglas MacArthur, John Adams and, on the seriousness of perjury
and obstruction of justice, former Attorney General Griffin Bell, a
Democrat. Bell, he said, had reached the heart of the matter when
he declared, ``A president cannot faithfully execute the laws if he
himself is breaking them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now at least 115 persons serving sentences for
perjury in federal prisons,'' Buyer said. ``Where is the fairness
to these Americans, if they stay in jail and the president stays in
the Oval Office?''
</P>
<P>
   But Buyer laid special emphasis, of a kind that had not been
heard in the trial, on the impact of Clinton's alleged crimes on
the armed services and on women.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats continue to insist that the whole controversy
stems from a private sexual matter, and is therefore beneath
constitutional notice, Buyer demanded, does that mean that the
evidence-gathering process in federal sexual harassment cases, like
the one brought against Clinton by Paula Corbin Jones, which led to
the Lewinsky case, are unimportant?
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of The Citadel, the South Carolina military college,
and a veteran of the Persian Gulf war, Buyer argued that Clinton's
``diminished veracity'' had had an ``inherently corrosive'' effect
on his capacity to function effectively as commander in chief and
to carry out his foreign policy duties.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Buyer said, American military personnel all over
the world ``know that, if accused of the same offenses as their
commander in chief, they would no longer be deserving of the
privilege of serving in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, much the folksiest of the 13 managers, was assigned to
explore Senate precedent, and he did so. He dutifully noted that
Judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada had been removed in 1986, for
filing a false income-tax return ``under penalties of perjury.'' He
noted that Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi had been removed in
1989, for lying to a grand jury about his efforts to fix a friend's
son's case in state court. And he noted that Judge Alcee Hastings
of Florida had been removed, also in 1989, for perjury and
conspiracy to obtain a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All three cases set significant precedents for this case, Graham
said. But he laid special emphasis on a statement by former Sen.
Charles Mathias of Maryland in the Claiborne case. Mathias, one of
the prosecutors in that matter, said the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachable conduct does not have to occur in the performance
of an officer's official duties. Evidence of misconduct,
misbehavior, high crimes and misdemeanors can be justified upon
one's private dealings as well as one's exercise of public
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defense is rooted to a considerable degree in the
argument that the offenses charged do not involve official
misconduct. On Saturday, his spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the
final presentations constituted ``a clear concession and admission
that their case isn't strong enough without witnesses,'' whose
calling the White House and most Democrats oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Hastings had been acquitted in criminal court,
Graham drew the lesson that crime was not a prerequisite to
impeachment, because, he said: ``Impeachment is not punishment.
Impeachment is about cleansing the office. Impeachment is about
restoring honor and integrity to the office.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graham also made a broader point, much at variance with the
apocalyptic tone of most of his Republican colleagues' remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you decide,'' he told the senators who sat
silently in judgment of a president whom all of them know, ``this
country will survive. If you acquit the president, we will survive.
If you convict him, it will be traumatic, but we will survive.
There is a calmness in the midst of something so important as this
that tells me we've done it right for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Canady's turn came, he gave perhaps the most lawyerly
speech of the whole three-day process _ tight, well-organized and
thoroughly documented. Whether he persuaded any senators remained
unfathomable, as has been the case throughout the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Canady argued that the purpose of the power to remove officials
granted to the Senate is ``to preserve, protect and strengthen our
Constitution by setting a standard of conduct for public
officials.'' Clinton, he said, had failed to meet that standard, as
construed in the light of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the claims of the president's lawyers,'' he said,
``there is not a bright line separating official misconduct by a
president from other misconduct of which the president is guilty.
It does violence to the English language to assert that a president
who has violated a duty entrusted to him by the Constitution is not
guilty of official misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have been reminded repeatedly, the Constitution imposes
on the president the duty to take care that the laws be faithfully
executed. A president who commits a calculated and sustained series
of criminal offenses has, by his personal violations of the law,
failed in the most immediate, direct and culpable manner to do his
duty under the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Canady reviewed at length the concept of impeachment as it
evolved in England, notably in the proceeding against Warren
Hastings, who was on trial during the Constitutional Convention.
Then he plunged into an example of the Framers' intent, one of the
most vexed questions in the whole debate.
</P>
<P>
   He relied heavily on comments by James Iredell, later a Supreme
Court justice, at the North Carolina ratifying convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
