<HEADLINE>
RAPPER'S COUSIN TO TESTIFY AGAINST HIM, OFFICIALS SAY  
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Va.)   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cousin of a well-known rap artist with the
Wu-Tang Clan has agreed to become a witness against the performer
in connection with a shootout with police officers, law enforcement
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The rap artist, Russell Jones, who alternately goes by the stage
names Ol' Dirty Bastard and Big Baby Jesus, was arrested in
Brooklyn about 8 p.m. Friday, shortly after the police said he
fired two shots at officers in an unmarked patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Jones faces charges of attempted murder of a police officer,
aggravated assault and criminal possession of a weapon, the
Brooklyn District Attorney's office said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick B. Clark, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office, said
Jones could face life in prison if convicted on the highest count
of the attempted-murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the shootout occurred after officers saw Jones,
29, driving his 1999 Chevrolet Tahoe erratically, with his
headlights off, after he left the United Kingdom Studios in the
Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When the officers neared the car, Jones fired two shots at them,
the police said, and they returned his fire.
</P>
<P>
   The car drove off, then stopped about a half-block away, where
Jones' cousin, Frederick Cuffie, the only other person in the
vehicle, jumped from the car and ran, the police said. Jones was
arrested as he got out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Cuffie, 37, was arrested about 11 p.m. after officers found him
in a nearby building. No weapon was recovered, the police said
</P>
<P>
   Although Cuffie also had faced attempted-murder charges, those
charges were dropped when he became a witness for the prosecution,
according to a law enforcement official who was speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``He is a material witness who we believe
was an uninvolved passenger in the car,'' and can connect Jones to
the shots that were fired, the official explained.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's shooting was the latest incident involving Jones,
who has survived two shootings and has often been accused of
exhibiting the lyrical aggression of the Wu-Tang Clan, a group
originally from Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Between September and November, he was arrested twice, for
allegedly threatening to kill his 27-year-old ex-girlfriend in Los
Angeles, and other time for allegedly threatening security guards
at a blues club there, according to the Associated Press. Last
July, he was charged with shoplifting in Virginia, the Associated
Press also reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also drew public attention when he stormed the stage of
the Grammy Awards at Radio City Music Hall last year, seizing a
microphone to complain about losing in the best rap-album category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
