<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE: BIG UPSETS, BIG CROWDS AND TALL PLAYERS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ontario, Conn., N.J. Ind. ,  Vt. )  By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ To most Boston College sports followers,
the biggest victory recorded by an Eagles team in the post World
War II era occurred in football. Boston College upset top-ranked
Notre Dame, 41-39, in South Bend on Nov. 30, 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Inglese would concede that a BC victory over the Irish may
have been the biggest upset, but she might differ on the sport. To
Coach Inglese, the 78-65 upset that her women's basketball team
registered at home on Dec. 30, 1998, over Notre Dame, then ranked
No. 7, was at least equally significant in Boston College sports
annals.
</P>
<P>
   While the Boston College men's team is enduring its worst season
in years, Inglese's Eagles have made it into the top 25 in the
national ranking for the first time since the women's varsity
basketball program began in 1972. Going into Saturday's Big East
game against Miami at the Conte Forum on the BC campus, the Eagles
_ ranked 21st by The Associated Press _ were 13-2 over all and 5-2
in the Big East, with the losses to the Hurricanes on Dec. 5 and at
Syracuse on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of their junior point guard and co-captain, Cal
Bouchard, was evident in the Eagles' loss to Syracuse. The 5-7
Bouchard, from Aurora, Ontario, injured her knee against Georgetown
last Sunday and is expected to miss at least a month. Bouchard, a
first-team all-Big East selection last season, is averaging 13
points a game.
</P>
<P>
   That 73-70 loss to Syracuse stopped a seven-game B.C. winning
streak. Considered with their 17-11 finish last season, the Eagles'
ability to win in bunches has established them as a formidable
force in the Big East, which also has Connecticut, Notre Dame and
Rutgers in the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great leadership and excellent teamwork have made us a much
better team,'' said Inglese, who knows something about establishing
a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to Boston College in 1993, Inglese, a native of
Wallingford, Conn., spent seven seasons as the head coach at
Vermont, where her teams went unbeaten in 57 regular-season games
during the 1991-92 and 1992-93 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big East women's conference has gotten a lot better _ we
have four teams in the top 25,'' Inglese said, ``and we've reached
a higher level over the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglese has attracted three 6-foot-plus frontcourt players from
New York State high schools, and they have been instrumental in the
Eagles' success this season. There are two seniors from the
metropolitan area _ Whitney Steele, who was the career-leading
rebounder at Northern Valley Regional High School in Old Tappan,
N.J., and Paula Bacso, the 6-1 co-captain, who was a three-time
Long Island player of the year while attending Farmingdale High.
The freshman Becky Gottstein, also 6-1, was a two-time all-state
selection from Albany High School.
</P>
<P>
   Gottstein, who is averaging 8 rebounds and 8 points a game, has
supplanted Steele as the team's leading rebounder. The 6-4 Steele,
the tallest starter, is averaging 5 rebounds and 13 points a game,
a point behind the junior guard Alissa Murphy of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   On a campus where sports has always been a rallying point, the
Eagles draw relatively small crowds despite their success. But
attendance is growing: the Notre Dame game drew a women's record of
4,133 at the Conte Forum, even though it was played during the
Christmas break. A doubleheader that featured BC against Michigan
State at the Fleet Center in Boston last Nov. 22 attracted 6,834
fans. Through seven games at home, the Eagles have averaged 1,827.
</P>
<P>
   They will play in front of far more spectators when they meet
Connecticut on Feb. 6 at the Hartford Civic Center, where the
Huskies, both men and women, draw capacity crowds to practically
every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what you dream of _ playing one of the country's best
teams in front of more than 15,000 people,'' said Bacso, who was
also recruited by UConn, Syracuse and St. John's, among other
schools. ``You can't ask for any more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Except perhaps another major upset. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
