<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BRAZIL-ECON-ART-2TA     01-16 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BRAZIL-ECON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S AUTOWORKERS, ONCE THE WORKING-CLASS ELITE, NOW REELING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art advisory.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO BERNARDO DO CAMPO, Brazil _ For 22 years and four months,
Luiz Porfirio Diniz reported daily to the bustling Ford do Brasil
automotive plant here, where three different car models are
manufactured. But then, just before Christmas, he got the bad news
he had been fearing ever since Brazilian interest rates shot to
nearly 50 percent four months ago: He was one of 2,800
assembly-line workers being laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Employees took over the plant on Jan. 5 to protest that move, so
Diniz still spends his day on the plant floor, playing dominos with
his fellow workers. The stoppage means that Ford is no longer
producing its daily quota of 1,000 cars, but the company has not
moved against the workers _ perhaps because car sales are declining
so dramatically in Brazil that Ford has the equivalent of nearly
two months of production stockpiled in storage areas here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to work, so all they have to do is give us the
word,'' said Valdecir Aparecido de Souza, another laid-off worker.
``But if nobody is spending any money, management is not going to
take us back, and we're not going to be able to find jobs anywhere
else. It's a real mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial crisis that has shaken Brazil in recent months,
culminating last week in a 21 percent devaluation of the country's
currency, the real, is first and foremost a threat to workers and
their families. But for that very reason, it also represents a
growing danger for the hundreds of multinational companies that
have flocked to Brazil and invested billions of dollars in recent
years, lured by a market of 165 million people that seemed to be
enjoying sustained growth and stable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Though all of Brazil is now reeling, the once-flourishing
automobile industry centered here in the industrial suburbs south
of Sao Paulo, which produced as many as 2 million vehicles a year
at its peak, was hit early and particularly hard. Car sales in
Brazil, the world's seventh-largest auto market, slumped 27.5
percent last year, falling from 1.64 million to 1.19 million, with
Ford registering an even larger decline, 33.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   James Cain, a Ford spokesman in Detroit, said the elimination of
a shift at the factory here and the resulting layoffs were driven
by the conclusion that ``we did not believe there would be any
substantive improvement in the market in 1999.'' The company lost
money in Brazil in 1998, Cain said, and it indicated to Wall Street
analysts at a briefing on Jan. 7, even before the major devaluation
announced Friday, that it was unlikely to earn a profit in Brazil
this year either.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's top automaker, Volkswagen, is also suffering from a
sharp decline in demand, but last month negotiated an agreement
with its workers here to reduce pay by 15 percent rather than cut
jobs. On Friday, General Motors do Brasil reached a similar accord,
laying off 1,000 of its 8,700 workers for five months but
continuing to pay them 80 percent of their normal salaries.
</P>
<P>
   For Brazil's 275,000 autoworkers, once considered the elite of
the working class, that means hard times after years of hard-won
improvements in their standard of living. ``Yesterday, I was
dreaming,'' reads the bumper sticker on a car parked outside the
Ford factory here. ``Today I can't even sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Diniz, who is 44, married and has two children, is a typical
example. Born in the arid interior of the impoverished northeastern
state of Paraiba, he, like millions of other northeasterners hoping
for a better life, came to Sao Paulo as a teen-ager, and by working
hard and scrimping and saving, managed to buy his own house and
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Ford and think of it as family,'' he said as he and a
group of other workers congregated at the Bar do Pascual, just
outside the plant's main gate here. ``I grew up with this company,
so being in this situation is enough to make me cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent years had been especially good, he and other workers
said. The government's Real Plan, announced in 1994, tied the value
of Brazil's currency to the dollar, forcing a level of fiscal
discipline that quickly reduced inflation from more than 1,000
percent a year in the early 1990s to single digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing down inflation made it easier for people like us to
buy food, clothing and appliances,'' said Adailton Coelho dos
Santos, 55, who works on the same line as Diniz and also emigrated
from the northeast. ``For the first time in our lives, we were able
to figure out what our money was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, millions of Brazilians could finally afford to buy
televisions, refrigerators, furniture and other consumer goods,
secure in the knowledge that their monthly payments would not
outstrip their wages. But measures taken by the government over the
past six months, especially the dramatic interest rate hike, have
driven the Brazilian economy into recession and forced consumers to
economize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of members who can no longer meet their rent or
mortgage payments, let alone think about buying appliances,'' said
Luiz Marinho, president of the metalworkers union of Sao Bernardo,
which represents the autoworkers here. ``We have guys who have had
to postpone their weddings because they don't have a cent to spend
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For American companies, the belt-tightening by working-class
Brazilians like those here is nothing but bad news. Brazil is the
United States' 15th-largest trading partner, and in recent years it
has been one of the fastest-growing markets for American-made
goods, ranging from equipment for heavy industry to potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   American banks also have a heavy exposure here. As of the middle
of 1998, they had about $16.7 billion in loans and other assets
outstanding in Brazil, with Citicorp, Chase Manhattan Bank and
BankAmerica each reporting more than $3 billion in assets here.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is especially alarming for the estimated 2,000
American businesses that are operating in Brazil, which has Latin
America's largest economy. American concerns have more than $27
billion invested here, giving them a higher profile here than in
other troubled areas like Russia or Southeast Asia, and weak
results this year, now expected to be the general rule as a result
of last week's economic turmoil, could affect their profit
statements back home.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the major car companies, for instance, Whirlpool
and General Electric manufacture appliances such as refrigerators,
stoves and microwave ovens. Companies like Johnson &AMP; Johnson and
Procter &AMP; Gamble make a wide variety of toiletries and cosmetics,
including soaps, shampoos and detergents.
</P>
<P>
   At their factories north of Sao Paulo, Motorola, Lucent,
Qualcomm and other companies turn out telecommunications equipment
such as cellular phones, whose availability has increased
dramatically as the result of the privatization of Brazil's
telephone system last year. With the market for computers here
having grown by as much as 30 percent a year recently, computer
makers such as Compaq and Dell have also installed themselves at
sites in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden and dramatic downturn here raises the question of
whether American, European and Japanese companies that have flocked
here in recent years may now have too much manufacturing capacity
installed in Brazil. Or as Pedro Reis Correa, a 39-year-old
assembly line worker, put it: ``If all of us are unemployed, who is
going to buy the products these companies make?''
</P>
<P>
   For Christmas, in fact, Correa, who earns a salary of about
$1,000 a month, had planned to buy a computer, mostly for use by
his two children, ages 8 and 11. He had even obtained a bargain
price through a nephew who works for a computer manufacturer and
saved up the down payment that would have allowed him to buy the
$1,600 machine on an installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   But when he received the layoff notice, he had to tell the
children that ``this is going to have to wait for some other
time,'' he recalled sorrowfully. ``I am trying to cut expenses as
much as I can, and that means no more car trips to the interior on
weekend or movies or candy bars for the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Carlos Santos knows only too well the effects of
decisions like that. For the past four years, he has parked every
day outside the entrance to the Ford plant here, and from the back
of his beat-up station wagon, sold items such as kitchen knives,
watches, videocassettes and toys to the workers, with gross sales
of about $1,300 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sales are down 50 percent in the past month, so of course I
am very worried,'' he said on Friday morning, as a constant drizzle
added to his woes by driving his few potential customers indoors.
``If the money of the workers here dries up, then people like me
are going to go bust. This situation affects everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Santos said, his family too has begun economizing,
anticipating that the situation is going to get worse before it
begins to improve. ``We're eating less meat and more rice and
beans, buying cheaper brands of shampoo and soap and cutting back
on our consumption of soft drinks, doing everything we can to save
a penny here and there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is not what companies like Coca-Cola or Nabisco, which
derives about 17 percent of its worldwide sales from Brazil, want
to hear. Brazil is Coke's second-largest overseas market,
accounting for about 5 percent of the beverage giant's worldwide
profits.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1995, Coke's sales in Brazil expanded by a
spectacular 34 percent. But growth was estimated at only 1 percent
for last year, and with people like Santos and his family
determined to drink less, the most optimistic projection for this
year is flat sales.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the money Coca-Cola takes in here is earned in the
now drastically devalued local currency. ``They're not hedged on
the real,'' explained Emmanuel Goldman, a global consumer products
analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``Whatever happens to the real, happens
to Coke's earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how Friday's decision by the Brazilian
government to allow the real to float freely against the dollar
will affect other companies. In theory, the long-urged devaluation
of the real should make Brazilian exports cheaper across the board
and therefore more attractive than those of its competitors, while
also encouraging investment by making Brazilian companies available
at bargain prices to foreign purchasers who may be attracted to the
market.
</P>
<P>
   But economists have expressed concerns that the devaluation of
the real could set off a chain reaction across Latin America and
the rest of the developing world, with country after country trying
to gain a competitive advantage by lowering the value of its
currency. In addition, the price of the components, raw materials
and finished goods that Brazil buys will now go up, fueling
inflation here and cutting consumer purchasing power further.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, thousands of Brazilians who purchased cars on an
installment plan opted for financing terms that peg their monthly
payments to the exchange rate between the dollar and the real. Not
only will they now have to pay substantially more each month or try
to sell their vehicle before it is repossessed, but the devaluation
is expected to drive many potential buyers out of the market
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the population is frightened and stops consuming, things
can only get worse,'' Marinho said. ``That's what we are
confronting right now, a moment that threatens to erase all of the
gains we have made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
