<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-DEATH-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE INVESTIGATE PRISONER'S DEATH
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nassau County police are investigating how a man
serving a 90-day sentence in the county jail for traffic violations
died on Thursday night, covered in bruises, with a lacerated spleen
and broken ribs.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Thomas Pizzuto, 38, of Hicksville died after suffering
multiple seizures at the Nassau County Medical Center, hospital
sources said. Mark Barber, president of the correction officers'
union, said that Pizzuto's injuries resulted from a seizure inside
a cell that was made of concrete and steel. But Pizzuto told his
father, two days before he died, that jail officers had beaten him,
the family's lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzuto's parents have filed a complaint with the police, said
the lawyer, Dennis Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy has not been completed on Pizzuto, a recovering
heroin user who had been in methadone treatment, and jail officials
would not comment Saturday. But Denis Dillon, Nassau County
district attorney, said the case was being investigated as a
possible homicide because of the family's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Pizzuto, the dead man's older brother, said in a
telephone interview that he was still in shock. ``I can't believe
that he went in for that little charge; a couple weeks he was
supposed to be out and that's it. It wasn't supposed to happen that
way. It just happened so quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that Thomas Pizzuto whispered to his father during a
hospital visit on Tuesday that jail guards had beaten him on
Friday, Jan. 8, the day after he entered the correctional facility.
Thomas Pizzuto had been taken to the hospital on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The evidence is just overwhelming that he was beaten,'' Kelly
said. ``There's just no other explanation for the trauma he
suffered. The explanation that the family had gotten was that he
fell. That's the standard explanation when somebody gets beat at
the Nassau County Jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County police officials refused to discuss the case
Saturday. According to Newsday, which reported the case on
Saturday, police are trying to find out why Pizzuto was kept in a
cell in the admission section instead of being released into the
general jail population after one or two days.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, president of the union representing the 1,000 sheriff's
deputies who work at the jail, said there was no documentation of
any incident involving Pizzuto, and that his bruises were easily
explained by seizure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has had a seizure before, the first thing you do
is you move the furniture out of the way,'' Barber said. ``The jail
cell is made of concrete and steel. If you have a seizure inside of
a cell, what do you have to bounce against? You have a steel bed
and concrete floor, concrete ceiling, concrete walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Pizzuto, who was married and had a 14-year-old son with Down
syndrome, was sentenced to 90 days for driving while under the
influence of drugs, leaving the scene of an accident and aggravated
unlicensed operation of a vehicle. Anthony Pizzuto said his brother
was taking methadone, a drug used to curb cravings for heroin, and
that he worked as a janitor and delivery man for the New York City
school district.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend in jail, Pizzuto was taken to the hospital
Monday, apparently after suffering a seizure. A source at the
Nassau County Medical Center who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said Pizzuto had at least two seizures while at the
hospital, one in the emergency room when he was first admitted and
another in the prison ward in the hours before his death.
</P>
</TEXT>
