A6148 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-16 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PROSECUTORS URGE SENATE TO REMOVE CLINTON AND TURN TO GORE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors urged the Senate Saturday to
remove President Clinton from office and sought to reassure
lawmakers that Vice President Al Gore would be ``waiting outside
the door'' to take over as president.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican prosecutors said the Senate should take the
unprecedented action because of Clinton's ``willful, premeditated
deliberate corruption'' of the nation's legal system during the
cover-up of his sexual dalliance with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The House last month impeached Clinton for perjury and
obstruction of justice. If the 100-member Senate convicts him by a
two-thirds vote, Clinton is automatically removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, argued that if the Senate fails to convict Clinton, the
presidency will have been ``deeply, and perhaps permanently
damaged'' in ``an unprecedented and unacceptable way.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors acknowledged for the first time that the
Senate faces a stiff political challenge as it weighs whether to
oust a popular president who has been elected twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking you to remove a popular president,'' conceded
Rep. Lindsay Graham, R-S.C. ``To set aside an election is a very
scary thought in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graham insisted the Senate can remove Clinton immediately to
``cleanse'' the presidency without provoking a constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president will be waiting outside the doors of this
chamber,'' Graham said. ``If that vice president is asked to come
in and assume the mantle of chief executive officer of the land,
chief law enforcement officer of the land, it will be tough, it
will be painful, but we will survive and we will be better for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., also cited Gore, for a different
purpose. Canady reminded senators that Gore, a Senate veteran when
he joined Clinton on the Democratic ticket in 1992, voted to
impeach federal Judge Claiborne for tax evasion in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Canady quoted Gore's statement at the time: ``It is incumbent
upon the Senate to fulfill its constitutional responsibility and
strip this man of his title.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican prosecutors also raised questions about Clinton's
ability to lead the nation's armed forces and to represent the
nation abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Stephen E. Buyer, R-Ind., a former Army lawyer called to
active duty during the Persian Gulf War who later ran for Congress,
said the nation's armed forces look to the commander-in-chief to
``exhibit the traits that inspire those who must risk their lives
at his command.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyer added that Clinton's ``own self-inflicted wounds have
called his credibility into question.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, in his summation, said Clinton's breach of ``trust'' with
the American people jeopardizes the ability of nations around the
world to trust the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental trust between America and the world can be
broken if a presidential perjurer represents our country in world
affairs,'' Hyde warned the Senate. ``And, because the executive
plays so large a role in representing the country to the world,
America can no longer be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also invoked the sacrifice of American GIs buried in
Arlington Cemetery, in the U.S. cemetery overlooking the D-Day
beaches in Normandy and the names of the dead etched into the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we keep faith with them?'' Hyde asked, urging the
Senate to remove Clinton. ``We work to make this country the kind
of America they were willing to die for ... an America where the
idea of sacred honor still has the power to stir men's souls.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defense begins in earnest in the Senate on Tuesday
with his team of lawyers opening the first of three days of counter
arguments. The next dramatic showdown in the struggle between the
GOP Congress and the Democratic chief executive takes place Tuesday
evening at 9 p.m., when Clinton is scheduled to deliver his annual
State of the Union address to a joint meeting of the House and
Senate on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican senators indicated their awareness of the
historical dimensions surrounding the question of whether to remove
a president from office for the first time in American history.
President Richard M. Nixon resigned in 1974 before a Senate trial
on House impeachment charges. President Andrew Johnson avoided
ouster by a single vote in his impeachment trial in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said the Senate would only move to
remove the president ``if the case holds together'' and a
bipartisan consensus builds to a ``vote way beyond any partisan
calculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith added: ``Knowing the popular will, I'd be very relieved if
the president's lawyers could present reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said he was not sure ``if the
country is ever ready for that sort of thing,'' adding: ``That is
``why this is such a gritty, difficult process for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House sought to fuel such concerns. Gregory Craig, the
White House lawyer leading Clinton's battle against impeachment,
emerged from Saturday's proceedings to insist that House
prosecutors failed to make the case for ``nullifying the results of
a national election.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig added: ``The House Republicans' case ends as it began _ an
unsubstantiated circumstantial case that does not meet the
constitutional standard to remove the president from office.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., remain at odds over fast-forwarding
Senate preparations to hear the witnesses sought by House
prosecutors. Lott suggested a bipartisan panel of senators to
``resolve in advance'' arrangements for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle countered, in the leaders' exchange of letters, that
creating such a panel now would ``violate the bipartisan
agreement'' on the timetable for consideration of witnesses that
was reached on Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle added: ``It is my hope that such arrangements will
ultimately prove unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is scheduled to take up the question of witnesses on
Jan. 25, with a majority vote of 51 senators required to call a
witness. Republicans hold 55 seats; Democrats hold 45 seats.
</P>
<P>
   To muster the 67 votes needed to remove Clinton from office,
Republicans would have to remain unified and enlist 12 Democratic
defectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
