<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-1STL     01-16 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGING STANDARD CAN HELP HOUSE IN FUTURE IMPEACHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds: Sub to include updated material) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When 100 senators vote on President Clinton's fate,
perhaps by the end of the month, they will fashion their own
definitions of high crimes and misdemeanors, the constitutional
standard for removing a president.
</P>
<P>
   And, in so doing, a standard will emerge that the House can
weigh the next time it considers impeaching a president and sending
the case to trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Described by late 19th-century historian James Bryce as ``the
heaviest piece of artillery in the congressional arsenal,''
impeachment has never before been fully employed against an elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon short-circuited the process by resigning in 1974
and Andrew Johnson, who survived the only other Senate trial by one
vote in 1868, took power after Abraham Lincoln was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't visit an issue once every century and a half and
feel that you are comfortable with it,'' said Sen. Dick Durbin,
D-Illinois. ``We have some guidance but certainly not a body of law
to turn to. I hope we don't have another impeachment trial for
another century, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, who finished their opening presentation
Saturday, argue that the presidency has been weakened by Clinton's
acknowledged misbehavior in the wake of his consensual extramarital
affair and that not removing him from office will make future
presidents untouchable by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar will be so high that only a convicted felon or a
traitor will need to be concerned,'' the prosecutors said. ``If
this is not enough, what is?''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which begins making its case Tuesday, contends
that removing Clinton on the evidence outlined by the House would
``substantially alter the delicate constitutional balance'' between
the Congress and the nation's chief executive. It would lower the
bar to a point where presidents could remain in office ``only at
the pleasure of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Constitutional experts dismiss these arguments as hyperbole
largely because of how the impeachment process is structured and
because there are never any assurances that whatever standard
emerges from Senate deliberations will be used by the House the
next time it calls for removal of the nation's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``While comity certainly is something we encourage and expect in
relations between the House and Senate, there is no constitutional
obligation for one to follow the expressed wishes of the other,''
said Victor Rosenblum, a law professor at Northwestern University.
``Each case is new as it arises.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment was written into the Constitution more than two
centuries ago as a way of reining in corrupt chief executives,
Cabinet members and federal judges. The Senate was picked by the
founding fathers to try impeachment cases because it was believed
to be less susceptible to popular passions than the House.
</P>
<P>
   The two-step process _ impeachment by a House majority, trial by
the Senate with a two-thirds vote required for conviction _ has
been used 14 times in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton _ the nation's 42nd president _ faces two articles of
impeachment, which were approved in close to a party-line vote by
the House four weeks ago. The articles allege that Clinton
committed perjury and obstructed justice in trying to hide his
White House affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already we've seen a lowering of the standard for
impeachment,'' said Bruce J. Schulman, a history professor at
Boston University. ``If Clinton is removed, then we will have
established a precedent for removing a president from office for
misconduct, which we've never done before. It will alter the
balance between the branches'' of government.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Bond, a political science professor at Texas A&AMP;M University,
said the bar for impeachment ``has been lowered by the House, but
by how much depends on how you weigh the other two cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was impeached largely because of disagreements with
radical House Republicans over reconstruction policies toward the
states of the former confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Nixon grew out of hearings pushed by
congressional Democrats that unearthed presidential misuse of
federal agencies and a conspiracy to cover up administration
involvement in the Watergate burglary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scales are imprecise. ... The Clinton case is between
those two types, but closer to the Johnson end in terms of
partisanship,'' Bond said. ``If we want to preserve this system of
government with its separation of powers, it's equal branches of
government, what we can hope for is that the Senate will dismiss
this case fairly quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although conventional wisdom holds that the Senate will come up
short of the 67 votes needed to convict Clinton and terminate his
presidency, no one expected his sexual misbehavior with a woman
half his age to snowball into a Senate trial while two-thirds of
the public approves of his job performance.
</P>
<P>
   While some pundits call the Clinton scandal and impeachment a
constitutional crisis, Ross Baker of Rutgers University dismisses
the characterization. ``A constitutional crisis occurs when the 2nd
Infantry shows up on the west lawn of the Capitol,'' Baker said.
``What we have going on in Washington is the normal functioning of
a process proscribed in the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the Senate's decision on Clinton's fate cannot be
appealed, the entire imbroglio ``has its costs,'' said Baker, a
political science professor. ``If the Republicans are determined
that the president must be removed from office, and he's as popular
as Clinton is, and people remember that in 2000, Congress will be
punished in the elections. It's one of the checks and balances
built into our system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of the checks against abuse of power is the requirement
that both the House and Senate vote to remove a president.
``Presumably, the two-part system of impeachment (by the House) and
Senate trial is designed to winnow out the frivolous
impeachments,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The first chance the 55 Republican and 45 Democratic senators
have to signal their intentions on Clinton's case will come Jan.
25, when they will consider motions to dismiss the case or to
proceed and summon witnesses, which are to be decided by majority
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and most Senate Democrats fear live testimony
will drag out the trial and could dredge up more damaging evidence
against Clinton. Some Republicans insist, however, that only a
full-scale trial with witnesses such as Lewinsky will do. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
