<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL LOOKS TO IMF FOR MORE RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BRAZIL-ECON) 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Brazil's Finance Minister began talks here
Saturday with the International Monetary Fund and said he might ask
for early release of the next round of international assistance to
the country to help stabilize its economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Minister, Pedro Malan, spoke a day after Brazil
dropped efforts to defend the value of its currency, raising fears
of another bout of global financial turmoil and economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   IMF officials said they had no comment on the meetings Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Malan and other members of Brazil's delegation will also meet on
Sunday with Clinton administration officials, including Deputy
Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, to review plans for
addressing Brazil's economic problems and carrying out a strategy
for managing its currency, the real.
</P>
<P>
   Malan said Brazil would unveil a new approach to stabilizing the
currency on Monday. Options range from allowing the real to float
in response to market forces, creating a range of values that the
government would try to maintain, to fixing the currency at a
specified level.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the United States and the fund have made clear
that they will press Brazil to take rapid steps to reduce its huge
budget deficit through tax increases and spending cuts as a first
step toward restoring international confidence. The faltering pace
of efforts to improve the country's fiscal condition was behind the
intense market pressure to devalue the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Malan reiterated that President Fernando Enrique Cardoso
remained committed to the fiscal program Brazil agreed on with the
fund, despite intense political opposition at home. Doubts about
Cardoso's ability to carry out the program came to a head this
month when the new governor of Brazil's second-largest state, Minas
Gerais, imposed a moratorium on his state's payments to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   About $9 billion of the $41.5 billion aid package to Brazil has
been disbursed, and $9 billion more could be released next month if
the fund and donor nations, including the United States, agree that
Brazil is making progress toward its fiscal goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
