<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MLK-STREETS _ A reporter visits MLK drives, boulevard and
streets throughout Georgia (Fort Valley, Albany, Darien, Macon,
Savannah) to see how MLK's name is used and honored. What do the
street signs say about the legacy of the civil rights movement,
40-plus years after King vaulted into national prominence with the
Montgomery bus boycott? (Osinski, Atlanta Journal-Constitution),
50. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/KING _ As he rode the streets of Selma, Ala., in 1975, a
camera in his hands, John Hindsman grew inspired. He was a black
man who grew up on a Georgia plantation in the 1920s, when the law
and the lash made a pipe dream of equality, but he left the South
for Dayton as a young man and stayed on the sidelines of the civil
rights movement. Yet on that spring day in Selma, he knew how he
could do his part. He could photograph every place where Martin
Luther King Jr. _ whom Hindsman had met in his long-ago Southern
days _ had taken his crusade for justice. (Keilman, Dayton Daily
News). 50. WITH PHOTOS (Several of Hindsman's photographs plus a
portrait of him). MOVED FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-WORD _ CONCORD, N.H. _ From high-profile lobbyists
and politicians to low-profile operatives who can deliver votes,
Bush backers in New Hampshire are eagerly awaiting word from
Austin. The right word can put a presidential campaign machine into
operation almost overnight. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
50. EDs: Moving in (a) general news category.
</P>
<P>
   w/TEXAS-INAUG-GUIDE _ AUSTIN _ Everything you need to know about
Tuesday's festivities at the Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The parade route, what will be in the parade, what time to
arrive. Street closings and parking, Seating info. Ticket info.
List of public inaugural events. What is a ``Texas Tux'' is and how
to wear one. What will the weather likely be. The oath. Plus, how
much the governor's salary is. A quiz for readers. A box comparing
President Bush's inauguration with this one. (Santos, Austin
American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS. EDs: Moving in (l) lifestyle
category.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-GACASES _ Overhauling welfare was meant to get people
off of aid and onto someone's payroll. But Georgia's shrinking
caseload, which dropped from about 114,000 when the overhaul began
to 73,000 by June 1998, isn't the sole result of people finding
jobs, numbers show. The lower numbers also resulted from fewer
people applying for welfare and the state turning away more
applicants, according to statistics reported to the federal welfare
agency by the Department of Human Resources, which operates
Georgia's welfare program. (Oglesby, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
32. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POPE _ MEXICO CITY _ Pope John Paul II will visit Mexico
City for four days beginning Fri., Jan. 22. And with no clear
agenda released yet by the Vatican, Mexicans wonder if the pope
will address human rights, poverty and the economy, religious
competition, abortion -- or even drug trafficking -- during his
visit. The visit marks the closure of a bishops' conference on
challenges to the Catholic church in the Americas. In addition to
church business, however, the frail Catholic leader often comments
on broader questions of social policy. A Catholic Diocese in
Mexico's Southern Chiapas state, is hoping the Pope will take on
the Mexican government and the long-simmering Chiapas conflict,
which has led to the expulsion and imprisonment of Catholic
priests. The Diocese may present a report to the Pope claiming that
Chiapas' poor and Indian populations are victims of human rights
violations, haphazard free-market economic policies and the
corruption of drug traffickers. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   w/CUBA-POPE _ HAVANA, Cuba _ It's been one year since Pope John
Paul II made his historic visit to Cuba. The visit brought a new
atmosphere of openness and reform to Cuba's one-party Marxist
society. But the church and the state are still in a tug-of-war
over just how much religious freedom should be allowed on the
island. While Cuba has released some political prisoners and has
granted visas for some foreign priests, the church remains closely
restricted by the state. We'll talk to church officials in Cuba and
in the United States to examine the events of the last year.
(Emling, Cox News Service). EDs: Photos to be placed in the
International folder on the Cox Server. EDs: Moving by noon Friday.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-BOX _ MEXICO CITY _ The travels of Pope John Paul II.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). EDs: Moving by noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week of Jan. 15. The
layout is now available on the Cox server in the International
folder slugged CoxNet FOCUS 0115)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-REED _ LONDON _ A story on the plans that London-based
Reed Elsevier has for Lexis-Nexis of Dayton, Ohio. More Tk.
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/REED-BOX _ LONDON _ A primer on Reed Elsevier; with data
suitable for a graphic. (Roughton, Cox News Service). EDS: Photos
to be placed in the International and Financial folders on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: The Dayton Daily News will place a graphic in the
International folder of the Cox Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   BASSHOTELS _ Bass Hotels is undergoing a lot of changes: moving
several top executives to London, focusing on international brands,
and focusing more on opporunities outside the industry, including
vacation ownerships and assisted living facilities. We talk to
Chairman Thomas Oliver and vice chair Craig Hunt about the outlook
for the company, the industry. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JANUARYSLUMP _With the new year under way, many people have
returned to work only to find that halfway through January, they're
still trying to shake off the holiday doldrums. But some find it
harder to shake off than the extra weight they may have put on.
This slump is psychological, physical, and seasonal, industrial
psychologists say. Cold temperatures and shorter days, less
sullight, aren't helping. How do you get back into the swing of
things? No. 1, make sure you're in a job you like, experts say.
Story w/ tipbox on how to motivate yourself. What management can do
to help motivate sluggish workers? (Conwell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   THARPE-COLUMN _ Think you know a lot about sports? Then answer
this: Why do professional athletes generally earn more than farmers
and steelworkers? Before answering, you need to understand it's an
economic question that was asked in a recent survey of consumers by
the Minneapolis Federal Reserve Bank. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-TAXES _ Interest is growing in a first-class way to save
for a college education and defer taxes on those investments.
Hundreds of thousands of families now pour their money into the
plans, turning over the investment decisions to others in return
for tax deferred earnings. The strategy has some risks, as does
anything in life. But it has some uncommonly attractive features,
too. Georgia does not have such a plan, but Peach State residents
can enroll in the plans sponsored by New York, New Hampshire,
Delaware and a handful of other states. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-ADVICE _ Ken Chenault, president of American Express and
arguably the highest ranking African American in corporate America,
had some special
</P>
<P>
   encouragement for students at Clark Atlanta last week. It's time
to quit worrying about the attitudes of racists and others who
stand in their way. The simple alternative, he said, to do your
best, associate with smart and ambitious people, regardless of race
and push hard to make contributions. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-WEB _ The good thing about the Internet also is the bad
thing, if you're a parent. There is information on almost any topic
you can name out there for the taking. So parents often face this
worry: Do I let my kids have full use of the Web and take a chance
that they'll run into adult material or violence or even strangers
who are dangerous? Or do I shield them from all that and take the
chance that they won't do as well at school as their friends who do
use the Internet. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS _ U.S. Savings Bonds, an old-fashioned investment, have
gone electronic. Although they pay rates of return below most
private investments, millions have been purchased over the years
because of their simplicity as an investment and because of their
Uncle Sam-guaranteed safety. But for many would-be investors in the
past, there was a problem: How to buy Savings Bonds. They could buy
them through a bank or broker, or through payroll deduction at
work. But about 120 million Americans worked for companies without
payroll deduction for the bonds. Last month, the U.S. Treasury
initiated the EasySaver Plan for Savings Bonds, which allows
investors to buy the bonds by authorizing the agency to deduct a
set amount each month from their checking account to pay for them.
(Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
