<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-PITT-NYT &LR;      01-16 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-PITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, PITTSBURGH IS NO THREAT TO UCONN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ This time, there was no need for dramatics, no
cause for scoring 5 points in the final 10 seconds and almost no
point in watching the second half at all.
</P>
<P>
   Just one month after Pittsburgh gave No. 1 Connecticut its
toughest test of the undefeated season, the Panthers lost to the
Huskies on Saturday the way most of the others have this season:
without much of a fight and looking befuddled. The final score was
81-58, but this game was over long before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Those who watched as Connecticut (15-0, 7-0) pulled out an
emotional, nail-biting 1-point victory before hostile fans at
Pittsburgh on Dec. 12 perhaps thought Saturday's game would have be
a classic rematch, full of running and gunning by two of the Big
East's fastest teams.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the first game's dramatics were such that they were
punctuated by a chest-thumping victory dance atop the scorer's
table by the Huskies' Khalid El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, which beat Kentucky early in the season, has never
recovered its confidence since the devastating loss to UConn and
has dropped to 9-7 with just one victory in six Big East games. The
16,294 fans at the Hartford Civic Center saw a deflated Pittsburgh
team , its tentativeness showing almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, who did not arrive until 1:15 a.m. Saturday
because of weather-related travel difficulties, never got into an
offensive rhythm. Under Connecticut's pressure defense, the
Panthers struggled to keep a handle on the ball and rarely got a
good look at the basket from close in, putting up terrible shots
and shooting just 29.4 percent from the field and 1 of 8 from the
3-point arc in the first half. They did not break the 20-point mark
until 2 minutes 55 seconds were left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun praised his team's defensive
effort, particularly center Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to the rim and he is in the game, you're going
to have to go through him,'' Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were slowed from establishing their fleet-footed
game by Pitt's foul-laden first half. The Panthers had 10 fouls by
7:32 of the game and the Huskies went to the line 20 times to
Pitt's 4 in the first half, Connecticut shot just 41.9 percent from
the field and showed just enough of its dominating game to put
together a 14-0 run that sank Pitt into a 20-point hole with 4
minutes left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Connecticut's early highlight reel plays came back to
back when Richard Hamilton, who was shut out in the first half,
sent a perfect bounce pass into Voskuhl for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, after Pittsburgh failed on two awful shots,
Hamilton grabbed the rebound and launched an outlet pass to
El-Amin, already running for the fast break. He sent a pass back to
Kevin Freeman in the lane for a monstrous dunk that opened the lead
to 25-11 with 7:51 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team can beat you in a lot of different ways,''
Pittsburgh Coach Ralph Willard said.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any link between the games these teams played this
season against each other, it was sophomore guard Albert Mouring.
In the first game, he hit the 3-pointer with 9seconds left to close
Pittsburgh's lead to 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he was the leading scorer in the first half with 13
points, including three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   How inept was Pittsburgh? Even after it quickly scored 6 points
in 25 seconds with 2:55 left in the first half, the Panthers still
trailed by 14. Calhoun had pre-game concerns that his team was
perhaps being lulled into overconfidence by the ease of its
victories. But that seemed to be the sign of coach struggling to
find something to worry about in what has all the marks of being a
magical season.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Connecticut was able to use play its
wide-open offense more to inflate the lead to 28 points. So
multifaceted is Connecticut's attack that even when Hamilton, a
player of the year candidate, is held to only 5 points, there is no
reason to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl had 14 points and 12 rebounds, El-Amin had 17 points and
Mouring had a career-high 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies led in every statistical category: free throws
attempted (an astounding 35 to 6 margin), second-chance points (21
to 12) and points in the paint (40 to 32).
</P>
<P>
   There were no dramatics this time. The only concern was Calhoun
fretting that his team appeared to be running up the score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
