<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 1/16/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 16, 1999 -- UTILITY-SOCIALWORK, 1-16 --
Joy Chatel, left, in her beauty parlor, meeting with Kristen Yontz,
an employee of Brooklyn Union Gas who helps Ms. Chatel pay off her
debts. Ms. Yontz is not a bill collector. She is a social worker,
part of the utility's experiment in getting people to pay their
bills by helping them straighten out their lives. ``The goal is to
teach people not to live in crisis, and maybe learn different
behavior so they are not living crisis to crisis,'' says Ms. Yontz.
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- IMPEACH-EAGLES-ALEXANDER, 1-16 --
With the presidency on his mind, Lamar Alexander went a-courting
donors and a-wooing photographers at The Breakers, a palatial
Italian Renaissance resort in Palm Beach on Wednesday. Alexander
knows he must do whatever he can to get his mug in the newspaper as
he struggles to stand out in an increasingly crowded field. (Cindy
Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Jan. 16, 1999 -- IMPEACH-EAGLES, 1-16
-- Four Republicans, from left, Ron Foster, Dan MacNamara, Peter
Flynn and Lake Coulson, during a golf tournament at The Breakers, a
palatial Italian Renaissance resort in Palm Beach. For years
Republicans, have been accused of using private retreats to buy
access to the powerful. Whether or not that is the case, it is
clear from meetings at lavish resorts like The Breakers, that the
party goes out of its way to pamper its most reliable -- and
altruistic -- backers. (Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 16, 1999 -- IMPEACH-RDP, 1-16 -- Sen.
John D. Rockefeller IV, Democrat of West Virginia, rushing up the
Capitol steps Saturday morning moments before the resumption of the
presentation of arguments by House members calling for the removal
of President Clinton in his impeachment trial in the Senate
chamber. Some Democrats say they are growing increasingly convinced
that Senate Republicans want to call witnesses simply to embarrass
President Clinton and draw out the trial. (Shana Raab/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Jan. 16, 1999 -- IMPEACH-ROSS, 1-16
-- Edmund Pitt Ross of Albuquerque, N.M., displays a portrait of
his great grandfather, Edmund G. Ross, who was a Senator from
Kansas. In American political legend, Sen. Ross chose personal ruin
rather than betray his principles, defying his party leadership in
voting to acquit President Andrew Johnson during the last
presidential impeachment, in 1868. If he had voted the other way,
American history might have been much different. (Steve Northup/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAC DU FLAMBEAU, Wis. -- - Jan. 16, 1999 --
INDIAN-RETURN, 1-16 -- Carl Edwards, a Chippewa Indian, on his
tribal reservation in Wisconsin. Edwards, 34, is part of a growing
number of Indians who are returning to their reservations after
having left in the early 1980s for jobs elsewhere. The growth of
tribal gambling, which has created thousands of jobs on
reservations, has meant homecomings for people like Edwards. ``I
grew up on that hill across the road,'' says Edwards. ``I know what
life on the reservation can mean.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SANTA ROSA DE AGUAN, Honduras -- Jan. 16, 1999 --
HONDURAS-HURRICANE-3, 1-16 -- Hurricane Mitch, which raked the
small Honduran town of Santa Rosa de Aguan, killed the husband and
three of the children of Mirtha Martinez Arriola, left, who
recently returned to her wrecked home with the support of a cousin,
Catalina Arzu. ``I would like to go far from here, to forget all
this,'' she says. ``Somewhere where there is a future.'' (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SANTA ROSA DE AGUAN, Honduras -- Jan. 16, 1999 --
HONDURAS-HURRICANE-2, 1-16 -- Otto Ricardo Lopez on the shore,
watching waves lap close to where his house once stood. Half of
this coastal village of 6,000 people -- more than 80 houses -- was
swept out to sea or submerged under the engorged River Aguan during
three days of flooding when Hurricane Mitch struck Honduras more
than two months ago. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SANTA ROSA DE AGUAN, Honduras -- Jan. 16, 1999 --
HONDURAS-HURRICANE-1, 1-16 -- In Santa Rosa de Aguan, a small
Honduran town devasted by the wrath of Hurricane Mitch, Hilda
Arriola Arouz, 67, paddles a disabled launch to go shopping.
Although she puts on a brave face, Mrs. Arriola Arouz, a widow,
says it is hard to confront each new day. ``Most days I pass in
sadness, because all the grandchildren that I lost during the
hurricane lived most of the time in my house. Now I'm sad and there
is nothing but this sadness.'' (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
