<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-2NDLD-W     01-16 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS END PRESENTATION WITH CALL FOR CLINTON'S REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for extensive rewriting in 1st take, with new reporting. Four
new grafs at end of 2nd take. Expands by 300 words.)  (See also IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK, IMPEACH-EAGLES,
IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP, DOWD-COLUMN,
EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW, IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES, IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER) 
(mk) 
 By R.W. APPLE JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Summarizing the Republican case against President
Clinton in a speech evoking the shades of heroes past, Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., said Saturday afternoon that the presidency could be
``permanently damaged'' if the Senate failed to remove Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``My solitary, solitary hope is that a hundred years from today,
people will look back at what we have done and say, `They kept the
faith,''' Hyde, the chief prosecutor, declared in an
emotion-drenched peroration.
</P>
<P>
   The argument over impeachment, Hyde said one last time, was not
about sex but about ``the rule of law'' _ ``one of the great
achievements of our civilization.'' He accused Clinton of fraying
the essential bonds of trust between those who govern the United
States and those who are governed. And he asserted that having ``a
presidential perjurer'' in the White House meant that ``America can
no longer be trusted'' in the world's councils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your judgment should rise above politics, above partisanship,
above polling data,'' Hyde told the Senate. ``This case is a test
of whether what the Founding Fathers described as `sacred honor'
still has meaning in our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., brought the Republican case to a
crescendo Saturday morning with the declaration that the president
must be removed because he had ``made himself a notorious example
of lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening the last of three days of the Republican presentation of
the impeachment case against Clinton, Canady, like Clinton a
graduate of Yale Law School, also argued that the Senate could not
set a lower standard for a president than for judges who have been
ousted in recent years for making false statements under oath.
Clinton is accused in one impeachment article of committing perjury
in his testimony to the grand jury investigating his sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, it will be Clinton's turn to make his case through
his lawyers, starting on Tuesday, hours before his State of the
Union Message.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's speech was a stemwinder from another era, a florid
20-minute throwback to the days of perfervid orators like William
Jennings Bryan _ moving to some in the chamber and no doubt outside
it, banal to others. Stocky and silver-haired, sometimes seemingly
on the verge of choking up, Hyde pulled out every stop on the
rhetorical organ, recalling Bunker Hill and Flanders Field and
Normandy, Saigon and Desert Storm, the Ten Commandments and Magna
Carta, Mosaic law and Roman law, the Gettysburg address and the
Spirit of '76.
</P>
<P>
   He complained about what he called ``massive and relentless
efforts to change the subject'' by the president's lawyers, and he
said it was a disservice to the House to suggest, as some Democrats
have, that ``it has brought these articles of impeachment before
you in a frivolous, mean-spirited or irresponsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Hyde read a letter from William Summers, a 13-year-old
third-grader in Room 304 at Chase Elementary School in Chicago, who
asked him, ``If you cannot believe the president, who can you
believe? If you have no one to believe in, then how do you run your
life?''
</P>
<P>
   Canady and two colleagues on the panel of House managers, Reps.
Steve Buyer, R-Ind., and Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., sought to
pre-emptively rebut arguments of Clinton's defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Citing British and American authorities in a session that often
turned the Senate chamber into a constitutional history classroom,
they contended that the offenses Clinton is accused of, perjury and
obstruction of justice, met the constitutional standard of ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' for impeachment; that missteps in
Clinton's private life had led to crimes in his public capacity;
that the Senate had convicted judges in recent years for analogous
offenses, and that if Clinton was guilty he must not be allowed to
remain in the White House, as Canady put it, ``in all his infamy.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has argued from the start that even if guilty,
nothing Clinton did justified the removal from office of a popular
president, twice endorsed by a national electorate. It was that
argument, which Buyer termed the ``so-what'' argument, that the
three sought to nail today.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer (pronounced BOO-yer) attacked on a number of levels at
once, urging the senators not to give way to any of several double
standards.
</P>
<P>
   In response to those who note that perjury, unlike treason and
bribery, is not enumerated in the Constitution among ``high crimes
and misdemeanors,'' Buyer cited Sir William Blackstone, the great
18th-century English jurist whose book of legal commentaries, James
Madison wrote, was ``in every man's hand'' as the constitutional
draftsmen went about their labors.
</P>
<P>
   Blackstone, Buyer said, included perjury among his list of
public offenses, placing bribery and perjury side by side. From
there, he jumped to the assertion that ``there is no difference''
between ``sitting before a federal judge and perjuring oneself''
and offering that judge a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging widely, Buyer quoted Black's Legal Dictionary, Gen.
Douglas MacArthur, John Adams and, on the seriousness of perjury
and obstruction of justice, former Attorney General Griffin Bell, a
Democrat. Bell, he said, had reached the heart of the matter when
he declared, ``A president cannot faithfully execute the laws if he
himself is breaking them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now at least 115 persons serving sentences for
perjury in federal prisons,'' Buyer said. ``Where is the fairness
to these Americans, if they stay in jail and the president stays in
the Oval Office?''
</P>
<P>
   But Buyer laid special emphasis, of a kind that had not been
heard in the trial before, on the impact of Clinton's alleged
crimes on the armed services and women.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats continued to insist that the whole controversy
stemmed from a private sexual matter, and was therefore beneath
constitutional notice, Buyer demanded, did that mean that the
evidence-gathering process in federal sexual harassment cases, like
the one brought against Clinton by Paula Corbin Jones, which led to
the Lewinsky case, was unimportant?
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of The Citadel, the South Carolina military college,
and a veteran of the Persian Gulf war, Buyer argued that Clinton's
``diminished veracity'' had had an ``inherently corrosive'' effect
on his capacity to function effectively as commander in chief and
to carry out his foreign policy duties.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Buyer said, American military personnel everywhere
``know that, if accused of the same offenses as their commander in
chief, they would no longer be deserving of the privilege of
serving in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, much the folksiest of the 13 managers, was assigned to
explore Senate precedent, and he did so. He dutifully noted that
Judge Harry Claiborne of Nevada had been removed in 1986, for
filing a false income-tax return ``under penalties of perjury.'' He
noted that Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi had been removed in
1989, for lying to a grand jury about his efforts to fix a friend's
son's case in state court. And he noted that Judge Alcee Hastings
of Florida had been removed, also in 1989, for perjury and
conspiracy to obtain a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
