<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH17-COX     01-16 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House sums up case for conviction
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has so damaged the presidency and
broken faith with the public that the Senate must convict him,
House Republican prosecutors said Saturday as they wrapped up their
case in the nation's second presidential impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Clinton a ``presidential perjurer,'' Rep. Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.) warned that acquitting Clinton of charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice could permanently injure the presidency and
damage the nation's reputation abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is an office of trust,'' said Hyde, chairman of
the House Judiciary Committee, which evaluated the evidence amassed
against Clinton. ``To break that covenant of trust is to dissolve
the mortar that binds the foundation stones of our freedom into a
secure and solid edifice.''
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of presenting their case, the prosecutors
focused on morality and the Senate's duty to carry out the
impeachment process, rather than on the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not tolerate one law for the ruler and one for the
ruled,'' Hyde said in arguing for convicting the president of lying
under oath and obstructing justice in an effort to conceal his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinksy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us be clear: The vote you are asked to cast is, in the
final analysis, a vote about the rule of law,'' Hyde said. ``For
the alternative to the rule of law is the rule of raw power.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, and some Democrats, in the Senate said they were
impressed by the case put on by the House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tied all the bits and pieces systematically together,''
said Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.). But he added that he expected an
``ardent defense'' of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors put on a ``strong case and raised some
very serious issues,'' said Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) ``When you
see it unrebutted, it has a force to it, but I think we have to
wait and hear from the other side before making a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) was among several Democrats who were
unimpressed by the final day of argument from the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I thought was tedious and, ultimately, it got
defensive,'' Cleland said. He described Hyde's statement as ``a
good Rotary Club speech, but a weak argument for impeaching the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers will begin their presentation on
Tuesday, the same day Clinton is scheduled to give the State of the
Union address to a joint session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Once the defense finishes its presentations, senators will get
to question both sides, most likely next weekend. The White House
is then expected to move to dismiss the charges. At that point, the
Senate will decide whether to move forward by calling witnesses or
end the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 senators on Saturday appeared no closer to resolving the
contentious issue of whether to call witnesses. It is a divide that
appears to split mostly along partisan lines, with Democratic
senators opposing it and Republican senators saying it would
clarify disputed facts.
</P>
<P>
   The big question of the day was whether Clinton would be invited
to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as a country we should invite the president,'' said
Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
``There are significant contradictions that must be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has the right to require the president to appear, but
it would not likely do so, said Hatch and other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And invitation or no invitation, the president still can invoke
his Fifth Amendment right not to incriminate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Buyer (R-Ind.) led off the day's orations, saying the
president's offenses ``assault the administration of justice.'' And
upholding justice, Buyer argued, is an essential element of the
prosecution's case because without confidence in the judicial
system society cannot avoid the abuse of power by politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer told senators that viewing the Clinton sex scandal and
cover up as merely an illicit affair, ``demeans our civil rights
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What message does that send to the women in America?'' Buyer
said, raising the specter that Clinton's acquittal also would
threaten protections for minorities and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The senators began to visibly relax when Rep. Lindsey Graham
(R-S.C.) began his presentation. In a folksy manner, reminiscent of
Clinton's own way of reaching out to audiences, Graham left the
podium to speak to the senators, often looking at them eye to eye.
He spoke without notes and told stories about his own upbringing in
the South during the Civil Rights era.
</P>
<P>
   Graham recalled how blacks were banned from walking inside his
parents' ``beer joint'' for no reason other than that was ``the way
it is.'' It would be a ``travesty,'' Graham said, if that same
reason were used to excuse the president's action toward Paula
Jones, the former Arkansas employee who alleged the president
sexually harassed her. It was Jones' lawsuit that touched off a
chain of events that brought forth the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   In making his case, Graham drew out the details of the
impeachment of three federal judges who were removed from the
bench, in part for lying under oath. He said the American people
would be well served by removing the president, and that the
country would survive if that happened.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady of Florida spent most of his time quoting
historians and politicians such as Alexander Hamilton to back up
his allegation that high crimes and misdemeanors have been
committed.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting John Jay, the first chief justice of the United States
Supreme Court, Canady said there is ``no crime more extensively
pernicious to society'' than perjury because it undermines the
faith the public has in the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The president should be removed from office, Canady asserted,
and the senate should not be influenced by Clinton's popularity and
the argument made by several prominent historians that the
institution of the presidency would be damaged if Clinton is forced
out.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the presentation was left to Hyde, whose 27-minute
speech about trust, honor and duty took senators to three military
cemeteries and included a letter from a Chicago third-grader who
suggested that Clinton write a 100-word essay as punishment for
telling lies.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde and Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.), who preceded the
white-haired chairman, also took issue with those who have branded
the House Republicans ``Clinton-haters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said, ``I must tell you, distinguished senators, that this
impeachment is not...a question of hating anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House was unmoved by the impassioned plea for
removing Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three uninterrupted days...they have failed to meet
their burden,'' White House lawyer Gregory Craig said following
Hyde's summation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
