<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES17-C     01-16 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WITNESSES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Push for live witnesses grows stronger
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before House prosecutors had put the final
flourishes on their three-day presentation accusing President
Clinton of high crimes and misdemeanors, several prominent Senate
Democrats were already asserting they had heard nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Republican prosecutors may not have changed many
Democratic minds about the allegations against Clinton, they appear
to have made great strides toward achieving their most crucial
short-term goal: convincing enough Senate Republicans that they
must hear from live witnesses to reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Several wavering Republican senators, who had previously said
they were dubious about the prospect of witnesses, said they are
now convinced that they are a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now increasingly of the view that if the president's
lawyers don't' stipulate to the facts, live witnesses are the only
way to proceed,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one who was skeptical about witnesses,'' said Sen.
Robert Bennett (R-Utah). ``As I go through this, I'm moving towards
being in favor of the calling of witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though most Democrats have come out against witnesses,
a few, such as Sens. Bob Graham (D-Fla.), and Max Baucus (D-Mont.),
still refuse to rule out that witnesses will have to be called.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reluctance against witnesses, generally, in the
caucus,'' said Baucus. ``But I would also guess that there are some
senators who are reserving judgment on that issue, waiting to see
how things stack up and what the lay of the land is when we come to
that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors also appear to have succeeded in
ratcheting up the pressure on Clinton and his defense team, who
will open their case on behalf of the president Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who believes that a formidable case hasn't been made
just hasn't been listening,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), the
influential chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``It's
incumbent on the president to show where these facts are wrong.
They are going to have to explain why this isn't perjury. They are
going to have to explain why this isn't obstruction of justice.
They are going to have to explain why this isn't witness
tampering.'' Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas) said she wants the
White House to argue ``the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than just arguing what is impeachable, arguing the facts
on what was the perjury, what was the obstruction of justice is
important,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to have a point by point presentation and rebuttal
on the facts and the interpretation of the facts,'' said Graham,
who added that he was most troubled by the allegations that Clinton
may have sought to influence his personal secretary, Betty Currie,
to lie about Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their three days of presentations, the 13 House
prosecutors followed a two-track strategy. First, they sought to
make a compelling case that the president perjured himself and
obstructed justice in his efforts to conceal his relationship with
Lewinsky from Paula Jones in her federal sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they sought to show that there were enough discrepancies
between Clinton's grand jury testimony and that of Lewinsky,
Currie, and friend Vernon Jordan, that live testimony was the only
way find the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a normal criminal trial, the House prosecution does not
have the discretion to call witnesses. Under the Senate impeachment
rules, the Senate must vote to call witnesses by a simple majority
of 51 senators. Each witness will be voted on separately.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats number only 45 in the Senate, so they need at least
six Republicans to vote against witnesses _ assuming that no
Democrats vote to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one Republican moderate is still undecided. ``I'm
not there yet,'' said Sen. Olympia Snowe (R-Maine). ``I want to
hear the complete testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers have warned that calling witnesses will force
them to construct a far more extensive defense and drag out the
trial for months, an outcome that neither Republicans or Democrats
want.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett noted that under the Senate rules adopted before the
trial the calling of witnesses is actually a two-step process. The
Senate first votes to depose witnesses and then votes whether to
have them appear to give their testimony on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that while he may vote for the first step, he may
not then find the need for the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm inclined to allow them to take depositions on those
witnesses, but I will reserve the right as to whether or not we
actually call them until after I have read the depositions,''
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding factor for many Republicans on the question of
witnesses appears to be how much of the factual record presented by
House prosecutors will be disputed by Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton's lawyers accept the factual interpretation of the
case laid out by the prosecutors _ which appears unlikely _ then
some senators believe there will be no need for witnesses. But if
the lawyers' dispute the facts, then they only way to resolve the
differences will be through witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the president contests _ or his lawyers
contest facts in the case, argue that there are conflicts in the
testimony or that there is confusion in the testimony, the House
will have a stronger case in arguing the need for witnesses to
clarify those confusions,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl (R-Ariz.), one of
three Senate Republicans who have met with House prosecutors to
discuss the parameters for calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Republicans and Democrats won't begin discussing the
witness issue until at least Jan. 25, after senators have had an
opportunity to pose questions to House prosecutors and White House
defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Senate minority leader Tom Daschle (D-S.D.) on Friday again
rebuffed an invitation by majority leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) to
form a bi-partisan ``witness group'' to start negotiating the
parameters of witness testimony, saying such discussions should
only ocurr after the White House has presented its case and
senators have posed questions to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
