<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-IMPEACH17-COX     01-16 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-IMPEACH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The crucial balance between politics and perfection
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Notable for their stateliness, among the various
actors who took their place this week on the stage of impeachment,
were the Official Reporters of Debate.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't a term for the tribe of journalists who have spent
the week chasing senators through the marble halls of the Capitol
and down to the congressional subway, hoping to coax something
off-the-cuff from senators and House members grimly determined to
avoid the unguarded remark.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it refers to the federal employees who stand in the
middle aisle of the Senate, steno machines slung around their necks
like xylophone players in a high school band, recording every word
of the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Every 10 minutes, with storklike grace, a fresh stenographer
would step quietly into place beside his or her colleague in a
seamless pass-off, the thousands upon thousands of words spent on
this matter unrolling on narrow spools of white paper.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters of debate were the physical embodiment of a
concept invoked over and over again by the House managers who made
their case against Bill Clinton: history, and the tremendous
responsibility of those whose deliberations will become a part of
the historical record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has a serious problem,'' Rep. Lindsey Graham of
South Carolina told the senators Saturday. ``I don't want my
country to be the country of equivocators and compartmentalizers
for the next century. And that's what this is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the House managers who presented the case this week was
given a specific legal assignment. It seemed clear that when Graham
addressed the Senate he was fulfilling a political assignment as
well, one that is crucial to the Republicans' case.
</P>
<P>
   In a confiding, Southern voice which invited comparison to
Clinton himself, Graham acknowledged that this is a popular
president, one who has gained particular recognition for advancing
the cause of civil rights. Graham said he didn't know if he agreed
with the Supreme Court's decision to let the Paula Jones case go
forward while the president was in office, and that he might have
told the same lies Clinton did if he'd been caught in an
embarrassing affair.
</P>
<P>
   But by lying to a grand jury eight months later, Graham said,
Clinton placed his personal interests above the rule of law, so
that to protect the historical record from corruption, the
presidency must be ``cleansed.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's words bespoke an uneasy dance between distaste and
detachment that was evident in all the speakers who brought the
first phase of the impeachment trial to its conclusion Saturday.
They aggressively sought to paint the president's alleged offenses
as bad enough to merit his removal, while being aware the
appearance of spite would make that outcome unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Gekas of Pennsylvania assured the senators that when
the president comes to Congress on Tuesday night to give the State
of the Union address, he would honor the office Clinton holds by
standing to applaud. Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois, who
has seen his own embarrassing personal history dredged up as a
byproduct of this long scandal, admitted that no one in Congress is
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the way of this world: flawed human beings must,
according to the rule of law, judge other flawed human beings,''
Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde employs a high rhetorical style well suited to the Senate
floor, and his speech Saturday won a lot of praise without much
mention that a big chunk of it was lifted straight from the speech
he gave in the House a few weeks ago. In a week which has seen so
much repetition, it only seemed natural.
</P>
<P>
   In a way the repetition worked as a code to conclude a long
process that has gone much farther than many thought it would. Next
week the high rhetoric of the King holiday _ certain to include
many defenses of the president _ and the high-wire act which under
Clinton the State of the Union has become will begin the last-ditch
effort to end it.
</P>
<P>
   tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
