gown and wanted one just like it, so the crew made her one. It was
made of white lace embroidered with iridescent thread, worn with a
white fox cape and white satin shoes trimmed with rhinestones. At
the ball, she carried a white lace fan, also given to her by the
movie crew.
</P>
<P>
   During the inaugural galas for Gov. Bill Clements' first term in
1979, a rumor went around that the Department of Public Safety
squad assigned to escort the governor had been reassigned to guard
the cloakroom. After all, the joke went, Clements only spent $7
million on his election. The minks _ and the foxes, lambs and
chinchillas _ in the coatrooms were worth considerably more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. James Stephen Hogg was inaugurated in 1891 there was a
torchlight parade up Congress Avenue. People in the parade wore
oilcloth coats to protect themselves from falling sparks and oil
drippings.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Sam Houston was inaugurated in 1859, the invitation
announced that there would be ``two bands of music in attendance,''
and ``supper by J.K. Johnston.'' Nowadays, hundreds of musicians
are employed at inaugural events, and dozens of dinners take place
to mark it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular events during Gov. Beauford H. Jester's
inauguration in 1947 was square dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most austere inauguration in Texas was that of Gov.
Pendleton Murrah in 1863. It was held during the last months of the
Confederacy (his administration was terminated when the Confederacy
fell). The state dinner featured simple cornmeal cakes. There was
no inauguration ball.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an inauguration theme?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and it's in both English and Spanish: ``Together, We Can,''
or ``Juntos Podemos.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidents of Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Know someone who thinks they are an expert in Texas history?
Give them this quiz: Before we had governors of Texas, we had
presidents of the Republic, for five terms. Can you name them? You
get bonus points if you know the dates they were in office. Answer:
David G. Burnet, March 16, 1836-Oct. 22, 1836; Sam Houston, Oct.
22, 1836- Dec. 10, 1838; Mirabeau B. Lamar, Dec. 10, 1838- Dec. 13,
1841; Sam Houston, Dec. 13, 1841-Dec. 9, 1844; Anson Jones, Dec. 9,
1844-Feb. 19, 1846.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the inaugural ball gowns. What are the men going to wear?
</P>
<P>
   Many of them will don Texas Tuxes in the coming days, as
inaugural parties and balls light up the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Tux consists of a tuxedo coat, boots, hat and khaki
pants or blue jeans. Traditionally a tux shirt and all that goes
with it _ black bow tie, studs and cummerbund _ are worn. Remember
the cummerbund pleats go up. A regular white shirt and bolo tie are
acceptable on less formal occasions. Want to practice for the day
you'll be governor?
</P>
<P>
   Here is the official oath of office used by the state of Texas,
the one that George W. Bush will utter on Tuesday: ``I, (your name
goes here), do solemnly swear that I will faithfully execute the
duties of the office of Governor of the State of Texas, and will to
the best of my ability preserve, protect, and defend the
Constitution and laws of the United States and of this State, so
help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   How much does the governor earn?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's annual salary is $99,122. He refused his last
raise.
</P>
<P>
   Should I bring an umbrella?
</P>
<P>
   Governors generally have had good luck with the weather on
inauguration day _ not too rainy, not too cold. The average high
temperature for the last five inauguration days (going back to
1979) was 58; the average low, 44. It's been foggy and gray for
some of those ceremonies, but the most precipitation Austin
received on those five dates was .71 inches, when Mark White was
sworn in on Jan. 18, 1983. The best weather was enjoyed by Gov. Ann
Richards, whose inauguration day had 10 hours and 36 minutes of
sunshine. The forecast for Tuesday is partly cloudy with a high in
the low 70s.
</P>
<P>
   What is there to do the day before the inauguration?
</P>
<P>
   There's a big Martin Luther King Jr. birthday celebration and
youth concert Monday morning in Houston. It's at 10 a.m. at the
George R. Brown Convention Center. Gov. Bush will be attending.
It's free and open to the public. Here in Austin, there's an
invitation-only children's program at 2 p.m. at the Paramount
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening on the big day?
</P>
<P>
   Prayer service
</P>
<P>
   A traditional inaugural event at First United Methodist Church,
1201 Lavaca, near the Capitol, the prayer service is a private,
invitation-only gathering for the governor, his family and close
associates. The Bushes are Methodist, so having the service here is
particularly appropriate. Time: 10 a.m. Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural ceremony
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Phillips, chief justice of the Texas Supreme Court, will
administer the oath to Bush, who will have his hand placed on Sam
Houston's Bible. This Bible is a treasured book that rarely sees
daylight, except during gubernatorial inaugurations. Time: Noon
Location: Capitol's south steps Parking: Where you can find it.
There is no reserved parking for the public. Street closings:
Colorado will be closed between 11th and 13th streets from 7 a.m.
to 5 p.m. Tickets: None necessary. The audience will stand.
Organizers expect 15,000 to 20,000 people Special guests: The
governor's parents, former President George Bush and former first
lady Barbara Bush, and former Texas governors will be there.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Barbecue and Celebration
</P>
<P>
   A successful tradition carried over from previous inaugurations,
the barbecue will provide Texas foods for Texas folks _ turkey,
brisket, sausage and pie. Time: 1 p.m. Where: South Lawn of the
Capitol. Tickets: $3. These may already be sold out. Call 494-1999
to check.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural parade
</P>
<P>
   There are 81 entries in this parade. Gov. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry will ride near the front of the parade, then review the
remainder of it. Plenty of music and color will fill Congress
Avenue, as a slew of marching bands and color guards entertain
parade-watchers. Time: 2:30 p.m. Where: Starts at Third and
Congress; goes up to Capitol When you should get there to get a
good seat: By 11 a.m. Bring a lawn chair. Parking: No reserved
parking for public; no free parking downtown. Find parking where
you can. Street closings: See accompanying map Who will be in the
parade?: Thirty-three marching bands will strut their stuff,
including the University of Texas Longhorn Band, the Fightin' Texas
Aggie Band and high school bands from Haskell, Cuero, Hillsboro,
Harlingen, Dumas, Center, Del Valle, McAllen, Mansfield, Arlington,
Aledo, Austin, Midland, Fort Worth, Sugar Land, El Paso, Humble,
Corpus Christi, Burnet, Hamilton, Allen, Houston, Blanco and other
cities. The Kilgore Rangerettes will be there, as will the Texas
Buffalo Soldiers Regiment, the Texas A&AMP;M Corps of Cadets, the UT
cheerleaders, the comptroller, the railroad commissioners, the land
commissioner, the commissioner of agriculture and an M1 tank.
Floats include a ``Texas Technology'' float, a ``Natural
Resources'' float, and a ``Read to Succeed'' float.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugural balls
</P>
<P>
   In an old Texas inaugural tradition, the governor, lieutenant
governor, their families and various other officials and
dignitaries make a tour of the inaugural balls in ``The Grand
Entrance March.'' This means that as long as you're at one of the
balls, if you stay there long enough you're bound to see the Bushes
in their inaugural finery. Time: All balls begin at 7:30 p.m.
Where: Frank Erwin Center Who's playing: Emilio, Mr. Fabulous,
Rotel &AMP; The Hot Tomatoes, The Big Time Where: Austin Convention
Center Who's playing: Rick Trevino, Dallas Brass &AMP; Electric, Johnny
Dee &AMP; the Rocket 88's, The Pictures Where: Palmer Auditorium Who's
playing: Lonestar, Dash Rip Rock, the Dragons, Duck Soup, The Image
featuring Tony and Dailyn Valdez Where: Austin Music Hall Who's
playing: Robert Earl Keen, Blue Mist, Chris Wall, Midlife Crisis
and the Hot Flashes Tickets: $50 per person; except for the Austin
Music Hall concert, which is $40 per person and meant for those 35
years old and younger. Call 494-1999 to order.
</P>
<P>
   Dad vs. son: Who had the better party?
</P>
<P>
   How do this week's inaugural festivities stack up against
President George Herbert Walker Bush's inaugural celebration in
Washington, D.C., in 1989? Take a look:
</P>
<P>
   Five-day inaugural celebration
</P>
<P>
   Washington Cathedral prayer service
</P>
<P>
   Nine inaugural balls; $175 tickets
</P>
<P>
   Children's program featuring Big Bird and Wilford Brimley
</P>
<P>
   Entertainers included Loretta Lynn, Randy Travis, Crystal Gayle
and the Oak Ridge Boys
</P>
<P>
   Parade included 53 marching bands
</P>
<P>
   Parade had 78 floats
</P>
<P>
   Two-day inaugural celebration
</P>
<P>
   First United Methodist Church service
</P>
<P>
   Four inaugural balls; $40 or $50 tickets
</P>
<P>
   Children's program featuring Mad Science and Cat Paws in Motion
</P>
<P>
   Entertainers include Robert Earl Keen, Rick Trevino and Chris
Wall
</P>
<P>
   Parade includes 33 marching bands
</P>
<P>
   Parade has 3 floats
</P>
<P>
   Watch it on the Web
</P>
<P>
   At www.governor.state.tx.usinauguration.html, you'll be able to
see a live broadcast of Gov. Bush taking the oath on Tuesday. This
site is loaded with inaugural history, traditions and trivia. Be
sure to listen to an audio clip montage of several governors and
lieutenant governors taking the oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-01-16-99 1711E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
