</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GRAHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER EVOKES OWN CHILDHOOD IN SEGREGATED SOUTH IN CASE VS.
CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES,
IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER) 
(nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like the other Republican congressmen appointed to
prosecute President Clinton, Lindsey Graham of South Carolina went
before the Senate on Saturday as a lawyer, entwining evidence and
precedents to argue for the president's expulsion from office.
</P>
<P>
   But in an evocative and sometimes provocative twist, Graham also
cast himself as ``a child of the South'' whose exposure to racial
discrimination had made him appreciate the importance of civil
rights, not just for blacks but for women.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments clearly sought to refocus attention on
Republicans' assertions that the president, by concealing his
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky, subverted the civil rights of Paula
Jones, whose sexual misconduct lawsuit against him triggered the
initial questions about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham also stole a favorite oratorical trick from Clinton's
bag, invoking the same racial bearings and weaving the same
autobiographical flourishes that Clinton, who grew up in Arkansas,
employed so often in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my lifetime,'' Graham told senators, ``I started school
with no black person in my class, and by the sixth grade _ I think
it was the sixth grade _ integration hit my area, and I can
remember my mom and dad being scared to death about what it would
do and what it would mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and mother owned a restaurant _ a beer joint, I
guess, is what we'd say in South Carolina,'' Graham recalled. ``I
can remember that if you were black, you came, and you had to buy
the beer, and you had to go because you couldn't drink it there.
`That's just the way it was' is what my dad said. I always never
quite understood that.''
</P>
<P>
   Folksy, confessional and shrewd, Graham's address stood out
among the more technical presentations of the other 12 Republicans
appointed as trial managers, or prosecutors. Graham said that that
was just what he intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was time to make the concepts we were talking
about real,'' Graham said in an interview after his presentation.
``I tried to talk to the Senate. They'd been lectured to a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all the senators appreciated what he had to say. Sen.
Tim Johnson, D-S.D., said there was ``a bit of eye rolling'' among
members of his party as Graham allied himself and the Republican
Party with civil rights and concern for women.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., also complained that
Republicans like Graham had not always acted in the best interests
of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Lindsey Graham,'' Schumer said. ``He's a nice guy. I
would just like the general concern for civil rights to spread
beyond today.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time in the impeachment debate that
Graham, 43, who was swept into Congress in the so-called Republican
revolution of 1994, drew special notice.
</P>
<P>
   On the House Judiciary Committee, he parted ranks with fellow
Republicans to vote against one of the four articles of impeachment
it was considering. That article charged Clinton with perjury in
the deposition he gave to Ms. Jones' lawyers, and Graham said at
the time that he did not think Congress had the right to judge
those remarks because a judge ultimately deemed the deposition
immaterial and Clinton was speaking about matters that were then
private.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Jones was very much on Graham's thoughts, and in his
words, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that people needed to treat sexual harassment as
seriously as they came to treat racial discrimination, Graham told
senators: ``It used to be in this country, not long ago, there was
really no recourse if you were sexually harassed. We have changed
things for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said later that he had decided to speak about his own
life ``literally five minutes before I stood up,'' because he
sensed that the senators needed a change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was well aware that Clinton had often given
speeches in a similar vein. ``He's very eloquent, but he's not the
only one to have experienced these things,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good spokesman for civil rights,'' Graham said of
the president. ``But what does civil rights mean if you just talk
about it and don't apply it in your own life?''
</P>
</TEXT>
