<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      01-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MANAGERS TACKLE TOUGHEST PART: CONVINCING SENATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES,
IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER, IMPEACH-GRAHAM) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For two days House Republican prosecutors played
the short game, trying to win the right to call witnesses. Saturday
they turned to their ultimate challenge: to convince senators,
particularly Democrats, that President Clinton's misdeeds are grave
enough to warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   For on this Saturday, the third and final day of their opening
arguments, the House managers tackled the most fundamental question
underlying the nation's second presidential impeachment trial. Do
Clinton's efforts to cover up his relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky amount to the ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' the
nation's founders had in mind for removal of an elected president?
</P>
<P>
   Some of their appeals stood on law and precedent and
interpretation of the Constitution, such as Rep. Charles B.
Canady's assertion that ``a president who commits a calculated and
sustained series of criminal offenses has _ by his personal
violations of the law _ failed in the most direct, immediate and
culpable manner to do his duty under the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Other managers played more to emotion than to law. Rep. Henry J.
Hyde wrapped up the three days by reading a letter from a schoolboy
asking ``if you cannot believe the president, who can you
believe?'' as well as appealing grandiloquently for Clinton to be
removed from office to keep faith with those who died on the
beaches of Normandy and in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   What is critical is how Democrats react to these arguments. For
with the Senate composed of 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats, the
House prosecutors are thought to have only a very slight chance of
gaining the 67 votes necessary to secure the president's
conviction. To do so, they must pull over at least 12 Democrats and
most likely even more, since the Republicans will probably not vote
as a solid bloc.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats in particular, while acknowledging that Clinton
lied in several legal proceedings and should be censured, have long
expressed doubts over whether such actions to cover up an
extra-marital affair amount to rise to the constitutional level to
remove a twice-elected president from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad behavior,'' Sen. John B. Breaux, D-La., said
Saturday, even after listening to the House managers. ``But the
standard for removing a president is not bad behavior. It is high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no fixed definition of what constitutes a high crime
and misdemeanor. And throughout the five months that Congress has
been grappling with impeachment, the White House has staked much of
its defense of the president on the grounds that his offenses do
not amount to an abuse of power that warrants his removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   As the president's lawyers wrote in a pretrial brief,
``impeachment was never intended to be a remedy for private wrongs.
It was intended to be a method of removing a president whose
continued presence in the office would cause grave danger to the
nation and our constitutional system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also pointed to a letter circulated by 400
historians and legal scholars _ prominent among them Arthur
Schlesinger Jr. _ saying that removal of Clinton because of the
case before Congress would ``mangle the system of checks and
balances that is our chief safeguard against abuses of power.''
</P>
<P>
   So Saturday, two of the House managers, Canady and Rep. Steve
Buyer of Indiana, sought to undermine the credibility of
Schlesinger, the Pulitzer Prize-winning author who was an aide to
John F. Kennedy, by using some of his own writings against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting a passage from ``The Imperial Presidency,''
Schlesinger's study of the growth of presidential power, Buyer
read, ``The continuation of a lawbreaker as chief magistrate would
be a strange way to exemplify law and order at home or to
demonstrate American probity before the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey O. Graham made an appeal to emotion. As a child of
the segregated south, he extolled the civil rights laws that Paula
Jones ultimately used to sue Clinton for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a high crime?'' the folksy South Carolina Republican
asked, before making a populist appeal on behalf of Ms. Jones'
right to sue and get truthful answers from Clinton. ``How about if
an important person hurts somebody of low means? It's not very
scholarly, but I think it's the truth. I think that's what they
mean by high crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was left to Canady to be the scholarly one. He reminded
senators they have impeached and removed federal judges for
perjury. ``The Senate should not establish a lower standard of
integrity for the president,'' he argued. He also took on Clinton's
defense that he has not committed the same kind of abuses that
Richard M. Nixon did during the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no principled basis for contending that a president
who interferes with the proper exercise of governmental power _ as
he clearly does when he commits perjury and obstruction of justice
_ is constitutionally less blameworthy than a president who misuses
the power of his office,'' Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president who lies to a federal grand jury in order to
impede the investigation of crimes is no less culpable than a
president who wrongfully orders a prosecutor to suspend an
investigation of crimes that have been committed,'' he said in
reference to the ``Saturday Night Massacre'' in 1973, when Nixon
ordered his attorney general, Elliot Richardson, to fire special
prosecutor Archibald Cox. Richardson resigned instead.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a long time before the Senate holds votes that will
show how much headway the prosecutors made Saturday in persuading
the necessary number of Democrats that Clinton's offenses rise to
the level of high crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some clues. Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del.,
said Saturday he had not been convinced. Nor was Sen. Charles E.
Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Graham, D-Fla., said: ``They made a good case for that.
The presentations the House managers have made have caused you to
do exactly what this process is supposed to: maintain an open
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., said, ``I think that's an uphill
climb still, but I think they pushed perhaps some in the Senate or
some in the country a little further up that hill than was the case
yesterday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
