<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-WORD17-COX     01-16 2027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-WORD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campaign corps awaits the word
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EXETER, N.H. _ In the photographs that line his living room and
the memories alive in his mind, 82-year-old Michael Dagostino sees
a political past that he hopes will be part of the political
future.
</P>
<P>
   Two generations back, a younger Dagostino delighted in driving
Connecticut Sen. Prescott Bush around when he visited New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   One generation back, Dagostino became a go-to guy for George
Bush during his frequent campaigns up here.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush became president, Dagostino was at the airport to
greet him every time he visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are my loyal, dear friend and I would like to have been on
hand to give you a big birthday abrazo (hug),'' Bush said in an
August 1996 note sending regrets for missing Dagostino's 80th
birthday bash.
</P>
<P>
   Dagostino also has a more-recent letter from a more-current
Bush. The New Hampshire presidential primary is a year away _ which
means it is already near full speed _ and Dagostino again is
excited about a Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be making up my mind on the year 2000 in the next
couple of months,'' Texas Gov. George W. Bush told Dagostino in a
Dec. 4 letter. ``Please tell your friends to keep their powder
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a message that has been heeded around this state among Bush
family loyalists who have resisted entreaties from GOP presidential
candidates already on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   As in many other states, Bush backers from campaigns gone by are
excited about getting involved in another one.
</P>
<P>
   In this historically pivotal state _ only twice since 1948 have
the Republicans nominated someone other than the winner of the New
Hampshire primary _ and elsewhere, Bush has a machine-in-waiting
cultivated for years by a famous dad who claimed any number of home
states.
</P>
<P>
   It means people to play host at coffees. It means people to hang
signs. It means money. It means votes.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, it adds up to a potentially powerful combination in
New Hampshire, a state that probably will remain significant even
if it does not succeed in defending its first- in-the-nation
primary against a wave of bigger states that have moved up on the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   For Dagostino, it's difficult not to smile when he thinks about
another Bush candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always figured he would run for president,'' Dagostino said.
``I think he will make a hell of a president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists his only immediate goal is being a hell of a
governor. On Tuesday, he will take the oath of office for a second
term that family friends here hope he never completes.
</P>
<P>
   While other potential and probable 2000 presidential candidates
have organizations in place in the Granite State, Bush's is
bubbling just below the surface, awaiting word from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the ``keep the power dry'' message and the
quarterly ``Bush News'' publication that recently hit their mail
boxes (and the boxes of all of Bush's 97,000 donors nationwide) to
tout his November re-election, his backers here have little doubt
that Bush will run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous corps of Bush family loyalists here just
waiting for the signal or the word,'' New Hampshire GOP Chairman
Steve Duprey said.
</P>
<P>
   Duprey is officially neutral but on-the-record excited about
what it would mean to add Bush to the field.
</P>
<P>
   The other 2000 presidential contenders are already here in body
and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Some are here so often they might qualify to vote in the New
Hampshire pri- mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Steve Forbes. Let's start the 21st century right,'' Forbes
says in a TV ad now running.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander never really left. Last summer, he drew a good
crowd for what has become his annual New Hampshire clam- bake.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle is gathering a team. The man heading the effort to
draft Elizabeth Dole was here last week. Gary Bauer planned to
spend Saturday in the state, including a speech at an anti-abortion
rally at the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he won't be anywhere near here any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I doubt there will be any visits to Iowa or New
Hampshire,'' he said recently, ``although I never say never. ... I
intend to be home doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   But family friends here expect to see him soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how he can not run, because everybody is after him
to run,'' said former GOP national committeewoman Victoria Zachos
of Concord, a Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a governor of a big state like Texas and everybody
is clamoring for you to run, wouldn't that turn your head?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush brigade
</P>
<P>
   Dagostino, legendary for his ability to put together a political
crowd, is typical of the Bush organization-in-waiting here.
</P>
<P>
   It includes veteran grass-roots activists who understand that
politics is handshake-to-handshake combat in New Hampshire. It also
includes well-placed officials, some so well-placed that it would
be impolitic for them to declare allegiance to Bush more than a
year before the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The years of New Hampshire handshaking by the elder Bush are
documented on the back of the ex-president's trading card, included
in a set published by the State Library's Archives of New
Hampshire's Political Tradition, a permanent exhibit chronicling
the state's role in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He campaigned tediously long hours and came to recognize more
New Hampshire voters by their names than any other presidential
candidate in the history of the primary,'' the card claims.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush won the New Hampshire primaries in 1988 and 1992,
though he failed here in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Family friends also got to know the Bush kids during those
campaigns. Though they'd rather see him here sooner than later,
George W. Bush supporters in New Hampshire say he would start out
on a first-name basis with many key folks.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Hugh Gregg, officially neutral at this point despite
long-standing ties to the Bush family, has been hearing from these
people in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has lots of people,'' Gregg said of the Texas governor. ``I
used to be his father's chairman. They call me. There are a lot of
people out there anxious to work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than polls that show him running at the top among
Republicans here (a dead heat with Elizabeth Dole, according to a
recent television-station poll), nobody knows how many Bush
supporters there are in New Hampshire. But the list includes
political pros who know how the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   They are people such as Ed Du Pont, a well-connected lobbyist,
former president of the state Senate and former gubernatorial
candidate; Robb Thomson, a former governor's son and a rumored 2000
gubernatorial candidate; and Zachos, a former GOP national
committee member who has dined with the Bushes at the family summer
home at Kennebunkport in neighboring Maine.
</P>
<P>
   They may be people such as former Gov. Steve Merrill, publicly
uncommitted but believed to be loyal to Bush, and former state Sen.
David Currier, a key Forbes campaigner in 1996 who now says he
could wind up as a Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   Currier, owner of a $21 million-a-year emergency-medical-supply
business in Henniker, still works for Forbes' Americans for Hope,
Growth and Opportunity PAC, but he is beginning to doubt Forbes'
electability.
</P>
<P>
   And, like many New Hampshire Republicans, Currier has Bush
family ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neal Bush (one of the former president's sons) used to live
with us when he was here during the campaign days,'' Currier said.
``Neal was the guy at the time doing a lot of the grunt work in New
Hampshire. He was doing so much grunt work that he found a bride
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In an office lined with political photos _ including former
President Bush _ Currier can pull a Forbes' PAC button from his
desk drawer but said his support might be available for the asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to somebody a while ago that if George H.W. Bush called
me and asked me to support (his son), I'd have a hell of a time
saying no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Concord, not far from the Statehouse, Zachos, too,
is awaiting word from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known the family for years,'' said Zachos, Bob Dole's
1996 state finance chairwoman. ``We are just waiting for the
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Du Pont, a Forbes backer in 1996, is eager to change
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, he has experience as a governor and a
name that looks pretty good on a national ticket,'' Du Pont said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vs. Quayle
</P>
<P>
   Not all New Hampshire politicos with Bush family ties are
heeding the call to keep their powder dry.
</P>
<P>
   The state offers the clearest example of the politically
incestuous weirdness that would develop if Bush-Quayle _ a ticket
in 1988 and 1992 _ becomes a battle between former Vice President
Quayle and his old ticketmate's kid.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. John Sununu, chief of staff in the Bush White House,
is a Quayle man. A Quayle source in Phoenix said look for Sununu to
wind up as a ``very, very senior official'' in the former vice
president's nationwide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sununu is symptomatic of the peculiar flow chart inherent in the
GOP shaping up for 2000. Many candidates have Bush links.
Alexander, Elizabeth Dole and Jack Kemp served in the Bush cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But there might never have been a Bush cabinet without Sununu,
who quarterbacked the Bush campaign to victory here over Bob Dole
in 1988. When Sununu's star fell in the White House, George W.
Bush, then working as a top, if unofficial, White House aide for
his dad, fired him.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire GOP Chairman Duprey said that as far as he knows,
Sununu's decision to go with Quayle is ``nothing personal'' against
the younger Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Sununu factor _ and how New Hampshire intramural politics
can affect leadership of the free world _ caught Barbara Bush's eye
during her husband's 1988 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Hampshire had some real problems for us,'' she wrote in
her book, recalling ``personal animosities'' between the Sununus
and the Greggs, two of the state's leading political families.
``John is a hero of mine. He's such a bright man, such a funny man.
Unfortunately, John does not suffer fools gladly and is sometimes
his own worst enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is personal, intramural battles such as the Sununus vs. the
Greggs that highlight how politics differs in New Hampshire. In
states such as Texas and California, big-money TV campaigns are
what counts. In New Hampshire _ which has long wielded clout beyond
its size _ handshaking and allegiance from key operatives can go a
long, long way.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, thanks to his dad, can sit it out longer than most,
according to Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is probably the only one who can, other than maybe
Elizabeth Dole or Colin Powell,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   While potential contender Bush is staying away, there has been
no shortage of sightings of the other potentials. The primary is
about a year away, but the campaigning here never dies down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Alexander ran third here (behind Pat Buchanan and Bob
Dole) with 23 percent of the vote. Since then, he's become part of
the New Hampshire landscape. His political-action committee has
been running ads here for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Lamar has been here the most. He never really left,''
state chairman Duprey said.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle and Forbes also have been regular visitors, keeping their
names out there and raising money for local candidates, a favor
that goes a long way in New Hampshire. Candidates who have all but
announced _ Forbes, Bauer and Alan Keyes, and probably Quayle _
will be here next month for a New Hampshire Christian Coalition
event. Bush will not be here.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a new face in the race _ New Hampshire Sen. Bob
Smith. But some top Republicans say he is on his way to becoming
the least-favored favorite-son candidate in recent memory. He
chalked up only 4 percent in a recent TV-station poll.
</P>
<P>
   Dagostino, from his living room/political hall of fame, is among
those scoffing at Smith's quixotic effort. Dagostino says he might
scoff at the entire GOP field if his old friend's son is not in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who the hell runs then,'' he said. ``They are the
same old faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
