</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-FALCONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS SHOULD HAVE PLENTY OF FIGHT IN THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Falcons arrived in the Twin Cities Friday,
toting their footballs and pads and helmets, but also one certain
heavyweight inspiration, Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited by the Falcons,'' said Holyfield, the
heavyweight champion and a proud native son of Atlanta. ``When I
was a kid I used to work in their football stadium and I was there
a lot at their games.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not always watching. That's because the Falcons then
seldom were mediocre, let alone good, and nothing like the Falcons
who will take on the Minnesota Vikings for the NFC championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd never seemed to be into it at their games,''
Holyfield said. ``That's because the team wasn't always doing a lot
on the field to get them going.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbolism of Holyfield's presence can't be escaped.
Holyfield was a huge underdog when he took on Mike Tyson for the
heavyweight title, just as the Falcons are a huge underdog against
the flashy Vikings, possessors of the NFL's most explosive offense.
Holyfield upset Tyson, just as the Falcons are confident they can
upset the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time for the Falcons,'' said Holyfield. ``It's
about time.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has a conference title game been contested between teams
with records this good, the 16-1 Vikings and the 15-2 Falcons.
Another first will be that a team that plays inside a dome will
make it to the Super Bowl for the first time, refuting the myth
that domes make teams too soft to win a championship when wills of
steel are mandatory for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get to the stadium,'' said Cris Carter, the
Vikings' superb wide receiver and the absolute leader of this team.
``I can't wait to look into my locker and see my uniform and the
whole thing. That's because since I was a little boy, I've always
dreamed of being a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Vikings get to the Metrodome, they will be without
Jake Reed, one of their outstanding trio of receivers, with Carter
and rookie Randy Moss. Reed was scratched from the game because of
a balky hamstring. Another question involves defensive lineman John
Randle, the All-Pro and well-nigh indispensable pillar of a defense
that already is average at best. Randle has a sore knee, did not
practice Wednesday, and said he is not sure how much he'll be able
to play.
</P>
<P>
   If Randle's words are to be believed _ and words seldom are
believable before games of this magnitude _ he may be too hurt to
play his usual role as a dominant pass-rusher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Stalin Colinet will play probably the first quarter,
and the second quarter, and maybe I'll just try to work myself into
the game,'' said Randle. ``I may play some nickel situations in the
first quarter. It just depends on the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Randle's status is far from the only worry for the Minnesota
defense. Free safety Orlando Thomas is still bothered by a strained
hamstring and missed many team drills in practice. If Thomas is
forced to sit, rookie Anthony Bass may start, either at free safety
or strong safety, with strong safety Robert Griffith possibly
moving to free safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the Vikings' only loss of the season, a 27-24 defeat in Tampa
Bay Nov. 1, the Bucs were able to win primarily because of a strong
running game, particularly on the part of Mike Alstott. The
Falcons, of course, have a strong running game with Jamal Anderson,
and the strategy is obvious: keep the Minnesota offense off the
field by dominating the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one good thing is that we're not playing outside in this
weather,'' said Atlanta coach Dan Reeves, a star for the Cowboys in
the famous Ice Bowl game in Green Bay for the NFL title 31 years
ago. ``When I look outside and see this weather, well, I'll take
the noise over the weather. After playing in Green Bay, there's no
question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Metrodome will be very noisy, even if the NFL
directed the Vikings to move a set of speakers from behind the
visiting team's bench farther toward the end zone. But noise will
not win or lose this game.
</P>
<P>
   Neither quarterback, the veteran Randall Cunningham of the
Vikings or the well-traveled Chris Chandler for Atlanta, has played
in a game of this magnitude. Which quarterback is more immune to
the pressure will be a key factor.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Atlanta defense, which was fourth in the league in
points allowed per game (18) and first in takeaways (44), has been
ignored in the publicity for the Minnesota offense. But the
Falcons' defense, sprinkled with such veterans as safety Eugene
Robinson, a veteran of Green Bay's Super Bowl wars, and corner Ray
Buchanan, may be a surprising match for the Vikings' offense.
</P>
<P>
   And the deciding factor just may be the receivers. No, not the
heralded duo of Moss and Carter for the Vikings, but Atlanta's Tony
Martin and Terance Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right up there with those guys,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   And the difference is that Martin and Mathis will be going
against a defense that may not be right up there with Atlanta's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
