<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY FOR JETS IS GROUND CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Terrell Davis is the best football player in the
National Football League this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just may be as good as any running back I have ever seen,''
said Jets head coach Bill Parcells, whose team will take on Davis
and the Denver Broncos in Sunday's AFC Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In a year of offensive wonders, the slashing Denver runner
outdid the great performances of quarterback Vinny Testaverde with
the Jets, Randall Cunningham and Randy Moss in Minnesota, plus
Jamal Anderson in Atlanta _ not to slight what Doug Flutie
accomplished in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the Jets' high command of Parcells and defensive
coordinator Bill Belichick can figure out how to take the
opponents' best player out of the offense and make them try to win
with lesser players.
</P>
<P>
   But, frankly, Davis scares Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Few teams have been able to even slow Davis down. In a Monday
night game a month ago, the Miami Dolphins handled Davis and beat
Denver. Last week, he came back to haunt them here in Mile High
Stadium with a 199-yard performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to stop this guy with seven defensive players
in the box,'' cautioned Jacksonville head coach Tom Coughlin, who
has been burned twice in the last year by Davis's sizzling running.
``You bring the eighth guy (a safety) up to help stop the run, and
then (John) Elway goes to work in the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   This, then, will be the test. Can the Jets get lucky with seven?
Can their defensive front stop Davis and force Denver into strictly
a passing game? If they can, they think they can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has tremendous power,'' said Parcells, who spoke with
both respect and fear in his voice. ``He sees the play. He makes
great cuts. And he can run through people. We will have our hands
full.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they don't say it publicly, the Jets expect to score a
lot of points. This offense might be working better than any unit
Parcells has ever coached in the NFL. The talent may not be equal
to what he has had on some other teams, but the schemes and the
efficiency have been exceptional in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   A critical factor for the Jets will be how they handle the noise
factor in Mile High Stadium. It is one of the toughest venues for a
visiting team. With all of the success that Denver teams have had
over the years, the home crowd has become as sharp as any in
raising the decibel level when the opposing quarterback comes to
the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The tackles and wide receivers, who are farthest from the
quarterback, will have a difficult time hearing Vinny Testaverde.
In each Denver home game, the crowd noise undoubtedly produces
``motion'' penalties, and, in turn, long-yardage passing situations
for visiting teams.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the Broncos want it. They have a complicated set of
blitzes and will be coming after Testaverde, hoping to force him to
throw the ball prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver defense is not great. It is helped by the fact that
the offense scores a lot of points and generally gives it a lead.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Jets is all packaged in the run. If they somehow
can slow down Davis, and also get a big game out of Curtis Martin _
as they did in beating Jacksonville last week _ they could be on
their way to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If not, it will be Davis heading to Florida and looking for his
third straight Most Valuable Player award, to go with last year's
Super Bowl and this year's regular season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
