<HEADER>
A6216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SUMMARY-NYT &LR;      01-16 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SUMMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: ADDS IMPEACH-ASSESS and IMPEACH-GRAHAM) 
 ( nk )
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Here's a summary of the impeachment trial stories that have moved
for Sunday's paper:
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Summarizing the Republican case
against President Clinton in a speech evoking the shades of heroes
past, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said Saturday afternoon that the
presidency could be ``permanently damaged'' if the Senate failed to
remove Clinton from office. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ On Saturday, the third and final
day of their opening arguments, House managers tackled the most
fundamental question underlying the nation's second presidential
impeachment trial. Do Clinton's efforts to cover up his
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky amount to the ``high crimes
and misdemeanors'' the nation's founders had in mind for removal of
an elected president? By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ In theory, the Paula Jones lawsuit
has been settled. But it continues to haunt the president. His
defense lawyers complained that the House Republican prosecutors
had been referring ``again and again'' to Clinton's deposition in
the Jones suit, despite the fact that the full House rejected
perjury charges built around that testimony. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK (Washington) _ A certain sloppiness has
infected the trial of President Clinton, at least when it comes to
spelling. The first big mistake came on the first day, when
senators signed their oaths to be impartial with pens whose
inscriptions scrambled the letters in the country's name: the
``Untied States.'' By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-EAGLES (Palm Beach, Fla.) _ Most of the Republicans who
gathered here at this sunny resort last week were less then eager
to draw attention to their presence as Washington is overcome not
only by frosty weather but by the impeachment trial of President
Clinton. But the fact that contributors traveled here _ and
politicians from Capitol Hill flew in to hobnob with them _ is
testament to how nothing gets in the way of Republicans courting,
wooing and hitting up the party's most reliable donors. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ It was a strange sight. Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., was offering a compromise plan that would have
abbreviated President Clinton's impeachment trial and avoided
witnesses. His proposal was shot down by his fellow Republicans in
the Senate, but it infuriated conservatives in his state, who have
vowed to field a candidate against him. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ROSS (Washington) _ With President Clinton on trial for
his political life, the name of Sen. Edmund G. Ross of Kansas is
apt to come up whenever people talk about courage, honor and duty.
According to American political legend, he chose personal ruin
rather than betray his principles, defying his party leadership in
voting to acquit President Andrew Johnson during the last
presidential impeachment, in 1868. If he had voted the other way,
Johnson would have been removed and American history might have
been much different. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ As the duel over impeachment
witnesses intensified, Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority
leader, has suggested to Democrats that a bipartisan group of
senators deal with the issue, but the Democratic leader rebuffed
his offer and called it premature. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ While there is an undeniable appeal
to the notion of enforced silence on usually prolix senators _ the
equivalent of a national mute button _ the Trial of the Century is
proving less than scintillating. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   EDIT-IMPEACH (Undated) _ Removing President Clinton from office
for the offenses presented by House impeachment managers sacrifices
something too important _ the orderly transfer of power on a
four-year schedule _ to accomplish a condemnation that can be
delivered through other means.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW (Washington) _ Whether they want to see
President Clinton driven from office or whether they have
completely tuned out the Senate impeachment trial, Americans, on
the first anniversary of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, do agree on
one thing: They want it to be over. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW (Undated) _ A friend recently gave Rep.
Henry Hyde the original Broadway cast recording of the ``Man of La
Mancha,'' and when in odd moments he listens to its hummable tunes
about the Spanish Inquisition, he also hears Quixote sing:
``Heathens and wizards and serpents of sin, all your dastardly
doings are past. For a holy endeavor is now to begin and virtue
shall triumph at last!'' By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton kept a studied
distance Saturday from his impeachment trial in the Senate,
focusing not on the charges laid out against him by Republican
prosecutors, aides said, but on the next big event on his political
calendar: the State of the Union speech on Tuesday. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JUDGES (Washington) _ Three House managers on Saturday
drew a parallel between the accusation that President Clinton lied
before the grand jury about his relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky and the Senate's perjury convictions of three federal
judges. By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER (Undated) _ For months, members of Congress
have taken to quoting famous historians to back up their own views
on the impeachment of President Clinton. Twice Saturday, for
example, House Republicans Steve Buyer of Indiana and Charles
Canady of Florida quoted the writings of Arthur Schlesinger Jr. to
argue for Clinton's removal. Just one problem: Schlesinger, the
Pulitzer Prize-winning author who was an aide to President John F.
Kennedy, has come out firmly against Clinton's impeachment. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GRAHAM (Washington) _ Like the other Republican
congressmen appointed to prosecute President Clinton, Lindsey
Graham of South Carolina went before the Senate on Saturday as a
lawyer, entwining evidence and precedents to argue for the
president's expulsion from office. In an evocative and sometimes
provocative twist, Graham cast himself as ``a child of the South''
whose exposure to racial discrimination had made him appreciate the
importance of civil rights, not just for blacks but for women. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1938EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
