u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-16 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HYPE: THIS IS ONE SUPERIOR SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ If your pigskin juices aren't flowing Sunday, stop
trying to lay any jive on someone about being a football fan.
You're a 1,000-percent fraud.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the day I circle on my annual Gotta Be There list is the
Saturday afternoon of the Final Four. For any legit hoop fan, it
doesn't get any better than being a part of the buzz about a
half-hour before the first game of the doubleheader. At that time,
all four teams share an equal belief, no matter how far-fetched,
that it clearly is their year, that destiny is on their side, and
that the only curious part of the whole affair is why the other
teams have even bothered to show up. If you're wearing the colors
of a competing school, you actually feel sorry for all those other
fans, since you know how disappointed they're going to feel when
the trophy is handed over to your team around 11:30 EST on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   I would have to think the only comparable day for the serious
football fan is this particular Sunday. It's the beginning of
football's Final Four, even if it's not all played out in one site
and the actual in-person attentions are split. For the televiewer,
it is pre-Super Sunday, only twice as good. You don't have to sit
around all damn afternoon and wade through the endless pregame
stuff, either. I mean, hey, the game here starts at 12:30 Eastern,
a fabulous 11:30 Central. Can't beat that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all pre-Super Sundays are not created equal, which is
why there is such general interest in today's. I'd have to say this
is about as good as it's been in a long time. You've got four teams
with a combined record of 59-9. The team with the most losses, the
Jets, has lost just once in their last 11 games, so they are as hot
as those other juggernauts.
</P>
<P>
   The scenarios in both the NFC and AFC are about the same, in
that each conference final headlines a team that has had auras of
both invincibility and inevitability for most of the season against
a team that may not completely stack up on paper but is plenty good
enough to pull off the so-called upset and is coached by someone
who has been there (as well as here and everywhere).
</P>
<P>
   The fact that one of the favorites is also the defending
champion spices the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing making the Broncos-Jets and Vikings-Falcons
matchups so intriguing is the unarguable fact that each favorite is
acknowledged to be better on offense than defense. No one is saying
the defenses are crummy or anything, but they're both better at
outscoring you than shutting you down. When I was in Denver last
week, for example, people were all over the Broncos' secondary,
which had been toasted by Dan Marino during that much-discussed
31-21 loss in Week 16. As an outsider, I thought, ``Gee, so they
were lit up by Dan Marino. Correct me if I'm wrong, but it seems to
me that's happened on one or two occasions to other teams over the
past 14 years.'' Anyway, the secondary took the heat and its
response, in conjunction with the rest of the Denver defense, was
to hold Miami to 3 points last Saturday. That, as an aside, is a
good way to make sure you cover.
</P>
<P>
   But Denver generally wins by outscoring you. They're an ``over''
kind of team. The lowest point total in any of their 17 contests
this season has been 37 (a 21-16 victory at Seattle in Week 6).
Since then, the fewest they've scored in victory is 27. Meanwhile,
they have allowed more than 30 twice.
</P>
<P>
   So logic tells you the Jets might very well be able to move the
ball. The only other thing I want to say about them is that
Keyshawn Johnson is a strange phenomenon. In contrast to Randy
Moss, whose basic image consists of making an over-the-shoulder
grab on a sideline about 40 yards downfield, Johnson is very much a
hard-hat receiver. He's big and strong and not afraid of nuthin'.
I'm not saying Moss is, just that Keyshawn is not what you'd
expect, given his mouth and all. No pretty boy, he. He will run the
sideline and he will also run across the middle, where danger
lurks. He will stick his nose in there. Who'd have believed that?
</P>
<P>
   Denver ought to win, sure, but the Jets absolutely, positively
have a shot _ if Bill Belichick &AMP; Co. can slow Terrell Davis a
little. You're saying, ``Oh, gee, I really need this guy to tell me
that?'' Well, sometimes life's all about restating the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   This game they're paying me to watch has fascination because
people are still wondering what the 15-2 Falcons are really all
about. We know what the Vikings are all about: They score points.
They are the highest-scoring team in NFL history, and they even
have a placekicker who is perfect on the season. This has never
happened before, and if I were the Vikes, I'd be worrying. I'm not
saying they're going to lose, Sunday, or two weeks from now, but if
and when they do lose, isn't it obvious how it would come down?
</P>
<P>
   The Vikes are trailing by 2 points in the final minute. They
drive down the field and position Gary Anderson for, oh, let's say,
a 29-yarder. The snap, ball down, kick is up . . . Omigod! He
hooked it!
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with this scenario is that the Vikings haven't
really had a close game since they lost at Tampa Bay nine
devastating victories ago. But if they do . . .
</P>
<P>
   Understand that the Falcons have had the best record in football
since the middle of last season. They must be taken seriously. It's
a macho team with a major running back in Jamal Anderson and a
front seven that led the league with a plus-20 turnover margin and
44 takeaways. On top of everything else, they're even trying to win
one for the Reever.
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure: Football doesn't always float my boat
completely. Sunday is the exception. My only regret is the fact
that Da Boss has me working, which means I've got to miss some of
the AFC game. I'm not complaining. I'm whining. For Sunday is pro
football's High Holy Day, and on this occasion I'm as much a
worshipper as the next guy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
