u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ARUM-BOS     01-16 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ARUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARUM ACCEPTS BLAME BEFORE FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Apparently, Bob Arum agrees with Groucho Marx. He
doesn't want to be a member of any club that would have him.
</P>
<P>
   It was announced last week that Arum would be among the newest
inductees into the Boxing Hall of Fame in June, joining rival
promoters Don King and Lou Duva, who have already been enshrined.
King was the first of the modern-day Three Muskeeters of boxing to
be elected, followed by Duva last year and now Arum, but the latest
honoree said Friday that he doesn't belong there, and neither do
the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first inclination was to turn the thing down, but several
people told me not to,'' Arum said. ``They said it was better not
to embarrass the Hall of Fame, which I think is a great thing
that's good for boxing. So I'll go to the induction and say what I
have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   What Arum has to say is the truth, which, frankly, isn't always
what comes out of a boxing promoter's mouth. The proof of that came
at a press conference years ago when Arum was asked about an
apparent contradiction in a position he was taking. He replied,
``Yesterday I was lying. Today I'm telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be an anthem for boxing promoters, but it is Arum's
honest position today that rather than being sent to a Hall of
Fame, modern promoters like himself and King should have a special
wing in the Hall of Shame for what they did to boxing over the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the current promoters should be in because when boxing
was rising high in the '70s and early '80s with Ali and Frazier and
Foreman and Hagler and Hearns and Ray Leonard and Roberto Duran and
all those other great fighters, it was no thanks to us,'' Arum
said. ``We had an opportunity to keep it riding high and we screwed
it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our greed and our backbiting and our double
dealing, what inevitably happened was that we lost the networks and
boxing fell out of favor with the public. To a large extent it was
our fault. Not solely, but to a large extent. We could have
prevented it. At the least, we allowed it to happen. That's why we
don't belong in the Hall of Fame. None of us. Including Bob Arum.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard Law School and a former Justice Department
attorney under Bobby Kennedy, Arum is a highly intelligent man who
stumbled into sport's red light district with Muhammad Ali and
never left. He has become a millionaire many times over from boxing
and staged some of his era's biggest fights yet, in the end, he is
right about what the big promoters have done to the sport that fed
them.
</P>
<P>
   But how could quick-witted men like Arum and King allow such rot
to eat away the game's foundation _ the small shows and free
network exposure that remains the key for any sport's long-term
growth?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're blinded by greed and competition,'' Arum said. ``The
greater good was always put on the back burner by all of us. I'm
ashamed to say that but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Shame is seldom associated with boxing promoters, who, as a
fraternity, will say just about anything to justify a fight or make
a buck. They are promoters in the P.T. Barnum sense, hustlers who
too often operate on the shady side of sport's streets.
</P>
<P>
   But they also have made many fighters millions and provided some
of the most glorious sporting events in history. The list of Arum's
big fights is a long one and over the years he has worked with
nearly every major gate attraction in the sport and done well by
them and for them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the final analysis, Arum is right about the collective
guilt he shares _ with King, in particular _ for the sorry state of
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Although boxing is undergoing a bit of a renaissance _ with
King, Arum, and Duva working together to book bouts such as the
Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight unification, the Oscar
De La Hoya-Ike Quartey welterweight showdown, and a Pernell
Whitaker-Felix Trinidad title fight _ Arum believes this may not be
quite the good sign some see it as. Rather, he fears it could be a
final death knell, a last gasp that will eventually be snuffed out
by the forces of greed and revenge that have battered boxing for 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What boxing needs is for all the elements to get together and
form a national commission to hear disputes,'' Arum said. ``Someone
who can iron things out and has the power to make us all behave the
way we should.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be the government, but the US Senate will enact
legislation that enables that to happen, I think. Someone like a
Mills Lane would be a perfect choice because no one has ever
questioned his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's not the only one. A Mike Trainer would be OK. He
knows the business but is long out of it.'' (Trainer is Leonard's
former adviser.) ``He's been removed from the combat. Or maybe some
retired federal judge with an interest in boxing. We need someone
to come in like Judge Landis did in baseball after the Black Sox
scandal and give it all credibility again.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the recent rash of big fights has convinced Arum that
things have changed, because what he sees is not a decision to
suddenly begin doing the right thing but a desperate attempt to
revive the industry with a short-term burst of clear thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were made because boxing is in such a deplorable state
that there is no other alternative,'' Arum said. ``If you don't put
A in against B, neither one can earn a living today because we're
down to a situation where there's HBO and pay-per-view so if HBO
says they won't do a fight except Whitaker-Trinidad, then it's
going to happen because there's no alternative for the promoters to
take the fighters anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, even the return of (Mike) Tyson is
counterproductive for the sport because he takes the focus away
from boxing. It becomes a circus that reflects badly on boxing.
Personally, I think time may be running out on boxing. We're
beginning to see our fan base erode and our corporate sponsorship
erode. Either we get a national commission with clout or we've got
no shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   You see some odd things at the fights. Here's one of them. Early
last week, a young Japanese man appeared at the MGM Grand in Las
Vegas with a huge ``Team Tyson'' tattoo on his forearm, complete
with tiger, and Tyson's likeness on his biceps. He spoke no English
but had come from Osaka to see Tyson fight, as he had many times
before. Tyson's manager, Shelly Finkel, met him in the lobby and
asked why he was such a fanatical Tyson supporter. The young man
told Finkel that on her death bed, his grandmother had told him to
follow Tyson and to be like him. When Finkel related the story to
Tyson, the former heavyweight champion replied, ``What the
(expletive) was wrong with his grandmother?'' . . . Here's another
story that will go basically unnoticed. While Tyson earned $10
million Saturday night and reportedly had another $13 million
advanced to him from future purses by Showtime to pay off IRS
liens, and while Francois Botha grossed $1.8 million, veteran
boxing judge Art Lurie had to turn down a $4,000 payday to work the
fight because he is a frequent golfing partner of Botha's at the
Las Vegas Country Club. Lurie had to settle for $500 for judging
one of the undercard fights . . . Already scrambling to replace a
canceled March appearance by Prince Naseem Hamed with a title shot
for former Olympic gold medalist David Reid, HBO Sports senior vice
president for programming Lou DiBella also had to scurry to flesh
out his Feb. 27 card after Shannon Briggs pulled out of a main
event with Lou Savarese at Madison Square Garden. HBO urged
Briggs's manager, Marc Roberts, to persuade Briggs to go through
with the bout, otherwise he might have seen the last of his fighter
on HBO because this is not the first problem he's caused the
network. Briggs did not relent, though, and the bout has been
replaced with a better fight: World Boxing Council lightweight
champion Cesar Bazan (34-2-1, 23 KOs) in a rematch with the man he
took the title from, Stevie Johnston (25-1, 14 KOs). The co-feature
remains International Boxing Federation light heavyweight champion
Reggie Johnson vs. Will Taylor, with HBO hoping to get Johnson to
fight Roy Jones Jr. next . . . Speaking of problems, HBO's
contractual ones with Hamed have been ironed out and he will fight
on the network April 10 in London. No opponent has yet been
scheduled but several are under discussion. The sides reached
agreement on a contract extension that increased Hamed's share of
the take while extending HBO's exclusive rights to his fights in
the US. HBO also will put Marco Antonio Barrera on the next two
Hamed undercards, trying to build him up for a potential November
pay-per-view fight with Hamed in the US . . . Meanwhile, Hamed's
former promoter, Frank Warren, just signed a $12 million check over
to King to end their contractual relationship after King beat him
in a lawsuit in England. Coincidentally, their relationship began
because King wanted to get his hands on Hamed and bring him to
Showtime. ``Best $12 million I ever spent,'' Warren said . . . King
may be out of Tyson's life but he wasn't out of Saturday night's
Tyson-Botha fight. His son, Carl King, still holds a contract with
Botha that gives him 16.7 percent of this purse. Botha's manager,
Sterling McPherson, gets the same percentage and is trying to
challenge King's claim with the Nevada Athletic Commission, saying,
``The difference is, I've helped Botha's career and helped him get
this fight with Tyson while Carl hasn't done anything. I've got the
feeling he thinks he's going to just come in the day of the fight
and collect $300,000.'' The commission will put the manager's end
of Botha's purse in escrow pending a postfight hearing . . . WBC
super featherweight champion Floyd Mayweather Jr. (19-0) returns
home to Van Andel Arena in Grand Rapids, Mich., Feb. 17 to make his
second title defense vs. Carlos Rios (44-2-1). He will receive the
key to the city that week as well as a relatively easy title
defense on TNT network. On the same card, ageless Jorge Paez
(62-12-4) faces former world champion Tom ``Boom Boom'' Johnson
(47-5-1) . . . Word is Mayweather's father, Floyd Sr., was irate to
learn that his son sat at Tyson's side during Tyson's
obscenity-laden meeting with a group of media last Monday.
Believing that kind of publicity is not good for young Mayweather
and fearing what the 21-year-old champion might conclude from
watching Tyson, the father reportedly told friends, ``I'm a ghetto
man myself, but there's something severely wrong with that man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
