<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-LPGAHAL     01-16 2237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-LPGAHALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LPGA'S HALL MANAGES TO RELAX A LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are about to change the lock, but you can't say they are
swinging open the door to the LPGA Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   It is universally regarded as the sports shrine with the
toughest standards for entrance, and that won't change, even if, as
expected, the player membership of the LPGA votes for the new
criteria. For more than 10 years, there has been talk of relaxing
the requirements, and there are those who feel they aren't going
far enough.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, players must meet one of these rigid standards:
(1) at least 30 wins, two of them majors; (2) 35 wins, one of them
a major; or (3) 40 wins. Talk about the bar being high. It is so
high that only 13 players have been inducted, a very exclusive club
indeed. (The other women who make up the 15-member Hall of Fame are
Dinah Shore, an honorary inductee for basically putting the game as
we know it on the map, and Betty Jameson, winner of 10 events
between 1947-55. The first Hall of Fame class, in 1951, was voted
in by members of the media and included Jameson.)
</P>
<P>
   The roll call includes no-brainers such as Patty Berg, Babe
Didrikson Zaharias, Kathy Whitworth, and Nancy Lopez, but there are
glaring omissions, such as Donna Caponi (24 wins, four majors),
Judy Rankin (26, 0), Sandra Palmer (19, 1), and Marlene Hagge (25,
1).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's abominable that they aren't in,'' says Jane Blalock, who
gives way to modesty in not adding her name to that list. She, too,
belongs, if for no other reason than her remarkable accomplishment
of making the cut in every tournament she entered from 1969-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why have a Hall of Fame?'' asks Blalock, the former New
Hampshire and New England Amateur champion who won 27 times (no
majors) in her 19 years on Tour. ``For what purpose? It should be
to honor people for great contributions to the sport, but they have
made it so sacred, with so few in it, that it's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you think this is simply the view of a bitter woman on
the outside looking in, consider what Patty Sheehan said after
qualifying for the Hall of Fame in 1993: ``They better change the
criteria or they are going to have a Hall of Fame with nothing but
dead players in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the bar is about to be lowered, ever so slightly, and two
current players will reap immediate fame. Amy Alcott and Beth
Daniel will meet the new four standards: (1) a major championship;
(2) at least one Player of the Year honor; (3) at least one Vare
Trophy for low scoring average; (4) 27 career points, with 1 point
for each victory, 2 for a major.
</P>
<P>
   This is great news for Alcott (29 victories, five of them
majors) and Daniel (32 wins, one major), two quality acts for a
long time, but what of those aforementioned stars? Those who helped
keep the Tour afloat all those years when few were watching? They
are left on the outside because the new criteria will not be
retroactive; they will apply only to those active in 1998 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A veterans committee will be created to review the
accomplishments of players such as Rankin and Caponi, but it seems
a slight to players who contributed so much to the game. Blalock
said she was introduced as a Hall of Famer at a recent dinner and
felt embarrassed. ``I feel as if our self-respect is being
attacked,'' says Blalock, who runs a sports management agency in
Boston, ``that we must defend ourselves for not having achieved
something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Hall of Fame should reward excellence, longevity, great
play,'' she says. ``But the Tour is different than it was in the
'50s and '60s. It is just so much harder to win now.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcott has been looking for that one painfully elusive win, her
first since the 1991 Dinah Shore, and while she thinks she still
has it in her (``I would like to win my way in''), her honor could
come via the ballot, not a march into the winner's circle. If
that's the case, Alcott need not apologize, for she earned her way
into the Hall of Fame a long time ago, requirements
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standards are tough,'' says Alcott. ``But they should be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   No argument here, but they shouldn't be as tough as they are,
not when you consider that a win today is so much harder to achieve
than it was when these standards were established. There is a place
for subjectivity, for giving weight to personality and credit to
those players who truly left the game better than it was.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Say Jack Nicklaus, think George Archer? Not usually, which is
not to show disrespect to Archer, the former Masters champ and one
of the most underrated players of his era. But Archer came to mind
when it was announced last week that Nicklaus, who turns 59
Thursday, will have hip replacement surgery, thus ending a string
of Masters appearances that began in 1959. He will need 4-6 months
to recuperate and there is no timetable for his return to
competition. A few years ago, Archer walked away from competition,
had the same kind of surgery, and last summer the tall, quiet man
from Northern California returned to cash a winner's check on the
Senior Tour. Can Nicklaus return as dramatically? Why not? He is
the most celebrated player in the sport's history, and if you need
a reminder of his greatness, think back to only April 1998, when he
battled kids half his age and became the oldest player to record a
top 10 finish in the Masters, finishing just three shots off the
lead. But what fuels Nicklaus's desire to get healthy and live
without the pain in his hip is not so much a thirst for more glory;
it is more celebratory, for in 2000 he would like to play all four
majors. The venues are special to him: Augusta National needs no
introduction, as he has won the green jacket six times; Pebble
Beach is where he won the US Open in 1972; St. Andrews was home for
two of his three Claret Jug triumphs; Valhalla in Louisville is a
course he designed, one in which he takes great pride. It seems
fitting to welcome in a new century of golf with the most
significant player from the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   So you say it's hard to fathom a Masters without Nicklaus? Does
the return of Seve Ballesteros to The Players Championship help?
Probably not, since you probably didn't realize that the Spaniard
had not been invited to the annual March gala since 1995. His game
certainly has not reminded anyone of vintage Ballesteros, so why
the change of heart? Perhaps it's hard to say no to a guy whose
career accomplishments are being hailed with the ultimate honor. A
few days before TPC _ and a short drive up the road _ Ballesteros
will be inducted into the World Golf Hall of Fame, so it seemed
natural to extend an invitation and help soothe bad feelings.
Ballesteros reportedly was angered at not being invited to last
year's TPC . . . He is ranked 52d in the world, but little is known
about Frankie Minoza of the Philippines, other than the fact he is
39 and a regular on the Japanese PGA Tour. Those who scoff at the
world rankings will be interested to see how Minoza fares in early
February when he tees it up in the Benson &AMP; Hedges Malaysian Open,
an event sanctioned jointly by the European PGA Tour. With Ryder
Cup points available, some iron has already committed, namely Lee
Westwood and Darren Clarke . . . During the never-ending coverage
of Michael Jordan's second retirement from the NBA, he noted that
he wanted to spend more time with his children _ or was it more
time with his golf clubs? Jordan will play in the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic Pro-Am, which begins Wednesday, and has been invited to
play in the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am two weeks later. Be
ready for more TV time devoted to Jordan (and the nauseating
Charles Barkley) than to those at the top of the leaderboard . . .
Nick Faldo ended 1998 on the upswing, with a strong effort at the
World Cup, and he talked of a renewed commitment to the European
Tour in hopes of qualifying for the Ryder Cup. Two rounds do not a
season make, but 1999 is off to a rocky start for the 41-year-old
Englishman. He opened with a 77 at the South African PGA Thursday
and, when asked if he were surprised, he told reporters: ``There
are no surprises anymore, just disappointments.'' Faldo didn't have
to wait long to prove himself correct, for he shot 76 Saturday and
was off to pack his bags, perhaps sharing a ride with countryman
Justin Rose, last summer's teen-age wonder who continues to hack it
around as a pro. He shot 78-74 . . . Packing bags is part of Fran
Quinn's lifestyle. The pride of Northborough was in Florida last
week, missing the cut at the first Nike Tour stop of the year.
Sunday he's playing in the final round of the South African PGA
championship, having shot 68-73 to make the cut . . . Another Bay
Stater, Geoff Sisk, started bogey-bogey-bogey at the Sony Open in
Hawaii, which is no way to embark upon a rookie campaign. Sisk
finished with a 77 Thursday and came back with a 72 Friday, but
missed the cut and was off to his next stop, the Hope Chrysler
Classic . . . Tough break for Retief Goosen. Literally, that is. He
fractured an arm skiing during the Christmas holiday and had to
withdraw from the South African PGA, just three months after
helping that country to a second straight Dunhill Cup victory . . .
What has been rumored for months may be made official this week:
The 2005 Ryder Cup in Ireland will be held at the K Club in
Straffan, County Kildaire . . . Ivan Lendl was awarded a sponsor's
exemption into this past week's Nike Tour stop and shot 79-77.
Please, find the man a senior tennis circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   News that the LPGA has embraced the Futures Tour as its official
developmental circuit is wonderful for players such as Pam
Kerrigan. The Franklin native is an instructor at the Mike Adams
Academy of Golf at PGA National in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., but at
34 she still has aspirations of playing professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be huge,'' says Kerrigan. ``Hopefully, if they take
it under their wing, it will be as great as the Nike Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The Futures Tour has been around for 19 years, and Kerrigan gave
it a shot a few years ago. But it was ``not up to par'' so she
began teaching. Last summer, Kerrigan played in a few Futures
events, and found that things had improved. Better venues. Better
fields. Better competition. Now that it is to the LPGA what the
Nike is to the PGA Tour, Kerrigan is seriously thinking about
joining full-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I didn't play any events until June and played
catch-up all summer,'' says Kerrigan. ``I would think about playing
it all year. It's a better measure than Tour School for getting
your card.''
</P>
<P>
   At her annual trip to Tour School last fall, Kerrigan fell one
shot shy. ``Very disappointing, to say the least,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The top three on the Futures money list will automatically get
cards for the next LPGA Tour season, and while Kerrigan and others
had hoped that figure would be five or 10, it is still a more
inviting option than Tour School.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 19 Futures events in 1999, and while the money is
small (total purses will be in the vicinity of $1 million), it is a
link to the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the growing number of women worldwide entering the game,
it was evident to me there was a growing chasm between amateur or
collegiate golf and the LPGA Tour,'' says LPGA commissioner Jim
Ritts. ``This continues to ensure that potential stars are not
being lost in that chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour will make its annual stop in Vermont, at Green Mountain
National GC at Killington July 22-24, and a second New England date
_ at Blue Run GC in Avon, Conn., July 15-17 _ has been added.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Smoke-free restaurants are part of our culture. But smoke-free
golf courses? Don't choke on those cigars, gentlemen, but last
weekend on the PGA Tour of Australia they played the SmokeFree
Victorian Open in Melbourne. A gent by the name of Kenny Druce won,
but what got more press Down Under was the sponsor's request that
holes 1, 10, and 17 (and the clubhouse) be smoke-free. In one
newspaper, defending champion Brad King was pictured with a
cigarette, and the accompanying story detailed little about his
golf, but lots about his grip on the butts. King missed the cut,
then criticized the journalists, claiming he had honored the
smoke-free holes. Smoke-free golf courses? Geeesh. And some think
equipment makers have gone too far . . . Just so you don't think
you have cornered the market on inconsistency, take note: In that
Melbourne event, Matthew Millar shot 66 to share the first-round
lead _ then put up an 81 and missed the cut. Justin McKenzie opened
with a 68 before going home early with an 80. Feel better about
that 80-96 now? . . . No surprise to those who know or have taken
lessons from her, but Holly Ridge GC head professional Jane Frost
was cited as one of America's top 100 teachers by Golf magazine.
Also honored: Kevin Walker of Nantucket GC and Keith Lyford of the
Cranwell Golf School in Lenox . . . On these cold winter days, no
doubt Frank Leist can still manage a warm smile looking back on his
summer accomplishment. The longtime member at Brae Burn CC in West
Newton proved quite efficient at the fourth hole of the club's
nine-hole ``Highland Course.'' In consecutive rounds, Leist
recorded three birdies and an ace, all with a 4-iron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
