</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS SHOULD BE SKY-HIGH FOR ELWAY'S HOME FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sixteen seasons. Almost 30 miles of passing yardage.
More than 3,000 yards rushing. Three hundred touchdown passes.
Twenty playoff games. A couple dozen impossible comebacks.
Seventeen car dealerships. One Super Bowl championship.
</P>
<P>
   . . . so far.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway, who hit .318 for one of George Steinbrenner's farm
clubs a couple of lifetimes ago, Sunday will take the field at Mile
High Stadium for the last time. The defending Super Bowl champion
Broncos play Bill Parcells's upstart Jets for the AFC Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Elway isn't saying for sure that this is the
last roundup, but even his coach, the maniacal Mike Shanahan,
conceded Friday, ``Chances are, this will be John's last game at
Mile High. Everyone knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows, just as we all knew Michael Jordan was done in
Salt Lake City last June when he won his sixth and final NBA
championship. Jordan made it official last week, and his retirement
did not go unnoticed in the Elway household. There were many who
felt Stanford John should stop last January when he finally won a
Super Bowl, but he came back for one more ride.
</P>
<P>
   Elway on Jordan: ``I just looked at him and realized what he had
done, even though I didn't want to see him retire. He walked away
even though he still had a lot of basketball in him. No, I didn't
compare it to my situation. I think I'll always have a lot of
football in me _ whether I can play or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks here in the Rockies are preparing for a big sendoff. The
local CBS-TV affiliate is orchestrating a postgame ``El-way'' chant
and asking fans to linger for a lengthy tribute. Shanahan said he
expects the loudest crowd in the history of Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be great, but I guess I'm not going to look at it that
way,'' Elway said of the proposed farewell kiss. ``The fans have
always been great here. They were before I got here and they have
been in my 16 seasons. They're there when we win and they've been
there when we've lost. They are the best fans of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway said there is no timetable for his decision (sounding a
lot like Mike), and that there will be no family vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He did say, ``I don't know how I'm going to handle being away
from football. Maybe after six months, I'll break out in hives.
Right now, I'm thinking about the Jets. They're at the top of the
list. I haven't gone past Sunday. That's my total focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said, ``Certainly, he is the prototype NFL quarterback.
You think of a guy you'd like to have play for your team. I've had
the opportunity to witness first-hand and he's right up there with
the very best that ever played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway said his favorite conference championship memory was the
15-play, 98-yard drive against the Cleveland Browns that led to an
overtime victory (``It was my fourth year and kind of put me on the
map. It was a nostalgic old stadium. That's probably the highlight
of all my championship games.'') Asked about his favorite Mile High
moment, he cited a similar playoff drive against the Houston Oilers
in 1991 that led to a game-winning field goal. No one has to ask
about his career highlight: It's the Super Bowl victory over the
Packers in San Diego last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Elway has always been a team player,'' said Shanahan.
``He never wanted the focus on John Elway, and in my opinion, that
makes him the greatest ever to play.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be another Super Bowl before he hangs up his helmet.
But first, the Broncos have to get past the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience helps,'' said Elway. ``We come into this game a
little different. We've won a Super Bowl and we're over that hump.
I think we're pretty balanced. But even though we're home, we still
have to go out and play a good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway's premier weapon is running back Terrell Davis, who
shredded the Dolphins with 199 yards in last week's 38-3 blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, when the game is over, the crowd will roar one last
time for John Elway as he makes his final trek toward the south
stands and disappears from view for the final time at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
