<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKESFALCONS-KICK     01-16 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKESFALCONS-KICKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKERS FOLLOWING IN EACH OTHER'S FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Flip open the phone book for Minneapolis-St. Paul
and start counting the ``Andersons.'' Page after page after page of
them, nearly 16 pages of ``Andersons.''
</P>
<P>
   Scandinavians apparently found the chill of this icebox very
familiar, so reminiscent of their homes in Sweden, Norway, and
Denmark that many settled here in the upper Midwest. And there were
many ``Andersons'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   Start counting. Begin with the 53 ``A. Andersons'' on the first
page, then count ``Aaron Anderson'' and keep going, page after page
after page, and finally, 16 pages of minute type later, end the
long count with ``Yvonne Anderson.'' All told, there are 7,684
``Andersons'' just in this rather modest section of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   And there are several variations of the name, with one of the
most numerous being ``Andersen.'' Start counting the ``Andersens,''
nearly a full page of them, one ``Andersen'' after another
``Andersen,'' all told some 382 of them.
</P>
<P>
   It is no different with football. Rest assured of this: An
``Anderson'' or an ``Andersen'' or yet another ``Anderson'' will
have a marked impact on Sunday's NFC Championship game in the
Metrodome between the Minnesota Vikings and Atlanta Falcons. And
the Minneapolis phone book notwithstanding, it is the Falcons who
have the Anderson advantage, with one ``Anderson'' (Jamal) and one
``Andersen'' (Morten) while the hometown Vikings must make do with
a solitary ``Anderson'' (Gary).
</P>
<P>
   But the Minnesota ``Anderson'' is perfect this season _ and who,
in any occupation, can say that? _ while the Falcons' ``Anderson''
is merely glittering like a gem and Atlanta's ``Andersen'' has to
be content with just being very good. It could be confusing if it
weren't so fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in football knows about the Falcons' superior runner,
Jamal Anderson. But a fascinating subplot could develop if Sunday's
game is close _ and it figures to be _ between Gary Anderson of the
Minnesota and Morten Andersen of Atlanta. Each is the placekicker
for his team, but that is far from the only similarity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fact their last names are nearly identical,
consider these head-scratchers for the kickers:
</P>
<P>
   Each has played 17 seasons in the NFL; they were the first two
kickers taken in the 1982 draft. Morten Andersen broke in with New
Orleans just as Archie Manning was winding up his career and Gary
Anderson began in Pittsburgh as Terry Bradshaw was winding down
there.
</P>
<P>
   Each was born outside the United States, Andersen in Struer,
Denmark, and Anderson in Durban, South Africa. Each came to the US
when he was 17 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen has kicked in 260 NFL games; Anderson has kicked in
261.
</P>
<P>
   Each has made 99 percent of his point-after attempts. Andersen
has made 401 of 510 field goal attempts, while Anderson has been
successful on 420 of 525 attempts. The percentage for each is right
around 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Each stayed with his first team for 13 years. Andersen moved to
Atlanta from New Orleans, Anderson went to Philadelphia after the
Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is second in career scoring (1,845 points), Andersen is
third (1,761). Anderson is first in career field goals with 420,
Andersen is second with 401.
</P>
<P>
   And they are, arguably, the two best pure kickers ever. Both of
them, Anderson and Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody, but nobody comes close to us,'' said the Vikings'
Anderson. ``There are some good kickers in the league but, until
they've done it for 17 years, they're in a different category.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made for the last 15 years about the quarterback
Class of '83, with Dan Marino, John Elway, Jim Kelly, Tony Eason,
and Ken O'Brien, but how about the kicker Class of '82?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the only ones from the Class of '82 still
around,'' said the Falcons' Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Andersen kicks the ball farther than Anderson
(Andersen has made as many 50-yard-plus field goals _ 35 _ as
Anderson has attempted). But Anderson is absolutely rhythmic in his
kicking. Anderson's field goals not only are always good _ at least
this season _ but they usually seem to split the uprights perfectly
in two. Few close calls with Anderson's field goals.
</P>
<P>
   And this year Anderson was perfect in his kicking, 35 of 35
field goals and 59 of 59 extra points. Anderson's perfect season
was the first in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good part of it is that I kick indoors now,'' said Anderson,
who played for a dome team for the first time this season. Still,
Anderson is not the first kicker ever to kick in a dome and, as he
good-naturedly points out, Andersen has played for a dome team his
entire career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not taking anything away from Morten, because he's a
tremendous kicker,'' said Anderson. ``He's a tremendous
long-distance kicker. But when you kick indoors, you're going to
try longer kicks. You don't have to worry about the wind or cold or
rain or snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the evidence, Anderson and Andersen are not twins.
The Falcons' Andersen has a shoe size of 12, while Minnesota's
Anderson has a more petite shoe, size 8.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Andersen kicks with his left foot, Anderson kicks with his
right.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Andersen already has a twin, a brother by the name of
Jakob.
</P>
<P>
   That said, though, in a state full of ``Andersons'' and
``Andersens,'' Gary and Morten may be the most noticeable of them
all Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
