<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATTERSO     01-16 2963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATTERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERSON NO PURPLE PATRIOT EATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The media love Jimmy Hitchcock, the former Patriot who tells us
how lousy everything was in New England.
</P>
<P>
   He is a player scorned, and now he has the right to gloat as a
member of the Minnesota Vikings, who will be in the Super Bowl if
they can get past the Atlanta Falcons Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of the Vikings' defense _ from 29th in the
league last season to 13th _ seems to have come about without major
personnel changes. Hitchcock was added at cornerback, and the only
other change was on the coaching staff, where Andre Patterson, also
a former Patriot (he assisted line coach Ray Hamilton), seems to
have had quite an effect on the aggressive Minnesota front line.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hitchcock, Patterson left the Patriots on good terms and
has no ax to grind. In fact, while he was grooming his players in
Minnesota this season, he also kept an eye on his former Patriot
players, particularly Chad Eaton, whom he also coached at
Washington State. Patterson, in fact, was the guy who saved Drew
Bledsoe's backside. Eaton would often get overanxious in practice
at Washington State and try to sack Bledsoe, who was off limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny,'' said Patterson. ``Chad was so excited in
practice. He gave everything in the games and everything in
practice. I'd have to say, `Don't touch Drew or you'll sit!' And he
finally got the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching Chad develop into the player he is now is a great
sense of joy for me. I knew when I had him at Washington State that
he had a chance to be a dominating defensive lineman in the NFL.
And we're seeing now that he's on his way to being that. All he
ever needed was a chance and for someone to believe in him, and
those coaches in New England _ Ray, Sid (defensive coordinator
Steve Sidwell) and Pete (Carroll) _ have given him the chance and
now he's delivering for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson certainly provides a different perspective on the
Patriots than Hitchcock. Hitchcock hated Bill Parcells and got his
chance to be a starter under Carroll, but turned on Carroll after
he was traded to the Vikings during last year's draft. Hitchcock
claims that Carroll promised him he'd be a starter and wouldn't be
traded. Problem is, personnel man Bobby Grier made the deal after
the Patriots decided to take Tebucky Jones with their second pick
in the first round; with Steve Israel and Chris Canty already
aboard, they felt Hitchcock was expendable.
</P>
<P>
   We know how Hitchcock feels about Carroll; how does Patterson
feel about him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a terrific football coach,'' said Patterson. ``I've taken
a lot of the things that Pete and Steve Sidwell and Ray Hamilton
taught me here to the Vikings. I enjoyed my time in New England. I
enjoyed all of the people, the players, everyone around the
organization. I went from a very good situation to a great
situation. I couldn't have asked for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson was asked about the offseason conditioning programs in
New England and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised when I left New England _ where the
program, I thought, was very well attended _ to come here where
guys are just scattered all over the place,'' he said. ``There are
guys who stay here and take part, but for the most part guys go off
to other places and condition themselves. I know that I don't see
my guys until the minicamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Denny Green does is, when you leave after the season he
tells each and every one of them that if they're not in shape when
they show up here for training camp, they're in jeopardy of losing
their jobs. Of course, you have guys like Cris Carter and Jake Reed
who just head down to Florida and work out like crazy. We have
players with a lot of pride when it comes to conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to conclude that the importance of offseason
conditioning programs is greatly exaggerated. The Vikings are 16-1.
</P>
<P>
   Around the league, attendance at strength and conditioning
programs is improving, as workout bonuses are added to contracts,
but the majority of teams have poorer attendance than the Patriots.
Tampa Bay and Denver seem to lead the pack. Players like living
year-around in Florida, where there is no state income tax, and in
Denver, because of the rich-and-famous lifestyle in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The best-attended program in the Northeast is the Jets', on Long
Island, where the fear that Bill Parcells instills in players has
made the program there as successful as it once was in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But who would want to stay in Minneapolis in winter?
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Viking Henry Thomas does not take part in the Patriots'
program and never took part in Minnesota's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too cold,'' said Thomas. ``Players want to go somewhere
to work out where it's hot and where they feel they're getting a
better workout. I stay in Houston. I understand I have to be in the
best shape I can be in when training camp starts. I understand the
consequences. Maybe some players don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Patriots strength coach Johnny Parker, one of
the best in the business, might just be one of those guys who would
think 99.9 percent attendance was too low? Probably. And that
attitude is a great one to have.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson also said it's not Willie McGinest's fault that he's
injured so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see a better-conditioned athlete,'' said Patterson.
``He works out all winter. If he didn't work out, if he didn't take
care of himself, OK, you'd say that's the reason he gets hurt. But
Willie is someone who enjoys working out. It's not torturous work
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you just have to say that it's bad luck. Maybe
people don't want to hear that. But I had the same situation here
with Derrick Alexander. Everybody kept telling me he was going to
be a good player but they couldn't keep him on the field. This
year, we kept him on the field and he's blossomed into a pretty big
force on our defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's going to happen to Willie. He's already been to
a Pro Bowl, and those guys are usually motivated to get the status
back. He's a great athlete. What people have to understand is that
Willie plays a very violent position.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson also shed some light on Green. Don't forget, when
Green returned to the Vikings at the start of training camp, he had
a lot to prove. After the publication of a controversial book, in
which he talked about buying part of the team, nearly got him
fired, Green returned stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first day of camp, Denny outlined to the team the
goals that he wanted to accomplish,'' said Patterson. ``And
everybody was with him. Each day, each week, the team tried to meet
those expectations. It's been a beautiful thing to watch as we've
gone through the season. Denny is the ultimate motivator and he has
a team that believes in everything he says and will go through a
wall for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson and the other Minnesota coaches have been awarded
contract extensions, though offensive coordinator Brian Billick may
leave to take a head job.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the NFC Championship game, Patterson said he
almost fell into the trap that most Falcons opponents have this
season: concentrating solely on Jamal Anderson and forgetting the
passing game. ``We have to be disciplined in our gaps,'' said
Patterson. ``What I have seen on Jamal is that he'll get his 3 or 4
yards for the first three quarters and then he'll start busting it
loose in the fourth quarter for 10-, 20-yard gains. What teams do
is they're so conscious of him they'll bring their safeties up to
stop him; meanwhile the two receivers are killing you. (Chris)
Chandler can hit you deep, and you have to be conscious of that and
conscious of the fact you need to have help in coverage of Tony
Martin and Terance Mathis.'' . . . The Patriots did the right thing
in the end by allowing Carroll to return as head coach. Give Bob
Kraft credit for not buckling under the pressure of the media and
talk-show blowhards. He did what a fair man would do, retaining a
coach that had taken the team to the playoffs despite injuries to
16 starters. Kraft expects Carroll to improve on some of his
shortcomings and will give him more authority to rule with a
stricter hand and leave no doubt that he is in charge. Kudos also
to Grier for recognizing that the locker room bickering was just a
case of players being players. They were the same players who
bickered when Parcells was here because he was too strict. They
wanted to be treated as adults, to motivate themselves, but when
they got their chance, they dropped the ball. Next year will be
different . . . Right before last year's draft, Irving Fryar was
asked by this reporter whether teams should stay away from players
who draw questions about their character, such as Randy Moss. His
response: ``When I see Randy Moss, I see myself. He has the talent,
the speed, and the love of the game. He might have taken a wrong
turn or two. But I got my life together because there were enough
people out there who showed me a little love and direction. If you
can surround him with the right players and coaches to show him the
right way to do things and act, it would be crazy to pass on a
talent like that.'' Fryar was a prophet. Moss may be the one
receiver in the league that nobody can cover. Speaking of Fryar, he
hasn't necessarily retired from football, just the Philadelphia
Eagles. His agent, Michael George, said Fryar ``would return to the
NFL with a Super Bowl contender.'' The leader in the clubhouse
right now is Green Bay, where Fryar could be reunited with Ray
Rhodes, his coach in Philadelphia. Fryar also would not be opposed
to returning to New England as a secondary receiver . . . The
Patriots have received more than 30 proposals to move their
training camp from Smithfield, R.I. One of them is from
Springfield, where the political machine thinks it can capitalize
on the Patriots' need for a Western Massachusetts season-ticket
base; but team officials say they already have one. The Patriots
have contracted with the state of Connecticut to build a $15
million facility somewhere in the state . . . Billick appears to be
the top choice in Cleveland, with Jacksonville offensive
coordinator Chris Palmer a close second. Palmer is also getting
serious consideration in Baltimore. It appears that Browns boss
Carmen Policy doesn't want a big-name coach after having personal
problems with Bill Walsh in San Francisco, which is why Policy
never made a bid for Mike Holmgren. One man the Cleveland media and
fans don't want back is Bill Belichick, who had four losing seasons
in five years of coaching the old Browns; despite his obvious skill
on defense, he was a complete bust handling the offense . . . Dom
Capers, fired in Carolina, appears to be the front-runner in Kansas
City . . . Speaking of Palmer, there were several reports around
the country that the Patriots were calling a press conference last
week to announce him as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Why not take some ex-Patriots out of their roles as critics,
commentators, and businessmen and let them coach the team? Here's
our suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   Assistant head coach: Andre Tippett.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator/quarterbacks coach: Steve Grogan.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach: John Hannah.
</P>
<P>
   Tight ends coach: Don Hasselbeck.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers coach: Randy Vataha.
</P>
<P>
   Running backs coach: Mosi Tatupu.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive assistant coach: Jim Rourke (never a Patriot, but a
personal favorite).
</P>
<P>
   Special teams/long snapping coach: Steve DeOssie.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking coaches: Gino Cappelletti, John Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator: Steve Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line coach: Fred Smerlas.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant defensive line coach: Mike Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers coach: Vincent Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs coach: Tim Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive assistant coaches: Roland James, Ronnie Lippett, Jim
Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   The head coach would be Hamilton, the current defensive line
coach, because he has the most experience.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Look for Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams, who has selected
Woolf Associates in Boston to represent him, to go to spring
training with the Texas Rangers but not make the squad. He'll
likely reject a demotion to the minors and be ready for the NFL
draft. The Redskins, who have the fifth and 11th picks, may trade
up to get Williams . . . Don't bet the ranch that Terry Glenn will
spend any more time in Parker's strength program. His agent, Jimmy
Gould, said, ``Terry will do what he thinks is best for himself. I
think there's a misconception out there that Terry wasn't in good
shape. He showed up to camp in very good shape. In addition to
taking part in some of the workouts in Foxborough, Terry did his
own and he also spent a week at Cris Carter's camp in Minnesota.
For Terry, it's been more a case of bad luck than lack of
conditioning.'' . . . Scituate's Jim Campbell was selected as the
all-time Patriots fan in a promotion run by the NFL in conjunction
with Visa. One fan was selected from each NFL city to be inducted
into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio, in ceremonies
Sunday. Campbell has been a Patriot season ticket-holder for all 39
years of the team's existence and once put off heart surgery to
attend a game . . . Some organizations are getting away from the
old boy network and taking chances on young, inexperienced head
coaches. One is clearly the Chargers, who hired young Mike Riley
from Oregon State, where he accumulated an 8-14 record. Riley was
once offensive coordinator at Southern Cal, a position that often
brings great exposure, and it didn't hurt that the son of San Diego
general manager Bobby Beathard played for Riley. Beathard wanted a
young, offensive-type coach who could help quarterback Ryan Leaf
develop and mature. Andy Reid, the quarterbacks coach for the
Packers, was selected for the same reasons by the Eagles, who have
the second pick in the draft and will likely take Williams or trade
down to get a quarterback. Reid is well-respected and could
probably make a living as a motivational speaker. In his interview
with the Eagles, Reid was extremely positive about a pretty bleak
situation and very detailed; he even explained how to execute an
effective screen pass, something the Eagles haven't been able to do
in four years. Whether he can run an entire team is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's increasingly clear how weighty the job of head coach can
be. Marty Schottenheimer had to resign after 10 years and take time
away from the game. Jimmy Johnson almost quit last week, only to be
talked out of it by Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga, who allowed
Johnson to hire Dave Wannstedt as assistant head coach. June Jones
left San Diego for the University of Hawaii, hoping to provide a
better lifestyle for his family, which includes a sick wife. Dennis
Erickson took Riley's job at Oregon State rather than try for
another pro job. Owners are becoming more unrealistic with their
demands on coaches, demands they would never make on CEOs of major
corporations. In some places _ including New England _ anything
short of the Super Bowl is considered failure. Fans and
front-office types are forgetting that providing entertainment and
building competitive teams for the long term are just as important
as winning one Super Bowl. The Patriots played some of the most
entertaining games in the league this season, but that seemed to be
forgotten when they lost in the wild-card game _ without their
starting quarterback, their best receiver, and other key players.
And because of that, people actually called for the coach's head.
Amazing . . . Former Patriots offensive coordinator Larry Kennan
could have had the Hawaii job before Jones came into the picture
but held off. Kennan could land on another NFL staff. Here is his
assessment of the remaining teams. The Vikings: ``Nobody throws the
deep ball better than Randall Cunningham, and I'm not sure that
anyone can cover Randy Moss. They have an explosive offense, an
explosive passing game that can't be rivaled.'' The Jets: ``I'm
amazed that Bill Parcells is still labeled as a guy who likes to
run the ball. He hasn't had a running team in the last eight years.
The Jets have been fun to watch. Because I coached Curtis (Martin),
I root for him. He's benefitted from a very good offensive line. I
think the difference there is Kevin Mawae. I coached Kevin in
Seattle and the Seahwaks made a huge mistake letting him go. He's a
very athletic center and he's very instrumental in the running
game.'' The Falcons: ``Chris Chandler has come a long way. He
throws the deep ball very well and teams have to respect that.''
The Broncos: ``They are the complete football team. They're
ferocious on defense, and Terrell Davis just controls the clock so
well.'' . . . The broken ankle of defensive lineman Brandon
Mitchell has healed, and the Patriots expect him to start at tackle
or end next season, which is one reason they exposed Ferric Collons
in the expansion draft. Mitchell, who lives in Louisiana, is
dealing with the recent death of his grandfather, who raised him .
. . Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy, both of whom may break the bank this
offseason, worked out at Foxborough all week in preparation for the
Pro Bowl Feb. 7 in Honolulu . . . Carroll is expected to choose an
offensive line coach and receivers coach this week. One offensive
line coach who may become available is Kansas City's Mike Solari,
who worked with Carroll in San Francisco . . . Another publicist
entered the world last week: David Samuel James, at 7 pounds 8
ounces and 19 1/2 inches, is the new son of Patriots director of
public relations Stacey James and his wife Beth. A belated
congratulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
