<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-COACHES-     01-16 2284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-COACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM AFTER A STORMY YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notice how quiet, how stable it is these days behind NHL
benches? A week before the All-Star Game, not a single head coach
has been fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Boston's Pat Burns, now in his 10th year as an
NHL head coach, ``these things go in cycles _ maybe it's football's
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL hasn't gone this long into a season without seeing a
coach dismissed since 1993-94, when Jim Schoenfeld replaced Terry
Murray in Washington (Jan. 27).
</P>
<P>
   ``A great business, isn't it?'' said Lindy Ruff, now in his
second season as Sabres coach. ``Sooner or later, you have to
realize that every year 10 or 11 teams are going to be under .500,
and a couple of teams are going to do very poorly. And it's just
not always the coach's fault. The prime example is New Jersey; one
year they win the Stanley Cup (1995) and the next year they don't
make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The end came voluntarily for Burns in Montreal. After four
years, he wanted a change of venue and switched to Toronto.
Reluctantly, former Leafs GM Cliff Fletcher dumped Burns 65 games
into the 1995-96 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, all of a sudden is Pat Burns not a good coach?'' said
Ruff. ``Is Roger Neilson (now leading the Flyers) not a good
coach?''
</P>
<P>
   The stability this season can be traced in part to all of the
turnover among coaches last year. During the season, Wayne Cashman
was dumped in Philadelphia, ditto for Terry Crisp in Tampa Bay and
Doug MacLean in Florida. Not to forget, either, that Ted Nolan,
Coach of the Year in 1996-97, wasn't brought back in Buffalo. Then
came the offseason purge: Pierre Page in Anaheim, Craig Hartsburg
in Chicago, Marc Crawford in Colorado, Jacques Lemaire (his choice)
in New Jersey, and Mike Murphy in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about a third of the league's coaches were given the
heave-ho.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm sure there'll be someone whacked again,'' said Burns,
``because there always is.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious candidate is Dirk Graham, the ex-Blackhawk who
is clearly out of his depth behind the Chicago bench. The Hawks
missed the playoffs last season for the first time since 1969,
leading owner Bill Wirtz to can Hartsburg not long after extending
his contract by three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing the best he can with what he has,'' said Chicago
general manager Bob Murray.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't always matter.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Word out of Vancouver early last week was that the Canucks
finally were set to deal  &UR; Pavel Bure  &LR; and general manager  &UR; Brian
Burke  &LR; hoped to have it done no later than Thursday. Come Friday
morning, still no white smoke. The place that makes the most sense
for Bure to land: Chicago, in a swap for  &UR; Tony Amonte  &LR; _ which, of
course, would mean the Canucks handing coach  &UR; Mike Keenan  &LR; the pink
slip at the same time, because it was Keenan who greased the skids
for Amonte in New York. Bure could play on a line with  &UR; Alexei
Zhamnov  &LR; _ undoubtedly enhancing Zhamnov's worth _ and Amonte could
bring some real life, along with maybe 40 or 50 goals, to the
moribund Canucks. And what better time for the Hawks to bring in a
legitimate marquee player, with  &UR; Michael Jordan  &LR; gone from the
Bulls? With no deal made, Burke figures he'll now wait until the
March trading deadline, when, he says, ``clubs are desperate.'' ...
Keenan, by the way, has abandoned his trademark forechecking
blueprint and has the Canucks playing a version of Detroit's
left-wing lock. One more team, short on talent, dumbing it down
with defense. ``We're the ones that are desperate,'' said Keenan
when apprised of Burke's remark. ``This team's got to make the
playoffs.'' ... Former Bruin  &UR; Mike Gillis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now Bure's agent,
reports that the Russian Rocket is in Moscow, ``hanging around with
the president of Belarus.'' Last week, according to Gillis, Bure
zipped through five laps at the Russian Red Army rink, timed in 79
seconds. The man holding the stopwatch: legendary coach  &UR; Viktor
Tikhonov &LR;  ... The Lightning officially gave up on ex-Bruin  &UR; Craig
Janney  &LR; last week, which is why he wasn't with the Bolts at the
Fleet last night. He's free to look around and try to make a deal,
but ultimately they could waive him, sending the 31-year-old former
Boston College Eagle to the minors for the first time. Janney: ``My
job is to create big plays and help us win games, and right now I'm
not doing it. I'm to blame for it.'' If someone will take his
salary (what remains of $1.7 million), the Bolts would let Janney
go for nothing ... Belmont Hill's  &UR; Paul Mara  &LR; didn't impress
Lightning brass at the World Junior Championships in Winnipeg. He
still figures to be the future of the Tampa blue line, but that
future could be a couple of years down the road. The seventh pick
overall in the '97 draft, the 19-year-old Mara is now in his third
season of junior hockey ...  &UR; Dave Andrews &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ex- of the IHL and the
Hartford front office, is expected to become top aide to  &UR; Craig
Patrick &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is now the Penguins' president and CEO as well as
general manager. Andrews will help with some of the dicey
bankruptcy issues confronting the team. Word around Pittsburgh is
that co-owner  &UR; Roger Marino &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ex- of Revere High, Northeastern,
and Hopkinton-based EMC, would be happy to find a buyer for his
portion of the troubled franchise, cut his losses, and walk away
from the financial nightmare ... Former Bruin  &UR; Sheldon Kennedy
 &LR; left the Manitoba Moose (IHL) last week and will play the rest of
the season in the German Elite League. True, it's another step back
from the NHL, but remember,  &UR; Brian Bellows  &LR; finished up in Germany
last year, then signed on for a ride to the Cup finals with the
Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, goalie-in-exile  &UR; Jim Carey  &LR; has
resurrected his game in Providence and will play in the AHL
All-Star Game next weekend at Philadelphia. Unwanted by the Bruins,
Carey now serves one purpose on the roster _ to be made available
for the expansion drafts this summer (Atlanta) and next (Minnesota
and Columbus) ... Does it make your heart warm to know that  &UR; Claude
Lemieux  &LR; leads all Colorado goal scorers with 17? Renews your sense
of fairness and good sportsmanship, doesn't it? ...  &UR; Grant Fuhr
 &LR; had the league buzzing 10 days ago when he said his playing days
will come to an end when his contract runs out after next season.
``I called him the next day and said, `Grant, did you mean it?'''
said  &UR; Jay Fee &LR; , &UR;  &LR; his Boston-based agent. ``I think it was a case of
his having a few aches and pains, he wasn't playing. Let's just say
he it's not a lead-pipe guarantee that it's over after next year.
He's just the kind of guy who wants to play every single game, and
when that's not happening, he gets frustrated.'' Fuhr's deal pays
$3.1 million this year and $3 million next season. He would be 38
entering the 2000-01 season, and don't be surprised if the Oilers
bring him back for a sunset tour ... Not many tears were shed
around the league when Sharks defenseman  &UR; Bryan  &LR; ``Mush''
 &UR; Marchment  &LR; separated his shoulder 10 days ago _ in a collision
with Nashville's  &UR; Sebastien Bordeleau &LR;  _ and had to go under the
knife (out a minimum of six weeks). Marchment's dirty hits have
kept emergency rooms hopping all over North America for years. It's
a tough loss for  &UR; Darryl Sutter's  &LR; defensive corps, already minus
 &UR; Gary Suter  &LR; (surgery to repair torn triceps) ... Last week, we
told you Devils defenseman  &UR; Scott Stevens  &LR; told the Sharks'  &UR; Brantt
Myhres &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a recovering alcoholic, to ``go have another drink''
during a game at New Jersey. Four days later, after tangling with
him in a fight, Buffalo's  &UR; Paul Kruse  &LR; rotated his wrist in a
drinking gesture _ meant to taunt Myhres _ as he departed for the
penalty box. There must be some interesting times when the Players'
Association calls everyone together for one of those union
brotherhood meetings. A guy tries to face up to his problems and
then his union brothers rub his face in it. Disgraceful ... LA's
 &UR; Luc Robitaille  &LR; recommitted himself to a weightlifting-to-go
program last summer and it has helped renew his scoring touch (24
goals, heading into the weekend). While he drove around the country
in a mobile home with family, he'd pull out his weights at
campsites. ``It was a little embarrassing sometimes, with people
looking at me,'' said Robitaille, who connected for his 500th
career goal a couple of weeks ago. Robitaille's regimen includes
doing situps while holding 75-pound weights.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers had some interest in acquiring  &UR; Felix Potvin  &LR; before
the Leafs dished him to Islanders last Saturday for  &UR; Bryan Berard &LR; .
But when Potvin refused to talk about a long-term deal _ his
current pact, paying $2.7 million, runs out this season _ Oiler
boss  &UR; Glen Sather  &LR; stopped talks with Leafs boss  &UR; Mike Smith &LR; . Not
hard to understand, considering the Oilers lost  &UR; Curtis Joseph  &LR; as
an unrestricted free agent to the Leafs last summer. Sather wanted
to tie up Potvin for at least four years, which would have meant
the netminder surrendering his first year of unrestricted free
agency. Smith likely would have wanted either  &UR; Roman Hamrlik  &LR; or
 &UR; Boris Mironov  &LR; off the Oiler roster ... The Leafs are figuring
that Berard, the key to revving their bankrupt power play, can
blossom under the tutelage of ex-defenseman  &UR; Pat Quinn &LR; . They could
be right. Quinn was a tough customer in his playing days, one of
the few who dared to run at  &UR; Bobby Orr &LR;  _ one time kicking No. 4
after he'd fallen in the crease in a game late in the '68-69
season. Ah, but who remembers that kind of thing, right? ... Smith
on the Berard acquisition: ``We didn't hit a home run, but we
wanted an asset.'' The other shoe to fall could be the Leafs
dealing blue liner  &UR; Jason Smith &LR; , &UR;  &LR; once a first-round New Jersey
selection (No. 18 overall), but they'll wait to see how Berard
blends into the mix before making another move. The 6-foot-3-inch
Smith could be interesting under the watch of  &UR; Jacques Laperriere
 &LR; here in Boston ... Now that he's bought into the Washington
Redskins,  &UR; Howard Milstein  &LR; will have to sell his 45 percent
interest in the Islanders _ in keeping with NFL ownership
regulations. His Islander partner,  &UR; Steve Gluckstern &LR; , &UR;  &LR; doesn't
have the dough to go it alone, but one scenario has him finding
limited partners. Another interested party is  &UR; Bob
Gutkowski &LR; , &UR;  &LR; former president of Madison Square Garden. And a third
possibility is former Islander  &UR; Clark Gillies &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now a stockbroker
on the Island, cobbling together a group and possibly taking over
as general manager. The latter move would mean buying out the
remainder of  &UR; Mike Milbury's  &LR; recently-inked five-year deal ... The
Islanders are expected to deal  &UR; Tommy Salo  &LR; now that Potvin is
their No. 1. Tampa has poked around on a deal, hoping to stop the
hemorrhaging in net that neither  &UR; Bill Ranford  &LR; nor  &UR; Corey Schwab
 &LR; can stem.  &UR; Daren Puppa &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 34 in April, remains out of the Tampa
lineup with a chronic groin injury ... Don't be surprised to see
the Blues unload the Bay State's  &UR; Jim Campbell  &LR; before the trade
deadline. Back in '91, when the Bruins made  &UR; Glen Murray  &LR; their
first-round pick, then-Boston scout  &UR; Joe Lyons  &LR; made a big pitch to
pick Campbell, who was chosen in the second round by Montreal.
Campbell has done next to nothing in his third year with the Blues,
after back-to-back 20-goal seasons ... Murray, by the way, will be
down for a few weeks after tearing up a knee while racing back on a
touch-up icing call a couple of weeks ago. When he exited, he was
LA's top performer (28 points/37 games), playing with the zip and
nastiness that the Bruins saw in him as a junior. Murray avoided
surgery, but by the time he gets back, the Kings' season could be
finished. Last week, he overexerted the knee in the weight room.
``He's an impatient patient,'' said Kings coach  &UR; Larry Robinson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Manon Rheaume  &LR; is living in Northern California these days with
husband  &UR; Gerry St. Cyr &LR; , &UR;  &LR; expecting their first child this summer.
Rheaume's agent,  &UR; Steve Bartlett &LR; , &UR;  &LR; says she hasn't given up the
thought of trying to play net for Canada in the 2002 Olympic Games
at Salt Lake City. Meanwhile, some endorsement deals still come her
way. ``Not in the numbers she saw before,'' reported Bartlett, from
his office near Rochester, N.Y. ``But she's beginning to hear from
manufacturers who might be interested in some crossover
endorsements _ athlete/mom and working mom kind of things.'' ...
Sorry to see the passing of  &UR; Doug Wickenheiser &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who died of lung
cancer Tuesday at age 37. Wickenheiser was the first pick overall
in the 1980 draft, Montreal opting to take him over local sensation
 &UR; Denis Savard  &LR; (No. 3 to Chicago). A malignant cyst was removed
from Wickenheiser's left wrist in '94, and he was believed to be in
remission until a tumor was found in his right lung in '97.  &UR; Guy
Carbonneau &LR; , who &UR;  &LR; was in Montreal with Wickenheiser at the start of
the '80s, said, ``He was always happy. He never brought his misery
to his work.'' ...  &UR; Cam Neely  &LR; played in a celebrity game last
weekend at Madison Square Garden, a fund-raiser for paralyzed actor
 &UR; Christopher Reeve &LR;  that brought in about $100,000. Some of the
Rangers' wives participated, and _ we are not making this up _  &UR; Ulf
Samuelsson's  &LR; wife requested to play on Neely's team ... Edmonton's
 &UR; Doug Weight &LR; , &UR;  &LR; recovering from knee surgery, is due back to the
lineup early next month. Limbering up on skates just after
Christmas, he lost his two front teeth when fitness expert  &UR; Daryl
Duke  &LR; errantly clipped him with his stick. ``Just a week late,''
said the good-natured Weight. ``I could have ordered 'em up for
Christmas.''
</P>
