<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN GULF GROWS AFTER PROSECUTORS MAKE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D., Ill., Fla., Ky., N.J., Ariz.)   (Eds: SUBS to rewrite throughout to ADD more on today's
presentations, senators' reaction, quotes; ADDS Schmitt to
byline.) 
 (Eds: This is a page 1 story replacing IMPEACH-REPUBS, which now
runs inside.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
consisting of biographies of four House managers is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-NOTEBOOK,
IMPEACH-EAGLES, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-ROSS, IMPEACH-RDP,
DOWD-COLUMN, EDIT-IMPEACH, IMPEACH-HOWLONG?-REVIEW,
IMPEACH-QUIXOTE-REVIEW, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-JUDGES,
IMPEACH-SCHLESINGER, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-GRAHAM) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ and ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the House managers' opening statements now
behind them, senators from the two parties spilled out of the
chamber Saturday afternoon with sharply divided opinions about the
strength of the prosecutors' case and where the trial should go
from here.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most blatant signs of the widening partisan gulf came
this weekend, when Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, suggested
to Democrats that a bipartisan group deal with the question of
witnesses. But the Democratic leader, Sen. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, quickly rebuffed him and called the idea premature.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by several Senate Republicans who are concerned about
the near party-line split over witnesses, Lott of Mississippi sent
a letter to Daschle on Friday evening, in the hope of reviving a
bipartisan discussion group. Lott has argued that the Senate should
begin talking about which witnesses it may want to call and how
they should be questioned before the Senate vote on the matter
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote this month on whether to take
depositions from witnesses, once the White House completes its
presentation and senators query both sides. If 51 senators choose
to move forward with the depositions, votes would be taken at some
point on which witnesses to summon before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that a bipartisan group of senators could
anticipate and help resolve in advance any complications that may
be presented by our hearing the testimony of witnesses,'' Lott
wrote. ``Forming a bipartisan group to consider witness issues now
may save us time and trouble in the days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle, who does not want to make it easier for Republicans
to win a vote on witnesses, turned Lott down. . Daschle responded
that discussions about witnesses should wait until the full Senate
vote on depositions. Daschle added that preliminary talks ``would
violate the bipartisan agreement that now governs our process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my hope that such arrangements will ultimately prove
unnecessary,'' Daschle wrote, ``regarding the many complicated
issues that will result if the Senate votes to call witnesses in
the impeachment proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday afternoon, after the House managers concluded their
presentation, the division in the Senate between the two parties
became increasingly obvious: Many Republicans, while stressing that
they are keeping an open mind, spoke highly of the House's case
against President Clinton. Many Democrats said outright that
Clinton's behavior, as described by the managers, does not merit
conviction and removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House has made a prima facie case of great power,'' said
Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, who chairs the Judiciary Committee.
``I don't think anybody doubts that. I've heard some of the
president's attorneys say that, `you've done a really good job' to
the House members. They've presented a great case of great power.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the opposite view, Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., said
that House managers ``did not tie these details to high crimes and
misdemeanors. The two questions were like ships passing in the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gregory Craig, special counsel to Clinton, said the House
prosecutors failed to meet their constitutional burden. ``The House
Republicans' case ends as it began, an unsubstantiated,
circumstantial case that does not meet the constitutional standard
to remove the president from office.''
</P>
<P>
   There were exceptions to the predictable assessments offered by
each side, however. Sen. James M. Jeffords, a Republican moderate
from Vermont, questioned whether the Senate may wind up setting the
conviction bar too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say lying about a noncrime can be converted into a high
crime by the way you handle it, that sets a pretty low standard,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, once again, it is the sticking point of witnesses that best
illustrated the party divide.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's exchange of letters was only the latest partisan volley
in the debate over the trial's second phase: whether the Senate
needs to hear from Monica S. Lewinsky, Betty Currie, Clinton's
secretary, and Vernon E. Jordan Jr., his friend, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In a war of words that is beginning to echo the verbal crossfire
in the House, some Democrats said they are growing increasingly
convinced that Senate Republicans want to call witnesses simply to
embarrass Clinton and draw out the trial. Republicans countered
that they must take seriously their mandate as jurors and judges,
and that means trying to clarify the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Now each side is pointing a finger at the other for the
breakdown in partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed because it just suggests it's almost
like someone wants to pick a fight and have a tempest, instead of
getting on with the major issue,'' said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said the witness issue is ``becoming
politically charged.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is divided up, and there are a lot of people in the
country who want the president removed from office, who didn't want
the president to be in office to begin with, who are saying we
ought to call witnesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Daschle expressed anger and surprise when he
learned that three Republicans had met secretly with House
prosecutors to discuss witnesses. Republicans invited Democrats to
attend the second meeting, but Daschle declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Senate took its bipartisan vote on Jan. 8, and
decided to postpone some votes on witnesses until later this month,
Lott had announced that a bipartisan group would look at the issue
during the beginning of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the group never materialized, and instead Lott appointed
three Republican senators to meet with House managers on the
question, sensing that negotiating a narrow list of witnesses would
help persuade senators to vote to consider some testimony.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican prosecutors have argued forcefully and
repeatedly during their presentations this week that the Senate
must hear from witnesses in order to deliver an informed verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Just Saturday, Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the House
Judiciary Committee, said bluntly that getting witnesses to appear
before the Senate is ``our purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We try,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Hyde said chances were ``50-50'' that House
managers would ask the Senate to invite Clinton to testify, adding
that the decision would be put off until next week.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' strategy has worked, for now. Many Republicans,
even those who were disinclined to hear from witnesses last week,
have said that prosecutors persuaded them to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sen. Richard G. Lugar, a moderate Republican from
Indiana, announced he would support calling relevant witnesses and
would vote against a ``motion to end the trial prematurely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, a Republican leader from Florida, said ``there
are more and more people who believe we will end up with
witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, also a Republican leader,
put pressure on the White House on Saturday by raising the
possibility that if Clinton were to acknowledge some of the
allegations presented by House prosecutors, the Senate may not have
to summon witnesses at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a rather strong case on that point,'' McConnell
said referring to the House push for witnesses. ``Maybe the
president will stipulate to the facts and it won't be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House is not likely to bend on the question of
stipulations. ``We already have stipulated to the record,'' White
House spokesman James Kennedy said. ``And, as we will demonstrate
next week, the House managers have ignored and misstated many of
the relevant facts contained in that record.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats remain opposed to witnesses and argued that the
time for preliminary meetings has passed. The next critical moment,
they say, will come when the Senate decides whether to dismiss the
case, a vote that is anticipated on Jan. 25. The vote requires a
simple majority, and will likely fail, but Democrats are painting
it as a decisive predictor of the trial's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is clear that significantly more than 34 senators
support dismissing the case, then the dynamics are altered,'' said
Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., ``because then it becomes a
question of what value these witnesses would provide if more than
one-third of the Senate believes the case should be dismissed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
