<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE CASE FOR WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, it seems clear that the House managers
weren't really trying to nail down 67 votes in just three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been a very high mountain to climb,'' said
David Steward, a defense attorney who represented US District Judge
Walter L. Nixon Jr. during his impeachment trial in 1989. ``So they
chose to take a different route . . . that lets them present their
case the best they can.''
</P>
<P>
   That route all but guarantees that President Clinton's
impeachment trial could continue for many more weeks, if not
months. The way the GOP prosecutors structured their case made it
evident their overriding _ and perhaps singular _ goal was to pave
the way for the calling of witnesses, several lawyers and legal
scholars said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And most of those interviewed said the Republicans did an
effective job attaining that objective.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' three-day presentation, which ended Saturday,
cannot be described as stunning or as having filled the Senate
chamber with soaring rhetoric. But the analysts said that by
weaving a solid story line with threads of persuasive evidence, the
House managers almost certainly convinced enough Republicans, and
perhaps some Democrats, that the truth cannot be evaluated without
live testimony.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds majority in the Senate is required to convict
Clinton and make him the first president to be removed from office.
But only 51 votes are needed to approve the calling of witnesses _
and that's the target most observers believe the House managers
were aiming for from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they recognized the evidence they had wasn't enough to
get 67 votes or to change public opinion,'' said Colin Diver, dean
of the University of Pennsylvania Law School. ``So it's pretty
apparent that the strategy was to take a legalistic referral from
the special prosecutor and reshape it into a compelling saga that
would convince enough senators to get to the next stage. . . . and
I think they've done a pretty good job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as each day of the prosecution's presentation passed,
more moderate Republicans publicly stated they were persuaded to
call witnesses. Minds could change after Clinton's lawyers offer
their defense beginning on Tuesday, but senators in both parties
believe at least 51 of the 55 Republicans would now vote to hear
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The divide over calling witnesses reveals how starkly partisan
the sentiment about Clinton's impeachment remains, notwithstanding
senators' efforts to appear above party considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in and out of Congress agree that a majority, if not
all, of the Republicans at the end of the month will approve the
calling of witnesses, regardless of what the president's lawyers
say in their three days of defense. Conversely, all or most
Democrats are expected to cast their ballots against live
testimony, irrespective of the strength of any arguments the House
managers might have made.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple: Without a damaging surprise from Monica S.
Lewinsky or another key witness, the effort to oust Clinton from
office seems sure to fail.
</P>
<P>
   So, even though many Democrats think witnesses could offer
testimony favorable to the president, they share the White House
view that calling them is not worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican prosecutors, meanwhile, want to call witnesses
and take their chances with unpredictable testimony because they're
unlikely to hit their mark of 67 senators without some new
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you're going to get is an entirely partisan vote
here,'' said Robert Dallek, a history professor and presidential
scholar at Boston University, about the effort to call witnesses.
He said the GOP strategy probably wouldn't succeed in removing
Clinton, but added: ``Everything else they have, no matter how well
presented, is so repetitious . . . so what else can they do?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Flaherty, a professor at Fordham University Law School,
said he had gleaned a three-part agenda from the House managers'
case.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ``essential and most important'' priority was
winning enough support to move the trial into a witness phase,
while ``a nominal item'' was to present their evidence as strongly
as possible on the chance they might persuade two-thirds of the
Senate. The problem with simultaneously pursuing those two goals,
Flaherty said, is that they conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go up and formally argue that there's enough here to
convict and then assert that you need more evidence through
witnesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican objective, according to Flaherty and the
other analysts interviewed, was to win voters to their side. On
that count, they agreed that the House prosecutors probably failed
_ and therefore would need compelling testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this has been a predicate for the larger goal of swaying
public opinion,'' said Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that would be difficult because most Americans
believe they know all they want to about the Clinton drama and have
already formed strong opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Dallek made the same point, saying the GOP task will be
particularly tough because ``most people aren't even watching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
