<HEADLINE>
IN THE SENATE, REALIZING THE GRAVITY OF TASK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla., S.C., Vt., Ohio, Mass., Neb., Del., Ind.)  (Eds: SUBS to rewrite throughout to UPDATE with today's
presentations, senators' reactions, quotes; No pickup.) 
 (jw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ When the final charges were fully heaped upon
President Clinton as a man of ``subversive and dangerous conduct''
who must not ``remain in office with all his infamy,'' the Senate
seemed a stunned court gravely taken with its task of judgment.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment of absolute silence as the chief House
prosecutor, Rep. Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, announced that he was
done. Senators stared from their chairs, as if realizing the task
before them was indeed momentous, not to be avoided and far from
over.
</P>
<P>
   Some lingered in the chamber, simply absorbing the day. Others
went out to the waiting reporters, with little new to say but their
moods deadly serious as they still faced crucial parts of the trial
extending into February.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to compare this to,'' said Sen. George V.
Voinovich, R-Ohio, a freshman heading out from a relentless three
days of denunciation of the president. ``After all is said and
done, each individual in that body will reach inside themselves and
try and make the right decision. I have faith that the higher
instincts in each of us will prevail rather than fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seemed to have an undertone of grimness as they now
have to await the president's rebuttal to the Republicans'
punishing impeachment charges. Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, openly
impatient to get beyond the trial to the agenda issues of his
constituents, spotted a Democratic colleague, Rep. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts, by a Senate doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see Barbara Mikulski's quote where she said she had a
dream last night?'' the senator asked his friend, referring to the
Democratic senator from Maryland. ``She dreamt that she was living
in the Colonial era,'' the senator said, grinning and moving on
through the Senate as if through the Twilight Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, one of the president's stalwarts in the House in arguing
against approval of the impeachment resolution, said he was spent
on the subject and was visiting a Senate office on an unrelated
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave at the office,'' he said sardonically. To Kerrey, he
offered a heartfelt, ``Better you than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most emphatic stipulation in Hyde's summary of the
case was his insistence that the impeachment charges brought by the
Republican-controlled House were not the work of
``Clinton-haters.'' ``This is a question of what we love,'' he
declared, citing the rule of law in a patriotism-steeped peroration
that ranged from Bunker Hill to Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting nearby to Hyde's left, David E. Kendall, the president's
personal counsel, listened quite intently and politely. He smiled
briefly, almost wistfully, when Hyde read a third-grader's
recommended punishment for the president: ``He should write a
100-word essay by hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Far less did Kendall smile at two of the day's main prosecutors,
Lindsey O. Graham of South Carolina and Charles T. Canady of
Florida, who mixed Southern folksiness and lengthy scholarship,
respectively, in excoriating the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose to cheat in in every manner you can cheat in a
lawsuit,'' Graham laconically told the senators, straying from the
lectern a bit like a lawyer trying to relax his jury.
</P>
<P>
   Canady packed his address with legal citations ranging from the
British Parliament to Alexander Hamilton in arguing for banishing
Clinton from office. ``His harmful example as president must not
stand,'' he said, anticipating a range of defense
counter-arguments, even Clinton's resilient standing in public
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The president's misdeeds ``pose a far greater danger to the
well-being of our government'' precisely because of his popularity,
Canady contended, saluting senators of 131 years ago for having the
courage to defend the unpopular President Andrew Johnson in his
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   A third prosecutor, Stephen E. Buyer of Indiana, even skewered
the president for his now famous testimony about the multiple
meanings of ``is.'' ``He murdered the plain-spoken English
language,'' Buyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery audience seemed no less engrossed than the Senate
court as they looked down upon the scene of an American president
being so thoroughly denounced before the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the Senate chamber and seeing this process at this
moment in history is awe-inspiring,'' said Ethan Gluck, an
architect, who brought his young son, Adam, to the trial,
explaining it as a once-in-a-life-time event but one far from
complete with the president's defenders only beginning their
arguments next week.
</P>
<P>
   Senators departed with much the same cautionary notion in mind,
that the court and the nation were still far from the final verdict
tally. ``My household is 2-to-2,''James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said in
gently making this point as he left the Senate after three long
days of listening.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords and his colleagues gratefully streamed out for a
weekend break, facing another week of impeachment argumentation
that will be relieved only by the president himself on Tuesday
night when his State of the Union address follows upon his lawyers'
opening argument that he should remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone has said, we'll just have to compartmentalize,''
said Voinovich, heading off from the impeachment courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
