<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE MANAGERS WRAP UP ARGUMENTS, CALL FOR CLINTON'S REMOVAL 
</HEADLINE>
 - 1ST-LEDE-WRITETHROUGH  
 (EDS: Corrects spelling of panorama in first paragraph)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Invoking a panorama of the American experience
ranging from the revolution to the enduring struggle for civil
rights, House managers Saturday cast President Clinton as a threat
to the nation's ``sacred honor,'' in the last act of their
three-day plea for the Senate to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The drama unfolded amid an escalating dispute over the merits of
prolonging the trial by summoning witnesses and inviting Clinton to
explain why he should not suffer the infamy of being the first
president convicted of ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a rapt Senate, the lead manager, House Judiciary
Committee chairman Henry J. Hyde, argued that equal justice demands
Clinton's ouster for allegedly violating the law by committing
perjury and obstructing justice to cover up his sexual affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot tolerate one law for the ruler, and another for the
ruled,'' Hyde said. ``If we do, we break faith with our ancestors
from Bunker Hill, Lexington, and Concord to . . . Saigon and Desert
Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's summation cleared the way for Clinton's lawyers to launch
a three-day rebuttal to the House case, beginning Tuesday at 1 p.m.
_ the same day Clinton will deliver his State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple truth is that the House Republican prosecutors
failed to demonstrate that the will and interests of the American
people would be served by nullifying the results of a national
election,'' said Gregory B. Craig, White House special counsel.
``We will present a strong, vigorous defense based on the facts,
the law, and the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican-controlled Senate nearly split along party
lines on whether to call witnesses, the White House faces an uphill
struggle to reverse the momentum and persuade senators to dismiss
the charges without permitting witnesses in this historic trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double-edged sword,'' Senator John F. Kerry said of the
challenge confronting Clinton's lawyers. ``It's entirely possible
that their presentation can itself beg for further elucidation'' by
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bipartisan blueprint for the trial, votes on whether to
dismiss the charges and call witnesses are scheduled for Jan. 25,
after the Senate has spent two days questioning the House managers
and Clinton's lawyers about their competing presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the growing divide, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott
of Mississippi, Saturday released a letter he sent Friday night to
the Democratic leader, Senator Thomas A. Daschle, asking to create
a bipartisan coalition ``to resolve in advance any complications
that may be presented by our hearing the testimony of witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, who lashed out at Senate Republicans last week for
holding private meetings with House managers over potential
witnesses, acknowledged in a written reply to Lott that the witness
controversy ``poses a number of troubling considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle said the blueprint for the trial required the Senate
to defer action on witnesses until next week. He added: ``It is my
hope that such arrangements will ultimately prove unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Senate's GOP majority indicated Daschle's hope is
unlikely to be fulfilled. ``I think there is a presumption there
will be witnesses,'' said Senator Judd Gregg of New Hampshire, the
Republican chief deputy whip.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Connie Mack, a Florida Republican, added, ``It's almost
reached a point of inevitability.''
</P>
<P>
   But a two-thirds majority, or 67 votes, is required to remove a
president, and most senators believe Clinton ultimately will be
acquitted, barring a dramatic turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the current record, they are not going to win this
trial,'' said Senator Robert G. Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat,
of the House managers. ``They need somebody to come before the
Senate and give unexpected testimony or to commit a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, who continue to investigate allegations
against Clinton and interview prospective witnesses, have said they
want to compel testimony from Lewinsky, Clinton friend Vernon E.
Jordan Jr., and several White House aides, including his personal
secretary, Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Although several managers have called for Clinton to appear, the
House team has yet to decide whether to request his testimony. They
also remain undecided over seeking other witnesses, including
Kathleen E. Willey, a former White House volunteer who accused
Clinton of groping her near the Oval Office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Completing a 15-hour, three-day presentation, Hyde and three
other House managers tried to make the case that Clinton's alleged
offenses warranted his removal from office. Their speeches ranged
in tone from Hyde's solemn eloquence to the stirring, folksy
delivery of Representative Lindsey Graham of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, declaring himself ``a child of the South'' like Clinton,
praised the president for his promoting civil rights. But he
excoriated Clinton for allegedly failing to practice the principles
he espouses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton allegedly launched an elaborate scheme to obtruct
justice to thwart a sexual-harassment lawsuit that Paula Corbin
Jones, a former Arkansas state worker, filed against him and
settled last year for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Clinton's support for equal rights, Graham said, ``I'm
here to tell you that when it was his case, when those rights had
to be applied to him, he failed miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Clinton's alleged assault on Jones's quest for
justice warranted his removal from office. ``What's a high crime?''
he said. ``How about when an important person hurts a person of low
means?''
</P>
<P>
   If a final vote is cast on the articles of impeachment, Graham
said, ``The vice president will be waiting outside the doors of
this chamber. If that vice president is asked to come in to assume
the mantle of chief executive officer of the land, it will be
tough, it will be painful, but we will survive and we will be
better for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde concluded the House case by reading a letter about lying
from a Chicago third-grader, William Preston Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe the president tells the truth anymore right
now,'' Sanders wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats, who generally called the speeches by Graham
and Hyde highly effective, urged the White House to exploit what
they described as a serious flaw in the House case: the reliance on
evidence stemming from the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The House last month rejected an article of impeachment charging
Clinton with lying under oath in the Jones case. ``They built their
case on the thin reed of the Paula Jones case, which was dismissed
by the House,'' said Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa. ``That has to be
reemphasized and hammered home again.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers said the impeachment charges directly relate
to the Jones case. They said Clinton allegedly lied before a
federal grand jury about his deposition in the Jones case and
committed several elements of the obstruction charge to stymie the
Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Senate Republicans said the House presentation
supported the charges. ``The managers made an overwhelming case
that these facts are important and that perjury and obstruction of
justice, if proven, are impeachable offenses,'' said Senator Orrin
G. Hatch of Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few Republicans who continued to voice skepticism was
Senator James M. Jeffords of Vermont. Although Jeffords has
indicated he will support GOP leaders in conducting a thorough
trial, which might include witnesses, he said he remains wary of
removing Clinton over charges stemming from a sexual affair. ``If
you say lying about a non-crime can be converted into a high crime
by the way you handle it, that sets a pretty low standard for me,''
Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said the House managers, despite
``some pretty good rhetoric,'' presented ``a thin argument'' to
support the charges. He argued that they did not adequately rebut
hundreds of constitutional scholars who have said the charges fall
short of the standard for impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure to cite thoughtful authority on this, I thought,
was a missing link,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
