<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCCAP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Falcons at Vikings Time: 11:35 a.m. tomorrow. TV: KDFW/Channel 4.
Radio: KTCK/AM 1310. Line: Vikings by 11. Series: Vikings lead,
13-6 Last meeting: Vikings 23, Falcons 17 (1996)STORY LINES VIKINGS
(15-1) Can Randall Cunningham and Dennis Green exorcise their
demons?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NFC Championship Game is unfamiliar territory for
quarterback Randall Cunningham and coach Dennis Green. As a matter
of fact, so is winning in the playoffs. Both have been maligned
throughout their careers because of their postseason failures.
Things seem to be falling their way this time. They have the
home-field advantage and they have best team. They also have had
each other for a full season and should put the past to rest with a
Super Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   Can they run to pass?
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' passing attack has received all the headlines.
However, running backs Robert Smith and Leroy Hoard have played a
big part in their offensive success. If the Falcons line up in a
nickel defense on regular downs, as most teams have, look for the
Vikings to attack with Smith and Hoard. Smith is the speedster, who
can take it the distance. Hoard is the plow horse who runs through
tacklers. FALCONS (14-2) Can they handle the noise?
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves has done everything he can do to
prepare his team for the Metrodome's acoustic atmosphere. He has
called the league to make sure the Vikings abide by league noise
rules. He has piped in music at practice to simulate game
conditions. The task for the Falcons is to not let the noise
distract them during the game. The Falcons have simplified their
blocking schemes and will use hand signals to cut down on
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Can they make it a low-scoring game?
</P>
<P>
   What the Falcons don't want is for the game to turn into a track
meet. That takes away their strength, running the ball and
controlling the clock. The Falcons led the league in time of
possession this season and hope to continue that trend. A game in
the 20s will be more to the Falcons' liking. Anything over that
will be bad news.
MATCHUPS VIKINGS DEFENSE vs. JAMAL ANDERSON The Vikings' goal on
defense is simple _ stop Falcons running back Jamal Anderson. There
is no question the Falcons will try to control the ball and the
game with Anderson. The Vikings have had trouble stopping the run
at times this season. The key against Anderson is to get to him in
the backfield before he gets started; the Falcons runner has proven
to be brutal once he gets in the secondary. The Vikings also must
get Anderson to run wide where they can use their speed to contain
him and not let him pound away at the middle of the defense. RANDY
MOSS vs. RAY BUCHANAN The Falcons are wary about the Vikings' pass
offense, especially 6-foot-5 receiver Randy Moss going against 5-9
cornerback Ray Buchanan. Buchanan has been the Falcons' best
defender all season, but he will be hard-pressed to handle Moss by
himself. The Falcons haven't done a lot of double-teaming, but they
might change that strategy against the Vikings and give Buchanan
some help. Of course, double-covering Moss means Vikings receiver
Cris Carter will get single coverage. However, it's a matter of
pick your poison. The Falcons would rather give up the plays
underneath than the big plays on top.
KEYS TO VICTORY VIKINGS Score fast and often to turn the game into
track meet.
</P>
<P>
   Stop Falcons running back Jamal Anderson and keep him from doing
the Dirty Bird touchdown dance.
</P>
<P>
   Establish the run with Robert Smith to keep the Falcons' pass
defense honest. FALCONS Play ball-control football to keep the
Vikings' offense off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Attack the middle of the Vikings' defense with running back
Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid giving up the big play on defense and force the Vikings to
work for their points.
THE EDGE Vikings run offense (121.0 ypg) vs. Falcons run defense
(75.2) Edge: Falcons
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Falcons ranked second in the league in run defense,
but the Vikings should be able to loosen them up with their pass
offense.
Vikings run defense (100.9) vs. Falcons run offense (131.3) Edge:
Falcons
</P>
<P>
   Comment: If the Vikings have a soft spot, it's stopping the run.
The Falcons have the weapon in running back Jamal Anderson to take
advantage of this weakness.
Vikings pass offense (270.5) vs. Falcons pass defense (220.7) Edge:
Vikings
</P>
<P>
   Comment: No one has stopped the Vikings' passing game all season
and this time shouldn't be different. Receiver Randy Moss is too
fast. Receiver Cris Carter is too good. Quarterback Randall
Cunningham is too accurate.
Vikings pass defense (215.8) vs. Falcons pass offense (211.6) Edge:
Falcons
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Quarterback Chris Chandler and receivers Terance Mathis
and Tony Martin have been overshadowed by the Vikings' success.
However, they are quite lethal themselves. Mathis and Martin ranked
second in the league in combined receiving yardage _ behind Moss
and Carter.
Special teams Edge: Vikings
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Vikings kicker Gary Anderson has had a perfect season.
He hasn't missed a field-goal attempt or an extra-point try. Kick
returner David Palmer is as dangerous as anyone in the league.
Besides, he also plays quarterback.
Coaching Edge: Vikings
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Atlanta coach Dan Reeves has done a great job turning
around the Falcons. However, Dennis Green hasn't gotten enough
credit for the Vikings' success. Make no mistake about, the Vikings
were the best team in the NFL this year because Green created them.
Bottom line Vikings 31, Falcons 17 (Clarence E. Hill Jr. is a
reporter for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
