<SLUG> BC-ITALY-KURD-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURDISH REBEL LEADER, WHO IS WANTED BY TURKEY, LEAVES ITALY
</HEADLINE>
   ( nk)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A Kurdish rebel leader wanted by the Turkish government
for terrorism left Italy on Saturday night, the Italian government
announced. The destination of the Kurd, Abdullah Ocalan, was not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that Ocalan, whose presence in Rome caused
relations between Italy and Turkey to plummet, had worn out his
welcome in Italy. ``Kurdish leader Abdullah Ocalan, having decided
to leave Italy, has been accompanied to the border,'' a government
statement said tersely.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, who fled Moscow for Italy in November, was arrested by
Italian law enforcement officials as he arrived at the airport
here. But the government refused to turn him over to Turkey, citing
an Italian law that prohibits the extradition of prisoners to
countries that have a death penalty. He was kept under house arrest
for part of his time here.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which also views Ocalan, as a terrorist,
spoke out in favor of his extradition. Italy hoped to rid itself of
the problem by extraditing him to Germany, which had issued a
warrant for Ocalan's arrest in 1990 on homicide charges.
</P>
<P>
   The German government, however, eventually decided not to seek
extradition, fearing that such an act would rekindle violence among
the three million Turks and Kurds in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan is leader of the Kurdistan Workers Party, which for the
last 14 years has been waging a war for autonomy from Turkey. The
conflict between Turkish troops and rebels has killed as many as
37,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish government was infuriated by Italy's refusal to
extradite Ocalan. While Kurdish protesters held vigils in Rome in
support of Ocalan, demonstrators in Ankara and Istanbul held
impassioned rallies, burning Italian flags and Armani ties. The
Turkish ambassador here left in protest after an Italian appeals
court ruled that without an extradition request from Germany, Italy
had no grounds to detain Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, who requested political asylum, remained in Rome, but he
came under pressure to find another country. The Italian news
service ANSA reported that he was believed to be headed for Moscow,
but neither the Italian or Russian governments confirmed it.
</P>
<P>
   After being forced to leave Syria and Russia, Ocalan apparently
chose Italy because he felt he would get support from Italian
Communists and even from the leftist government.
</P>
<P>
   When he first arrived, Italy's prime minister, Massimo D'Alema,
a former Communist, had initially sounded supportive of him, saying
shortly after his arrest that Italy would consider Ocalan's request
for political asylum. But as relations with Turkey deteriorated and
D'Alema failed to garner support from other European allies, his
stance grew firmer.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, D'Alema warned that if Ocalan chose to remain in
Italy, he might be put on trial on terrorism charges.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has not yet been any official ruling on Ocalan's
request for political asylum, D'Alema has said on several occasions
that Ocalan's chances of qualifying for political asylum were not
good.
</P>
<P>
   ANSA quoted one of Ocalan's lawyers, Luigi Saraceni, as saying,
``Let us hope that those who have shown sensitivity for the Kurdish
people will continue their effort even the chief protagonist has
left the stage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
