<SLUG> BC-SKI-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THERE WAS IFFY, BUT SKI SLOPES IN FINE FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The snow finally fell last week, just in time for what
the region's ski businesses hoped would be a successful weekend on
the slopes after a long wait through an unusually warm winter.
</P>
<P>
   But some skiers were deterred by the combination of news reports
about messy, icy roads making for poor driving conditions, and the
rain that capped the snow with a crunchy cover. They shouldn't have
been, according to reports from the mountains Saturday at the start
of what is a long weekend for many.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the groomers can do with this stuff is make a nice packed
powder,'' said David Anderson, marketing director of Loon Mountain
in New Hampshire. ``We had a nice crowd Sunday, but we didn't sell
out. I think some people probably stayed away because of the
roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 25 miles away from Boston, Nashoba Valley ski instructor
Cindy Liming said she was skiing on her day off because the good
conditions surprised her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a lot worse than this,'' said Liming,
who had been worried about rain melting the trails. ``We have more
snow now than we did two days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said better ski conditions were likely to be
found farther north. Friday night's rain turned to snow early
Saturday in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   At Vermont's Jay Peak ski resort, anxious travelers from far
away canceled reservations, but their spots were filled by
diehards, many from Massachusetts. ``There's a lot more license
plates from Massachusetts than usual,'' said marketing vice
president Conrad Klefos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a packed powder surface,'' Klefos said. ``We're in great
shape.'' He said Saturday was the busiest day of the season for Jay
Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Switchboard operator Shelley Martin said people who traveled to
the mountain from New York had a tough time, with trips lasting
twice as long as they would normally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people arriving through the night,'' she said. ``And
some people canceled because of the icy roads. But I guess it
didn't discourage everyone. We have a full mountain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990116.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-SURVIVE-ART     01-16 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-SURVIVE-ART-2TAKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SURVIVING OCTUPLETS, PROGRESS COMES IN OUNCES
</HEADLINE>
 
repeating to fix coding 
(ATTN: Nigeria, Texas)  (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with smallest baby fighting an
infection; Pickup new 4th graf, The strongest ... )  
 ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ At first glance, it is hard to tell a baby is there.
</P>
<P>
   Then the clues come from following the tubes that blow air into
the baby's tiny nostrils. Another tube carries nutrients into a
vein. The boy has black hair. He is barely a foot long. He is
curled up on a pillow and strapped in a cloth bumper, dotted with
hearts, to keep his arms and legs in the same flexed position they
were in in the womb. As he sleeps beneath a radiant warmer in the
dark and quiet room, machines track his skin temperature, heart
rate, blood pressure, oxygen level and other vital measurements.
Two Beanie Babies lie nearby. One toy serves an extra function: the
Beanie's weight holds the air tubes in place.
</P>
<P>
   Above, a cardboard sign identifies him as Baby F, or Ikem. At 1
pound 7 ounces, he is the smallest of the seven surviving octuplets
born here last month. On Friday night, when Ikem developed signs of
an infection, doctors began administering antibiotics and stopped
his feeding. When the infection subsides, in two to three days,
feeding will resume. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The strongest and largest, at 2 pounds 10 ounces, is his only
brother, Jioke. He rests in a similar warmer in the same room. The
five surviving sisters are in nearby rooms. The babies are turned
from time to time. As a nurse starts the task, she playfully offers
a finger, and the baby's hand grasps it.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving octuplets look and sound like babies, just
miniature ones. Sometimes they open their eyes and look around.
When bothered, they cry.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the eight babies, Ebuka, a girl, was born on Dec.
8, nearly four months earlier than the mother's due date of April
1. The mother, Nkem Chukwu had been treated at the MacGregor
Fertility Clinic in Houston and because of religious beliefs had
rejected the idea of destroying any of the fetuses to give the
others a greater chance of survival. The seven others were born on
Dec. 20, making them the world's first set of octuplets to be born
alive. The largest weighed less than 2 pounds. The smallest, a girl
named Odera, weighed 10.3 ounces and died on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The births made the octuplets an immediate sensation in the news
and renewed the debate about fertility drugs and their enormous
medical and human costs, but here in the neonatal intensive care
unit on the fourth floor of Texas Children's Hospital, the glare of
world attention fades away next to the blip of the infant monitors.
Now, although two babies remain under a pound and a half, all are
gaining weight, ounce by ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chukwu, 27, has visited regularly since her discharge from
the hospital on Dec. 30. When she can hold one of the infants, she
sits in a chair, unbuttons her blouse and touches the baby against
her chest. She does not try to nurse them; the babies cannot yet
suck and swallow well enough. It takes about 20 minutes for the
nurses, who must keep the tubes and wires connected, to get a baby
into her arms.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Iyke Louis Udobi, a respiratory therapist, also
visits and touches the infants. The parents, American citizens born
in Nigeria, gave the babies Nigerian names based on the
characteristics of God.
</P>
<P>
   The babies have a 95 percent chance of surviving to their
expected discharge in late March, said Dr. Leonard E. Weisman, the
head of the neonatal unit. As he led a visiting doctor through the
unit, Weisman said he was ``cautiously optimistic'' that the
babies, all listed in critical condition, would turn out normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a 10 percent or so risk of some long-term
problems, but I hope we are not going to see anything like
blindness, deafness, mental retardation or severe cerebral palsy,''
Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his 25-year experience as a pediatrician, Weisman
added: ``You learn in this business that things can turn on a
dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisman based his prediction on his study of 1,925 premature
infants the Texas Children's Hospital treated from 1986 through
1994, and reported last June in Pediatrics, a scientific journal.
Texas Children's describes itself as the largest pediatric hospital
in the United States. Of the hospital's 456 beds, 120 are for those
needing the most intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patti M. Savrick, the pediatrician who will care for the
babies after their discharge, said: ``By the time they are 2 to 3
years old, they are going to be good, normal kids, barring any
unforeseen disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Savrick said her optimism was based in part on an ultrasound
test of each baby's head that was performed about a week after
their birth. The test is a strong predictor of serious neurological
problems. When no baby showed evidence of bleeding or cysts, ``that
was dramatically good news,'' Dr. Savrick said. Her practice
includes five surviving sextuplets, two sets of quadruplets and
many sets of triplets and twins.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman credited a drug, surfactant, that supplies a missing
component to premature infants with underdeveloped lungs, as
``certainly the No. 1 reason that these kids are doing as well as
they are.'' Surfactant, which was first marketed in 1990, was given
in the first day of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Two octuplets have had general anesthesia for surgery. Eboka had
heart surgery as a 3-day-old to close a blood vessel (patent ductus
arteriosus) in her heart that failed to do so on its own. The other
was to repair a hole in Gorom's small intestine that was recognized
when her belly swelled and an X-ray showed air present where it was
not supposed to be. Both operations were performed at the bedside,
as is often the case for premature infants.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven surviving octuplets, six had good scores on the
10-point Apgar scale of a newborn's health, 8s or 9s at five
minutes; Gorom was rated at 6.
</P>
<P>
   All received antibiotics for the first two days after birth
because the doctors did not know whether an infection caused the
mother to go into labor. Two babies developed infections later.
</P>
<P>
   All are fed intravenously. In addition, the mother brings in
breast milk to the hospital. For now, the milk is given through a
tube into the stomach of each infant. In about a month the babies
will start feeding by mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, all the babies breathed with the aid of mechanical
ventilators. Now the surviving octuplets breathe on their own. A
pump blows air through the tubing to help keep their chest walls
from collapsing. The babies also receive caffeine to prevent apnea
and stimulate their breathing. As the babies grow and strengthen
their underdeveloped chest muscles in the next few weeks, the air
tubes will be removed.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a month, Dr. David K. Coats, a pediatric
ophthalmologist, will start dilating the infants' eyes each week or
two to check for a potentially blinding condition, retinopathy of
prematurity.
</P>
<P>
   A mild form of the condition develops in most premature babies.
But in about 9 percent it is severe enough to require treatment
with either a laser or freezing technique. The aim is to prevent
detachment of the retina. But treatment fails in about 10 percent
of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Some premature babies who do not develop the retinopathy
condition later develop weak eye muscles as young children.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors also will test the babies' hearing by putting sounds
in their ears and then measuring brain wave responses in a
technique known as brain stem auditory evoked response. The risk of
deafness and severe hearing problems is about 4 percent, Weisman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheezing from a chronic lung disease resembling asthma is among
the babies' other potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the octuplets' problems, like immature lungs, a
perforated intestine and the heart vessel condition, are those
faced by any premature infant. Some problems were compounded by
their numbers. Multiple fetuses create a crowded womb, which
increases the risk of growth retardation. Multiple fetuses also
increase the likelihood that the babies will be born prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman estimated the total cost for the octuplets at about $2
million. It will be covered by the health insurance that the father
receives through his work as a respiratory therapist for a local
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the costs are almost irrelevant. ``The expense, as
large as it is,'' Weisman said, ``has to be measured over the
babies' lifetimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
