A6257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-HNS &LR;      01-16 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOUSE MANAGERS SEE GOAL WITHIN REACH; WITNESSES MAY YET BE CALLED
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By BENNETT ROTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three days of making exhaustive arguments
about why President Clinton should be ousted from office, House
Republicans did not appear to have changed many minds.
</P>
<P>
   But they may have achieved one of their short-term tactical
goals _ to persuade Senate Republicans to at least keep the trial
moving forward by calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   With White House attorneys set to argue their case against
conviction next week, the situation remains fluid.
</P>
<P>
   But as of Saturday, when Republican House managers completed
their opening arguments before the Senate, the chance of persuading
two-thirds of the upper chamber to remove the president remained
remote.
</P>
<P>
   To convict the president, a dozen Democrats would have to join
all 55 Republicans. So far no senator from the president's party
has indicated a willingness to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And a number of them said they did not hear anything new in the
House managers' presentation that would cause them to alter their
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the dynamics have changed from where we began,''
said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. ``Those of us who are
unconvinced remain unconvinced.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg also complained that the 13 Republican House members,
acting as prosecutors, may have erroneously believed that by
repeating the same arguments for more than 17 hours they would win
converts.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that one colleague related how a preacher once told
him, ``If you ain't saved a soul in 20 minutes, you ain't saved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The House managers' major short-term goal was to convince a
majority of senators that the case warrants the calling of key
witnesses, including former White House intern Monica Lewinsky;
Clinton's personal secretary, Betty Currie; and presidential
confidant Vernon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster that case, the House managers hammered on the
inconsistencies between Lewinsky's testimony about her affair with
the president and Clinton's denial of the sexual relationship in
the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A number of GOP senators said they needed to hear from a host of
characters in the Clinton-Lewinsky saga to determine who was
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense developing that there will probably be
witnesses called,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla. ``It's almost
reached the point of inevitability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are contradictions that are significant. Anybody with a
brain would want to have these contradictions resolved,'' said Sen.
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is expected to cause the first major partisan showdown
in the Senate. Many Democrats and the White House are opposed to
calling witnesses, claiming it will unnecessarily prolong the trial
and create a circus atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said that the evidence provided by the
House managers was sufficient for him to judge the case. He said
parading a series of witnesses before the Senate would take too
much time and prevent lawmakers from taking care of the business of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening presentation, the House members built a
detailed circumstantial case that Clinton not only lied under oath
about his affair with Lewinsky but also concocted an elaborate
scheme to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have said that even if Clinton did commit the
alleged offenses, they are not sure the charges rise to the
standard of high crimes and misdemeanors outlined in the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still the threshold issue of what is an impeachable
offense,'' said Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D., who added the Republicans
had ``a very very difficult case to make.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday three Republican House members tried to address that
issue, claiming that the Senate has convicted judges for offenses
similar to those charged against the president.
</P>
<P>
   They also argued that perjury accusations against Clinton were
equivalent to bribery, which the Constitution does define as a high
crime.
</P>
<P>
   These arguments resonated with a number of Republican senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never understood the argument that perjury and
obstruction of justice do not rise to the constitutional level
(required for impeachment),'' said Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats complained that the Republicans had
overstated their case.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that his Democratic colleagues began ``rolling
their eyes'' when managers Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., and Steve Buyer,
R-Ind., claimed that Clinton had undercut civil rights laws by his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom. Harkin, D-Iowa, said he was unimpressed when Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., invoked American war efforts from Bunker Hill
to Desert Storm as reasons to oust the president. ``Mr. Hyde's
summation indicated the overkill in this case,'' said Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the reaction broke down along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, a Democrat from Florida, praised the House
presentation. ``I think if we were in a court of law and a motion
was to be made to today to dismiss the case because of lack of the
prosecution having carried out its responsibilities, I would reject
that motion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Sen. James Jeffords, a Republican from
Vermont _ which Clinton carried twice _ was skeptical of the House
managers' case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say lying about a noncrime can be converted into a high
crime by the way you handle it, that sets a pretty low standard for
me,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
