<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6258 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-16 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY DESERVES PROPER SENDOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We want to see Denver quarterback John Elway go
out the way Michael Jordan did, with his right wrist frozen in a
follow through after one final strike in a closing frame for the
archives and maybe even the ages.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be a shame for the future Hall of Famer's NFL career to end
on a sour note like his college career at Stanford did. Of course,
nobody expects a repeat today _ or ever _ of the 1982 ``Big Game,''
when the Stanford band spilled onto the field after the clock had
run out but before Cal's Kevin Moen had finished his sprint into
the end zone for the winning points on a lateral-laden kickoff
return.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's phenomenal professional career promises to play out more
melodiously, even if it should end today with a loss to the New
York Jets in the AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Understand: Elway hasn't exhausted his eligibility; this time
it's his body that's pooped. That's why no one will be surprised if
Elway's 16th season is his last.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever today's outcome, it'll be an awesome sight when the
game ends and 70,000-plus fans rise like an orange sun to offer a
Mile High salute to the player who gave this frontier city a face
(and finally, this past January a Super Bowl title).
</P>
<P>
   A standing ovation would seem an inadequate acknowledgement of
Elway's legacy. At the very least, the fans should flick on
lighters for the man who has been an incandescent figure in their
midst since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Elway didn't turn Mile High Stadium into Colorado's
eighth-largest city every autumn Sunday, he just put it on the map.
There was a waiting list for season tickets 13 years before Elway
slipped on a Broncos jersey. What he did was take that rabid
following and deliver it to the Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Elway,'' Broncos receiver Shannon Sharpe has said, ``led
Denver out of obscurity and into the land of milk and honey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Prince of Pike's Peak arrived on the scene after escaping
the clutches of a Baltimore franchise that had stubbornly insisted
on drafting him against his will. The moves that forced the Colts
to trade him to Denver for Mark Hermann, Chris Hinton and a
first-round draft pick in 1984 would go down as Elway's first
memorable scramble under duress.
</P>
<P>
   We claim Elway because he came out of Granada Hills High. Our
transplanted son, in turn, owns Denver. It has been an enduring
partnership but not always an enjoyable one.
</P>
<P>
   Elway signed what was then the league's wealthiest contract long
before his career had any context. With his five-year, $5 million
deal he hit paydirt, the likes of which had not been seen in
Colorado since cowboy Robert Womack's strike at Cripple Creek in
the late 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The money and the attendant media build-up created expectations
that William ``Buffalo Bill'' Cody would have had a hard time
overtaking. Early in his career, the two largest newspapers in the
city ran daily reports on Elway that sometimes bordered on the
absurd, covering everything from what he did (or didn't) eat at
training table to what kind of candy he gave out at Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos, 2-7 in the strike-shortened season before Elway's
arrival, went 33-15 in his first three years. Winning games proved
easier than winning over the fans. They seemed more inclined to boo
him than embrace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Elway said in November of 1984
after throwing for five scores in a 42-21 win over visiting
Minnesota. ``I think some people expected me to walk this high off
the water. I feel the coolness from the fans, from the whole city
of Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   The chill Elway spoke of settled in the bones of his wife Janet,
and one day she cracked. In December of 1985, less than two months
after the birth of the couple's first child, Elway was intercepted
five times in a game against Kansas City and the Mile High fans
began piling on him.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually pulled out a 14-13 victory with a scoring drive in
the final minute, but not before Janet slapped a fan who had
screamed loud enough for practically the whole stadium to hear,
``You can get your . . . wife pregnant, but you can't . . . do
anything else, you bum.''
</P>
<P>
   All that's stiff about Elway are his joints, as Broncos fans
gradually came to realize after giving him enough space (barely) to
finish growing up.
</P>
<P>
   His 45 game-winning drives and 11 winning seasons and and six
AFC Championship Game appearances and four Super Bowl berths are
sublime and his 75 percent winning percentage at Mile High,
something else altogether. But it is scenes like these two that
mark the man:
</P>
<P>
   _In the first game of the 1991 season, Elway orchestrated a
45-14 win over Cincinnati and, for an encore, tossed a football to
a Mile High fan in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   The league promptly fined him $1,000, which didn't even begin to
cover the value of the ball in the eyes of its beholder. How many
zeroes, after all, are in priceless?
</P>
<P>
   _On the first Sunday of December in 1996, the Broncos beat
Seattle 34-7 to clinch their sixth AFC West title of the Elway era.
After changing out of his cape and tights, Elway limped out into
the murky Mile High night, observed a dozen kids playing football
on the field and, to their amazement, fell in with them for a few
downs.
</P>
<P>
   Elway calls himself ``a big kid at heart,'' but he also is a
proud parent. After every home game he makes it a point to wave to
his four kids as he walks off the field. Sometimes they're even
there to wave back.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many in their hometown _ Barrel Man quickly comes to
mind _ the Elway children aren't obsessed with the Broncos. They
have outside interests, such as soccer and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Elway lately has had to persuade 13-year-old Jessica,
11-year-old Jordan, 9-year-old Jack and 7-year-old Juliana to come
watch him play. He makes a pretty convincing argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he tells them, ``dad's not going to be playing
football forever. You ought to come and watch while you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the city ought to heed his words and not spare any
sentimentality in saying so long. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
