<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FIT, STRAWBERRY LOOKS FORWARD TO NEW SEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ The gaunt figure who rode down the Canyon of
Heroes after the Yankees won their 24th World Series is now back up
to his playing weight of 215.
</P>
<P>
   A robust-looking Darryl Strawberry made his first public
appearance Saturday since the victory parade. Filling out a red
sweat shirt as if he were in midseason form, he drew cheers upon
his arrival at the Roosevelt Field Mall. Some waited as long as two
hours for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 days ago, Strawberry underwent an operation to remove
scar tissue, an aftereffect from surgery to remove a malignant
tumor from his colon last October.
</P>
<P>
   `'I feel pretty good for just having surgery again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 36, was cautiously optimistic about his return to
baseball this year and about remaining with the Yankees. The
pitchers and catchers report to the Yankees' training camp on Feb.
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season could happen, and it may not happen,'' said
Strawberry, who hit 24 home runs in 1998. ``With my luck, it always
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is scheduled to receive weekly chemotherapy through
April. He has been lifting weights, even on days when he receives
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't affected my daily living performance,'' he said. ``I
don't think it's going to have any major effect on me playing. I
feel great. Being that I'm such a young age, and you face something
like that, your body has a tendency of being a little stronger than
it normally would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's weight had dipped to 185 pounds, the lowest since
he played at Crenshaw High School in South Central Los Angeles. But
through diet and lifting, he looks like the Strawberry of old. Both
the Yankees and Strawberry are waiting to see if he performs like
the Strawberry of old.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, has said he
wants the left-handed slugger back. The team still plans to sign
Strawberry to a minor league contract so that a $2.5 million option
on his contract will not be subject to major league baseball's
luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has not swung a bat since doctors excised a a
three-inch tumor from his intestine on Oct. 3. He faces plenty of
competition in the outfield and at designated hitter, with Chad
Curtis, Ricky Ledee and Chili Davis all returning. These are among
the same Yankees who produced 114 regular-season victories and a
sweep of the San Diego Padres in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said that if the Yankees decide to go with those
players instead of him, ``There are other opportunities for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His greatest moment on the field last season was hitting a grand
slam to bring the Yankees back from a four-run deficit against
Oakland on Aug. 4. The Yankees won the game. The low point came
Oct. 1 when his cancer was diagnosed while the team was in
Arlington, Texas, completing a three-game sweep of the Rangers in
the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, heavily favored to muscle through the post-season,
rode Strawberry's inspiration to the American League championship
against Cleveland and their second World Series title in three
years. Steinbrenner and Manager Joe Torre wept for Strawberry in
dedicating the Series to him. Pitcher David Wells led a toast to
him in the clubhouse at Qualcomm Stadium in San Diego after the
clinching victory.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have found no additional cancer, but the initial
pathology report indicated that the cancer had spread to one of 36
lymph nodes removed in the operation. Chances for his long-term
survival range widely, doctors said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
