<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MAIN-HNS &LR;      01-16 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
OPENING ARGUMENTS CONCLUDED IN SENATE; HYDE SAYS CLINTON `DEBASED'
OVAL OFFICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
c.1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors wrapped up their opening
arguments against President Clinton on Saturday with a plea for his
ouster to keep the presidency from being ``deeply and permanently
damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a crowded Senate chamber and national television
audience, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill. _ the chief House prosecutor _
urged senators to ``rise above politics, above partisanship, above
polling data'' and convict Clinton on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations _ outlined in two articles of impeachment _ grew
out of the president's effort to conceal a sexual relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, a deception that took
root a year ago today (1/17) when he testified under oath in Paula
Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hyde maintained that the case is ``not a question of
lying about sex,'' he alluded to Clinton's effort to keep his
affair secret as an indication of how the presidency ``has been
debased and the justice system jeopardized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Morally serious men and women can imagine circumstances at the
far edge of the morally permissible'' in which a president could
shade the truth for the good of the nation, Hyde said. ``But under
oath, for a private pleasure?''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee chairman urged senators not to
shrink from removing Clinton if they believe, as some Democrats
have suggested, that his behavior violated the public's trust. If
senators believe Clinton violated the law yet vote to acquit him,
``the office of the presidency has been deeply and perhaps
permanently damaged,'' said Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate trial _ only the second of a president _ recessed
until Tuesday when a team of private attorneys and White House
lawyers will begin mounting a defense. Next weekend, senators will
be allowed to raise questions, then cast a series of votes on
whether to continue the trial and whether to begin summoning
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Senate chamber, skirmishing continued through the
weekend on the witness issue as partisan lines began hardening over
seeking more testimony. Democrats rejected a Republican invitation
to form a bipartisan working group of senators to work out details
for questioning witnesses, if a majority of the Senate wants them
called.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., in a letter to
Democratic leader Tom Daschle, suggested that the working group
``could anticipate and help resolve in advance any complications''
brought about by witness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle rejected Lott's proposal saying issues related to
witnesses should only be addressed if the Senate votes to compel
such testimony. ``It is my hope that such arrangements will
ultimately prove unnecessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To convict Clinton, two-thirds of the Senate _ or 67 of the 100
members _ would have to vote for at least one of the articles of
impeachment. Republicans hold a 55-45 majority, so even if all GOP
senators vote against Clinton, a dozen Democratic votes would be
needed to terminate his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In the only previous trial of a president, Andrew Johnson
escaped conviction by one vote in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the current trial recessed for the weekend, White
House Special Counsel Greg Craig told reporters that the case
presented by House Republicans ``ends as it began _ an
unsubstantiated circumstantial case that does not meet the
constitutional standard to remove the president from office.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton revised sections of his State of the
Union address and practiced it in the Family Theater. He is to
deliver the speech _ an outline of his agenda for the coming year _
Tuesday night in the House of Representatives, about eight hours
after lawyers begin his defense in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the president did not watch any of Saturday's Senate
session.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hyde's final remarks, other House prosecutors anticipated
Clinton's likely impeachment defense and cautioned senators against
buying into arguments that the president's behavior was not bad
enough to remove him from office. Perjury and obstruction of
justice, the prosecutors said, warrant terminating a presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will hear next week ... that the offenses charged by the
House are not impeachable. In other words, that even if the
allegations as set forth in the articles of impeachment are true,
so what?'' said Rep. Steven Buyer, R-Ind. ``I'm not offended by the
`so what?' defense, because if that's all you have, then try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyer characterized Clinton's effort to conceal his relationship
with Lewinsky as a ``premeditated assault on the administration of
justice (which) must be interpreted as a threat to our system of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham rarely referred to his notes and paced the
area behind the podium, his soft South Carolina drawl amplified by
a lapel microphone as he pleaded for ``cleansing'' the presidency
by removing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``President Clinton chose to cheat in every manner you can
cheat in a lawsuit,'' Graham said, referring to allegations that
the president lied in his deposition in the Jones case. ``If you
put him in jail after he leaves office, that would not solve the
constitutional problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Impeachment is not about punishment. Impeachment is about
cleansing the office. Impeachment is about restoring honor and
integrity to the office,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In his summary of the House case, Hyde defended the approval
last month _ largely along party lines _ of the two articles of
impeachment. Those in the Republican-controlled House who voted to
impeach are not, as some have suggested, ``Clinton-haters,'' Hyde
said. ``It is a disservice to the House to suggest that it has
brought these articles of impeachment before you in a mean-spirited
or irresponsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's five-hour session capped presentations over three
days by the 13 House managers. They detailed a case alleging abroad
conspiracy by Clinton to illegally conceal the Lewinsky affair from
the Jones lawyers, and then to hide the relationship from a federal
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The managers listed a half-dozen alleged lies by Clinton to the
grand jury and another eight in his Jan. 17, 1998, deposition in
the Jones case. And they identified several other acts they said
the president committed to hide evidence or influence the testimony
of other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   To make their case, the House prosecutors asserted that the
grand jury testimony of Lewinsky and presidential secretary Betty
Currie, which conflicts with testimony of the president, was more
believable. They repeatedly tried to bolster the former intern's
version of the affair, calling her ``very credible'' and her
assertions in past testimony ``common sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
