<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA READY TO PLAY `LET'S MAKE A DEAL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Begin ital) Warning: The following column may include a
reference to the salary cap. Reader indiscretion is advised. (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is on the cusp of a talent-acquisition riot the likes of
which won't be duplicated until a tractor-trailer jammed with
Furbies flips over a curb next to a hair salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be madness,'' said player agent Eric Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not going to happen until the league's new collective
bargaining agreement is written. It's been 10 days since the deal
between the players' union and owners was ratified, but a lawyer
from the O.J. Simpson trial would have hammered out this
contentious tome in four.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say any true stories about Bulls in Detroit, the
scattered plague of mediocre point guards, and sightings of a
misunderstood coach-choker in Florida won't occur until, well,
early this week. And anything that sounds like a fine deal probably
will be murdered by the ... salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the player movement will be mostly centered around
trades,'' said agent Bill Duffy , the representative for Michael
Stewart, a Sacramento Kings free agent who through the blindness of
strangers (also known as NBA general managers) managed to go
undrafted in 1997 after completing his eligibility at Cal. Who has
the inside track on the 6-foot-10 shot-blocker? ``Until something
happens,'' said Duffy, ``you'll hear a million stories.''
</P>
<P>
   We're only offering a few:
</P>
<P>
   How about Sherman Douglas choosing to pick up a pen and sign
with the Clippers? It makes dollars and a little sense. The
veteran, free-agent point guard should be affordable; he also
played for new Clips coach Chris Ford in Boston and Milwaukee.
Douglas, entering his 10th NBA campaign, spent last season with New
Jersey, averaging 8 points and 4 assists in his 21 minutes per
game.
</P>
<P>
   But it should be noted that Douglas was part of the package Ford
and the Bucks shipped to Cleveland in exchange for superior point
guard Terrell Brandon
</P>
<P>
   . Another problem with liberating Douglas from Jersey swamp land
could be defense. The Clippers want a point guard who is guilty of
playing a little.
</P>
<P>
   And now ... the departing lineup for your world champion Chicago
Bulls! Starting on the first tee is Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   . Reportedly shooting the curl over to the beaches of Phoenix is
center Luc Longley
</P>
<P>
   . Threatening to take his all-time, NBA-best 3-point percentage
to dreaded Detroit is former Palisades High hotshot Steve Kerr
</P>
<P>
   . At small-change forward, a disgruntled, below-market-value
free agent who may sign with Houston or San Antonio if he's not
traded to the Lakers is free agent Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Chicago Tribune, a deal sending a
signed-to-be-traded Pippen to Shaq Nation for Eddie Jonesand other
concerns may be sabotaged by the greediness of Bulls general
manager Jerry Krause
</P>
<P>
   . At the risk of blowing a deal and getting nothing for Pippen,
Krause reportedly wants draft picks, and any Lakers picks figure to
come toward the end of any upcoming drafts.
</P>
<P>
   We would have had the lowdown on their power forward, but are
proud to admit having no connection with anyone (or thing) who
could provide information about Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The homecoming of Brent Barry could be imminent. Hold it. The
free agent ex-Clipper is not expected to be lured back into the
loving embrace of the Sports Arena; Barry, the son of Golden State
Hall of Famer Rick Barry.
</P>
<P>
   (Brent still has a fine crop of hair, thank you), grew up in the
Bay Area and soon may be a Warrior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's a rumor,'' said Barry after a recent workout at
Veterans Park Sports Complex in Carson, ``until something gets
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the rumor: Barry, who was traded to Miami last season,
could be packaged with two other Heaters in a deal that would bring
three Warriors to Florida. One of these Warriors would be Latrell
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Or Barry could sign with the Bulls and be the hair apparent at
the off-guard position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any preferences,'' Barry said. ``I'm just going
to sit and wait patiently. I expect a few of the early signings to
have a domino effect on what happens with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it a Domino's Pizza effect that has the 6-6 Barry weighing in
at 222 pounds an increase of 17 pounds from early last season?
</P>
<P>
   Nah, weight lifting and healthy food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (extra weight) feels great,'' said the former NBA slam-dunk
champion, who spent much of last week running circles around his
ex-Clipper cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time to be rollin' with Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers fans remember this guy, which is why we should toss a
reminder at our readership's remaining 99 percent. McDyess was the
hot prospect the Clips selected with the second pick in the 1995
draft, then immediately traded to Denver for three fine players.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the bouncy, 6-9 McDyess who's averaged 15 points
and 7.5 rebounds in three NBA seasons (two in Denver, one in
Phoenix) the Clippers received Barry, Brian Williams and Rodney
Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   You know about Barry. Williams bolted after one season, then
became a bargain-basement Bull, a champion, and a rich Piston. A
few months back, he visited Tibet and became Bison Dele.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, if you're scoring at home, is still a Clipper. McDyess,
if you're burning your Clippers' T-shirt may return to Denver or
stay in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Former Long Beach State coach Tex Winter will continue as
offensive coordinator for the Bulls and new coach Tim Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   But with only four Bulls under contract, teaching Winter's
complicated ``triangle offense'' during an abbreviated training
camp may lead to one alternative:
</P>
<P>
   Circling the wagons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
