</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A FIRE DRILL WAITING TO HAPPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some advice for the following 48 hours as the NBA
launches into an accelerated signing period with all the speed,
twists and turns of a Six Flags roller coaster: Remain seated, stay
calm and maybe swallow a couple dramamine.
</P>
<P>
   This ride promises to be bumpy, disorienting, even dizzying.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200 free agents will find employment, and a couple dozen
more could be dealt in swap-meet fashion. All in a period that
should open Tuesday and end when the last general manager has
passed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league,'' notes Laker Kobe Bryant, ``might look completely
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The process began Saturday, as players and teams began
unofficially making deals that can't be signed until the NBA and
players union finalize the new labor deal in the next day or so.
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, Matt Geiger and Derrick Coleman are off the
market, agreeing to sign with New Jersey, Philadelphia and
Charlotte, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still the matter of finding homes for the likes of
Scottie Pippen, Antonio McDyess, Damon Stoudamire and Tom
Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   Both L.A. teams will be active, the Lakers probably sending
Elden Campbell to a team in need of a center and the Clippers
searching for a point guard to complement Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be some surprises,'' Shaquille O'Neal said slyly
of the Lakers' plans.
</P>
<P>
   We now know who probably isn't coming to the Lakers, but who is
remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, carrying 300 pounds and twice that amount in baggage,
is not. Charles Oakley, trapped in Toronto, isn't either.
Gugliotta's a 50-50 proposition, and Pippen is slightly below that.
Chris Webber's a longshot possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would love to put Gugliotta in the frontcourt,
hustling for rebounds and drawing crowds away from O'Neal. Problem
is, to obtain Gugliotta in a sign-and-trade deal, the Lakers have
to match his salary with some combination of players in return.
</P>
<P>
   Same deal with Pippen, and both players figure to get contracts
averaging more than $10 million a year. Campbell, wanted by several
teams as a starting center, makes $7 million. The Lakers are loathe
to part with Eddie Jones, and adding his salary of about $2.5
million won't be enough to balance either of those deals anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters further is the NBA's new labor deal isn't
complete, and general managers aren't certain what the precise
rules are concerning sign-and-trade deals.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a good chance the Lakers will lose out on both
Pippen and Gugliotta. Nothing is final, but reports over the
weekend indicated Pippen was leaning toward signing with Houston
and Gugliotta was leaning toward staying in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   A deal sending Campbell to Orlando for Horace Grant has also
been rumored, but Grant's salary of about $15 million isn't a good
match, and the Magic will probably fill its center need with
ex-Clipper Ike Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the old Webber scenario. Sacramento had vowed not
to trade him under any circumstances, but Kings ownership is in
flux and anything could happen now as general manager Geoff Petrie
threatens to quit one minute and decides to stay the next.
</P>
<P>
   The Latrell Sprewell relocation project will also be completed
in the next couple of days, and his fate could be linked to former
Clipper Brent Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Barry is a free agent with interest from several teams,
including Chicago, but he could be re-signed by Miami and packaged
in a deal to Golden State for Sprewell. A Bay Area native, Barry is
one of the few NBA commodities actually interested in playing for
the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Various reports have San Antonio, Indiana and the New York
Knicks alternately pulling out of and re-entering the Sprewell
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   What will happen? Who the heck knows? Just take the
motion-sickness pills, turn on ESPN and if you're keeping score at
home, write in pencil and keep an eraser handy.
</P>
<P>
   Laker makeover: Just what will the 1999 Lakers look like?
</P>
<P>
   All that's certain is they won't look like the team currently on
paper. Three rookies _ guards Tyronn Lue and Sam Jacobson and
forward Ruben Patterson _ tentatively fill the three open roster
spots, but that's unlikely to become permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' self-described Achilles heel last season was youth,
and trading Nick Van Exel for Lue and Tony Battie only made them
younger. Count on an influx of at least two veterans, hopefully
with playoff experience. They've lacked that element since Byron
Scott and Jerome Kersey moved on after the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we need is obviously leadership, an old
veteran,'' Eddie Jones said. ``Not a guy that will come in and give
you 20 or 30 (points), but an older guy that will come in and give
you that leadership, that authoritative person on the court, a guy
that's not afraid to say anything. I think that's what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   An old O'Neal pal, Dennis Scott, remains a possibility. Point
guard Kevin Johnson has been talked about. And Rick Fox, though he
appeared to be out of the capped-out Lakers' price range, is still
an option, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Count point guard Derek Fisher among those who would welcome a
veteran presence _ even if it's a point guard like Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if they made some changes to solidify
the point guard position,'' said Fisher, who became the starter
last season and solidified his role when Van Exel was traded.
``Even though I feel I'm ready, as an organization I don't know if
I would feel comfortable with a guy that's only been in the league
for two years (himself) and a rookie (Lue) leading my team to the
NBA title.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said he's heard talk of the Lakers signing Johnson, an
11-year vet with Finals experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have respect for him,'' Fisher said. ``He'll make our
team better, that's the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad move: The NBA players union, which already took a PR beating
_ and a loss at the bargaining table _ dealt its own credibility a
blow by decertifying agent Steve Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the dissident agent who filed a number of unfair labor
practice complaints against the union during the lockout, was
notified of the decision last week. Without union approval, Woods
would no longer be able to represent players. His current clients
are Kevin Willis and Willie Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Even Marc Fleisher, a union loyalist for most of the lockout,
was taken aback by the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all he did was express his opinion, I'm concerned about
taking this type of a measure without due process,'' Fleisher
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
