<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA CAN BEAT MINNESOATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - They have 15 wins, the most anonymous two-time
loser in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   They have a running back with tree-trunk thighs, the son of Mike
Tyson's security chief.
</P>
<P>
   They have a quarterback who has been tossed around like a rag
doll and the worst end-zone ritual this side of Ickey Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But, really, the remarkable transformation of the Atlanta
Falcons is all about one man, a coach who has finally found
unanimous respect, nearly dying in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reeves, the man who was run out of Denver and fired in New
York, has single-handedly put this thing together. A team with just
14 players that preceded his arrival in 1997. A team that is poised
to stun the Vikings and the world, and if they do, the menu will be
tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   Not because of the batch of lutefisk Jesse Ventura must ship to
Georgia in the traditional governor's bet.
</P>
<P>
   More like Reeves vs. John Elway. In the Super Bowl. A match-up
that would have a staff of cardiologists on call.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good week of practice,'' Reeves said. ``And I think
our football team is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons can beat the Vikings because they, too, play in a
dome. Because they have the speed on defense. Because they have a
workhorse named Jamal Anderson and a running game that can keep the
Vikings off the field. Because the Vikings are hurting with Jake
Reed inactive and John Randle questionable because of a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the presence of Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that cockiness that makes everyone around him
confident,'' Falcons receiver Terance Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 54, is the reigning Coach of the Year, certainly the
sentimental choice after undergoing a quadruple coronary bypass in
mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   He had a tumultuous career in Denver, where he frequently
clashed with the golden child. Reeves thought Elway was a baby, and
he was right. Elway thought Reeves was stifling his creativity, and
he was right. They were both stubborn and headstrong, and in the
end, the owner wisely sided with the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   With a heavy drawl, he was somewhat miscast in New York, even
though he was Coach of the Year after guiding the Giants to an 11-5
record in 1993. Eventually, he was fired because he wanted more
power than ownership was willing to give.
</P>
<P>
   But he got his wish in Atlanta, full control of the team that
threw away Brett Favre, a team coming off a disastrous 3-13 season
under June Jones. His first priority was quarterback, and after
pondering Elvis Grbac, he stole Chris Chandler from Houston. His
next priority was defense, signing free-agent cornerback Ray
Buchanan, who will line up across from Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, there were 39 new faces in uniform and a team
that won its second NFC West title in 33 years. A team that has won
21 of its last 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Falcons won their first playoff game since 1991,
and they're hardly content. In their locker room back in Atlanta, a
Purple Pride towel is tacked to a bulletin board. So is a quote
from the Vikings' Andrew Glover, who said the Vikings are
``impossible to beat'' at home. So is a poster of a Super Bowl ring
with the caption: ``See something you like? Go out and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' best maneuver, however, was his attack on the noose of
noise. It is no consolation to Cardinals fans, but Reeves asked the
NFL to investigate the Metrodome's policy on sound, and the league
responded. Today, those ridiculous sideline speakers behind the
visitors' bench will be moved closer to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   If the hosts prevail, the league will be salivating. The Vikings
are the glamorous ratings choice for the Super Bowl, a team that is
0-4 in the big game. An outfit that will no doubt be hyped as
possibly the best team in history, from the state that elected a
wrestler as governor.
</P>
<P>
   But in this season of redemption, destiny smells like Reeves vs.
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if his heart can handle it. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
