<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-PREVIEW-AZR &LR;      01-16 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSIVE, AND PROUD OF IT  
 VIKINGS RESHAPE FORMULA FOR SUCCESS IN NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ If defense wins championships, why are the
Minnesota Vikings one win away from claiming the NFC title today?
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Vikings' defense is bad, but it was their
record-setting scoring-machine offense that carried them to a
league-leading 15 regular-season wins, to 41 points in their
playoff opener against the Cardinals, and has positioned them as
the strongest threat to unseat defending Super Bowl champion Denver
in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there is the matter of the NFC championship game at
the Metrodome against the Atlanta Falcons, and their defense that
was surpassed only by San Diego's against the run.
</P>
<P>
   A test, yes, but the Vikings have been built to score: two
quarterbacks who could start almost anywhere; the league's
strongest threesome of wide receivers; a breakaway running back;
three All-Pro linemen opening holes.
</P>
<P>
   In a league of imitators, the Vikings have created the latest
trend with their financial commitment to players who can put points
on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are going to be copying the way our team is put
together, where we've spent the money,'' Vikings receiver Cris
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   As important as having high-powered pieces on the field is
having an offensive coordinator who knows what to do with them.
Brian Billick, a candidate for head coaching vacancies in Cleveland
and Baltimore, has pushed all the right buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has an amazing offensive mind,'' Vikings running back
Robert Smith said. ``The ways that he has attacked defenses has
been truly amazing. He is wrapping it up in so many different
packages that they feel like we are doing things that they haven't
prepared for. A moment's hesitation by the defense is all you need
when you have the kind of athletes that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, Atlanta's only hope in the din of the Metrodome is to
score first and control the ball. If the Falcons fall behind, well,
one need look no further than last week when the youthful Cardinals
became rattled in the incredible noise and quickly fell behind,
17-0. The Falcons' offense is directed by a veteran quarterback,
Chris Chandler, who might not be as inclined as Jake Plummer was to
developing the yips.
</P>
<P>
   But a league-record 556 regular-season points followed by scores
on 7 of 10 possessions against the Cardinals says that stopping, or
even slowing, the Vikings is a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to have any chance against them, we have got to play as
well as we possibly can,'' said Falcons Coach Dan Reeves, who plans
to be on the sideline despite having had bypass surgery last month.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Falcons, with a pair of corners not much taller than
the pompon line and reinforced by safeties who are well into their
30s, can deal with the Vikings' corps of tall, speedy receivers is
the story of the day. The ball is delivered to them by 35-year-old
quarterback Randall Cunningham, whom the Vikings had to coax out of
retirement last year.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Johnson was the Vikings' quarterback until he opened the
door for Cunningham with an early season injury. Johnson has become
trade bait. The Vikings would want a top-eight draft pick in a
trade package for Johnson, creating the scary spectre of yet
another weapon being added to their arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall came in and really played well,'' said Dennis Green,
the Vikings coach. ``If you look at what he's accomplished, he has
poise, confidence, a big, strong arm and a great feel for the game.
I think everyone's looking for players that have found peace and
want a second chance. I think a lot of guys leave the game and
leave many times before they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teams are interested in trading for Johnson, including
NFC teams Philadelphia and Washington. Imagine the Vikings with the
Eagles' second pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with what they have now is tall order enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tall quarterback (6 feet 4), we have tall receivers
(6-3, 6-4, 6-3). It's designed toward what we do,'' Green said.
``Cris Carter has been a great competitor for years. I think he's a
future Hall of Famer. Jake Reed is a player who developed for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Moss came to us as a polished, accomplished receiver. I
think most people think that Randy just has the ability to run
deep, but he can work all different routes and go one-on-one. His
best asset is probably that he's a great competitor. That's what he
brings to the football field when he goes against a defensive
back.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cunningham having so many receiving targets coupled with
the luxury of handing off to a game breaker like Smith, the Vikings
are changing thinking around the league: Defense might win
championships, but you can't beat what you can't catch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
