<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO DENYING PARCELLS' SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER - He stood at a lectern decorated with the familiar NFL
logo, a red, white and blue shield picturing a football on a field
of five-pointed stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any questions?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Before New York magpies could reply, all at once he exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   A deep sigh into a live microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells looked and sounded tired. Tired from the long
flight from New York. Tired from the traveling media circus that
surrounds his team. Tired from staying up late trying to figure out
how to beat John Elway and Terrell Davis and the Denver Broncos,
who almost never lose at home, in today's AFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching is a grindstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is never final,'' he once said. ``There's always more
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave it up once, or tried. Twenty years ago, after coaching
at Air Force, Parcells decided to spend more time with his family
and put down roots in Colorado Springs. He took a job with a land
development company.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife had Broncos season tickets. They attended every
home game. ``I could walk to those seats right now,'' Parcells
fondly recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But the self-imposed exile didn't last. Just as some are called
to preach, some are called to coach. Parcells was born for the job.
And no one in his profession is better.
</P>
<P>
   His resume is familiar to anyone who follows pro football.
Parcells won two championships with the New York Giants. Then he
moved to New England and took the Patriots to the title game. Now,
surprise, he is one win away from returning to the Super Bowl with
another team, the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who, in 1996 were 1-15.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year, Parcells led them to a 9-7 record. This year
they finished 12-4 and won their first AFC East title and now here
they are in Denver feeling as high as the altitude and thinking, so
what if they are the underdogs. Anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets beat Miami and Buffalo on the road. They won 11 of
their past 12 games. Led by Vinnie Testaverde _ cut by the
Baltimore Ravens _ the Jets believe in themselves and what they are
doing, which is a tribute to their coach. A charming grouch,
Parcells is the best in the business at motivating players.
</P>
<P>
   This is all you need to know about the man's confidence and his
outlook. On his first day of training camp, the new coach, who has
total control of football operations, was asked why anyone who had
been to three Super Bowls would take over the worst team in the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells answered with a story. ``Two guys are sent to Australia
to sell shoes to the Aborigines. One guy calls his boss and says,
`There's no opportunity here. The natives don't wear shoes.' The
other guy calls and says, `There are a lot of opportunities here.
These people don't have any shoes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He is an opportunist. A salesman. The best at what he does, bar
none. What other coach could help Testaverde suddenly bloom at 35?
Who else could handle Bryan Cox, the temperamental and disruptive
ex-Dolphin/ex-Bear?
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jets played the Dolphins, Parcells placed a
half-empty gasoline can in Cox's locker. It was the coach's
needling way of questioning whether the veteran linebacker had
anything left in his tank. He did, and does.
</P>
<P>
   After an early season loss to the St. Louis Rams, Parcells
abruptly walked off the field during practice and took his
assistant coaches with him.
</P>
<P>
   Another day he wore one of his glittering Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   Like all great coaches, Parcells measures his players'
competitiveness against his own. He knows what buttons to push, and
not to push. He surrounds himself with ``his guys'' _ guys like
5-foot-7 return man Dave Meggett, who was out of football when
Parcells recently signed him. Meggett played for Parcells in New
York and New England. The Jets have nine former Giants and
ex-Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Today they will play in Mile High Stadium wearing the same style
of uniforms Joe Namath and his Jets wore when they won Super Bowl
III 30 years ago. Parcells made the decision to resurrect those
uniforms the day after he took the job.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes don't make the man. A coach can't make plays. But
Parcells is the person responsible for bringing the Jets this far,
this fast. His team may not win. But I would never bet against
him. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
