<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6288 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-PREVIEW-AZR &LR;      01-16 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINAL HOME GAME HURRAH  
 ELWAY LEAVING ON HIS TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He doesn't want any weeping goodbyes, so those who
adore him are giving His Rocky Mountain Majesty a one-game farewell
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway's teammates aren't about
to let him walk out of Mile High Stadium for the last time as a
loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very emotional,'' tight end Shannon Sharpe
said.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Super Bowl champions have won 18 consecutive home
games going into today's AFC championship game against the New York
Jets. They've won 24 regular-season games in a row at Mile High
Stadium, 32 of 35 under Coach Mike Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are well aware of the historical implications. One
minute, cornerback Otis Smith refers to Elway as ``the Michael
Jordan of Denver.'' The next minute, linebacker Bryan Cox talks
about crashing Elway's party.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to do, send a cheer for him?''' Cox said.
``He had a great career, and he's doing the same thing as Michael
Jordan. He's leaving on his terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) damn, I ain't got nothing to do with that. I'm not
worried about his last game. I'm trying to get to the next game,
and we have to get through the best team to do that. I don't give a
crap about the rest of the stuff. I'm not sentimental.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are fighting words in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Elway could run for mayor or governor of Colorado. Fans still
are hoping that the future Hall of Famer will come back for a 17th
season, but he maintains it's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, his family voted, 5-1, in favor of him playing
another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no votes this year, at least not yet,'' said Elway,
who is married with four children. ``I've been too busy. They're
never home, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get a full ballot, and they're always out. And there
are no absentee ballots.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos players, coaches and team officials, knowing today is
Elway's last home game, are asking the fans to scream louder than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``How loud can the decibel level go at Mile High Stadium?''
defensive end Alfred Williams said. ``Whatever answer is, that's
how loud it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos owner Pat Bowlen gets choked up just thinking about the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be the last time I watch Number 7, period,'' he said.
``I'm not assuming we're going to win. I'm hoping we're going to
win, but that will be an emotional moment for me that drags out for
a long time. I don't want to be overly dramatic or anything, but
this could be the last time I kneel down next to John in the locker
room, holding hands when we say the team prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotion that will be there should be unbelievable because
John has been the franchise, no matter how far back you look over
the last 38 years. I don't think we'll ever have a player who will
be raised to that stature. . . . John obviously will have his
special place in Denver because he really brought this franchise
from the idea that it was guys in funny orange jerseys from the
mountains into national prominence. Even though Denver went to the
Super Bowl in 1977, nobody ever took the team seriously until
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many are taking the Jets' chances seriously. They're
nine-point underdogs against a team that scored 501 points during
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has averaged 35 points a game at Mile High and has been
particularly devastating in the first quarter when it outscored
opponents, 158-54. Of those 158 points, 54 have been scored on the
first drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous challenge to try to stop these guys,'' Jets
Coach Bill Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is the reason many Jets fans think they can get the
upset. He has taken the New York Giants to two Super Bowls and the
New England Patriots to one. Now, he has a team that was 1-15 two
years ago one step away from Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has been in three conference championship games and won
all of them. He is considered the ultimate big-game coach, a master
motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put something on the bulletin board this week,'' Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde said. ``He said one mistake at the
wrong time can send a team packing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets know they can't make many mistakes against the Broncos'
high-powered offense. They have the NFL's Most Valuable Player in
running back Terrell Davis, who ran for 2,008 yards and 21
touchdowns. If Davis gets untracked, it makes Elway and the passing
game that much more effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can run the football with the best of them,''
said Shanahan, whose rushing attack was ranked second in the
league. ``They can stop us, but at what cost?''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets also have great offensive weapons. Testaverde led AFC
passers with 61.5 percent completions for 3,256 yards and 29
touchdowns. He was intercepted only seven times.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Curtis Martin rushed for 1,287 yards. Wide receiver
Keyshawn Johnson had 83 catches for 1,131 yards and 10 scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was around Jerry Rice, every time he touched the ball
he thought he was going to score,'' said Shanahan, formerly
offensive coordinator of the San Francisco 49ers. ``I see the same
thing in Keyshawn Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have a slogan for today's game: ``Carpe diem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means seize the day, seize the moment,'' tight end Kyle
Brady said. ``One thing that's been made very clear to us by the
older veterans is that in this league, you don't know how many
opportunities you are going to get at something like this. So,
you'd better take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, meanwhile, has only one more opportunity at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's retiring, John would rather think this one's for the
fans,'' Bowlen said. ``Because John is well aware that he's had the
greatest fans. They've elevated him, and he's elevated himself, to
a stature somewhere up there with the Rocky Mountains.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
