<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFF-SEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS ASSESS WHAT WENT RIGHT, FOR A CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What goes on when the minds of the Cardinals congregate to
evaluate a season?
</P>
<P>
   Who throws the darts, and who strains a muscle patting himself
on the back? More important, who brings the doughnuts?
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' brass was in the unaccustomed position last week
of grading itself on a successful season, its first winning record
since 1984, its first playoff appearance since 1975, and its first
playoff win since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to take credit for discovering the players who
made it happen. By one account, there were not enough feathers for
the headdresses.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Coach Vince Tobin and his assistants have replaced
contempt with credibility in the locker room and on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, territorial niches are guarded as tightly as Aeneas
Williams rubbing out Michael Irvin. The games the big boys play are
fascinating, and front-office relationships border on the
dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   The team is owned by Bill Bidwill, who is content to leave
football decisions to football people. He has hired a good one in
Bob Ferguson, vice president for player personnel. Ferguson was a
key mover in building Super Bowl teams at Buffalo and Denver. He
has made his point by finding a number of ``keepers'' in the late
rounds for the Cardinals, the biggest being defensive tackle Mark
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bidwill Jr., a vice president, has veto power on all
football operations. He took over negotiations with first-round
draft pick Andre Wadsworth during a 44-day holdout. Bidwill Jr. is
credited with signing quarterback Jake Plummer to an extension that
includes a league-record $15 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The peacemaker, and at times dealmaker, is Bidwill Jr.'s
brother, Michael. His primary duty is getting voter approval of the
Rio Salado Crossing, which would include a retractable-roof,
natural-grass stadium for the team in Mesa. He was the closer in
the Wadsworth deal.
</P>
<P>
   They have a team of scouts tripping over each other to prove to
their higher-ups that they can spot talent _ not unlike the manner
in which fans suddenly tripped over themselves to hop on the
bandwagon that for years was parked in the barn.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Mr. B isn't crazy about seeing any of them quoted
in the newspaper, it's easier getting Susan McDougal to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this is the group that will chart the course of a team that
has made giant steps, and one positioned to make even more. The
roster is young, it has high draft picks _ two in the first round _
and it has salary-cap room.
</P>
<P>
   So there they were, in a room together for hours on end every
day last week, assessing the state of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in pretty good shape,'' Bidwill Jr. said. ``We have four
unrestricted free agents who are pretty valuable. If we sign them
back, we'll have no glaring holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The four are outside linebacker Jamir Miller, offensive left
tackle Lomas Brown, wide receiver Rob Moore and safety Kwamie
Lassiter. Even if the salary cap increases by the anticipated 10
percent, Miller or Moore might have to be ``franchised'' to fit
them both in.
</P>
<P>
   One break the team expects is an enormous rookie salary pool
given its high picks and the three compensatory picks its expects
to be awarded for free agents lost last year.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be unanimity on two issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two things we couldn't do,'' Ferguson said, ``was pick up
the yard on fourth and 1 or first and goal, and we got the ball run
down our throats. Which will we address first? Everyone has their
own opinion on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals need a big back, a lead blocker who also can
convert for them in short-yardage situations.
</P>
<P>
   They have to determine if their highly regarded defensive line
is just young, or if some of the luminaries are overrated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals used their last three first-round picks on
defensive players _ ends Simeon Rice in 1996 and Wadsworth last
year, and cornerback Tom Knight in 1997. The success of the
Minnesota Vikings, who put the bulk of their resources into
building an offense that took them to an NFL-best 15-1 record while
scoring a league-record 566 points, adds weight to the argument
that it's time to spend more on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be shocked to see the Cardinals use one of their
first-round picks on an offensive lineman, especially in view of
the uncertainty regarding rookie Anthony Clement, a 6-foot-7,
355-pound behemoth coming off surgery on a herniated disc. He is
expected to recover, but until the Cardinals see it on the field,
they're not certain.
</P>
<P>
   They need at least one more receiver. The Vikings have shown
that a team can't have too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   On the defensive side, linemen Eric Swann and Brad Ottis are in
limbo because of injuries. Swann still is on crutches after the
second surgery in two months on his arthritic right knee. Ottis
fractured the same foot twice in four months. The bone graft from
the second surgery seems to have taken. The Cardinals won't have a
good read on either until after the bulk of free-agent signings.
</P>
<P>
   The team might need another outside linebacker. Can Tony
McCombs, a second-year player who started most of the season,
continue to improve? Is Patrick Sapp, who replaced him during the
playoffs, the answer? Or neither?
</P>
<P>
   Is Ron McKinnon the real deal at middle linebacker, or just the
beneficiary of Swann's dominance up front?
</P>
<P>
   Another safety and a return specialist also are needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have (4,000) people out to greet you at the airport,
as we did on one occasion, it is symbolic of the groundswell
support that has been generated,'' Michael Bidwill said. ``We
appreciate that and thank our fans. It has been an unbelievable
year, on the field and in the community. We've got a good watermark
now. We'll try to continue to improve upon that, on the field and
in the community.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
