<HEADLINE>
RUMORS DOG SCHOTTENHEIMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Kansas City Chiefs Coach  &UR; Marty Schottenheimer will be
the 1999 version of  &UR; George Seifert, a coach in waiting whose name
will surface for every NFL job next season.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there are rumors that Schottenheimer will replace  &UR; Dick
 &UR; Vermeil in St. Louis after next year.
</P>
<P>
   He also could have his pick of other jobs.  &UR; Pete Carroll, still
haunted by the ghost of  &UR; Bill Parcells, is in trouble in New
England. Just last week, he fired two assistants, a sure sign that
the next pink slip will be that of the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bobby Ross also could be dumped in Detroit. Team officials
wanted to bring in  &UR; Matt Millen as a front-office executive over
him, but after Ross objected and threatened to quit, the Lions
withdrew the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where Schottenheimer goes, he had to get out of
Kansas City, where talk about his personal life has been the rage.
It got so out of control that during the news conference last week
to announce his resignation, he said, ``There have been rumors
during this last season regarding my marriage and my personal life.
Those rumors are absolutely false and untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife,  &UR; Pat, was at the news conference. For months, she has
had to endure gossip and innuendo that her husband has been having
an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Their son,  &UR; Brian, who was on the Chiefs' coaching staff, said
he also had heard the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard them all, too,'' he said. ``All the crazy stories.
And I can tell you, they're completely untrue. Everyone has someone
they know that's convinced it's a fact, so sometimes it's hard to
listen to it. But I know better, and you just have to laugh it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, I'm 25. I'm single. I go to bars. Of course, I hear the
stories. If anything, the rumors should be about me. I don't know,
maybe people were confusing my dad with me. But I think a lot of
that comes with just being an NFL coach and being a public
figure.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether his mother was bothered by the rumors, the
younger Schottenheimer's said, ``Not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's tougher than all of us put together. She's been an NFL
coach's wife for a long time.'' &QL; 
Renaissance man
</P>
<P>
   Seifert, the new coach of the Carolina Panthers, enjoys fishing
for 165-pound marlins and going to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   He said his favorite show is ``Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it five times,'' Seifert said. ``I love it. The
first time I saw it I was in London. It brought tears to my eyes. I
don't know if I could ever watch it and not be moved by it.'' &QL; 
History major
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ron Wolf, general manager of the Green Bay Packers, researched
how teams that replaced successful head coaches from within fared.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered that nearly all of the time the assistants were
colossal failures, including in Green Bay when  &UR; Phil Bengston
replaced
 &UR; Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   The only times the promoted assistants did well were in Oakland
when
 &UR; Tom Flores replaced  &UR; John Madden and in San Francisco when Seifert
replaced  &UR; Bill Walsh. Both Flores and Seifert went on to win Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   He used that information to explain to Packers offensive
coordinator
 &UR; Sherman Lewis why he was bypassed for former Philadelphia Eagles
Coach
 &UR; Ray Rhodes in replacing  &UR; Mike Holmgren, who left to become general
manager-coach at Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands it,'' Wolf said of Lewis. ``I'm not sure he
accepts it.''
</P>
<P>
   Going, going, gone?
</P>
<P>
   Two former Cardinals were among the five players left
unprotected by the 49ers for the Cleveland Browns' upcoming
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers exposed  &UR; Chuck Levy, the Arizona product who was a
second-round draft pick of the Cardinals in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   They also made available deep snapper  &UR; Randy Kirk, whom 49ers
teammates call ``White Trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Terry Kirby got Kirk a baseball cap inscribed with
that nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby wouldn't say why Kirk was given that moniker but
acknowledged that Kirk often was seen leaving the team's practice
facility carrying a 12-pack of beer. &QL; 
Unhappy campers
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's  &UR; Bill Cowher now is the dean of NFL coaches, but
Steelers officials aren't happy the team slipped from 11-5 and six
consecutive playoff seasons to 7-9 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is talented enough to be in the playoffs,'' said
 &UR; Ton
 &UR; Donahoe, director of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   Team President  &UR; Dan Rooney said he can't accept the team ending
the season with a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were definitely capable of winning the division,
and I still do,'' Rooney said. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   If the Washington Redskins fire  &UR; Norv Turner, the Cardinals'
 &UR; Vince
 &UR; Tobin will be the most senior coach in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are $28 million over the estimated $57 million salary
cap for next season.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka, on offensive coordinator
 &UR; Danny Abramowitz being under fire: ``As long as I'm here, he's
here. When they get rid of me, Danny and I are going to go out
dancing together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
