<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS THE REAL SUPER SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Welcome to the happiest day of the whole NFL
season, conference championship day, the really Super Sunday. Twice
the games and half the calories.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades' experience shows that if you want a great
football game, you're more likely to see it in today's conference
championships than two weeks from now in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not in the past decade, (begin ital)both(end
ital) conference title games were harder fought than the Super Bowl
they set up.
</P>
<P>
   Will it happen again with the Atlanta Falcons vs. the Minnesota
Vikings and the New York Jets vs. the Denver Broncos? Don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Do know these teams will have an easier time cracking the list
of the top 10 Super Bowls, if there is such a list, than our list
of the top 10 conference title-games, which follows.
</P>
<P>
   10.: Minnesota 24, Los Angeles 13; Dec. 26, 1976: Of the four
Rams playoff losses to the Vikings in an eight-year span, this was
the most heartbreaking, though the turning point came early.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence McCutcheon fell short of a touchdown on a controversial
call. Tom Dempsey tried a field goal. Nate Allen blocked it. Bobby
Bryant grabbed the ball on a big hop and ran 90 yards through the
12-below wind at the old Met.
</P>
<P>
   A John Cappelletti fumble and a blocked punt put the Rams in a
deep hole and a late interception thrown by Pat Haden kept them
there.
</P>
<P>
   Did you have to bring it up?
</P>
<P>
   9.: Pittsburgh 16, Oakland 10; Jan. 4, 1976: It was 3-0 Steelers
after three quarters on the ice at Three Rivers Stadium, and then a
hockey game broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth they went. Franco Harris, 25 yards for a
touchdown. Ken Stabler, a TD pass to Mike Siani. Terry Bradshaw, a
TD pass to John Stallworth. Forty-eight-year-old George Blanda, a
field goal. The Raiders recovered an offside kick but time ran out
on them.
</P>
<P>
   8.: Miami 21, Pittsburgh 17; Dec. 31, 1972: Bob Griese, out with
a broken ankle since October, relieved Earl Morrall in the second
half and led drives to two Jim Kiick TDs for the Dolphins on their
way to a 17-0 season.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bradshaw's forward fumble had given the Steelers an early
lead, but the tackle knocked him out of the game with dizziness,
and when he returned he threw two late interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   7.: Pittsburgh 20, Indianapolis 16; Jan. 14, 1996: Almost the
greatest ending in conference-championship history _ but Jim
Harbaugh's Hail Mary pass to Aaron Bailey fell incomplete at the
gun. Bam Morris had scored the winning TD with 1:34 to play.
</P>
<P>
   6.: New York Giants 15, San Francisco 13; Jan. 20, 1991: The
Giants' defense and ball-control offense _ an NFL record-low 14
turnovers in the regular season _ won it the hard way with five
Matt Bahr field goals. The last split the uprights from 42 yards as
time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   5.: Washington 24, San Francisco 21; Jan. 8, 1984: Mark Mosely's
winning field goal from 25 yards with :40 on the clock wasn't the
most dramatic thing about this game. Three Joe Montana TD passes in
the fourth quarter had wiped out a 21-0 Redskins lead. Montana's 27
completions set an NFL championship record but this was one game he
couldn't pull out.
</P>
<P>
   4. San Diego 17, Pittsburgh 13; Jan. 15, 1995: Neil O'Donnell
had an AFC championship-record 32-for-54 day but Stan Humphries'
pair of 43-yard TD passes in the second half for the Chargers put
the Bolts ahead. The Steelers had first and goal at the 9 but
O'Donnell's fourth-down pass was deflected by Dennis Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   3.: Denver 38, Cleveland 33; Jan. 17, 1988: Earnest Byner would
like this to be remembered for the John Elway-led 75-yard drive _
The !ital!Other Drive _ to the Broncos' winning TD at 4:01. But
it's remembered for the Byner fumble that ended the Browns' ensuing
drive at the 3 with a little over a minute left.
</P>
<P>
   Byner had run for 67 yards and a score and caught passes for 120
and a score but came out of it as the biggest goat in conference
championship history.
</P>
<P>
   2.: Denver 23, Cleveland 20 (overtime); Jan. 11, 1987: The
Drive. Broncos trail 20-13. Ball on their own 2. Elway takes them
98 yards in 15 plays, nine of them passes, ending with the
game-tying 5-yarder to Mark Jackson with 37 seconds to play. Then
Rich Karlis' field goal wins it in OT.
</P>
<P>
   1.: San Francisco 28, Dallas 27; Jan. 10, 1982: The Catch. It
was already a classic before that, the 49ers and Cowboys trading
leads five times to put Joe Montana at a 27-21 disadvantage with
less than five minutes to go and the ball at his own 11.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen plays later, Montana rolled right from the Cowboys' 6,
threw high in the corner of the end zone and Dwight Clark reached
as high as he could to pull it down.
</P>
<P>
   For the 49ers, who went 2-14 two seasons earlier, it was the
first of four conference titles under Bill Walsh. For what it's
worth, it was Vin Scully's last football game.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. One fan's ranking of the best conference-title games.
</P>
<P>
   Top 10 Super Bowls to follow as soon as we get to 10 good ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
