<HEADLINE>
BUDGET PLAN A THREAT TO OHV FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Arizona's Joint Legislative Budget Committee has
proposed a budget plan for fiscal year 2000 that would transfer $1
million to the general fund from State Parks' Off-Highway Vehicle
recreation funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Office of Strategic Planning, on the other hand,
doesn't recommend changing the allocation of OHV funds to State
Parks.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, according to State Parks officials, the joint
committee budget would severely affect the availability of funding
for OHV grants and programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Education and Natural Resources Joint Appropriations
Subcommittee is scheduled to hear the State Parks budget on Feb. 5
at 9 a.m. in Senate Hearing Room 1.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is this: OHV operators often are criticized by the
public for tearing up terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The OHV program addresses those perceptions with grants to
establish OHV courses and to educate operators on proper ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that when the Legislature sees a tight budget, it
often turns to State Parks for funding?  &QL; 
Great Western studied &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service is exploring the possibilities of adding
the Great Western Trail to the National Trails System.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,100-mile trail would run from the U.S. border with Mexico
to Canada. It would accommodate the full gamut of outdoor travelers
from off-highway vehicles, to bicycles, to horses, to hiking.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of the trail is to link western towns and provide an
opportunity to discover the heritage of the communities in addition
to the outdoor experience.
</P>
<P>
   Congress requested that the Forest Service study the feasibility
of the trail becoming part of the National Trails System.
</P>
<P>
   The trail already is well-established in Utah and parts of
Arizona. The trail will use existing roads and trails, mostly on
public land.
</P>
<P>
   The study will determine if such a trail is feasible and
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Informational public meetings are scheduled this week in Tucson,
Phoenix and Flagstaff. The meetings will include information about
proposed routes. Videos, maps and land management personnel will
provide the information.
</P>
<P>
   All meetings will start at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson meeting is Tuesday at the Arizona Doubletree Hotel,
445 S. Alvernon Way; The Phoenix session is Wednesday at Tonto
National Forest offices, 2324 E. McDowell Road; and Flagstaff's
meeting is Thursday at the city hall, 211 W. Aspen Ave. &QL; 
Sunrise, Snowbowl open &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warm weather that hit Arizona last week, some slopes
at both Sunrise and Arizona Snowbowl ski areas remain open.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Sunrise, between Pinetop and Springerville,
reported a 24-inch snow base and said 33 percent of the slopes were
open. Lifts 1, 3 and 8 are operating.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise still is manufacturing snow at night to keep the slopes
skiable.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Snowbowl near Flagstaff reported a 26-inch base and
eight runs open on Mount Agassiz.
</P>
<P>
   The report predicted warm weather and good skiing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, it will turn nasty in the mountains. Otherwise, both
ski areas _ especially Snowbowl, which can't make snow _ could be
in trouble. That's not to mention the cross-country courses, which
already are in deep trouble. &QL; 
Walleye anglers meet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Walleye Anglers have two meetings scheduled this
week in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Warnecke, the Arizona Game Fish Department biologist in
charge of lakes formed by the Salt, Verde and Agua Fria rivers,
will be the speaker on Tuesday when the Phoenix chapter holds its
monthly meeting, beginning at 7:30 p.m. at the American Legion hall
at Cave Creek Road and Peoria Avenue. He will explain walleye
stocking plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa chapter will hear from Ty Gray, an urban lakes
biologist, at it's meeting Thursday. That meeting also begins at
7:30 p.m. at Citrus Gardens, 4065 E. University Drive.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the public is welcome free of charge. &QL; 
Perez, Angulo win &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Perez and Frank Angulo, both of Tempe, weighed in a
six-bass limit totaling 10.18 pounds to win the second BestBet
Aluminum Boat bass fishing tournament at Bartlett Lake.
</P>
<P>
   They won $1,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The BestBet circuit is new, and participants can fish only from
aluminum boats. None can be on the pro circuits. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
