<HEADLINE>
CASINO BEEFS UP SECURITY FOR TYSON FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The MGM Grand went back into the boxing business
Saturday as though it were going to war.
</P>
<P>
   Heightened security was evident throughout the hotel and casino
before the Mike Tyson-Frans Botha bout, the first fight at the MGM
since the near-riot after Tyson bit Evander Holyfield's ears in
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 180 uniformed and plainclothes officers were assigned to
various details in and around the hotel's arena. The MGM said it
paid for the additional costs in security.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson fights often have been marred by violence and other
problems. After Tyson's victory over Bruce Seldon, rapper Tupac
Shakur was gunned down near the Strip in a suspected gang killing.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bite Fight, the casino was closed when gunshots were
reported. MGM management later said loud pops were the result of
breaking champagne bottles and exploding firecrackers instead of
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   During a stampede for the doors, $134,000 worth of chips
disappeared from a blackjack table. The hairdresser for former NBA
star Dominique Wilkins, Jeffrey Jerome Campbell, eventually pleaded
guilty to attempted grand larceny. &QL; 
Religious gifts
</P>
<P>
   Tyson received presents from Zaneb and Fatima Ali, the daughters
of Valley businessman Tahir Ali, who is the fighter's sponsor at
the Islamic Community Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson received a traditional head covering, a prayer rug from
Mecca and some prayer beads.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts are exchanged during a three-day celebration of Eud
ul-Fitr at the end of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan. &QL; 
Strange bedfellows
</P>
<P>
   Botha trainer Panama Lewis was not in the corner Saturday night
because of a ban for altering gloves that was imposed in 1983 by
then-New York Commissioner Randy Gordon. Today, Gordon works for
Botha as a media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think Panama did it,'' Gordon said of the trainer, who
did a couple of years in prison as a result of removing padding
from Luis Resto's gloves in a terrible battering of Billy Collins.
``But we have an understanding of each other's roles in terms of
helping Botha.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Ken Starr and Al Gore on the same presidential
ticket in 2000? &QL; 
Rumor rings true
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of talk that Charles Barkley is headed to the
Seattle SuperSonics, and Barkley himself did most of the talking
late Friday after he and Sonics guard Gary Payton arrived for the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where am I going to be playing?'' he yelled to a crowd that
had gathered around him at the MGM casino.
</P>
<P>
   The chorus-like response was ``Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' Barkley said. &QL; 
Briefly &QL; 
Happy birthday: Muhammad Ali is 57 today. A party for him is
scheduled at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's new trainer, former Evander Holyfield cornerman Tommy
Brooks, signed for three fights at close to $1 million per bout.
Brooks averaged about $250,000 a fight with Holyfield. Brook's best
payday was Bite Fight, when he collected $500,000. &QL; 
Republic writer Kelly Ettenborough contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
