</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-OVERLOOKED SQUAD LOOKS GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So who were the biggest losers when it came to filling out the
rosters for the NHL's World and North American All-Star teams?
</P>
<P>
   A few names immediately come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Kings'  &UR; Luc Robitaille, who entered the weekend
with 24 goals and 42 points? Or Edmonton's  &UR; Bill Guerin, who had 18
goals and 33 points at the time of the selections? And then you
have other woulda-coulda-shouldas such as Buffalo's  &UR; Michael Peca,
Dallas'
 &UR; Jere Lehtinen and Philadelphia's  &UR; John Vanbiesbrouck and  &UR; Rod
 &UR; Brind'Amour.
</P>
<P>
   The nonselection of Robitaille, fresh off his 500th goal, is
perhaps the worst case, which Kings Coach  &UR; Larry Robinson wasn't
afraid to address when asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised. I was even more surprised when I saw who
made it,'' Robinson said. ``I'm not saying (Montreal's)  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Recchi is not a great hockey player, but he's having a (expletive)
year. The All-Star Game isn't about what you did. It's about what
you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerin, snubbed yet again, wasn't about to add fuel to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I got screwed,'' Guerin said. ``Luc
Robitaille's not there and he's having a hell of a year.'' &QL; 
Band on the run &QL; 
Rock bands split up all the time, but there's not a lot you can do
when your drummer gets traded to Anaheim and one of your guitarists
gets dealt to Phoenix. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the expansion Nashville Predators banded
together this season and formed a group. Apparently, they were
pretty good. But goalie  &UR; Dominic Roussel, the band's leader, was
traded to the Mighty Ducks in October. Then last week, defenseman
 &UR; J.J. Daigneault was shipped to the Coyotes for future
considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got together and tried to make something happen _ and we
did,'' Daigneault said. ``I don't think we're all that good, but
we're having fun and it sounds like a song when we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it ``did.'' The band was versatile, though, playing
everything from ``Sweet Home Alabama'' to ``With or Without You''
and was in the process of adding some country tunes to the play
list. And not just because  &UR; Garth Brooks is a close friend of Coach
 &UR; Barry Trotz.
</P>
<P>
   They still were searching for a name for the band before
Daigneault left. Dry Ice, the Crosscheckers and the Offsiders were
among some of the ideas being bandied about. But now that the band
has shrunk to a trio consisting of  &UR; Denny Lambert, Darren Turcotte
and
 &UR; Sebastien Bordeleau, maybe the remaining members should borrow
another hockey term and simply call themselves Short-Handed. &QL; 
Mileage marker
</P>
<P>
   Further proof that Eastern Conference teams have it easier when
it comes to traveling during the course of an 82-game schedule,
especially against conference opponents:
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia will travel an estimated 18,558 miles to face teams
in its own conference this season. By contrast, a team such as the
Dallas Stars will travel 32,694 to face foes in the Western
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know how good they've got it in the East,'' Stars
forward  &UR; Dave Reid said. ``It's so much easier in the East, it's
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Stars, by the way, on Saturday wrapped up a
five-game Western swing to Calgary, Vancouver, Edmonton, San Jose
and Anaheim that covered 5,304 miles. &QL; 
How Swede it is &QL; 
Anaheim defenseman  &UR; Fredrik Olausson, with an 18-point spurt since
Dec.13, is six points away from becoming the second non-North
American blueliner to reach the 500-point plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Swedish defensemen led the pack over fellow Europeans (Russians,
Finns and Czechs). The all-time leading blueline scorer born
outside of the United State and Canada is Sweden's  &UR; Borje Salming,
who racked up 787 points. Next is Olausson, followed by fellow
Swedes
 &UR; Calle Johnansson (431),  &UR; Nicklas Lidstrom (393) and  &UR; Stephen
Persson (369).
</P>
<P>
   Olausson, a former Winnipeg Jet, had hardly displayed any
offensive production for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was thinking defense first because that's what (Craig)
Hartsburg wants,'' teammate  &UR; Teemu Selanne said. ``But Freddie can
do so much damage, offensively. That's what makes him so good.'' &QL; 
Slumping Shanahan &QL; 
One of the reasons the Detroit Red Wings have been in a bit of
tailspin is because  &UR; Brendan Shanahan is in one, too. Goal-less in
10 straight games entering the weekend, his game has fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman has been so frustrated with his star wing
that he's yanked him off the power-play unit and slashed his
minutes to 12 to 14 a game. That won't last for long, though.
Shanahan is simply in a slump and should pull out rather soon.
</P>
<P>
   Captain  &UR; Steve Yzerman isn't terribly concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mere presence keeps a lot of guys honest,'' Yzerman said.
``If he's not scoring, he's still effective and doing a lot of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate  &UR; Darren McCarty's take on the overall situation in
Detroit?
</P>
<P>
   ``Team Schizophrenia, that's what it feels like,'' McCarty said.
``We're the only ones who can fix it. We know when we do play our
game, we're successful. When we don't, we suck. And right now, we
suck a lot.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
