<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FREE-AGENCY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-AGENT DANCE ABOUT TO GET HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Analysis 
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It is the biggest, most expensive game of musical
chairs ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the next few days, when the NBA and its players
union finally get their new collective bargaining agreement down in
writing, 29 teams will try to place almost 200 free agents on
rosters at about the same time training camps begin.
</P>
<P>
   And the general managers and coaches of those 29 teams don't
even know whether the music stops Tuesday or even later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than speculation at this point, it's confusion,''
said one NBA general manager.
</P>
<P>
   As a public service, then, we'll try to figure this out. But
remember, this is for entertainment purposes only. Please, no
wagering.
</P>
<P>
   The three players who will determine much of what happens in the
entire league are the Suns' Antonio McDyess, Chicago's Scottie
Pippen and Minnesota's Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   They are the three most desirable free agents on the board, and
once they decide where they will play, the rest of the free agents
will begin falling into place.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess is a mystery. A friend who is fielding phone calls for
him said McDyess may wait until Tuesday to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do the Suns find themselves in a situation where, if
money isn't a factor, they don't have an advantage in getting a
player. But that appears to be the case. The Suns can pay McDyess
more than Houston or Denver, although state tax laws in Texas put
Houston on nearly equal ground.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing speculation that McDyess will go to Denver,
Pippen will end up in Houston and Gugliotta will stay in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that's how it falls.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns would fill out their roster with less flashy names, try
to work some trades and end up as a playoff team, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Houston will re-sign Charles Barkley and have another aging
team, but one that is capable of winning a championship if those
aging players stay healthy. If the Rockets don't get Pippen or
McDyess, Barkley might bolt to Seattle. He was in Las Vegas on
Saturday for the Mike Tyson fight with SuperSonics Gary Payton and
Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Some other free agents who will probably receive healthy new
contracts include centers Isaac Austin, Vlade Divac and Matt Geiger
and point guard Rod Strickland. The bet is Austin will wind up in
Orlando or Chicago. Charlotte's reported deal with Miami free agent
Derrick Coleman could mean Divac will end up in Sacramento. Geiger
will probably sign for far more than he's worth with Philadelphia.
Strickland is likely to remain in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   What about the players the Suns don't re-sign from last year's
team?
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Kevin Johnson is considering Seattle and the Los
Angeles Lakers. John ``Hot Rod'' Williams is being lured by Houston
but that could be part of the effort to get McDyess. The Rockets
were also showing interest in George McCloud until they started
moving toward Pippen instead of McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Robinson will probably end up back with the Suns if
McDyess goes to Denver, or he could be signed and traded. That
means Detroit will try to land center Chris Dudley, who played for
the Knicks last season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what about the Bulls, who are without Michael Jordan,
Pippen and Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have plenty of money, and they'll try to grab Miami
free agent Brent Barry. They'd love to get McDyess, but may turn to
Austin. The Bulls may also try to get involved in some
sign-and-trade deals. They'd like to find a way to get Orlando's
Anfernee ``Penny'' Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the toughest call for teams will be on forward Christian
Laettner, who played in Atlanta last season and blew out his knee
during the lockout. Some teams probably would have been reluctant
to go after Laettner because of his personality. Throw in a bad
knee, and it's not a desirable situation for the 6-foot-10 forward.
But Laettner is a talent.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Pistons apparently are ready to make him an offer,
bad knee and all. He played with Detroit's Grant Hill in college,
so why not?
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we're a long way from 200 players.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the free agents will stay with the teams they finished
with last season. Some, like Suns free agent George McCloud, will
wait to see what the big-name players do before sorting through
their options. The money won't be much of a factor.
</P>
<P>
   That will only leave two issues unresolved: Which coach will
wear Latrell Sprewell's fingerprints on his neck next? And what
will happen to Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, there are a handful of teams that want Sprewell,
including the well-grounded Indiana Pacers, who are coached by
Larry Bird. We want some big money on the coach in that one, by the
way. But the Knicks are his most likely destination.
</P>
<P>
   As for Rodman, put him in a WCW leotard and forget about him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
