<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-YOUNT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNT: BLUE-COLLAR HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm just a human being gifted with the ability to play
baseball. I'm nothing special. I'm just another person.'' _ Robin
Yount in 1993. &QL; 
PHOENIX - To hear those who know him best, there was never a day
Robin Yount played baseball for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yount's unselfishness paid off in a manner he could never have
imagined when he became one of just 34 players ever elected into
the Hall of Fame during his first year of eligibility. Considering
236 players have been admitted into Cooperstown's hallowed halls,
the accomplishment is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   To Yount, who was reared in Southern California but has lived in
Arizona since 1983, the feat is absolutely mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to grasp,'' Yount said last week at the
Leinenkugel's Ballyard Brewery adjacent to Bank One Ballpark, the
one he and brother Larry co-own with Diamondbacks managing general
partner Jerry Colangelo. ``It's like this is a fictitious story.
I'm having a lot of trouble accepting what has happened. It doesn't
feel real. This was never ever something I thought about.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount will formally be enshrined into baseball's Hall of Fame in
late July. His plaque will hang alongside those of Willie Mays,
Babe Ruth, Frank Robinson and all of the other great names the game
has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he will maintain the pursuits that have kept
him busy since his retirement _ co-owning an auto-racing team,
serving as a part-time instructor in the Brewers organization,
taking part in a business venture or two and staying involved in
the lives of his four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 20 years in the big leagues, and it's almost like now
I'm asking myself, `What do I do now?' '' said Yount, who resides
in Paradise Valley. ``Of course, there's never any shortage of
things to do. Once I'm up in the morning, I don't stop doing things
all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the players in the Hall, Yount managed to
distance himself from the spotlight throughout most of his 20-year
major league career.
</P>
<P>
   That he spent each of those seasons with the Milwaukee Brewers
easily is the biggest reason Yount was never considered a major
superstar during his career. But talk to those he played with and
against, and they attest to the true greatness that made Robin
Yount a rare first-ballot Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he played and handled himself, it was not even a
question that he's a Hall of Famer,'' said longtime Brewers
teammate Jim Gantner. ``Robin never got the publicity he should
have because he played in Milwaukee. If he had played in New York,
Chicago or Los Angles, you would have seen him make 10 All-Star
teams instead of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even through all that, I never heard him complain. Not once
did he mention he should have made this team or that team. And
there were plenty of years where he should have been an All-Star
and didn't get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Like those in the city he played in, Yount was all about being a
blue-collar kind of player and a man of simple tastes. He shunned
the press. In turn, though, the press never shunned him, twice
naming him the American League's Most Valuable Player. More
astonishing was the fact Yount was an MVP at two different
positions, shortstop and center field.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to other great players who come across as aloof or shy,
Yount always expressed himself best when on the playing field. An
excellent athlete, Yount made the climb to the major leagues after
just 64 games in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   At age 18, he broke in as the Brewers' everyday shortstop in
1974, a time when a kid athlete making the jump to the highest
level was almost unheard of. Now, of course, there are players such
as Kobe Bryant and Eric Lindros breaking in within months of their
high school graduation. That was not the case back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he choked up on the bat and stood up on the
plate,'' Nolan Ryan, who along with George Brett also will be
enshrined in Cooperstown this summer, told reporters last week. `I
can remember after his first at-bat thinking to myself, `That kid
hung in there. He wasn't intimidated.' That's what I found
throughout his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Yount surpassed the magical number of 3,000 hits, a figure that
basically guarantees election into the Hall of Fame. (Pete Rose,
who is banned from baseball, is the only eligible player with at
least 3,000 hits not in the Hall of Fame.)
</P>
<P>
   These days Yount basks in the fruits his career in the majors
brought and has his hands elbow-deep in his more deep-rooted
passion, auto racing.
</P>
<P>
   Yount and partners Bill Fickling and Dave Goadby own the P1
Racing Team. They have two cars on the Toyota Atlantic Racing
Series, which usually runs races just before big-time Indy-type
races in several cities.
</P>
<P>
   Yount is so involved in the venture that he spent all of last
summer attending each of the events. It's a rather expensive hobby,
but one Yount has been following since before he became a
big-league player. He spends his winters trying to attract sponsors
for the team's two cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything with an engine, I love,'' Yount said. ``I started
racing dirt bikes competitively when I was 13 and have been hooked
ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Yount spends time honing his 5 handicap in golf and
watching his four children grow up. Yount and his wife, Michele,
have been married for 25 years. One daughter, Melisa, is in
college; another, Amy, is a senior at Chaparral High, where son
Dustin is a sophomore. Another daughter, Jenna, is 10.
</P>
<P>
   Yount has spent time in the past helping the Chaparral High
baseball team, for which Dustin plays.
</P>
<P>
   On this occasion, Yount was helping publicize the fact
Leinenkugel's has begun selling its beer to other restaurants and
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he and his brother own 49 percent of the ballpark
brewery, Yount admitted he doesn't keep up with much on the
business side of the operation. The Younts came to own their shares
through a partnership when they amicably sold the land it and some
of the ballpark sits on.
</P>
<P>
   Yount remains involved in baseball and is a part-time instructor
in the Brewers organization, although mostly as a goodwill
ambassador for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   He basically has an open invitation to join the organization in
any capacity he wants. If Yount wanted to manage the Brewers
tomorrow, the club's front office would make it possible.
</P>
<P>
   For now though, Yount sees far too many problems in the game to
want to return to Milwaukee, the only place he says he would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready for that commitment just yet,'' said Yount, who
will play in the AT&AMP;T Pro-Am golf tournament next month. ``I don't
want to do it, just to do it. Plus, I don't like where baseball is
at right now, the imbalance the game has in place. There's only a
handful of competitive clubs right now, and that's not right. The
small-market teams are at a huge disadvantage. It's the biggest
problem baseball faces now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look back at last season, and by all accounts it was a
wonderful season. But all of it was centered around individual
achievements. There really were no pennant races. Take away the
things Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, Kerry Wood and David Wells did,
and what are you left with? I never remember going to spring
training thinking we didn't have some kind of chance. There are too
many teams now that will go to spring training with no chance. The
game needs to be fixed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
