<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUTGERS-STJOHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED STORM'S BACKCOURT LEADS WAY AT THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
   ( nk ) 
 By   CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Facing an aggressive Rutgers team Saturday night, St.
John's got crucial performances from its poised backcourt and from
its enthusiastic sixth man.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm's starting backcourt of Bootsy Thornton (19
points) and Erick Barkley (15 points) made critical plays that kept
St. John's in front when Rutgers kept threatening in the second
half. And the sixth man, forward Lavor Postell, a junior, had a
season-high 21 points to go along with a key block and a key steal
in the final four minutes. The result was an 88-78 St. John's
victory before 10,689 people at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The victory extended the Red Storm's winning streak to three
games, all at the Garden, as St. John's improved to 15-3 overall
and 6-1 in the Big East. The 15-3 start, in coach Mike Jarvis's
first season at St. John's, is the school's best since a 15-3 start
in 1990-91. St. John's has won all 12 home games this year and 14
consecutive home games dating back to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers, losing for the second time this season to St. John's,
fell to 10-6 over all and 3-4 in the Big East. But the outcome was
in doubt until the final minutes. St. John's led, 75-71, with four
minutes to play. Dahntay Jones of Rutgers was fouled on a drive,
but he missed both free throws. On the next possession, Thornton
was fouled on a drive, and he made one of two foul shots to give
the Red Storm a 76-71 lead with 3 minutes 49 seconds left. After a
time out, Geoff Billet of Rutgers was called for traveling, then
Thornton made a crucial 3-pointer from the top of the key to put
St. John's ahead, 79-71 with 2:42 left. Rutgers never seriously
threatened thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it looked as if St. John's might take control earlier
in the game, Rutgers responded with a key basket, often by forward
Jeff Greer, a sophomore, who led all scorers with 23 points. And
with both teams playing an up-tempo style, baskets came in bunches.
The shot clock was hardly necessary for this game, because neither
team needed encouragement to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, the fast-paced game seemed to wear down Rutgers.
Barkley and Thornton picked up the backcourt pressure for St.
John's as the game wore on. Rutgers began to hurry its shots, and
the Red Storm forced several turnovers that led to easy baskets.
St. John's scored 22 points in the game off of 21 Rutgers
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With Barkley doing a solid job running the offense, St. John's
continued to get high-percentage shots, and St. John's had a major
advantage on the backboards, outrebounding Rutgers, 34-22. Ron
Artest had a solid all-round game for St. John's with 12 points, 12
rebounds and 6 assists, while Barkley added a game-high 7 assists.
</P>
<P>
   A well-played first half ended with St. John's leading, 42-37.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams entered the game missing key players. St. John's was
without Tyrone Grant (sprained right wrist), a 6-foot-7-inch senior
center who is one of the team's leaders. And Rutgers was without
Rashod Kent (hip pointer), its second-leading rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   However, both offenses looked in sync during a fast-paced first
20 minutes that was close throughout. Thornton had a strong first
half (11 points), and an 8-0 run just before intermission gave the
Red Storm its halftime edge.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range shooting has been a key for St. John's this season,
and it was again Saturday night. With Rutgers leading, 35-34,
Artest made a 17-foot jumper, then followed with a 3-pointer from
the deep right corner, followed by Barkley's 3-pointer from the top
of the key.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm was 6 for 12 from 3-point range during the first
half, and both Artest and Barkley are shooting better than 40
percent from behind the arc this year. But Rutgers also played the
first half with confidence. Greer led Rutgers with 10 first-half
points, and the Scarlet Knights had a balanced attack and moved the
ball crisply against St. John's man-to-man defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers had reason to feel good about its chances. In the
Scarlet Knights' first meeting this season with St. John's, on Jan.
2, they jumped to an early 14-point lead before Artest's 25-point
effort led St. John's to a comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the second half started Saturday night, the
Scarlet Knights were the team hoping they could put together a
comeback. And they played well enough in the first half to let St.
John's know that they were not simply going to lie down on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's next game is Wednesday at Providence, while Rutgers
will play host to Syracuse on Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
