<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UDALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPIRIT ALIVE IN THE LAND': UDALL PRAISED IN EULOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Morris Udall still walks among us, urging us to
follow him up the mountain, the former congressman's eulogists said
Saturday in a memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``His spirit is still alive in the land,'' said Stewart Udall, a
former Interior secretary and brother of the beloved Arizona
Democrat, known so well across America for his wit, his wisdom and
his wonderment at nature.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Udall died Dec. 12 in a Washington, D.C., hospital where
he had spent most of the past seven years. Udall, 76, suffered from
Parkinson's disease, which ended his three decades in Congress in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Udall was memorialized repeatedly on Saturday as a giant who not
only overcame adversity but pursued excellence in everything he
did.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what he often described as his 18th-century upbringing
in the isolated farming community of St. John's and the loss of his
right eye at age 7, Udall went on to become a professional
basketball player, an accomplished lawyer and prosecutor, and one
of the most prolific and popular politicians of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   One of his seven children, Anne Udall, asked the more than 1,500
people gathered at the University of Arizona's Centennial Hall to
build on her father's ideals of social and environmental justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For each of us not to take the best of Dad . . . would be to
squander the legacy of Morris Udall.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his advocacy for the environment, Udall was
remembered as a pioneer for civil rights, for campaign finance and
civil service reforms, and for his early opposition to the war in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   One of his sons, Rep. Mark Udall, D-Colo., recalled a speech
against the war the congressman delivered in the same auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``America isn't perfect,'' Mark Udall quoted his father, ``but
we're not done yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., took a break from President Clinton's
impeachment trial to be at the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the most overlooked of Morris Udall's
accomplishments was his advocacy for American Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
