<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-SPORTS-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT UPSETS NCAA SPRINT CHAMP
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Jarrett described himself as ``one of those
athletes who would have been, should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Jarrett, a 25-year-old sprinter at New York
Tech, got a wide-eyed look at what he still could be. He defeated
the National Collegiate Athletic Association 55-meter champion
Ja'Warren Hooker of the University of Washington in the 60-meter
dash, providing a stunning upset in the New York Sports Museum
Track and Field Invitational at the 169th Street Armory in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett later won the 200 meters on the Armory's new rubber
track in a sizzling 21.22 seconds, qualifying him for the NCAA
indoor championships in March.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett did not know who Hooker was until he heard his name and
his accomplishments over the public address system before their
semifinal heat: NCAA champion at 55 meters, third-place finisher in
the 100 meters. When Jarrett sped by an eased-up Hooker in the
heat, the feeling was that Hooker was merely playing possum.
</P>
<P>
   But the final unfolded the same way. Jarrett, a sinewy 6-foot-2,
burst from the blocks slightly ahead of the shorter Hooker and
never ceded ground. Jarrett finished in 6.73 seconds, making him a
provisional NCAA qualifier at that distance. Hooker's time was
6.77.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to cop out and say this is why I lost the
race,'' Hooker said of his lower left leg, which was heavily taped
to protect a shin splint. ``I ran well for 59 meters. He ran good
today. He beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   The question was who beat him? A laughing Jarrett acknowledged
that the query was a reasonable one. He won the state 100 and 200
meter titles in 1990 and 1991 while at Farmingdale High School on
Long Island, then ran with modest success at St. John's before
dropping out because of academic difficulties. He spent a year and
a half out of college before resurfacing at New York Tech, a
Division II school in Old Westbury. He was the Division II
100-meter champion last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the biggest accomplishment for me,'' said
Jarrett, who ran the second leg on Jamaica's fourth-place 400-meter
relay team at the Goodwill Games last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The other NCAA champions won as expected Saturday night. Carmen
Douma of Villanova, who won the indoor mile last year, captured the
mile in 4 minutes 51.65 seconds. Angie Brown of George Mason won
the long jump (19 feet 11{ inches), and Dominique Calloway, an
All-American from Ohio State, edged teammate Donika Merriman in the
60-meter hurdles (8.34).
</P>
</TEXT>
