</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANTHERS SCORE FIRST AND ISLES, OF COURSE, FOLD THEIR TENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ Frustration. That has become the Islanders'
byword, and Saturday night they received yet another dose of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Panthers, no juggernaut themselves, scored early and
made the lone goal hold up for a 1-0 victory before 19,097 at
National Car Rental Arena. And not long after the Panthers scored,
the Islanders' best player, defenseman Kenny Jonsson, was helped
from the ice after spraining his right knee. Jonsson, who will be
re-examined Sunday, could miss up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The loss took the Islanders' streak without a victory to 10
games (0-9-1) and left them at 29 points, the second-lowest total
in the Eastern Conference. They lost all five games on their
current road trip, the last three by one goal each.
</P>
<P>
   They are now 0-24-1 when the opponent scores first.
</P>
<P>
   It was no consolation that the Islanders outshot their hosts,
27-19. The game ended with center Bryan Smolinski taking a
desperation 65-foot shot, which goalie Sean Burke stopped easily as
time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' star winger, Zigmund Palffy, was held without a
goal for his sixth straight game.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Islanders 4 minutes 47 seconds to launch their first
shot. They would get six more by the end of the first period, but
none took any special effort for Burke to turn away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Felix Potvin, starting his third straight game in
goal for the Islanders, was victimized by a deflection during a
Florida power play 12:23 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers center Rob Niedermayer shot from the left point, and
the puck bounded from Potvin's stick to where the veteran right
wing Dino Ciccarelli was looming. Ciccarelli jabbed a 5-footer into
the net's left corner as Potvin's momentum was carrying him away
from the shot.
</P>
<P>
   The goal gave Ciccarelli his 1,200th career point, making him
the 28th player in National Hockey League history to reach that
plateau.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was another exercise in futility, though this
time for both teams. The Islanders won the shot battle, 10-8, but
couldn't crack Burke, who came in with a respectable 2.57
goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors swarmed the net early in the period, but were
unable to finish the job once center Robert Reichel bumped into
Burke in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Near the midway point of the period, with the Islanders playing
short-handed, Palffy almost slipped a slap shot past Burke from the
left side. Almost.
</P>
<P>
   The liveliest action of the period came after the Panthers'
bullying defenseman Ed Jovanovski went headhunting with his
forearms, knocking Smolinski to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of shoving and shouts between the teams ensued, as the
crowd stoked the emotions with their yells.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Jovanovski was tagged with a two-minute roughing
penalty, but the Islanders managed two harmless shots on the
following power play.
</P>
<P>
   New York entered the game eighth over all in the league in power
play effectiveness, but that is deceiving because the Islanders
have been great on the power play at home and woeful on the road.
That form held up.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders came out with particular fire in the final period,
producing the first four shots and 9 of the first 10.
</P>
<P>
   Florida withstood that heat, and eventually the Islanders flamed
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
