<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL STILL HAS RANGERS' NUMBER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Midway through the third period Saturday night, Wayne
Gretzky picked up a loose puck behind the Montreal Canadiens' goal
without a defender near him. As he looked left and right for an
opening, the sold-out crowd at the Molson Center was anticipating
something special.
</P>
<P>
   But the opening never came for Gretzky, and when he finally
unloaded the puck to Jeff Beukeboom, it presented little threat. It
was about as dangerous as the Rangers appeared all night. By the
time this chance passed, the chants of Rangers fans in the upper
decks had changed from, ``Let's go Rangers'' to ``Jets, Jets,
Jets.'' The fans would save their breath for another day.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (17-19-7) succumbed to the Canadiens with little
fight, 3-0. The loss was the Rangers' second in two nights,
dropping them into a tie with the Canadiens, 4 points behind the
Boston Bruins and Pittsburgh Penguins for the final playoff berth
in the Eastern Conference. For the Canadiens (17-20-7), the victory
was their third in three tries against the Rangers this season.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was particularly disheartening after the Rangers fell,
3-1, on Friday night to a Chicago Blackhawks team that had not won
in its seven previous games. If that was supposed to wake the
Rangers up, they slept in, falling behind early and never posing a
threat. In the third period, trailing by 2-0 until an empty-net
goal by Vincent Damphousse in the final seconds, the Rangers had
just three shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it was Jocelyn Thibault who stymied them. Saturday,
it was Jeff Hackett, who recorded a shutout on Friday night in
Washington, his first since joining the Canadiens on Nov. 16, and
followed it with another by stopping 17 Rangers shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had surrendered goals on the first shot three times
in their last four games. This time they were able to avert that
problem as Dan Cloutier (29 saves) withstood four shots in the
opening two minutes. Still, the Rangers found themselves playing
from behind when the Canadiens made quick work of their first
power-play opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Chris Tamer was sent off for cross-checking at 7
minutes 31 seconds of the first period. On the ensuing faceoff,
Saku Koivu beat Petr Nedved to the puck, sending it to Brian
Savage, who fed Vladimir Malakhov at the point. Malakhov fired a
shot from just inside the blue line, beating Cloutier to his glove
side, three seconds into the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had their chances in the period, but just as they
had in the final minutes of Friday night's loss to the Blackhawks,
they could not take advantage. On Friday, Gretzky had had a pair of
point-blank chances, but could not convert. Saturday, Manny
Malhotra, Mike Knuble and Scott Fraser had shots from close range
that Hackett stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Rangers not score on their only power play in
the period, but they also nearly gave away a goal when Nedved
chased down the puck behind the Rangers' net. But he tossed his
stick, which was broken, along the boards and left the puck, which
was picked up by the Canadiens, feeding Patrick Poulin alone just
outside the crease. Cloutier came up with a glove save, and the
Rangers went to the locker room trailing by just one goal at the
first intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
