<SLUG> BC-KING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACY LIVES ON IN KING'S SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB PETRIE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy being a King.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin Luther King III says he's doing the best he can to
carry on his father's name and legacy of making America freer of
poverty, racism and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never focused on trying to be my father. I know I can't be
that,'' King said Saturday during an interview at Tempe's first
official Martin Luther King Jr. holiday celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what I can do is work toward my own dream, to make sure
his dream is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference,
King works to fight a more subtle form of racism, far from the days
of Jim Crow and the basic civil rights his father fought for in
freedom marches across the South decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, King says, the SCLC, co-founded in 1957 by his father,
works with corporations accused of not fairly treating minority
customers or workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is to create opportunities for everyone that may
be excluded from participating in the vast wealth we have to
offer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   King also makes about 100 appearances a year, including the
Tempe stop. He spoke to a crowd of about 1,200 people, warmed up by
a rousing gospel music performance by the River of Life Church in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the keynote speaker at a dinner Saturday evening to
celebrate Tempe's diversity, which attracted a sellout crowd of
300.
</P>
<P>
   King began his day with a museum tour of a traveling display of
black and white prints taken during the height of the civil rights
struggle in the 1950s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   They were highlighted by stark photos of his father's April 1968
murder, the blood on the hotel balcony, and the riots in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   King was paid $12,000 for his Tempe appearance, which city
officials said came from corporate sponsors, not taxpayers.
Sponsors included ``The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was well into the festive atmosphere, which also
included dance performances, food booths, and arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful celebration and it's a celebration that
exemplifies what Dr. King stood for,'' said LaVerne DaCosta of
Mesa, an ASU student. ``I'm glad to see Tempe taking a step and
being part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempe resident Tanya Moulton called the elder King a
compassionate man who was ahead of his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he were still alive today,'' she said, ``to help guide
the youth today.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger King was 10 when his father was shot and killed
outside Room 306 of the Lorraine Motel, while working on behalf of
striking sanitation workers in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of America, he learned of the shooting on TV, and
remembered the immediate sorrow ``of losing a father and not
knowing what was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were prepared as much as we could be for children (for his
father's death),'' King said. ``We were at a certain point where we
knew what our father was doing was dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   King said he marvels at what his father did to break down the
seemingly impenetrable walls of hard-core racism, when it wasn't
the popular thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was criticized for what he did,'' he said. ``Most
people say they love him now, but during his lifetime they
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   How Dr. King did it was so simple, yet so complex, given the
sentiment of the times, his son explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the law of the land, the Constitution, the Declaration
of Independence, and applied it to all people,'' King said. ``He
took the English language and used it in a positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who worked with Phoenix civil rights activists in 1992 on
successful passage of an official state King holiday, says Arizona
seems to have come a long way to recognize and celebrate diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always going to be individuals who are not going to
embrace the holiday,'' he said. ``But this means there'll be much
more work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. Day is Monday. &QL; 
Bob Petrie can be reached at 444-7941 or at bob.petrie(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
