<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARREST-RAPPER-JONES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPPER'S COUSIN TO TESTIFY AGAINST HIM, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Va.)  (Eds: UPDATES grafs 3 and 4 with Jones pleading not guilty at
arraignment, bail set.) 
 (DW) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A cousin riding with a well-known rapper in the
Wu-Tang Clan has agreed to become a witness in connection with a
shooting involving the performer and police officers, law
enforcement officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper, Russell Jones, who alternately goes by the stage
names Ol' Dirty Bastard and Big Baby Jesus, was arrested in
Brooklyn about 8 p.m. Friday, shortly after the police said he
fired at officers in who had chased a car Jones was driving.
</P>
<P>
   Jones pleaded not guilty Saturday night to charges of attempted
murder of a police officer, aggravated assault and possession of a
weapon, according to Patrick B. Clark, a spokesman for the Brooklyn
District Attorney's Office. Judge Jo Ann Ferdinand set bail at
$150,000 and ordered Jones to appear in court again on Jan. 21. He
could face life in prison if convicted on the most serious charge.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the shootout took place after officers in an
unmarked police car saw Jones, 29, driving his 1999 Chevrolet Tahoe
erratically, with his headlights off, after he left the United
Kingdom Studios in Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant section.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to stop him but when the plainclothes officers neared
the car and identified themselves, Jones fired two shots at the
officers, who returned his fire, Detective Joseph Pentangelo, a
Police Department spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle sped off, then stopped several blocks away, and
Jones's cousin, Frederick Cuffie, the only other person in the
vehicle, jumped from the car and ran, police said. Jones was
arrested as he got out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Cuffie, 37, was arrested about 11 p.m. after officers found him
in a nearby building. No weapon was recovered, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cuffie had also faced attempted-murder charges, those
charges were dropped when he became a witness for the prosecution,
according to a law enforcement official speaking on the condition
of anonymity. ``He has stated that Jones knew these were police
officers and that they wanted him to stop,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's confrontation was the latest incident involving
Jones, who has survived two shootings. In September, he was
arrested and accused of threatening to kill his ex-girlfriend in
Los Angeles, and in November he was arrested after the police said
he threatened security guards at a blues club there, according to
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stormed the stage of the Grammy Awards at Radio City Music
Hall last year, seizing a microphone to complain about losing in
the best rap-album category.
</P>
</TEXT>
