<HEADER>
A6532 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX     01-16 1961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS' REEVES HAS HEART OF A CHAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
SUWANEE, Ga. _ When Dan Reeves was hired two years ago by the
Atlanta Falcons, some suspected the spirit of the NFL's winningest
active coach might not be equal to the challenge. Rebuilding the
turmoil-scarred Falcons was a job for a younger man, they thought.
They worried that Reeves was a discouraged and burned-out veteran
returning to his home state with an eye on retirement.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Obviously, they didn't know him well enough.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves not only is putting his heart into his work, he has
resurrected the Falcons from the scrap heap to the brink of the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Although still somewhat feeble from his quadruple-bypass surgery
only five weeks ago, Reeves, who will be 55 on Tuesday, will be a
commanding presence when he walks the sideline in today's NFC
Championship Game at Minnesota. He had the attention of his players
before. He has their admiration now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to risk having a heart attack for us,'' Atlanta
defensive end Chuck Smith said. ``Compared to that, playing
football is easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves demands from his players preparation, dedication,
truthfulness and strict adherence to football fundamentals. He
expects no less from himself. Those values plus a series of
fortuitous roster moves explain the Falcons' quick turnaround, team
members say.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds familiar, perhaps it should.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Dan Reeves is Dan Reeves is because of Tom
Landry,'' said Dr. Charles Harrison, the team's physician for the
past 32 years. ``He's a Tom Landry clone.''
</P>
<P>
   In Reeves' eyes, that is the ultimate compliment. For the love
of the game Former Cowboys head coach Tom Landry took a chance on
Reeves first as a player and later as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves set 10 school records as a South Carolina quarterback,
but wasn't among the 400 players drafted by the NFL. Scouts
considered him too small and slow. The Cowboys signed him in 1965
as a free agent, and as usual, he did what it took to play and
succeed. He still hates the word ``overachiever,'' perhaps because
the term so frequently has been used to describe him.
</P>
<P>
   He became a running back, and in his second season his 16
touchdowns set a team record that stood until Emmitt Smith broke it
in 1992. The next year, he accounted for Dallas' only offensive
touchdown in the legendary ``Ice Bowl'' game in Green Bay, throwing
a 50-yard halfback pass to Lance Rentzel.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves blew out his knee in 1968, lost his starting job the next
year to Calvin Hill, and began to think about life after football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my career was coming to an end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Landry didn't cut or trade Reeves. Instead, he offered
him a promotion of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured Dan would make a good coach,'' Landry said this
week. ``He was a fierce competitor, and he had a great knowledge of
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, between the '69 and '70 seasons, Landry asked Reeves to
become a player-coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never even thought about coaching,'' Reeves recalls. ``But
I thought, gosh, this would be a good way I could still play. I
hadn't heard about teams cutting any coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Reeves enjoyed his dual role with the Cowboys.
However, his enthusiasm waned in 1971 when he supervised running
backs and had to deal with the uncooperative Duane Thomas, whose
talent was exceeded only by his sour personality. The silent
treatment Thomas gave the media extended to teammates and coaches,
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   After a frustrating 1972 season _ an injury to Roger Staubach
forced Reeves into the role of backup QB behind Craig Morton _ he
walked away from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   For a year, he worked in Dallas real estate and developed
townhouses. He liked being at home with his family instead of
spending six weeks each summer at training camp in Thousand Oaks,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I felt like a duck out of water,'' he said. ``Somebody
wanted to talk to me about real estate, I had no answers. Somebody
talked to me about football, at least I felt comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I really realized how much \Rfootball\S meant to
me. I figured I wouldn't have to deal with as many problems. But I
learned that everywhere you go, you've got problems to handle.
Building a hundred townhouses, I had a hundred Duane Thomases to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry took Reeves back in 1974 as special teams coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I knew what my focus was, that I wanted to coach,''
Reeves said. ``So I really paid more attention to details and tried
to learn everything I could, how to be a good assistant but also
trying to see how you did things as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I couldn't have learned from anybody any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his dozen years as head coach at Denver, Reeves took
the Broncos to three Super Bowls. He lost each time, but previously
earned Super Bowl rings with Landry's Dallas Cowboys as a player in
January 1972, and as an assistant coach and offensive coordinator
in January 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had the chance to move on to Denver \Rin 1980\S, I
knew he would be successful,'' Landry says. ``He knew the job that
had to be done and he always did it well, probably better than any
coach I ever had.'' Up from the ground This season began as the
most fulfilling of Reeves' coaching lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, he came to Atlanta as damaged goods. His successful
tenure with the Broncos ended after an 8-8 season in 1992 when he
and John Elway couldn't agree on offensive philosophy. He became
the NFL's Coach of the Year _ an award he also won this year _ in
1993 with the New York Giants, then was replaced after losing teams
in 1995 and 1996 when he disagreed with owner Wellington Mara and
then-general manager George Young over authority in personnel
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The late Falcons owner Rankin Smith Sr. passed a chance to hire
Reeves in 1977 in favor of Leeman Bennett. Two decades later, he
didn't let Reeves get away again.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, a native of Americus, Ga., came home in 1997 and was
given the keys to the team. He was named head coach and executive
vice president of football operations. With full authority, Reeves
wasted no time shaking the tree.
</P>
<P>
   He scrapped previous coach June Jones' outdated run-and-shoot
offense. He signed 22 free agents in his first two years, six that
are now starters; in the three years prior to his arrival, the
Falcons signed four. He drafted four more starters, and traded for
journeyman quarterback Chris Chandler and receiver Tony Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get enough credit for his administrative
abilities,'' said current Dallas head coach Chan Gailey, who served
under Reeves in Denver, grew up in Americus and once was coached by
Reeves in Little League baseball. ``Dan makes good decisions from
top to bottom in an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves made changes upon changes, but made them the right way
and for the right reasons, say his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood what he had to do, but he didn't come in here
and start hammering on people,'' said defensive end Smith. ``We had
some players who could contribute, and he saw that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves also instilled a new code of discipline, and went to work
mending bad attitudes that had festered through 26 losing seasons
in 31 years of the Falcons' existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a perfect marriage,'' agreed wide receiver Terance
Mathis. Surviving a scare Of course, it looked like the old days
when the Falcons lost seven of their first eight games under Reeves
last season.
</P>
<P>
   But since that point, Atlanta has won 21 of 25 games, tied with
Denver for best in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was on top of the world last month as the Falcons
approached their second-ever NFC West title. For a coach who was
burned out, his team suddenly was burning up the league. Jamal
Anderson ranked second in the NFL in rushing behind only Denver's
Terrell Davis. Chandler, who had been played for five other teams,
ranked fourth in the league in pass rating.
</P>
<P>
   And Reeves felt lousy. There was this nagging matter of a
burning sensation in his chest and the back of his throat, which
worsened under game-day stress.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't tell anyone. He had undergone angioplasty procedures
in August 1990 and January 1991 to clear arteries, and bounced back
in three or four days each time. After the season, he reasoned,
he'd go in and have another one done.
</P>
<P>
   The burning in his chest became worse, though, after the
Falcons' 27-17 victory on Dec. 13 against New Orleans in the
Superdome. On the plane home, he confided in Dr. Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 the next morning, Reeves was on his back at Piedmont
Hospital in Atlanta, where dye tests showed serious blockages in
his heart arteries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day and this could have been fatal,'' Harrison said.
``He was that close.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and a second doctor advised Reeves and his wife, Pam,
that immediate quadruple bypass surgery was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote was three to one in favor,'' Harrison said. ``I don't
have to tell you who the one was.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves underwent a four-hour operation in which veins from the
inside of his legs and from behind his chest muscles were used to
bypass the blockages. When he awakened and the breathing tube was
removed, his first words were to inquire about the severity of the
knee injury his fullback, Bob Christian, suffered the day before.
Christian's injury was season-ending, but Reeves wasn't told. True
grit Reeves returned to the hospital with an irregular heartbeat
shortly after the surgery, but by last week's NFC semifinal against
the San Francisco 49ers, he was roaming the sideline again. His
manner was deliberate, and his quick comeback seemed risky, but
keeping him down might have been even more stressful.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is the same man who continued to play football
despite five knee surgeries in his 20s, and who cried when his
Americus high school coach wouldn't let him play with a pin in his
broken collarbone. The coach ultimately relented, and Reeves bent
the pin.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate stress test, he had admitted before the 49ers game,
would be a blown official's call.
</P>
<P>
   He got a doozy, when an apparent Atlanta fumble return for a
touchdown was negated, and the ball was given back to San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happened, he was the first person I thought about,''
Mathis said. ``I sat there on the bench watching him the whole
time. He was moving back and forth, and his blood was really
boiling, and right behind him the doctor was moving back and forth
with him. Everybody was watching them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he got through that,'' said Dr. Harrison, ``then he's
passed the test.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons prepared last week for today's test against the
Vikings, Reeves spoke to Landry and Gailey by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling Coach Landry about how similar the things I'm
doing here are to the things he used to do,'' Reeves said after
Wednesday's practice. ``Naturally, I've changed some of those
things that if you'd been in charge you'd like to have tried. But
there were very few of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this season has been a totally different
experience. It was the most rewarding season I'd ever gone through,
and then all of a sudden I'm an outsider looking in. When you watch
your team battling for a division championship from an ICU unit,
that doesn't happen many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' voice cracked with emotion, but only for an instant. He
quickly was back in charge and headed toward the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Burnout? A kinder, gentler Reeves? Don't tell his players that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see him on the sideline when things go wrong?'' Anderson
said. ``Heart or no heart, I don't care. He's a great guy, but you
don't relax. Remember, he's the guy \Rwho\S cut Phil Simms.''
(Randy Moss writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
