<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-VINNY-TEX     01-16 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-VINNY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE FINALLY LIVING UP TO EARLY HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ It has taken 12 years, six head coaches, and
four cities that groaned with each of his gut-wrenching
interceptions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet Vinny Testaverde, who joined the NFL in 1987 with a Heisman
Trophy in tow, is finally living up to the expectations afforded a
former No. 1 draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has shaken off his reputation as a mistake-prone
quarterback to lead the New York Jets (13-4) to their biggest game
in 30 years. Whether or not Vinny and the Jets upset the defending
Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos (15-2) in today's AFC
Championship Game, the 35-year-old native New Yorker considers this
his ``dream season.'' It is a season in which he has rehabilitated
his career under the leadership of head coach Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me a lot of my father in that he's very
demanding,'' Testaverde said. ``I'd only seen coach Parcells from
TV and seeing what he says in the paper. You always see him on game
day with that mean looking face of his and never smiling much. I'll
tell you what, I knew that after meeting with him the first time
that I wanted to play for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Parcells: ``What Vinny has given us is just too much to
have hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells didn't expect much from Testaverde. After all,
Testaverde had a .367 career winning percentage (48-83-1) in 11
previous seasons. The only thing worse was his ghastly
touchdown-to-interception ratio (175-183). Thus, when Parcells
signed Testaverde last June following his release from the
Baltimore Ravens, it was to back up promising 27-year-old Glenn
Foley, whose career record was 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hoped to get a guy that maybe we could use as a
quarterback if we needed to,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Foley has become a footnote in the Jets' remarkable
season. Testaverde started _ and won _ the third and fourth games
as Foley sat with a rib injury. Testaverde was named the starter
for good in Week 7 after Foley's 5-for-15 performance in a 30-10
loss the previous week against the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly able to pass to Pro Bowl wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson
or hand off to 1,000-yard running back Curtis Martin, Testaverde
began playing like everyone thought he would when he came out of
the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He posted a 12-1 record as a starter and led the Jets to their
first division title since the AFL-NFL merger in 1970. He was named
to his second Pro Bowl. He completed 61.5 percent of his passes for
3,256 yards with a club-record 29 touchdowns and only seven
interceptions. His passer rating of 101.6 was second in the league
behind Minnesota's Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is such a different quarterback from when he was in Tampa
Bay and I was in Detroit,'' Broncos cornerback Ray Crockett said.
``He's playing in a controlled system where he doesn't have to go
out and make a great play all the time. He doesn't have to be Brett
Favre. He can just walk the ball up the field and let the other
guys work for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde did not have that luxury in Tampa Bay. The Buccaneers
had no offensive Pro Bowlers and only one 1,000-yard rusher in
Testaverde's six seasons there. Often, he was asked to win games by
himself. He rarely succeeded. He threw 35 interceptions in 1988,
the second highest single-season total in league history.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers finally grew tired of Testaverde and did not
re-sign him following the 1992 season. He played three seasons in
Cleveland and two more in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   As the talent around Testaverde improved, so did his
performance. He had 77 touchdowns and 112 interceptions in Tampa
Bay. He had 98 touchdowns and 71 interceptions with the Browns and
Ravens. In 1994, Testaverde led the Browns to an 11-5 record and a
victory over the Parcells-led Patriots in an AFC wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells studied Testaverde on film, particularly his days in
Cleveland and Baltimore. He noticed Testaverde's problems came when
he tried to force the ball deep downfield, and when he tried to
scramble. When Parcells signed Testaverde last summer, he stressed
the importance of being smart with the ball, and the importance of
utilizing his tight ends and running backs.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde responded with the lowest interception total (seven)
of his career in seasons with at least six starts. Today,
Testaverde will take with him lessons learned from a career that
has hardened his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting off the year as a backup I certainly didn't expect
what has taken place to this point,'' Testaverde said. ``I think
you go through highs and lows as a player. But I've always had
confidence in my work habits and my preparation. I knew if I
continued to work hard, someday I'd have an opportunity. It
probably came sooner than I thought it would.
</P>
<P>
   But not too soon for the Jets. (Kevin Lyons writes for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
