<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-16 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COL-LEBRETON-TEX     01-16 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COL-LEBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO PARCELLS, JETS HAVE A CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DENVER _ By most expert accounts, the Tuna boat stops here.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here at the Denver Broncos' eternal Love-In. Here at the John
Elway Two-Minute Miraclefest and Farewell Party. Here at Mile High
Stadium, where the local papers have been filled all week with
quotes from the players, exhorting an always-ear-rattling crowd to
yell even louder.
</P>
<P>
   If you're measuring bad karma, in other words, the New York Jets
would already be trailing by two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Except the Jets hold the day's one trump card. He is their
ticket to Miami. He is their Shanahan, their Elway, their
crowd-muzzler, their entire raison d'etre on this threshold to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, alias the Big Tuna, is all that and two Super
Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   You can count up the open-heart surgeries, the asthma fields and
the West Coast Offenses, and Parcells would still be the one coach
whose presence makes the dream all seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, the Jets don't have the horses to get past
the home-field Broncos today. But they do have the Tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is trying to do something no head coach has ever done
before _ take three different organizations to the Super Bowl. Not
Tom Landry, nor Bill Walsh, nor Jimmy Johnson has ever done that.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the Jets' astounding turnaround from a
1-15 season just two years ago. But the New England Patriots were
2-14 and foundering, too, when the Tuna took them over. And the
first Giants team that Parcells coached, 1983, began its Super Bowl
drive with a 3-12-1 season.
</P>
<P>
   Some pro football teams search forever for that combination,
that one coach who can turn their Gatorade into wine and finally
align the franchise planets. Parcells has done it, packed it away,
and then done it again and again.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, a franchise that played literally and figuratively in
the shadow of the NFC Giants, made the fateful decision in 1997
that Parcells was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Bob Kraft's ego and Parcells' large footprint
made for an uncomfortable fit. But a vindictive Kraft charged the
Jets with tampering. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue had to resolve the
dispute and award the compensation.
</P>
<P>
   It included the Jets' No. 2 pick in 1998 and their No. 1 choice
in 1999, a veritable ransom considering that Kraft no longer wanted
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, however, is old news. Parcells jumped, and no one has
heard Jets owner Leon Hess complain since.
</P>
<P>
   No one has heard Hess, period, in fact, because it is the Big
Tuna who is captain of this ship. Parcells makes all the personnel
decisions _ the draft picks, the free agent signings, the daily
sift through the waiver wire.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in the league does it better.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells scoured the NFL dumpster and found linebacker Bryan
Cox, who had been abandoned as a ticking hot-air bomb. Parcells
also sent a lifeboat to greet fullback Keith Byars, safety Corwin
Brown and, in the most celebrated resurrection, quarterback Vinny
Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had been cut by the Baltimore Ravens. He once threw
35 interceptions in a single season. When you ask him now, Parcells
says he just had a feeling that Broadway Vinny ``would fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time you hear a coach or owner whine about how the salary
cap and free agency have eaten away at their franchise, remind them
how Parcells rebuilt the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first of all,'' Parcells told reporters two weeks ago,
``I didn't start with a $35-million cornerback.''
</P>
<P>
   He's talking about you, Owner Jones. But we digress.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Todd Burger left the Chicago Bears to the accompaniment of
shrugs from line coach Tony Wise. With the Jets, he is the starting
left guard. Likewise, Parcells needed a center, and so he signed
free agent Kevin Mawae from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells tells interviewers about something his old friend, Gene
`Stick' Michaels, the former general manager of the New York
Yankees, told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about getting a superstar here or there,'' Parcells
said. ``It's about putting your team together so that your needs
are met, not the public's needs and not the media's needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the signing of Testaverde has prompted the most epistles
in the Jets' turnaround season, the deal that defined Parcells was
the signing of running back Curtis Martin. He had been the legs
upon which Parcells and the Patriots ran to Super Bowl XXXI.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin was a restricted free agent, which meant he not only
cost the Jets a five-year, $26-million contract, but also their No.
1 and No. 3 picks in last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Mike Holmgren (as of last week) and maybe Jimmy
Johnson, there may not be another coach in the league who would
have the guts to go to his owner with that.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 38 of the 53 players on the Jets roster have been added
since Parcells inherited the team. Of the 22 starters on offense
and defense, 14 were brought in by Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1-15 to the conference championship game in two years _
teams aren't supposed to do that,'' Jets receiver Keyshawn Johnson
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a tribute to the guy who has put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the din of today's crowd, the ``guy'' is the one factor
that most teases us to think the New York Jets have a chance. He is
their builder. He is their meal ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Tuna, anyone? (Gil LeBreton is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
