<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES COLUMN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a tree falls in a forest with no one around, is the noise
loud?
</P>
<P>
   If an NBA team wins a championship without Michael Jordan
around, is the title valid?
</P>
<P>
   While the league's individual players begin the impossible task
of becoming the Air-Apparent, 28 rejuvenated teams will fight for
the scraps Jordan left behind. Not only his worldwide legion of
fans, but also the championship trophy he hogged for six of the
past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a quiet voice inside everyone saying, `Fine, now
there's a chance,' '' said Miami Heat coach Pat Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a championship, you get a championship _ whether it's
with him or without him,'' added Indiana Pacers point guard Mark
Jackson, whose team lost to Jordan's Bulls in Game 7 of the Eastern
Conference Finals last summer. ``Everybody's path becomes easier
without him. He's been a headache to a lot of teams for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   With its greatest player gone and its greatest fear realized,
the NBA will kneel in forgiveness to fans, duct-tape together a
shortened 50-game schedule and likely crown an asterisked champion
other than the Bulls for the first time since 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty games is more credible than, say, 35, but you could say
it's not a full-blown championship unless you play 82,'' said Utah
Jazz owner Larry Miller. ``But if we win it, I may feel
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan gone and the Bulls' decade-long dynasty soon to
crumble with the expected departure of Scottie Pippen, the road to
the '99 title is suddenly crowded with optimistic contenders.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, the Pacers are the favorite to reach the Finals.
They have all their key players signed and have been the only team
to consistently practice together during the lockout. In
Washington, coach Bernie Bickerstaff said his players looked so out
of shape that he's considering three-a-day practices. And in
Milwaukee, the Bucks had exactly zero players show up at their
training facility last week.
</P>
<P>
   Before the frenzied free-agent bonanza begins this week, the
Jazz and Lakers appear prepared to return to the Western Conference
Finals. Each team has 10 players under contract and no key free
agents other than L.A.'s Rick Fox. Houston, courting Pippen and
Antonio McDyess, could join the favorites. The Suns, meanwhile,
have only five players signed, and the Clippers will play at least
until mid-February without No. 1 overall pick Michael Olowokandi,
who is in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that the championship used to go through
Chicago,'' said Lakers guard Eddie Jones, whose team was swept 4-0
by the Jazz last May. ``But now, I think it's us.''
</P>
<P>
   Minus 32 games, teams will essentially start 16-16 when the
season starts Feb. 5, 6 or 7. History shows that shortened seasons
can produce more competitive games, and wacky results.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball lost 54 games in '81, and wound up with the team with
the best overall record (Cincinnati Reds) not making the postseason
because it took the division winners from a first and second half.
Football in '82 lost seven games and saw the Washington Redskins
win the Super Bowl despite missing the playoffs the previous five
seasons. Even the St. Louis Cardinals made those playoffs. Hockey
in '95 lost 30 games and saw the New Jersey Devils make and win
their only Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   This must be good news for the Mavericks, who have 10 players
under contract and haven't made the playoffs the past eight
seasons. If nothing else, the mini-season should keep the Mavericks
from finishing 30 games out of first place in the Midwest Division,
something they've done six times in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it starts, it's going to be ugly, real ugly,'' said
Orlando Magic guard Nick Anderson. ``Who knows what's going to
happen? Guys tried to stay in shape, but no one is used to being
away from basketball this long. And two weeks in training camp
isn't going to suddenly put people back in top shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Magic forward Horace Grant, ``You've heard of Abbott and
Costello? Well, that might be what it looks like at the start.''
</P>
<P>
   So not only may the season be hideous, the prize will be a
silver medal, since Jordan took the gold and went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys wanted me to come back so they could take the
title from me,'' Jordan said. ``But that's the cute thing about
retiring. They won't be able to say they beat me, even if they win
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess he had one last ``shot'' in him after all. IN THE PAINT
Offbeat Beat Is there any doubt Celtics guard Kenny Anderson became
the players' poster boy during the lockout? First, he whined about
struggling to pay the insurance on his nine cars. He made amends
for that blunder by giving away 500 free turkeys during
Thanksgiving. But last week in New York, minutes after the lockout
ended, he blew off a kid asking for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   At least Anderson deserves a chance to explain his actions:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a heckler on the left side of me,'' Anderson said.
``I think he was drunk and he was swearing me down. The kid, I
thought, was in the back because I wasn't looking at him. I was
telling the cameraman \Rfrom CNN\S that I had to find my car and
get out of there. That's what that was about. It made me seem rude
to the fan. It was just the wrong timing. There were a lot of
cameras. There were a lot of people pushing. I was cold. It was a
hectic environment. I'm not saying it was the right thing to do.
Maybe I made a mistake and I learned from it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the supposedly fan-friendlier NBA, Anderson attempted to be
repentant.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the incident, he went on New York television
inviting the young fan to contact the Celtics for free airfare to
Boston, two tickets to a game and as many autographs as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Celtics' office was flooded with at least
100 calls claiming to be ``the kid that Kenny dissed.'' Numbers
Game Jordan's golf handicap. Instead of hanging on too long like
Muhammad Ali (taking a beating from Larry Holmes) or Nolan Ryan
(not retiring a single batter in his last outing), look for Jordan
to appear on the Celebrity Tour Challenge in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   47: Times Jordan appeared on the cover of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   290: Estimates from teammates on Cavaliers All-Star forward
Shawn Kemp's weight. Kemp, who last season played between 260-265,
doesn't appear concerned about his extra baggage. ``My optimum
weight is 20 points and 10 rebounds,'' he said. Best and Worst Best
Jordan finale: Fittingly, his last move in the NBA was a fadeaway.
</P>
<P>
   Worst Jordan finale: Ever the dimwit, Bulls owner Jerry
Reinsdorf re-raises Jordan's retirement banner with his career
spanning ``84-93.'' Some of us have known since June 14 that a
banner reading ``84-98'' should have been produced. Quotes of Note
``If it was going to be done, I'd rather have the best of all-time
do it to me.'' _ Jazz forward Bryon Russell, ``posterized'' on
Jordan's final shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the years that they done freakin' destroyed people,
it's payback time. And people are not going to care that Michael
and Scottie aren't. All they're going to see is that Chicago Bulls
jersey and if you can beat 'em by 50, by God, beat 'em by 60.
They're gonna get drilled.'' _ Minnesota Timberwolves forward Sam
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a business where agents steal, pay off clients and cheat
each other, I get kicked out for trying to do the right thing.'' _
Stephen Woods, decertified as an agent by the NBPA after
consistently criticizing the union stance during the lockout.
Crystal Roundball If it isn't already, the NBA should look into
updating its Jerry West-silhouette logo with a flying Jordan.
Already in the works is a television marketing campaign focusing
more on teams instead of individuals. 24 SECONDS West: In case you
missed it, Mavericks coach/GM Don Nelson predicted German sensation
Dirk Nowitzki would win Rookie of the Year. Remember, however, this
is the same Nellie who last year predicted the Mavs would contend
for the playoffs before their 20-62 disaster. ... On his Nov. 11
radio show in LA, Jazz forward Karl Malone said he would demand a
trade once the lockout was lifted. Malone has since retracted those
comments (at least he didn't say he was misquoted) and plans to
meet with Miller this week to talk about a contract extension.
``It's priority No. 1,'' Miller said. ... By refusing to reveal how
he voted in New York, Lakers guard Kobe Bryant all but confirmed he
was one of the five dissenters against the agreement. Bryant, who
previously salivated at the thought of becoming the league's first
$150 million man, can now sign an extension of only seven years and
$66 after the season. ``If you ask me, personally, I didn't like
the deal too much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   East: Pistons forward Jerome Williams came back from New York
saying ``I heard it more than once. More than twice.'' What was it?
That teammate Grant Hill will be a marked man for his passive,
anti-union stance during the lockout. ``I did communicate with
Billy Hunter and Patrick Ewing, but I didn't always agree with
everything,'' said Hill. ... Wizards guard Tim Legler also expects
to attract some attention, after being the first player to
criticize the union. He and veteran Mitch Richmond supposedly
cleared the air last week. ``We talked, and there's no bad blood,''
said Richmond. ``Not anymore.'' ... Knicks center Patrick Ewing
showed up at the Heat's workout last week wearing a Knicks T-shirt.
Tim Hardaway and Keith Askins made him reverse it. ``Not much was
said,'' explained Hardaway. ``Everybody just started looking, and
he turned it around. We had to protect our gym.'' (Richie Whitt
writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
