r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-COLORADOSTATE     01-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-COLORADOSTATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU'S OVERTIME VICTORY CAUSES FUROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT COLLINS, Colo. _ Horned Frogs coach Billy Tubbs thrust both
hands upward after No. 20 TCU's 92-89 overtime victory against
Colorado State yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rams coach Ritchie McKay took exception, and so began an
exchange of words between coaches until assistants from both teams
stepped between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to go shake the coach's hand, and he started calling
me some obscene names. He didn't want a piece of me,'' Tubbs said.
``But you've got to remember he's just a young pup. He's just a guy
learning the game, but he's got a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay's outburst provided a wild conclusion to what already had
been a wild game at Moby Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Horned Frogs guard Ryan Carroll tipped in a Vladimir Jaksic miss
with 15.4 seconds remaining in overtime to lock up the victory as
TCU improved to 14-3 and 2-1 in the Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't done much the whole game. I had to do something,''
said Carroll, who got four of his 12 points in overtime. ``I
thought he was going to make it. Instead, he missed it, and I just
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs' defense, which had struggled in the waning
seconds of regulation, allowing Rams guard Milt Palacio to sail in
unmolested for a game-tying layup with 7.1 seconds remaining, then
stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   TCU prevented Rams players from getting a shot on their last
overtime possession, Horned Frogs forward Marquise Gainous blocking
Nick Mayer's last-ditch attempt as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you think you have a game won, you should have
a game won, and instead it goes into overtime,'' Tubbs said. ``A
lot of times you don't respond. ... It was tough. We fought every
circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue, foul trouble and a hyped bunch from Colorado State
(11-5, 1-3), to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game ended a stretch of three games in six days for
the Frogs. It began with an after-hours, ESPN-televised victory
against SMU on Monday and followed with a trip _ and a loss _ to
Wyoming on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Horned Frogs preseason all-American Lee Nailon fouled out
with 3:31 remaining in regulation. He got his fourth and fifth
fouls in a 12-second span. Until that point, Nailon and Gainous had
been TCU's main weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous finished with 24 points and 12 rebounds to lead all
players, and Nailon chipped in 15 and seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we've been leaning on Lee all season,'' said Horned
Frogs forward Shannon Long, who finished with 17 points. ``So when
he fouled out, we said: `OK, it's time for other guys to step up.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, Long and Frogs guard Prince Fowler contributed big
baskets down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's victory against Colorado State looked a lot like its loss
to Wyoming. The Horned Frogs once again shot well, 57 percent on
the game, including 64 percent in the second half. They also
outrebounded the Rams, 41-26.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, unlike against Wyoming, the defense was able to
step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a weird week,'' Carroll said later.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs ``imposed a lockout'' all week, refusing to talk to Denver
and Colorado Springs media because of an article that mentioned an
incident that is alleged to involve Tubbs, his middle finger and
Colorado fans back in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs got blamed back then. McKay took blame yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little of my inexperience, I guess,'' said McKay,
in his first season at Colorado State. ``I just thought he
should've just shook my hand and left the court. He didn't need to
celebrate like that at our fans. However, my reaction is not how I
want my team to be represented.'' (Jennifer Floyd writes for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
