<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCCAP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFC PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
Jets at Broncos Time: 3:05 p.m. TV: KTVT/Channel 11 Radio: KTCK/AM
1310 Line: Broncos by 9 Series: Broncos lead, 13-12-1 Last meeting:
Broncos 31, Jets 6 (1996)STORY LINES BRONCOS (15-2) Are the Broncos
poised to be one of the greatest teams in NFL history?
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't win 13 consecutive games to start the season and 18
consecutive overall and not be considered great. A win today would
give the Broncos 32 victories the past two seasons, and 45 over the
past three. Both marks would tie league records. Ten of their
victories this season have come by 10 or more points. During the
13-game winning streak, they trailed just twice in the fourth
quarter of games for a total of 16:21. But first, Denver needs to
win today, then in two weeks at the Super Bowl to be considered an
all-time great team.
</P>
<P>
   What has been the key to the Broncos success?
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter. In 1998, the Broncos were the third-fastest
starting team in league history. They outscored their opponents in
the first quarter of games 144-54. The 90-point difference in the
first quarter trails only the 1966 Chiefs (158-30) and the 1986
Vikings (151-60). The Broncos outscored their opponents 47-9 on
opening drives during the regular season. In the playoffs last
week, Denver scored a touchdown on its first offensive drive and
outscored the Dolphins 14-0 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   JETS (13-4) Do the Jets have enough defense to stop the Broncos?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. The Jets finished seventh in total defense during the
regular season. But they never faced a great offense down the
stretch. San Francisco, Atlanta and Tennessee were the only top-10
offenses the Jets faced this season. The top-ranked 49ers, who had
a more balanced attack than the Broncos, scored 36 points in the
season opener. New York held seventh-ranked Atlanta to three
points, but that was with Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler on the
sidelines. The Jets held ninth-ranked Tennessee to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Jets too young to win such a big game on the road?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. The Cowboys were a very young team when they went on
the road to defeat the 49ers in the 1992 NFC Championship Game. The
Jacksonville Jaguars were very young when they defeated the Broncos
in a 1996 divisional playoff game. And the Cardinals were very
young when they defeated the Cowboys two weeks ago. So throw
playoff experience out the window. Besides, head coach Bill
Parcells is 11-5 in the playoffs and 3-0 in conference championship
games. Players such as Keith Byars, David Meggett, Curtis Martin,
Pepper Johnson and Jumbo Elliott, who have been with Parcells in
either New England or the New York Giants, have plenty of
championship game experience.
</P>
<P>
   KEY MATCHUPS TERRELL DAVIS vs. JETS LINEBACKERS Davis can bull
ahead to make a tough five-yard gain or cutback and go for 50. In
1998 he joined O.J. Simpson, Eric Dickerson, and Barry Sanders as
the only backs to gain 2,000 yards in a season. In the postseason,
Davis has no equal. He has averaged a league-record 145.2 yards
rushing in six postseason games. Jets linebackers Mo Lewis, Pepper
Johnson, and Bryan Cox are veteran playmakers who must fill the gap
in Bill Parcells' defensive alignment, which will mix between a 3-4
and a 4-3. Lewis, who made the Pro Bowl, Johnson, and Cox are part
of a unit that struggled at times, with a No. 14 ranking against
the run. They allowed 276 yards rushing in the last two regular
season games, but bounced back to hold Jacksonville to less than
100 last week. KEYSHAWN JOHNSON vs. DARRIEN GORDON and RAY CROCKETT
Johnson, the No. 1 draft pick out of USC in 1996, came into his own
this year. He caught a career-high 83 passes for 1,131 yards and 10
touchdowns. Against Jacksonville last week he had his best
all-around game as a pro, catching nine passes for 121 yards and a
touchdown, rushing for another touchdown, and recovering a fumble
that kept a Jets drive alive. He also lined up in the nickel
defense and made an interception on the Jaguars' last drive. At
6-foot-3, 212 pounds, Johnson uses his size and jumping ability to
position himself for most receptions. Crockett is 5-10, Gordon
5-11. Both have been beaten for big plays this year, but they've
also responded with big plays. Crockett has three interceptions and
a touchdown return, Gordon has four and a touchdown return of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS TO VICTORY BRONCOS Jump out in front early and get the Jets
to start wondering if they are good enough to be here.
</P>
<P>
   Keep quarterback John Elway healthy, because if you are down in
the fourth quarter, Elway has proven he can win it.
</P>
<P>
   Try to get tight end Shannon Sharpe lined up on a linebacker to
open up the passing attack. JETS Stay with running back Curtis
Martin who can break the game open on any play.
</P>
<P>
   Give Vinny Testaverde time to throw so Keyshawn Johnson and
Wayne Chrebet can work on an undermanned Broncos secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Make a big play on special teams and keep Mile High Stadium real
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   THE EDGE Broncos run offense (154.3 ypg) vs. Jets run defense
(103.7) Edge: Broncos
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Broncos are one of three NFL teams that started the
same five in the offensive line in all five games. Terrell Davis
has averaged 145.2 yards in six postseason games, an NFL-record by
34.5 yards over runner-up John Riggins.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos pass offense (226.5) vs. Jets pass defense (190.0) Edge:
Broncos
</P>
<P>
   Comment: John Elway will hope to make his last game at Mile High
Stadium a winning one with passes to Shannon Sharpe and Ed
McCaffrey. The Jets defender, cornerback Aaron Glenn, likely will
miss his fifth game with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Jets run offense (117.4) Broncos run defense (80.4) Edge: Even
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Curtis Martin (1,287 yards) has been worth the bushel
of draft picks the Jets gave New England to get him last year.
Nobody runs on Denver because they spend so much time passing to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Jets pass offense (239.8) vs. Broncos pass defense (228.0) Edge:
Jets
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Vinny Testaverde has a pair of 1,000-yard receivers in
Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet. The Broncos allow too many big
plays and don't get enough consistent pressure on the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams Edge: Broncos
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Broncos punt returner Darrien Gordon has a career punt
return average of 13.2 yards, best in league history. The Jets best
kick returner, Aaron Glenn, is expected to miss the game with an
ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching Edge: Jets
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Jets coach Bill Parcells is 3-0 in conference
championship games and with a win would become he first coach in
league history to take three teams to the Super Bowl. Denver's Mike
Shanahan is one of the brightest offensive minds in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line Broncos 28, Jets 27 (Kevin Lyons is a writer for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
