<HEADLINE>
SOLVING FINANCIAL WOES, OTHER NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
The last time George Will was at Arlington Stadium, he was seen
daintily eating his barbecued ribs with a knife and fork. That
alone is enough to question his placement on Commissioner Bud
Selig's blue ribbon panel being formed to study baseball's alarming
economic situation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selig is facing another revolt by small-market owners aghast at
the latest round of mega contracts handed out to Kevin Brown, Mo
Vaughn, Albert Belle and others this winter. Those owners are
voicing the same concerns about revenue and competitive disparity
that led to the 1994-95 players strike and the cancellation of the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The stark reality is the bandage solutions devised to end that
nightmare have done little to solve the underlying problems that
caused the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Now many owners are looking at the recent NBA deal enviously and
wondering why they can't have payroll caps and salary maximums,
conveniently forgetting the players have successfully fought off
such attempts in the past.
</P>
<P>
   So Selig is calling on Will, former Federal Reserve boss Paul
Volcker, former Senator George Mitchell and Yale economics guru
Richard Levin to study the situation and come up with a solution
that would avoid another labor war.
</P>
<P>
   Selig is also on that committee, along with 13 other owners. The
Players Association, naturally, is not represented. So much for
that partnership supposedly being forged between the barons and
their multi-million dollar serfs.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball last called on Volcker in 1994. His committee then
recommended elimination of salary arbitration and reducing the
number of years needed for free agency from six to three years.
They also advocated greater sharing of ticket receipts and local
broadcast revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Small-market owners have been against lowering free-agent
eligibility because it reduced the number of years they can hold
onto their best players. But they're now finding out that because
of arbitration and other factors, they have to trade away their
best players long before they get close to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Big-market owners are naturally resistant to revenue sharing.
Rangers owner Tom Hicks just paid $250 million for his franchise
and isn't interested in sending some of his profits off to the
Kansas City group that paid $70 million for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   But the owners are never going to get the players to help solve
their problems or get them to agree to an NBA-type contract.
Baseball union founder Marvin Miller wasted no time in blasting the
basketball union for agreeing to salary maximums, comments that
were no doubt directed toward his own successors Don Fehr and Gene
Orza.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's competitive balance in the free-agency era will
forever be tied to revenue. The more revenue sharing, the better
chances Kansas City and Montreal have. The more money George
Steinbrenner, Peter Angelos and Rupert Murdoch have to outspend
their opponents, the worse it will be for the lower-, middle- and _
like the Rangers _ upper-middle class teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will have an $80 million payroll, and it's still
hard to imagine them threatening the New York Yankees and the
Cleveland Indians. If they do, don't doubt that either Steinbrenner
or Cleveland general manager John Hart will redouble their efforts
to pry Roger Clemens away from Toronto. Short hops There is nothing
more overblown around here than the debate about whether or not
Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez should be allowed to play winter
ball. The Rangers' concern about Rodriguez wearing down would be
more understandable if manager Johnny Oates were willing to give
Rodriguez more time off during the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Oates was hardly more willing to use reserve catcher Bill
Haselman last year than he was Dave Valle or Henry Mercedes in
previous years. And if he wasn't willing to use Haselman more then
he'll hardly get excited about Gregg Zaun or John Marzano.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Jimmy Carter, retired Gen. Colin Powell and
former Atlanta mayor Andrew Young are among the many dignitaries
expected for the Feb. 5 Hank Aaron Gala, which will celebrate
baseball's all-time home run leader's 65th birthday and the 25th
anniversary of his record-breaking 715th home run. Organizers, who
expect to raise $1 million for Aaron's Chasing the Dream
Foundation, are also hoping to get Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's new ownership is trying to push out club president
Claude Brochu, the boss who presided over the demise of a
once-competitive franchise. But the Expos still need to find a new
boss, get their ownership group in place and have it all approved
by Major League Baseball. They also need to find a way to build a
new stadium, otherwise the franchise is headed to Northern
Virginia. The latest deadline is March 5 for approval by MLB, but
the Expos are unlikely to get it all done.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Boston general manager Dan Duquette signed Jose
Offerman to that ridiculous contract with the idea of having him
play second base. But manager Jimy Williams wants Jeff Frye at
second, Offerman at first and Reggie Jefferson and Mike Stanley
platooning at designated hitter. It could get interesting in spring
training. (T.R. Sullivan writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
