<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCURRY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCURRY SAY CLINTON CRITICISM IN BBC INTERVIEW TAKEN OUT OF
CONTEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's former chief spokesman says the
politics of impeachment ``grate'' on Clinton in ways he doesn't
publicly show, but that the president still aspires to be
remembered positively in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would not be a human being if it didn't grate on him, but
he understands that if he dwells on this all day long, it's going
to take all the energy that he needs to do the other stuff,''
former White House press secretary Mike McCurry said in an
interview with ``The Arizona Republic.'' ``I think he does a pretty
good job of disciplining himself so he doesn't focus on that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, who stepped down in October after nearly four years at
the White House, said Clinton ``is a student of the presidency, and
he knows how presidents have been treated in history, and I think
he cares very much about what the historical record will be of his
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first president to be impeached by the House
since Andrew Johnson in 1868. Judging by their opening statements
at Clinton's Senate trial last week, House managers seem to believe
Clinton's legacy cannot be salvaged. Failing to hold Clinton
accountable for his efforts to conceal his affair with Monica
Lewinsky ``will cause a cancer to be present in our society for
generations,'' Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., told the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCurry, Clinton ``knows that there is nothing he
can do about events that have already transpired, but there is
something he can do about trying to get things done in his capacity
as president that will reflect well on him in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry, 44, who now works at a public relations consulting
firm, lived in the Valley for a few years during the 1980s. He was
a top aide on then-Gov. Bruce Babbitt's unsuccessful 1988 campaign
for the Democratic presidential nomination. In the 2000 race,
McCurry said he hopes to be ``as helpful as I can'' to Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry has given few interviews since telling the BBC's
``Newsnight'' program last month that he had ``enormous doubts''
about Clinton and his ``incredibly bizarre personal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry later had to explain that his widely quoted comments
were excerpted from a broad assessment of Clinton that included
good and bad points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the interviewers) kind of bored in. They said, `You,
personally, weren't you troubled by his behavior?' And I said,
`Well, yeah, sure, anybody would be troubled. The guy's fooling
around with a 21-year-old staff member. I mean, that's not a good
thing.' And I said, `Of course, you have to look at the larger
picture.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The affable McCurry, widely respected as a press secretary, said
former White House colleagues gave him ``a hard time'' about the
remarks. But he never heard from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him when I left that I was not going to trash him and
be disloyal to him, and I meant that. And that's why I'm kind of
aggravated that I got myself in a situation where some of the
things I said sounded critical,'' McCurry told ``The Republic.''
``The other thing that really killed me was that they taped the BBC
interview that I did, and they aired it the Friday night before the
(House) impeachment. When it came out, looked like it was just
uncommonly bad piling on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I should write him a note or something, but I
don't know what I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been silent on impeachment since the Senate
arguments began Thursday, according to White House aides, largely
because he doesn't want to appear to interfere with the process.
</P>
<P>
   While some pundits have speculated that Clinton may be depressed
or in denial, McCurry suggested neither extreme is true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably like most Americans. They go to work; they do
their jobs. They don't sit around dwelling on politics all day
long,'' McCurry said. ``I think that's one of the reasons why
people basically still give him a pretty good job approval rating,
because they say, `Look, despite all the scandal stuff, he's
continuing to do a pretty good job as president.' And that gets him
a little bit of slack, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House's attention to Clinton's legacy is evidenced by
its frequently updated Internet site, detailing pages and pages of
Clinton-Gore accomplishments that ``transformed'' the nation.
Recently, the site also began featuring a trial brief defending
Clinton against the two articles of impeachment being considered by
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's stewardship of his public image has its limits. As
far as McCurry knows, Clinton has not tried to rein in or rebuke
former senior officials, including McCurry, who have made
unflattering remarks about their former boss after leaving the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   As the scandal unfolded, former press secretary Dee Dee Myers
said in August that the facts ``have not led me to conclude that he
has been telling the truth,'' and former senior adviser George
Stephanopoulos urged Clinton to ``come forward, clear the decks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Clinton) never, in my earshot, said anything critical
about George or about Dee Dee,'' McCurry said. ``I think it would
be a little self-obsessed to imagine that he tracks all of our
quotes. I'll be candid with you, I don't think he sits around and
worries very much about what Dee Dee Myers and George
Stephanopoulos and Mike McCurry say about him. I think he's got
other things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   As the scandal intensified, the former Clinton aides inevitably
faced a ``gut check'' decision about the nature of their future
political analysis, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (Stephanopoulos and Myers) have always had pretty
interesting commentary, but then when things suddenly are sour and
it's a real controversy and confrontation, then you get this gut
check moment. Do you say what you really think, or do you sort of
say, `Well, here's what the White House line is.' It's a different
balance for every person.''
</P>
<P>
   As for him, McCurry said he'll often leave listeners with the
notion that Clinton is a ``complicated'' man.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're giving a 45-minute speech, at the end of it people
say, `Well, you obviously have a lot of affection for Bill Clinton,
you have a lot of respect for some of the things he did. But you
also clearly came away thinking that some of the stuff he did was
wrong.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-16-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
