<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER STAGGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Technically, Lance ``Mount'' Whitaker passed the
test.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8 behemoth from Northridge beat an established
(albeit aging) heavyweight for the first time in his young career.
</P>
<P>
   However, his seventh-round technical knockout of 34-year-old
former contender Alex Stewart on the undercard of the Mike
Tyson-Francois Botha fight was hardly the coming out that Whitaker
and Co. might've imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker nearly went down in the fourth round and was cut below
his left eye before the bout was stopped at 1:40 of the seventh
because of a deep gash below Stewart's right eye that bled from the
second round on.
</P>
<P>
   As one member of Whitaker's camp said, ``Whew! Welcome to the
big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   In another bout involving a local fighter, Robert Garcia
outpointed John John Molina to retain his IBF junior lightweight
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really that tough,'' said Whitaker, playing down his
apparent difficulties. ``I got careless and he caught me a couple
of times. I wasn't in that much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``...I'm not trying to be cocky. He caught me and I was a little
wobbly, but I came back and won. That's what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly looked tough from outside the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker (18-0, with 16 knockouts) outworked Stewart (43-9, 40
KOs) from the beginning. Stewart admitted it.
</P>
<P>
   And in the third round, a round after Stewart was cut from a
punch, Whitaker appeared to take charge. He hurt Stewart with a
flurry of his George Foreman-like, battering-ram punches late in
the round.
</P>
<P>
   However, Whitaker inexplicably has a bad habit of carrying his
hands at his waist and he paid the price against a big-punching,
veteran fighter who has been in the ring with many of the big-name
heavyweights of the past decade, including Tyson and Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   He landed a left hook squarely on Whitaker's jaw. Whitaker
smiled but clearly he was hurt. Stewart, sensing the kill, went
after the bigger man, but he couldn't put him away. His window of
opportunity had closed.
</P>
<P>
   By the sixth round, the cut was bleeding profusely and Stewart
was tiring. No one was surprised when it was stopped in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Goossen, Whitaker's trainer, agreed it was anything but an
easy fight but was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of the one punch, it was a picture-perfect
fight,'' he said. ``You could see the brutality of Lance's punches.
(Stewart) took a beating. I thought they stopped the fight with
Lance dominating.
</P>
<P>
   ``...This win puts Lance right in the (championship) mix. You
have the top six, seven guys and then another group of four or five
right behind them. Lance is in that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me six to nine months and I'll put him in there with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who said he ran out of energy by the sixth round, gave
Whitaker credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat me,'' he said. ``You gotta give him that.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (32-0, 24 KOs) survived a late rally by Molina (45-6, 30
KOs) to retain his title.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxnard resident controlled the fight for the first eight
rounds, consistently beating Molina to the punch and getting the
best of several furious exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   However, Garcia was unable to put away or even hurt the durable
Puerto Rican and Molina picked up momentum. He outboxed the
champion for the latter third of the fight _ when Garcia's right
eye was swollen almost shut _ but couldn't pick up enough points to
win.
</P>
<P>
   Molina knocked down Garcia in the 12th round but still lost by
the same score on all three cards: 115-112.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was particularly significant for Garcia because of
Molina's reputation _ he gave Oscar De La Hoya one of his toughest
fights _ and the fact it was on international pay-per-view TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a warrior,'' Garcia said. ``He always comes to fight. I
trained good, I trained hard for this fight.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
