</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAD ADDRESSES FAILED POLYGRAPH, DENIES INVOLVEMENT IN
DISAPPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Mikelle Biggs' father, responding to news reports
that he failed a polygraph test, stated flatly at a news conference
Saturday that he was not involved in the disappearance of his
11-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know myself that I wasn't in volved in it. I can't
comprehend somebody doing that to their own daughter,'' said
Michael Darien Biggs, 35, leaning against the family's car in front
of their Mesa home, his hands stuffed in his jeans pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel guilt? Heck yeah. Do I feel responsible? Absolutely.
Isn't that the definition of a parent?''
</P>
<P>
   Sources told ``The Arizona Republic'' that Biggs failed a
voluntary polygraph test about the Jan. 2 disappearance of his
daughter, who vanished after bolting outside her house after she
thought she heard an ice-cream truck.
</P>
<P>
   But Biggs said police told him the test was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa police have not characterized Biggs as a suspect in the
investiga tion, describing him as one of hundreds of leads in the
case. And both police and Biggs said distress over his daughter's
disappearance may have affected the results of the FBI-administered
exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get scared, I get angry. And when I get angry, I can't
think straight,'' Biggs said. ``There was a period of three or four
days there when I was consumed with nothing but rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggs said he and his wife, Tracy, immediately agreed to take
poly graphs and submit fingerprints. And, he said, he is not upset
that investi gators asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would've thought the police were doing a poor job if they
hadn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikelle was riding a bicycle belong ing to her sister, Kimber,
9, when she disappeared two weeks ago, four doors away from her
home at El Moro Avenue and Toltec Street. The bicycle and two
quarters for ice cream were found nearby in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents took the polygraph tests, independently, a little
more than a week ago, Biggs said. He couldn't recall the exact day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the questions were fairly general,'' he said, adding
that about three were related to Mikelle's disap pearance.
</P>
<P>
   He said he took the test in a stark room, where he sat strapped
to the device and staring at paint swirls on a blank wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing isn't designed to make you feel very at ease,
anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs said he took more than one test that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI agent said, `Look I think you've got too much anger
and this isn't going to work,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have declined to reveal the results of Tracy Biggs' test
and her husband said he can only assume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was OK, or she'd be out here talking to you,'' he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs offered to take another test, but wouldn't predict the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now added to the . . . fear and anger that I feel is
apprehension. What if I fail again?''
</P>
<P>
   Biggs said he hadn't hired a lawyer, but wasn't ruling out the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   He has never shied from the public eye. Often decked out in blue
jeans and athletic shoes, he has calmly shared details about his
life and his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs added that he hopes his even-keeled statements and lack of
emotion in public aren't construed as a lack of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not normally an emotional person anyway. I tend to hide
that from people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, he has tried to remain calm in case Mikelle sees
television reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to make her feel any better to see her dad
crying on TV,'' he said. ``Dad is always the strong one that holds
everything together.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, time is taking its toll. His daughter's
disappearance enters its third week today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really a feeling of numbness after two weeks. This
can't be happening to us,'' he said. ``Nothing has a lot of meaning
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kym Pasqualini of the Nation's Missing Children Organization
Inc. said polygraph tests are commonly given to family members
after a disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process of ruling them out,'' Pasqualini said, adding
that being strapped to a polygraph device comes with its own set of
stresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's intimidating for the families _ intimidating and
frightening. They feel like suspects,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikelle's father said he hopes the publicity about him won't
deter the thousands who have helped the exhaustive search for his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Community volunteers said they are working as hard as ever to
help find the missing child.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday they plastered large vinyl stickers, featuring a
full-color picture of Mikelle, on dozens of car windows in the
parking lot of Simon's Warehouse Foods in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Most said they hadn't read the morning papers' stories about
Biggs failing a polygraph test.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa Police Department has fielded more than 4,000 calls
over the past two weeks, and checked out scores of leads.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa police ask that anyone with information about Mikelle's
where abouts call (602) 644-2002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
